<html><TITLE>Spotlight - Ewing v. National Basketball</TITLE><body bgcolor=ffffff

vlink=ff0000> 

<I>Seven professional basketball players, including Michael Jordan and Patrick Ewing,

filed this suit against the National Basketball Association challenging the league's

salary cap, draft, and restricted free agency system. If they win, team owners will not

be able to lock out the players next season, which they have threatened to do if the two

sides cannot agree on a new labor agreement.</I>

<center> <H4>IN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT     FOR THE DISTRICT OF

MINNESOTA</H4><P><img width=250 height=668 align=left src=/images/spotlight/jordon.gif 

alt="[photo]">    PATRICK EWING, MICHAEL JORDAN, STACEY AUGMON, DALE DAVIS, ALONZO

MOURNING, HOWARD EISLEY, and STACEY KING,<P>  Plaintiffs,<P>  v.<P>  NATIONAL BASKETBALL

ASSOCIATION, ATLANTA HAWKS, L.P., BOSTON CELTICS LIMITED PARTNERSHIP, CHARLOTTE NBA

LIMITED PARTNERSHIP, CHICAGO PROFESSIONAL SPORTS LIMITED PARTNERSHIP,: NATIONWIDE

ADVERTISING SERVICE, INC., DALLAS BASKETBALL LIMITED, THE DENVER NUGGETS LIMITED

PARTNERSHIP, DETROIT PISTONS BASKETBALL COMPANY, GOLDEN STATE WARRIORS, ROCKET BALL,

LTD., PACERS BASKETBALL CORPORATION, LAC BASKETBALL CLUB, INC., THE LOS ANGELES LAKERS,

INC., THE MIAMI HEAT LIMITED PARTNERSHIP, MILWAUKEE BUCKS, INC., MINNESOTA PROFESSIONAL

BASKETBALL LIMITED PARTNERSHIP, MEADOWLANDS BASKETBALL ASSOCIATES, MADISON SQUARE GARDEN

CORPORATION; ORLANDO MAGIC, LTD. THE PHILADELPHIA 76ERS BASKETBALL CLUB, INC., PHOENIX

SUNS LIMITED, TRAIL BLAZERS INC., SACRAMENTO KINGS LIMITED PARTNERSHIP, SAN ANTONIO

SPURS, LTD., ACKERLEY COMMUNICATIONS, INC., JAZZ BASKETBALL INVESTORS, INC., CAPITAL

BULLETS BASKETBALL CLUB, INC., TORONTO RAPTORS BASKETBALL CLUB, INC., and VANCOUVER

BASKETBALL LIMITED PARTNERSHIP,<P>  Defendants.</center><Pre>





</pre>  LINDQUIST & VENNUM P.L.L.P.<br> 4200 IDS Center<br> Minneapolis, Minnesota

55402<br> (612) 371-3211<P>  WEIL, GOTSHAL & MANGES<br> 767 Fifth Avenue<br> New York,

New York 10153<br> (212) 310-8000<P>  Civil Action  No.         <H4>CLASS ACTION

COMPLAINT</H4> Plaintiffs, by their undersigned attorneys, for their Complaint herein

allege as follows:<P>  <H3> INTRODUCTION</H3> 1. This action is brought to enjoin

violations by each defendant of the federal antitrust laws and the common law of torts

of the various states with respect to plaintiffs and similarly situated basketball

players who have entered and will enter into player contracts with NBA teams, and to

redress injuries sustained by plaintiffs and similarly situated basketball players as a

result of violations by each defendant of the federal antitrust laws. Plaintiffs are

professional athletes who have been employed by individual teams in the National

Basketball Association ("NBA"). Defendants are the NBA and each of its member teams (the

"NBA Defendants"). The NBA Defendants have jointly agreed and conspired to deny

plaintiffs the ability to market their services as professional basketball players in a

competitive market through a comprehensive set of anticompetitive restrictions. As a

result of defendants' anticompetitive agreements, plaintiffs and other similarly

situated NBA players are prevented from receiving a competitive market value for their

services and are denied the freedom of movement available to employees in virtually

every other industry in the United States. Although defendants were previously held to

be protected by the nonstatutory labor exemption to the antitrust laws as long as there

was a "continuing collective bargaining relationship," the players in the NBA have

chosen to give up their collective bargaining relationship in order to assert their

rights under the antitrust laws.  <H3> JURISDICTION AND VENUE</H3> 2. These claims arise

and are brought under Sections 1 and 2 of the Sherman Antitrust Act, 15 U.S.C. 1, 2, and

the common law of torts of the various states.<P> 3. This Court has jurisdiction over

these claims pursuant to 28 U.S.C.  1331, 1337 and 1367. <P>4. Venue in this action is

proper pursuant to 28 U.S.C.  1391 and 15 U.S.C.  22. Each of the defendants can be

found, resides, has an agent, or transacts business in the District of Minnesota, and

the unlawful activities were carried on in part by one or more of the defendants within

this district.  <H3> THE PARTIES</H3> 5. Plaintiff <b>Patrick Ewing</b> is a

professional basketball player who, since 1985, has been employed in interstate commerce

by defendant Madison Square Garden Corporation, which owns and operates the New York

Knickerbockers. After the 1996-97 NBA season, his contract with the Knickerbockers will

expire on July 1, 1997.<P> 6. Plaintiff <B>Michael Jordan</B> is a professional

basketball player who, since 1984, has been employed in interstate commerce by defendant

Chicago Professional Sports Limited Partnership, which owns and operates the Chicago

Bulls. After the 1995-96 NBA season, his contract with the Chicago Bulls will expire on

July 1, 1996. <P>7. Plaintiff <B>Stacey Augmon</B> is a professional basketball player

who, since 1991, has been employed in interstate commerce by defendant Atlanta Hawks,

L.P., which owns and operates the Atlanta Hawks. After the 1994-95 NBA season, Mr.

Augmon opted-out of his contract with the Hawks, and is currently a free agent. <P>8.

Plaintiff <B>Dale Davis</B> is a professional basketball player who, since 1991, has

been employed in interstate commerce by defendant Pacers Basketball Corporation, which

owns and operates the Indiana Pacers. Mr. Davis has the right to opt-out of his contract

with the Pacers after the 1995-96 NBA season. <P>9. Plaintiff <B>Alonzo Mourning</B> is

a professional basketball player who, since 1992, has been employed in interstate

commerce by defendant Charlotte NBA Limited Partnership, which owns and operates the

Charlotte Hornets. Mr. Mourning is in the third year of a six year contract, but has the

right to opt-out of his contract after the 1995- 96 NBA season. <P>10. Plaintiff

<B>Howard Eisley</B> is a professional basketball player who was selected by the

Minnesota Timberwolves as the 30th pick in the 1994 NBA draft. Mr. Eisley was employed

in interstate commerce by the Minnesota Professional Basketball Limited Partnership,

which owns and operates the Minnesota Timberwolves, but was released by the Timberwolves

after the All-Star break. Mr. Eisley then signed with the San Antonio Spurs and was

re-released just prior to the end of the regular season. Mr. Eisley is currently a free

agent. <P>11. Plaintiff <B>Stacey King</B> is a professional basketball player who,

since 1989, had been employed in interstate commerce by defendant Chicago Professional

Sports Limited Partnership, which owns and operates the Chicago Bulls. In February of

1994, Mr. King was traded to the Minnesota Timberwolves, which is owned and operated by

defendant Minnesota Professional Basketball Limited Partnership. His contract with the

Timberwolves having expired, Mr. King is currently a free agent. <P>12. Defendant NBA,

which maintains its office at 645 Fifth Avenue, New York, New York 10022, is an

unincorporated association consisting of the 29 separately- owned and operated

professional basketball teams listed in paragraph 14. The NBA is engaged in interstate

commerce in the business of, among other things, operating the sole major league

professional basketball league in North America. <P>13. The other defendants are the 29

NBA member teams, each of which, upon information and belief, is a corporation, except

where noted below. Upon information and belief, each of the defendant teams is a

separately-owned and independent entity which operates a professional basketball

franchise for profit under the team name and in the cities set forth below: <UL>NBA

Defendant, Team Owner; State or Province of Organization,Citizenship or Incorporation;

Team Name (City) <P>Atlanta Hawks, L.P.; Georgia; Atlanta Hawks <P>Boston Celtics,

Limited Partnership; Massachusetts; BostonCeltics <P>Charlotte NBA, Limited Partnership;

North Carolina; CharlotteHornets <P>Chicago Professional Sports, Limited Partnership;

Illinois;Chicago Bulls <P>Nationwide Advertising Service, Inc.; Ohio; ClevelandCavaliers

<P>Dallas Basketball, Limited; Texas; Dallas Mavericks <P>The Denver Nuggets, Limited

Partnership; Colorado; DenverNuggets <P>Detroit Pistons Basketball Company; Michigan;

Detroit Pistons <P>Golden State Warriors; California; Golden State Warriors <P>Rocket

Ball, Ltd.; Texas; Houston Rockets <P>Pacers Basketball Corporation; Indianapolis;

Indiana Pacers <P>LAC Basketball Club, Inc.; California; Los Angeles Clippers <P>The Los

Angeles Lakers, Inc.; California; Los Angeles Lakers <P>The Miami Heat, Limited

Partnership; Florida; Miami Heat <P>Milwaukee Bucks, Inc.; Wisconsin; Milwaukee Bucks

<P>Minnesota Professional Basketball, Limited Partnership;Minnesota; Minnesota

Timberwolves <P>Meadowlands Basketball Associates; New Jersey; New JerseyNets <P>Madison

Square Garden Corporation; New York; New YorkKnickerbockers <P>Orlando Magic, Ltd.;

Florida; Orlando Magic <P>The Philadelphia 76ers Basketball Club, Inc.;

Pennsylvania;Philadelphia 76ers <P>Phoenix Suns Limited; Arizona; Phoenix Suns <P>Trail

Blazers, Inc.; Oregon; Portland Trail Blazers <P>Sacramento Kings, Limited Partnership;

California; SacramentoKings <P>San Antonio Spurs, Ltd.; Texas; San Antonio Spurs

<P>Ackerley Communications, Inc.; Washington; Seattle SuperSonics <P>Jazz Basketball

Investors, Inc.; Utah; Utah Jazz <P>Capital Bullets Basketball Club, Inc.; Maryland;

WashingtonBullets <P>Toronto Raptors Basketball Club, Inc.; Ontario; Toronto Raptors

<P>Vancouver Basketball, Limited Partnership; British Columbia;Vancouver Grizzlies</ul> 

<H3> CLASS ACTION</H3> 14. Plaintiffs Patrick Ewing, Michael Jordan, Stacey Augmon, Dale

Davis, Alonzo Mourning, Howard Eisley, and Stacey King (hereinafter sometimes referred

to as the "class plaintiffs") are representatives of a class, as defined by Rules

23(b)(1) and (b)(2) of the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure, and bring this action on

behalf of themselves and the class members as described in paragraph 17 below.<P> 15.

The class represented by plaintiffs is comprised of (i) all players who have been, are

now, or will be under contract to play professional basketball for an NBA club at any

time from June 28, 1995 to the date of final judgment in this action and determination

of any appeal therefrom, and (ii) all college and other basketball players who, as of

June 28, 1995, to the date of final judgment in this action and the determination of any

appeal therefrom, have been, are now, or will be eligible to play basketball as a rookie

for an NBA team.<P> 16. The class is so numerous and geographically so widely

distributed that joinder of all members is impracticable. There are questions of law and

fact common to the class. The claims of the plaintiffs are typical of the claims of the

class they represent, and the plaintiffs will fairly and adequately protect the

interests of the class they represent. <P>17. Each person in the class is, has been,

and/or will be subject to uniform agreements, rules and practices among the defendants

restraining competition for players' services which are or will be uniformly imposed by

the NBA Defendants. <P>18. Except for provisions as to individual compensation and other

variations which do not materially affect this action, the player contracts are

substantially identical throughout the NBA. <P>19. In construing and enforcing their

uniform agreements, rules and practices, and in taking the actions described below, the

NBA Defendants have acted, have refused to act, and will act, on grounds generally

applicable to the class, thereby making appropriate injunctive relief or corresponding

declaratory relief with respect to the class as a whole. <P>20. The prosecution of

separate actions by individual members of the class would create the risk of: <P>  (a)

inconsistent or varying adjudicationswith respect to individual members of the

classwhich would establish incompatible standards ofconduct for the party apposing the

class, or <P>  (b) Adjudications with respect to individualmembers of the class which

would as a practicalmatter be dispositive of the interests of otherclass members not

parties to the adjudications orwould substantially impair or impede the abilityof such

absent class members to protect theirinterests.<H3>NATURE OF INTERSTATE TRADE AND

COMMERCE</H3> 21. The primary business in which defendants are engaged is the operation

of major league professional basketball teams and the sale of tickets and telecast

rights to the public exhibition or the individual and collective basketball talents of

players such as plaintiffs. To carry on this business, the NBA Defendants must compete

with each other for and retain the professional services of players, such as plaintiffs,

who are signed to play basketball for one of the NBA defendant teams. <P>22. The

business of major league professional basketball is distinct from other professional

sports businesses, as well as from college and minor league basketball. Its

distinguishing features include, but are not limited to: the rules of the sport and the

season during which it is played, the talents and rates of compensation of the players,

for whom playing basketball is their full-time profession; the nature and amounts of

trade and commerce involved; and the unique demand for the NBA Defendants' games by the

consuming public, both as ticket purchasers and as home viewers of and listeners to

television and radio. <P>23. The NBA Defendants' operation of and engagement in the

business of major league professional basketball involves a substantial volume of

interstate trade and commerce, including, inter alia, the following interstate

activities: travel; communications; purchases and movement of equipment; broadcasts and

telecasts of league games; advertisements; promotions; sales of tickets and concession

items; employment of players and referees; and negotiations for all of the above. <P>24.

The NBA Defendants' aforesaid interstate transactions involve collective annual

expenditures and receipts in excess of one billion dollars. <P>25. The plaintiffs have

been employed by and/or are seeking new employment with one or more of the defendant

teams in interstate commerce as professional basketball players in the NBA.  <H3>

BACKGROUND</H3> 26. The NBA member teams constitute the only market in the United States

and North America for the services of major league professional basketball players. The

NBA member teams are the only participants in that market, and the only potential for

competition in that market is between the separately-owned and independently- operated

NBA teams. However, rather than engaging in competition for the players' services, the

NBA Defendants are combining and conspiring to eliminate such competition among

themselves for the vast majority of NBA players, including plaintiffs, through group

boycotts and concerted refusals to deal. This is accomplished by the NBA Defendants

jointly adopting and imposing "rules" and "policies" that have the purpose and effect of

preventing players from offering their services to other NBA teams in a competitive

market when their player contracts expire, or from renegotiating with their current team

during the term of their contracts free from unreasonable restrictions upon those

renegotiations. <H3>The Expired CBA</H3> 27. In 1987, a class of professional basketball

players filed an antitrust lawsuit, Bridgeman. et al. v. National Basketball

Association. et al. (D.N.J. 87-4001), against the NBA and its member teams challenging

the unilateral implementation of a variety of anticompetitive restrictions, including a

"salary cap." In November of 1988, the United States District Court for the District of

New Jersey approved the Bridgeman Stipulation and Settlement Agreement ("BSA"). The BSA,

along with a new collective bargaining agreement ("CBA"), substantially modified the

anticompetitive restrictions imposed by the NBA owners, but did not eliminate them

completely. It was agreed to for a limited period of time by the NBA class in order to

provide some relief to players during their short-lived professional careers. By its

terms, the BSA and the CBA expired on June 23, 1994 -- the day after the last playoff

game of the 1994 NBA season. <H3>The Salary Cap System</H3> 28. The Salary Cap contained

in the BSA and CBA was a system whereby the aggregate salaries of a team's players were

fixed at artificially low levels. A number of exceptions were provided, but salaries

were still depressed below competitive market levels. The Salary Cap system is a

league-wide price-fixing agreement among competitors to restrict the wimages of all NBA

players. <H3>The NBA Draft</H3> 29. The BSA and CBA also included a so-called "NBA

Draft," which has the purpose and effect of dividing the market for the most wanted

first year, or "rookie," player services among the NBA clubs who would otherwise compete

against each other for those players. Under the NBA Draft, each NBA team is given the

right, pursuant to certain rules and procedures, to choose specific college and other

rookie players with whom the team will have the exclusive NBA negotiating rights. If a

rookie player for any reason does not wish to sign a contract with or play for the NBA

team which "owns" the rights to him, he may not negotiate with or play for any other NBA

club. <P>30. The allocation of negotiating rights effectuated by the NBA Draft is

enforced by a group boycott and agreement among the NBA Defendants. This group boycott

and agreement takes the form of a concerted refusal to deal with potential NBA players

except through restrictive anticompetitive practices. <H3>Restricted Free Agency</H3>

31. The BSA and CBA also included a number of other anticompetitive restrictions,

including restrictions on the ability of NBA players with less than four years of NBA

experience to market themselves as free agents. These players were subject to an

anticompetitive "Right of First Refusal" by their previous team.  <H4> The Williams Case

And The Continuation Of The Salary Cap System During The 1994-1995 NBA Season</H4> 32.

On June 17, 1994, the NBA filed a lawsuit against 17 NBA players in the U.S. District

Court For The Southern District of New York, seeking a declaratory judgment that

continued implementation by the NBA and its teams of the Salary Cap, the NBA Draft, and

the so-called "Right of First Refusal" do not violate the antitrust laws. National

Basketball Association v. Williams, No. 94 Civ. 4488 (KTD) (S.D.N.Y.). <P>33. On June

27, 1994, a group of then-current and prospective NBA players counterclaimed in the

Williams action, alleging that the continued implementation of the Salary Cap and the

Right of First Refusal, and the holding and subsequent enforcement of the 1994 NBA

Draft, violated Sections 1 and 2 of the Sherman Act, even while the NBA and the National

Basketball Players Association ("NBPA") continued to negotiate over a potential new CBA.

The NBPA was then the recognized collective bargaining representative of players who are

employed as professional basketball players by NBA teams. The counterclaims in the

Williams action sought injunctive relief on behalf of the counterclaim-plaintiffs and an

unspecified class, and damimages on behalf of the individual defendants/counterclaim-

plaintiffs. The counterclaims in the Williams action did not seek relief for any

class-wide damimages. <P>34. on July 1, 1994, Judge Kevin T. Duffy was assigned the

Williams case, and a hearing was conducted on Friday, July 8, 1994. At the hearing,

Judge Duffy informed the parties that a preliminary injunction hearing that the

counterclaim-plaintiffs had requested would be consolidated with a one-day trial on the

merits, which "trial" was conducted four days later, with no pre-trial discovery, on

Tuesday, July 12, 1994. <P>35. At the "trial," counsel for the NBPA and the

counterclaim-plaintiffs stated that he had no objection to certification of a class.

However, no notice was provided to the class members prior to that date, or at any other

time in the Williams action. <P>36. On July 18, 1994, the district court in Williams

held that the non-statutory labor exemption to the antitrust laws continued to shield

restraints previously agreed to in an expired CBA from the antitrust laws until there

was no longer a collective bargaining relationship between the parties. In its opinion,

the Williams district court stated as follows: <P>Antitrust immunity exists as long as a

collective bargaining relationship exists. Accordingly, the NBA is granted the

declaration it seeks -- the continued implementation of these challenged measures by the

NBA do not violate the antitrust laws as long as the collective bargaining relationship

exists. <P>This does not mean that the Players are "stuck" with these provisions

forever. Certainly, they can attempt to bargain these provisions away -- including

exerting economic pressure by means of a strike. Or the Players may request

decertification of the NBPA as a collective bargaining agent. I do not mean by this

ruling to encourage the Players to decertify their union so that they may bring an

antitrust claim. But, decertification is certainly an option the Players have. In fact,

this is exactly what the National Football League Players Union did following Powell

II.<P> National Basketball Ass'n v. Williams, 857 F. Supp. 1069, 1078 (S.D.N.Y. 1994)

(citations omitted) (emphasis added). <P>37. On July 21, 1994, the Williams district

court entered judgment in that action. The Judgment stated that the action was thereby

certified as a class action pursuant to Fed. R. Civ. P. 23(b)(1) and (b)(2) on behalf of

and against a class of NBA players and prospective NBA players who were defined as

follows: <P>(1) all basketball players who were, are or will be under contract to a team

in the NBA from the date of formal expiration of the 1988 Collective Bargaining

Agreement through the date of final judgment in this action; and (2) all college and

other basketball athletes who, from the date of formal expiration of the 1988 Collective

Bargaining Agreement through the date of a final judgment in this action, were, are or

will be eligible under the Constitution and By-Laws of the NBA to play basketball for an

NBA team . <P>The Judgment stated "that the NBA's continued implementation of the

college draft, right of first refusal and salary cap does not violate the antitrust laws

as long as it is implemented as part of a continuing collective bargaining

relationship." (Emphasis added). <P>38. On January 24, 1995, the Second Circuit affirmed

the Williams decision, on the basis that the NBA players had to end their collective

bargaining relationship, if they wanted to pursue their antitrust rights. 45 F.3d 684

(2d Cir. 1995). <P> <H3> The "No Lockout/No Strike Agreement"</H3> 39. on October 27,

1994, the NBPA and the NBA executed an agreement pursuant to which, from that date until

the earlier of the day of the last game of the 1995 NBA Finals or the date upon which a

"successor collective bargaining agreement" is executed, the NBA agreed not to engage in

a lockout of the NBPA, and the NBPA agreed not to engage in "any strikes, cessations or

stoppimages of work, or any other similar interference with the operations of the NBA."

The agreement also included a moratorium on player signings. Upon information and

belief, the No Lockout/No Strike Agreement was subsequently extended by the NBPA and the

NBA to July 1, 1995.<P> The Negotiations And The Proposed New Collective Bargaining

Agreement Between The NBPA And The NBA <P>40. In and before June 1995, the NBPA and the

NBA engaged in negotiations over the terms of a potential new collective bargaining

agreement. During the course of those negotiations, numerous players asked the Executive

Director of the NBPA to disclose the potential terms that were being discussed with the

NBA. The Executive Director refused to disclose those terms. <P>41. During this same

period, from media reports and other sources, numerous NBA players became aware of the

terms of a new collective bargaining agreement that had been negotiated between the NBA

and the NBPA Executive Director. The NBA players learned that the agreement would

include onerous terms that were substantially worse and even more anticompetitive than

the terms of the old BSA and CBA. <P>42. On June 21, 1995, NBA players received a

memorandum from the President and Executive Director of the NBPA. Upon information and

belief, the shipping costs of this mailing, approximately $50,000, was paid by the NBA.

The memorandum stated that "we finally have reached an agreement in principle on the

terms of a new six-year collective bargaining agreement," and had attached to it a five

page "outline" that the memorandum stated "sets forth virtually all the proposed terms

of this deal." A copy of that outline is attached hereto as Exhibit A. <P>43. The

President and Executive Director of the NBPA also stated in the memorandum that the

NBPA's 27 player representatives would be meeting the next day in Chicago, "so that they

may vote on whether they accept our recommendation to ratify this deal." (Two of the 29

NBA teams, Toronto and Vancouver, are new expansion teams, and do not yet have player

representatives). The Executive Director confirmed in media reports that the new CBA

would not be submitted to the players for a ratification vote, and that the CBA would be

ratified and go into effect if approved by 21 player representatives the day after the

"outline" of the deal was distributed. Upon information and belief, not submitting the

new CBA to a ratification vote by all the NBA players was unprecedented, as all prior

CBA's in the NBA were voted on by all NBA players. <P>44. Numerous players opposed to

the conduct of the NBPA in its negotiations with the NBA attended the June 22 player

meeting in Chicago. At that meeting, the player representatives attending the meeting

voted to table the CBA that had been presented to them for ratification.  <H3> The

Decertification Of The NBPA</H3> 45. On June 21, 1995, the day before the Chicago

meeting, seventeen NBA players filed a petition with the National Labor Relations Board

requesting that an election be held to "decertify" the NBPA as the collective bargaining

representative of NBA players. In support of the petition, statements signed by more

than 30% of the collective bargaining unit renouncing the authority of the NBPA were

submitted to the NLRB within 48 hours of the filing of the petition.<P> 46. During the

past week, NBA players continued to sign decertification petitions despite the

vociferous opposition of the NBPA's Executive Director and a few of its officers. On

June 28, 1995, the petitioning players notified the NBA and the NBPA that more than 50%

of the bargaining unit had signed petitions renouncing the authority of the NBPA to

collectively bargain on their behalf, and copies of those petitions were delivered to

the NBA and NBPA. As a result, because the NBPA is a voluntarily "recognized" union,

rather than a "certified" union, the NBPA may no longer be voluntarily recognized by the

NBA as having the authority to collectively bargain on behalf of NBA players, and any

collective bargaining relationship with the NBA has ended. The NBA players no longer

want to engage in, and are no longer represented in, collective bargaining with the NBA.

<P>47. As a result, as of July 28, 1995, there is no collective bargaining

representative to shield (under any ruling) the NBA Defendants' anticompetitive

restraints from antitrust review. <P>The NBA's Continued Imposition Of Anticompetitive

Restrictions Upon NBA Players <P>48. The NBA and its teams have announced that they will

hold the 1995 NBA Draft on June 28. On July 1, 1995, all player contracts that do not

extend beyond the 1994-95 NBA Season will expire. Upon information and belief, on and

after July 1, 1995, the NBA and its member teams will continue to enforce the market

division rules of the NBA Draft, and will also do one or more of the following: (i)

implement a claimed "lockout" prohibiting all player signings or player employment; (ii)

impose a system of anticompetitive restraints on player movement, salaries, and contract

signings substantially similar to the anticompetitive restrictions agreed to in the

proposed CBA that was rejected by the players; or (iii) impose a system of

anticompetitive restraints on player movement, salaries, and contract signings

substantially similar to the terms of the prior CBA. <P>49. Any "lockout" on player

signings by the NBA and its member teams would be an illegal group boycott in violation

of Section 1 of the Sherman Act, under both the per se rule and the rule of reason

standard. Any imposition of a system of restraints substantially similar to the old CBA

or the restrictions in the proposed CBA would be an illegal restraint of trade in

violation of the Sherman Act.  <H3> COUNT I</H3>  <H4> Section 1 of the Sherman Act</H4>

50. Plaintiffs repeat and reallege each of the allegations contained in paragraphs 1

through 49. <P>51. There is a relevant market for the services of major league

professional basketball players in North America, and a relevant submarket in the United

States. The restrictions imposed by the NBA Defendants substantially restrain and injure

competition in these markets. <P>52. The restrictions imposed by the NBA Defendants

constitute an agreement among competitors to suppress competition for the services of

major league professional basketball players in North America and the United States, in

violation of Section 1 of the Sherman Act. This system operates as a perpetual

horizontal group boycott and/or horizontal division of markets, which constitutes an

unreasonable restraint of trade. Each of the NBA Defendants is a participant in this

unlawful combination or conspiracy. <P>53. The purpose and effect of the anticompetitive

restrictions is to suppress the market for player services and earn monopoly profits for

the NBA owners. No procompetitive purpose is furnished by these restrictions. <P>54. The

plaintiffs and class members have suffered and will suffer antitrust injury to their

business or property by reason of the continuation of this unlawful combination or

conspiracy. The restrictions imposed by the NBA Defendants injure plaintiffs and class

members by depriving them of the ability to offer their services as professional

basketball players to the teams of their choice in a free and open market upon first

entering the NBA as rookie players and upon expiration of their player contracts. This

causes them to receive salaries that are substantially lower than they would have

received in the absence of those restrictions. Veteran players are also hurt by the NBA

draft, which has the effect of lowering the salaries of all NBA players. <P>55.

Plaintiffs and class members face threatened loss or damage by reason of defendants'

continued violation of the antitrust laws when their present contracts expire.  <H3>

COUNT II</H3>  <H4> Section 2 of the Sherman Act</H4> 56. Plaintiffs repeat and reallege

each of the allegations contained in paragraphs 1 through 49. <P>57. There is a relevant

market for the services of major league professional basketball players in North

America, and a relevant submarket in the United States. The restrictions imposed by the

NBA Defendants substantially restrain and injure competition in these markets. <P>58.

Defendants possess monopoly power in the markets for the services of major league

professional basketball players in North America and the United States. <P>59. The

restrictions imposed by the NBA Defendants are willfully intended to help defendants

acquire and maintain their monopoly power in the market for the services of major league

professional basketball players in North America and the United States, in violation of

Section 2 of the Sherman Act, by operating as a perpetual horizontal group boycott

and/or horizontal division of markets. <P>60. The plaintiffs and class members have

suffered and will suffer antitrust injury to their business or property by reason of the

restrictions imposed by the NBA Defendants. This system injures plaintiffs and class

members by depriving them of the ability to offer their services as professional

basketball players to the teams of their choice in a free and open market upon first

entering the NBA as rookie players and upon expiration of their player contracts. This

causes them to receive salaries that are substantially lower than they would have

received in the absence of those restrictions. <P>61. Plaintiffs and class members face

threatened loss or damage by reason of defendants' continued violation of the antitrust

laws when their present contracts expire.  <H3> COUNT III</H3> <H4>Tortious Interference

With Prospective Contracts</H4> 62. Plaintiffs repeat and reallege the allegations

contained in paragraphs 1 through 49. <P>63. By implementing the aforesaid restrictions

defendants intentionally interfere with plaintiffs' and class members' rights to enter

into prospective contracts with NBA clubs other than their prior clubs. Absent these

restrictions, plaintiffs and class members would enter into contracts with other NBA

clubs. <P>64. The aforesaid conduct violates the antitrust laws, the common law of torts

of the various states, and is intended to harm the players, and earn monopoly profits

for the NBA owners, by suppressing the market for player services. <P>65. Plaintiffs and

class members will be deprived, by reason of the restrictions imposed by the NBA

Defendants, of the ability to negotiate and obtain more favorable contract terms, and

will receive compensation substantially less than they would have received if they were

not prevented from entering into contracts with other NBA teams. Absent such

restrictions imposed by the NBA Defendants, the plaintiffs and class members would be

free to offer their services to other NBA teams in a competitive market. Plaintiffs and

class members will suffer severe and irreparable harm if they are prevented from

offering their services to other NBA teams in a competitive market.  <H3> PRAYER FOR

RELIEF</H3> WHEREFORE, plaintiffs pray for judgment with respect to their Complaint as

follows: <UL>1.   Declaring that, as of June 28, 1995, the restrictions imposed by the

NBA Defendants violate  1 and 2 of the Sherman Act: <P>2.   Declaring that, as of June

28, 1995, the restrictions imposed by the NBA Defendants constitute a tortious

interference with prospective contracts; <P>3. Enjoining defendants from implementing or

enforcing those restrictions, or any similar restrictions, which would prevent or

restrict rookie players from freely negotiating or entering into contracts with any NBA

club, and which would prevent or restrict veteran players from freely negotiating or

entering into contracts with any NBA club after their existing contracts expire; <P>4.

Awarding plaintiffs and the class they represent treble the amount of damimages they

sustained as a result of the violations of the antitrust laws alleged herein: <P>5.

Awarding plaintiffs and the class they represent the damimages they sustained as a

result of defendants' interference with their entering into prospective contracts; <P>6.

Enjoining defendants from implementing or enforcing the restrictions imposed by the NBA

Defendants, or any similar restrictions which would interfere with the prospective

contracts of plaintiffs and the class they represent with other NBA teams; <P>7.

Awarding plaintiffs and the class they represent their costs and disbursements in this

action, including reasonable attorneys' fees; <P>8. Granting plaintiffs and the class

they represent such other and further relief as may be appropriate.</UL>  <H3> DEMAND

FOR JURY</H3> Pursuant to Rule 38 of the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure, plaintiffs

demand a trial by jury. <P>Dated: June 28, 1995 <P> /s/James W. Quinn<br> Jeffrey L.

Kessler<br> David G. Feher<br> Yoav M. Griver<br> WEIL, GOTSHAL & MANGES<br> 767 Fifth

Avenue<br> New York, New York 10153<br> (212) 310-8000 <P>and<P>  /s/Edward M. Glennon,

#34503<br> Charles J. Loyd #174257<br> LINDQUIST & VENNUM P.L.L.P.<br> 4200 IDS

Center<br> Minneapolis, Minnesota 55402<P> Attorneys For Plaintiffs<P> <hr size=5> 

