<html><TITLE> Spotlight - CNN Coverage Biased?</TITLE><body bgcolor=ffffff

vlink=0000ff><img width=100 height=92 border=0 align=left src="/images/spt2.gif" alt=" *

"><I>The following are excerpts from the Counsel Connect online forum, <b>OJ Trial

Notebook.</b> Here, attorneys  discuss CNN and the media's coverage of the

Simpson murder trial. Do you think the media are biased?<Pre>



</pre>Since the trial began, I have seen quite a bit of CNN's 10:30 pm wrap-ups of the

trial and its news summaries on both the normal news and Headline news.  I now believe

that CNN's coverage (with the exception of Larry King Live) has become biased in favor

of the prosecution.   (For example, CNN's treatment of the FBI guy the last two days as

a "defense witness who turned" is terribly misleading.)  Does anyone else believe that

CNN's coverage has become biased?<P></i>-Mark R. Cheskin <br> Steel Hector -

Miami<P><I>Most of the coverage I have seen is biased in that those covering the trial

seem to ignore the concept that one should hear both sides of an argument before

reaching a decision. The trial is being covered as if it were a boxing match and I

believe the news media is doing an incredible disservice to the American system of

justice. For many people, the OJ trial is their first real exposure to a trial. Future

jury pools will now consist of people who might analzye the evidence presented as it is

being analyzed by commentators- punch by punch.<P>For example, most polls I've seen

reported ask whether the respondent believes OJ is guilty, rather than the proper

question (if such a question is proper at all at this point in the trial): Do  you

believe OJ is guilty beyond a reasonable doubt.</i>-H. Alan Altschuler <P> H. Alan

Altschuler - Closter<P><i>At least with televised coverage you eventually get both

sides. How often have we seen the print media run a front-page story on one side's

supposed knockout, only to bury next day's story about the cross-examination that

undercut it?<P></i>-Scott Graham <br> The Recorder - San Francisco<P><I>I am sure that

Mark, who just coincidentally happens to be a huge Buffalo Bill/OJ Simpson fan,  has

made an objective and well-supported comment about CNN's coverage.  Putting him aside,

however,  I am sure an average OJ hater/prosecution supporter would believe that the

coverage on CNN after the infamous glove demonstration, which CNN and others reported as

a terrible goof that the prosecution made, was biased in favor of OJ (even though some

would say that he appeared to be practicing his Naked Gunacting techniques when he tried

them on).  Bias, like beauty, is often in the eyes of the beholder.<P></i>  -Edwin

Torres <br> Steel Hector - Miami<P><I>One thing that has puzzled me throughout this

trial is the oft-heard insistence from commentators that we must  **all ** presume OJ

innocent until (and unless) we've heard all the evidence and he's been proven guilty

beyond a reasonable doubt? Why?  I'm not on the jury;  I can reach whatever conclusion I

want using whatever standard I want.  If I believe that , on balance, he appears to be

guilty despite some doubt, is it somehow illegal,immoral or unethical for me to hold

that belief?  The court ofpublic opinion quite properly has very different rules.  If OJ

walks, he may find that out the hard way.<P></i>-David L. Eades <br> Moore & Van Allen -

Charlotte<P><I>Edwin....are you saying that the glove thing WASN'T a terrible

prosecution screwup? If so, I'd be interested in your expanded views....David...you can

believe what ever you want, and surely will. As will we all.  It surely isn't

unamerican...perhaps quite the contrary.  If he gets off, there will be lots of folks

who will think he's guilty, anyhow; if he is convicted, there are lots ofpeople who will

think he is innocent, anyhow.<P></i>-Barry D. Bayer <br> Law Office Tech Rev -

Homewood<P><I>The distinction David draws is very important, particularly if OJ walks. 

It will also become more apparent --when OJ faces the Goldman family's wrongful death

suit, where the standard of proof for liability is only "more likely than not." Then

also consider OJ's custody battle for his children, which would be heard before a judge

sitting without a jury.<P>  The importance of the difference between the jury'sverdict

and the public's opinion on the issue of OJ's guilt hasled me to a prediction: Even if

OJ is eventually released, he will make out his own punishment for the crime -- via

suicide.  <P>I reach this prediction after considering two facts. First, here we have a

guy who lived on the adultation of the masses.  If he is released and seeks to return to

the "white world" in which he lived -- and where 80+% of the people thinkhe's guilty,

he'll never be able to go to another restaurant, theatre, party, or other public place

without someone yelling "murderer!" at him.  This will be too much for him to

handle.<P>Second, his note to the public before he took off on thelow speed chase

certainly hinted at the prospect of suicide.  And that was BEFORE the public had any

firm opinions that he was guilty.  <P>Once OJ is released back into the real world, all

the congratulatory back-patting from Johnnie Cochran and Robert Shapiro  won't help him

for long.<P></i>-Jon Drucker <br> Hill Wynne Troop - Los Angeles<P><i>Tyson and Von

Bulow didn't commit suicide. And Tyson was convicted. William Kennedy Smith seems to be

holding his own. John Dean survived. Leona Helmsly is back in her commercials. Imelda

Marcos even went back to the Phillipines. Michael Milken is doing quite well thank you.

So is Ivan Boesky. The Mayflower Madam now gives sex advice. Michael Jackson got a new

wife and a new album. <P>What suicide? The nature of  the celebrity will simply change.

Hey, this is America. Did someone mention Hugh Grant? <P></i>-Stephen Gillers <br> NYU

Law School - New York<P><I>It's a free country. You can believe whatever you please.<P>I

just think it is an aspect of good citizenship to presume innocence and hold the

government to its proofs before it exercises the power to imprison or kill. Why? First,

it's a kind of civic calisthenics; too much mobocracy makes the libertarian muscles

flaccid. It is simply a very good habit to be very skeptical of the exercise of these

state powers, and that skepticism is built into our discourse by the presumption

ofinnocence. It'd be nice if that standard was robust in jurors' civic consciences

*before* they were chosen to decide a fellow citizen's fate<br>else the transformation

we ask of people from theGeraldo level of ratiocination to judgment in court under law

would be too artificial to be counted on. True liberty ain't beanbag;  it takes

work.<P>Second, the presumption of innocence encourimages a quality that is sorely

missing from our public life: intellectual humility. We live in the era of snap

judgments and instant expertise. The presumption of innocence might remind us that we

don't know the whole story, that common sense as well as common decency suggestwe should

hear both sides of a dispute before rendering judgmenton it, that life is full of

surprises.<P>That said, there's no question that by now in the Simpson case most

people<br>including jurors -- know which way they'd vote. At this point, you might

argue, the presumption of innocence is nothing more than a necessary fiction. Like,

perhaps, an oath to tell the truth.<P></i>-Terry Moran <br> Court TV - New

York<P><I>Your point that "this is America -- anything is possible" might be well taken;

only time will tell.  Except for Tyson, though, none of the defendants you mention did

the "rags to riches" ego trip. And Tyson can fight again.  <P>What will OJ do after his

defense depletes his entire fortune?  Pump gas?  Work at the Brentwood McDonald's?  Or,

since this is America, maybe he'll run a pay-per-view TV show for $79.95 in which he

promises to tell where he hid the knife.  Wow, what a concept:  It could be the "TV

event of the Century"!  Stay tuned.<P></i>-Jon Drucker <br> Hill Wynne Troop - Los

Angeles<P>Gordon Liddy had a successful acting career and is now a syndicated radio talk

show host making, one assumes, a lot of money.<P>The not convicted Rodney King beaters

seem to be having no problem, and Fuhrman has apprently retired and is living in Idaho

(with thewhite extremists?)<P>And as someone noted on the radio the other day "Carl Van

Dorencome back...what you did wasn't so bad."<P>But while folks are entitled to make

whatever opinions they wish, and will do so....I do think it unseemly for TV and Radio (

and cable) folks ostensively on the "news" side assuming of course OJ is guilty, anyone

who thinks otherwise is an idiot, and making jokes about it.<P></i>-Barry D. Bayer <br>

Law Office Tech Rev - Homewood<P><I>Back to CNN Bias.  If you think CNN is biased - try

Rivera Liveand the Charles Groden show.  The problem with most news media and the tv

shows is that they want to try the case in 10 second sound bites while ignoring the

mundane but crucial foundational evidence.  For example, all the news shows talked about

the sock. Following the photographer's testimony about the sock not present at 3:13, the

media made a big ado about the next witness who said the sock was removed prior to 3:00. 

The media portrayed this as a major setback for the defense.  Yet most of them

completely ignored the testimony of Fung who said he took the sock at about4:30 or

something like that.  So which witness is right.  The media chose to ignore that these

witnesses were prosecution witnesses who were probable rebuttal witnesses.<P>The point

is that the media is interested in sensationalism - notjustice.  Justice is too often

too boring for the media.</i><P>-James Milliman <br> Middleton Reutlinger -

Louisville<P><I>To Terry:  I agree that the government shouldn't be able to exercise its

powers of incarceration unless it meets the "beyond the reasonable doubt" standard.  But

*I* don't have the power to incarcerate (and don't want it).  Are you really suggesting

that good citizenship  requires me to employ the  stringent reasonable doubt standard in

forming my  personal beliefs and opinions about the bad things people might have done?  

Think about it .  Am I morally required  to trust  (with my money?  with my children?)

someone  whom the evidence strongly (but not conclusively) suggests committed a horrible

crime just because he or she avoided a  conviction?<P></i>-David L. Eades <br> Moore &

Van Allen - Charlotte<P><I>I think it has to do with keeping an open mind until you hear

all the evidence. No one is under any legal obligation to do so, butit makes good sense

to me.<P>Deciding that OJ Simpson is guilty merely because of the prosecution evidence

seems equivalent of deciding the first speak in a debate wins the debate merely because

he or she made persuasive arguments.<P>The reason for "presumed innocent" is that the

state has tremendous power to accuse anyone of a crime, vast resources to investigate.

There are many examples in America and other countries of the state abusing its power.

So, to level the playing field, they not only have to prove someone is probably guilty,

but guilty beyond a reasonable doubt.<P></i>-H. Alan Altschuler <br> H. Alan Altschuler

- Closter<P><i><P>That the news is biased toward sensationalism is true, but I worry,

too, about non-news media use and abuse of the O.J. trial. Dennis Miller, for example,

on his weekly HBO show, at least some of which is humerous in the way his old SNL

"newscasts" were, continuously assumes that OJ is guilty; nay, worse, implies that

anyone who does not must be an idiot.<P>There is nothing to be done for this, I suppose,

but collectively cringe, and hope against hope that if it's a hung jury, there are

enough jurors who voted for acquittal to defuse the already-building California forces

in favor of legislation or aninitiative eliminating unanimous verdicts.<P>I recently had

a discussion with a non-yet-first-year law student, my step-nephew, who thought that

there was nothing wrong with cameras in the courtroom, and thought the televising of the

OJ trial was just swell.  Sigh.<P></i>-Richard Targow <br> Appellate Attorney -

Sebastopol<I><P>I haven't watched enough CNN to decide if they are biased, and I'd be

reluctant to say so if I had, since my view would be biased. But....I will say that as

the dedicated reader of our own Court TV dialy logs of phone complaints and reader of

all of our mail, we usually get lots of complaints of bias for one side or another when

that side is putting on its case or crossing the other side's witness. In other words,

it seems to me that when we simply try to explain what one side is doing we get tagged

with siding with that side.<P> That's why early on Gregg Jarrett, for example, was the

target of constant complaints about a pro pros. bias, whereas now I keep reading and

hearing that he's a stooge for the defense. And Terry was often accused of being the

third Menendez brother (which, asbest we can tell, he isn't.)<P>My impression is that

CNN is being as scrupulous as we are tryingto be. As for Geraldo Rivera-ne-Rivers,

that's a whole other story. But who expects him to be a real journalist? <P></i>-Steven

Brill <br> American Lawyer Media - New York<I><P>Of what relevance to bias are calls

from the public....or at least number of calls from the public?<P>I assume that SOMEONE

at Court TV who doesn't have a part in this or that specific broadcast is charged with

examining the substance of the complaints on bias and also in examining the tapes of the

commentaries.<P></i>-Barry D. Bayer <br> Law Office Tech Rev - Homewood<P><I>In keeping

with the best of Counsel Connect, this thread has expanded far beyond its original

narrow focus to

some very broad, telling issues facing our society (and not just the legal system).  I

may not have the technically correct philosophical terminology here, but I see a

distinction between rights and moral imperatives.<P>So, for example, I disagree with

Richard Targow:  based on what I know of the facts -- not the evidence -- (which of

course is far more than the jury knows or should know), there is no logical conclusion

but that O.J. committed the murder.  That is, however, an entirely different conclusion

than whether the jury, on the basis of the evidence admitted at trial, should conclude

that O.J. have been proven guilty beyond a reasonable doubt.  I thus agree with David

Eades and am troubled when we are told that our moral view of the case must be guided by

the constitutional standard ofguilty beyond a reasonable doubt.  I think it perfectly

coherent that our system allows people to avoid criminal punishment who society

nonetheless may pronounce blameworthy.  This dichotomy exists, of course, is the power

of the state and its potential for abuse, as pointed out by Alan Altschuler.  I am

prepared, ofcourse, to listen with annoyance to talking heads telling us how O.J. must

start with a clean slate if the jury does find him "notguilty."  <P>(Aside:  I also have

the view, educated largely visits to this forum and the review of the occasional

newspaper article, that O.J. should be found guilty by the jury unless the defense finds

some evidentiary support for its alibi/conspiracy theories.  I'd be the first to admit I

don't know enough of the trial evidence to have a conclusive opinion.)  <P>This

philosophical problem pervades other areas of our society, some of which have been the

subject of other threads here.  Think back to the the thread discussing Court TV

decision on televising the Simpson children's testimony.  Again there was the confusion

between the First Amendment right to communicate information through a free press with

the moral decision of the individual member of the press to decide whether or not to

transmit that information.  Brill & Co. were mightily castigated for falling down on

their First Amendment "duty" to publish the kids' testimony.  I myself was pleased that

Court TV exercised its moral right not to transmit the information without confusing the

First Amendment as a moral obligation to do so.  I think that thepress (construed

broadly  to include all the new media) should be free to publish without governmental

interference.  I hope that this right is exercised with the sort of discretion shown by

CourtTV.<P>Now if we could just get conversations of this level of activity, energy, and

thought going on some of the "substantive" discussion groups here on Counsel Connect.

&#60;g&#62;<P></i>-Tom F. Koegel <br> Folger & Levin - San Francisco<I><P>I think we as

attorneys have a special obligation to choose our words carefully, even if the general

public doesn't always catch the distinction.  <P>I'll readily admit that I think OJ

*killed* these 2 people, but I don't know if he's *guilty* yet.  There is a distinction

there which has been pointed out by Tom.  We don't have all the evidence, we're not in

the courtroom day after day, and we hear information/rumor which is never introduced

into court.  It's very difficult to filter that out when we look at the case, which

*may*result if our having a different opinion than the jury.  But they make the

guilty/not guilty decision.  We should stay away from those words until we hear the

entire case.<P></i>-Pamela Perrone <br> CVLSF - Chicago<I><P>I know that in Scotland a

jury has an available verdict of "NotProven."  Can someone tell me what effect that

verdict has?  It might be interesting to add it to American

jurisprudence.<P></i>-Mitchell Miller <br> Gray Gleicher - Beverly Hills<I><P>Excuse me

every one! let's talk about the media and how they completely forgot that two people

were murdered. Add that every feminist group now has a famous example of a wife beater.

Everyone is using poor OJ as a scape goat. Wether he did it or not I feel sorry for him.

No matter what he does some one will hate him. They will try to kill this man in the

electric chair even though they are not exactly sure if he did it, yet they this lady in

South Carolina who ADMITTED she killed her own kids- no knows her and she didn't do

anything very controversial like beating a spouse she just killed her kids.<P></i>

-George Stallings <br> Lexis/Nexis - New York<P><I>Holy cow!  You'd think Fabulous

himself wrote the last one.  By the way, the state is not seeking the death

penalty.</i>-John Gomila <br> Jones, Walker - New Orleans<P><I><P>No doubt, many t.v.

viewers already have judged O.J. Simpson as guilty, regardless of the presumption of

innocence and not having the advantage (or disadvantage) of seeing the actual evidence

presented to the jury. (I have prejudged  him innocent, as noted by my colleague Ed

Torres above.) But does that make it right for the news media?  (I'm not talking about

Jerry Spense on Larry King Live,  Geraldo, or Dennis Miller, etc.)</i><P>-Mark R.

Cheskin <br> Steel Hector - Miami<P>   <hr size=5> <P><a

