<html><body bgcolor=ffffff vlink=ff0000><TITLE> Spotlight - Microsoft v. US</TITLE><img

width=170

height=250 align=right src=/images/spotlight/gates.gif alt="[photo]"><pre>









</pre><I> The Department of Justice responds in this memorandum to Microsoft's demand

that a Civil Investigative  Demand issued by the DOJ be set aside. The DOJ claims that 

Microsoft has a monopoly on personal computer operating  software, and that packaging

software for its own network  along with Windows 95, an operating system, amounts to 

"bundling" and gives Microsoft an unfair competitive advantage in the lucrative on-line

market.</I><Pre>



</pre> <center>IN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT FOR THE SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW

YORK<P>MICROSOFT CORPORATION, <P>  Petitioner, <P> v.<P>ANNE K. BINGAMAN, in her

official capacity as Assistant Attorney General in charge of the Antitrust Division of

the United States Department of Justice,<P>    Respondent. <P>     Misc. Action No.

M8-85<P><B>MEMORANDUM OF THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA IN OPPOSITION TO MICROSOFT

CORPORATION'S PETITION TO SET ASIDE CIVIL INVESTIGATIVE DEMAND NO. 13187</B></center><P>

Microsoft Corporation ("Microsoft") asks this Court to set aside a Civil Investigative

Demand ("CID") issued by the Antitrust Division of the United States Department of

Justice (the "Division") that seeks information concerning the inclusion of software

relating to the Microsoft Network ("MSN") with Microsoft's Windows 95 operating system.

This conduct, Microsoft principally argues, simply "Cannot Violate the Antitrust Laws,"

Microsoft's Memorandum in Support of its Petition 10 (July 3, 1995) ("Mem." or

"Microsoft's Mem. in Support"), and, consequently, the government's investigation must

be terminated. <P> Microsoft seeks to bolster its argument with the protestation that it

has recently been the subject of considerable antitrust scrutiny. Although true, that

fact -- and the results of the Division's efforts -- tend to undermine Microsoft's

claim. Last year, the Division filed a complaint alleging violations of Sections 1 and 2

of the Sherman Act, 15 U.S.C. 1-2, and a consent decree, see <I>United States v.

Microsoft Corp.,</I> 1995-1 Trade Cas. (CCH) 11 71,027 (D.C. Cir. June 16, 1995)

(ordering decree entered), reversing 159 F.R.D. 318 (D.D.C. 1995) (refusing to enter

decree because, inter alia, it was too narrow in scope). And only a few months ago,

Microsoft abandoned a major acquisition after the government filed suit, alleging that

the transaction violated Section 7 of the Clayton Act, 15 U.S.C. 18, see <I>United

States v. Microsoft Corp.,</I> No. C 95 1393 WHO (N.D. Cal. filed Apr. 27, 1995). <P>

The government's present investigation likewise should be allowed to go forward, and the

CID upheld. The government believes that Microsoft's forced inclusion of the MSN access

software with Win95 might, under certain facts, violate the antitrust laws, and

Microsoft points to no potentially applicable exemption from those laws. Whether that

conduct actually does violate the antitrust laws, of course, depends on the facts, which

the Division properly has been trying to gather before Microsoft releases MSN, in an

attempt to avoid unnecessary disruption of Microsoft's business plans -- or a

potentially difficult problem of antitrust remedy. The Division pressed that objective

hard; Microsoft now complains that the Division left it too little time to negotiate

modifications of, and then to respond to, Civil Investigative Demand No. 13187, although

Microsoft had every reason to believe that the government, if asked, would have granted

more time. In any event, the deadline for responding has passed, and there is now ample

opportunity to accommodate both Microsoft's legitimate interests and the Division's

undoubted right to investigate, with or without the Court's involvement. <H3>

STATEMENT</H3> Microsoft is the world's largest producer of software for personal

computers. It develops, licenses, sells, and supports a wide variety of software,

including both operating systems, which control the basic operations of personal

computers, and applications programs, which work with the operating system to perform

useful functions for computer users. Microsoft is best known for its operating system

software, including both MS-DOS and various versions of Windows. Operating system

software is essential to the operation of personal computers, and Microsoft "dominates

the world market for operating systems software that runs on IBM-compatible personal

computers ('PCs')." Microsoft, 1995-1 Trade Cas. at 74,824. <P> Microsoft's dominance in

the market for personal computer operating system software amounts to a monopoly. Its

MS-DOS operating system, introduced in 1981, runs on over 120 million personal computers

world-wide; its Windows products have an installed base of over 50 million. See

Microsoft, 159 F.R.D. at 322. No other PC operating system has more than a small

fraction as many users. Last year, the United States filed suit against Microsoft,

alleging that it had monopolized the market for operating systems for IBM-compatible

personal computers, and Microsoft, without admitting liability, consented to the entry

of judgment against it. See id. The district court concluded that "Microsoft has a

monopoly on the market for PC operating systems," id.; the court of appeals, reversing

on other grounds, said nothing to the contrary. <P> Microsoft plans to release its

latest operating system product, Windows 95 ("Win95"), on August 24, 1995. In essence a

simultaneous upgrade and replacement for the current MS- DOS and Windows 3.1, Win95 is

expected to be an extraordinary commercial success. So computer magazines proclaim: "For

the existing mass of 60 million Windows users -- and the new users who join this club

every day -- there seems to be little doubt that Windows 95 will be their

next-generation [operating system]." David S. Linthicum, How Best to Migrate to Windows

95, Byte, July 1995, at 51, attached as Exhibit A hereto. Thus, "analysts estimate that

Microsoft may sell as many as 20 million copies of Windows 95 within the first three

months of its release." Elizabeth Corcoran, Justice Dept. Again Scrutinizing Microsoft,

Wash. Post, June 9, 1995, Hruska Aff. Ex. D, Microsoft's Mem. in Support, while other

analysts suggest that sales may reach 30 million copies in the first four months, see

Dave Kansas, Wall Street Anxiously Awaits Microsoft's Windows 95, Wall St. J., June 19,

1995, Hruska Aff. Ex. C. The release of Win95 is, as yet another analyst explains, "not

your normal upgrade cycle; it is a very significant event." Molly Baker, Successful

Launch Would Be A Boon To Dozens of Firms, Wall St. J., June 19, 1995, Hruska Aff. Ex. C

(internal quotations omitted). <P> Microsoft plans to launch another product, MSN, the

Microsoft on-line service, on the same day that it releases Win95. Microsoft apparently

will require OEM-licensees to provide certain icon placements, and to provide MSN access

software and certain screens to end users who receive Win95. Thus, every user who

purchases Win95 to upgrade an existing computer, as well as the millions who buy

computers for the home with Win95 already installed, will, it appears, automatically

receive the MSN access software. <P> Microsoft announced its plan to include the MSN

access software with Win95 in November 1994. It was not then clear whether other on-line

services would be included in the package, or whether OEMs would have a choice as to

taking or not taking the MSN access software and accompanying screens, with icons in

place. [FN1] Despite this factual uncertainty, public comment, almost immediately,

focused on potential antitrust problems. Thus, for example, the November 21, 1994, issue

of PC Week, an industry newspaper, reported that Microsoft's competitors were concerned

about "the antitrust implications of bundling Microsoft Network with Windows 95." Payoff

for Marvel may be Years away, PC Week, Nov. 21, 1994, at 121, attached as Exhibit B

hereto. It quoted Nina Lytton, president of Open Systems Advisors Inc., as saying

"'[t]his is a monopoly in the making."' Id. at 128. Columnist Jesse Berst noted in PC

Week that bundling the MSN access software with Win95 would give MSN "an unbeatable

edge" over competitors, and wrote: "I'm not an expert in antitrust law, so I don't know

whether this advantage is illegal. But I do know that it feels unfair. It feels like

Microsoft is using a monopoly in one area to gain a monopoly in another." Jesse Berst,

Microsoft's on-line rivals could end up in 'cyberia,' PC Week, Dec. 12, 1994, at 120,

attached as Exhibit C hereto. <P> The Division learned more about the Microsoft Network

in the course of its investigation of Microsoft's proposed acquisition of Intuit Inc.,

for the Microsoft Network played a role in Microsoft's plans for Intuit's personal

finance software. Thus, the Division discovered that Microsoft's Manager, Business

Development and Investments, wrote in an August 1994 analysis of the proposed

acquisition that Microsoft "owns Windows and Marvel [as MSN was then known] and

therefore is in a much better position to access many millions of users in the future

with [personal finance] service options," and that once Microsoft also owned Intuit.

"[Microsoft] would be dominant in that area. Complaint 11 4, <I>United States v.

Microsoft Corp.,</I> No. C 95 1393 WHO (N.D. Cal. filed Apr. 27, 1995), attached as

Exhibit D hereto. <P> Aware of this public concern, as well as Microsoft's monopoly

power and its history of anticompetitive practices, the Division began an investigation

related to the Microsoft Network. It also filed suit on April 27, 1995, to block the

Intuit acquisition, which led to the abandonment of the planned merger on May 20, 1995.

<P> On June 2, 1995, Microsoft's attorneys met with the Division to discuss the Network.

See Letter from Bingaman to Neukom, June 4, 1995, Memorandum of United States in Support

of Motion to Strike Ex. A (June 26, 1995) ("Strike Mem."). On June 4, Respondent sent

CID No. 13025 (which addressed both the Network and other matters) to Microsoft. The CID

specified a return date of June 9, but the cover letter pointed out that the Division

"stand[s] ready to negotiate this with you." Id. at 2. On June 9, counsel for Microsoft

wrote respondent the customary letter complaining of burden and denying any possibility

of an antitrust violation. See Letter from Urowsky to Bingaman, June 9, 1995, Hruska

Aff. Ex. F. Nevertheless, Microsoft stated that it would cooperate with the

investigation, and it and the Division negotiated concerning the CID, reaching at least

tentative agreement during the week of June 4, which was memorialized in a letter the

following week; the agreement pushed deadlines off as late as June 26 and made other

modifications. See Letter from Vogt to Cohen, June 12, 1995, Strike Mem. Ex. B.

Microsoft has since produced approximately fourteen boxes of documents in compliance

with CID No. 13025, has answered the interrogatories requested, and has supplied an

affidavit requested by the Division. <P> On June 19, Respondent sent Microsoft a letter

stating that Microsoft would receive a "follow-up and supplemental CID" later that day.

The letter, after noting the return date of June 23, four days off, explained that "much

(but not all) of the document production under this CID . . . can be postponed." Letter

from Bingaman to Neukom, June 19, 1995, Strike Mem. Ex. C. Through inadvertence, the

Division on June 19 sent Microsoft only the document schedule and interrogatories

intended to be attached to the CID, but not the formal CID itself. See Horwitz Decl. 3,

Strike Mem. Ex. D. The next day, counsel for Microsoft met with Respondent; but they

said nothing about this document schedule and set of interrogatories, even though

Microsoft already had received the letter and accompanying requests. <P> On June 21,

1995, Respondent sent CID No. 13187, the CID at issue here, to Microsoft, with a return

date of June 23, and a cover letter indicating that the CID was a substitute for the

(missing) June 19 CID, which the letter described as "withdrawn." Letter from Bingaman

to Neukom, June 21, 1995, Petition of Microsoft Corporation Ex. D (June 23, 1995 )

("Petition"). Nothing indicated, however, that the June 19 letter, proposing to postpone

much of the document production, had been withdrawn. See id. Microsoft received the CID

by fax on June 21 and by overnight courier on June 22. See Vogt Aff. 11 7. Microsoft's

Mem. in Support. <P> Microsoft and the Division entered into negotiations concerning the

June 21 CID on June 22. See Horwitz Decl. 3-17; Vogt Aff. 7-14. Microsoft made a

"compromise proposal," Vogt Aff. 9, which addressed the CID as a whole and which

Microsoft apparently intended to be considered only as a whole, id. 12. Counsel for the

Division wanted to present Microsoft's proposal to others in the Division and agreed to

get back to Microsoft promptly. The discussion ended at approximately 3:20 PM Eastern

time. See id. 14. <P> Microsoft filed its petition shortly after 9:30 am the following

day, see Urowsky Aff. 8, Microsoft's Mem. in Support, three business hours later and

before the statutory deadline for doing so. Although Microsoft had not yet received the

Division's response to its compromise proposal, Microsoft never requested an extension

of time in which to comply. Upon filing its petition, Microsoft apparently lost interest

in its own compromise proposal, or indeed in any other compromise, see id. at 10,

despite the Division's continuing willingness to negotiate.  <H3>ARGUMENT</H3>By

including the MSN access software with Win95, Microsoft is taking advantage of market

position in operating systems to gain an advantage elsewhere. Such use of economic power

to gain advantage has been a persistent source of concern under both section two of the

Sherman Act, see. e.g., <I>United States v. Griffith,</I> 334 U.S. 100, 107 (1948)

("[T]he use of monopoly power, however lawfully acquired, to foreclose competition, to

gain a competitive advantage, or to destroy a competitor is unlawful."); <I>Berkey

Photo. Inc. v. Eastman Kodak Co.,</I> 603 F.2d 263, 275 (2d Cir. 1979) (holding that "a

firm violates section two by using its monopoly power in one market to gain a

competitive advantage in another"), and section one of the Sherman Act, see. e.g.,

<I>Jefferson Parish Hospital Dist. No. 2 v. Hyde</I>, 466 U.S. 2, 17 (1984) ("the

likelihood that market power exists and is being used to restrain competition in a

separate market is sufficient to make per se condemnation appropriate"); <I>Betaseed,

Inc. v. U & I Inc.,</I> 681 F.2d 1203, 1220-21 (9th Cir. 1982) (coercive reciprocity

analysis identical to tying analysis under section one). Whether Microsoft's ongoing

course of conduct with respect to its provision of MSN and Win95 violates the antitrust

laws is currently under investigation; indeed, the facts continue to unfold on a daily

basis as market developments occur and as Microsoft changes its "beta" (i.e., test

version) of Win95. <P> <B>I. Microsoft's Conduct Is The Proper Subject Of A Government

Investigation And The Government's CID Requested Information Reasonably Relevant To That

Investigation </B><P> Microsoft argues that the government's CID should be set aside

because its "potential antitrust claims . . . are so plainly insubstantial." Mem. at 13.

According to Microsoft, a CID is improper if, prior to obtaining the very information

upon which a decision to file a complaint might be based, the government "cannot assert

. . . claims consistent with its obligations under Rule 11 of the Federal Rules of Civil

Procedure." Id. at 10. Indeed, in an argument heading, Microsoft asserts that its

conduct "Cannot Violate the Antitrust Laws." Id. <P> Microsoft misapprehends the concept

of "investigation," perhaps confusing it with post-complaint discovery. [FN2] Because

the purpose of an investigation is to gather evidence in order to determine whether an

enforcement action is warranted, the validity of a CID does not hinge on the

government's ability to articulate a fully-developed legal claim in advance of learning

the very facts the investigation is designed to discover. All that is required is that

the conduct under investigation faD within the Division's statutory authority.

Microsoft's conduct plainly meets this test. <P> Microsoft's contention that the CID

seeks irrelevant information is similarly flawed. The Division may seek information

"'not plainly incompetent or irrelevant to any lawful purpose,"' <I>FTC v. Invention

Submission Corp.,</I> 965 F.2d 1086, 1089 (D.C. Cir. 1992) (quoting <I>Endicott Johnson

Corp. v. Perkins, </I>317 U.S. 501, 509 (1943)), cert. denied, 113 S. Ct. 1255 (1993),

and Microsoft has failed to carry its burden of demonstrating that the information

requested was not reasonably relevant to the government's investigation. <H4>A.

Microsoft's Conduct Is The Proper Subject Of A Government Investigation </H4><B>1.</B> A

CID issued by the Assistant Attorney General in charge of the Antitrust Division is a

"civil administrative subpoena." H.R. Rep. No. 1343, 94th Cong., 2d Sess. 13 (1976),

reprinted in 1976 U.S.C.C.A.N. 2596, 2607. Its validity, consequently, depends on both

the requirements of the Antitrust Civil Process Act, 15 U.S.C. 1311-14, and the general

legal principles applicable to administrative subpoenas. See. e.g., <I>Associated

Container Transportation (Australia) Ltd. v. United States,</I> 705 F.2d 53, 60 (2d Cir.

1983); <I>United States v. Markwood,</I> 48 F.3d 969, 976 & n.11 (6th Cir. 1995);

<I>United States v. Witmer,</I> 835 F. Supp. 208, 220-21 (M.D. Pa. 1993), aff'd, 30 F.3d

1489 (3d Cir. 1994) (Table); Petition of Gold Bond Stamp Co., 221 F. Supp. 391, 395-96

(D. Mirm. 1963), aff'd, 325 F.2d 1018 (8th Cir. 1964) (per curiam). <P> An

administrative subpoena invokes "a power of inquisition . . . which is not derived from

the judicial function" but rather "is more analogous to the Grand Jury, which does not

depend on a case or controversy for power to get evidence." <I>United States v. Morton

Salt Co.,</I> 338 U.S. 632, 642 (1950). The agency accordingly may exercise its powers

"'merely on suspicion that the law is being violated, or even just because it wants

assurance that it is not."' In re McVane, 44 F.3d 1127, 1135 (2d Cir. 1995) (quoting

Morton Salt, 338 U.S. at 642-43). Microsoft's claim that its conduct is lawful

ultimately may prove correct. But the issuance of a CID to determine whether that is so

is entirely appropriate. <P> The government's CID, furthermore, need not, indeed

properly does not, focus on a specific narrowly-defined antitrust claim. Although a CID

must generally "state the nature of the conduct constituting the alleged antitrust

violation" and "the provision of law applicable thereto," 15 U.S.C. 1312(b)(1), [FN3]

"in the pre-complaint stage," the Division "is under no obligation to propound a

narrowly focused theory of a Possible future case."<I> FTC v. Texaco Inc.,</I> 555 F.2d

862, 874 (D.C. Cir.) (en banc) (emphasis in original), cert. denied, 431 U.S. 974

(1977); accord Invention Submission, 965 F.2d at 1090. Congress granted the Antitrust

Division "broad investigatory powers," Associated Container, 705 F.2d at 58 (emphasis

added), and it is "[o]nly when permitted to utilize [this] investigatory authority will

the Division be able to exercise its expertise to determine whether the antitrust laws

have been violated," id. at 60. <P> If the Division ultimately concludes that the facts

uncovered and applicable law do not warrant an enforcement action, it will not file a

complaint. But, because the very purpose of an investigation is to gather facts upon

which the decision to commence an enforcement action might be based, the conduct under

investigation need only fall "'within the authority of the agency."' In re McVane, 44

F.3d at 1135 (quoting Morton Salt, 338 U.S. at 652). See generally <I>FTC v. Invention

Submission Corp.,</I> 1991-1 Trade Cas. (CCH) 11 69,338 (D.D.C. 1991), aff'd, 965 F.2d

1086 (D.C. Cir. 1992), cert. denied, 113 S. Ct. 1255 (1993). In light of the breadth of

the Division's investigative authority, further inquiry by the Division would be

improper only if Microsoft established that there is no conceivable possibility that the

inclusion of MSN access software with Win95 on Microsoft's terms could violate the

antitrust laws, no matter what facts an investigation revealed. Microsoft, however, has

made no such showing. <P> <B>2.</B> It requires little analysis to show that the fact

and manner of Microsoft's inclusion of MSN access software in Win95 could, depending on

the evidence uncovered, violate the antitrust laws. As Microsoft has been advised, the

Division is investigating not only whether Microsoft's conduct violates section two of

the Sherman Act, as specified in the disputed CID, but also Sherman Act section one.

See. e.g., Letter from Bingaman to Neukom, June 4, 1995, Strike Mem. Ex. A; Letter from

Zastrow to Neukom, June 28, 1995, Hruska Aff. Ex. E.; CID No. 13025, Strike Mem. Ex. A.

The possibility of a section one violation arises because Microsoft's inclusion of the

MSN access software is imposed on the marketplace primarily through Microsoft's

contracts with OEMs, and these contracts supply the concerted action required by section

one. [FN4] Microsoft also is aware, see Letter from Bingaman to Neukom, June 4, 1995,

Strike Mem. Ex. A; Letter from Zastrow to Neukom, June 28, 1995, Hruska Aff. Ex. E, that

the Division is considering whether Microsoft's conduct violates 11 IV(E) of the consent

decree in <I>United States v. Microsoft, </I>1995- 1 Trade Cas. (CCH) 71,027 (D.C. Cir.

June 16, 1995), to which Microsoft agreed to be bound pending entry of the decree, see

59 Fed. Reg. 42,845, 42,849 (1994). [FN5] <P> In any event, the Court need not decide

whether the Department's communications with Microsoft provided adequate notice that the

CID's scope encompassed more than section 2, cf. e.g., <I>Finnell v. United States Dep't

of Justice,</I> 535 F. Supp. 410, 412 & n.1 (D. Kan. 1982) ("It has been held that a CID

with an insufficient description of the conduct constituting the antitrust violation

should not be set aside if the recipient of the CID had actual knowledge of the conduct

being investigated."); <I>Material Handling Institute, Inc. v. McLaren, </I>426 F.2d 90,

92 (3d Cir.) (CID interpreted in light of correspondence), cert. denied, 400 U.S. 826

(1970), because the CID is fully valid under section two alone. <P> This is not the time

or the place to set forth the theory of the government's complaint in a case that it has

not yet decided to bring. As courts consistently have recognized, such a requirement

would severely narrow prosecutorial discretion in a manner inconsistent with the

purposes of a grant of investigatory power. See, e.g., Texaco, 555 F.2d at 874 ("The

district court is not free to speculate about the possible charges that might be

included in a future complaint, and then to determine the relevance of the subpoena

requests by reference to those hypothetical charges. The court must not lose sight of

the fact that the agency is merely exercising its legitimate right to determine the

facts, and that a complaint may not, and need not, ever issue."); cf. Microsoft, 1995-1

Trade Cas. at 74,833 (refusing to construe the Tunney Act to allow inquiry into claims

that the government did not raise and explaining that to hold otherwise would

impermissibly allow "a district judge to assume the role of Attorney General"). <P> As

explained above, see supra p.12, all that the Division needs to show to establish that

its investigation is within its statutory authority, see In re McVane, 44 F.3d at 1135,

is that, depending on what the facts might indicate, there is some possible complaint,

based on any theory that may properly be argued. To avoid unnecessary discussion,

however, we analyze below a wholly conventional section two case in order to show that

Microsoft's conduct cannot be considered, without further investigation, beyond the

reach of the antitrust laws. <P> The Division's investigation might -- or might not --

find facts that support a charge that Microsoft is using its monopoly power in operating

systems [FN6] in an attempt to monopolize the market for on-line services. [FN7] "[I]t

is generally required that to demonstrate attempted monopolization a plaintiff must

prove (1) that the defendant has engaged in predatory or anticompetitive conduct with

(2) a specific intent to monopolize and (3) a dangerous probability of achieving

monopoly power." <I>Spectrum Sports. Inc. v. McQuillan,</I> 113 S. Ct. 884, 890-91

(1993). As for the first element, although Microsoft baldly asserts that "[t]he

inclusion of MSN access software as a feature of Windows 95 is in no sense predatory,"

Mem. at 12, the Division is entitled to assure itself that this is so. The Division

properly may consider, inter alia, whether the inclusion of MSN access software with

Win95 raises rivals' costs, "impair[s] competition in an unnecessarily restrictive way,"

or constitutes an "attempt[] to exclude rivals on some basis other than efficiency."

<I>Aspen Skiing Co. v. Aspen Highlands Skiing Corp., </I>472 U.S. 585, 605 (1985)

(internal quotations omitted). Until the Division obtains the necessary facts, it may

properly "refus[e] to speculate" as to what they might show. Associated Container, 705

F.2d at 59. And if the facts do show predatory or anticompetitive conduct, the second

element, specific intent to monopolize, may be inferred. See Spectrum Sports, 113 S. Ct.

at 892. <P> With respect to dangerous probability of success, Microsoft's arguments are

meritless. Market definition presents a quintessential question of fact, see. e.g.,

<I>Hayden Pub. Co. v. Cox Broadcasting Corp.,</I> 730 F.2d 64, 70 n.8 (2d Cir. 1984),

but the Division cannot obtain such facts unless it is permitted to investigate. The

precise parameters of the on-line market, and whether there are "obvious substitutes" to

on-line services that "are equal if not superior," Mem. at 10, remain to be determined.

Microsoft cannot avoid these questions with the simple assertion, see id. at 10-11, that

some of the information such services provide also may be acquired elsewhere. Courts

routinely find relevant markets even though particular goods or services available in

that market are separately available. See. e.g., <I>United States v. Philadelphia Nat'l

Bank,</I> 374 U.S. 321, 356-57 (1963) (finding commercial banking a distinct market

despite the availability elsewhere of particular services); <I>Thurman Industries. Inc.

v. Pay 'N Pak Stores. Inc., </I>875 F.2d 1369, 1377 (9th Cir. 1989) (discussing a

"cluster approach" to market definition that "is appropriate where the product package

is significantly different from, and appeals to buyers on a different basis from, the

individual products considered separately" (internal quotations omitted)); <I>Bon-Ton

Stores, Inc. v. MaY Dep't Stores Co.,</I> 881 F. Supp. 860, 867-75 (W.D.N.Y.1994)

(finding "traditional department stores" a distinct product market despite the

availability elsewhere of many products sold by such enterprises), amended, 1995-1 Trade

Cas. (CCH) 70,917 (W.D.N.Y. Mar. 6, 1995). Depending on the facts, that may or may not

be the case here. <P> Nor is it necessarily "fatal," Mem. at 11, to an attempted

monopolization claim that Microsoft currently lacks any subscribers to its on-line

service. A new entrant, depending on the facts, plainly could pose a dangerous

probability of monopolizing a market. No one supposes that Microsoft's share of the

on-line services market will remain at 0% for long after August 24 when millions of

copies of Win95 are sold. How fast that share will rise depends on many factors, which,

of course, the Division is investigating. See infra section II.B. To be sure, a low

market share, other things being equal, makes successful monopolization less likely, and

only unusual circumstances make plausible an attempted monopolization claim against a

new entrant. But the combination of Microsoft's monopoly power in PC-operating systems

with its proposed inclusion of MSN access software in Win95 certainly qualifies as

unusual. [FN8] <P> Finally, although Microsoft asserts that its entry into on-line

services will foster competition, see Mem. at 12, as the Supreme Court has noted, "[i]t

is sometimes difficult to distinguish robust competition from conduct with long-term

anticompetitive effects," Spectrum Sports, 113 S. Ct. at 892. The Division currently is

engaged in precisely this task of determining whether Microsoft's conduct is

procompetitive or, instead, threatens dominance that will be obtained through

anticompetitive means. <P> If the Division concludes that Microsoft's conduct violates

the antitrust laws and institutes an enforcement action, Microsoft will be entitled to

present its defenses. Cf. Associated Container, 705 F.2d at 59. But at this juncture,

Microsoft has failed to establish that its conduct could not violate the antitrust laws

under any set of facts. Microsoft's contention that its conduct is exempt from

investigation, consequently, is meritless. [FN9] <H4> B. The Materials Sought By The CID

Were Relevant</H4>  Microsoft disputes the relevance of the information sought in the

disputed CID. See Mem. at 8-9. This argument too lacks  merit.<P>  <B>1.</B> Information

sought by a CID must be "'reasonably relevant"' to the investigation. In re McVane, 44

F.3d at 1135 (quoting Morton Salt, 338 U.S. at 652). However, "[t]he standard for

judging relevancy in an investigatory proceedings is more relaxed than in an

adjudicatory one." Invention Submission, 965 F.2d at 1090. "The requested material . . .

need only be relevant to the investigation -- the boundary of which may be defined quite

generally," id. (emphasis in original), "or, put differently, 'not plainly incompetent

or irrelevant to any lawful purpose of the [agency],"' id. at 1089 (quoting <I>Endicott

Johnson Corp. v. Perkins,</I> 317 U.S. 501, 509 (1943)). Because relevance is

"interpreted . . . broadly," In re McVane, 44 F.3d at 1136, it is sufficient that the

items sought "'might have thrown light upon' the object of the investigation," id.

(quoting <I>United States v. Noall, </I>587 F.2d 123, 125 (2d Cir. 1978), cert. denied,

441 U.S. 923 (1979)). Indeed, "a showing of some possible relationship to the

investigation should be sufficient." <I>Finnell v. United States Dep't of Justice,</I>

535 F. Supp. 410, 414 (D. Kan. 1982). Moreover, "in light of the broad deference .

afford[ed] the investigating agency, it is essentially [Microsoft's] burden to show that

the information [sought] is irrelevant." Invention Submission, 965 F.2d at 1090. <P>

<B>2.</B> In attempting to meet its burden, Microsoft focuses only on four categories of

information. See Mem. 8-9. [FN10] All, however, are relevant to the likelihood of

successful monopolization of the on-line services market, a question plainly within the

scope of an investigation of possible attempted monopolization of that market. More

specifically, the categories of information Microsoft challenges are relevant to the

investigation in the following ways. <UL> <B>a.</B> Because the success of an on-line

service may depend on the attractiveness of its content and the availability of that

content elsewhere, relationships with independent content providers clearly are relevant

to the potential success of MSN and, therefore, to whether Microsoft has a dangerous

probability of monopolizing the on-line services market. Microsoft appears to concede

the relevance of facts concerning these relationships, for it carefully asserts that

"almost all of [these relationships] are non-exclusive." Mem. at 8 (emphasis in

original). Interrogatories 6(d) and 7(d) in the challenged CID specifically address the

substance of that assertion. Interrogatories 8 and 9(c) pertain to it as well. <P>

<B>b.</B> Microsoft's investment and cost-structure in its on-line service are relevant

to the likelihood of MSN's successfully achieving a monopoly. Obtaining these facts may

aid the Division in both assessing the likely success of MSN and the barriers to entry

that other potential new entrants might face, see <I>Kelco Disposal. Inc. v.

Browning-Ferris Indus.,</I> 845 F.2d 404, 408 (2d Cir. 1988), aff'd on other grounds,

492 U.S. 257 (1989); see also 2A Phillip E. Areeda et al., Antitrust Law 11 421a, at 63-

64 (1995) (economies of scale may constitute a barrier to entry). See generally

Department of Justice, Horizontal Merger Guidelines 3.0 to 3.3 (1992) (entry analysis).

<P> <B>c.</B> The CID's inquiries concerning Blackbird also pertain to content and

exclusivity. As Microsoft explains, Blackbird is a tool, or set of tools, for content

development. See Mem. at 8. Interrogatories 17 and 18 plainly address possible (or, it

may turn out upon investigation, impossible) ways in which Blackbird could influence

content exclusivity, which, as noted above, even Microsoft concedes to be relevant. <P>

<B>d.</B> Finally, Interrogatory 19, which addresses the use of information about its

competitors' customers that Microsoft might obtain through use of the on-line

registration feature in Win95, also bears upon the likelihood of successful

monopolization, for such information might facilitate targeted marketing, which in turn

may make successful monopolization of the on-line services market more likely.</ul> <P>

In sum, each item of information sought "'might have thrown light upon' the object of

the investigation." In re McVane, 44 F.3d at 1136 (quoting <I>United States v.

Noall,</I> 587 F.2d 123, 125 (2d Cir. 1978), cert. denied, 441 U.S. 923 (1979)). The law

requires no more. [FN11] <P> <B>II. Microsoft's Remaining Objections To The CID Are

Unsupported Or Should Be Resolved Through Negotiations With The Division; In The

Alternative, The Court Should Modify The CID To Require Microsoft To Respond In 10

Days</B> <P> Because a CID is entitled to a "presumption of regularity," Finnell, 535 F.

Supp. at Inc., 498 U.S. 292, 300-01 (1991) (same 411 (citing cases); cf. <I>United

States v. R. Enters.</I> with respect to a grand jury subpoena), it is Microsoft's

obligation to specify the particular features of the CID that it finds objectionable and

the reasons for objecting. Apart from the specific objections discussed above, Microsoft

has failed to do so. <P> Microsoft argued in its Petition that the CID should be set

aside because "[p]ortions of the June 21 CID are duplicative of requests for information

contained either in the June 4 CID or other information requests that the DOJ has

issued." Petition 11 44. But Microsoft failed to pursue this contention in its

Memorandum. Indeed, a single affidavit submitted by Microsoft asserts, and then only in

general terms, that portions of items requested by the June 5 CID, the validity of which

is not at issue here, previously were produced to the Division, see Vogt Aff. 11 27 (in

any event, there is no suggestion that the parties failed to resolve the problem through

negotiations). Microsoft, consequently, has not met its burden of demonstrating that CID

No. 13187 required production that was substantially and unreasonably duplicative of

prior requests. See Petition of Columbia Broadcasting Sys., Inc., 235 F. Supp. 684, 689

(S.D.N.Y. 1964) (petitioner, by merely asserting that the "bulk" of the data requested

previously had been supplied, failed to meet its burden of demonstrating that a

''significant number of the items requested in the C.I.D." previously had been

furnished); <I>Phoenix Bd. of Realtors, Inc. v. United States Dep't of Justice,</I> 521

F. Supp. 828, 832 (D. Ariz. 1981) (finding petitioner's general assertion that "the

information and documents requisitioned [were] 'essentially the same"' as a prior

request insufficient to establish that a CID was duplicative). [FN12] <P> Microsoft also

asserts that DOJ's "Accelerated Schedule for Compliance" is unreasonable. Mem. at 13. Of

course, the original return date specified in the disputed CID has long since past. The

Division, moreover, consistently has indicated its willingness to negotiate with

Microsoft in order to reach agreement on a production schedule that lessens Microsoft's

asserted burden, see Strike Mem. at 5-6, and stands ready today to enter into such

negotiations. Accordingly, the Court should order the parties to meet for the purposes

of negotiating in good faith a reasonable schedule for Microsoft's achieving compliance

with the demand. See Phoenix Board of Realtors, 521 F. Supp. at 832-33 (requiring the

parties to "attempt to resolve" petitioner's objections to the scope and burden of the

demand when the government "repeatedly indicated its willingness to negotiate with

petitioner"); <I>First Multiple Listing Serv., Inc. v. Shenefield, </I>1980-81 Trade

Cas. (CCH) 63,661, at 77,551 (N.D. Ga. Sept. 3, 1980) (directing counsel to meet "in a

good faith attempt to settle questions as to the burdensomeness of the CIDs"), vacated

without opinion, 638 F.2d 1233 (5th Cir. 1981) (Table). If those negotiations fail to

produce an agreement, the Court should entertain further motions at that time. <P> If

the Court concludes that Microsoft is no longer willing to enter into such good faith

negotiations, cf. Urowsky Aff. 10, it should modify the CID to specify a return date of

ten days from entry of the Court's judgment and otherwise deny the petition. Ten days is

a reasonable period of time in which to produce the items requested. This action,

moreover, preserves Microsoft's ability to negotiate with the government for additional

time within which to achieve compliance, should Microsoft choose to do so.<H3>

CONCLUSION </h3>Microsoft's Petition For An Order Setting Aside Civil Investigate Demand

No. 13187 should be denied. The parties should be directed to negotiate in good faith in

order to resolve the issue of when Microsoft must comply with the demand; in the

alternative, the Court should modify the CID to specify that compliance is required

within ten days of entry of the Court's judgment. <P> Respectfully submitted. <P> Anne

K. Bingaman   Assistant Attorney General <P> Joel I. Klein   Deputy Assistant Attorney

General <P> Ralph T. Giordano (RG0114)   Robert J. Zastrow, Jr.   David Seidman  Mark S.

Popofsky   Attorneys <P> United States Department of Justice   Antitrust Division   10th

& Pennsylvania Ave., N.W.   Washington D.C. 20008   (202) 514-2401 <P> July 13, 1995

<H3>END NOTES</H3> 1 The Division is still in the process of gathering all pertinent

facts pertaining to these issues, since Microsoft's agreements with OEMs are not yet

final. <P> 2 Although the permissible scope of CID provisions is governed by either the

grand jury subpoena standard or the civil discovery standard, see 15 U.S.C.

1312(c)(1)(A) & (B), the House report accompanying the 1976 amendments to the ACPA

[Antitrust Civil Process Act] reveals a preference for the less stringent grand jury

subpoena standard, 'tailored as it is to reflect the broader scope and less precise

nature of investigations."' <I>Associated Container Transportation (Australia) Ltd. v.

United States,</I> 705 F.2d 53, 58 (2d Cir. 1983) (quoting H.R. Rep. No. 1343, 94th

Cong., 2d Sess. 11 (1976), reprinted in 1976 U.S.C.C.A.N. 2956, 2606). Indeed, the ACPA

specifically provides that the civil discovery standard applies only to the extent that

it is "consistent with the provisions and purposes" of the Act. 15 U.S.C. 1312(c)(1)(B).

<P> 3 As a leading case explains: <P> [n]ecessarily . . . the nature of the conduct

[under investigation] must be stated in general terms. To insist upon too much

specificity with regard to the requirement of [section 1312] would defeat the purpose of

the Act, and an overly strict interpretation of this section would only breed litigation

and encourage everyone investigated to challenge the sufficiency of the notice. <P> Gold

Bond Stamp, 221 F. Supp. at 397. <P> 4 There is, of course, no need to specify have any

applicable theory of a 1 violation. We note, however, that Microsoft's Win95 contracts

with OEMs possibly could restrict access by other on-line services to installation by

OEMs of their access software or otherwise restrain trade between OEMs and the other

on-line services. It also is possible that Microsoft's contracts could be viewed as a

tying arrangement that impermissibly restricts choice by OEMs and tends to foreclose

opportunities for other on-line services. See supra p.9. Whether these possibilities

correspond to the facts is a proper matter for investigation. <P> 5 As in the case of a

potential 1 violation, there is no need to specify here any applicable theory of a

consent decree violation. We note, however, that if the contractual arrangement between

Microsoft and OEMs could be viewed as one in which the licensing of Win95 is conditioned

on the licensing of another product, the MSN access software, IV(E)(l) of the consent

decree would come into play. There also may be other ways in which a violation plausibly

could be argued. Whether these possibilities correspond to the facts is another proper

matter for investigation. <P> 6 As explained above, there is no need to discuss whether

the Division could or would bring a case alleging a 2 violation based on the simple fact

that Microsoft is using its monopoly position in one market to obtain a competitive

advantage in another market. See Griffith, 334 U.S. at 107; Berkey Photo, 603 F.2d at

275. We mention this basis for an enforcement action here, however, to avoid any

implication that, by not referring to that theory, the Division has somehow estopped

from bringing such a case. <P> 7 Microsoft also is aware that the Division is also

investigating whether the inclusion of MSN access software entrenches Microsoft's

operating system monopoly, see Letter from Bingaman to Neukom, June 4, 1995, Strike Mem.

Ex. A, in violation of 2. <P> 8 Although its value as precedent may be undercut by its

reliance on a Ninth Circuit doctrine repudiated in Spectrum Sports, 113 S. Ct. at

891-82, <I>H.J.. Inc. v. International Tel. & Tel. Corp., </I>86? F.2d 1531 (8th Cir.

1989), an attempted monopolization case, is nevertheless instructive. There, the

defendant had a 0% share of the relevant market at the time of the challenged conduct,

see id. at 1543, but by the time of trial it had eliminated its only competitor, see id.

at 1536. <P> Microsoft cites <I>United Air Lines. Inc. v. Austin Travel Corp.,</I> 867

F.2d 737 (2d Cir. 1989), in support of its assertion that MSN's present 0% market share

necessarily is fatal to any attempted monopolization claim, see Mem. at 11, but the case

cannot be read to stand for the proposition that a low market share in all circumstances

necessarily must defeat an attempted monopolization claim as a matter of law. Rather,

the court emphasized that it upheld the dismissal of the attempted monopolization claim

in that case based on the "evidence in the record." Id. at 742 (emphasis added).

Different facts could require a different analysis. "'It should be remembered that this

court has often announced that each case arising under the Sherman Act must be

determined upon the particular facts disclosed by the record, and that the opinions in

those cases must be read in the light of their facts and of a clear recognition of the

essential differences in the facts of those cases, and in the facts of any new case to

which the rule of earlier decisions is to be applied."' <I>Amateur Softball Ass'n of Am.

v. United States,</I> 467 F.2d 312, 316 (10th Cir. 1972) (quoting <I>Maple Flooring

Mfrs. Ass'n v. United States,</I> 268 U.S. 563, 579 (1925) (emphasis added by court)).

<P> 9 Microsoft also asserts that the Division's investigation should be pretermitted

because the Division did "nothing for months while Microsoft and hundreds of third

parties went forward with their plans." Mem. at 14. Although Microsoft makes no specific

allegation that the investigation was brought in bad faith, cf. Markwood, 48 F.3d at 978

(discussing the heavy burden required to sustain this defense to a CID), Microsoft

apparently wanted the Division to do something different between the time that it

received Microsoft's March 31, 1995, letter, Petition Ex. E, and the beginning of June.

See Mem. at 14. Of course, as Microsoft itself explains, see Petition 24-29, the

Division, during this period, was evaluating Microsoft's proposed acquisition of Intuit

Corp., an investigation that, on April 27, 1995, resulted in a lawsuit. Also during this

period, Microsoft claims, its lawyers were working 60-hour weeks responding to Division

information requests related to that investigation. See Vogt Aff. 26. <P> 10 Although

Microsoft generally states that it "could similarly critique the balance of the

interrogatories and document requests in the CID," Mem. at 9, it has not done so.

Because the burden is on Microsoft to establish that the information sought by the

Division is irrelevant, the Division addresses only the four categories of information

to which Microsoft specifically objects. Cf. <I>Phoenix Bd. of Realtors. Inc. v. United

States Dep't of Justice,</I> 521 F. Supp. 828, 832 (D. Ariz. 1981) (general objection

that a CID sought duplicative information insufficient). <P> 11 Microsoft's claim that

the DOJ is acting as "a Roving Commission," investigating merely "in Hopes that

Something Will Turn Up," Mem. at 7; accord Petition 11 39, is analytically and legally

flawed. When, as here, the investigation is within the Division's statutory authority,

the subject of that investigation is adequately described, and the material sought is

reasonably relevant, there can be no claim that the Division "is engaged in an

unlimited, exploratory investigation whose purposes and limits can be determined only as

it proceeds," H.R. Rep., supra, at 10, reprinted in 1976 U.S.C.C.A.N. 2956, 2605

(internal quotations omitted). See Gold Bond Stamp, 221 F. Supp. at 396. And, in light

of the purposes of a grant of investigatory power, a bare claim that the Division is

conducting a "fishing expedition" will not suffice. See Morton Salt, 338 U.S. at 642;

Gold Bond Stamp, 221 F. Supp. at 396. <P> 12 That Microsoft must "recanvas its files a

second time after having already searched them once" is not a sufficient basis for

establishing that a demand is unreasonable.<I> Sterling Drug. Inc. v. Clark,</I> 1968

Trade Cas. (CCH) 72,629, at 86,250 (S.D.N.Y. Nov. 14, 1968). <P>

