<html><TITLE>A Company's Trade Name and Its Use (and Abuse) on the Internet</TITLE><body

bgcolor=ffffff vlink=ff0000>LEONARD, RALSTON, STANTON, REMINGTON & DANKS <br>1000 Thomas

Jefferson Street, N.W. Suite 609<br> Washington, DC  20007<br> Telephone (202)

342-3342<H3>A Company's Trade Name and Its Use (and Abuse) on the

Internet</H3><H4>Introduction</H4>A recent newspaper headline announced, "Address for

Success: Internet Name Game, Individuals Snap Up Potentially ValuableCorporate E-Mail

IDs."  The article, on the front page of The Washington Post, noted that individuals

have registered "coke.com", "hertz.com", "mtv.com", "trump.com", "esquire.com",

"nasdaq.com", "windows.com" and other valuable corporate or business names.  Other

newspapers and magazines have published similar articles.  The companies that use these

trade names daily will now be prevented from using them on the Internet.  These

companies either will have to litigate the use of their name on the Internet or reach an

agreement with the individuals or companies that registered their names.  These are not

the alternatives a company wants to face when it is thinking of going

"on-line".<P>Today, the Internet is, by various accounts, the forerunner of the National

Information Infrastructure ("NII"), or the NII itself in embryonic form.  Whatever its

eventual status, the Internet currently is an important business tool and a significant

means of communicating with suppliers, customers, and potential customers. For the

almost twenty-three million users of the Internet, it can be the first place they

encounter a company or an individual representing a company.<P><H4>Identity of an

Organization on the Internet</H4>Organizations, including companies, are identified on

the Internet by a domain name, usually the name that they use in their everyday

business.  Electronic Mail ("email") addresses, World Wide Web("www") access sites, File

Transfer Protocol ("ftp") access and other Internet services require the use of this

name.  If someone else is using a company's name on the Internet, actual or potential

customers may turn to that entity for information, believing it represents the company. 

If that transaction does notwork out well, the customer may never look to the company

again. Companies must take affirmative steps to protect their trademarked names on the

Internet.<P>Even when a company discovers the use of its trade name on the Internet and

begins to work to retrieve the name, the damage to its business can occur very quickly. 

For example, the Coke and Pepsi of college test preparation courses are Kaplan Test Prep

and the Princeton Review, and they are just about as fiercely competitive as the soft

drink giants.  The Princeton Review created an Internet address with the name

"kaplan.com" and sent advertisements from this address to potential clients concerning

the benefits of the Princeton Review.  This is the equivalent of putting Pepsi

advertisements on the side of every can of Coca-Cola.  While this would be unthinkable

in the everyday business world, the rules of the road have not yet been written on the

information superhighway or the Internet.  In a just-finished arbitration proceeding,

Princeton Review was forced to turn over the "kaplan.com" address to Kaplan Test Prep,

but only after many potential customers of Kaplan were told by "kaplan.com" that

Princeton Review was the better service.<P>The United States has committed itself to

building an information superhighway or superhighways.  If not already on-line, most

American, and many foreign, companies -- including small businesses -- will participate

in the new electronic distribution system.  But the issue of trade names, service names

and trademarks on the Internet has only begun to be addressed.  An understanding of

Internet addresses and the importance these addresses play in accessing information and

services on the Internet is crucial for businesses that want to participate on the

information superhighway.<H4>What is an Internet Address</H4>An Internet address is

equivalent to a postal address: it tells the digital transmission system of the Internet

where to contact a person.  A typical Internet email address could resemble

jsmith@psych.umn.edu .  This address consists of four parts: (1) the name of the

individual; (2) the "name" of the computer or computer network on which the individual"s

computer is located (optional); (3) the "domain" within which the computer network

islocated; and (4) the "suffix" which indicates the type of organization.  The "domain

name" consists of the domain and suffix.  These are roughly equivalent to the person's

name, street address, city and state in a postal address.<P>In the address above, the

person"s name is "jsmith."  A standard Internet convention is to use the first initial

of a person's first name, and his or her last name as the email "name" (or sometimes the

first name and first initial of the last name). Thus Jane Smith becomes "jsmith" or

"smithj."  There is a limit of eight characters to the length of this first name.  A

longer name, such as Newt Gingrich, would be truncated in an email address to"ngingric"

or "gingricn."<P>The second part of the address is the name of the computer or computer

network on which the individual is located.  Some organizations have a large number of

computers or computer networks within their overall network.  Each of these computer

networks has a "name."  In the above example, the name of the computer network on which

Jane Smith is located is "psych" (these computers, especially at educational

institutions, tend to have whimsical names, not the more mundane name used in this

example). Smaller organizations may not maintain separate computer network names;

therefore, it is not unusual, but, in fact, rather commonas more small businesses begin

using the 'net, to see a name such as jsmith@smallbiz.com that contains no network

reference.<P>The third part of the address is the domain.  This is the name of the

organization under which the computer network is located.  In the above example, the

domain name is "umn.edu."  This stands for the University of Minnesota and it is the

primary designation oforganizations on the Internet.<P>The final part of the address is

the "tag" or suffix.  This is part of the domain name.  In the early days of  the

Internet, organizations on the Internet were usually educational institutions, private

research groups and government institutions. Most were within the United States.  These

original organizations were given a tag on the end of their domain name indicating type

of organization.  Educational institutions received the extension".edu", government

organizations received the suffix ".gov",commercial organizations were tagged ".com",

and so forth.  As the Internet grew and became international, these extensions gave way

to extensions identifying the country in which the organization was located.  Thus the

tag ".ch" indicates that the organizationis located in Switzerland, ".uk" is the United

Kingdom, ".fr" is France.  American organizations, for the most part, maintain the old

naming convention and do not append a ".us" to the end oftheir name.  There are a number

of variations on this naming scheme, including multiple tags (e.g.

"jsmith@mycorp.reston.va.us").<H4>What is So Important about a Domain Name</H4>As stated

above, domain names identify the organization to which a person is attached and are used

to access information services offered by a company.  While a domain name can be

anything, it most often is the name that the organization has adopted in the commercial

world.  While the University of Minnesota could have a domain name of "school.edu" or

"here.edu", there is no obvious connection between that name and the University.  To

help identify the organization to which a person is attached, and to help identify the

organization for use in providing other Internet services, an organization uses a domain

name that calls to mind the organization's primary business name.<P>This kind of

identification can be highly important to a business that conducts some of its affairs

on the Internet.  In the case ofthe hundreds or thousands of potential test preparation

course customers sent advertisements by "kaplan.com", many potential customers probably

believe that the Kaplan corporation, or a representative of the Kaplan corporation, told

them to go to its competitor, Princeton Review.  Imagine how customers, or potential

customers, would react if they received mail from an address witha company's name,

telling them to go to a competitor, or received inferior services from an organization

with the same name and became unhappy with those services.<P>Unfortunately, InterNIC,

the organization that assigns domain names on the Internet, does not have the capacity

or the competency to check for trade name conflicts in issuing domain names.  If the

domain name is not already assigned and there is a computer on the network that responds

to the name when "pinged" (sent a test message to see if a computer responds) InterNIC

will issue the domain name.<P>Recently, many people and organizations have begun to

register domain names that consist of the names of other companies.  Names such as

"hertz.com", "coke.com", "mcdonalds.com", "nasdaq.com" and others have been registered

by individuals other than the owners of those trademarked names.  While it is possible

that the owners of these trademarked names can sue for trademark infringement and win,

this solution is both time consuming and resource consuming. Furthermore, as this

particular scenario has not been litigated, it is not clear that the requisite elements

of trademark infringement could be found in cases involving an Internet address.<H4>What

Should Be Done</H4>Companies that plan or hope to participate in the NII or the Internet

and companies that merely want to protect their trademark from dilution should register

their domain name.  There are only two registration requirements: (1) the name cannot

already havebeen registered; and (2) there must be a computer attached to the Internet

that answers to that name.  There are companies that will register a domain name for

another company and supply a computer that will respond to the domain name when "pinged"

by InterNIC. The cost is minimal.<P>Companies that discover that their name is currently

being used as a domain name on the Internet must consider the possible dilution of their

trademark or trade name by this unchallenged, unauthorized use of their mark or name on

the Internet.  There are several options available to companies in this particular

situation.  We are prepared to assist you in exploring thes eoptions.  For further

information contact Michael J. Remington, Esq. or George Galt, Esq. at the law firm of

Leonard, Ralston,Stanton, Remington & Danks by telephone at (202) 342-3342 or by email

at mreming@us.net or ggalt@us.net.<H4>January 1995</H4><ul>The Intellectual Property

Group at Leonard, Ralston, Stanton,Remington  & Danks periodically prepares memoranda on

topics ofinterest to clients and colleagues.  The purpose of each memorandum is to

encourage discussion and debate.  We welcome critiques and comments.</ul><P><hr size=5>

