<h3 align=center><font color=42426F>SIMPLIFYING THE U.S. SENTANCING GUIDELINES </font></h3> <blockquote>


<H4>October 2 - October 23</H4>







<P>In cooperation with the United States Sentencing Commission, Counsel Connect will hold an online
hearing to generate advice on simplifying the U.S. Sentencing Guidelines. </P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>-- How can judges and courts apply uniform sentences while also making sentences proportionate to
the crimes?  </P>

<P>-- When should judges be able to depart from the guidelines? </P>

<P>-- To what extent should a defendant's role in the offense or other personal characteristics affect
a sentence? </P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>A copy of the transcript from this hearing will be filed with the U.S. Sentencing Commission to
assist in its ongoing guideline simplification effort.  Influence the rulemaking process! </P>

<P><B>Our distinguished hearing panel includes: </B></P>

<P>Alan Zegas (hearing officer), co-moderator of Counsel Connect's Criminal Law and Procedure  Forum </P>

<P>Gerald Shargel (hearing officer), co-moderator of Counsel Connect's Criminal Law and Procedure Forum</P>


<P>Fred Bennett, Catholic University of America Law School, DC  </P>

<P>Jim Bishop, U.S. Probation Office, FL</P>

<P>Joe Brown, U.S. Trustees Office, TN</P>

<P>Sam Buffone, Ropes & Gray, DC</P>

<P>Stanley Harris, U.S. District Court, DC</P>

<P>Tom Hutchison, Federal Public and Community Defenders, DC </P>

<P>Marc Mauer, The Sentencing Project, DC</P>

<P>Matthew Roland, U.S. Probation Office, NY </P>

<P>Joe Whitley, Kilpatrick & Cody, GA</P>

<P>Ronald Wright, Wake Forest University,  SC </P>

<P>David Yellin, Hofstra University Law School, NY </P>

<P>For more information call 800-569-4086, or e-mail us at <a href=mailto:joining@counsel.com>joining@counsel.com</a>. </P>








