<h3 align=center><font color=42426F>RUNNING THE 21ST CENTURY LAW LIBRARY</font></h3> <blockquote>
<H4>SEPTEMBER 30 - OCTOBER 21</H4>


<P>Is Managing Your Law Library More of a Challenge Than You'd Like? </P>



<P>Where Does the Internet Fit Into the Big Picture of Your Information
Resources? </P>

<P>What Is the Best Way to Deal with Upper Management?  </P>

 

<P>Whether you're a law librarian in a firm or in a corporate, government
or academic setting, or a solo or a small firm lawyer, you need to know
how to manage your information resources in the most efficient,
cost-effective way possible.   A library is no longer simply books and
periodicals!  And management, budgeting and access questions are
increasingly complicated. </P>

<P>Starting September 30 in the PRIVATE menu, a panel of experienced law
library professionals will gather online to discuss the timely issues in
library management and research.  For a registration fee of $75, we'll
permission you into this PRIVATE seminar to learn about such issues as: </P>


<P><B>I.  Information media</B></P>

<P>-- The ups and downs of print versus electronic resources </P>

<P>-- Is CR-ROM just another fad, or is it here to stay?   </P>

<P>-- Training issues</P>

<P>-- Working with the MIS department</P>

<P><B>II.  Marketing the Library</B></P>

<P>--  Communications tools, such as newsletter and special events </P>

<P>--  Working with firm management</P>

<P>-- Budget issues such as the impact of publishers consolidation on
pricing and purchasing options </P>

<P>-- The impact of the Internet</P>

<P><B>III.  Other topics</B></P>

<P>--  Vendor-neutral citation form</P>

<P>--  Summer associates, first-year associates </P>

<P>--  Space management</P>

<P>Why should you attend this seminar?  You'll learn the best ways to
handling these issues -- right  from your desk, day or night.   You'll
interact with the panelists and other attendees: ask a question, comment
on a statement, or pursue a particular issue to your satisfaction. </P>

<P><B>Panelists include:</B></P>

<P>Beth Blondin, Buckingham, Doolittle, Atlanta  </P>

<P>Guilliano Chicco, Manager, Legal Resources and Law Librarian,
Minneapolis </P>

<P>Betsy Klampert, White & Case, New York (co-moderator)  </P>

<P>Lynn Merring, Paul, Hastings, Cosa Mesa, CA (co-moderator)  </P>

<P>Amy Osborne, Lexington, Kentucky</P>

<P>Michael Roth, Head of Reference, Cravath, Swaine & Moore, New York</P>



<P>Michael Saint Onge, Coudert Brothers, San Francisco  </P>

<P>Ken Svengalis, Rhode Island Supreme Court, Providence  </P>

<P>Kathy Taggert, Leboeuf Lamb, Newark, New Jersey </P>

<P>You get all this -- useful, important information, and the wisdom and
experience of our panelists -- for just $75.  If you would like to
attend this program, send an email to Executive Editor Laurie Gordon or
just reply privately to this message.  If you have any questions about
this program, call 800-955-5291. </P>



