SEMINARS"></a></P>


<h3 align=center><font color=42426F>Faith and the Law:  An Online Symposium</font></h3> 
<blockquote>

<H4>August 5 - 25</H4>

<P>How do members of the legal profession -- lawyers, judges and law
professors -- reconcile their professional lives with their spiritual
lives?</P>

<P><I>Texas Tech Law Review </I> recently posed that question to a broad cross-section
of the legal community.  The resulting collection of essays -- sometimes
surprising, often profound, and always thought-provoking -- recently was
published in the Law Review's special Faith and the Law Symposium issue.</P>

<P>Counsel Connect, in cooperation with the <I>Texas Tech Law Review</I>, will
continue the discussion in a unique online symposium led by a panel of
prominent lawyers from a wide range of specialties and religious
traditions.  Among the issues they'll address in this program are:</P>
<UL>
<P><LI> How religious beliefs shape their approach to their legal work</P>

<P><LI> Whether their faith lives and professional lives are in harmony or
discord</P>

<P><LI> How faith has contributed to their career in times of crisis and
success.</P>
</UL>
<P>Join our more than 20 panelists, including Texas Supreme Court Justice Raul
A. Gonzalez, St. Mary's School of Law Dean Mary Aldave, and University of
Texas School of Law Profession Sanford Levinson, for this lively debate.  
We look forward to getting your input on this intellectually provocative
topic beginning August 5 in the Faith and the Law forum under Counsel
Connect Seminars.
</UL>
<P>Join the online panel in DISCUSS under Counsel Connect Seminars and Special
Events beginning July 24.  Please call our Customer Service Department if
you have any questions about this program. </P>





