<h3 align=center>Government 
Contracts: Doing Business With the Feds</h3></a>

<h4  align=center>April 15 - 30</h4>
<blockquote>

<P>On February 10, 1996, President Clinton signed into law the National Defense
Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 1996. The Act, an enormous piece of omnibus
legislation,  includes two distinct pieces of acquisition reform that will
shake  to the federal procurement process.</P>

<P>Join this  Counsel Connect Seminar to explore this
legislation's implications.  Our expert panel
will discuss its impact on government spending, high technology procurements, 
and companies doing business with the government.</P>
</blockquote>
<h4 align=center>Panelists include:</h4>
<ul><P>
<B>Jon W. Van Horne</B>, (Moderator) McDermott, Will & Emery 
<BR>


<B>Lee P. Curtis</B>, Howrey & Simon
<BR>
<B>Rand L. Allen</B>, Wiley, Rein & Fielding
<BR>
<B>Christopher R. Yukins</B>, Wiley, Rein & Fielding
<BR>
<B>Jim Taylor</B>, Editor, <I>National Contract Management Journal</I>
<BR>
<B>Lanny Elderkin</B>, Computer Sciences Corp.
<BR>

<B>John A. Howell</B>, Ross & Hardies
<BR>

<B>Marcia G. Madsen</B>, Morgan, Lewis & Bockius
<BR>
</P>


