<HEAD>
<TITLE>Opinions Unlimited: VersusLaw</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#ffffff>





<CENTER><IMG SRC=opunl.gif HEIGHT=80 WIDTH=400 BORDER=0></CENTER><BR>
<CENTER><IMG SRC=loisban.gif></CENTER>




<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE=+1>

The LOIS Law Library on the Web (www.pita.com) offers complete collections of federal and state law, including case law back to the 18th century, along with statutes, administrative codes, court rules, jury instructions and attorney general opinions. Twenty-seven state and federal law libraries are now in the LOIS collections and new jurisdictions are being added regularly.
<P>
Counsel Connect members have a free one-week tryout of the LOIS Law Library.
<P>
They also enjoy 10 percent discounts for the service when they subscribe through Opinions Unlimited.
<P>
Pricing for Counsel Connect members is as follows:
<P>
<IMG SRC=orangeba.gif align=left>
Daily access for $8 (with a limit of three days per year)
<P>
<IMG SRC=orangeba.gif align=left>
Unlimited weekly access for $90 (normally $100)
<P>
<IMG SRC=orangeba.gif align=left>
Unlimited yearly access to a member's state law plus their federal circuit cases and the U.S. Reports and U.S. Code is just $865 per year (normally $960)
<P>
<IMG SRC=orangeba.gif align=left>
Unlimited yearly access is $1,822 per year (normal price is $2,025)
<P>
<CENTER>The LOIS library currently contains:</CENTER>

<P>

Full state libraries with cases, statutes, acts, administrative regulations and more are available for Arkansas (cases from 1924), Colorado (1924), Connecticut (1899), Georgia (1939), Louisiana (1949), Massachusetts (1925), Missouri (1949), Nebraska (1949), North Carolina (1778), Oklahoma (1949), South Carolina (1900) and Wisconsin (1939). Federal databases now on LOIS include the U.S. Supreme Court, with opinions back to 1899, all 13 federal circuits back to 1971, and the U.S. Code.
<P>
Among the libraries LOIS will offer soon are California, Florida, Illinois,    Indiana, Kansas, Michigan, New Hampshire, New Jersey, Rhode Island, Virginia and the Code of Federal Regulations. All 50 states are expected  to become available in the next 18 months. LOIS databases are updated within 72 hours of a law's release. U.S. Supreme Court opinions are fully hyperlinked to cases and statutes within two hours of their issue.
<P>

<CENTER><A HREF=http://www.counsel.com/opinions/signup.html>Register or Renew your subscription</A></CENTER><BR>
<CENTER><A HREF=http://www.counsel.com/opinions/signup.html><IMG SRC=register.gif align=center BORDER=0 HEIGHT=100 WIDTH=100 ALT="Sign Up" ALIGN=middle></A></CENTER><BR>

<P>

</FONT>


</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


