<HEAD>
<TITLE>Counsel Quote - Counsel Canvass</TITLE>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="paper.gif">
<p align=center><img src="/counselquote/canvasheader.gif" width=600 height=100 alt="COUNSEL CANVAS"></P>
<HR>
<center><A HREF="/images/cquotenavbar.map"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/counselquote/cquotenavbar.gif" ISMAP></A></center>
<HR>

<BLOCKQUOTE><H2 align=center><font color=ff0000>A Fine Line: Ethics and Morals</font></H2>


<P>What do you do if your client is running a sweatshop? In the Hofstra
Legal Ethics Seminar, which took place in March and April, Counsel
Connect members and some of the foremost voices in the legal ethics
community debated the ethical and moral obligations of attorneys. In a
thread titled "Code of Ethics," members discussed what an attorney
should do when he or she finds a client's actions immoral. </P>

<P>From March 22 to June 17, 1996, Counsel Connect surveyed members on
whether a lawyer can ethically drop a client who doesn't measure up to
the attorney's moral standards. We received 154 responses. Eighty-one
percent of the responses said, yes, an attorney could drop the client.
Nineteen percent said he or she could not ethically drop the client.</P>

<H4>Survey Question and Answers</H4>

<P>Can a lawyer ethically drop a client who doesn't measure up to the
attorney's moral standards?</P>

<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Yes: 124 responses (81 percent)</P>

<P>No: 30 responses (19 percent)</P></BLOCKQUOTE>


</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
</HTML>



</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT07-B36-99</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA022-000238-B024-32</DOCOLDNO>
