<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Counsel Quote - Counsel Canvass</TITLE>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="paper.gif">
<p align=center><img src="/counselquote/canvasheader.gif" width=600 height=100 alt="COUNSEL CANVAS"></P>
<HR>
<center><A HREF="/images/cquotenavbar.map"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/counselquote/cquotenavbar.gif" ISMAP></A></center>
<HR>

<BLOCKQUOTE><H2 align=center><font color=ff0000>Would You Know it if You Saw It?</font></H2>

</P>

<P>A kiss is just a kiss -- or is it?</P>

<P>Most people would recognize sexual harassment in its most blatant form. But
sexual harassment based on a hostile environment, increasingly the basis of
litigation, is harder to define.  </P>

<P>From March 8 to May 15, Counsel Connect asked members to look at three
hypothetical situations and decide whether sexual harassment had occurred.
No consensus emerged: 71 percent of responses said the first hypothetical
described sexual harassment, 53 percent of responses said the second
hypothetical described sexual harassment, and 25 percent of responses said
the third hypothetical described harassment.</P>

<H4>The Survey and Responses:</H4>

<P>1) Buck, a male associate in the patent section of a major law firm, is
asked out for a drink after work by Hillary, a female managing partner in
the litigation section. She's been eyeing Buck--and is pleased that he
doesn't work in her department. </P>

<P>Buck agrees to the date because Hillary is a partner, and Buck wants to get
promoted to the litigation panel. As they continue drinking at the bar,
Hillary occasionally touches Buck's thigh, and after five drinks, she
propositions him. He reluctantly agrees (he's also smashed). </P>

<P>Hillary later learns from Donna, another partner, that that Buck has "told
all" about the incident. Mortified, she says to Donna, "It's probably best
Buck not be put in litigation--because it would be uncomfortable for me to
supervise him." Donna agrees. </P>

<P>Despite Buck's assessment that his work seemed fine, he is not made
partner, nor was his request to move to litigation ever approved. Is this
sexual harassment?</P>

<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Yes: 139 responses (71 percent)</P>

<P>No: 58 responses (29 percent)</P></BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><B>2)</B> Solo practitioner Bill has three female secretaries. He requires them to
wear skirts or dresses (no pants) because he thinks women should show off
their legs, but he has not made any comments to the women about their legs.</P>


<P>Bill keeps the thermostat at 60 degrees because he believes you get more
productivity out of women when the office is kept cool. He also believes
you get better productivity from women if you yell at them and slam the
door. </P>

<P>Bill does not yell at the male law clerk. The male law clerk wears pants.</P>

<P>Is this sexual harassment?</P>

<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Yes: 105 responses (53 percent)</P>

<P>No: 92 responses (47 percent)</P></BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><B>3)</B> Candy has just finished secretarial school and starts a new job with the
law department of a major bank. Candy's direct supervisor is Lori, a
secretary who has been with the bank for 15 years. </P>

<P>Candy, wanting to get promoted, asks Jim, the general counsel and senior
vice president, out for a date. The dating between Jim and Candy is obvious
to fellow employees and lasts several months. Jim frequently leaves
messages of a sexual nature on Candy's e-mail; Lori sees one in passing and
finds it to be offensive. </P>

<P>After three months, Candy is promoted by Jim to the job classification of
legal assistant, a position that pays more than Lori receives as senior
secretary.</P>

<P>Is this sexual harassment?</P>

<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Yes: 49 responses (25 percent)</P>

<P>No: 148 responses (75 percent)</P></BLOCKQUOTE>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
