<TITLE>Baker  & McKenzie
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Antitrust</H2>
<H3>Baker  & McKenzie
</H3>

</CENTER>
<B><CENTER>Chicago:</B> One Prudential Plaza,  130 East Randolph Drive,  Chicago,  IL 60601<BR>
Tel 312-861-8000  <B>*</B>  Fax 312-861-2898<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> 815 Connecticut Avenue,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20006<BR>
Tel 202-452-7000  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-452-7074<BR>
<B>Amsterdam:</B> Leidseplein 29,  1017 PS Amsterdam,  P.O. Box 19720, <BR>
1000 GS Amsterdam,  The Netherlands<BR>
Tel 31-20-55-17-555  <B>*</B>  Fax 31-20-62-67-949<BR>
<B>Brussels:</B> 40 Boulevard du R &#232;gent-Regentlaan 40,  Fifth Floor,  1000 Brussels,  Belgium<BR>
Tel 32-2-506-36-11  <B>*</B>  Fax 32-2-511-62-80<BR>
<B>Frankfurt:</B> Bethmannstrasse 50-54,  D-60311 Frankfurt/Main,  Germany<BR>
Tel 49-69-299-080  <B>*</B>  Fax 49-69-299-08108<BR>
<B>London: </B>100 New Bridge Street,  London EC4V 6JA,  England<BR>
Tel 44-71-919-1000  <B>*</B>  Fax 44-71-919-1999<BR>
<B>Paris:</B> 32 Avenue Kl &#232;ber,  75116 Paris,  France<BR>
Tel 33-1-44-17-53-00  <B>*</B>  Fax 33-1-44-17-45-75<BR>
<B>Sydney: </B>A.M.P. Centre,  50 Bridge Street,  Sydney,  N.S.W. 2000,  Australia<BR>
Tel 61-2-225-0200  <B>*</B>  Fax 61-2-223-7711<BR>
<B>Toronto:</B> 112 Adelaide Street East,  Toronto,  Ontario M5C 1K9,  Canada<BR>
Tel 416-863-1221  <B>*</B>  Fax 416-863-6275<BR>
<BR>
1, 700 lawyers  <B>*</B>  75 lawyers in the Antitrust Practice Area<BR>
<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profile in the following other directory:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/baker.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P><B>B</B>aker  & McKenzie represents domestic and international clients in antitrust proceedings in the United States and other jurisdictions,  including Australia,  Canada,  the European Union,  France,  Italy,  Germany,  the Netherlands,  Spain,  and the United Kingdom. This representation encompasses multinational transactions (e.g.,  acquisitions) as well as criminal prosecutions and civil antitrust proceedings involving market dominance,  restrictive distribution,  pricing,  and licensing of intellectual property. The firm also assists clients in developing antitrust compliance programs and advises them on the antitrust implications of joint ventures,  franchising agreements,  and other complex transactions. Our attorneys have substantial government antitrust experience,  and include a former commissioner of the Federal Trade Commission and a former principal legal advisor to the European Commission.
<P><BR><P>The firm's international scope allows it to represent clients in connection with transactions under antitrust review in several different jurisdictions. For example,  the firm has successfully represented clients in several multijurisdiction merger investigations involving such industries as writing instruments,  plating,  and synthetic rubber. Additionally,  the firm recently completed preparation of an extensive U.S. antitrust compliance program for a major foreign-based trade association. Also,  the firm advises the Dutch government in connection with its revision of Dutch antitrust legislation.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>David A. Clanton</B> (<I>Washington; 202-452-7014</I>) Mr. Clanton,  a former commissioner of the Federal Trade Commission,  coordinates the firm's antitrust practice in the United States. He advises and represents clients on antitrust matters before the FTC,  the Justice Department's Antitrust Division,  and state and federal courts.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David J. Laing</B> (<I>Washington; 202-452-7023</I>) Mr. Laing specializes in all types of antitrust litigation. He joined the firm in 1994 after spending several years at the Antitrust Division litigating merger and criminal cases.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Carla Hamburger</B> (<I>Amsterdam; 31-20-55-17-437</I>) Ms. Hamburger chairs the Antitrust and Trade Law Department in the firm's Amsterdam office. She practices in all areas of EU and Dutch antitrust law,  including representation of clients before the European Commission,  the Court of First Instance of the EC,  and the European Court of Justice.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jacques H. J. Bourgeois</B> (<I>Brussels; 32-2-506-36-11</I>) Mr. Bourgeois is a former principal legal advisor to the European Commission. He participated in drafting the EU Merger Control Regulation and concentrates on advising and representing clients in connection with EU matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Joachim Treeck</B> (<I>Frankfurt; 49-69-299-080</I>) Mr. Treeck heads the Antitrust Group in the Firm's Frankfurt Office. The Group practices in all areas of EU and German antitrust law with specific emphasis on merger control,  restrictive practices (including criminal and administrative proceedings),  and distribution and licensing arrangements.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Lynda Martin Alegi</B> (<I>London; 44-71-919-1000</I>) Ms. Alegi chairs the Competition and Trade Law Department in the London office. Her practice focuses on U.K. and European competition law,  with emphasis on distribution,  franchising,  merger control,  joint ventures,  and trade regulation.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Monique P. Nion</B> (<I>Paris; 33-1-44-17-53-00</I>) Ms. Nion chairs the Antitrust and Trade Law Department in the Paris office. The group practices in all areas of EU and French antitrust law with specific emphasis on merger control,  restrictive practices,  and distribution and licensing arrangements.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>S. Janice McAuley</B> (<I>Toronto; 416-865-6905</I>) Ms. McAuley advises clients on compliance with Canada's Competition Act with respect to both criminal matters and reviewable trade practices,  including merger issues.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
