<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Berger  & Montague,  P.C.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Antitrust</H2>
<H3>Berger  & Montague,  P.C.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<B><CENTER>Philadelphia:</B> 1622 Locust Street,  Philadelphia,  PA 19103-6365<BR>
Tel 215-875-3000  <B>*</B>  Fax 215-875-4603<BR>
<BR>
59 lawyers  <B>*</B>  12 lawyers practicing in antitrust<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>B</B>erger  & Montague was founded in 1970 by David Berger to concentrate on the representation of plaintiffs in a series of antitrust actions,  including the landmark electrical equipment price-fixing cases. Since the firm's creation,  Berger  & Montague's lawyers have represented both plaintiffs and defendants in antitrust actions,  the latter in both civil and criminal proceedings. The firm has recovered well over $1 billion for its clients as plaintiffs in both class and individual antitrust actions,  and has obtained successful results for corporate and individual defendants in both criminal and civil antitrust matters,  including class and individual cases. Among those cases was <I>Bogosian </I>v.<I> Gulf Oil Corp</I>.,  which alleged horizontal and vertical restraints among 15 oil companies,  and resulted in substantial monetary settlements plus ground-breaking injunctive relief.
<P><BR><P>As a firm devoted almost exclusively to litigation,  and with its roots solidly in contingent fee business work,  Berger  & Montague has long been accustomed to being paid solely for results. Working with a client from the inception of a new matter,  Berger  & Montague structures its own incentives so that it profits by obtaining the best outcome for its clients.<BR><P>Berger  & Montague's lawyers participated on behalf of plaintiffs in the first modern class antitrust actions,  filed and successfully pressed even before the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure were amended in 1967 to codify the mechanisms applied in these cases. Berger  & Montague's lawyers have displayed the same creativity in representing defendants in both civil and criminal antitrust matters. The firm's lawyers have represented clients in antitrust matters before Congress,  state and federal courts and agencies throughout the United States,  and in tribunals in other nations.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>David Berger</B> (<I>215-875-3030</I>),  who specializes in complex litigation,  is the founding member of the law firm. Mr. Berger headed the first antitrust class action and for over 30 years has successfully litigated numerous antitrust cases,  one of which was the famous Bogosian case discussed above. Mr. Berger,  who is a former city solicitor for the City of Philadelphia and is a life member of the American Law Institute and the Judicial Conference of the Third Circuit Court of Appeals,  was appointed by the U.S. Supreme Court and served on the committee which drafted the Federal Rules of Evidence. He is a member of the Board of Overseers of the University of Pennsylvania Law School. The university has established the David Berger Chair of Law.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>H. Laddie Montague,  Jr.</B> (<I>215-875-3010</I>),  who has been practicing antitrust law for more than 30 years,  is the chairman of the firm's antitrust department. He has tried numerous complex antitrust class actions representing the plaintiff class,  including <I>In re Master Key Antitrust Litigation</I> and <I>In re Corrugated Container Antitrust Litigation</I>. Mr. Montague has been lead or co-lead counsel in numerous class action antitrust cases,  including <I>Bogosian </I>v.<I> Gulf Oil Corp.</I>,  and <I>In re Infant Formula Antitrust Litigation</I>,  which resulted in settlements of more than $120 million. He recently was one of the trial counsel for plaintiffs in the <I>Exxon Valdez</I> oil spill trial (District of Alaska). Mr. Montague,  who has testified before committees of the U.S. Senate and House on antitrust and RICO bills and lectured at seminars sponsored by Columbia University and Temple University's schools of law,  is a trustee of Dickinson School of Law.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Merrill G. Davidoff</B> (<I>215-875-3084</I>) has tried numerous antitrust and trade regulation cases,  representing both plaintiffs and defendants. He defended several corporations in a series of individual and class actions brought against them by former franchisees and dealers,  and obtained successful judgments or settlements in all of these cases. In proceedings against the world's largest hops brokers,  Mr. Davidoff successfully represented the brokers in a government proceeding and then favorably resolved a series of class and individual civil actions in which they were defendants. Mr. Davidoff represented a Canadian communications firm in a landmark Canadian case which resulted in the first decision breaking Bell Canada's monopoly over telecommunications equipment. He has lectured frequently on antitrust and other litigation topics,  and served on the ABA subcommittee which revised the standard `Antitrust Civil Jury Instructions' in 1985.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Howard I. Langer</B> (<I>215-875-3044</I>) specializes in complex litigation. He has tried several antitrust and other complex commercial cases throughout the country,  both as lead trial counsel and as a member of trial teams in complex multidistrict litigation. Most recently,  he was responsible for briefing by private plaintiffs in the U.S. Supreme Court in <I>Hartford Fire Insurance Co. </I>v. <I>California</I>,  a case involving the construction of the insurance industry exemption from the antitrust laws. Mr. Langer is a member of the American Law Institute and graduated from the University of Pennsylvania Law School in 1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Martin I. Twersky</B> (<I>215-875-3054</I>) has practiced antitrust law and complex litigation at Berger  & Montague for 15 years,  during which he has successfully represented numerous plaintiffs and defendants in both individual and class actions pending in state and federal courts. His practice has involved litigation in the oil and gas,  banking,  airline,  waste hauling,  agricultural chemicals and other regulated industries. He is a graduate of the University of Pennsylvania Law School.</UL><BR>
<BR>
<P>In addition,  Berger  & Montague has a corps of other senior lawyers,  associates,  and support staff experienced in the intricacies of complex antitrust matters.



</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
