<HEAD>
<TITLE>Blecher  & Collins
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Antitrust</H2>
<H3>Blecher  & Collins
</H3>

</CENTER>
<B><CENTER>Los Angeles:</B> 611 West Sixth Street,  Suite 2000,  Los Angeles,  CA 90017<BR>
Tel 213-622-4222  <B>*</B>  Fax 213-622-1656<BR>
<BR>
10 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers in antitrust practice<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>F</B>ounded in 1971,  Blecher  & Collins engages in complex business litigation,  with emphasis on antitrust. The firm's exceptional expertise in the antitrust field has resulted in many precedent-setting decisions in the U.S. Supreme Court and several courts of appeal. Blecher  & Collins has had extensive trial experience in federal and state courts on behalf of both plaintiff and defendant for a broad spectrum of domestic and international clients. Our clients have ranged from Fortune 500 companies to small and medium-sized businesses,  as well as individuals. The firm has handled cases against the U.S. Department of Justice,  and such companies as ARCO,  AT &T,  the NFL,  the NBA,  3M and HBO. Small by design,  Blecher  & Collins consists of a team of highly skilled attorneys experienced in all aspects of antitrust litigation. The firm strives to provide a high degree of flexibility and responsiveness to the needs of clients,  working closely with them from the initial decisions on staffing and budget through every stage of the case from discovery to trial or settlement. Costs are carefully controlled.
<P><BR><BR>
Representative antitrust litigation matters include:<BR><UL><BR><P><LI> Representing Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum Commission in connection with the relocation of the Raiders football team to Los Angeles.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> Representing Handgards,  Inc. in a successful antitrust claim against a bad faith patent infringement suit.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> Defending Suyfy Enterprises against government charges of monopolization of movie theaters in Las Vegas.<BR>
<BR><BR></UL>
<LI><B>Maxwell M. Blecher</B> is a prominent antitrust trial attorney who has litigated significant cases in every court,  including the U.S. Supreme Court. Renowned for his expertise in the antitrust field,  Mr. Blecher has been invited to testify before Congressional hearings and has served on the National Commission for the Review of Antitrust Laws and Procedures. Mr. Blecher is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers,  a member of the American Board of Trial Advocates,  and was a Ninth Circuit Judicial Delegate. He has authored numerous articles on antitrust and civil practice and litigation. He frequently lectures at programs sponsored by the American Bar Association and the Practising Law Institute,  as well as federal,  state and local bar associations. University of Southern California,  LL.B.,  1955.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Douglas H. Altschuler</B> has experience in civil litigation,  including antitrust,  class actions,  and general business. University of Arizona College of Law,  J.D.,  1984.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John E. Andrews</B> has broad experience in civil litigation specializing in antitrust law and intellectual property. Albany Law School,  J.D.,  1982.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Florence F. Cameron</B> has handled civil litigation cases including antitrust,  intellectual property,  entertainment,  and complex business litigation. She served as a law clerk to Judge Carl McGowan,  U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit. Columbia Law School,  J.D.,  1986.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Harold R. Collins,  Jr.</B> has practiced in the areas of antitrust and complex business litigation since 1964. He has represented clients in a wide variety of industries throughout the United States. University of California at Berkeley,  Hastings College of Law,  J.D.,  1964.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Ralph C. Hofer</B> has defended antitrust,  breach of contract,  business tort,  securities,  and contract claims. A former assistant U.S. attorney on the Presidential Task Force on Narcotics Enforcement,  Mr. Hofer is an adjunct professor of antitrust law at Loyola Law School. University of Southern California,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William C. Hsu</B> has represented clients successfully against defendants such as HBO,  the Recording Industry Association of America,  and 3M. University of California at Los Angeles,  J.D.,  1982.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James R. Noblin</B> has an extensive background in antitrust law,  civil litigation and intellectual property law. Mr. Noblin was a clerk to Judge William A. Norris,  U.S. Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit. Harvard University,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1983.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Donald R. Pepperman</B> specializes in antitrust,  intellectual property and complex business litigation,  involving industries such as biotechnology,  computer hardware and software,  transportation,  and electronic components. Mr. Pepperman has litigated against companies including AT &T,  Sharp Corporation,  and Dollar Rent-A-Car. Whittier College School of Law,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1983.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Alicia G. Rosenberg</B> has litigation and appellate experience in the areas of antitrust,  unfair competition,  and business torts. Ms. Rosenberg has represented clients in the petroleum,  computer,  entertainment,  sports and health care industries. She was managing editor of the <I>UCLA Law Review</I>. University of California at Los Angeles,  J.D.,  1985.</UL><BR>


</UL></BODY>
