<CENTER>
<H2>Antitrust</H2>
<H3>Collier,  Shannon, Rill  & Scott
</H3>

</CENTER>
<B><CENTER>Washington:</B> 3050 K Street,  N.W.,  Suite 400,  Washington,  DC 20007<BR>
Tel 202-342-8400  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-338-5534<BR>
<BR>
85 lawyers  <B>*</B>  30 lawyers in Antitrust and Trade Regulation<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/collier.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/collier.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>C</B>ollier,  Shannon,  Rill  & Scott,  founded in 1956 in Washington,  D.C.,  today has approximately 85 lawyers offering counsel in five core practice areas. Our attorneys are highly specialized in their fields of practice. A number have served at the highest level in government and private industry. The Firm's client base includes domestic and international corporations,  including numerous Fortune 500 corporations engaged in manufacturing,  communications,  finance,  agriculture,  health care,  energy,  and services.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Antitrust and Trade Regulation Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>For more than 35 years the lawyers at Collier,  Shannon,  Rill  & Scott have been on the cutting edge of antitrust and trade regulation. Practicing in Washington,  D.C. enables us to maintain the freshness of thinking,  familiarity with government enforcement trends,  and frequent contact with decisionmakers in the federal agencies. We are one of the largest antitrust practices in the U.S.,  boasting a breadth and depth of expertise and experience second to none,  and unmatched in a law firm our size.<BR><P>With our substantial experience before the Department of Justice and the Federal Trade Commission,  in federal and state courts,  with committees and members of Congress,  and with numerous state attorneys general,  we have the expertise to handle problems in every area of antitrust and trade regulation law. We counsel,  litigate,  advocate,  speak,  and write in areas of the law as diverse as mergers and acquisitions,  joint ventures,  vertical and horizontal distribution questions,  deceptive advertising and trade practices,  criminal price-fixing and market allocation conspiracies,  and Robinson-Patman pricing. Our clients have included 3M,  Allegheny Ludlum,  American Stores,  ConAgra,  Cooper Industries,  CSX,  General Mills,  GTE,  International Paper,  Mobil Chemical,  Olin,  RJR,  Schering-Plough,  and Thomson Consumer Electronics.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>James F. Rill</B> served as assistant attorney general,  Antitrust Division,  Department of Justice (1989-1992),  and was responsible for the publication of the joint Department of Justice/FTC Horizontal Merger Guidelines 1992. Mr. Rill is heavily involved in domestic and international mergers,  acquisitions and strategic alliances,  and complex antitrust litigation. Harvard University,  LL.B.,  1959.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James R. Loftis III</B> has been an officer of the ABA Antitrust Section since 1985 and provides counseling and litigation experience on all aspects of antitrust and consumer protection,  with particular expertise in mergers,  telecommunications issues,  and criminal antitrust litigation. George Washington University,  J.D.,  1968.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Sean F. X. Boland</B> has broad experience in all aspects of mergers and acquisitions,  joint venture transactions,  criminal grand jury investigations,  civil litigation,  and distribution practices. Georgetown University,  J.D.,  1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William C. MacLeod</B> served as director of the Bureau of Consumer Protection of the Federal Trade Commission and has an extensive practice involving advertising,  consumer protection,  and unfair competition. University of Miami,  J.D.,  1979.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Timothy J. Muris</B> was formerly associate director of the OMB,  1985-1988,  and director of the FTC's Bureau of Competition,  1983-1985,  and Bureau of Consumer Protection,  1981-1983. University of California,  J.D.,  1974.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Judith L. Oldham</B> provides counsel in connection with FTC and state investigations of national advertising campaigns,  consumer perception evidence,  and ad substantiation requirements. Georgetown University,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John B. Williams</B> has focused his litigation practice on matters involving antitrust and intellectual property. He has represented both plaintiffs and defendants and has won several substantial judgments. Catholic University,  J.D.,  1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Christopher J. MacAvoy</B> is an experienced antitrust litigator who also provides specialized counseling in distribution practices and pricing and the representation of trade associations. Georgetown University,  J.D.,  1982.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William A. Henry</B> has been heavily involved in planning and implementing innovative corporate alliances with special expertise in health care industries. Columbia University,  J.D.,  1984.<BR>
<BR>
