<TITLE>Fried,  Frank,  Harris,  Shriver  & Jacobson
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Antitrust</H2>
<H3>Fried,  Frank,  Harris,  Shriver  & Jacobson
</H3>

</CENTER>
<B><CENTER>New York:</B> One New York Plaza,  New York,  NY 10004<BR>
Tel 212-859-8000  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-859-4000<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Washington,  D.C.,  Los Angeles,  London<BR>
<BR>
357 lawyers  <B>*</B>  12 lawyers in Antitrust Practice Group<BR>
<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/fried.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/fried.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/fried.html"> White Collar Crime</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P><B>F</B>ried Frank is a national law firm with a practice that is international in scope,  having its principal office in New York and other offices in Washington,  D.C.,  Los Angeles and London. The Firm's more than 350 attorneys represent businesses and individuals in complex matters,  many of them in the forefront of financial and legal developments.<BR>
<P>Fried Frank attorneys are involved in all aspects of litigation involving business competition in the marketplace. They advise on and litigate antitrust,  unfair competition,  and consumer protection matters,  and also appear before government agencies in connection with these matters. The practice encompasses the full range of trade regulation issues,  including price-fixing,  monopolization,  tying,  exclusive dealing,  resale price maintenance and price discrimination,  franchise litigation,  false advertising claims,  and unfair competition matters.<BR>
<P>Our attorneys have a proven track record litigating cases of this type. By way of example,  we successfully moved to terminate the decades-old consent decree restricting the operations of Loews Theatres and the order restricting the operations of Tri-Star Pictures,  the first time that a movie industry decree had been terminated. We also frequently litigate trade practice issues,  such as dealer termination suits for the U.S. distributor of Mont Blanc pens,  as well as false advertising claims brought by state agencies,  the FTC,  and private parties. And we regularly appear before the Federal Trade Commission and Department of Justice in connection with mergers governed by the Hart-Scott-Rodino Act. Examples of transactions in which we successfully represented clients in their merger activities include General Instrument in the sale of its defense business to Litton Industries,  Connaught Laboratories in its vaccine joint venture with Merck,  and Sundstrand in its acquisition of Westinghouse's Electrical Systems Division. Among other major antitrust,  unfair competition,  and consumer protection clients are Arthur Andersen,  Columbia Pictures,  A.B. Electrolux,  GKN,  Hilti,  Hunter Douglas,  Ivaco,  L.A. Gear,  McCrory,  National Service Industries,  Pullman,  Sears Roebuck,  Televisa,  S.A.,  and 3M.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Linda R. Blumkin</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8085</I>) Linda Blumkin's practice runs the gamut of antitrust issues,  with special emphasis on mergers and acquisitions (including the premerger notification rules) and compliance matters. From 1977-1979,  she served as an Assistant Director,  Bureau of Competition,  Federal Trade Commission. She co-edited <I>Corporate Sentencing Guidelines: Compliance and Mitigation</I>. She is on the Board of Editors of the <I>Health Care Antitrust Manual</I>. Chair,  Clayton Act Committee,  ABA Antitrust Section (1991-1992). Barnard College,  A.B.,  <I>cum laude, </I> Phi Beta Kappa,  1964; Harvard Law School,  LL.B.,  <I>cum laude, </I> 1967,  LL.M.,  1973.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Victor S. Friedman</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8050</I>) Victor Friedman's practice encompasses all aspects of the antitrust laws. He frequently appears before state and federal antitrust agencies and has litigated major antitrust cases for such diverse clients as General Electric,  Burlington Northern,  Mayflower,  GeLCo,  RTZ,  and Harcourt Brace Jovanovich. Assistant to Deputy Attorney General of the U.S.,  1957-1959; fellow,  American College of Trial Lawyers. Harvard College,  B.A.,  <I>magna cum laude, </I> 1954; Yale Law School,  LL.B.,  Order of the Coif,  1957; case editor,  <I>Yale Law Journal</I>,  1956-1957.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Allen Kezsbom</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8148</I>) Allen Kezsbom has a trial and appellate practice encompassing the full range of antitrust,  unfair trade practice,  and consumer protection law. He has written and spoken extensively on monopolization,  price-fixing,  tying,  and resale price maintenance,  and the trial of complex antitrust cases. He was,  for example,  trial attorney for Xerox in the <I>SCM </I>v.<I> Xerox</I> monopolization litigation and for Sears in the down content mislabeling litigation. Brooklyn College,  B.A.,  1962; Harvard University,  LL.B.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1965; <I>Harvard Law Review</I>,  1963-1965.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Ira S. Sacks</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8061</I>) Ira Sacks represents clients in a wide range of antitrust and trade regulation issues,  including dealer termination and price-fixing. He also represents clients in mergers,  including contested matters,  before the Department of Justice and the FTC. He regularly counsels on antitrust compliance issues,  including annual presentations at national sales meetings and to groups of executives. Massachusetts Institute of Technology,  B.S.,  1970; Georgetown University,  J.D.,  1974; senior topics editor,  <I>Law  & Policy in International Business</I>,  1973-1974.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Alexander R. Sussman</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8005</I>) Alexander R. Sussman has represented clients in numerous antitrust matters. He is a coauthor of <I>Takeover Defense</I> (three volumes,  Prentice-Hall Law  & Business,  1990) and the author of its chapter on `Antitrust Considerations.' Princeton University,  A.B.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  Phi Beta Kappa,  1968; Fulbright Scholar,  University of Bordeaux,  1969; Yale Law School,  J.D.,  1972; <I>Yale Law Journal</I>,  1970-1972.<BR>
