 nation's two largest plaintiffs' antitrust jury verdicts affirmed on appeal. In January 1994,  the Supreme Court denied <I>certiorari</I> in a case in which the jury awarded our clients over $600 million in damages for monopolization. Earlier,  a jury awarded another client $275 million for damages it suffered from monopolization.<BR><P>The firm has built its reputation on its capability to take the largest,  most complex cases to trial and to defend the largest and most challenging mergers. That experience enables lawyers in the firm to handle any antitrust litigation efficiently and effectively. The breadth of antitrust experience in the firm is also frequently called upon by clients for regular counseling and to design business and acquisition strategies to avoid or minimize antitrust risk in the U.S. or internationally.<BR><BR><P>Representative clients: Anheuser-Busch Companies,  Inc.; Ashland Oil,  Inc.; Carolina Power and Light Co.; Caterpillar,  Inc.; Columbia-HCA Healthcare Corp.; COMSAT Corporation; Cyprus Amax Minerals Company; Dana Corporation; Encyclopaedia Britannica,  Inc.; Exxon Corporation; Gates Corporation.; H.J. Heinz Company; Johnson  & Johnson; Litton Industries,  Inc.; Lockheed Martin Corporation; LTV Corporation; Mead Corporation; Mobil Corporation; Nestl &#232; Companies; PepsiCo,  Inc.; Prudential Insurance Co. of America; Quaker Oats Company; Rockwell International Corporation; Schering-Plough,  Hoechst Celanese; Shell Oil Company; Siemens Corporation; Uniroyal Chemical Co.; and Witco Corporation.<BR><UL><BR><LI><B>Robert G. Abrams</B> Represents clients in the petroleum and heavy machinery industries,  as well as other clients in complex antitrust litigation,  including class actions and dealer terminations.<BR><BR><LI><B>Ray S. Bolze</B> Represents clients in the petroleum,  utility,  paper,  hospital/health care,  and other industries in complex litigation.<BR><BR><LI><B>John DeQ. Briggs III</B> Represents clients in aerospace,  chemicals,  computer hardware and software,  consumer products and heavy manufacturing in mergers and acquisitions,  as well as all facets of civil antitrust counseling and litigation. Chair of the ABA Antitrust Law Section,  1995-1996.<BR><BR><LI><B>Richard T. Colman</B> Experienced in civil and criminal antitrust litigation and mergers and acquisitions. Lead counsel in obtaining a $600 million jury verdict.<BR><BR><LI><B>Raymond A. Jacobsen,  Jr.</B> Represents clients in industries including defense,  contracting,  and health care in mergers and acquisitions and antitrust litigation.<BR><BR<LI><B>Peter E. Moll</B> Represents a major brewer,  multinational food companies,  high-tech companies,  and others in all facets of antitrust litigation,  including class actions and distributor terminations.<BR><BR><LI><B>Keith E. Pugh,  Jr.</B> Represents food products,  medical,  telecommunications,  electrical equipment,  chemical,  computer,  and weight-loss companies in all facets of antitrust,  trade regulation,  and consumer protection counseling and litigation.<BR><BR><LI><B>Robert F. Ruyak</B> Represents manufacturers of computers and components and semiconductor devices; major steel companies; and others in complex antitrust and unfair competition litigation.<BR><BR><LI><B>Ralph J. Savarese</B> Managing partner. Represents clients in complex antitrust litigation,  including mergers and acquisitions.<BR><BR><LI><B>Mark Schechter</B> Until April 1995 was deputy director of operations for the Antitrust Division,  U.S. Department of Justice,  where he supervised all civil nonmerger investigations and litigation for the Division.<BR><BR><LI><B>Marc G. Schildkraut</B> Until 1993 was assistant director at the FTC,  managing the antitrust investigation and litigation of the country's largest acquisitions.<BR><BR><LI><B>Terrence C. Sheehy</B> Represents food manufacturers,  a major brewer,  and other large corporations in all facets of antitrust litigation and counseling,  including mergers and acquisitions.<BR><BR><LI><B>Mark D. Wegener</B> Represents telecommunications,  publishing,  oil,  and other companies in all facets of antitrust litigation and counseling.<BR><BR><LI><B>Alan M. Wiseman</B> Represents a major forest products company and others in all facets of antitrust litigation and mergers and acquisitions.<BR><BR><LI><B>Margaret M. Zwisler</B> Represents consumer products companies in government investigations,  class actions,  and other complex litigation with a particular focus on price-fixing,  vertical restraints,  and monopolization.<BR><BR><BR></UL></UL></BODY></HTML>
