<TITLE>Hoyle,  Morris  & Kerr
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Antitrust</H2>
<H3>Hoyle,  Morris  & Kerr
</H3>

</CENTER>
<B><CENTER>Philadelphia:</B> One Liberty Place,  Suite 4900,  1650 Market Street, <BR>
Philadelphia,  PA 19103-7397<BR>
Tel 215-981-5700  <B>*</B>  Fax 215-851-0436<BR>
<BR>
45 lawyers  <B>*</B>  6 lawyers in Antitrust Group<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/hoyle.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/hoyle.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/hoyle.html"> Product Liability</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>H</B>oyle,  Morris  & Kerr has a national litigation practice that includes the broad spectrum of commercial litigation. Firm attorneys are particularly experienced in complex litigation,  including class action litigation,  at both trial and appellate levels.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Antitrust Group</H3></CENTER>

<P>Hoyle,  Morris  & Kerr lawyers are experienced in defending allegations under virtually every substantive area of the antitrust laws,  including monopolization,  price-fixing,  refusals to deal,  exclusive dealing,  tie-ins,  and price discrimination,  as well as defending Federal Trade Commission actions and other actions involving application of antitrust laws to various regulated industries and to international trade and commerce. Firm attorneys have also counseled clients in various aspects of the antitrust laws,  including compliance with the Robinson-Patman Act.<BR><BR><P>Our lawyers have represented clients at both the trial and appellate level in antitrust actions brought against companies doing business in diverse industries including the motion picture,  entertainment ticketing,  food franchise,  tobacco,  horseracing,  insurance,  public utility,  asphalt paving,  antiques,  petroleum products,  sugar,  plumbing,  water heaters,  glassine paper,  baby food and infant formula,  directory advertising,  television,  freight transportation,  petroleum products,  and baseball card industries. We have experience in class action proceedings and matters before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation.<BR>
<BR><P>In antitrust cases as with other complex litigation handled by the Firm,  our attorneys are especially experienced at working with expert witnesses to marshal the relevant evidence from their professional disciplines.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Lawrence T. Hoyle,  Jr.</B> Mr. Hoyle has defended clients in the transportation and plumbing supply industries in antitrust litigation. Instructor,  Antitrust Law,  Temple University Law School,  1969-1971; deputy attorney general,  civil litigation division chief,  Department of Justice,  Commonwealth of Pennsylvania,  1971-1972; executive director,  Pennsylvania Crime Commission,  1972-1974. Fellow,  American Bar Foundation. Duke University,  B.A.,  1960; University of Chicago,  J.D.,  1965. Admitted in Pennsylvania,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Alexander Kerr</B> Mr. Kerr has litigated antitrust actions on behalf of clients in the dairy,  television,  infant formula,  fuel oil,  glassine paper,  insurance,  and advertising industries. Law clerk to Justice Samuel J. Roberts,  Pennsylvania Supreme Court,  1970-1971; deputy attorney general,  Pennsylvania Department of Justice,  1972-1974. Yale University,  B.A.,  1967; University of Pennsylvania,  J.D.,  1970; editor,  <I>University of Pennsylvania Law Review</I>,  1968-1970. Admitted in Pennsylvania,  1971.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Arlene Fickler</B> Ms. Fickler has defended antitrust claims brought against a nationally known common carrier by New York City garment trucking companies,  and worked on the successful appeal of a verdict of monopolization in the baseball card industry. University of Pennsylvania,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1971,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1974. Admitted in Pennsylvania,  1974,  and the District of Columbia,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard M. Bernstein</B> Mr. Bernstein has defended clients in the sugar,  tobacco,  horse racing,  and iron ore industries in antitrust litigation. Brown University,  B.A.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1963; Princeton University,  Ph.D.,  1969; University of Pennsylvania,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude, </I> 1976; <I>University of Pennsylvania Law Review</I>,  1974-1976. Admitted in Pennsylvania,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Denise D. Colliers</B> Ms. Colliers represented the City of Philadelphia in prosecuting an antitrust action for activities surrounding a city-awarded sludge utilization contract. In private practice,  Ms. Colliers participated in litigation on behalf of clients in the paint,  consumer `small bags, ' water heater,  art materials,  and copper wire tubing industries. Swarthmore College,  B.A. with honors,  1976; University of Pennsylvania,  J.D.,  1979. Admitted in Pennsylvania,  1979.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Sean P. Wajert</B> Mr. Wajert has defended clients in the automobile,  railroad,  and iron ore industries in antitrust litigation. Law clerk,  Judge Arlin M. Adams,  U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit,  1984-1985. Harvard University,  A.B.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1981; University of Pennsylvania Law School,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1984; Order of the Coif; editor-in-chief,  <I>University of Pennsylvania Law Review</I>,  1983-1984. Admitted in Pennsylvania,  1984.<BR>
