g monopolization claims brought by a former Tuscan dealer. In the U.S. Supreme Court,  we recently acted for Allied Tube and Conduit Corporation in its litigation with Indian Head,  Inc.,  a case involving significant questions concerning the extent to which U.S. antitrust law regulates lobbying activities.<BR><BR><P>Our antitrust litigation practice includes defending against criminal price-fixing and related charges,  both pre-indictment and at trial. Our criminal antitrust work has covered a number of industries,  among them brewing (hops),  food retailing,  kosher food,  defense (aircraft parts),  tool-making,  and securities.<BR><BR><P>Kramer Levin's antitrust group has played an active role in connection with our firm's trademark licensing,  franchising,  and merger and acquisition practices. We regularly shepherd transactions through the Department of Justice and Federal Trade Commission and advise with respect to antitrust aspects of international transactions as well.<BR><BR><P>Also on the counseling side,  the firm has conducted antitrust audits and prepared numerous antitrust compliance programs in several diverse industries,  including trucking (at the advent of deregulation),  packaged foods,  baking,  milk processing,  fashion apparel,  and disposable food service supplies.<BR><BR><UL><BR><LI><B>Robert M. Heller</B> heads the firm's antitrust practice. Mr. Heller has more than 30 years experience in the field handling the full range of antitrust matters litigation,  transactional and counseling. His representations span a broad range of manufacturing,  financial,  and service industries. Member,  antitrust sections,  American and New York State Bar Associations. Former member,  trade regulation committee,  Association of the Bar of the City of New York. Attorney adviser to Commissioner Philip Elman,  Federal Trade Commission,  1967-1969. Law clerk,  Judge Paul R. Hays,  U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit,  1966-1967. Columbia University,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1963,  LL.B.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1966; Phi Beta Kappa; Kent Scholar; notes and comments editor,  <I>Columbia Law Review</I>.<BR><BR><LI><B>Marvin E. Frankel</B> heads our litigation practice and chairs the firm's management committee. Mr. Frankel has argued more than 20 cases before the U.S. Supreme Court,  including important antitrust matters. He served as a U.S. District Judge in the Southern District of New York from 1965 to 1978,  presiding over a number of significant antitrust cases. Since his return to private practice,  Mr. Frankel has successfully litigated,  or participated in,  a wide variety of antitrust actions. Assistant to U.S. Solicitor General,  1952-1956. Professor of Law,  Columbia University,  1962-1965. Chair,  Lawyers Committee for Human Rights,  1980-present. Queens College,  A.B.,  1943; Columbia University,  LL.B.,  1948; editor-in-chief,  <I>Columbia Law Review</I>.<BR><BR><LI><B>Gary P. Naftalis</B> heads our white collar criminal defense practice. He defends criminal antitrust investigations and prosecutions. One of the nation's leading trial lawyers and a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers,  he served as an assistant U.S. attorney in New York for seven years,  holding the title of deputy chief of the criminal division. Law clerk,  Judge William B. Herlands,  U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York,  1967-1968. Rutgers University,  B.A.,  1963; Brown University,  M.A.,  1965; Columbia University,  LL.B.,  1967; Phi Beta Kappa; editor,  <I>Columbia Law Review</I>.<BR><BR><LI><B>Thomas H. Moreland</B> has litigated major civil antitrust matters,  most recently the successful prosecution of a tender offer case in which the defense relied on a purported `antitrust out, ' and the defense of a series of cases alleging monopolization of the milk processing industry in New York and New Jersey. Law clerk,  Chief Judge J. Edward Lumbard,  U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit,  1968-1969. Wesleyan University,  B.A.,  1965; Harvard University,  LL.B.,  1968; case editor,  <I>Harvard Law Review</I>.<BR><BR><LI><B>Michael J. Dell</B> In addition to civil antitrust litigation,  Mr. Dell recently defended executives in the kosher food and toolmaking industries against criminal price-fixing claims. Law clerk,  Judge Stanley A. Weigel,  U.S. District Court for the Northern District of California,  1978-1979. Oxford University (Wadham College),  B.A.,  with honors,  1975; Harvard University,  J.D.,  magna cum laude,  1978; associate editorial director,  Harvard Law Review.<BR><BR><BR></UL></UL></BODY></HTML>
