<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Antitrust</H2>
<H3>Paul,  Weiss,  Rifkind,  Wharton  & Garrison
</H3>

</CENTER>
<B><CENTER>New York:</B> 1285 Avenue of the Americas,  New York,  NY 10019-6064<BR>
Tel 212-373-3000  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-757-3990<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> 1615 L Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20036-5694<BR>
Tel 202-223-7300  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-223-7420<BR>
<B>Paris:</B> 199,  boulevard Saint-Germain,  75007 Paris,  France<BR>
Tel 33-1-45-49-33-85  <B>*</B>  Fax 33-1-42-22-64-38<BR>
<B>Hong Kong:</B> 13th Fl.,  Hong Kong Club Building,  3A Chater Road,  Central Hong Kong<BR>
Tel 852-2536-9933 and 852-2846-0300  <B>*</B>  Fax 852-2536-9622<BR>
<B>Tokyo:</B> Akasaka Twin Tower,  17-22,  Akasaka 2-chome,  Minato-ku,  Tokyo 107,  Japan<BR>
Tel 81-3-3505-0291  <B>*</B>  Fax 81-3-3505-4540<BR>
<B>Beijing:</B> Scite Tower (Noble Tower),  Room 904,  22,  Jianguomenwai Dajie, <BR>
Beijing,  100004,  People's Republic of China<BR>
Tel 86-1-512-3628  <B>*</B>  Fax 86-1-512-3631<BR>
<BR>
345 lawyers  <B>*</B>  30 lawyers practice antitrust and trade regulation<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/paul.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/paul.html"> Corporate Securities</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/paul.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/paul.html"> ERISA</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/paul.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
   <LI><A HREF="..//paul.html"> International</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/paul.html"> Product Liability</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/paul.html"> Workout</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>P</B>aul,  Weiss,  Rifkind,  Wharton  & Garrison,  one of the largest New York-based law firms,  is a globally-oriented full service firm with experience in almost every significant field of contemporary law. We have been very active in antitrust and trade regulation practice for over 40 years.<BR>
<BR><P>As with other areas of our practice,  our clients on antitrust matters come from all parts of the United States and many parts of the world. We have been involved in antitrust matters involving virtually every industry,  including: motion pictures,  recorded music,  insurance,  financial services,  automobiles,  auto parts,  steel,  soft-drink bottling,  tobacco,  electrical products,  electronics,  computers,  food products,  food retailing,  forest products,  chemicals,  pharmaceuticals,  agricultural products,  mining,  airlines,  industrial equipment,  oil and gas,  machine tools,  health care,  and consumer goods.<BR><BR><P>Our antitrust practice includes extensive counseling and advice,  as well as representation of clients in litigation and regulatory matters. On the counseling side,  we have devised antitrust compliance programs for a variety of clients,  and we regularly advise clients on such matters as mergers,  acquisitions,  joint ventures,  distribution practices,  dealership and franchising issues,  pricing programs,  promotional programs,  consent decrees,  trade association activities,  and advertising regulation.<BR>
<BR><P>In counseling our clients on antitrust matters,  we bring to bear our constant review of developments in the law and changes in enforcement policies and practices,  as well as our extensive experience litigating antitrust cases. We are thus especially well-equipped to bring an important dimension to our antitrust counseling,  advising clients on the basis of practical experience with how a governmental agency,  judge,  or jury will react to the facts,  as well as our knowledge of the relevant legal principles.<BR>
<BR><P>Our antitrust litigation experience includes many of the most significant antitrust cases of the modern era and cases involving great complexity. Among other matters:<BR>
<UL><BR><LI> We represented ASCAP at trial and on appeal in <I>BMI and ASCAP </I>v.<I> CBS</I> the seminal U.S. Supreme Court decision in the area of joint associations and joint ventures and have been involved in virtually every important antitrust case involving the recorded music industry,  as well as landmark actions involving cable television.<BR>
<BR><LI> We handled at trial and on appeal <I>FTC </I>v.<I> BOC International</I> and <I>In re</I> <I>B.A.T. Industries,  Ltd. and Appleton Papers,  Inc.</I> leading cases that significantly limited the potential competition doctrine under Section 7 of the Clayton Act.<BR>
<BR><LI> We represented the motion picture industry in its antitrust suit against the television networks.<BR>
<BR><LI> We defeated a hostile attempt to take over our client Consolidated Gold Fields by private antitrust litigation,  establishing (in the Second Circuit) that a takeover target has antitrust standing under Section 7 of the Clayton Act.<BR>
<BR><LI> We represented Brown  & Williamson Tobacco Company in what we believe is the largest Robinson-Patman Act claim to go to a jury.<BR>
<BR><LI> We represented British Airways in the antitrust litigations growing out of the demise of Laker Airways.<BR>
<BR><LI> We represented a number of <I>amici curiae</I>,  and successfully argued the appeal,  in antitrust litigation by the Department of Justice against Massachusetts Institute of Technology,  a pivotal case involving charges of conspiracy among the eight Ivy League universities.<BR>
<BR><LI> We successfully defended Armstrong World Industries in the retrial of a claim under Section 1 of the Sherman Act,  obtaining a judgment in Armstrong's favor after a first trial resulted in an adverse judgment of $239 million.<BR>
<BR><LI> We are currently representing one of the NASDAQ market makers involved in a group of class actions under Section 1 of the Sherman Act,  and a much-publicized Justice Department investigation,  concerning market making practices on NASDAQ.<BR></UL>
<BR><P>Our antitrust practice embraces representations in virtually all forums and procedural settings. We have been before the Federal Circuit and other federal courts in complex patent-antitrust cases,  and our lawyers have handled class actions and individual actions in courts throughout the United States involving virtually all aspects of federal and state antitrust and trade regulation law. We also have substantial experience representing clients in civil and criminal investigations and actions by federal and state law enforcement authorities,  and we frequently represent clients before the Justice Department and the Federal Trade Commission in connection with mergers,  acquisitions,  and divestitures.<BR>
<BR><P>Paul,  Weiss's international orientation is well reflected in our antitrust and trade regulation work. We have advised many clients based outside the United States concerning the antitrust aspects of acquiring and operating companies in this country. We have also counseled international clients concerning the extraterritorial reach of the U.S. antitrust laws and the circumstances in which conduct abroad may violate those laws.<BR>
<BR><P>Our lawyers have handled significant international antitrust cases in the United States such as the Laker Airways litigation and the Gold Fields/Minorco takeover battle. We successfully represented Komatsu Electronic Metals,  Inc.,  in a major antitrust dispute with Union Carbide Corporation,  which,  among other things,  tested the extent to which antitrust claims may be subject to international arbitration. We represented another Japanese client in connection with a U.S. Justice Department investigation of alleged bid rigging involving Defense Department contracts let in Japan. We have also represented companies from the United States and other countries in antitrust matters before the Commission of the European Communities and the International Court of Justice.<BR>
<BR><P>Among our partners and counsel who practice in the area of antitrust and trade regulation and have written and lectured on the subject are:<BR>
<BR><UL>
<LI><B>Jay Topkis</B> Mr. Topkis joined Paul,  Weiss in 1950 and became a partner in our Litigation Department in 1960. He has tried many criminal and civil antitrust cases and handled significant appeals,  including <I>CBS </I>v.<I> BMI and ASCAP</I> in the Supreme Court. Mr. Topkis graduated from Columbia University in 1946 and Yale School of Law in 1949.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Martin London</B> Mr. London joined Paul,  Weiss in 1962 and became a partner in our Litigation Department in 1969. He was lead trial counsel in the Brown  & Williamson Robinson-Patman Act case and in the Armstrong World Industries case. Mr. London graduated from Cornell University in 1955 and New York University Law School in 1957.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Sidney S. Rosdeitcher</B> Mr. Rosdeitcher joined Paul,  Weiss in 1962 and became a partner in our Litigation Department in 1972. He served as attorney advisor to Commissioner Philip Elman of the FTC in 1965-1966. He is the coordinator of our antitrust practice group. He has handled significant antitrust litigations involving a variety of industries and argued <I>St. Paul Fire  & Marine Insurance Co. </I>v.<I> Barry</I>,  a major insurance industry antitrust case,  in the Supreme Court. He also counsels on a wide variety of antitrust and distribution matters. Mr. Rosdeitcher graduated from Columbia University in 1958 and Harvard Law School in 1961.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Mark H. ALCott</B> Mr. ALCott joined Paul,  Weiss in 1964 and became a partner in our Litigation Department in 1974. He has handled a number of significant antitrust cases,  including the Wheat Farmers Antitrust Class Action,  in which he was lead counsel for the grain industry; the broiler chicken price-fixing litigation; and multiple cases arising out of the alleged cornering and subsequent collapse of the silver market. Mr. ALCott graduated from Harvard College in 1961 and Harvard Law School in 1964.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Daniel J. Beller</B> Mr. Beller joined Paul,  Weiss in 1978,  after serving as assistant U.S. attorney (1974-1978) and chief of the Major Crimes Unit (1977-1978) in the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Southern District of New York. He became a partner in our Litigation Department in 1981. He acted as trial counsel,  with Mr. Topkis,  in <I>In re B.A.T. Industries,  Ltd.  & Appleton Papers,  Inc.</I>,  has served as lead counsel for major clients in criminal antitrust investigations,  and has provided antitrust advice on transactions and compliance issues. Mr. Beller graduated from Harvard College in 1968 and Yale Law School in 1972.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Moses Silverman</B> Mr. Silverman joined Paul,  Weiss in 1973 and became a partner in our Litigation Department in 1981. He has advised clients and litigated cases in many areas of antitrust law. He is currently representing defendants in Section 1 class actions concerning market makers on NASDAQ and the agricultural chemicals industry,  and is also representing parties in a variety of foreign and domestic administrative and investigative antitrust proceedings. Mr. Silverman graduated from Colby College in 1969 and New York University School of Law in 1973.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gerard E. Harper</B> Mr. Harper joined Paul,  Weiss in 1979 and became a partner in our Litigation Department in 1986. He has substantial experience in advising clients in Hart-Scott-Rodino preclearance review and in litigating Sherman Act and Robinson-Patman Act cases. Mr. Harper graduated from Rutgers College in 1975 and New York University School of Law in 1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard Rosen</B> Mr. Rosen joined Paul,  Weiss in 1978 and became a partner in our Litigation Department in 1986. He has had significant experience both defending private civil antitrust lawsuits and providing advice on a variety of antitrust questions,  including issues surrounding acquisitions and sales of businesses. Mr. Rosen graduated from Brown University in 1975 and Harvard Law School in 1979.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Daniel J. Leffell</B> Mr. Leffell joined Paul,  Weiss in 1987 and became a partner in our Litigation Department in 1992. He acted as trial counsel,  with Martin London,  in the Brown  & Williamson Robinson-Patman Act case and has advised clients on a variety of antitrust matters. Mr. Leffell graduated from Yale University in 1977 and Columbia School of Law in 1981.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</UL><BR>


</UL></BODY>
