<HEAD>
<TITLE>Thelen,  Marrin,  Johnson  & Bridges
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Antitrust</H2>
<H3>Thelen,  Marrin,  Johnson & Bridges
</H3>

</CENTER>
<B><CENTER>San Francisco: </B>Two Embarcadero Center,  San Francisco,  CA 94111<BR>
Tel 415-392-6320  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-421-1068<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Los Angeles,  New York,  San Jose (California)<BR>
<BR>
180 lawyers  <B>*</B>  22 lawyers in antitrust practice<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>T</B>helen,  Marrin,  Johnson  & Bridges is a national law firm with 180 attorneys in four offices: Los Angeles,  New York,  San Francisco,  and San Jose. Founded in 1924,  Thelen provides expert counsel in virtually all areas of the law to global and Fortune 500 corporations as well as regional businesses and individuals. The 22 attorneys in the firm's antitrust practice handle matters nationwide and are based in each of the offices.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Antitrust Litigation and Counseling</H3></CENTER>

<P>Thelen's litigation practice has successfully taken a number of large antitrust jury trials to verdict in California courts and elsewhere in the U.S. during the past decade. The firm has represented clients with respect to antitrust and trade regulation issues in civil and criminal government investigations; private suits brought by individuals,  corporations,  and plaintiffs' classes; and various administrative actions before the Federal Trade Commission,  International Trade Commission,  and International Commerce Commission. Areas of particular expertise include cases involving charges of price-fixing,  bid-rigging,  tying arrangements,  predatory pricing,  price discrimination,  monopolization,  unfair competition,  and various forms of conspiracies. Many cases have involved state antitrust claims under California's Cartright Act and similar statutes elsewhere.<BR><P>The firm regularly counsels clients on antitrust considerations with respect to prospective mergers,  Hart-Scott-Rodino Act filings,  pricing and marketing practices,  membership in trade associations,  Robinson-Patman Act compliance,  and the extraterritorial application of the U.S. antitrust laws to firms doing business abroad. It also conducts audits for clients to identify potential violations. Thelen has significant experience in antitrust exemptions,  including agricultural,  labor,  nonprofits,  and insurance exemptions under various federal laws.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Robert B. Pringle</B> (<I>San Francisco; 415-955-3535</I>) Chair of the firm's antitrust practice,  Mr. Pringle has extensive antitrust litigation and counseling experience. He has represented clients in the high technology,  manufacturing,  agricultural,  communications,  and financial services industries,  among others. He is the coauthor of the ABA Antitrust Section's handbooks on antitrust discovery and antitrust evidence. Mr. Pringle served as the 1992 chair of the annual meeting of the ABA Antitrust Section and is a frequent speaker on antitrust issues at ABA,  state bar,  and other continuing education seminars.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kenneth L. Nissly</B> (<I>San Jose; 408-292-5800</I>) Mr. Nissly has substantial counseling experience with respect to antitrust issues related to patent and trade secret claims. His experience also includes representation of clients in a recent nationwide manufacturing antitrust case.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Rauer L. Meyer</B> (<I>San Francisco; 415-955-3541</I>) Mr. Meyer has broad experience with respect to antitrust matters with particular emphasis in the area of antitrust and intellectual property.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jonathan E. Polonsky</B> (<I>New York; 212-297-3225</I>) Mr. Polonsky is an experienced antitrust litigator and counselor. He has served as counsel in multidistrict federal litigation involving the insurance industry,  Robinson-Patman litigation between rival distributors,  and antitrust litigation involving the recycling industry.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
