<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>V</B>inson  & Elkins L.L.P. is one of the world's largest international law firms,  representing clients in substantially all areas of law. Since its formation,  the Firm has handled all types of commercial disputes before state and federal trial and appellate courts as well as federal and state regulatory bodies,  and grand juries. We also conduct investigations of incidents and occurrences that ultimately may involve litigation.
<P><BR><P>Vinson  & Elkins began its antitrust practice over 50 years ago. In a 1993 survey of law firms by Euromoney Publications,  Vinson  & Elkins was ranked in the top ten nationally in antitrust law and fourth in arbitration and litigation. We handle the full range of antitrust issues that arise in our clients' activities,  especially the defense of antitrust claims brought by civil litigants. We have represented plaintiffs in billion-dollar antitrust litigation. A growing part of our practice is the defense of clients under investigation by federal grand juries and in criminal trials. Our antitrust practice spans a range of industries,  including the oil and gas,  airline,  computer,  media,  shipping,  telecommunications,  supermarket,  health care,  insurance,  and banking industries. Our partners with significant antitrust practices include:<BR><UL><BR><LI><B>Page I. Austin</B> (<I>Houston; 713-758-2240</I>) practices primarily in complex litigation,  including antitrust litigation and antitrust counseling. Member,  American Law Institute.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>David M. Bond</B> (<I>Houston; 713-758-2586</I>) practices primarily in business litigation,  including antitrust,  securities,  civil RICO,  and lender liability litigation,  and in antitrust counseling. Adjunct professor of antitrust law at University of Houston School of Law.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Ky P. Ewing,  Jr.</B> (<I>Washington; 202-639-6580</I>) practices primarily in antitrust and business litigation,  including merger and other investigations by the U.S. Department of Justice and the FTC,  and antitrust counseling. Served as deputy assistant attorney general,  Antitrust Division,  U.S. Department of Justice. Co-editor-in-chief,  <I>State Antitrust Practice and Statutes</I> (3 vols.,  1990). <I>Who's Who in American Law</I>.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Orrin Harrison III</B> (<I>Dallas; 214-220-7715</I>) practices primarily in securities,  antitrust,  and other complex business litigation. Former president,  Dallas chapter,  American Board of Trial Advocates.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>David T. Harvin</B> (<I>Houston; 713-758-2368</I>) practices primarily in antitrust and other business litigation. Trial counsel in <I>Business Electronics Corp. </I>v.<I> Sharp Electronics Corp.</I>,  485 U.S. 717 (1988). Fellow,  American College of Trial Lawyers.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Richard D. Milvenan</B> (<I>Austin; 512-495-8542</I>) practices primarily in antitrust and business litigation representing clients in the automobile,  banking,  insurance,  oil and gas,  publishing,  real estate,  and grocery industries.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>John L. Murchison,  Jr.</B>'s (<I>Houston; 713-758-2338</I>) antitrust practice includes advisory work,  government investigations,  and antitrust litigation. Fellow,  American College of Trial Lawyers.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Charles T. Newton,  Jr.</B> (<I>Houston; 713-758-2146</I>) practices in complex litigation involving the accounting,  securities,  health care,  oil and gas,  banking,  and other industries. Chair,  Antitrust Section of Texas State Bar Association,  1980-1981.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Harry M. Reasoner</B> (<I>Houston; 713-758-2358</I>) practices primarily in complex litigation,  including antitrust litigation. Currently serves as the Firm's managing partner. Served as lead counsel in securing on behalf of ETSI Pipeline a $1.035 billion antitrust verdict,  and as lead counsel for the <I>Dallas Morning News</I> in obtaining a take-nothing verdict in the <I>Dallas Times Herald</I> $100 million antitrust claim. Chair,  Antitrust Law Section,  ABA,  1989-1990; fellow,  American College of Trial Lawyers.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Alison L. Smith</B> (<I>Houston; 713-758-2250</I>) practices primarily in antitrust and general business litigation,  emphasizing antitrust litigation,  counseling,  and defense of clients under investigation by federal grand juries. Deputy assistant attorney general of the U.S. Department of Justice's Antitrust Division (1989-1991). Adjunct professor of antitrust law at The University of Texas School of Law (1992-1993).<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Allan Van Fleet</B> (<I>Houston; 713-758-2006</I>) practices in complex litigation and antitrust counseling,  representing clients in the microelectronics,  telecommunications,  oil and gas,  energy transportation,  petrochemical,  and other industries. Chair,  Business Torts and Unfair Competition Committee,  Antitrust Section of the ABA.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Robert C. Walters</B> (<I>Dallas; 214-220-7704</I>) practices primarily in antitrust and antitrust counseling,  technology,  professional liability,  and general business litigation. Former vice-chair,  Regulated Industries Committee,  Antitrust Section of the ABA; chair,  Publications Committee,  Antitrust Section of the ABA.<BR>
<BR>
</UL>

