<HEAD>
<TITLE>Wilmer,  Cutler  & Pickering
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Antitrust</H2>
<H3>Wilmer,  Cutler  & Pickering
</H3>

</CENTER>
<B><CENTER>Washington:</B> 2445 M Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20037-1420<BR>
Tel 202-663-6000  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-663-6363  <B>*</B>  E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:Law@Wilmer.Com">Law@Wilmer.Com</A><BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Berlin,  Brussels,  London<BR>
<BR>
215 lawyers  <B>*</B>  12 partners in the antitrust area<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/wilmer.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/wilmer.html"> Corporate Securities</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/wilmer.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="..//wilmer.html"> International</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/wilmer.html"> White Collar Crime</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/wilmer.html"> Workout</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>W</B>ilmer,  Cutler  & Pickering has a national and international regulatory,  commercial,  and litigation practice often involving important legal and public policy issues.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Antitrust Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>Wilmer,  Cutler  & Pickering has a broad-ranging antitrust law practice. The firm regularly represents clients in securing clearance for mergers,  acquisitions,  and joint ventures from the antitrust enforcement agencies and in government criminal and civil antitrust investigations,  including many cutting-edge cases. The firm handles private antitrust litigation and provides counseling to clients on the full range of antitrust issues including joint ventures,  licensing agreements,  price discrimination,  distribution issues,  and trade association activities,  as well as other horizontal and vertical business arrangements. The firm also assists clients in developing antitrust compliance programs and conducting antitrust audits of their operations. The firm's Brussels office has an active practice counseling a wide variety of clients and representing them before the European Commission in matters relating to EU competition law.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Experience  & Clients</H3></CENTER>

<P><BR><BR>
Recent activities in the antitrust area include:<BR><BR><LI>Representing a major securities firm in a Justice Department investigation and private class action litigation involving alleged collusion on the NASDAQ market.<BR><BR><LI> Representing a major marketer of consumer goods in securing FTC clearance for the sale of two brands to its leading competitors.<BR>
<BR><LI> Representing a large university hospital in a major Justice Department grand jury investigation of alleged price fixing and other alleged antitrust violations.<BR>
<BR><LI> Securing dismissal of the FTC's administrative complaint challenging the exclusive contract between ABC and the College Football Association.<BR>
<BR><LI> Representing a retailer in a private action alleging that Virginia wine wholesalers had divided territories and allocated customers.<BR>
<BR><LI> Representing a major telephone company in structuring and obtaining government approval for its acquisition of a substantial interest in a major cable operator.<BR>
<BR><BR><UL>
<LI><B>Robert A. Hammond III</B> has counseled and represented clients with respect to acquisitions and mergers,  pricing and distribution,  joint ventures and other cooperative arrangements,  and alleged monopolization. He served as Chief of the FTC's Division of Mergers and as deputy assistant attorney general for the Justice Department's Antitrust Division. Harvard Law School,  1955.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Daniel K. Mayers</B> has had broad antitrust litigating experience,  involving the defense of FTC and Justice Department actions as well as private suits. Mr. Mayers has served in both the Justice and State Departments. Harvard Law School,  1960.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Ronald J. Greene</B> counsels clients about actual and potential antitrust problems,  usually involving vertical restraints,  distribution,  or pricing issues. Harvard Law School,  1968.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gary D. Wilson</B> has been involved in a number of large merger investigations before the Justice Department and FTC,  as well as a number of private antitrust suits involving the airline industry. Stanford Law School,  1968.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>C. Loring Jetton,  Jr.</B> has handled numerous mergers and acquisitions,  as well as a number of major private treble-damage actions. Columbia Law School,  1969.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>A. Douglas Melamed</B> has represented communications,  financial,  and other clients in numerous antitrust and regulatory matters,  involving both counseling and litigation in the Supreme Court,  lower courts,  and the Federal Trade Commission. He has taught antitrust law at Georgetown University Law Center. Harvard Law School,  1970.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William J. Kolasky,  Jr.</B> has handled numerous mergers and acquisitions,  several major criminal investigations,  and a number of private treble-damage actions. He also counsels clients about antitrust issues arising from joint ventures and distribution arrangements. Mr. Kolasky teaches antitrust law at American University. Harvard Law School,  1971.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John Rounsaville,  Jr.</B> has represented clients in Justice Department and FTC investigations,  both criminal and civil. He has counseled clients regarding mergers and other planned consolidations and has negotiated their completion with government officials. Harvard Law School,  1972.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James S. Venit</B> has had extensive experience in representing multinational companies before the European Commission and has written extensively on EU competition law. New York University Law School,  1979.<BR>
<BR>
</UL><BR>


</UL></BODY>
