<HEAD>
<TITLE>Bronson,  Bronson & McKinnon
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Commercial Litigation</H2>
<H3>Bronson,  Bronson & McKinnon
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>San Francisco:</B> 505 Montgomery Street,  San Francisco,  CA 94111<BR>
Tel 415-986-4200  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-982-1394<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Los Angeles,  San Jose (California)<BR>
<BR>
142 lawyers  <B>*</B>  32 lawyers in commercial litigation law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/bronson.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/bronson.html"> Labor</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/bronson.html"> Product Liability</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>F</B>ounded in 1918,  Bronson,  Bronson  & McKinnon is a full-service firm,  representing clients ranging from individuals to Fortune 500 corporations throughout the United States. Our commercial litigation department is the firm's largest practice group. The department's trial lawyers have a wide range of experience in all aspects of commercial litigation both in state and federal courts and specialize in litigation involving securities,  intellectual property,  unfair competition,  banking,  professional liability,  antitrust,  officers and directors,  and specialized contract litigation. They also have broad experience in all aspects of arbitration,  mediation,  and virtually all types of alternative dispute resolution techniques.
<P><BR><P>Representative commercial litigation clients include ADT Security Systems,  Inc.; Advanced Micro Devices,  Inc.; Apple Computer,  Inc; Arthur Andersen LLP; Coopers  & Lybrand L.L.P.; Federal Express; Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation; Fleming Companies,  Inc.; Gulfstream Aerospace; Hambrecht  & Quist; International Business Machines Corporation; Jardine Insurance Brokers; Marcus  & Millichap; PACCAR,  Inc.; Pacific Gas  & Electric Company; Pharmacia AB; Russian National Orchestra; Sanwa Bank; The First Boston Corp.; The Hillman Company; Varian Associates,  Inc.; Westamerica Bank; and Westinghouse Electric Corporation.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Richard A. Ardoin</B> is the managing partner of the firm. His practice emphasizes securities and professional liability defense litigation. Rich's experience includes litigation and trial representation of brokerage firms,  individuals,  governmental agencies,  receiverships,  and banks in business tort,  securities,  and contract actions.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Alexander L. Brainerd</B> is a member of the firm's Management Committee. His practice emphasizes intellectual property,  securities,  antitrust,  and construction litigation including representation of owners,  contractors,  and design professionals. Lex is a member of the American College of Trial Lawyers.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Carlyn Clause</B> handles complex business litigation in both federal and state courts. Her practice emphasizes intellectual property litigation,  including unfair competition,  trade secrets,  and trademarks,  antitrust litigation and counseling,  and securities class action litigation. Her other areas of expertise include shareholder derivative actions,  lender liability,  and commercial contract litigation.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Stephen H. Dye</B> has substantial commercial litigation experience in lender liability,  real estate,  and professional liability litigation. Steve also handles matters involving a variety of specialized commercial contracts.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>David Eiseman</B> specializes in complex business litigation in the federal courts. His practice focuses on intellectual property litigation including patent,  copyright,  and trade secrets/unfair competition litigation.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Frederick S. Fields</B> has over 30 years of extensive trial experience. His practice specializes in the defense of officers and directors,  accounting malpractice cases,  and class action securities matters,  as well as a wide spectrum of business and corporate matters.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Kenneth E. Keller</B> specializes in complex commercial litigation,  with an emphasis on intellectual property litigation. His practice also covers environmental matters,  white collar crime,  financial institutions,  and the defense of licensed professionals,  including attorneys,  architects,  engineers,  and health care practitioners. Ken is a member of the American Board of Trial Advocates.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Richard C. Macias</B> has substantial commercial litigation experience representing national and international trade suppliers,  manufacturers,  and financial institutions in litigation involving contract enforcement actions,  bankruptcy,  business transactions,  antitrust,  and dealer terminations.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Robert N. Phillips</B>' practice emphasizes secured financing litigation,  foreclosures,  real estate receiverships,  and joint venture/partnership litigation. Rob's litigation experience involves complex matters in state and federal court,  as well as in adversary proceedings in bankruptcy.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Stan G. Roman</B>'s practice consists primarily of complex business litigation,  often involving the representation of accountants,  attorneys,  and corporate officers and directors.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Robert J. Stumpf,  Jr.</B> practices in the area of banking litigation,  securities litigation,  contract and partnership disputes,  unfair competition,  real estate litigation,  bankruptcy litigation,  and other types of business litigation,  often involving class actions. Bob is the chair of the Commercial Litigation Department and of the firm's Appellate Department.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Keith R. Weed</B> specializes in intellectual property,  securities,  and trade related litigation. Keith has substantial experience in litigation matters involving class actions as well as NASD and AAA arbitration and SEC investigations.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
