<HEAD>
<TITLE>Covington  & Burling
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Commercial Litigation</H2>
<H3>Covington  & Burling
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington:</B> 1201 Pennsylvania Avenue,  N.W.,  P.O. Box 7566, <BR>
Washington,  DC 20044-7566<BR>
Tel 202-662-6000  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-662-6291  <B>*</B>  E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:glevy@cov.com">glevy@cov.com</A><BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Brussels,  London<BR>
<BR>
300 lawyers  <B>*</B>  150 lawyers in litigation<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/covington.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/covington.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>C</B>ovington  & Burling,  founded 75 years ago,  is one of the largest law firms in Washington,  D.C.,  and also has more than 20 lawyers in Europe. The firm's practice includes advice and representation in regulatory and legislative matters,  litigation,  and transactional work both here and abroad.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>The Litigation Practice Group</H3></CENTER>

<P>Throughout its history,  Covington  & Burling's practice has been heavily concentrated on the litigation of complex,  difficult,  important,  and novel matters. The firm's litigation practice continues to reflect those characteristics and today runs the gamut of subject-matter areas,  including antitrust,  employment,  environmental,  insurance coverage,  intellectual property,  product liability,  professional responsibility,  securities,  toxic tort,  and regulatory cases in judicial,  arbitral,  and administrative forums across the country and overseas. The hallmarks of our litigation practice are mastery of the law,  the formulation and execution of effective and creative strategies,  cost-sensitive case management,  and adherence to the highest professional standards.<BR><BR><P>Many of our cases require us to navigate undeveloped and uncertain areas of law and fact. Last year,  for example,  in a case presenting novel questions of commodities law pertinent to foreign currency derivatives trading,  the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit affirmed a substantial trial court judgment that we had obtained for our client,  a subsidiary of Salomon Brothers. <B>Eugene Gulland </B>and<B> William Iverson</B>,  who took the lead in that litigation,  have each handled many major litigation matters in the antitrust and securities fields.<BR>
<BR>
<P>In the intellectual property area,  we have filed pathbreaking lawsuits to curb the importation of gray market goods. On behalf of Parfums Givenchy,  we recently obtained a Ninth Circuit affirmance of an injunction barring such imports under the copyright laws. Our wide-ranging intellectual property practice has also included recent trial representations of AT &T,  the American Petroleum Institute,  the National Football League,  and Sun Life of Canada. <B>Charles Buffon</B>,  who has substantial experience in various areas of commercial litigation,  leads the firm's intellectual property litigation practice.<BR><BR><P>The firm's ability to operate in uncharted areas and successfully to take major cases to trial is evidenced by our pioneering representation of corporate policyholders in lawsuits against their insurance carriers. <B>Robert Sayler</B>,  who recently served as chair of the ABA's Section of Litigation,  was lead trial counsel for Armstrong World Industries in the California coordinated asbestos insurance coverage litigation,  said to be the lengthiest civil trial in United States history. The firm's success at the trial of that case was replicated when we later obtained for Boeing the first jury verdict for a major corporate insured in an environmental insurance coverage case. The successes of the firm in this area have steadily mounted,  and include victories in trials and arbitrations,  as well as through highly favorable settlements.<BR>
<BR><P>Our track record in more traditional areas of litigation is equally strong. <B>Peter Nickles</B>, <B> Herbert Dym</B>,  and<B> Joanne Grossman</B>,  whose work reflects the breadth of the firm's litigation practice,  have substantial experience defending complex toxic tort and product liability cases,  including cases pursued as class actions or on a coordinated basis. <B>Bruce Baird</B>,  who headed the securities fraud unit of the U.S. Attorney's office in New York City,  is a mainstay of the firm's criminal and securities fraud practices. <B>Jeffrey Huvelle</B>,  who secured a jury verdict for the defense earlier this year in a race discrimination lawsuit against the World Football League,  also represents IBM and other companies throughout the country in employment cases.<BR>
<BR><P><B>Bobby Burchfield</B> and<B> Mark Lynch</B>,  whose litigation practices span numerous subject-matter areas,  recently played leading roles in the firm's successful efforts to extricate National Medical Enterprises from a maze of civil lawsuits and criminal investigations. <B>Arvid Roach</B>,  whose roster of litigation clients includes Union Pacific,  has an impressive array of successes in transportation and pension-related matters. Finally,  while many of the firm's trial lawyers are experienced appellate advocates,  <B>Edward Bruce</B> is widely recognized for his work in appeals courts throughout the country and in the Supreme Court.<BR>
<BR><P><B>Gregg Levy</B>,  whose antitrust work has included recent victories for the National Football League,  and <B>Mitchell Dolin</B>,  who represents Exxon and other policyholders in insurance coverage lawsuits,  coordinate the firm's 150-lawyer litigation practice group and are available to provide additional information.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>




</UL></BODY>
