<TITLE>Dow,  Lohnes  & Albertson
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Commercial Litigation</H2>
<H3>Dow,  Lohnes  & Albertson
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington:</B> 1255 23rd Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20037-1194<BR>
Tel 202-857-2500  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-857-2900<BR>
<B>Atlanta:</B> One Ravinia Drive,  Suite 1600,  Atlanta,  GA 30346-2108<BR>
Tel 404-901-8800  <B>*</B>  Fax 404-901-8874<BR>
<BR>
130 lawyers  <B>*</B>  25 litigators<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>F</B>ounded in 1918,  Dow,  Lohnes  & Albertson (DL &A) is a national law firm with a substantial commercial litigation practice. Long known as one of the country's preeminent media law firms,  DL &A also specializes in representing high-technology and health care companies,  and educational and non-profit institutions. It has extensive experience in representing such companies in a wide variety of court cases and administrative proceedings,  both as plaintiffs and defendants,  as well as in government investigations.<BR>
<P>DL &A's litigation practice was rated one of the highest for service,  quality and value in a national survey of 400 in-house lawyers published in <I>The American Lawyer</I> (`Client's Choice, ' January-February 1995). Its commercial litigators have litigated numerous business tort,  antitrust,  securities,  tax,  complex contracts,  intellectual property,  libel,  fraud,  RICO,  and government contract suits. Its litigation partners include many lawyers with government experience,  including several former assistant U.S. attorneys with substantial trial experience.<BR><P>Representative clients: Act III Broadcasting,  Inc.; Advance Publications,  Inc.; Airline Tariff Publishing Company; The Atlanta Journal and Constitution; Broadcast Capital,  Inc.; California Community Colleges; Charter Medical Corporation; Comcast Corporation; Cox Enterprises,  Inc.; Eaton Corporation; the estates of MaLColm Forbes,  Joseph Lauder,  and S.I. Newhouse; The Evening Post Publishing Co.; First Media Corporation; George Washington University; Gannett Co.,  Inc.; Hawaiian Airlines,  Inc.; Louis Harris  & Associates; Manheim Auctions,  Inc.; MetroVision,  Inc.; Phillips Colleges,  Inc.; Primestar Partners,  L.P.; State University of New York; Time Inc.; The Toledo Blade; Vanguard Cellular Communications,  Inc; Wheelabrator,  Inc.<BR>
<P>A partial list of DL &A litigators follows. Unless otherwise noted,  the lawyer is located in DL &A's Washington,  D.C. office.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Peter C. Canfield</B> (<I>Atlanta</I>) Mr. Canfield represents communications companies as to newsgathering and publication issues,  telecommunications,  regulatory matters,  and advertising,  antitrust,  intellectual property,  and business tort and contract disputes. He clerked for Judge Frank M. Johnson,  Jr.,  U.S. Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit and Judge Myron Thompson,  U.S. District Court for the Middle District of Alabama. A former prosecutor and Justice Department civil rights attorney,  he graduated from Amherst College in 1976 and was an editor of the <I>Yale Law School Journal</I>.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Jonathan D. Hart</B> Mr. Hart specializes in the representation of media companies in libel,  privacy,  and related newsgathering tort litigation; constitutional litigation; and administrative appellate litigation. He clerked for Chief Judge Almeric L. Christian of the U.S. District Court for the Virgin Islands,  and for Judge Jerome Farris of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit. Mr. Hart is a graduate of Middlebury College and Stanford Law School.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Michael D. Hays</B> A former assistant U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia who has tried dozens of jury trials,  Mr. Hays has represented broadcast,  cable,  cellular telephone,  and high-technology manufacturing companies in securities fraud,  defamation,  breach of contract,  business torts,  and trade secret actions and individuals and companies in various investigations. He is a 1970 graduate of Princeton University,  was an editor of the <I>Georgetown Law Journal</I>,  and clerked for Judge Lloyd F. MacMahon,  U.S. District Court Judge for the Southern District of New York.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Jonathan B. Hill</B> Mr. Hill represents a variety of companies in fields ranging from complex antitrust issues to commercial letters of credit. A former litigating attorney with the U.S. Department of Transportation,  he has litigated for companies in the aviation,  environment,  publishing,  transportation,  and retail businesses. Mr. Hill is a graduate of Colby College and Boston University Law School.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Judith A. Mather</B> A former deputy assistant general counsel for the U.S. Department of Energy,  Ms. Mather has represented environmental,  broadcasting,  and cable companies in complex business litigation involving claims of fraud and other business torts,  and in contract,  franchising,  and programming disputes. Ms. Mather clerked for Judge Herbert F. Murray,  U.S. District Court Judge for the District of Maryland,  and was an editor of Georgetown University's <I>Law And Policy In International Business</I>.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>David E. Mills</B> Mr. Mills is a former assistant U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia,  where he handled dozens of jury and bench trials and conducted numerous grand jury investigations. He represents a wide variety of businesses and individuals in commercial tort and contract litigation; in intellectual property,  antitrust,  and consumer protection cases; and in government investigations. He graduated from Brandeis University and Duke University School of Law.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Timothy J. O'Rourke</B> Mr. O'Rourke has represented broadcasters,  cable companies,  newspaper publishers,  and a major health care provider in government antitrust investigations as well as in private Sherman Act litigation and counseling and business tort and related commercial litigation. Mr. O'Rourke is a former deputy assistant attorney general of the U.S. Department of Justice and a 1981 graduate of the University of Virginia School of Law.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>James A. Treanor</B> Mr. Treanor served as law clerk to Chief Judge Matthew F. McGuire,  U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia and later as an assistant U.S. attorney in Washington,  D.C. Mr. Treanor has represented newspapers,  magazines,  television stations,  radio stations,  and cable systems in private antitrust litigation,  in merger investigations initiated by the Department of Justice and the Federal Trade Commission,  and in a wide variety of commercial disputes and government investigations. He is a 1960 graduate of The College of Holy Cross and a 1965 graduate of Fordham University School of Law.<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
