<CENTER>
<H2>Commercial Litigation</H2>
<H3>Dyer,  Ellis,  Joseph  & Mills
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington:</B> 600 New Hampshire Avenue,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20037<BR>
Tel 202-944-3000  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-944-3068<BR>
<BR>
30 lawyers  <B>*</B>  8 lawyers concentrating in litigation<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>O</B>ur Washington-based national litigation practice has focused on substantial,  non-routine controversies presenting a variety of complex regulatory,  economic,  accounting,  and contract issues. Recent cases have involved the federal securities laws,  the Bankruptcy Code,  secured transactions,  federal procurement law,  admiralty,  and judicial review of federal agency actions.<BR><P>Our litigation group is experienced in prosecuting and defending cases before federal and state courts,  at both trial and appellate levels,  and before federal agencies and contract appeals boards. We also regularly participate in arbitration,  mediation,  and other forms of alternative dispute resolution. We are accustomed to handling matters requiring emergency injunctive relief.<BR><P>We are a relatively small litigation group,  committed to efficient case management through litigation risk analysis,  effective use of paralegal personnel,  and computerization.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Michael Joseph</B>,  who heads the firm's litigation group,  has had more than 30 years of experience in complex litigation,  having begun his career as a trial and appellate lawyer in the Office of the General Counsel of the SEC. Since entering private practice in the mid-1960s,  he has handled a variety of government and private contract disputes and cases arising under various regulatory statutes,  including the antitrust laws and other statutes regulating the transportation and health care industries.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Alex Blanton</B>,  in over two decades of litigating controversies concerning federal agency decisions affecting commercial property rights,  has developed considerable expertise in administrative law. In addition,  he has had extensive experience in litigating a broad range of issues affecting maritime commerce and fisheries,  ship construction and repair,  and the marine environment.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard A. Kirby</B> specializes in securities litigation and bankruptcy reorganization. Mr. Kirby also has nearly 20 years of litigation experience and spent a number of years in the General Counsel's Office of the SEC,  where he headed up the SEC's reorganization work and litigated many significant SEC cases. He also has applied various alternative dispute resolution techniques to the settlement of large complex securities fraud actions.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Wayne A. Keup</B> has over 15 years of litigation experience with an emphasis in federal procurement law. Before entering private practice,  he served as a procurement attorney and as a senior trial attorney with the Office of the General Counsel,  Department of the Navy. He currently represents clients in the prosecution of a variety of claims relating to the formation and performance of prime contracts and subcontracts. <BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Joseph O. Click</B> developed expertise in litigating complex legal issues while serving two years as a staff attorney with the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit,  and two years with the appellate litigation group in the General Counsel's Office of the SEC. His litigation experience with the firm has covered the spectrum of the firm's litigation practice,  with particular emphasis on bankruptcy,  securities fraud,  and federal agency litigation.
</UL>


