<HEAD>
<TITLE>Hall  & Evans,  L.L.C.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Commercial Litigation</H2>
<H3>Hall  & Evans,  L.L.C.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Denver:</B> Suite 1700,  1200 Seventeenth Street,  Denver,  CO 80202-5800<BR>
Tel 303-628-3300  <B>*</B>  Fax 303-628-3368<BR>
<B>Colorado Springs: </B>Suite 600,  102 South Tejon,  Colorado Springs,  CO 80904-2264<BR>
Tel 719-578-5600  <B>*</B>  Fax 719-635-7458<BR>
<BR>
77 lawyers  <B>*</B>  49 lawyers in commercial litigation<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/hall.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/hall.html"> ERISA</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/hall.html"> Labor</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>H</B>all  & Evans is one of the largest firms in the Rocky Mountain Region,  and we have provided legal services in litigation,  business,  and insurance law for over 60 years. Our practice includes class action and multidistrict litigation at the regional and national levels,  and our commercial litigators address:<BR><UL><BR>
<LI> Antitrust<LI>Aviation<LI>Bankruptcy<LI>Contracts<LI>Commercial Finance<LI>Computers<LI>Construction>LI>Employment<LI>Entertainment<LI>Environmental<LI>ERISA<LI>Franchise<LI>Insurance and reinsurance<LI>Intellectual property<LI>Lender Liability<LI>Loan Transaction<LI>Professional Malpractice<LI>Media/Communications<LI>Oil and gas<LI>Products liability<LI>Public Utilities<LI>Real estate<LI>Regulatory Compliance<LI>RICO/COCCA<LI>Securities<LI>Transportation
<BR></UL>
<BR><LI><B>C. Willing Browne</B> directs the firm's transportation litigation,  defending railroads and trucking entities in lawsuits throughout the Rocky Mountain Region. He currently represents Amtrak in all Colorado litigation.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Eugene R. Commander </B>and<B> Jeffery B. Stalder</B> represent clients from virtually every sector of the real estate and construction industry in litigation involving lease and construction contract disputes,  construction defects and product failures,  mechanic's liens and fee collection proceedings,  bonding and insurance matters,  malpractice claims against construction industry professionals,  and professional licensing and disciplinary issues. Additionally the firm arbitrates construction claims both on behalf of involved parties and as the neutral arbitrator or mediator. Clients include La Farge Concrete Products,  Construction Management Technology,  Inc.,  Haselden Construction,  Inc.,  and Frank M. Hall  & Co.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Paul R. Franke III</B> directs the firm's representation of financial institutions and coordinates complex litigation involving lender liability; loan collection; and related financial,  regulatory,  and commercial litigation issues such as suits against directors and officers of failed institutions. Clients include Great Financial Bank,  PMI Mortgage Insurance,  and First Denver Mortgage Company.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Charles Greenhouse</B> heads the firm's practice in creditor's rights and bankruptcy,  representing financial entities,  insurance companies,  and other institutional clients. He has tried numerous adversary proceedings and contested matters in the bankruptcy court,  and he also litigates commercial matters concerning oil and gas,  accounting,  and contracts. Clients include Halliburton Company and Guaranty Bank  & Trust.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Peter F. Jones</B>, <B> James W. Britt</B>, <B> </B>and<B> Kevin E. O'Brien</B> lead the firm's Product Liability Group,  which represents manufacturers of a wide range of commercial and industrial products including pharmaceuticals,  automobiles,  trucks,  ATVs,  computer equipment,  and hazardous materials. The firm also defends third-party actions and advises clients on risk management and state-of-the-art issues and government regulations. Under their direction the firm serves as national counsel to Chrysler Corporation and Northern Telecom (NORTEL).<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Chris A. Mattison</B> is the chair of the firm's Environmental and Toxic Tort Group. He directed the successful defense of the Denver Water Board in <I>Renaud </I>v.<I> Martin Marietta Corp.</I>,  a landmark toxic tort case in Colorado.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>John D. Phillips,  Jr.</B>,  directs the firm in antitrust,  securities,  libel and slander,  civil RICO and COCCA,  franchise,  professional malpractice,  and aviation litigation. He has served as lead counsel to Panhandle Eastern Pipe Line Corporation in the defense of multimillion-dollar take-or-pay claims arising from natural gas purchase contracts and defends complex securities fraud cases throughout the southwestern United States.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Daniel R. Satriana,  Jr.</B>,  and<B> Cathy Havener Greer</B> lead the firm's Employ- ment Practice Group,  representing employers in claims involving discrimination,  civil rights,  wrongful discharge,  noncompetition covenants,  the Fair Labor Standards Act,  libel and slander,  and invasion of privacy. Mr. Satriana also litigates entertainment issues on behalf of media and communications entities. Clients include Continental Airlines,  Inc.,  EG &G Rocky Flats,  Inc.,  Monfort,  Inc.,  Kmart Corporation,  and Jacor Broadcasting of Colorado,  Inc.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>David N. Schachter</B>,  from California's Silicon Valley,  oversees the firm's work in financing,  development,  protection,  and transfer of intellectual property for clients ranging from venture start-up enterprises to public corporations. We litigate cases involving trademark,  copyright,  and patent infringement; computer law; unfair competition; and trade secret theft.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Edward H. Widmann </B>and<B> Clinton P. Swift</B> direct the defense of complex insurance litigation,  addressing ERISA plans and claims concerning ERISA's preemption,  fiduciary obligations,  reporting,  and disclosure requirements; MEWA-related issues; Department of Labor audits; wrongful denial of health,  disability,  life,  or accidental death benefits; and COBRA or conversion issues. They also defend and monitor director and officer litigation,  and Mr. Swift litigates public utilities issues. Clients include the AIG entities,  the Chubb Group of Insurance Companies,  Lincoln Trust Company,  and Whittaker Corporation.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</UL><BR>


