<HEAD>
<TITLE>Hedlund Hanley  & John
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Commercial Litigation</H2>
<H3>Hedlund Hanley  & John
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Chicago:</B> Sears Tower,  Suite 5700,  233 S. Wacker Drive,  Chicago,  IL 60606<BR>
Tel 312-441-8600  <B>*</B>  Fax 312- 441-8666<BR>
<BR>
18 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers practice in complex business litigation<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>H</B>edlund Hanley  & John was founded in 1991 on the idea that a medium-sized law firm,  confining its practice to advocacy and related disciplines such as environmental law,  can provide more effective representation in sophisticated,  complex litigation and at less cost than is typically provided by large,  general practice firms.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Complex Business Litigation</H3></CENTER>

<P>Hedlund Hanley  & John represents companies of all sizes in business litigation  throughout the federal and state court systems of the United States. Its attorneys have experience in virtually every facet of corporate and commercial litigation.<B><BR><P></B>The firm's clients include: Ashland Oil Company; Glaxo,  Inc.; Envirotech-Illinois,  Inc.; Indeck Energy Services,  Inc.; Johnson  & Johnson; MacMillan,  Inc.; Medline Industries,  Inc.; Montgomery Ward; Sears,  Roebuck and Company; Tenneco,  Inc.; Trinova Corporation; USG Corporation; and Unitrin,  Inc.<BR>
<BR><P>The following lawyers are partners in the firm.<BR>
<BR><UL><LI><B>Reuben L. Hedlund</B> Mr. Hedlund is a founding partner of the firm and has specialized in the trial and appeal of cases involving securities fraud,  shareholder rights,  antitrust claims,  construction claims,  consumer class actions,  accountant's liability,  and corporate takeovers. Listed in <I>The Best Lawyers in America</I>. Fellow,  American College of Trial Lawyers. Currently chairman,  Chicago Plan Commission; member,  Board of Governors,  Seventh Circuit Bar Association; director,  Unitrin,  Inc. Coauthor,  `Another View of Expediting the Large,  Complex Case, ' 6 <I>Ohio State Journal on Dispute Resolution</I> 61,  1990. University of Chicago and Denison University,  B.A.,  1956; Yale University,  LL.B.,  1959; member,  board of editors,  <I>Yale Law Journal</I>,  1957-1959.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Peter C. John</B> Mr. John has tried numerous jury and nonjury cases involving commercial contract disputes,  merger and acquisition contracts,  products liability,  professional malpractice,  and personal injury defense. Listed in <I>The Best Lawyers in America</I>. Fellow,  American College of Trial Lawyers; Illinois Society of Trial Lawyers; American Board of Trial Advocates. Member,  Illinois Supreme Court Committee on Jury Instructions in Civil Cases,  1988- ; International Academy of Trial Lawyers. Coauthor,  `The New Legal Malpractice Statute of Repose and Pre-Existing Claims, ' <I>Illinois Bar Journal</I>,  October 1993,  Volume 81. Author,  Illinois State Bar Association LAW ED Program Trial Evidence,  `Discovery Under Rule 220 Expert Witnesses, ' 1990. Cornell University,  A.B.,  1963; Villanova University,  LL.B.,  1966; member,  <I>Villanova Law Review</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Charles L. Glick</B> Mr. Glick has experience in international financial litigation; securities laws actions; merger,  acquisition,  and proxy fight litigation; accountant's liability; shareholder suits; banking and workout litigation; U.S. and foreign governmental investigations; multijurisdictional disputes; commodities brokerage litigation; and real estate investment litigation. Indiana University,  B.A.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1976; Yale Law School,  J.D.,  1982; Phi Beta Kappa; senior editor,  <I>Yale Law Journal</I>,  1981-1982.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Marion B. Adler</B> Ms. Adler specializes in complex insurance coverage law,  as well as having experience in a variety of commercial disputes,  including statutory and common law consumer claims,  products liability,  employment matters,  international arbitration,  and appellate advocacy. Author,  `Appellate Advocacy and Complex Insurance Disputes, ' in <I>Trying Insurance Coverage Disputes</I> (National Law Journal Press,  1995). Speaker,  `New Twists on the Trigger and Scope of Coverage' at the American Bar Association,  Litigation Section,  Insurance Coverage Litigation Committee,  1993. Middlebury College,  A.B.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1976; Yale University,  M.A.,  political science,  1977; University of Chicago,  J.D.,  with honors,  1982; Phi Beta Kappa.; associate editor,  <I>University of Chicago Law Review</I>,  1981-1982; Order of the Coif; J.H. Beale Prize for excellence in writing.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kay L. Pick</B> Ms. Pick handles environmental actions,  and her practice includes representation in multiparty environmental matters,  defense of clients before environmental enforcement authorities,  regulatory and transactional work,  counseling on compliance with environmental laws,  and liability in acquisition,  sales,  and financial transactions. Author,  `Environmental Law, ' IICLE,  <I>Starting Points: The Fundamentals of 11 Practice Areas</I>,  1994; `Responsible Property Transfer Act: A Trap for the Unwary, ' <I>CBA Record</I>,  February 1989. University of Rochester,  B.A.,  with honors,  1966; DePaul University College of Law,  J.D.,  1980.<BR><BR><LI><B>Steven J. Roeder</B> Mr. Roeder specializes in real estate,  construction,  securities,  and other complex commercial litigation; and has broad experience in civil litigation involving trials and preliminary injunction proceedings in state and federal courts before both judges and juries. University of Chicago,  B.A.,  with honors,  M.A.,  1980; University of Illinois,  J.D.,  1984; editor,  <I>University of Illinois Law Review</I>,  1983-1984; Rickert Award for Excellence in Legal Writing.<BR></UL>

</UL></BODY>
