<HEAD>
<TITLE>Ice Miller Donadio  & Ryan
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Commercial Litigation</H2>
<H3>Ice Miller Donadio  & Ryan
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Indianapolis:</B> One American Square,  Box 82001,  Indianapolis,  IN 46282-0002<BR>
Tel 317-236-2100  <B>*</B>  Fax 317-236-2219<BR>
<BR>
164 lawyers  <B>*</B>  60 lawyers in litigation practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>P</B>roviding our clients with cost-effective,  quality service has placed Ice Miller at the forefront of Indiana litigation for many years. Our clients draw upon a long tradition of experience in trial and appellate litigation as well as arbitration and mediation. This experience is key to our ability to serve each client's special needs for case management,  cost containment,  and quality legal services. The Firm's litigators are regularly called upon to pursue or defend claims or to plan a litigation avoidance strategy in areas such as securities litigation,  antitrust and trade regulation,  commercial transactions,  franchising,  employee benefits,  creditors' rights and bankruptcy,  product liability,  mining law,  media law,  directors and officers liability,  intellectual property,  and construction law.<BR>
<P>Ice Miller's Intellectual Property Group handles complex litigation in a wide range of areas including patents,  trademarks,  copyrights,  licensing,  computer law,  and trade secrets. Our Employee Benefits Group regularly represents employers,  officers,  plans,  insurance companies,  third-party administrators,  and other service providers in benefits disputes and litigation. These matters include such claims as fiduciary breach,  prohibited transactions,  and defects in plan administration.<BR><P>Our litigators have represented many different industries in all types of private antitrust litigation. The firm also handles antitrust matters on behalf of state and local governmental entities.<BR>
<P>Since the inception of modern product liability law,  many national manufacturers have been defended by Ice Miller in lawsuits involving a diverse range of products. Ice Miller also handles drug and chemical product litigation. We serve as national counsel in toxic tort litigation involving allegations of adverse health effects from chemical exposure. We also serve as Indiana counsel for manufacturers in litigation involving numerous prescription drug products,  vaccines,  and medical devices.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Evan E. Steger</B> Mr. Steger has extensive experience in all phases of commercial litigation,  particularly in the substantive areas of franchise law,  dealer/distributor litigation,  product liability,  intellectual property,  and labor relations. Recent significant cases include class actions involving alleged securities law violations and a dispute between the minority and majority shareholders of a closely held corporation concerning the effect of a restrictive stock transfer agreement. Mr. Steger is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers and has been recognized in <I>The Best Lawyers in America</I> in the area of corporate litigation. Indiana University,  J.D.,  1962.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Arthur P. Kalleres</B> Mr. Kalleres represents numerous commercial entities. He concentrates in the areas of business litigation,  construction law,  employee benefits,  and legal risk management. He has recently handled complex class action litigation involving Indiana's Public Employees' Retirement Fund and several significant commercial and legal malpractice suits. Mr. Kalleres has been a managing partner since 1987. He is a fellow in the American College of Trial Lawyers and is listed in <I>The Best Lawyers in America </I>in business litigation. Indiana University,  J.D.,  1966.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James L. Petersen</B> Mr. Petersen has handled a variety of commercial matters including employee benefits,  contract disputes,  Uniform Commercial Code litigation,  franchise terminations,  and product liability. Mr. Petersen is a member of the International Association of Defense Counsel and its Business Litigation and Product Liability Committees,  and the American Bar Association's Forum Committee on Franchising. Indiana University,  J.D.,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Philip A. Whistler</B> Mr. Whistler has represented numerous business clients in both litigation and mediation in state and federal courts throughout Indiana and in other states. His practice includes antitrust,  franchising,  distribution law,  business torts,  and other complex commercial litigation. He is a member of the Civil Justice Reform Act Advisory Committee for the U.S. District Court for the Southern District of Indiana. Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jay G. Taylor</B> Mr. Taylor concentrates in intellectual property litigation including patent,  copyright,  and trademark matters. He has litigated numerous disputes in state and federal courts. He serves as the head of the Firm's Intellectual Property Department. He is a member of the American Intellectual Property Law Association. Indiana University,  J.D.,  1967.<BR>
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
