<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Kramer,  Levin,  Naftalis  & Frankel</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL><CENTER><H2>Commercial Litigation</H2><H3>Kramer,  Levin,  Naftalis  & Frankel</H3></CENTER><CENTER><B>New York:</B> 919 Third Avenue,  New York,  NY 10022<BR>Tel. 212-715-9100  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-715-8000<BR> <B>*</B> Home page: <A HREF="http://www.kramer-levin.com/">www.kramer-levin.com</A><BR><BR>140 lawyers  <B>*</B>  41 lawyers concentrating in complex business litigation<BR></CENTER><P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR><UL><BR>   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/kramer.html"> Antitrust</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/kramer.html"> Corporate Securities</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/kramer.html"> ERISA</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/kramer.html"> Intellectual Property</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/kramer.html"> Labor</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/kramer.html"> Product Liability</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/kramer.html"> White Collar Crime</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/kramer.html"> Workout</A></UL><P><P><P><B>C</B>omplex litigation is central to our practice,  covering the entire spectrum of business problems important to manufacturing and financial services firms,  multinational businesses,  entrepreneurs,  and government entities. Our litigators are also trained in and frequently use alternative dispute resolution.<BR><BR><P>Our litigation capabilities match the size and diversity of our clients. We recently obtained a multimillion-dollar jury verdict,  including punitive damages,  against John Z. DeLorean for breach of contract and fraud upon his former lawyers. For The Procter  & Gamble Company,  we have handled false advertising and product liability cases,  as well as franchise,  real estate,  and accounting disputes. We represent Liz Claiborne,  Inc. in class action securities litigation and actions to enforce its trademarks and license agreements. We also represent various professionals in highly publicized securities,  RICO,  and antitrust litigations,  including cases brought by Ticketmaster-New York,  Inc.; the asbestos manufacturer Keene Corporation; and investors in the failed Towers Financial Corporation.<BR><P>We recently defended Kidder,  Peabody in litigation brought by MAXUS Inc. arising out of insider trading by Ivan Boesky and Wickes Companies in a novel and complex class action suit. We regularly represent bidders,  targets,  and independent committees of directors in corporate control and investment litigation.<BR><BR><P>Other clients have included General Electric Company and affiliates,  MAXXAM Inc.,  Wal-Mart Stores,  Inc.,  and Long Island Lighting Company in major securities and commercial cases; the National Music Publishers' Association and several prominent performers in copyright litigation in the U.S. Supreme Court and other federal courts; Tuscan Dairy Farms Inc. in commercial and antitrust matters; and professionals,  fiduciaries,  and officers and directors in complex liability disputes.<BR><BR><P>In addition,  white collar criminal defense,  including SEC proceedings and other administrative agency enforcement actions,  has long been an integral part of our practice. We represent institutions and individuals in all phases of criminal matters,  from investigation through trial and on appeal.<BR><BR><P>We also represent a variety of companies and institutions through our growing employment and labor practice,  headed by <B>Kevin B. Leblang</B>,  and have substantial experience in ERISA and other fiduciary litigation.<BR><UL><BR><LI><B>Marvin E. Frankel</B> chairs our litigation practice. Formerly a U.S. District Judge in the Southern District of New York,  Mr. Frankel has argued more than 20 cases in the U.S. Supreme Court,  including,  in recent terms,  leading cases involving antitrust and copyright law. His practice focuses on securities,  employment,  and intellectual property litigation,  and he often serves as a mediator and arbitrator.<BR><BR><LI><B>Gary P. Naftalis</B> One of the nation's leading trial lawyers,  Mr. Naftalis served as an assistant U.S. Attorney in New York for seven years,  holding the title of deputy chief of the criminal division. Recent matters include successful representations of Saudi Arabian banker Sheikh Khalid Bin Mahfouz relating to the demise of the Bank of Commerce and Credit International; Salomon Brothers in the federal criminal and SEC investigations of U.S. Treasury auction bidding practices; and Kidder,  Peabody in the Wall Street insider trading scandals.<BR><BR><LI><B>Michael J. Dell,  David S. Frankel,  Alan R. Friedman,  Thomas H. Moreland,  Ellen R. Nadler,  </B>and<B> Jeffrey S. Trachtman</B> concentrate on complex securities litigation,  as well as corporate control and proxy contests. Recent representations include MAXXAM Inc. and The Pacific Lumber Company in class action securities litigation; investor groups in proxy fights involving Hills Stores Company,  Marietta Corp. and Van Dorn; and the successful representation of major shareholders of Cities Service Company in litigation against Gulf Oil arising out of its terminated tender offer for Cities,  resulting in one of the largest arbitration awards ever rendered in a commercial dispute.<BR><BR><LI><B>Harold P. Weinberger </B>and <B>Michael S. Oberman</B> Mr. Weinberger concentrates on false advertising and product disparagement,  including recent matters for The Procter  & Gamble Company and Johnson  & Johnson. Mr. Oberman handles copyright and trademark cases,  representing clients such as the National Music Publishers Association.<BR><BR><LI><B>Robert M. Heller</B> handles the full range of antitrust and trade regulation matters. Recent matters include representation of a major investment banking firm in the NASDAQ market-maker antitrust and securities litigation,  and prosecuting monopolization and tying claims on behalf of a Johnson  & Johnson subsidiary against Abbott Laboratories.<BR><BR><LI><B>Charlotte M. Fischman,  Philip S. Kaufman,  </B>and<B> Arthur H. Aufses III </B>specialize in lender and professional liability litigation,  representing lending banks and corporate borrowers,  as well as investment banking,  accounting,  and law firms. Major bank clients have included Bank of New York,  Banque Nationale de Paris,  UMB Bank and Trust Company,  and Anchor Savings Bank.<BR><BR></UL></UL></BODY></HTML>
