<HEAD>
<TITLE>Leonard,  Street and Deinard
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Commercial Litigation</H2>
<H3>Leonard,  Streetand Deinard
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Minneapolis:</B> Suite 2300,  150 South Fifth Street,  Minneapolis,  MN 55402<BR>
Tel 612-335-1500  <B>*</B>  Fax 612-335-1657  <B>*</B>  E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:JGB1512@email.leonard.com">JGB1512@email.leonard.com</A><BR>
<BR>
130 lawyers  <B>*</B>  68 lawyers in the litigation practice  <B>*</B>  26 lawyers concentrating<BR>
in complex commercial litigation<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>L</B>eonard,  Street and Deinard is a full-service law firm with a business and litigation practice reaching throughout Minnesota and the Upper Midwest. Our litigation practice is enhanced and supported by our business practice in the areas of corporate,  securities,  banking,  real estate,  bankruptcy,  employee benefits,  tax,  environmental,  health care,  intellectual property,  governmental relations,  and trade regulation.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>The Commercial Litigation Practice</H3></CENTER><BR><BR>
<P>Litigation comprises about half of the firm's practice,  and we have specialized litigation departments in the areas of construction law,  employment law,  environmental law,  products liability,  and real estate valuation. In addition,  the Commercial Litigation Department handles complex litigation in the following areas:<BR>
<BR><UL><LI>Antitrust<LI>Advertising<LI>Banking<LI>Bankruptcy<LI>Copyrights<LI>Dealer Terminations<LI>ERISA<LI>Fiduciary Duty<LI>Franchising<LI>Fraud<LI>Insurance<LI>Lender Liability<LI>Patents<LI>Product Disparagement<LI>Professional Liability<LI>RICO<LI>Securities<LI>Trade Libel<LI>Trade Secrets<LI>Trademarks<LI>Trusts<LI>Unfair Competition<LI>White Collar Crime<LI> RICO<BR>
</UL><BR>
<P>The commercial litigation practice involves a diverse group of clients,  including large and medium-sized corporations,  lending institutions,  and individuals from all parts of the country. We regularly appear in both state and federal court,  and we pride ourselves on providing cost-effective solutions to commercial litigation problems.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Representative Clients</H3></CENTER>

<P>Representative clients include: Burger King,  Inc.; Dataserv,  Inc.; Dow Brands L.P.; Edina Realty,  Inc.; Honeywell,  Inc.; Hubbard Broadcasting,  Inc.; Knutson Mortgage Corp.; Lull Industries,  Inc.; Marquette Banks; Midwest of Cannon Falls,  Inc.; Nabisco Brands,  Inc.; National City Bank of Minneapolis; Piper Jaffray,  Inc.; Prudential Securities,  Inc.; Resolution Trust Corp.; Rollerblade,  Inc.; St. Jude Medical,  Inc.; Terra International,  Inc.; Snapper Lawnmowers; and Field  & Stream Licenses Company.<BR><P>Inquiries about the commercial litigation practice should be directed to the following shareholders in the Commercial Litigation Department:<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Allen I. Saeks</B> (<I>Minneapolis; 612-335-1548</I>) Mr. Saeks' practice is focused on trial,  appellate,  and counseling matters in the areas of bankruptcy,  professional malpractice,  securities,  white collar criminal law,  and business and commercial litigation. He served as an assistant U.S. attorney for the District of Minnesota from 1956-1957. He is certified as a civil trial specialist by the Minnesota Bar Association. He is a frequent lecturer at continuing legal education seminars on trial practice. University of Minnesota Law School,  1956; Order of the Coif.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Charles A. Mays</B> (<I>Minneapolis; 612-335-1537</I>) Mr. Mays is chairman of the firm's Litigation Division and a member of the Board of Directors. His practice is focused on trial and appellate work and consulting in the areas of business and commercial litigation,  intellectual property (including trademark,  copyright,  and patent litigation),  unfair competition,  and advertising law. He served as an assistant U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia from 1965-1969. He is a frequent lecturer at continuing legal education seminars on trial practice. George Washington University Law School,  1964.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael A. Nekich</B> (<I>Minneapolis; 612-335-1581</I>) Mr. Nekich's practice is focused on trial,  appellate,  and counseling matters in the areas of intellectual property (including trade secret and patent litigation),  business and commercial litigation,  and bankruptcy. Harvard Law School,  1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert L. DeMay</B> (<I>Minneapolis; 612-335-1524</I>) Mr. DeMay's practice is focused on trial,  appellate,  and counseling matters in the areas of antitrust,  distribution and franchising,  and trade secret litigation. University of Minnesota Law School,  1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James G. Bullard</B> (<I>Minneapolis; 612-335-1512</I>) Mr. Bullard is the chairman of the Commercial Litigation Department. His practice is focused on trial,  appellate,  and counseling matters in the areas of securities,  banking,  and complex financial litigation. University of Chicago Law School,  1980; Order of the Coif.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Douglas B. Greenswag</B> (<I>Minneapolis; 612-335-1527</I>) Mr. Greenswag's practice is focused on trial,  appellate,  and counseling matters in the areas of bankruptcy and intellectual property litigation. He is a certified business bankruptcy specialist and a member of the American Bankruptcy Institute. University of Iowa,  1983; Order of the Coif.<BR>
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
