<HEAD>
<TITLE>Milberg Weiss Bershad Hynes  & Lerach
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Commercial Litigation</H2>
<H3>Milberg Weiss Bershad Hynes  & Lerach
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>New York:</B> One Pennsylvania Plaza,  49th Floor,  New York,  NY 10119<BR>
Tel 212-594-5300  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-868-1229<BR>
<B>San Diego:</B> 600 West Broadway,  Suite 1800,  San Diego,  CA 92101<BR>
Tel 619-231-1058  <B>*</B>  Fax 619-231-7423<BR>
<B>Los Angeles:</B> 355 South Grand Avenue,  Suite 4170,  Los Angeles,  CA 90071<BR>
Tel 213-617-9007  <B>*</B>  Fax 213-617-9185<BR>
<B>San Francisco:</B> 222 Kearny Street,  10th Floor,  San Francisco,  CA 94108<BR>
Tel 415-288-4545  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-288-4534<BR>
<BR>
98 lawyers  <B>*</B>  95 lawyers in commercial litigation<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>T</B>he practice of Milberg Weiss Bershad Hynes  & Lerach focuses on complex litigation,  with an emphasis on prosecution of civil actions for securities violations,  accountants' misconduct,  and breach of duty by corporate fiduciaries. Much of our work concentrates on representing plaintiffs in securities fraud cases,  both for private clients and as lead counsel in class actions. We also take on significant antitrust,  commercial and consumer fraud,  toxic and other health-related tort,  and environmental cases. We generally represent plaintiffs,  and have handled matters on contingency,  hourly,  and mixed-fee bases. We practice in federal and state courts throughout the country and have an active arbitration practice for complex disputes.<BR>
<BR><P>Recent cases in which the firm is playing or has played a lead or major role representing plaintiffs include the Washington Public Power Supply System securities litigation; the Keating-Lincoln Savings securities litigation; the FDIC's audit failure case against Ernst  & Young in Tennessee; securities litigation against Apple Computer; the Stringfellow toxic waste dump site environmental litigation; the Alaska oil spill litigation; and the City of San Jose's action against brokers and accountants involving investment of funds all of which have gone to trial in the last few years. In addition,  we have represented class plaintiffs in numerous major securities actions,  including the Drexel/Milken litigation (acting as co-counsel with Cravath,  Swaine  & Moore,  which represented the FDIC and RTC in those matters); have acted as counsel for bankruptcy estates or trustees in such major corporate failures as Phar-Mor,  Inc. and Colonial Realty Co. in actions against their former accountants; and represent plaintiffs in antitrust actions in the beer and prescription drug industries. We are also co-counsel for IBM in defending securities fraud actions. We have been lead counsel in class actions with aggregate recoveries for plaintiffs in excess of $4 billion.<BR><BR><P>In addition to our class action work,  we represent private clients in most of our practice areas. For example:<BR>
<UL><BR><LI> We have frequently represented substantial stock purchasers and acquiring companies in asserting securities fraud and related claims against issuers,  sellers,  and accounting firms. Occasionally we also take on defense work in those areas.<BR>
<BR><LI> We have represented minority owners of significant business enterprises in disputed control,  transactional,  and takeover situations.<BR>
<BR><LI> Due to our familiarity with accounting issues,  we have represented plaintiffs asserting malpractice and fraud claims arising out of failed audits,  acquisition reviews,  and related matters. <BR>
<BR><LI> We take on significant claims against brokers and other fiduciaries,  including complex churning,  unsuitability,  and other investment matters and breach of fiduciary duty cases against corporate trustees and others.<BR>
<BR><LI> We represent private clients asserting claims,  often involving price-fixing or price discrimination,  in complex antitrust litigations.<BR>
</UL><BR><P>The practice of all of our litigation attorneys generally extends over the firm's entire fields of representation,  without significant further specialization. The resulting flexibility in attorney staffing of cases,  and our background in prosecuting cases for plaintiffs,  often on a contingent basis,  mean that we use the 'leanest' approach possible,  consistent with achieving superior results,  in litigating our cases.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Melvyn I. Weiss</B> (<I>New York</I>) is the firm's senior partner and co-founder. He was co-lead counsel in the WPPSS securities litigation,  where class plaintiffs recovered in excess of $800 million; is lead negotiator for major securities claimants in Drexel/Milken matters; and is lead settlement counsel in the <I>Exxon Valdez</I> oil spill litigation,  among his many involvements in major cases. He is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers and was named as one of the `100 Most Influential Attorneys' by the <I>National Law Journal</I> in 1994 and one of the `100 Most Influential People in Accounting' by <I>Accounting Today</I> in 1994. <B>William S. Lerach</B> (<I>San Diego</I>) is senior managing partner in the San Diego office. He leads the prosecution of numerous securities class actions and is heavily involved in litigation against the tobacco industry. He was named as one of the `100 Most Influential Attorneys' by the <I>National Law Journal</I> in 1994 and is a master of the American Inns of Court. He has served as a lawyer-delegate to the Ninth Circuit Judicial Conference and is a member of the California Senate Commission on Corporate Governance and Stockholders' Rights. <B>David J. Bershad</B> (<I>New York</I>) is managing partner in the New York office. He is expert in analyzing and negotiating complex business and financial matters,  and has achieved recoveries in excess of $200 million in the Baldwin United annuities class actions and $150 million for a group of nine private investors in the telecommunications industry. <B>Patricia M. Hynes</B> (<I>New York</I>) was executive assistant U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New York before joining the firm,  and has the most extensive trial experience among our senior partners. She is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers and is active in trials and arbitrations across our fields of practice. All of our partners also have significant involvement in policy-oriented and educational work in our fields.<BR><BR>


</UL></BODY>
