<TITLE>Morrison  & Foerster
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Commercial Litigation</H2>
<H3>Morrison  & Foerster
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>San Francisco:</B> 345 California Street,  San Francisco,  CA 94104-2675<BR>
Tel 415-677-7000  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-677-7522<BR>
<BR>
510 lawyers  <B>*</B>  220 lawyers in commercial litigation<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/morrison.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/morrison.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/morrison.html"> Labor</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>M</B>orrison  & Foerster provides clients with skilled trial and appellate representation,  advice on alternative methods of dispute resolution,  and preventive counseling to avoid controversies. Our lawyers represent clients in most major types of commercial litigation,  including: antitrust and trade regulation; intellectual property; securities; financial institutions and transactions; land use and environmental law; real estate and construction; energy law; criminal; regulatory; professional liability; airports and aviation; insurance; and product liability.<BR><BR><UL>
<LI><B>William H. Alsup</B> (<I>San Francisco; 415-677-7206</I>) Mr. Alsup's experience spans a broad range of complex cases. From 1978 to 1980 he was Assistant to the Solicitor General in the U.S. Department of Justice. Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  1971.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jack C. Auspitz</B> (<I>New York; 212-468-8046</I>) Mr. Auspitz specializes in complex civil litigation with emphasis on securities litigation. He has lectured for the Practising Law Institute on subjects ranging from the rights of minority shareholders to direct and cross-examination. Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  1968.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James J. Brosnahan</B> (<I>San Francisco; 415-677-7189</I>) Mr. Brosnahan has tried more than 100 jury cases. He is the author of a book to assist California trial lawyers,  the <I>Trial Handbook for California Lawyers</I> (Bancroft-Whitney). He is a former assistant U.S. attorney. Harvard Law School,  LL.B.,  1959.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Cedric C. Chao</B> (<I>San Francisco; 415-677-7061</I>) Mr. Chao chairs the firm's international litigation section. He is a former assistant U.S. attorney. Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Stephen S. Dunham</B> (<I>Denver; 303-592-2251</I>) Mr. Dunham's litigation practice includes contracts,  securities,  antitrust,  higher education issues,  product liability,  insurance,  employment,  accountant,  and general commercial litigation. From 1985 to 1988 he served as general counsel of the University of Minnesota. Yale Law School,  J.D.,  1969.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kathleen V. Fisher</B> (<I>San Francisco; 415-677-7222</I>) Ms. Fisher is chair of the firm's Litigation Department and former managing partner of the firm's San Francisco office. She has tried many jury and nonjury cases. University of California at Davis Law School,  J.D.,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard D. Fybel</B> (<I>Los Angeles; 213-892-5283</I>) Mr. Fybel specializes in complex civil litigation. He represents large financial institutions in matters involving complicated contracts,  real estate,  trust,  and labor issues. University of California at Los Angeles School of Law,  J.D.,  1971.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Melvin R. Goldman</B> (<I>San Francisco; 415-677-7311</I>) Mr. Goldman specializes in defense of securities litigation,  representing numerous companies,  financial institutions,  and their directors and officers. Northwestern School of Law,  J.D.,  1961; Stanford University School of Law,  LL.M.,  1963.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Seth M. Hufstedler</B> (<I>Los Angeles; 213-892-5803</I>) Former president of both the State Bar of California and the Los Angeles County Bar Association,  Mr. Hufstedler is engaged in an active business trial and appellate litigation practice. Stanford University,  LL.B.,  1949.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Shirley M. Hufstedler</B> (<I>Los Angeles; 213-892-5804</I>) Former Secretary of the U.S. Department of Education,  Ms. Hufstedler practices in business litigation with emphasis on federal and state appellate matters. She is a former Judge of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit,  Associate Justice of the California Court of Appeal,  and Judge of the Los Angeles County Superior Court. Stanford University,  LL.B.,  1949.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert H. Loeffler</B> (<I>Washington; 202-887-1506</I>) Mr. Loeffler has broad experience in handling complex government-related problems and administrative litigation,  with a particular emphasis in recent years on energy law issues. Columbia University Law School,  J.D.,  1968.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Carroll E. Neesemann</B> (<I>New York; 212-468-8138</I>) Mr. Neesemann has prosecuted and defended numerous cases,  for foreign and domestic clients,  in areas including securities,  business torts,  breach of contract,  antitrust,  trademarks,  unfair competition,  patents,  and real estate. He is currently vice-chairman of the Arbitration Committee of the Dispute Resolution Section of the ABA. University of Maryland School of Law,  J.D.,  1969.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert D. Raven</B> (<I>San Francisco; 415-677-7294</I>) Mr. Raven has over 40 years of experience as a trial lawyer. He was president of the American Bar Association in 1988-1989 and served as chair of the ABA's Section on Dispute Resolution in 1993-1994. Boalt Hall School of Law,  University of California,  LL.B.,  1952.<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


