<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul,  Weiss,  Rifkind,  Wharton  & Garrison
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Commercial Litigation</H2>
<H3>Paul,  Weiss,  Rifkind,  Wharton  & Garrison
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>New York:</B> 1285 Avenue of the Americas,  New York,  NY 10019-6064<BR>
Tel 212-373-3000  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-757-3990<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> 1615 L Street,  NW,  Washington,  DC 20036-5694<BR>
Tel 202-223-7300  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-223-7420<BR>
<B>Paris:</B> 199 Boulevard Saint-Germain,  75007 Paris,  France<BR>
Tel 331-4549-3385  <B>*</B>  Fax 331-4222-6438<BR>
<B>Tokyo:</B> Akasaka Twin Tower,  17-22,  Akasaka 2-chome,  Minato-ku,  Tokyo 107,  Japan<BR>
Tel 813-3505-0291  <B>*</B>  Fax 813-3505-4540<BR>
<B>Beijing:</B> Scite Tower (Noble Tower),  Room 1910,  22,  Jianguomenwai Dajie, <BR>
Beijing 100004,  People's Republic of China<BR>
Tel 861-512-3628  <B>*</B>  Fax 861-512-3631<BR>
<B>Hong Kong:</B> 13th Floor,  Hong Kong Club Building,  3A Chater Road,  Central Hong Kong<BR>
Tel 852-2536-9933  <B>*</B>  Fax 852-2536-9622<BR>
<BR>
341 lawyers  <B>*</B>  113 lawyers practice litigation<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/paul.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/paul.html"> Corporate Securities</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/paul.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/paul.html"> ERISA</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/paul.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
   <LI><A HREF="..//paul.html"> International</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/paul.html"> Product Liability</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/paul.html"> Workout</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>T</B>he Paul,  Weiss Litigation Department handles every kind of dispute resolution device recognized by the law,  from traditional court cases to domestic and international arbitrations,  from alternative dispute resolution processes to administrative tribunals of all kinds. We recognize that the possible end result of every case is a trial,  and our management of each case,  particularly the pretrial process,  is based upon that assumption. We also recognize that litigation costs can be substantial,  and carefully manage our cases to ensure that costs remain under control.<BR><P>We try cases and handle appeals in state and federal courts throughout the United States and its territories,  and we supervise and manage transnational litigation for clients needing centralized strategy for cases pending in foreign jurisdictions. We believe that mastery of the trial and appellate process,  in whatever form and before whatever tribunal,  is the key to successful litigation. We recognize that while procedures vary before administrative agencies,  arbitration panels,  private institutional tribunals,  legislative investigations,  and different courts,  the process is essentially the same: to identify facts that support our client's position,  to resolve disputed facts in its favor,  and to identify and apply the existing doctrines of law and to create new ones that support its position.<BR><P>Our practice and experience encompass complex cases of all kinds. We have handled securities,  corporate,  and intellectual property matters; criminal and civil RICO matters; communications matters involving over-the-air and cable television,  motion pictures,  music recording and publishing,  theater,  and home audio and video taping; defective product and product liability cases; grand jury investigations and criminal trials involving diverse issues ranging from the employment practices of a state legislative body to securities fraud,  insider trading,  and tax evasion; libel and defamation,  trade libel,  and corporate defamation and disparagement cases; major tax cases; real estate valuation matters; takeover litigations for bidders,  targets,  and financial advisors; copyright royalty disputes,  including the fees to be paid by radio and television stations for the use of copyrighted material; cases involving title to art that disappeared in World War II; and constitutional litigation of all kinds. Many of these cases were referred to us by former adversaries or other law firms who recognized the quality and breadth of our litigation capacity.<BR><P>One of our most dramatic recent victories involved our retention by Armstrong World Industries for the retrial of an antitrust,  breach of contract,  and tortious interference action. The first trial had resulted in a $239 million jury verdict for the plaintiff,  a producer of a video magazine for flooring retailers. After a successful appeal,  we handled the six-month retrial,  at the conclusion of which the jury awarded the plaintiff nothing.<BR><P>In an era of the `big case, ' we have maintained our capacity to handle not only the big cases,  but cases of different sizes,  in a cost-effective way.<BR><P>Below we highlight certain of our litigation practice areas:<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Intellectual Property</H3></CENTER>

<BR><BR>
<P>Paul,  Weiss has one of the leading intellectual property practices in the United States. It is far-reaching and diverse.<BR><P><I>Copyright/Entertainment Matters</I> In part due to our renowned Entertainment Department the largest and most active of any general practice firm in New York our litigators have for many years represented leading motion picture,  Broadway,  and off-Broadway producers,  as well as a wide variety of authors,  directors,  composers,  lyricists,  music publishers,  and performing artists in judicial,  administrative,  and arbitration proceedings across the country.<BR>
<BR><P>In recent years,  our litigators have represented subsidiaries of our client Time Warner Inc. in the successful renewal of their Manhattan cable television franchises; won summary judgment for Eddie Murphy,  Richard Pryor,  and Paramount Pictures in a copyright infringement action; brought several successful suits to enforce Lucasfilms' rights in the `Indiana Jones' character; successfully represented the National Music Publishers Association in proceedings before the Copyright Royalty Tribunal to establish an industry-wide royalty rate; handled several suits involving copyright infringement claims relating to computer software; argued before the U.S. Supreme Court in the recent landmark case defining the applicability of the `fair use' doctrine to parody; successfully defended Michael Jackson,  owner of the copyrights to the Beatles' songs,  in a suit by a company that claimed it had acquired the rights to create rap versions of the Beatles' songs; and are presently defending against copyright infringement allegations as to the <I>Regarding Henry</I> and <I>Star Trek</I> motion pictures.<BR>
<BR><P><I> Patents and Trade Secrets</I> In recent years,  we handled major litigations and related settlement negotiations for a large Japanese company that was simultaneously asserting rights under its U.S. patents and defending against claims that it had infringed its competitors' U.S. patents; represented a Japanese corporation in a successful action to invalidate a U.S. competitor's patent; and secured an unprecedented summary determination of noninfringement in a Section 337 patent proceeding before the International Trade Commission. In a recent case of first impression,  we successfully defended a major medical research institution against a claim by former employees under a royalty-sharing provision of the U.S. Patent Law.<BR>
<BR><P>We advise clients regularly on the protection of trade secrets and have successfully litigated numerous trade secret claims. We have defended a major European manufacturer against a claim that it misappropriated jet engine technology; obtained injunctive relief to prevent a client's competitor from misappropriating computer technology; obtained injunctive relief on behalf of a major U.S. company barring key computer personnel from joining a rival firm; and successfully prosecuted or defended many actions,  often on an expedited basis,  to enforce confidentiality agreements and restrictive covenants in the merger and acquisition and employment contexts.<BR>
<BR><P><I> Trademarks,  Unfair Competition,  and Advertising</I> We have successfully: defeated a preliminary injunction motion to attempt to block the launch of Revlon's new fragrance `Charlie Red' on the ground that it infringed Giorgio Beverly Hills' trademark in the fragrance `Red'; prosecuted claims on behalf of the owner of the trademark `Bayer' for aspirin and other products in the United States; represented a foreign manufacturer in a lengthy arbitration against a former U.S. distributor,  which asserted various Lanham Act and other claims; defended a beer manufacturer in an action brought over its use of the word `Lite'; prosecuted trademark claims to enforce the `At-a-Glance' trademarks; represented the producers of the play <I>Six Degrees of Separation</I> in defeating right to privacy and right of publicity claims; and represented Castrol Inc. in a series of matters halting various false or misleading advertisements of its competitors.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Securities and Commodities</H3></CENTER>

<P>From the beginning of the current era of securities regulation,  the firm has been involved in some of the most important civil and criminal securities cases,  including the first private action under the Williams Act (<I>Chris-Craft </I>v.<I> Piper</I>); landmark decisions defining a `security' (<I>United Housing </I>v.<I> Forman</I>) and a `tender offer' (<I>Wellman </I>v. <I>Dickinson</I>); the lengthy SEC investigation that culminated in <I>SEC </I>v.<I> Gulf  & Western</I>; the takeover defense of Consolidated Goldfields; the successful criminal defense of <I>U.S. </I>v.<I> GAF Corporation</I>; and the massive civil and criminal investigations and suits involving Michael Milken. More recently,  we represented a major investment bank in one of the largest investment banker malpractice actions ever brought; represented the Special Committee of the Woolworth Corporation in connection with its investigation into reporting and accounting irregularities; obtained a $22.3 million judgment in the Delaware Court of Chancery in a tax sharing dispute; and obtained for American Express the dismissal of shareholder derivative litigation arising from the company's alleged disparagement of a competitor. We successfully represented Pan-Alberta Gas Ltd. in a natural gas dispute,  the first `fast-track' arbitration under the auspices of the Paris-based International Chamber of Commerce. We are also currently serving as counsel to a select committee investigating the governance structure of the NASD and the NASDAQ stock market.<BR><BR><P>We pride ourselves in the breadth and depth of the firm's capacity and proficiency in virtually every aspect of securities and commodities litigations,  arbitrations,  and investigations. Nearly all of our 30 litigation partners devote a major portion of their professional time to securities and commodities litigation. While the firm is frequently retained in high-stakes matters,  its lawyers' extensive experience in securities and commodities matters of all types enables the firm to serve its clients with uncommon efficiency.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Products Liability</H3></CENTER>

<P>Paul,  Weiss has substantial experience and expertise in all phases of products liability litigation,  case management,  and counseling. We have recently represented manufacturers of asbestos products,  cigarettes,  medical products,  valves for nuclear power plants,  school buses,  and washing machines.<BR><P>We have advised a major corporation in the coordination of its defense of asbestos cases across the country and negotiated its membership in the Asbestos Claims Facility. We also represent future asbestos health claimants with respect to the Manville Personal Injury Settlement Trust.<BR>
<BR><P>The firm also represents a large manufacturer of medical and hospital equipment in a series of cases across the country brought by individuals who claim to have contracted AIDS as a result of their use of our client's products.<BR>
<BR><P>Paul,  Weiss litigators have also been active in litigation assessing governmental responsibility for damages in products liability cases.<BR>
<BR>
<P>We highlight below a few members of the Litigation Department:<BR>
<BR><UL>
<LI><B>Arthur L. Liman</B> primarily handles civil and criminal securities,  takeover,  products liability,  and general commercial litigation cases. Assistant U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New York,  1961-1963. Joined Paul,  Weiss,  1963; partner,  1966. Harvard University,  A.B.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1954; Yale School of Law,  LL.B.,  1957; comment editor,  <I>Yale Law Journal</I>,  1956-1957.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Martin London</B> primarily handles antitrust,  products liability,  libel,  defamation,  and entertainment law matters. Joined Paul,  Weiss,  1962; partner,  1969. Cornell University,  A.B.,  1955; New York University Law School,  LL.B.,  1957; associate editor,  <I>New York University Law Review</I>,  1956-1957.<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
