<HEAD>
<TITLE>Schuyler,  Roche  & Zwirner
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Commercial Litigation</H2>
<H3>Schuyler,  Roche  & Zwirner
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Chicago:</B> One Prudential Plaza,  Suite 3800,  Chicago,  IL 60601<BR>
Tel 312-565-2400  <B>*</B>  Fax 312-565-8300<BR>
<B>Evanston:</B> 1603 Orrington Avenue,  Suite 1190,  Evanston,  IL 60201<BR>
Tel 708-491-9760  <B>*</B>  Fax 708-491-0658<BR>
<BR>
38 lawyers  <B>*</B>  17 lawyers in the Commercial Litigation Practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/schuyler.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/schuyler.html"> ERISA</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/schuyler.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/schuyler.html"> Labor</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>S</B>chuyler,  Roche  & Zwirner is a strong mid-sized firm composed of service- oriented attorneys who combine outstanding legal skills with a heavy dose of common sense. We are committed to finding creative,  cost-effective solutions to legal problems. Averaging 20 years of experience,  our commercial litigation partners aggressively handle a wide variety of complex matters in trial and appellate forums throughout the country. Representative clients include PaineWebber Incorporated,  National Car Rental System,  Inc.,  and the Chicago Transit Authority.<BR><BR><UL>
<LI><B>Michael B. Roche</B> heads our Commercial Litigation Practice. An accomplished litigator with broad trial and appellate experience,  he concentrates on securities litigation. University of Notre Dame,  A.B.,  1963,  J.D.,  1966.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Ralph E. Brown</B> has represented clients in a wide variety of matters including complex civil litigation,  defense of business crimes,  and bankruptcy. University of Illinois,  B.S.,  1949; University of Chicago,  J.D.,  1953.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Randall L. Mitchell</B> has represented clients nationally in business litigation matters,  including complex cases such as class actions. He heads the firm's insurance litigation group,  and also concentrates in securities and employment litigation. University of Michigan,  B.A.,  1964; University of Illinois,  J.D.,  1967.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Joseph J. Stevens</B> concentrates in labor and employment law,  representing both public and private sector employers. A skilled negotiator,  he has substantial experience in state and federal courts and in arbitrations,  including interest arbitrations. DePaul University,  B.A.,  1961,  J.D. 1964.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David M. Allen</B>,  a litigator with broad experience in commercial litigation,  heads the firm's estate and trust litigation practice. He has also handled several complex commercial arbitrations. Williams College,  B.A.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1968; University of Chicago,  J.D.,  1972.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kael B. Kennedy</B> represents trade and professional associations and other business clients. He concentrates in antitrust and competition law (civil and criminal),  white collar defense,  and employee benefits litigation. Loyola University,  B.S.,  1963; University of Iowa,  J.D. 1966.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James D. Adducci</B> has broad-based litigation experience. He heads the firm's intellectual property litigation practice,  which encompasses disputes concerning trademarks,  service marks,  copyrights,  unfair competition,  and restrictive covenants. Loyola University of Chicago,  B.A.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1973; Harvard University,  J.D.,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Paul E. Lehner</B> heads the firm's labor and employment litigation group,  and also handles a variety of other commercial litigation matters. He has substantial experience in federal and state courts,  and before administrative agencies. Columbia University,  B.A.,  1970; Georgetown University,  J.D.,  1975.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>L. Andrew Brehm</B> concentrates in securities and commodities litigation. His practice includes virtually all other types of business litigation. University of Notre Dame,  A.B.,  1976; University of Michigan,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1979.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Frank M. Pawlak</B> has represented clients in all aspects of employer-employee relations,  including discrimination,  wrongful discharge,  and non-compete cases. He has substantial experience in federal and state courts,  arbitrations,  and before governmental agencies. Loyola University,  B.A.,  1975,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jeffrey E. Schiller</B> has considerable experience in commercial litigation,  in both trial and appellate courts,  including intellectual property,  antitrust,  employment,  and shareholders' rights cases. University of Michigan,  B.A.,  1976; Northwestern University,  J.D.,  1979.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael F. Braun</B> is an experienced commercial litigator. His practice includes employment matters,  such as wrongful discharge,  enforcement of restrictive covenants,  and discrimination claims. University of Illinois,  B.A.,  1978,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Marshall L. Blankenship</B> has litigated a wide variety of cases,  including intellectual property,  insurance,  and employment matters. University of Notre Dame,  B.A.,  1983; University of Illinois,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1986.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David M. Giangrossi</B> concentrates in the enforcement of creditors' rights and has represented major banks and commercial lenders. University of Wisconsin,  B.A.,  1974; John Marshall Law School,  J.D.,  1979.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
