<HEAD>
<TITLE>Spriggs  & Hollingsworth
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Commercial Litigation</H2>
<H3>Spriggs  & Hollingsworth
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington: </B>1350 I Street N.W.,  Ninth Floor,  Washington,  DC 20005<BR>
Tel 202-898-5800  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-682-1639<BR>
<BR>
35 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers concentrate in complex business litigation<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/spriggs.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/spriggs.html"> Product Liability</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/spriggs.html"> White Collar Crime</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>T</B>he firm represents manufacturers and other corporations in toxic tort and product liability litigation involving both personal injury and property damage claims. We serve as national coordinating trial counsel for the defense of such cases where multiple litigation is involved. The firm defends individual lawsuits,  mass tort claims,  and class actions alleging product liability in connection with product design,  manufacture,  and warnings; chemical contamination; radiation contamination; and waste disposal. These cases involve asbestos-containing products,  hazardous wastes,  military hardware,  `sick buildings, ' chlorinated and other synthetic pesticides,  solvents,  radioactive materials,  herbicides,  petroleum byproducts,  feedstocks and derivatives,  and various other chemicals and chemical products. The firm has extensive experience in defending against allegations of chemical carcinogenicity,  immunogenicity,  and latent toxicity. The firm represents corporations in civil,  criminal,  and administrative matters involving alleged contamination of ground and surface waters,  land,  and air. We represent manufacturers and successor corporations in proceedings involving Superfund/CERCLA,  RCRA,  and other statutes related to hazardous substances. We regularly negotiate on behalf of individual clients and on behalf of committees of potentially responsible parties with state and federal agencies concerning permits,  site investigations,  site remediations,  and similar issues arising under federal and state statutes affecting disposal of hazardous wastes. We represent corporate clients seeking to maximize their insurance coverage for toxic tort,  bodily injury,  and property damage claims,  and for remedial action and pollution cleanup expenses,  under comprehensive general liability policies.<BR><P>Our governmental contracts litigation and counseling activities run the gamut from bid preparation and contract negotiation to injunctions,  bid protests,  claims,  disputes,  and cost recovery. Our clients offer federal,  state,  local,  and foreign governments a wide range of services and supplies. We represent our clients in informal and formal negotiations,  before administrative tribunals,  and in federal and state courts. The firm practices extensively in all facets of private and public construction law and represents a diverse group of construction clients,  including several of the top 100 general construction firms,  subcontractors,  developers,  and project owners. The firm's construction practice is evenly distributed among federal/military,  state,  local,  and privately owned construction projects. We participate in informal and formal mediation,  arbitration,  and litigation at every level of federal,  state,  and administrative courts. The firm also represents clients in all phases of the investigation and trial of charges of false claims or fraud in the execution and performance of government contracts.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>William J. Spriggs</B> Extensive experience in all phases of government contracts law including injunctions,  protests and claims.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Joe G. Hollingsworth</B> Practice emphasizes trial and appellate work in toxic tort,  toxic and pharmaceutical product liability,  and environmental law. As national trial counsel in the defense of myriad chemical and chemical product exposure claims,  he defends against allegations of toxic exposure and injury,  property damage,  groundwater contamination,  and toxic air emissions.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Donald W. Fowler</B> Extensive experience in federal and administrative litigation in the areas of environmental law and toxic torts. His practice includes representation of companies in litigation and before the Environmental Protection Agency in matters arising under the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act and Superfund,  including private cost-recovery actions.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Edward J. Beder,  Jr</B>. Has been extensively involved in complex multiparty litigation covering the defense of toxic tort personal injury and property damage suits,  as well as the prosecution of actions to maximize insurance coverage.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Stephen R. Spivack</B> Extensive experience in all aspects of white collar criminal investigation and defense matters,  including the conduct of internal investigations on behalf of our corporate clients.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Charles S. Leeper</B> Extensive experience in the defense of white collar criminal investigations and prosecutions including bank fraud,  tax and antitrust violations,  securities fraud,  and government contract fraud.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jerry Stouck</B> Represents clients in large-scale business tort cases,  government and private contractor disputes,  and complex litigation involving regulated companies and claims by or against governmental entities.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John D. Bond III</B> Focuses on private and public construction and contract law,  primarily serving general contractors,  subcontractors,  construction managers,  developers,  project owners,  and sureties.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Bruce J. Berger</B> Practices in civil litigation and has extensive experience in toxic tort and environmental law.<BR>
<BR>
