<P>
<P><B>W</B>inston  & Strawn has more than 450 lawyers located in five offices. We provide assistance in virtually every major legal discipline to a wide range of clients throughout the United States and abroad,  including governments and governmental entities,  Fortune 500 companies,  and major commercial and financial institutions,  as well as individuals and small and midsize companies.
<P><BR><P>Winston  & Strawn has more than 110 litigators who have compiled an impressive track record in major civil and criminal litigation at both the trial and appellate levels. We have tried cases in federal district courts and many state courts throughout the country,  and have argued appeals in each of the circuits of the U.S. Court of Appeals and in the U.S. Supreme Court. We also have appeared before special tribunals including the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit,  the U.S. Claims Court,  the Judicial Panel on Multi-District Litigation,  and the U.S. Tax Court.<BR><P>We have tried essentially every type of lawsuit which might arise in the course of operating a sophisticated business,  including matters involving breach of contract,  common law fraud,  RICO,  mergers and acquisitions,  supply contract disputes,  breach of fiduciary duty,  lender liability,  federal and state securities laws,  bid award contests,  shareholder rights,  common law fraud,  condemnation,  mortgage foreclosure,  patent/copyright/trademark infringement,  antitrust,  dealer termination,  commodities fraud,  international trade,  product liability,  licensing agreements,  bankruptcy,  consumer fraud,  professional negligence,  construction,  and insurance coverage. Our lawyers also are experienced in state and federal court class action litigation,  including cases involving national consumer and shareholder classes.<BR>
<BR><P>Our lawyers attempt to assist clients in resolving disputes short of litigation if possible. However,  if a problem does result in a lawsuit,  our trial lawyers bring our clients broad experience in procedural and substantive issues.<BR>
<BR><P>Our most senior litigators are recognized leaders among the trial bar,  and several partners are members of the American College of Trial Lawyers. The following describes our litigation leaders in each U.S. office.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Dan K. Webb</B> is the chairman of Winston  & Strawn's Litigation Department and a former U.S. attorney. Widely recognized as one of the nation's leading trial attorneys,  he has tried more than 100 jury cases,  including major commercial,  regulatory,  and white collar crime cases. Among his major commercial trials in recent years are <I>Shields </I>v. <I>Keating,  Jr.</I> (the Lincoln Savings  & Loan civil fraud trial) and <I>Burroughs WelLCome </I>v.<I> Barr Laboratories</I> (the AZT patent trial). In addition,  Mr. Webb recently received national attention for his work as lead trial counsel for General Electric in <I>United States </I>v. <I>General Electric Co.</I>,  in which he successfully defended the company against criminal price-fixing allegations (cover story of the January/February 1995 issue of <I>The American Lawyer</I>).<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Daniel R. Murdock</B>,  head of our New York litigation practice,  has extensive experience in a wide variety of complex litigation. He was principal defense counsel for the Washington Public Power Supply System in the massive securities fraud lawsuits arising out of the Supply System's default on $2.25 billion in bonds issued to construct two nuclear power plants. Mr. Murdock also represented the Supply System in the Securities and Exchange Commission's parallel investigation. More recently,  Mr. Murdock had a central role in major lawsuits concerning Drexel Burnham's High-Yield Bond Department,  representing more than 100 defendants. Mr. Murdock was part of a small group that coordinated the defense in multibillion-dollar FDIC/RTC litigation on behalf of these Michael Milken-related clients and subsequently negotiated a `global' settlement of more than 180 class and derivative actions across the country. Mr. Murdock is a former chief assistant U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New York.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard A. Hibey</B> heads the firm's Washington,  D.C. litigation practice. His trial experience includes cases involving white collar crime,  antitrust matters,  corporate and federal securities law,  and complex commercial transactions. He has represented a number of high-profile clients in cases ranging from espionage,  human rights violations,  and RICO and other white collar crimes,  to complex civil matters. He also has tried cases before various international arbitration panels and the Ethics Committee of the U.S. House of Representatives. He has published articles on a variety of subjects,  including the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act,  jury selection,  jury fraud,  and health care fraud. Mr. Hibey taught criminal law for 13 years at American University's Washington College of Law,  where he was an adjunct professor. He also is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
