<CENTER>
<H2>Corporate Securities</H2>
<H3>Bass,  Berry  & Sims
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Nashville: </B>2700 First American Center,  Nashville,  TN 37238<BR>
Tel 615-742-6200  <B>*</B>  Fax 615-742-6298<BR>
<B>Other office:</B> Knoxville<BR>
<BR>
90 lawyers  <B>*</B>  26 lawyers in Corporate and Securities Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profile in the following other directory:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/bass.html"> Workout</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>B</B>ass,  Berry  & Sims' Corporate and Securities Group consists of 26 lawyers with extensive experience in advising publicly and privately held corporations in all types of corporate,  securities,  and merger and acquisition transactions. The firm represents companies in their corporate finance activities and serves as counsel for national and regional investment banking firms in public and private equity and debt offerings as well as other types of financing transactions. The firm also represents its public clients in meeting the continuing disclosure,  periodic reporting,  and other requirements of the Securities and Exchange Commission,  the NASD,  and the major stock exchanges,  and has extensive experience serving as counsel in venture capital transactions.
<P><BR><P>The firm maintains an active merger and acquisition practice. This practice includes representation in customary negotiated transactions as well as structured auctions and complex reorganization transactions such as spinoffs,  recapitalizations,  and leveraged buyouts. The firm also is experienced in counseling clients in connection with takeover situations,  and in counseling investment bankers in their advisory roles in merger and acquisition transactions.<BR><P>Representative clients include American Healthcorp,  Inc.,  J.C. Bradford  & Co.,  Coventry Corp.,  Dollar General Corporation,  Gaylord Entertainment Co.,  Gensesco Inc.,  First American Corp.,  O'Charley's Inc.,  Service Merchandise Co.,  Inc.,  Regal Cinemas,  Inc.,  Thomas Nelson,  Inc.,  and Vanderbilt University.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>J. Bradbury Reed</B> specializes in business planning,  mergers and acquisitions,  and owner disputes. Mr. Reed has served as chairman of the Tennessee Higher Education Commission,  on the Board of Directors of Legal Services of Middle Tennessee,  Inc.,  and as a lecturer in law at Vanderbilt University. Duke University,  B.A.,  1961; Vanderbilt Law School,  LL.B.,  1964.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James H. Cheek III</B> focuses on securities law,  corporate law,  and mergers and acquisitions. Mr. Cheek is the immediate past chairman of the Legal Advisory Committee of the New York Stock Exchange,  currently serves on the Legal Advisory Board of the National Association of Securities Dealers,  and is an adjunct professor of law at Vanderbilt University. Mr. Cheek has been elected to become the chair of the Business Law Section of the ABA,  having previously served as chairman of the American Bar Association's Committee on Federal Regulation of Securities and as secretary of the ABA's Committee on Corporate Laws. Duke University,  A.B.,  1967; Harvard Law School,  LL.M.,  1968.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Bob Thompson</B> focuses his practice on securities law including public offerings,  mergers and acquisitions,  and financial institution regulatory matters. Mr. Thompson's service for the Business Law Section of the American Bar Association includes acting as the chairman of the Liaison with State Administrators Subcommittee of the State Regulation of Securities Committee and as vice-chairman of the Regulatory Enforcement and Officer and Director Liability Subcommittee of the Banking Law Committee. He serves on the Advisory Board of the Southern Banking Law and Policy Conference and on the Government Relations and Lawyers Advisory Committees of the Tennessee Bankers Association. Princeton University,  A.B.,  1969; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  1975.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Leigh Walton</B> concentrates her practice in corporate,  securities,  and health law matters. She is a member of the ABA's Committee on Negotiated Acquisitions,  serving on its Editorial Subcommittee. She currently serves as co-chair of the Tennessee Bar Association's Task Force on Limited Liability Companies,  which introduced LLC legislation in 1994. Ms. Walton is an editor of the <I>Tennessee Health Law Update</I> and a former lecturer in law at Vanderbilt University Law School. She is on the standing panel of ALI-ABA's Tax and Business Planning Seminar. Randolph-Macon Women's College,  B.A.,  1973; Vanderbilt Law School,  J.D.,  1979.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Samuel E. Stumpf,  Jr.</B> concentrates in mergers and acquisitions and venture capital finance law. He was formerly in private practice in Atlanta and was an assistant professor of law at Washington  & Lee University. Yale University,  B.A.,  1972; Vanderbilt Law School,  J.D.,  1982.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>F. Mitchell Walker,  Jr.</B> focuses on representation of companies and underwriters in public offerings and in mergers and acquisitions. Harvard University,  A.B.,  1979; Vanderbilt Law School,  J.D.,  1982.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>J. Page Davidson</B> concentrates his practice on corporate and securities law. Vanderbilt University,  B.A.,  1982; Duke University,  J.D.,  1985.<BR>
