<TITLE>Dickstein,  Shapiro & Morin,  L.L.P.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Corporate Securities</H2>
<H3>Dickstein,  Shapiro & Morin,  L.L.P.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington:</B> 2101 L Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20037<BR>
Tel 202-785-9700  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-887-0689<BR>
<BR>
160 lawyers  <B>*</B>  6 lawyers in the Corporate Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profile in the following other directory:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/dickstein.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>S</B>ophisticated corporate clients need not only innovative legal strategies,  but broader business solutions. Dickstein,  Shapiro  & Morin,  L.L.P. advises corporate and institutional clients on how to solve problems efficiently. We concentrate on five major areas: mergers and acquisitions,  corporate finance,  project finance,  financial services,  and corporate counseling.
<P><BR><P>Dickstein,  Shapiro  & Morin represents acquirers and target companies in connection with negotiated and contested merger and acquisition transactions involving both public and private companies (including leveraged buyouts,  asset sales,  divestitures,  and other restructurings). In addition,  the Firm represents issuers,  principal shareholders,  and investment banking firms with respect to public and private offerings of equity and debt securities (including lease securitization transactions).<BR><P>The group structures highly complex project finance transactions,  particularly in the energy field. We act as project counsel for utility and nonutility investors and represented one of the first independent power producers in construction financing.<BR>
<BR><P>Corporate attorneys counsel clients in connection with the organization and operation of,  and extraordinary transactions involving,  investment companies. The firm has also developed a special expertise in counseling the independent directors and trustees of mutual funds.<BR>
<BR><P>Our corporate finance attorneys handle public offerings and private placements of equity and debt securities. Clients seek our counsel for transactions ranging  from $1 million to over $200 million.<BR>
<BR><P>The common thread unifying the Corporate Practice group is our role as counsel on general corporate and commercial matters,  from compliance with disclosure and reporting obligations under federal securities laws to standards of care and fiduciary responsibility of boards of directors.<BR>
<BR><P>Dickstein,  Shapiro  & Morin represents Harbour Group,  a leading St. Louis-based leveraged buyout organization,  and all of its portfolio companies; J. Makowski Company,  a major energy developer firm,  and its independent power projects; and the mutual funds advised or administered by Federated Investors,  one of the nation's largest investment company complexes.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Emanuel Faust,  Jr.</B> practices in corporate finance,  mergers and acquisitions,  joint ventures,  and project finance. He also advises clients in banking and creditors rights. He has handled conventional public offerings and private placement of conventional debt and equity securities as well as novel structured financings and secured transaction financing. He recently completed an approximately $100 million initial public offering of a group of manufacturing companies owned by an investment fund. He was also counsel to a Fortune 250 company in the combination of two of its operating subsidiaries with an independent company. University of South Carolina,  B.A.,  1980; Duke University,  J.D.,  1983.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John W. Griffin</B> heads the corporate practice group and concentrates on both corporate and securities law. He represents corporations and financial institutions in connection with a wide variety of corporate matters,  including mergers and acquisitions,  asset sales,  leveraged buyouts,  and hostile takeovers. He also represents companies facing SEC investigations and advises on internal corporate investigations. Mr. Griffin was formerly the associate director and chief counsel,  Division of Corporate Finance,  U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission. He authored the section of <I>The Lawyers Desk Book on White Collar Crime</I> entitled `Dealing With the Press During a Corporate Criminal Investigation.' Trinity College,  B.A.,  1969; Georgetown University,  J.D.,  1973.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Neil Lefkowitz</B> is primarily engaged in a corporate transactional practice,  with an emphasis in mergers and acquisitions. Neil is also engaged in a number of debt financing transactions,  including loans to facilitate mergers and acquisitions. Oberlin College,  B.A.,  1975; University of North Carolina,  J.D.,  1979.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Matthew G. Maloney</B> concentrates on securities law,  investment company regulation,  and general corporate law. He advises clients on compliance with securities law and represents companies,  underwriters,  and selling stockholders in initial public offerings. The offerings he has completed range from $15 million to over $200 million. He is also special counsel to a complex of more than 70 investment companies with assets in excess of $70 billion. Georgetown University,  B.S.F.S.,  1978; University of Virginia,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Rebecca L. Wright</B> focuses her practice on debt and equity financing transactions,  mainly on a project-financed basis,  in the energy and natural resources industries. In energy financing transactions,  she has led efforts to structure and negotiate credit documentation,  intercreditor agreements,  and credit enhancement facilities. Ms. Wright is experienced in investor partnership and joint venture and equity support arrangements for energy and natural resources projects. Vassar College,  B.A.,  1970; Johns Hopkins University,  M.A.,  1972; Georgetown University,  J.D.,  1979.<BR>
