<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Kramer,  Levin,  Naftalis  & Frankel</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL><CENTER><H2>Corporate Securities</H2><H3>Kramer,  Levin,  Naftalis  & Frankel</H3></CENTER><CENTER><B>New York:</B> 919 Third Avenue,  New York,  NY 10022<BR>Tel 212-715-9100  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-715-8000  <B>*</B> Home page: <A HREF="http://www.kramer-levin.com/">www.kramer-levin.com</A><BR><BR>150 lawyers  <B>*</B>  60 lawyers practicing corporate law<BR></CENTER><P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR><UL><BR>   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/kramer.html"> Antitrust</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/kramer.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/kramer.html"> ERISA</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/kramer.html"> Intellectual Property</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/kramer.html"> Labor</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/kramer.html"> Product Liability</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/kramer.html"> White Collar Crime</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/kramer.html"> Workout</A></UL><P><P><P><B>K</B>ramer Levin's corporate securities and financial services group applies a wealth of experience and a tough,  pragmatic approach to problem-solving to the corporate finance needs of a broad range of business clients. We regularly represent companies large and small,  domestic and foreign,  public and private,  and mature and entrepreneurial in cutting-edge as well as conventional transactions.<P><BR><P>In the public markets,  we represent issuers as well as bulge-bracket and mid-size underwriters. We have recently participated in major public offerings for leading producers of high-technology products,  licensed toys,  construction supplies,  and branded apparel. We also frequently advise investors,  issuers,  and financial institutions in connection with private placements,  including our recent involvement in the formation of a major entertainment industry venture. These transactions involve debt and equity securities,  both secured and unsecured; asset-backed securitization transactions; warrants; Eurobonds; gold,  silver,  and copper indexed securities; low-income housing tax credit partnership interests; and privately and publicly owned investment funds.<BR><P>Our active mergers and acquisitions practice includes recent representations for Tyco Laboratories in its $1.4 billion acquisition of Kendall International Ltd.; complex acquisition transactions for a major U.S.-based accounting firm; and acquisitions for European-based networks of advertising and marketing agencies. We represent special committees and independent directors in a variety of contexts and often advise shareholder groups in proxy fights and consent solicitations,  including those involving Hills Stores Company and Marietta Corporation.<BR><BR><P>In addition to investment banks,  we represent financial institutions in a variety of transactions including foreign banks in the origination and structuring of commercial loans and money center banks,  such as Bankers Trust,  Citibank and U.S. Trust,  as corporate trustees in securitizations and other debt offerings. We have a substantial specialty practice in representing Canadian financial institutions in the United States,  including the Toronto Stock Exchange and a majority of the independent Canadian broker-dealers.<BR><BR><P>Our financial services group specializes in the representation of many mutual fund complexes,  closed-end funds,  hedge funds,  banks,  savings associations,  bank and thrift holding companies,  investment advisers,  broker-dealers,  commodity trading advisers,  and investment limited partnerships (including funds sponsored by Chase Manhattan Bank,  NationsBank,  and AIM Funds).<BR><BR><P>We believe that a corporate lawyer's task is to add value to a client's endeavors. Therefore,  in representing corporate clients on a continuing basis,  we assemble a team of lawyers with primary responsibility for all matters handled for that client. These clients look to Kramer Levin for counsel with a working knowledge of the everyday needs of their business,  as well as expertise in corporate finance.<BR><BR><P>Clients for whom we provide ongoing corporate representation include large publicly held companies,  such as MCI Communications Corporation,  Liz Claiborne Inc.,  Tyco Laboratories,  Vishay Intertechnology Inc.,  MAXXAM Group Inc.,  and a major Northeastern public utility; many smaller public companies; private enterprises of all sizes; and individual entrepreneurs. The services we provide involve securities law matters,  antitrust advice,  the design of management and employee compensation plans,  employment agreements,  joint ventures,  licensing and distribution agreements,  and restructurings and reorganizations.<BR><BR><UL><BR><LI><B>Thomas E. Constance</B> has practiced corporate law in the areas of financings,  mergers and acquisitions,  1933 Act offerings,  tender offers,  and proxy fights. New York University,  B.S.,  1958; St. John's University,  J.D.,  1964.<BR><BR><LI><B>Carl Frischling</B> specializes in,  among other things,  mergers and acquisitions of investment companies,  and investment managers. He is a pioneer in bank-related mutual funds and has counseled clients in developing and structuring comprehensive mutual fund complexes. Mr. Frischling also advises mutual funds and their independent directors on their fiduciary obligations under federal securities laws. Columbia University,  B.A.,  1958,  J.D.,  1962,  M.B.A.,  1963.<BR><BR><LI><B>Ezra G. Levin</B> has been involved in corporate law for the past 30 years as a practitioner,  teacher,  and director. He serves on the board of directors of clients including a Fortune 200 company and a foreign bank. He served as trustee (appointed by the Securities Investor Protection Corporation) of a failed brokerage firm and has held several judicial appointments,  most recently as a mediator in litigation. He has taught courses in corporate law,  corporate finance,  and securities regulation,  and has advised public and private corporations in those areas. Columbia University,  A.B.,  1955,  LL.B.,  1959.<BR><BR><LI><B>Richard Marlin</B> specializes in mergers and acquisitions,  public offerings,  private placements,  and other financing transactions,  and general representation of public and private companies and high-net-worth families. Yale University,  B.A.,  1955,  LL.B.,  1958; New York University,  LL.M.,  taxation,  1964.<BR><BR><LI><B>Scott S. Rosenblum</B> is the firm's managing partner. He represents investment banking firms and public and private companies engaged in basic manufacturing,  real estate,  and service industries,  and specializes in domestic and foreign mergers,  acquisitions,  joint ventures,  public and private financings,  and general corporate advice to management and boards of directors. Dartmouth College,  A.B.,  1971; University of Pennsylvania,  J.D.,  1974.<BR><BR><BR></UL></UL></BODY></HTML>
