<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Corporate Securities</H2>
<H3>Lord,  Bissell  & Brook
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Chicago:</B> 115 South LaSalle Street,  Chicago,  IL 60603<BR>
Tel 312-443-0700  <B>*</B>  Fax 312-443-0336<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Los Angeles; Atlanta; London; Rockford and Oak Brook (Illinois)<BR>
<BR>
295 lawyers  <B>*</B>  17 lawyers in Corporate Securities and Finance Practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>L</B>ord,  Bissell  & Brook,  a pioneer in representing the domestic and foreign insurance industry,  has used that experience to build a broad securities and finance practice servicing manufacturers,  distributors,  service organizations,  underwriters,  banks,  and a host of other commercial interests. Corporate clients range in size from large multinational corporations to privately held businesses. Engagements range from public offerings for New York Stock Exchange-listed companies,  to IPOs for emerging businesses,  to private placements of debt or equity securities for privately held concerns.
<P><BR><P>Sixty-five firm lawyers provide legal services other than litigation to our corporate clients. The corporate securities and finance group of ten partners and seven associates concentrates on handling securities transactions,  financing alternatives,  mergers,  and acquisitions. Our securities and finance capabilities are complemented by a full range of related capabilities including general corporate,  business litigation,  antitrust,  taxation,  real estate,  employment,  product liability,  transportation,  health care,  and estates and probate.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>John T. Anderson</B>,  with more than 35 years of experience,  heads the corporate and securities finance practice. His experience includes handling all securities transactions during a  20-year period for each of two corporations as they evolved from private ownership to New York Stock Exchange listing. He also has extensive experience representing investment advisers and banks in lending transactions. DePauw University,  B.A.; Harvard University,  LL.B.,  <I>cum laude</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>George L. Burgett</B> represents lending institutions in a wide variety of financing transactions. He also counsels health care facilities,  physicians and alternate delivery systems on corporate matters,  financing,  health care contracting,  joint ventures,  acquisitions,  and affiliations. Marquette University,  B.A.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>; University of Notre Dame,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John S. Chapman</B> has more than 25 years of experience representing public and private companies on a broad range of corporate and securities law matters,  including mergers and acquisitions,  complex debt and equity financing arrangements,  and counseling boards of directors and management. Yale University,  B.A.; Harvard University,  LL.B.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Roger R. Fross</B> represents closely held and emerging corporations in meeting their financing needs,  including raising equity capital and debt,  joint venture participation,  disclosure and compliance matters,  and with day-to-day concerns of corporate ownership such as acquisition,  distribution,  key employee,  and other contractual matters. DePauw University,  B.A.; University of Chicago,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Louis F. Harrison</B>'s practice emphasizes the estate planning aspects of partnerships and privately owned businesses,  charitable dispositions,  and gifting strategies. He has authored more than 35 published articles on a broad range of tax and estate planning subjects. Colgate University,  B.A.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>; Duke University,  J.D.,  with high honors.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David L. Kendall</B>'s practice focuses on mergers,  purchases,  and sales of assets and stock; tax-free exchanges; leveraged buyouts; and general and high-technology joint ventures. He also has significant experience with general commercial and bank lending transactions. University of Michigan,  B.B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>; University of Illinois,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kay W. McCurdy</B> has more than 20 years of experience concentrating in the general corporate,  finance,  and securities areas,  handling complex transactions for publicly traded and privately held clients. She is a member of the Illinois Secretary of State Business Corporation Acts Advisory Committee. Bradley University,  B.A.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>; University of Chicago,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Louis E. Rosen</B> has more than 30 years of experience counseling clients on all aspects of corporate and securities law. He has broad experience in acquisitions,  debt and equity financing (for issuers,  investors,  and underwriters),  and general corporate matters. His clients range from medium-sized owner-managed businesses to national publicly held companies in various industries. He is a certified public accountant. University of Illinois,  B.S.; University of Chicago,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael Schuette</B> has more than 30 years of experience,  primarily in the bank lending,  merger and acquisition,  and general business areas. He has tailored unusual financial arrangements to meet clients' needs and was instrumental in initiating the revolver-to-term lending procedures common today. Northwestern University,  B.S.,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David L. Skelding</B> has over ten years' experience in business,  general corporate,  and securities law. He has represented clients in connection with acquisitions,  public offerings,  private placements,  and other financing transactions,  and provides a wide range of advice to investment advisers,  mutual funds,  private investment partnerships and broker-dealers. University of Chicago,  A.B.; Cornell University,  J.D.
