<B>Hong Kong:</B> 13th Floor,  Hong Kong Club Building,  3A Chater Road,  Central Hong Kong<BR>
Tel 852-2536-9933  <B>*</B>  Fax 852-2536-9622<BR>
<B>Tokyo:</B> Akasaka Twin Tower,  17-22,  Akasaka 2-chome,  Minato-ku,  Tokyo 107,  Japan<BR>
Tel 81-3-3505-0291  <B>*</B>  Fax 81-3-3505-4540<BR>
<B>Beijing:</B> Scite Tower (Noble Tower),  Room 904,  22,  Jianguomenwai Dajie, <BR>
Beijing,  100004,  People's Republic of China<BR>
Tel 86-1-0512-3628  <B>*</B>  Fax 86-1-0512-3631<BR>
<BR>
345 lawyers  <B>*</B>  30 lawyers practice securities and corporate finance<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/paul.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/paul.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/paul.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/paul.html"> ERISA</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/paul.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/paul.html"> Product Liability</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/paul.html"> Workout</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>P</B>aul,  Weiss has an extensive securities and corporate finance practice representing both issuers and underwriters. We regularly are involved in a range of offerings in the U.S. capital markets,  including initial public offerings,  other primary offerings,  and secondary offerings,  as well as private placements. The public offerings involve equity securities,  debt securities,  and derivative products. Private placements include traditional private placements,  structured finance (monetization/securitization) transactions,  and Rule 144A offerings.
<P><BR><P>As the securities markets have become more globalized,  we have experienced significant growth in the range of activities that involve non-U.S. clients and non-U.S. capital markets. We have been involved in the establishment of American Depositary Receipt programs (including programs listed on a U.S. stock exchange or involving the raising of equity capital in the United States) and have represented issuers,  underwriters,  and placement agents in connection with offshore offerings under Regulation S. We also have been involved in the establishment of offshore investment funds and offerings by such funds of interest to U.S. and non-U.S. investors. We also represent Canadian issuers and underwriters in cross-border offerings under the multijurisdictional disclosure system. In addition,  we regularly advise foreign clients on a range of issues arising under the U.S. securities laws by virtue of their offshore activities.<BR><P>As part of our general representation of corporate clients that are public companies,  we regularly are involved in reviewing periodic reports and evaluating companies' disclosure obligations,  dealing with the staffs of the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and principal U.S. stock exchanges,  preparing or reviewing proxy statements,  and preparing or reviewing insider trading policies.<BR>
<BR><P>Although our corporate finance and securities expertise resides principally in the firm's Securities Group,  which is part of its corporate department,  transactions in this area often require an interdisciplinary approach. For example,  the structuring of initial public offerings by real estate investment trusts requires significant input from our tax and real estate departments. Structured finance transactions often require an analysis of tax and bankruptcy issues. Due diligence reviews in connection with a public offering or private placement may involve lawyers in our real estate,  litigation,  tax,  and bankruptcy departments and our environmental group.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Mark S. Bergman</B>,  co-head of the firm's Securities Group,  has represented both issuers and underwriters (including Donaldson,  Lufkin  & Jenrette; First Boston; Goldman Sachs; Merrill Lynch; PaineWebber; and Salomon Brothers) in public offerings (including initial public offerings),  and both issuers and placement agents in private placements. A number of these transactions have involved foreign issuers accessing the U.S. capital markets.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard S. Borisoff</B>,  co-head of the firm's Securities Group,  has handled a broad range of securities matters,  both public and private,  including transactions under Regulation S and Rule 144A,  ADR offerings,  derivative securities,  rated and unrated debt,  offerings by closed-end investment companies,  and initial public offerings. He regularly represents both issuers and underwriters,  and generally represents several public companies on a regular basis. He also consults regularly on Section 16(b),  Rule 144,  proxy,  and Regulation D issues.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James M. Dubin</B> represents both underwriters (including PaineWebber; Salomon Brothers; and Donaldson,  Lufkin  & Jenrette) and issuers (including Carnival Cruise Lines,  Conaire Corporation,  and Orion Pictures Corp.) in debt and equity public offerings and private placements.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David K. Lakhdhir</B>,  the resident partner in the firm's Tokyo office,  has substantial experience with securities transactions. He represents Japanese corporations and banks in connection with U.S. capital markets activities and also advises U.S. investment banks on matters relating to their operations in Asia.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Edwin S. Maynard</B> has represented U.S. issuers and underwriters in public and private financings,  and has represented a number of Canadian underwriters and Canadian and other foreign issuers in U.S.-directed financings.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Leonard V. Quigley</B>,  co-head of the firm's Securities Group,  generally represents foreign issuers,  principally Canadian issuers,  in U.S. public and private financings and acquisitions.<BR>
