<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>R</B>oss  & Hardies has provided legal services in corporate organization,  securities,  and finance to public- and private-sector clients since 1902. A substantial portion of the corporate practice consists of securities and finance work. This work is generally handled by lawyers in the Chicago and New York offices of the firm,  with specialized regulatory help coming from the firm's office in Washington,  D.C.
<P><BR><P>Ross  & Hardies attorneys work with clients which have recently gone public,  which are in the process of preparing their initial public offerings,  or which are entrepreneurial entities beginning to explore these possibilities. The firm's clients are in a wide variety of businesses,  including manufacturing,  software,  telecommunications,  financial services,  biotechnology,  investment banking,  commodities futures,  health care services,  real estate,  consumer products,  transportation,  retail sales,  entertainment,  visual arts,  and electronics. In addition to its representation of emerging public companies,  the firm represents a variety of established corporate clients and national and international financial and real estate institutions in corporate and securities matters,  and has in-depth experience in mergers and acquisitions,  corporate finance,  institutional lending,  business insolvency,  tax,  and similar areas. Attorneys in the Group have represented clients in numerous securities offerings,  contested and friendly mergers,  acquisitions and divestitures,  proxy fights,  venture capital transactions,  leveraged buyouts and recapitalizations,  and numerous lending and credit transactions. These include secured and unsecured credit facilities; term loans; complex financial restructurings with capital appreciation rights; institutional placements of mezzanine and subordinated debt; standby,  direct,  and commercial letters of credit; asset-based financings; tax and strategic financial planning; business insolvencies and workouts; and federal and state regulatory compliance.<BR><P>Complementing the corporate practice,  the firm also has substantial practices in other areas such as labor and employment law,  ERISA,  bankruptcy and creditors' rights,  health care,  international trade and customs,  intellectual property,  communications and telecommunications,  government contracts,  environmental law,  commodities regulations,  real estate and land use,  and estate planning,  which can be helpful when such knowledge is required. <BR>
