<P>
<P>
<P><B>T</B>he corporate practice at Seyfarth,  Shaw,  Fairweather  & Geraldson includes approximately 80 lawyers. We represent companies in all aspects of corporate and securities matters,  including mergers and acquisitions; divestitures and joint ventures; environmental,  tax,  employee benefits,  labor,  and antitrust issues; and public,  private,  and government financing. We have handled all types of transactions,  including negotiated asset and stock acquisitions of publicly and privately held enterprises,  tender offers for public companies,  and leveraged buyouts. We are involved in structuring transactions and assessing their impact and the effect on financial statements. Our real estate practice is diverse,  representing participants in all phases of commercial transactions.
<P><BR><P>In the area of securities law,  we assist with routine and complex securities matters at the state and federal level,  including private placements,  public offerings,  and periodic filings with the SEC and related disclosure issues,  as well as preparing registration statements,  prospectuses,  private placement memoranda,  other financing and offering documents,  and underwriter representation.<BR><P>Seyfarth Shaw has a large practice in the representation of financial institutions,  including the organization and acquisition of financial institutions,  representation before regulatory agencies,  counseling clients on compliance matters,  and commercial and asset-based lending and leasing. We also represent borrowers in secured and unsecured loan transactions.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Theodore E. Cornell III</B> (<I>Chicago</I>) is the head of the Firm's business law group. He practices in the areas of finance and business combinations,  including mergers and acquisitions,  venture capital,  secured lending,  and leasing.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael E. Blount </B>(<I>Chicago</I>) practices corporate and securities law,  representing U.S. and foreign companies in mergers,  acquisitions,  and divestitures; joint ventures; financings; and 1933 Act and 1934 Act matters. <BR>
