<HEAD>
<TITLE>Willkie Farr  & Gallagher
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Corporate Securities</H2>
<H3>Willkie Farr  & Gallagher
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>New York: </B>One Citicorp Center,  153 East 53rd Street,  New York,  NY 10022<BR>
Tel 212-821-8000  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-821-8111<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Washington,  D.C.,  Paris,  London<BR>
<BR>
401 lawyers  <B>*</B>  128 lawyers in Corporate and Financial Services Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/willkie.html"> ERISA</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/willkie.html"> White Collar Crime</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>W</B>illkie Farr  & Gallagher engages in the general practice of law,  including the corporate and financial services,  bankruptcy and business reorganizations,  employee benefits and employee relations,  environmental,  intellectual property,  international trade,  legislative and governmental relations,  litigation,  real estate,  tax,  telecommunications,  and trusts and estates areas.
<P><BR><P>Our Corporate and Financial Services Group handles a wide variety of financial transactions. We offer clients broad expertise in all types of acquisition,  joint venture,  transaction financing,  and regulatory matters.<BR><P>With respect to mergers and acquisitions,  we have extensively and successfully represented bidders,  targets,  special committees of boards of directors,  debt and equity investors,  financial advisers,  and arbitrageurs in some of the most significant acquisitions of publicly traded companies. Our M &A practice includes contested takeover situations,  strategic industrial alliances,  leveraged buyouts,  and acquisitions from reorganization proceedings.<BR>
<BR><P>Our extensive experience in the area of public offerings includes all types of debt and equity securities by both U.S. and foreign issuers. We handle transactions of all sizes,  from issuances by seasoned public companies to initial public offerings of new entities,  and represent both underwriters and issuers in all fields of commerce and industry. Recent public offerings have involved a wide variety of industries,  including fiber optic telecommunications,  television broadcasting,  health care,  natural resources,  defense electronics,  and investment banking. We have also been significantly involved in offerings of real estate investment trusts.<BR>
<BR><P>We regularly assist a number of venture capital firms that provide seed money to start-up enterprises and make special equity investments in established enterprises such as health care,  biotechnology,  computers,  consumer products,  electronics,  publishing,  telecommunications,  and environmental cleanup and control. On numerous occasions,  we have represented enterprises from their start-up and venture capital stages through their eventual public offerings of securities and onward through further stages of financial development and growth by acquisitions.<BR>
<BR><P>We are routinely involved in a wide variety of important private placement transactions for which we advise several major U.S. institutional investors. These transactions take the forms of traditional and Rule 144A private placements,  both domestic and cross-border,  and include secured and unsecured note issues,  acquisition finance,  oil and gas finance (including production payments and reserved-based lending),  asset-backed finance,  leasing,  and project finance of assets and facilities as diverse as power plants,  pipelines,  aircraft,  satellites and transponders,  manufacturing plants,  resource recovery and cogeneration facilities,  and financial restructurings.<BR>
<BR><P>We represent a sizeable number of domestic and foreign money managers with total assets under management in excess of approximately $90 billion. We also assist investment advisers to both registered and exempt investment companies. We are experienced in dealing with the fiduciary and regulatory issues that are frequently involved in transactions governing the acquisition of investment management businesses and the reorganization of investment companies.<BR>
<BR><P>We have a substantial public finance practice directed to the issuance by governmental units and agencies of tax-exempt and taxable securities,  the proceeds of which are used to finance public projects such as power facilities,  state and local infrastructure,  housing,  airports,  colleges,  and hospitals. The firm represents approximately 65 percent of the issuers of municipal securities in the State of New York,  including most of its counties and fire districts,  villages,  school districts,  towns,  and special district corporations. In addition,  we serve as counsel to many of the country's larger underwriters (including,  in some instances,  banks) of tax-exempt bonds. The public finance group has been at the forefront of the development of municipal derivative products,  including inverse floating rate instruments,  auction rate securities,  and municipal securities involving explicit and implicit interest rate floors,  caps,  and swaps. It also represents governmental units and agencies through the United States,  with a special emphasis on New York State and the western United States.<BR>
<BR><P>The firm has a growing structured finance practice representing underwriters,  issuers,  and investors in publicly offered and privately placed mortgage-backed and asset-backed transactions. These cutting-edge financings involve a broad range of asset types from residential and commercial mortgages to auto and boat loans to equipment lease,  trade,  and health care receivables. The structured finance group is comprised of a team of attorneys with corporate,  securities,  real estate,  bankruptcy,  tax,  ERISA,  and secured lending expertise who actively seek those matters that require special effort because they are interdisciplinary and unique.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>John S. D'Alimonte</B> is a senior partner specializing in the corporate and securities areas in the U.S. and abroad. His experience includes representing issuers and underwriters in public offerings and flotations in the United States and internationally. In addition,  his practice encompasses strategic corporate investments,  merger and acquisition activities (both hostile and negotiated transactions),  privatizations,  venture capital investments,  corporate joint ventures,  and commercial contracts and relationships of all types. Since 1980 Mr. D'Alimonte has been an adjunct professor of law at St. John's University School of Law in New York,  teaching basic courses and advanced seminars in the areas of U.S. and international securities law. St. John's University,  J.D.,  1968.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Steven J. Gartner</B> is a corporate partner with significant experience in mergers and acquisitions and public and private offerings of both U.S. and non-U.S. issuers. He spent more than two years in Willkie Farr's London office representing the firm's clients in the U.K. and Europe. St. John's University,  J.D.,  1984.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Peter J. Kenny</B> specializes in the financing of public projects and programs such as power generation and transmission facilities,  state and local infrastructure,  housing,  airports,  colleges and hospitals,  industrial development,  clean water revolving funds,  small business loan pools,  and single-family mortgage programs. His practice includes the representation of issuers and underwriters of tax-exempt and taxable debt securities of state and local governmental units and public authorities,  as well as financial guarantors and other credit enhancement providers. His experience includes public debt offerings,  private placements,  variable rate tender option bonds,  inverse floating rate securities,  interest rate swaps,  certificate of participation issues,  and structured financings,  among others. He is currently vice-chairman of the American Bar Association Urban Law Section Committee on Public Securities. St. John's University,  J.D.,  1966.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Christopher E. Manno</B>,  the managing partner of Willkie Farr  & Gallagher's London office from 1988 to 1995,  is an international corporate and securities lawyer who began his career with Willkie Farr in 1978. In addition to his years of practice in the United States and England,  Mr. Manno was assigned to the firm's Paris office from 1983 to 1986 where he gained significant experience dealing in commercial legal matters on the Continent,  in the Middle East,  and in Africa. Mr. Manno is the coauthor of <I>Doing Business in Europe: Before and After 1992</I> (NYSBA,  1992) and was also a U.S. company law contributor to Peat Marwick McLintock's <I>Guide to Acquisitions in the U.S.</I> (Butterworths,  1989). He is a foreign member of the British Law Society. St. John's University,  J.D.,  1979; managing editor,  <I>St. John's Law Review</I>,  1979.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard D. Rudder</B> is head of the structured finance group and has,  since 1977,  developed a broad background in asset-backed financings,  including mortgage and asset-backed securities and leveraged leases of real estate and equipment. He has represented almost all of the major underwriters and life insurance companies,  and certain of the state pension funds,  in public and privately placed transactions. Mr. Rudder was an instructor at the New York University Real Estate Institute,  where he created a full semester course in mortgage-backed securities. He has also served on numerous panels dealing with topics in securitization. New York University,  J.D.,  1966.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Nora Ann Wallace</B> is a partner whose practice is in the corporate and securities area,  with a special emphasis in public offering,  institutional,  private placement,  and general corporate and contract matters. Harvard University,  J.D.,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Brent W. White</B> has significant experience in corporate secured and unsecured public and private debt transactions (including mortgage,  receivables,  and other asset-backed syndicated loans),  debt restructurings and workouts,  credit enhancements,  interest rate and currency swaps,  structured finance,  public debt offerings,  mortgage banking,  tax-exempt financings (including authorizing legislation and the establishment of new issuers and programs),  tax-exempt synthetic securities,  and secondary market securities dispositions by financial institutions. Vanderbilt University,  J.D.,  1973.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
