   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/wilmer.html"> White Collar Crime</A>
   <LI><A HREF="..//wilmer.html"> Workou</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>
<BR>

<P><BR>

<P><B>W</B>ilmer,  Cutler  & Pickering's corporate and transactions practice covers the full range of business,  commercial,  and securities transactions,  including initial public offerings; mergers and acquisitions; joint ventures and partnership arrangements; divestitures; equity and debt financing; restructurings and recapitalizations; proxy contests and takeover defense; project development and financing; subsidiary,  franchise,  and distribution arrangements; and technology and licensing matters.<BR><BR><P>Our work on initial public offerings,  registration of securities,  financing,  and transactions matters includes the following:<BR><UL><BR>
<BR><P><LI> We represented US West in the recent formation of a joint venture of USWest's domestic cellular telephone operations and those of AirTouch Communications,  the cellular telephone company spun off by PacBell.<BR><BR><P><LI> We are counsel to investment banking firms,  including Donaldson,  Lufkin  & Jenrette,  Merrill Lynch,  PaineWebber,  and Goldman Sachs,  on various federal securities law issues and financing transactions.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> We provided corporate and tax advice to Carr Realty Corporation in connection with its formation and a complex real estate `rollup, ' and we were its counsel in its initial public offering.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> We represented Capital Cities/ABC in its recent $2 billion tender offer for shares of its common stock and in its recent acquisition of a 20 percent ownership position in Scandinavian Broadcasting Systems,  a public company. We also represent Capital Cities/ABC in several venture capital investments.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> We represented the Aerospace Creditors Liquidating Trust in registering its certificates of beneficial interest (CBIs) with the SEC and listing the CBIs on the Pacific Stock Exchange.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> We are representing the Berlin-Brandenberg Airport Authority in connection with both the financial and the regulatory aspects of building a new airport in Berlin.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> We represented Jerry Jones in his acquisition of the Dallas Cowboys and Texas Stadium,  and continue to represent the Cowboys on partnership,  financing,  and contract issues.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> We have represented Lufthansa in several transactions,  including its acquisition of a controlling interest in DHL International,  and we continue to represent DHL in Brussels.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> We represented Household Finance Corporation in the acquisition of a $2.25 billion portfolio of consumer loans from ITT Consumer Finance Corporation and in the acquisition and divestiture of other businesses.<BR>
<BR>
<BR></UL><LI><B>Louis R. Cohen</B> has been involved in a number of complex corporate and securities law matters. Mr. Cohen served as deputy solicitor general in the U.S. Department of Justice from 1986 to 1988. He also has taught corporate finance courses at both Stanford Law School and Harvard Law School. Harvard University,  A.B.,  1962,  LL.B.,  1966; Oxford University (Wadham College).<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Michael R. Klein</B> has represented many companies and boards of directors in connection with takeover contests,  acquisitions and dispositions,  and internal investigations. Mr. Klein has taught courses in corporate and securities laws at several law schools and has lectured broadly on a number of corporate and securities law issues. University of Miami,  B.B.A.,  1963,  J.D. 1966; Harvard University,  LL.M.,  1967.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Richard Cass</B> has represented companies and entrepreneurs in complex corporate and securities transactions and has advised various companies and boards of directors in connection with takeover contests,  acquisitions and dispositions,  and public securities offerings. In 1985 he was adjunct professor of law at Georgetown University where he taught corporate finance. Princeton University,  A.B.,  1968; Yale University,  J.D.,  1971.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Stephen F. Doyle</B> has represented clients in a variety of international corporate and commercial transactions,  including mergers,  acquisitions,  and divestitures,  as well as the formation and ongoing affairs of multinational joint ventures. Mr. Doyle also has worked in distribution and licensing,  particularly in the computer area. Harvard University,  A.B.,  1972; University of Texas,  J.D.,  1976.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>William J. Perlstein</B> is the senior administrative attorney in the firm's bankruptcy practice and has been involved in the securities law aspects of many public company reorganizations. He is a frequent lecturer at Practising Law Institute and other professional education seminars. Union College,  B.A.,  1971; Yale University,  J.D.,  1974; London School of Economics.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Russell J. Bruemmer</B> practices primarily in the corporate and commercial areas,  including the negotiation and documentation of acquisition,  joint ventures,  and financing transactions,  and the federal regulation of financial institutions. Mr. Bruemmer has served as chief counsel (legislation) at the Federal Bureau of Investigation,  special counsel to the Director of Central Intelligence,  and general counsel of the Central Intelligence Agency. Luther College,  B.A.,  1974; University of Michigan Law School,  J.D.,  1977.<BR>
