<HEAD>
<TITLE><\2>Beveridge  & Diamond,  P.C.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Environmental</H2>
<H3>Beveridge  & Diamond,  P.C.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington:</B> 1350 I Street,  N.W.,  Suite 700,  Washington,  DC 20005<BR>
Tel 202-789-6000  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-789-6190<BR>
<B>New York:</B> 437 Madison Avenue,  40th Floor,  New York,  NY 10022<BR>
Tel 212-702-5400  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-702-5450<BR>
<B>San Francisco:</B> One Sansome Street,  Suite 3400,  San Francisco,  CA 94104<BR>
Tel 415-397-0100  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-397-4238<BR>
<B>Fort Lee:</B> One Bridge Plaza,  Suite 400,  Fort Lee,  NJ 07024<BR>
Tel 201-585-8162  <B>*</B>  Fax 201-529-7720<BR>
<BR>
82 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers in Environmental Regulation and Litigation<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>
<BR>

<P><BR>

<P><B>B</B>everidge  & Diamond,  P.C.,  is a law firm with a national practice of more than 80 environmental lawyers. Since its establishment in 1974,  the firm's practice has been devoted to environmental law,  litigation,  and related practice areas. With offices in Washington,  D.C.,  New York,  California,  and New Jersey,  the firm offers services on a regional basis while at the same time providing full benefit of the institutional experience of its nationwide practice. The location of the firm's headquarters in Washington also puts it at the center of regulatory,  legislative,  and judicial developments at the national level.
<P><BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Overview of Environmental Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>The firm's practice spans the entire range of contemporary environmental issues,  including air,  water,  wetlands,  natural resources,  solid and hazardous wastes,  Superfund,  NEPA,  EPCRA,  toxic torts,  environmental insurance,  TSCA,  biotechnology,  pesticides and food safety,  OSHA,  and international environmental issues. In addition,  the firm has a comprehensive environmental litigation practice,  including representation before federal and state courts at all levels,  and complete environmental transactional compliance capabilities. The firm provides a multidisciplinary approach to identifying and resolving clients' problems.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Practice Groups</H3></CENTER>

<P>The Superfund Group has extensive experience negotiating,  counseling,  and litigating matters under CERCLA (Superfund),  including cost-recovery and natural resource damage claims. The group has represented individual companies or served as common counsel at over 100 Superfund sites,  and is closely involved in the Superfund reauthorization effort.<BR>

<P>The RCRA Group has participated in virtually every major RCRA rulemaking and challenge,  and handles enforcement,  permitting,  and corrective action matters. The RCRA practice also focuses heavily on solid waste/resource recovery and recycling issues.The Water Group represents industrial and municipal clients in federal and state enforcement actions,  wastewater discharge permitting,  and EPA rulemakings,  including storm water regulation. The group is also experienced in Safe Drinking Water Act matters.<BR>
The Wetlands and Natural Resources Group represents developers,  industrial corporations,  and state and local government agencies regulated under Section 404 of the Clean Water Act. The group is experienced in permit negotiations,  enforcement proceedings,  and legislative and regulatory lobbying,  and has also dealt extensively with the Endangered Species Act,  NEPA,  and issues relating to natural resources.<BR>
The Air Group represents clients on every aspect of the Clean Air Act and risk assessment relative to toxic pollutants. It lobbies legislative issues,  negotiates and defends enforcement actions,  handles agency rulemaking proceedings,  and advises on compliance with air standards on the federal,  state,  and local levels.<BR>
The Product Regulation Group represents major producers in all aspects of the EPA's regulation of pesticides,  including special reviews,  data compensation and arbitrations,  registration transfers,  and compliance with federal requirements. The firm also represents clients on all aspects of TSCA,  food safety,  product labeling,  and biotechnology issues.<BR>
The International Environmental Practice Group advises multinational clients on a broad range of environmental matters arising under international agreements and the domestic environmental laws of other countries.<BR>
The lawyers below can direct you to an attorney within the above-listed practice groups who can best serve your needs.<BR>

<P><BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>John S. Guttmann,  Jr.</B> (<I>Washington; 202-789-6020</I>) Mr. Guttmann is the managing director of Beveridge  & Diamond,  P.C. His practice is principally devoted to litigation in the environmental area. He has served as lead counsel in numerous cases arising under CERCLA,  RCRA,  and the Clean Air Act,  has counseled clients on regulatory requirements under federal and state air programs,  and has performed numerous environmental due diligence investigations.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert D. Wyatt</B> (<I>San Francisco; 415-983-7701</I>) Mr. Wyatt is the administrative director of the firm's San Francisco office. Mr. Wyatt is a former deputy regional counsel of the U.S. EPA,  Region IX. His practice has focused on issues concerning RCRA,  CERCLA,  the Clean Water Act,  wetlands regulations,  and compliance audits.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Stephen L. Gordon</B> (<I>New York; 212-702-5410</I>) Mr. Gordon is the administrative director of the firm's New York and New Jersey offices. He is a former Deputy Attorney General of New Jersey and former First Deputy Commissioner for the New York State Department of Environmental Conservation. Mr. Gordon has experience in land use,  litigation,  and most other environmental areas.<BR>
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
