<HEAD>
<TITLE>Cutler  & Stanfield
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Environmental</H2>
<H3>Cutler  & Stanfield
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington:</B> 700 14th Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20005<BR>
Tel 202-624-8400  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-624-8415<BR>
<B>Denver:</B> 1625 Broadway,  Denver,  CO 80202<BR>
Tel 303-592-4200  <B>*</B>  Fax 303-592-4205<BR>
<BR>
15 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers in environmental regulation and litigation<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>T</B>he exclusive focus of Cutler  & Stanfield is on a national practice in environmental, land use,  and natural resources law. The firm was founded in 1988 by lawyers who believed that the increasing complexity of environmental law justified a firm's exclusive attention to those areas and that the firm's clients would be well-served by the breadth of experience and the depth of expertise that such a firm could provide. Cutler  & Stanfield has represented clients in a wide range of environmental matters in more than 30 states and several foreign countries.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Experience</H3></CENTER>

<P>In addition to all significant federal and state statutory and regulatory regimes,  Cutler  & Stanfield's environmental practice embraces related matters such as the supervision of environmental audits of clients' operations and properties,  and the representation of U.S. government contractors concerning their environmental responsibilities and liabilities. The firm has undertaken the primary litigation responsibility in scores of environmental and related civil matters in state and federal trial and appellate courts throughout the United States. These cases have included the defense of the largest single enforcement action brought by the U.S. government under the Clean Water Act and other major multiparty and multiforum complex litigation under CERCLA and other federal and state statutes.<BR><P>Cutler  & Stanfield lawyers combine sophisticated legal skills with an understanding of government and politics which comes from direct,  personal experience. As a result,  the firm maintains an unusual and successful practice specialty in general representation,  negotiations,  and litigation concerning complex public sector undertakings. For example,  Cutler  & Stanfield lawyers negotiated an intergovernmental agreement for the development of the new Denver International Airport which the <I>Denver Post</I> said `nearly defies political gravity.'<BR>
<BR><P>Cutler  & Stanfield has represented a broad range of both large and small corporate and other private and commercial clients,  including Air Products and Chemicals,  Bechtel,  The Walt Disney Co.,  General Electric,  EG &G Rocky Flats,  Kaiser Resources,  Petro-Canada,  Revlon,  and Skanska AB. The firm's public sector clients have included the FDIC,  the State of Indiana,  the Puerto Rico Aqueduct and Sewer Authority,  the City of Chicago,  the Raleigh-Durham Airport Authority,  the California Institute of Technology,  and dozens of county and local governments.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Eliot R. Cutler</B> Complex public sector negotiations and litigation; land use; airport development and noise. Former legislative assistant to U.S. Senator Edmund S. Muskie; drafted NEPA,  Clean Air Act,  CERCLA,  and other federal legislation. Former associate director for natural resources,  energy,  and science,  White House Office of Management and Budget. Admitted in District of Columbia,  Maine,  and New York.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jeffrey L. Stanfield</B> Federal facilities,  toxic and hazardous wastes; energy-related environmental issues. Former associate undersecretary of the Department of Energy; responsible for DOE budget and policy formulation,  particularly in areas of energy research,  weapons production,  and environmental remediation. Admitted in District of Columbia and Tennessee.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Sheila D. Jones</B> Toxic and hazardous wastes regulation and litigation; general environmental litigation. Former assistant chief,  Department of Justice Environmental Enforcement Section; headed litigation team in first Superfund enforcement case tried under CERCLA. Also litigated numerous cases for EPA under Clean Air Act,  Clean Water Act,  and RCRA. Admitted in District of Columbia and Colorado.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Perry M. Rosen</B> General environmental and land use litigation. Former Department of Justice trial attorney. Admitted in District of Columbia,  Colorado,  and Idaho.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James H. Holt</B> Environmental issues related to energy production and transportation; Federal Energy Regulatory Commission proceedings; and federal court litigation. Admitted in District of Columbia.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Peter J. Kirsch</B> Clean Water Act; NEPA; Endangered Species Act; airport expansion and development; historic preservation; land use. Admitted in District of Columbia,  Washington, and Maryland.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
