<HEAD>
<TITLE>Danaher,  Tedford,  Lagnese  & Neal
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Environmental</H2>
<H3>Danaher,  Tedford,  Lagnese  & Neal
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Hartford:</B> Capitol Place,  21 Oak Street,  Suite 700,  Hartford,  CT 06106<BR>
Tel 203-247-3666  <B>*</B>  Fax 203-547-1321<BR>
<B>New York:</B> 20 Exchange Place,  31st Floor,  New York,  NY 10005<BR>
Tel 212-269-7100  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-269-2976<BR>
<BR>
26 lawyers  <B>*</B>  18 lawyers practicing in environmental and toxic tort litigation<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profile in the following other directory:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/danaher.html"> Product Liability</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>D</B>anaher,  Tedford,  Lagnese  & Neal is a medium-sized law firm in Hartford,  Connecticut which has established a national practice in the area of defensive toxic tort litigation.
<P><BR><P>The firm originated with a focus on complex litigation with strong ties to Connecticut. Over approximately the last 12 years,  it has expanded into a practice which involves both direct trial and appellate responsibility and litigation management on a national basis. The litigation management is conducted under the supervision of the firm's attorneys largely through a staff of paralegals and a network of local counsel. Historically,  much of this practice and experience has included not only the traditional litigation of individual cases,  but the management of such more recent phenomena as large class actions,  federal multidistrict proceedings,  repetitive punitive damages issues,  and claims regarding junk science. Over the years,  the firm's practice has been broadened to include numerous environmental and toxic tort matters,  such as cases involving asbestos,  solvents,  pesticides,  formaldehyde,  the disposal of nuclear waste,  breast implants,  and the Dalkon Shield. The firm's clients in these areas are both national and local corporations,  medical society risk management pools,  and a quasipublic state agency.<BR><P>The firm also has an insurance coverage practice related to environmental issues. This typically involves the representation of insurance companies in cases involving Superfund sites and groundwater contamination. It has also involved the representation of parties in other coverage matters such as DES litigation. Finally,  the firm has performed environmental litigation support services for Hartford insurers such as the retrieval and organization of documents for national discovery purposes.<BR>
<BR><P>The firm has a general practice in addition to the above environmental and toxic tort litigation concentration. This includes a corporate and commercial department which deals with environmental regulatory matters as part of its banking and real estate practice.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>R. Cornelius Danaher,  Jr.</B> Mr. Danaher is the senior partner of the firm. He is the national litigation counsel for a major corporation and has extensive experience in both direct toxic tort litigation and insurance coverage for environmental claims. He is the author of `Duty to Defend, ' <I>Insurance Coverage and Practice: DRI Course Book</I>,  May 1985; and `Insurance Perspectives in Drug Litigation, ' Toxic Tort Section of the American Bar Association Convention,  1985. Georgetown University,  J.D.,  1973.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Joyce A. Lagnese</B> Ms. Lagnese,  one of the firm's managing partners,  is an experienced trial attorney with extensive experience in toxic tort litigation and is also very involved in the litigation of breast implant and other medico-legal cases. Hofstra University,  J.D.,  with honors,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Frederick B. Tedford</B> Mr. Tedford has over 20 years of trial experience,  primarily in the areas of asbestos and other toxic tort litigation. Suffolk University,  J.D.,  1972.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kenneth R. Neal</B> Mr. Neal has 25 years of trial experience,  again primarily in the area of toxic tort litigation. He has tried numerous cases to completion both in Connecticut and throughout the nation. Boston College,  J.D.,  1969.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Frank H. Santoro</B> Mr. Santoro concentrates on environmental,  insurance coverage,  and appellate litigation. He is the former chief of the Civil Division of the U.S. Attorney's Office for the District of Connecticut,  a former special counsel to the Commissioner of the Department of Environmental Protection for the State of Connecticut,  and the author of `The National Environmental Policy Act in Connecticut, ' 62 <I>Connecticut Bar Journal</I> 290 (1988) and `Connecticut Environmental Companies' (1993). Georgetown University,  J.D.,  1967; University of London,  LL.M.,  1971.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kathleen F. Munroe</B> Ms. Munroe concentrates on environmental insurance coverage matters. She was a former officer of the Travelers Insurance Company with extensive experience managing environmental insurance coverage litigation,  toxic tort,  and pollution claims. She is the author of ` Lost Policy' Issues: The Burden of Proof, ' 4 <I>Environmental Claims Journal</I> 63 (Autumn 1991).<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
