<HEAD>
<TITLE>Goodwin,  Procter  & Hoar
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Environmental</H2>
<H3>Goodwin,  Procter  & Hoar
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Boston:</B> Exchange Place,  Boston,  MA 02109<BR>
Tel 617-570-1000  <B>*</B>  Fax 617-227-8591<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> 901 Fifteenth Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20005<BR>
Tel 202-414-6160  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-789-1720<BR>
<B>Albany:</B> One Steuben Place,  Albany,  NY 12207<BR>
Tel 518-472-9460  <B>*</B>  Fax 518-472-9472<BR>
<BR>
289 lawyers  <B>*</B>  22 lawyers concentrating in environmental law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profile in the following other directory:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/goodwin.html"> Product Liability</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>T</B>he Environmental Law Department at Goodwin,  Procter  & Hoar was established in 1977 and is one of the oldest and largest in the United States. The Department includes attorneys with degrees and experience in science and engineering,  as well as a full-time staff scientist,  and takes pride in finding practical solutions to complex environmental and health and safety problems for its clients. 
<P><BR><P>The Department has developed a national and international reputation for its expertise and experience in a broad range of environmental and health and safety issues. Its work includes regulatory counseling; compliance audits and assessments; project development,  environmental impact review,  permitting,  due diligence,  and environmental opinions in connection with corporate and real estate transactions; negotiation and mediation among and between private parties and government agencies concerning cleanup actions and allocation of response costs at state and federal Superfund sites; defense of governmental enforcement actions; environmental insurance counseling and coverage litigation; practice before federal and state courts and administrative agencies throughout the United States; and a multifaceted overseas practice with a focus on due diligence review and compliance counseling and audits. <BR><P>The Department's attorneys have authored books and articles for a variety of national and international publications,  including a leading four-volume treatise on hazardous waste management,  cleanup,  and liability,  <I>The Law of Hazardous Waste</I>,  published by Matthew Bender  & Co. The Department has also authored the <I>Massachusetts Environmental Law Handbook</I>,  published by Government Institutes.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Nancer Ballard</B>,  head of the firm's Insurance Practice Group,  represents numerous companies in multi-site,  multi-insurer insurance coverage litigation. She also represents clients in connection with private party claims and in negotiations with federal and state environmental agencies.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jeffrey C. Bates</B> represents clients in environmental litigation and provides advice on complex regulatory requirements in the United States and abroad. He has particular experience in contaminated site and groundwater issues,  chemical regulation,  audits,  and enforcement matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Donald S. Berry</B>,  P.C.,  represents and counsels clients on a variety of environmental matters,  including hazardous waste management,  Superfund liability and site cleanup,  air and water pollution control,  and environmental impact review,  as well as matters in connection with corporate and real estate transactions.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gregory A. Bibler</B>,  head of the firm's Environmental Litigation Practice Group,  represents manufacturing companies and financial institutions in litigation involving a range of environmental issues and has established a number of precedents in environmental tort cases involving contaminated property.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Susan M. Cooke</B>,  P.C.,  a former EPA enforcement attorney,  chairs the firm's Environmental Department. She was an originator of environmental opinion letters and her practice includes hazardous waste,  chemical regulation,  and air and water pollution issues; workplace health and safety matters; Superfund negotiations; and due diligence reviews.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Christopher P. Davis</B>,  a former engineer,  represents and counsels companies in environmental litigation and Superfund matters. His practice also includes defense and settlement of enforcement actions,  compliance counseling,  and resolution of complex environmental liability and technical issues.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael S. Elder</B>,  resident partner in the firm's Albany office,  is a former U.S. Justice Department attorney who represented the EPA in Love Canal-related litigation. A former head of the New York Attorney General's Environmental Crimes Unit,  he has extensive experience in complex civil and criminal litigation.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Paul C. Nightingale</B> heads the firm's International Environmental Law Practice Group. He advises and represents clients in connection with state and federal waste site cleanups and business transactions involving environmental liability concerns,  and has particular experience in advising lending institutions on such matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Stephen H. Schroeder</B>,  a former engineer,  headed the enforcement attorneys at the EPA's Boston office before joining the firm. He represents and counsels clients on a wide variety of environmental matters,  including air and water pollution regulation,  environmental enforcement,  and Superfund issues.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>E. Michael Thomas</B>,  a former EPA Superfund and RCRA attorney,  represents and counsels clients in enforcement actions,  cleanup negotiations,  and permitting of industrial facilities,  as well as in release reporting and toxic substances control matters. He also serves as a Superfund allocation consultant.<BR><BR>

</UL>


