</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/hall.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/hall.html"> ERISA</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/hall.html"> Labor</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>H</B>all  & Evans is one of the largest firms in the Rocky Mountain Region,  and we have provided legal services in litigation,  business,  and insurance law for over 60 years. We handle environmental and toxic tort law issues efficiently and cost-effectively with active participation by our clients. We deliver innovative solutions,  prompt dispute resolution,  and multidimensional legal strategies.
<P><UL><BR><BR>
<BR><P>Our environmental attorneys address:<LI> Hazardous Waste Act compliance and enforcement;<BR>
<LI> leaking underground storage tank enforcement and cleanups;<BR>
<LI> toxic tort and personal injury claim defense;<BR>
<LI> on- and off-site contamination claims;<BR>
<LI> Superfund defense at the administrative stage and in litigation;<BR>
<LI> government and private-party cost-recovery defense under CERCLA/RCRA;<BR>
<LI> CWA,  CAA,  TSCA,  and FIFRA compliance;<BR>
<LI> criminal matters involving environmental compliance;<BR>
<LI> penalty assessment defense; and<BR>
<LI> insurance coverage analysis and litigation.<BR></UL>
<BR><P>Our attorneys are well versed in environmental commercial matters including:<BR><UL><LI> ongoing advice and assistance in environmental compliance;<BR>
<LI> OSHA issues;<BR>
<LI> mining and gravel permitting;<BR>
<LI> real estate transactions;<BR>
<LI> environmental audits; and<BR>
<LI> SARA Title III.<BR></UL><BR>
<BR><P>Our clients include manufacturers; generators,  transporters,  and users of hazardous materials; owners and operators of hazardous waste sites; and governmental entities faced with environmental compliance and enforcement issues. Our practice is enhanced by the scientific and technical backgrounds in environmental sciences,  chemistry,  mining,  and engineering of many of our attorneys. We handle complex claims throughout the United States,  and we are known for our ability to quickly assemble specifically tailored teams of highly qualified experts,  attorneys,  and support staff who are able to meet the legal needs created by extraordinary events.<BR>
<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Chris A. Mattison</B> chairs Hall  & Evans' Environmental and Toxic Tort Defense Practice Group. His practice focuses on environmental and insurance litigation and administrative claims. He defends administrative enforcement matters under CERCLA,  RCRA,  CWA,  FIFRA,  TSCA,  and various state statutes,  as well as in third-party and governmental cost recovery actions under Superfund and RCRA. He has represented a number of national companies in toxic tort and product liability claims involving leaking underground storage tanks and solvent,  beryllium,  fertilizer,  and pesticide exposure. He serves as regional counsel for a major insurer in coverage matters for contaminated sites in Colorado and other western states. He was responsible for directing the successful defense of the Denver Water Board in <I>Renaud v. Martin Marietta Corp.</I>,  a landmark toxic tort case in Colorado.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John A. Bachmann</B>'s practice focuses on the regulatory and environmental control aspects and the transactional requirements of natural resource development. He sustains his client's position in permitting mineral exploration and development operations with federal,  state,  and local administrative agencies as well as in defending these operations in administrative and civil enforcement actions. In addition,  Mr. Bachmann has more than a decade of experience in occupational safety and health defense matters. He also negotiates,  structures,  and completes complex business transactions. Prior to joining Hall  & Evans as counsel,  he served as counsel with Chevron Corporation and Gulf Oil Corporation for 17 years.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Anthony L. Joseph</B> focuses on white collar criminal defense representation,  where he addresses violations related to hazardous waste disposal and organizational safety as well as fraud and anticompetitive behavior. He was the co-first chair on the defense team in <I>U.S. </I>v.<I> Pacific Enterprises Oil Company</I>,  a criminal defense case involving numerous hazardous waste disposal violation issues,  and achieved a highly favorable disposition for his client. He also recently represent- ed a major oil company in a RCRA civil penalties enforcement action.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Marilyn Sterrenberg-Rose</B> chairs the firm's Insurance Coverage Practice Group,  where she represents insurers on the local through national levels in the areas of insurance coverage and bad faith. With respect to environmental coverage issues she provides analysis or litigates suits directly in connection with hazardous waste sites in Colorado,  Wyoming,  Texas,  Michigan,  Kansas,  and Oklahoma.<BR>
<BR>
<P>Additional attorneys in our Environmental and Toxic Tort Law Practice Group include firm members <B>Edward H. Widmann</B> (insurance coverage and bad faith; toxic tort defense),  <B>Richard A. Hanneman</B> (toxic tort defense including asbestos),  <B>Linda S. Comer</B> (medical causation as related to environmental matters),  and <B>Matthew Y. Biscan</B> (toxic tort defense including lead poisoning and pharmaceutical contamination).<BR>
<BR>
<BR>


</UL></BODY>
