<P><BR>

<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Energy Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P><B>T</B>he firm represents energy clients in all phases of litigation,  regulatory,  and commercial practice. A significant portion of the regulatory practice is before the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission and federal courts,  where the firm represents electric companies,  natural gas companies,  and oil companies in ratemaking,  rulemaking,  certificate,  accounting,  and investigatory proceedings involving complex economic issues. The firm is also extensively engaged in representing gas and electric clients in industry,  restructuring,  and in assessing commercial opportunities arising in the newly competitive energy markets.
<P><BR><P>Hogan  & Hartson also has an extensive energy project finance and transactional practice that includes project development; negotiating power purchase,  fuel supply,  and transportation agreements; representing investors in newly privatized enterprises; and representing issuers in public and private offerings of equity and debt securities. Hogan  & Hartson is particularly strong in the area of energy project finance,  including multilateral institutional financing.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Environmental Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>Hogan  & Hartson attorneys counsel clients regarding compliance with regulations,  advise clients on enforcement issues,  and represent clients in federal and state litigation and rulemaking proceedings. In addition,  they assist clients with environmental issues in connection with mergers and acquisitions,  financings,  public offerings,  and property transfers.<BR><P>Hogan  & Hartson attorneys provide advice in the areas of Clean Air Act permitting and enforcement issues affecting mobile and stationary sources; solid and hazardous waste; Superfund liability,  including transactional contractual issues; biotechnology; chemical control; underground storage tanks; Clean Water Act compliance and defense matters,  including wetlands issues; chemical and pesticide issues involving registration,  marketing,  manufacturing,  import,  and export of pesticides and products on which pesticides are used; worker safety; and issues arising under the National Environmental Policy Act.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Tamara Adler</B> has represented energy clients in project financings,  sales,  mergers,  acquisitions,  Rule 144A,  public,  private,  and tax-exempt transactions.<BR><BR><LI><B>Raymond Batla</B> handles international energy financing and commercial matters and is especially active in energy project development.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Joseph Bell</B> advises on trends in the electric power industry,  counsels clients in domestic and international energy transactions,  and represents a major power marketer.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Claudette Christian</B> handles international and project finance and the securitization of U.S. government guarantees; and assists clients in obtaining financial assistance from international financial institutions.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kenneth Farber</B> represents clients in administrative and legislative proceedings with the EPA,  Congress,  and state agencies on issues under environmental statutes. He also conducts civil mediations.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kevin Lipson</B> represents interstate natural gas pipelines,  local distribution companies,  and one of the nation's largest users of natural gas for the generation of electricity in regulatory and commercial matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John Mathis</B> handles regulatory and project finance matters (including international projects) for electric utility and independent power companies,  integrated oil companies,  and significant end-users of electricity and natural gas.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Karol Lyn Newman</B> represents energy companies before the FERC and in the courts,  and on transactional matters including the development of energy projects.<BR>
<BR>
