<TITLE>Honigman Miller Schwartz and Cohn
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Environmental</H2>
<H3>Honigman MillerSchwartz and Cohn
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Detroit:</B> 2290 First National Building,  Detroit,  MI 48226<BR>
Tel 313-256-7800  <B>*</B>  Fax 313-962-0176<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Lansing,  Los Angeles,  Orlando,  Tampa,  West Palm Beach<BR>
<BR>
220 lawyers  <B>*</B>  21 lawyers concentrating in environmental law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profile in the following other directory:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/honigman.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>H</B>onigman Miller Schwartz and Cohn has a diverse,  well-established environmental practice. We handle the full spectrum of transactional,  administrative,  and litigation matters involving environmental issues.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Environmental Practice and Experience</H3></CENTER>

<P>Our attorneys have broad experience in all aspects of environmental law,  including air quality,  water quality,  solid waste,  hazardous waste,  Superfund,  Michigan Act 307,  underground storage tanks,  wetlands,  and land use matters. Many of the firm's attorneys have received degrees in technical areas such as engineering,  biology,  environmental sciences engineering,  and chemistry.<BR><P>We counsel clients on permitting,  reporting obligations,  compliance issues,  liability for cleanup costs,  and civil and criminal enforcement. We frequently appear before the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency,  the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers,  the Michigan Department of Natural Resources,  the Florida Department of Environmental Regulation,  and other state environmental agencies,  as well as state and federal courts. The firm also represents numerous real estate developers and has substantial experience with due diligence and lender liability issues. In addition,  we have successfully represented many clients seeking insurance coverage for environmental cleanup costs.<BR>
<BR><P>In <I>National Wildlife Federation </I>v.<I> Consumers Power Co.</I>,  we obtained a reversal by the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit of a lower court determination that the operation of a hydroelectric facility added pollutants to Lake Michigan in violation of the Clean Water Act. In <I>McLouth Steel Products Corp. </I>v.<I> Thomas</I>,  we successfully challenged the use of an EPA model to predict levels of hazardous constituents expected at receptor wells under the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act waste delisting procedures. The firm served as special environmental counsel to the City of Detroit in the development of cleanup standards for the site of a major new Chrysler automobile plant and has served in similar capacities in connection with other new automobile plants in and around Detroit,  including Mazda Motor Manufacturing (USA) Corporation's Flat Rock plant and General Motors Corporation's Hamtramck plant.<BR>
<BR><P>Our clients include companies involved in real estate development,  automotive-related manufacturing,  iron and steel,  chemicals,  paper products,  and waste management,  as well as municipalities. Among the firm's clients are Ford Motor Company,  Masco Corporation and its affiliates,  and Hughes Aircraft Company.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Joseph M. Polito</B> (<I>Detroit</I>) Chairperson of the Environmental Law Department. Substantial experience in most areas of environmental law with particular emphasis on hazardous waste management and CERCLA. Past chairperson of the State Bar of Michigan's Environmental Law Section. Listed in <I>The Best Lawyers in America</I>. University of Michigan,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1975.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Philip A. Grashoff,  Jr.</B> (<I>Detroit</I>) Concentrates on environmental litigation,  right-to-know,  and transactional matters. Past chairperson of the State Bar of Michigan's Environmental Law Section. Listed in <I>The Best Lawyers in America</I>. Wayne State University,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1972.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John W. Voelpel</B> (<I>Tampa; 813-222-6632</I>) Focuses on air quality,  solid waste,  and hazardous waste. Past chairperson of the State Bar of Michigan's Environmental Law Section. Listed in <I>The Best Lawyers in America</I>. University of Illinois,  B.S.,  chemical engineering; Wayne State University,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1972. Admitted in Michigan and Florida.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William A. Wichers II</B> (<I>Detroit</I>) Former senior staff attorney-environmental and nuclear,  The Detroit Edison Company. Has extensive experience in most areas of environmental practice including compliance,  permitting,  and transactional matters. University of Detroit,  J.D.,  1973.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>E. Lee Worsham</B> (<I>West Palm Beach; 407-838-4515</I>) Concentrates on transactional matters,  land use,  water quality and usage rights,  CERCLA,  and litigation. Former general counsel of St. Johns River Water Management District and former special district attorney for the State of Florida. Colorado State University,  B.S.,  watershed management and hydrology; University of Florida,  J.D.,  with honors,  1974.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael G. Cooke</B> (<I>Tampa; 813-222-6614</I>) Focuses on air quality,  water and hazardous waste permitting and counseling,  and transactional matters. Former environmental attorney with the Office of General Counsel,  General Motors Corporation. George Mason College of the University of Virginia,  B.S.,  with distinction,  biology,  M.S.,  biology; Catholic University of America,  J.D.,  1985. Admitted in Michigan and Florida.<BR>
<BR>
