<HEAD>
<TITLE>Howrey  & Simon
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Environmental</H2>
<H3>Howrey  & Simon
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington:</B> 1299 Pennsylvania Avenue,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20004<BR>
Tel 202-783-0800  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-383-6610<BR>
<B>Los Angeles:</B> 550 South Hope Street,  Suite 1400,  Los Angeles,  CA 90071<BR>
Tel 213-892-1800  <B>*</B>  Fax 213-892-2300<BR>
<BR>
300 lawyers  <B>*</B>  50 lawyers concentrating in environmental counseling, <BR>
negotiation litigation,  and insurance coverage<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/howrey.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/howrey.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/howrey.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/howrey.html"> Product Liability</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/howrey.html"> White Collar Crime</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>F</B>ounded in 1956,  Howrey  & Simon has a national and international practice,  with offices in Washington,  D.C. and Los Angeles. The firm has an emphasis on litigation and government regulation. Our work is supported by Capital Economics,  Capital Accounting,  and Capital Environmental,  affiliates with more than 30 economists,  financial analysts,  and environmental specialists.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Environmental Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>Howrey  & Simon provides its clients with the full range of legal services required to deal with the complex world that environmental laws have created. Our environmental practice group focuses on applying creative approaches to comprehensive management of environmental matters and compliance with government requirements. The practice group brings to bear its experience and expertise in negotiations,  alternate dispute resolutions,  and litigation in representing its clients before the EPA and state agencies,  and in private party disputes. We also defend companies in toxic tort actions,  pursue recoveries from insurance carriers,  develop and implement ongoing environmental assessment programs,  and perform environmental due diligence investigations and contract negotiations for corporate transactions.<BR><BR><LI><B>David B. Graham</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-6737)</I> Chair of the Environmental Practice Group in Washington,  D.C. Because of his extensive experience in the field of environmental law,  Mr. Graham is often called upon to represent companies facing significant challenges from the EPA or state environmental agencies,  as in the cases of a large petroleum company he is representing with respect to an underground petroleum release,  and a large chemical company alleged to be the largest generator at a Superfund site in Rhode Island. Mr. Graham's practice has focused primarily on CERCLA,  RCRA,  and the Oil Pollution Act. He is a member of the Council of the ABA Section on Natural Resources,  Energy and Environmental Law,  and chair of the Solid  & Hazardous Waste Committee.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>David A. Giannotti</B> (<I>Los Angeles; 213-892-7910)</I> Chair of the Environmental Practice Group in Los Angeles. Mr. Giannotti has more than 20 years of extensive environmental law experience,  covering air,  water,  toxic substances,  Superfund,  and hazardous waste issues ranging from compliance counseling to litigation. He also has extensive experience in due diligence investigations as well as developing and implementing environmental auditing programs for clients. He has represented the OII Steering Committee in a wide range of negotiations and litigation,  including the successful negotiation of the two largest partial consent decrees in the Superfund program.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>William M. Bumpers</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-7160)</I> Mr. Bumpers concentrates on Clean Air Act compliance and litigation. Mr. Bumpers represents a large number of electric utilities on CAA compliance,  regulatory and litigation matters. He also represents a variety of other industrial clients on CAA matters involving hazardous air pollutants,  nonattainment,  PSD,  permitting and other compliance issues. He serves as a member of the New Source Review Reform Subcommittee of the EPA's Clean Air Act Advisory Committee<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Steven L. Leifer</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-6517)</I> Mr. Leifer handles a broad array of environmental issues,  with emphasis on hazardous waste matters. Before entering private practice,  Mr. Leifer worked for 11 years with the EPA,  where he held a number of staff and management positions in various environmental programs. Serving as director of the Hazardous Waste Enforcement Division,  he directed policy development and litigation support activities under RCRA and Superfund.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Christopher H. Marraro</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-6749)</I> Mr. Marraro represents members of the industrial community in a broad range of environmental issues relating to toxic chemicals and hazardous waste. He has extensive experience with New Jersey's ECRA statute,  and with RCRA and CERCLA. He also has extensive experience with hazardous waste management at petroleum refineries and petrochemical facilities. He is currently representing a major recycler alleged to be an incinerator violating RCRA land ban requirements in a precedent-setting case in Louisiana. In addition,  Mr. Marraro has successfully represented clients in difficult private-party cost-recovery actions under CERCLA and state law.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Richard E. Wallace,  Jr.</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-6752)</I> Mr. Wallace,  an environmental litigator,  has successfully defended a major petroleum company in multiple personal injury and property damage suits in federal and state courts involving one of the country's largest underground oil spills. Mr. Wallace has also prosecuted and defended private cost-recovery cases under CERCLA,  RCRA,  and state statutes. He has represented industry in appellate challenges of environmental regulations,  and he has litigated environmental insurance coverage claims.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Elizabeth M. Weaver</B> (<I>Los Angeles; 213-892-7916)</I> Ms. Weaver's practice has involved a wide range of environmental issues and has focused in recent years on matters arising under CERCLA and other environmental cleanup statutes. In addition,  she has broad experience advising clients regarding compliance with RCRA and the Clean Water and Clean Air Acts. Ms. Weaver's practice is evenly divided between client counseling and environmental litigation. She represented the Hardage Steering Committee on claims for cost reimbursement against the government and other waste generators at the Hardage site.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Gordon Davidson</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-7446)</I> Mr. Davidson,  who is not an attorney,  is president of Capital Environmental,  a consulting affiliate of Howrey  & Simon. As the director of the Office of Federal Facilities Enforcement for EPA until 1993,  he developed and directed implementation of national policy for compliance and enforcement at federal facilities under all environmental laws. Mr. Davidson also coordinated strategic efforts on accelerated cleanup,  innovative technology development,  pollution prevention,  multi-media compliance and enforcement,  and issues specific to the Departments of Defense and Energy.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Ira R. Feldman</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-7037)</I> Mr. Feldman,  vice-president of Capital Environmental,  provides an interdisciplinary blend of legal,  policy and technical expertise. He has practiced environmental law for ten years,  initially in private practice,  and most recently serving as special counsel in the Office of Compliance at the EPA. Mr. Feldman provides advice on compliance,  benchmarking,  and `excellence' activities,  and he has represented the U.S. in the ISO 14000 international voluntary standard-setting arena.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Insurance Coverage Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>Howrey  & Simon has a substantial insurance coverage practice representing commercial policyholders in coverage litigation arising out of toxic tort suits,  environmental contamination,  and product liability claims. These matters involve claims under comprehensive general liability policies (CGL); environmental impairment liability policies (EIL); first-party property policies; directors and officers liability policies (D &O); and errors and omissions policies (E &O). We have established important precedent concerning coverage for a variety of environmental contamination and toxic tort claims.<BR><P>In conjunction with due diligence assessments of the policyholder's ability to recover insurance proceeds,  we perform historical insurance audits,  reconstruct missing policies and perform risk analysis utilizing software developed by our affiliate,  Capital Economics,  in order to develop the best litigation and settlement strategies. Our work is also supported by Capital Environmental,  our affiliate,  which provides environmental management consulting services.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Sherry W. Gilbert</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-6732)</I> Ms. Gilbert has extensive experience in litigating,  on behalf of corporations,  disputes with insurance companies regarding coverage for asbestos,  pharmaceutical,  environmental,  medical services,  and other large-scale tort claims. These actions,  in federal and state courts throughout the country,  have involved a variety of procedural and substantive issues,  often of first impression.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Philip H. Hecht</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-6724)</I> Mr. Hecht has been lead counsel in coverage litigation involving environmental contamination at various sites around the country,  and has played a leading role in obtaining coverage for asbestos bodily injury and property damage claims on behalf of several Fortune 500 policyholders. Mr. Hecht also has secured insurance coverage for a bank faced with potential lender liability under Superfund.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>John E. Heintz</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-6711)</I> Mr. Heintz leads the firm's environmental and toxic tort insurance coverage practice. He obtained a landmark decision favorable to policyholders in a Minnesota Supreme Court case concerning coverage for Superfund liabilities. Mr. Heintz has also played a leading role in obtaining coverage for asbestos bodily injury and building claims on behalf of a major policyholder in <I>In Re Asbestos Insurance Coverage Cases</I>,  a 60-party proceeding now on appeal in California.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Michael J. Hurley</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-7186)</I> Mr. Hurley has represented several major utility companies in insurance coverage cases involving liabilities arising out of the operation of former manufactured gas plants. He has developed a unique expertise litigating against Lloyd's of London and London Market insurance companies. Mr. Hurley previously served as a captain in the Army Judge Advocate General's Corps,  prosecuting more than 100 criminal court-martial cases and representing the United States on appeal in 120 cases.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Lisa I. Latorre</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-6712</I>) Ms. Latorre has significant experience handling the case management,  site-specific discovery,  and pretrial preparation aspects of major environmental coverage cases. She has authored several papers and lectured on a variety of insurance coverage topics.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Ezra C. Levine</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-7055)</I> Mr. Levine has represented potentially responsible parties in Superfund litigation,  negotiated settlements of air emission violations,  and litigated cases involving groundwater contamination at municipal landfill sites. In addition,  he has been active in coverage litigation involving former manufactured gas plant facilities. Previously,  Mr. Levine was the assistant general counsel for interpretations and rulings at the United States Department of Energy and its predecessors.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Harold D. Murry,  Jr.</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-6532)</I> Mr. Murry has been litigating insurance coverage disputes and providing counsel to major companies and corporations on insurance-related issues for 15 years. He has served as lead counsel in numerous cases for major corporations seeking insurance coverage for asbestos,  pharmaceutical,  environmental,  and other business-related claims. These cases involve litigation in both state and federal courts throughout the country as well as in arbitrations and proceedings in bankruptcy court.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Charles H. Samel</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-7226)</I> Mr. Samel has extensive experience as a civil litigator in matters involving breach of contract and other commercial disputes,  arbitration,  environmental law,  insurance coverage,  and construction claims. He represents the firm's corporate clients in both environmental and insurance coverage lawsuits involving,  for example,  coverage for cleanup of former manufactured gas plant facilities and private cost recovery actions under Superfund.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Robert H. Shulman</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-7419)</I> Mr. Shulman has had extensive experience in litigating,  on behalf of corporations,  disputes with insurance companies regarding coverage for environmental,  pesticide-related agricultural,  asbestos,  and other large-scale tort claims. He also has litigated and provided general counseling with respect to insurance coverage issues under directors and officers liability policies and indemnity-related commercial litigation matters.<BR>
<BR>


</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
