<TITLE>Kilpatrick  & Cody
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Environmental</H2>
<H3>Kilpatrick  & Cody
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Atlanta:</B> Suite 2800,  1100 Peachtree Street NE,  Atlanta,  GA 30309<BR>
Tel 404-815-6500  <B>*</B>  Fax 404-815-6555<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> Suite 800,  700 13th Street N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20005<BR>
Tel 202-508-5800  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-508-5858  <B>*</B>  E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:info">info</A> @kiLCody.com<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Augusta (Georgia),  London,  Brussels<BR>
<BR>
218 lawyers  <B>*</B>  20 lawyers in environmental regulation and litigation<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/kilpatrick.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/kilpatrick.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/kilpatrick.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="..//kilpatrick.html"> International Arbitration</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>K</B>ilpatrick  & Cody is a major international law firm with over 200 professionals serving clients on legal,  business,  and policy matters around the world from offices in the United States and Europe and through affiliations in Latin America and Asia.
<P><BR><P>The firm's Environmental and Natural Resources Practice Group assists public and private sector clients in avoiding environmental liability and regulatory conflicts through preventive counseling and management of environmental permit processes. Because the Practice Group is situated within a large general practice firm,  it can efficiently involve attorneys with expertise in other areas when client needs extend beyond environmental matters. The Group represents clients in enforcement actions (civil and criminal),  environmental litigation,  and policy and regulatory matters before state and federal courts and agencies and the United States Congress. Clients include firms involved in textiles,  chemical manufacturing,  metal casting,  forest products,  transportation engineering,  hazardous waste management,  electronics,  residential and commercial development,  food and beverages,  and state and local governments.<BR><P>The Group includes professionals trained in economics,  engineering,  chemistry,  biology,  risk assessment,  and the physical sciences in addition to law,  thus blending legal and technical experience necessary to provide a comprehensive approach to a broad range of domestic and international matters including the following:<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>U.S. Environmental Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P><UL><BR><BR>
<BR><P><LI> Resolution of regulatory problems through administrative and judicial proceedings arising from federal and state environmental and health laws,  including the Clean Air Act,  the Clean Water Act,  the Pesticide Act (FIFRA),  the Occupational Health and Safety Act (OSHA),  the Food and Drug Act (FFDCA),  the Toxic Substances Control Act (TSCA),  Superfund (CERCLA and SARA),  and the Hazardous and Solid Waste Act (HSWA or RCRA).<BR><P><LI> Representation of individual parties and steering committees responsible for hazardous substances sites under the Comprehensive Environmental Response,  Compensation and Liability Act (CERCLA/Superfund).<BR>
<BR><P><LI> Conduct of environmental due diligence investigations necessary for business acquisitions and mergers; purchase,  sale and leasing of real property; and public and private debt financing.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> Resolution of controversies arising from natural resource exploitation,  including fisheries,  timber management,  endangered species,  and wetlands permitting.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> Representation of policyholders in negotiations and litigation to obtain insurance coverage for environmental damages.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</UL><BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>International Environmental Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P><BR><BR>
Members of the firm have provided legal and technical assistance to governments,  private enterprises,  and international financial and political institutions for projects in Latin America and the Caribbean,  Europe,  Asia,  and the Middle East. Recent projects include:<BR><P><UL><LI> Performing environmental due diligence for the acquisition of natural resources or industrial facilities in Brazil,  Costa Rica,  the Dominican Republic,  the European Union,  Honduras,  Mexico,  and the Philippines.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> Drafting legislation to implement the 1973 Marine Pollution Convention for English-speaking countries of the Wider Caribbean Region.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> Submitting the first NAFTA Petition For Investigation to the North American Commission for Environmental Cooperation in Montreal.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> Counseling on European Union pesticide regulations and negotiating data compensation agreements.<BR>
<BR>
<BR></UL>
<LI><B>Vance Hughes </B>(<I>Washington,  D.C.; 202-508-5830</I>) manages the Practice Group in Washington. He has almost 25 years of environmental experience both in senior government positions (Department of Justice and EPA) and in private practice,  and currently represents clients in a range of matters including permitting,  enforcement,  and administrative proceedings. He is active in international environmental matters in Latin America and Europe,  and is a Trustee of the Center for International Environmental Law.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Rick Horder</B> (<I>Atlanta; 404-815-6538</I>) manages the Practice Group in Atlanta. Mr. Horder has also held senior positions in government and in the private sector,  having served as an assistant U.S. attorney and as associate general counsel for Georgia-Pacific in charge of environmental compliance and litigation. His current practice covers all areas of environmental law.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR><BR>


</UL></BODY>
