<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Environmental</H2>
<H3>Lowenstein,  Sandler,  Kohl,  Fisher  & Boylan,  P.A.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<BR>
<B>Roseland:</B> 65 Livingston Avenue,  Roseland,  NJ 07068<BR>
Tel 201-992-8700  <B>*</B>  Fax 201-992-5820<BR>
<B>Other office:</B> Somerville (New Jersey)<BR>
<BR>
124 lawyers  <B>*</B>  22 lawyers practicing in environmental and energy law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/lowenstein.html"> Corporate Securities</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/lowenstein.html"> White Collar Crime</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P><BR>

<P><B>L</B>owenstein Sandler provides full legal service to its corporate business clients. Areas of practice include corporate,  litigation,  environmental,  and white collar criminal defense.
<P><BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Environmental Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>The environmental department is composed of 19 attorneys who devote their full time to the practice of environmental law and litigation and approximately 25 additional attorneys who offer substantial support to the environmental practice,  primarily for litigation support in the areas of environmental insurance coverage and environmental crime.<BR>

<P><BR><BR>
<P>The environmental department of the firm began in 1974 defending some early landmark litigation in New Jersey,  and some of the first federal hazardous waste cases in the country. The department serves clients in two distinct areas: <BR><BR><UL><LI>It has an active and sophisticated regulatory practice which advises major and smaller corporations with respect to environmental matters. The practice covers all aspects of environmental regulation,  e.g.,  air,  water,  solid and hazardous waste,  permitting,  compliance reviews,  environmental audits,  and ECRA.<BR><BR><LI>It also maintains an active environmental litigation section which may be divided into four distinct areas: civil and criminal enforcement; environmental insurance litigation; toxic tort cases; and miscellaneous environmental suits such as defense of citizen's enforcement actions,  hazardous waste facility siting litigation,  private CERCLA actions,  and `major project' environmental litigation.<BR><BR></UL><P>Representative clients include AlliedSignal Inc.; American Standard Inc.; Ciba-Geigy Ltd.; CPC International; E.I. du Pont de Nemours  & Co.; General Electric Company; General Instrument Corporation; The Marmon Group,  Inc.; Rutgers,  The State University; SmithKline Beecham Corporation; and Union Carbide Corp.<BR>
</UL><BR>

<P><BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Energy Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>The firm's energy practice is a multidisciplinary group with attorneys drawn from several departments throughout the firm. The practice is focused on assisting those companies involved in the development and operation of energy projects including fossil fuel-fired power plants and cogeneration facilities,  both QF and non-QF. The group serves clients in preparing and reviewing environmental due diligence opinions; preparing planning and zoning board applications; reviewing and preparing air,  water,  sewer,  stream encroachment,  coastal and wetland permits; drafting power purchase and interconnection agreements; and advising on financing and tax implications of their energy projects.<BR>
<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Michael L. Rodburg</B> Chairman of the firm's environmental department,  Mr. Rodburg has extensive experience in all phases of counseling and trial work. He served as trial counsel in landmark litigation (<I>New Jersey </I>v.<I> Ventron</I>) involving liability for a hazardous site. His practice concentrates in hazardous waste and substances litigation and acquisition counseling. Massachusetts Institute of Technology,  S.B.,  1968; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1971; editor,  <I>Harvard Law Review</I>,  1969-1971. Admitted in New Jersey,  U.S. District Court for the District of New Jersey,  and U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael Dore</B> Mr. Dore has extensive experience in complex toxic tort and hazardous substance litigation,  defense,  and insurance. He is an author of the legal source book <I>Law of Toxic Torts: Litigation,  Defense,  Insurance</I> (Clark Boardman Co. Ltd.,  1987). Amherst College,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1972; Rutgers University School of Law,  J.D.,  1975; editor,  <I>Rutgers Law Review</I>. Admitted in New Jersey,  1980; New York,  1976; and Pennsylvania,  1975.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James Stewart</B> Mr. Stewart's practice concentrates primarily in the areas of environmental litigation and class action toxic tort matters. His experience includes the impact of environmental litigation on mergers and acquisitions. Language: Chinese. Seton Hall University,  B.A.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1976; New York University School of Law,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1981. Admitted in New Jersey,  1981; and New York,  1982.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert D. Chesler</B> Mr. Chesler has extensive experience in the prosecution and management of environmental insurance coverage litigation. Rutgers University,  B.A.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1973; Phi Beta Kappa; Princeton University,  M.A.,  1975,  Ph.D.,  1979; Fulbright Fellow; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1982. Admitted in New Jersey,  New York,  U.S. District Court for the District of New Jersey,  and U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard F. Ricci</B> Mr. Ricci provides hazardous waste litigation and counseling to clients. He has broad experience in complex negotiations and litigation including multiparty Superfund and toxic tort litigation. Duquesne University,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1979; University of Notre Dame School of Law,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1982. Admitted in Michigan and New Jersey.<BR>



