<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>M</B>ayer,  Brown  & Platt has had a substantial environmental practice since the 1960s. Our practice group partners,  who have on average over 20 years' experience in environmental law,  assist clients in all kinds of environmental matters,  from permits to due diligence in business transactions to complex trials.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Environmental Practice Group</H3></CENTER>

<P>The Environmental Practice Group is experienced in all phases of administrative proceedings,  negotiating with federal,  state,  and local agencies,  participating in rulemakings,  and assisting in permits,  air and water regulatory challenges,  and enforcement matters. We have handled every kind of environmental case,  including enforcement actions,  CERCLA cost recovery actions,  insurance coverage disputes,  toxic tort litigation,  oil spill litigation,  natural resource damages,  and regulatory matters. We assist clients with legislative solutions to environmental problems at the federal,  state,  and local levels.<BR><P>Our environmental lawyers oversee environmental due diligence investigations in business transactions in the United States and the European Union and in Mexico in conjunction with our Mexico City affiliated firm,  J &#242;uregui,  Navarrete,   Nader y Rojas,  S.C. We advise several clients on issues related to wetlands regulations. We routinely advise clients throughout the United States on environmental compliance questions.<BR>
<BR><P>Mayer,  Brown  & Platt's environmental clients represent a wide variety of industries. Chemical and oil industry clients include NaLCo,  Sherex,  Stepan,  Kerr-McGee,  Quantum,  Clark,  and Elf Aquitaine. A broad cross-section of companies in many fields which look to the firm for environmental representation includes Cargill,  Inc.,  CPC,  Caterpillar,  General Electric,  Microdot,  VuLCan Materials,  WMX,  and Williams Pipeline. In conjunction with our real estate and financial practice lawyers,  we advise clients such as LaSalle Partners,  JMB Realty,  National Westminster Bank pLC,  Chemical Bank,  Bank of Montreal,  Security Capital,  and Sanwa Bank.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Percy L. Angelo</B> (<I>Chicago; 312-701-7330</I>) Percy served with the Illinois Environmental Protection Agency as chief of air pollution enforcement,  and has handled all kinds of environmental litigation and administrative proceedings. She is chairman of the Environmental Law Committee of the ABA Public Utility Law Section. Smith College,  B.A.,  1967; Stanford Law School,  J.D.,  1970; articles editor,  law review. Admitted in Illinois.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John C. Berghoff,  Jr.</B> (<I>Chicago; 312-701-7315</I>) John has tried a broad range of environmental cases in the past 25 years,  beginning with the phosphate detergent cases in the early 1970s. Since then he has handled such environmental cases as <I>Ethyl </I>v.<I> EPA</I> (removal of lead in gasoline),  <I>Brown </I>v.<I> Kerr McGee</I> (radioactive exposure) and the <I>Mega Borg</I> oil tanker spill. Northwestern University,  B.A.,  1963,  J.D.,  1966; Wigmore Key. Admitted in Illinois.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Russell R. Eggert</B> (<I>Chicago; 312-701-7350</I>) Russ taught environmental law in 1973-1974,  and was chief of the environmental division of the Illinois Attorney General's office and legal counsel to the Illinois Attorney General before joining MB &P. University of Illinois,  A.B.,  1970,  J.D.,  1973. Admitted in Illinois.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James W. Gladden,  Jr.</B> (<I>Chicago; 312-701-7253</I>) Jim became involved in environmental matters in the late 1960s and chaired one of the first Superfund steering committees,  setting the initial guidelines for private site cleanups. DePauw University,  B.A.,  1961; Harvard Law School,  LL.B,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1964. Admitted in Illinois.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Lloyd S. Guerci</B> (<I>Washington; 202-778-0637</I>) Lloyd served in senior positions at the U.S. Department of Justice and U.S. Environmental Protection Agency,  including director of CERCLA and RCRA enforcement. He has co-authored the ABA Section of Natural Resources,  Energy,  and Environmental Law's year-end review of hazardous waste law developments for the last 13 years. Lehigh University,  B.S.,  1969; Rutgers Law School,  J.D.,  highest honors,  1973; law review. Admitted in the District of Columbia and New Jersey.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kathleen Hennessey</B> (<I>Chicago; 312-701-7627</I>) Kathleen handled environmental litigation while she served in a senior position with the City of Chicago. She has concentrated in environmental law since joining Mayer,  Brown  & Platt in 1989. University of Michigan,  A.B.,  with honors,  1981; University of Chicago Law School,  J.D.,  1985. Admitted in Illinois.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John P. Schmitz</B> (<I>Washington; 202-778-0645</I>) John served as deputy counsel to the President,  1989-1993,  and deputy counsel to the Vice-President,  1985-1989. He helped develop the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990,  and worked on a variety of international environmental projects. Georgetown University,  B.A.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1976,  Phi Beta Kappa; California Institute of Technology,  M.S.,  1987; Stanford Law School,  J.D.,  1981; law review. Admitted in District of Columbia.<BR>
