<B>Boston:</B> 250 Summer Street,  Boston,  MA 02210<BR>
Tel 617-439-7500  <B>*</B>  Fax 617-439-7590<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Raynham,  Springfield,  Worcester,  and Yarmouth Port (Massachusetts);<BR>
New York; San Francisco; Grand Rapids and Southfield (Michigan);<BR>
Providence; Hartford; London<BR>
<BR>
180 lawyers  <B>*</B>  14 environmental lawyers<BR>
<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profile in the following other directory:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/morrison,  mahoney.html"> Product Liability</A>
</UL>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Environmental Defense Practice Group</H3></CENTER>

<P><B>T</B>he Environmental Defense Practice Group has extensive experience representing private parties facing potential liability to state and federal governments for costs associated with the investigation and remediation of federal Superfund sites and damages to natural resources. It actively represents both major and <I>de minimis</I> parties involved in Superfund sites throughout New England.
<P>The Environmental Defense Practice Group also represents parties in private actions involving the recovery of cleanup costs and claims for property damage and personal injury under state and federal law arising from the release or threatened release of hazardous materials and oil. The Group also defends personal injury claims arising from exposure to toxic substances in the workplace.The Group also provides advice to businesses outside of the context of litigation on issues of compliance with federal,  state,  and local statutes and regulations relating to underground storage tanks; the treatment,  storage,  and disposal of hazardous wastes; and compliance with the Massachusetts Contingency Plan and the Massachusetts Wetlands Protection Act. It additionally counsels commercial lenders on risks posed to lenders under state and federal environmental statutes.<BR>
Representative clients include Boston Edison Company,  The Coleman Company,  Inc.,  S.C. Johnson  & Sons,  Inc.,  B.F. Goodrich,  Proctor  & Gamble,  Petroleum Heat  & Power Company,  Brown  & Sharpe Manufacturing Company,  Data General Corporation,  Chrysler Corporation,  Kenyon Oil Company,  and High Voltage Engineering Corporation.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Environmental Coverage Practice Group</H3></CENTER>

<P>Morrison,  Mahoney  & Miller is involved in diverse aspects of the representation of business clients and individuals who face environmental liabilities,  representing liability and property insurers as well as domestic and foreign reinsurers in coverage disputes involving pollution,  asbestos,  medical devices and implants,  Agent Orange,  DES,  fire retardant plywood,  hearing loss,  lead paint,  repetitive stress,  UFFI,  and other `environmental' liabilities. These representations encompass (1) policy and treaty drafting,  (2) the preparation of coverage opinions,  (3) resolution of claims through coverage litigation and/or alternative dispute resolution,  and (4) reinsurance arbitrations.
<P>The firm,  a member of the American Law Firm Association (ALFA),  a national law firm network,  represents a number of insurers on a direct or coordinating basis in cases throughout the United States. We have successfully argued landmark cases in these areas before several state supreme courts as well as the U.S. Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit.Representative clients include Continental Insurance Company,  TIG Insurance Company,  and Sentry Insurance Company.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Alan G. Miller</B> Mr. Miller chairs the firm's reinsurance practice group as well as being actively involved in other practice areas such as environmental,  accident and health,  regulatory,  and insurance coverage. Member of the Federation of Insurance and Corporate Counsel. University of Illinois,  A.B.,  1952; Harvard University,  J.D.,  1955.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Mark S. Granger</B> Mr. Granger has served as defense counsel on numerous Superfund sites and as liaison counsel in federal court litigation on Superfund. Extensive trial experience in defending complex litigation including toxic tort,  environmental claims,  lead paint,  flammable liquids,  and product liability. Regularly advises clients on environmental matters. Frequent presenter in symposia on environmental law. Dickinson College,  B.A.,  1971; Boston University School of Law,  J.D.,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael F. Aylward</B> Mr. Aylward chairs the firm's environmental coverage practice group. Over the past ten years,  he has represented liability insurers in numerous claims,  suits,  and appeals throughout the United States,  and serves as regional counsel to several insurers on pollution claims. He is a frequent speaker on environmental and toxic tort coverage issues. Dartmouth College,  B.A.,  1976; Boston College,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Thomas G. Fiore</B> Mr. Fiore's practice focuses on representing private parties at state and federal Superfund sites. Prior to joining Morrison,  Mahoney  & Miller,  Mr. Fiore was an attorney with the EPA's Office of Enforcement  & Compliance Monitoring in Washington,  D.C.,  where he was involved in enforcement actions brought by the EPA under the Comprehensive Environmental Response,  Compensation,  and Liability Act (CERCLA) and the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act (RCRA). Wesleyan University,  B.A.,  1979; Northeastern University,  J.D.,  1984.<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
