<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/paul.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/paul.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/paul.html"> Corporate Securities</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/paul.html"> ERISA</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/paul.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
   <LI><A HREF="..//paul.html"> International Arbitration</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/paul.html"> Product Liability</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/paul.html"> Workout</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>T</B>he Environmental Practice Group counsels our financial,  industrial,  and natural resources clients in corporate transactions,  regulatory disputes,  and litigations arising under federal and state environmental laws.
<P><BR><P>In the corporate and financing areas,  we advise buyers,  sellers,  lenders,  borrowers,  investors,  issuers of securities,  and investment bankers on the nature and extent of environmental risks of contemplated business transactions in the steel,  paper products,  automotive,  rubber,  telecommunications,  chemical,  coal,  and manufacturing industries. Because of the interdisciplinary nature of environmental law,  the group works closely with the firm's other departments to address environmental issues in credit arrangements,  to protect lenders from potential liability under environmental laws,  and to deal with environmental issues in corporate reorganizations and in bankruptcy court litigations.<BR><P>Our attorneys have a broad range of environmental litigation experience,  both civil and criminal. We have defended industrial clients in multiparty suits and purported class actions based on allegations of air and groundwater contamination and occupational exposure to toxic substances. We routinely represent potentially responsible parties in administrative and litigation proceedings under the Comprehensive Environmental Response,  Compensation,  and Liability Act (CERCLA) and the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act (RCRA),  as well as analogous state statutes. We represent clients in both the prosecution and defense of suits to allocate responsibility for expenditures to clean up past contamination under environmental indemnity provisions of contracts,  CERCLA,  and the common law.<BR>
<BR><P>In the areas of land use planning and natural resource commitment,  the Group has extensive experience under the National Environmental Policy Act,  the National Historic Preservation Act,  and similar state statutes,  as well as experience under local land use planning ordinances. In the regulatory area,  we are experienced in representing industrial and governmental entities before the EPA and state environmental authorities in matters relating to the nation's air,  water,  and hazardous wastes programs.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Gaines Gwathmey III</B> Mr. Gwathmey's practice has been devoted almost entirely to environmental matters,  both civil and criminal,  for over 15 years. Mr. Gwathmey's principal areas of concentration have been the CERCLA,  RCRA,  air,  and water programs. He has represented PRP groups,  both small and large,  in proceedings brought by federal and state environmental authorities. Mr. Gwathmey has as well acted as lead counsel in significant NEPA,  SEQRA,  cost recovery,  and land use matters. Assistant U.S. attorney,  Southern District of New York and chief,  Environmental Protection Unit,  1977-1982. Harvard University,  A.B.,  1969; Georgetown University,  LL.B.,  1973; editor,  <I>Georgetown Law Journal</I>,  1972-1973. Admitted in New York,  1974; the District of Columbia,  1975; U.S. District Courts for the Southern,  Eastern,  and Northern Districts of New York,  1975; U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit,  1978; and New Jersey,  1986.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Cameron Clark</B> Mr. Clark's practice includes both civil and criminal environmental litigation. He has served as lead defense counsel in multiparty toxic tort litigation and has significant jury trial experience in the defense of suits arising out of groundwater contamination. Bigelow Teaching Fellow,  University of Chicago Law School,  1969-1970. University of Minnesota,  J.D.,  1969. Admitted in New York,  1969; U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit,  1970; U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York,  1971; U.S. Supreme Court,  1978; U.S. Court of Customs and Patent Appeals,  1978; U.S. Court of International Trade,  1978; U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of New York,  1978; <I>conseil juridique</I>,  France,  1980; and the District of Columbia,  1982.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jane L. Stewart</B> Ms. Stewart's areas of expertise include RCRA,  the Clean Air Act,  and international environmental issues. Member,  New York State Superfund Management Board,  1986- ; Nongovernmental Organization Representative to U.S. Delegation to United Nations Environmental Programme (UNEP),  1988-1989; New York State Hazardous Waste Treatment Facilities Task Force,  1983-1985. Litigating attorney,  1981-1990; member,  Management Committee,  1987-1990; Natural Resources Defense Council,  Inc. Brown University,  A.B.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1976; New York University School of Law,  J.D.,  1979; Root-Tilden Scholar; editor-in-chief,  <I>New York University Review of Law and Social Change</I>,  1979.<BR>
