<HEAD>
<TITLE>Ross  & Hardies
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Environmental</H2>
<H3>Ross  & Hardies
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Chicago:</B> 150 North Michigan Avenue,  Chicago,  IL 60601<BR>
Tel 312-558-1000  <B>*</B>  Fax 312-750-8600  <B>*</B>  E-Mail: JHarrin+aRoss%573-0397@mcimail.com<BR>
<B>New York:</B> 65 East 55th Street,  New York,  NY 10022<BR>
Tel 212-421-5555  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-421-5682<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> 888 16th Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20006<BR>
Tel 202-296-8600  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-296-8791<BR>
<BR>
198 lawyer  <B>*</B>  13 lawyers in environmental practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/ross.html"> Corporate Securities</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/ross.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/ross.html"> Labor</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>R</B>oss  & Hardies,  a national business law firm founded in 1902,  has an established environmental practice grounded in thorough knowledge of environmental issues and laws,  longstanding experience in representation,  and sensitivity to clients' business goals and situations.
<P><BR><P>Two basic principles direct the Environmental Group of Ross  & Hardies. First,  Ross  & Hardies is client-oriented. It is the firm's responsibility to provide clients with the kind and amount of services they desire and to be responsive to their directions in terms of objectives,  deadlines,  reporting relationships,  and budget. Second,  Ross  & Hardies is solution-oriented. It is the firm's role to develop creative solutions to problems,  keep minor problems from becoming big ones,  and,  whenever possible,  prevent problems from occurring in the first place. While Ross  & Hardies is staffed for successful litigation,  the firm has found it is generally in the client's long-term best interest to seek early resolutions of issues and avoid protracted litigation. Attorneys' combined prior experience in government,  private practice,  and corporations help the Environmental Group to understand client needs as well as the business,  political,  and regulatory environment in which they operate. Ross  & Hardies develops solutions which are effective and cost-efficient without jeopardizing longstanding relationships with government agencies or the public.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>James T. Harrington</B> Mr. Harrington,  chairman of the Environmental Practice Group,  has been practicing law since 1969 in the fields of environmental law,  regulation,  and litigation. He has represented major industrial clients in both common law and regulatory litigation,  the development of state and federal regulations,  and the review of regulations,  permits,  and related requirements. He is a frequent speaker at state and national panels,  both before bar associations and industry trade groups. He clerked for two years in the U.S. District Court for the Northern District of Indiana. He holds undergraduate and law degrees from the University of Notre Dame.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Raymond T. Murphy</B> Mr. Murphy's background includes 17 years' experience as a corporate counsel. Prior to joining the firm he was assistant general counsel with Baxter Healthcare Corporation and oversaw that firm's environmental efforts. He began his career as a member of the General Motors legal staff in Detroit. He is on the Editorial Advisory Board of the <I>Environmental Law Reporter</I>,  former chairman of the Chicago Bar Association Environmental Law Committee,  and co-founder of the Environmental Auditing Roundtable. He received his Bachelor of Engineering degree from General Motors Institute,  his Master of Engineering degree from Cornell University,  and his law degree from Cleveland State University Law School.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Charles M. Chadd</B> Mr. Chadd has represented manufacturing companies in occupational safety and health and environmental regulatory matters for 20 years. His practice includes counsel to companies in litigation with government agencies,  as well as a broad range of problem-solving activities for clients in the environmental and OSHA areas. He speaks at conferences of trade associations,  business institutes,  corporations,  and continuing legal education organizations,  and regularly publishes articles in publications of the Bureau of National Affairs and the American and the Illinois Bar Associations. Prior to joining Ross  & Hardies,  he spent 25 years in private practice at Pope,  Ballard,  Shepard  & Fowle,  Ltd. He received a B.S. in Industrial Engineering from Illinois Institute of Technology and a law degree from Northwestern University.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
