<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shearman  & Sterling
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Environmental</H2>
<H3>Shearman  & Sterling
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>New York:</B> 153 East 53rd Street,  New York,  NY 10022<BR>
Tel 212-848-4000  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-848-5252<BR>
<B>Other offices: </B>Abu Dhabi,  Los Angeles,  Beijing,  Paris,  Budapest,  San Francisco,  Dusseldorf,  Taipei,  Frankfurt,  Tokyo,  Hong Kong,  Toronto,  London,  Washington,  D.C.<BR>
<BR>
525 lawyers  <B>*</B>  5 lawyers in the Environmental Practice Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>S</B>hearman  & Sterling,  founded in 1873,  has broad experience in all major areas of the law. For years,  Shearman  & Sterling has been an international leader in corporate law and securities,  banking,  finance,  mergers and acquisitions,  tax,  environmental law,  real estate,  country debt restructuring,  litigation,  arbitration,  antitrust,  and international trade.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Environmental Practice Group</H3></CENTER>

<P>The makeup and experience of our Environmental Practice Group have put us in a strong position to respond to the concerns of industry and the financial community arising from environmental matters,  domestic and international. The practice of the group is diverse and extends to a broad range of environmental issues in corporate transactions,  regulatory matters,  government affairs,  and litigation proceedings.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Experience and Clients</H3></CENTER>

<P>In the corporate context,  the major strengths of our Environmental Practice Group are: (1) advising buyers and sellers in acquisitions and divestitures where environmental risks must be identified and allocated; (2) representing lenders in financings and workouts where exposure to environmental costs and liabilities must be assessed,  quantified,  and integrated into the structure and price of the credit; and (3) representing parties in contested matters,  litigated proceedings,  and enforcement proceedings. Representative clients in these aspects of our work include American Cyanamid,  British Steel,  Chemical Bank,  Citibank,  Deere  & Co.,  Fort Howard Corp.,  Mennen,  Morgan Stanley,  Seagram,  and Viacom.<BR><P>On the regulatory front,  the focus of the Group's work has been (1) resolving environmental compliance,  permitting,  and enforcement issues (civil and criminal) for major industrial operators; and (2) designing,  negotiating,  and implementing large-scale site characterization and remediation programs under a variety of regulatory regimes in various locations around the United States. Major petroleum,  chemical,  and manufacturing businesses have been our clients in these areas.<BR>
<BR><P>With respect to Government affairs,  the Group has been chief legal advisor to the Government of Kuwait in the preparation of claims for environmental damages resulting from the Gulf War. It advised the Government of Mexico on environmental aspects of NAFTA,  and it currently is environmental counsel to the Government of Kazakhstan in the development of oil reserves in the Caspian Sea.<BR>
<BR><P>The Group also has extensive experience in designing and supervising environmental assessments performed by technical consultants for both transactional and regulatory purposes.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Partners</H3></CENTER>

<BR><UL><LI><B>Margaret Murphy</B> (<I>New York; 212-848-4344</I>) From 1976-1990 Ms. Murphy was with the firm of White  & Case,  where she became a partner in 1984. She developed White  & Case's environmental practice before joining the Shearman  & Sterling Environmental Practice Group in August 1990. She has a depth of experience in environmental law and has devoted substantial time to environmental issues as they affect the domestic and international financial and investor communities. Ms. Murphy heads our Environmental Practice Group. New York University School of Law,  J.D.,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Daniel L. Rabinowitz</B> (<I>New York; 212-848-4383</I>) From 1975-1977 Mr. Rabinowitz served as law clerk to Judge Herbert J. Stern of the U.S. District Court for the District of New Jersey. From 1978-1981 he served as an assistant U.S. attorney for the District of New Jersey. Since entering private practice in 1981,  Mr. Rabinowitz has handled all aspects of environmental law and has developed a particular concentration in site remediation and enforcement matters. He has served as a visiting lecturer at Yale Law School. Yale Law School,  J.D.,  1975.<BR></UL>


</UL></BODY>
