<TITLE>Spriggs  & Hollingsworth
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Environmental</H2>
<H3>Spriggs  & Hollingsworth
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington:</B> 1350 I Street,  N.W.,  Ninth Floor,  Washington,  DC 20005<BR>
Tel 202-898-5800  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-682-1639<BR>
<BR>
35 lawyers  <B>*</B>  21 lawyers in environmental regulation and litigation and toxic tort litigation<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/spriggs.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/spriggs.html"> Product Liability</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/spriggs.html"> White Collar Crime</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>T</B>he firm represents numerous corporations in civil,  criminal,  and administrative matters involving alleged contamination of ground and surface waters,  land,  and air. We represent manufacturers and successor corporations in proceedings involving Superfund/CERCLA,  RCRA,  and other statutes related to hazardous substances. We regularly negotiate on behalf of individual clients and on behalf of committees of potentially responsible parties with state and federal agencies concerning permits,  site investigations,  site remediations,  and similar issues arising under federal and state statutes affecting disposal of hazardous wastes. We have litigated claims arising from sites across the country,  and have obtained summary judgments,  <I>de minimis</I> settlements,  and innovative negotiated remediation plans for our clients. We have also filed amicus briefs on behalf of trade associations and manufacturers' groups interested in the development of environmental law. We regularly conduct on-site environmental audits,  both at individual plants and as part of nationwide programs. We also conduct property audits to protect our clients against hidden or unforeseen environmental liabilities in connection with the sale and purchase of property and other assets.
<P><BR><P>The firm represents manufacturers and other corporations in toxic tort and product liability litigation involving both personal injury and property damage claims. We serve as national coordinating trial counsel for the defense of such cases where multiple litigation is involved. With the help of contacts from our national network of local counsel and experts,  we are able to introduce our clients' most sophisticated and technical defenses into all parts of the country. The firm defends individual lawsuits,  mass tort claims,  and class actions alleging product liability in connection with product design,  manufacture,  and warnings; chemical contamination; radiation contamination; and waste disposal. Because we are a litigation firm,  we handle cases from the earliest pre-trial and investigative stages through trial and through resolution on appeal. These cases involve asbestos-containing products,  hazardous wastes,  military hardware,  `sick buildings, ' chlorinated and other synthetic pesticides,  solvents,  radioactive materials,  herbicides,  petroleum byproducts,  feedstocks and derivatives,  and various other chemicals and chemical products.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Joe G. Hollingsworth</B> Emphasizes trial and appellate work in toxic tort,  toxic and pharmaceutical product liability,  and environmental law. As national trial counsel in the defense of myriad chemical and chemical product exposure claims,  he defends against allegations of toxic exposure and injury,  property damage,  groundwater contamination,  and toxic air emissions. Mr. Hollingsworth also represents a number of companies involved at major Superfund sites around the country.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Donald W. Fowler</B> Extensive experience in federal and administrative litigation in the areas of environmental law and toxic torts. His practice includes representation of companies in litigation and before the Environmental Protection Agency in matters arising under the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act and Superfund,  including private cost recovery actions. Mr. Fowler has extensive experience in designing and implementing compliance programs,  in conducting environmental audits and due diligence reviews,  and in negotiating environmental aspects of real estate and other corporate transactions.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Edward J. Beder,  Jr.</B> Has been extensively involved in complex,  multiparty litigation focusing on the defense of toxic tort personal injury and property damage suits as well as the prosecution of actions to maximize insurance coverage for clients confronted with such claims.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Bruce J. Berger</B> Practices in civil litigation and has extensive experience in toxic tort and environmental law. Mr. Berger also counsels clients on the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act,  Superfund,  and other environmental statutes.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Patrick R. Harkins</B> Practices primarily in the field of product liability and has extensive experience in the defense of asbestos-related claims. Mr. Harkins also has considerable experience in legislative and regulatory matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Katherine R. Latimer</B> Emphasizes multiple toxic exposure matters involving pesticides,  solvents,  and manufacturing-use chemical compounds. She is experienced in mass tort,  class action,  and multijurisdiction litigation,  and has served as national coordinating co-counsel in complex toxics matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Frank Leone,  Jr.</B> Has extensive experience in environmental litigation and counseling,  including Superfund,  hazardous waste,  hazard communication,  asbestos,  clean water,  clean air,  wetlands,  state environmental laws,  and environmental auditing.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Bonnie J. Semilof</B> Has extensive experience in presenting,  defending,  and cross-examining expert witnesses. She has appeared in matters involving chlorinated and other synthetic pesticides and she is counsel and national coordinating co-counsel on multiple pending chemical exposure matters.<BR>
<BR>

