<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Environmental</H2>
<H3>Varnum,  Riddering,  Schmidt  & Howlett LLP
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Grand Rapids:</B> Bridgewater Place,  P.O. Box 352,  Grand Rapids,  MI 49501-0352<BR>
Tel 616-336-6000  <B>*</B>  Fax 616-336-7000<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:amylo@vrsh.mhs.compuserve.com">amylo@vrsh.mhs.compuserve.com</A><BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Detroit,  Lansing,  Kalamazoo,  Battle Creek,  and Grand Haven (Michigan)<BR>
<BR>
129 lawyers  <B>*</B>  17 lawyers in Environmental Law Practice Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>V</B>arnum,  Riddering,  Schmidt  & Howlett LLP is a Great Lakes regional law firm practicing in all areas of the law including business and corporate,  environmental,  litigation,  commercial and financial,  labor and employment relations,  municipal and administrative,  intellectual property,  oil and gas,  international,  real estate,  utility,  telecommunications,  health care,  and computer law. Clients of the firm include businesses,  utilities,  financial institutions,  individuals,  health care providers,  colleges and universities,  and governmental units.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Environmental Law Experience and Clients</H3></CENTER>

<P><BR><BR>
Members of the Environmental Law Practice Group have been engaged in environmental planning and problem-solving for the regulated community of industry,  government,  and commercial institutions since the early 1970s. As environmental law grows increasingly complex,  our attorneys have multidisciplinary support to provide the necessary comprehensive counsel and representation. We offer full service in such areas as:<BR><BR><UL><LI> PRP representation in Superfund proceedings (including cost-recovery litigation and serving as common,  shared,  and administrative counsel to PRP groups)<BR>
<LI> acquisition of air emission,  wastewater discharge,  and natural resource permits<BR>
<LI> hazardous waste management regulation and permitting<BR>
<LI> response to and reporting of spills<BR>
<LI> environmental insurance coverage claims<BR>
<LI> solid waste management,  waste-to-energy incineration,  and recycling options<BR>
<LI> hazardous chemical `right-to-know' programs and claims<BR>
<LI> conduct of compliance audits throughout North America<BR>
<LI> site assessments for property transactions<BR>
<LI> UST corrective actions and financing<BR>
<LI> pro-active counsel on environmental rulemaking.<BR></UL><BR><P>The Group has 12 partners,  five associates,  an environmental regulatory specialist,  two paralegals,  as well as liaison partners in related practice areas,  including the former chair of the Michigan Natural Resources Commission.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Jon F. DeWitt</B>,  co-chair of the Environmental Law Practice Group,  has over 20 years of environmental law experience. In addition to his national reputation in the area of hazardous waste cleanups,  Mr. DeWitt is a recognized authority on waste-to-energy facility development. Member,  Environmental Law Section Council of the State Bar of Michigan and Solid Waste and Hazardous Waste Advisory Committee of the Michigan Manufacturers Association. University of Michigan Law School,  LL.B.,  1962.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Matthew D. Zimmerman</B>,  co-chair of the Environmental Law Practice Group,  maintains an environmental practice encompassing natural resource and development issues (such as wetlands and sand dunes),  landfill site selection,  licensing and closure,  environmental site assessments,  industrial redevelopment,  and UST issues. Member,  Solid  & Hazardous Waste/Insurance Committee of the Environmental Law Section of the State Bar of Michigan and Insurance Litigation Subcommittee of the Environmental Litigation Committee of the Environmental Law Section of the American Bar Association. University of Michigan Law School,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Charles M. Denton</B> specializes in environmental law and litigation,  with a focus on Superfund liabilities (including natural resources damages) and RCRA hazardous waste management issues throughout the Midwest. Member,  Information Network for Superfund Settlements; chair,  Environmental Law Section of the Detroit Bar Association. University of Michigan Law School,  J.D.,  1981. Admitted in Indiana.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Teresa S. Decker</B> is primarily involved in environmental litigation (including criminal defense) and has extensive experience in land use,  municipal,  and environmental litigation before federal and state courts. Member,  Section of Natural Resources,  Energy and Environmental Law (SONREEL) of the American Bar Association,  Environmental Law Section of the State Bar of Michigan,  and West Michigan Chapter of the Federal Bar Association. University of Michigan Law School,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David E. Preston</B>'s experience includes federal and state air permitting,  RCRA hazardous waste management issues,  Superfund cleanups,  remedial actions for PCBs,  and facilities with on-site contamination. Member,  Air Subcommittee of the Environmental Law Section of the State Bar of Michigan. Bowling Green State University,  M.S.,  1975; University of Toledo,  J.D.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1987.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>George B. Davis</B>' environmental practice focuses on water quality issues,  and his experience ranges from municipal Superfund cases to land use matters. Member,  Michigan Manufacturers Association,  the Environmental Law Section of the State Bar of Michigan,  the American Waterworks Association,  and the National Association of Local Government Environmental Professionals. National Law Center,  George Washington University,  LL.M.,  land use and environmental law,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1981; McGeorge School of Law,  University of the Pacific,  J.D.,  1980.<BR></UL><BR>


</UL></BODY>
