<TITLE>Vinson  & Elkins L.L.P.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Environmental</H2>
<H3>Vinson  & Elkins L.L.P.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Houston:</B> 2300 First City Tower,  1001 Fannin Street,  Houston,  TX 77002-6760<BR>
Tel 713-758-2222  <B>*</B>  Fax 713-758-2346<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> The Willard Office Building,  1455 Pennsylvania Avenue N.W., <BR>
Washington,  DC 20004-1008<BR>
Tel 202-639-6500  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-639-6604<BR>
<B>Dallas:</B> 3700 Trammell Crow Center,  2001 Ross Avenue,  Dallas,  TX 75201-2975<BR>
Tel 214-220-7700  <B>*</B>  Fax 214-220-7716<BR>
<B>Austin:</B> One American Center,  600 Congress Avenue,  Austin,  TX 78701-3200<BR>
Tel 512-495-8400  <B>*</B>  Fax 512-495-8612<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> London,  Moscow,  Mexico City,  Singapore<BR>
<BR>
510 lawyers  <B>*</B>  27 lawyers in the Administrative and Environmental Law Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/vinson.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/vinson.html"> Product Liability</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>V</B>inson  & Elkins L.L.P. is one of the largest U.S.-based general practice law firms in the world,  representing clients in substantially all areas of law.
<P><BR><P>Since 1970 Vinson  & Elkins L.L.P. has worked with clients to solve their problems associated with protection of air and water quality,  land use,  and natural resources. The Firm worked on energy and water resources with their attendant environmental issues for many decades prior to the enactment of today's environmental protection programs.<BR><P>Vinson  & Elkins represents private clients and local governmental entities on matters relating to the development and use of lands and waters; the siting,  construction,  and operation of facilities; the disposal of wastes; and the regulation of public utilities,  energy,  transportation,  and other matters subject to the jurisdiction of federal,  state,  and local agencies. We counsel clients concerning regulatory requirements of administrative agencies,  litigate before those agencies and federal and state courts,  and provide assistance on federal and state legislative matters. We assist in the planning,  structuring,  and negotiation of new projects from the earliest stages and assist in the evaluation,  structuring,  and negotiation of business transactions. Although we negotiate to avoid litigation,  we have an active toxic tort defense practice and defend both civil and criminal enforcement actions,  including grand jury investigations.<BR>
<BR><P>The Firm's practice encompasses all types of environmental programs. Specific areas of practice include air and water pollution,  solid and hazardous waste,  medical waste,  toxic substances,  and Superfund,  as well as: asbestos,  coastal zone management,  drainage,  dredge and fill operations,  endangered species,  archeological resources,  all phases of energy activities,  environmental impact statements,  floodplains,  zoning,  historic preservation,  levees and reclamation projects,  offshore activities,  public utilities,  rights to use surface and ground water,  surface and underground mining and reclamation,  transportation,  wastewater service and other utilities,  and wetlands.<BR>
<BR><P>Representative clients include ALCoa,  Brown  & Root,  Compaq Computer Corp.,  E.I. DuPont de Nemours,  Enron Corp.,  Fina Oil and Chemical Co.,  City of Houston,  The Lubrizol Corporation,  Halliburton Co.,  Vitro,  S.A.,  Elf Atochem North America,  Rhone-Poulenc Basic Chemicals,  and Simpson Paper Co.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Carol E. Dinkins</B> (<I>Houston and Washington</I>) Practices in all areas of environmental law and is a frequent lecturer and author. From 1984-1985,  she was the Deputy Attorney General of the United States,  the second-ranking official at the Department of Justice. From 1981-1983,  Carol was the Department's Assistant Attorney General for the Environment and Natural Resources Division. Member of the ABA House of Delegates,  vice chair of the Section on Natural Resources,  Environmental,  and Energy Law,  and past chair of the State and Local Government Section. Member of various boards. University of Texas,  B.S.,  1968; University of Houston,  J.D.,  1971.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Charles L. Berry</B> (<I>Houston</I>) Principal litigator in the Firm's administrative and environmental law areas. He has been counsel in a number of NEPA,  CERCLA,  and Clean Water Act cases and litigation under RCRA. Texas Tech University,  B.A.,  1965; University of Texas,  J.D.,  1968.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Larry W. Nettles</B> (<I>Houston</I>) Practice includes all areas of environmental law,  with wide experience in business transactions and oil,  gas,  and energy development. Rice University,  B.S.,  civil engineering,  1978; University of Texas,  J.D.,  with honors,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Sharon M. Mattox</B> (<I>Houston</I>) Broad environmental and toxic tort litigation experience,  including successful trials and appeals in NEPA,  wetlands,  and personal injury and property damage cases. University of Texas,  Ph.D.,  botany,  1978,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Arthur E. Murphy</B> (<I>Houston</I>) Toxic tort,  water pollution,  and CERCLA litigation,  including jury trials. Adjunct professor of law in toxic tort litigation at South Texas College of Law. Yale University,  B.A.,  1982; Vanderbilt University,  J.D.,  1985.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Christopher B. Amandes</B> (<I>Houston</I>) Regulatory practice in all areas,  with especially broad experience in air,  wastewater,  and hazardous waste. Rice University,  B.A.,  environmental science and engineering and biology,  1976,  Master's of Environmental Engineering,  1978; University of California at Los Angeles,  J.D.,  1985.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Molly Cagle</B> (<I>Austin</I>) In addition to regulatory and permitting work before state and federal agencies in hazardous waste and water quality cases,  she is involved in a number of Superfund cases. Texas Tech University,  B.S.,  engineering technology and textile chemistry,  1978; University of Texas,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Amanda G. Birrell</B> (<I>Austin</I>) Practice focuses on Superfund litigation and administrative matters. Yale University,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1974; Georgetown University,  J.D.,  1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Norman D. Radford,  Jr.</B> (<I>Dallas</I>) Of counsel. Practice includes all aspects of environmental regulation and multiregion enforcement settlements. Norm chaired the Environmental and Natural Resources Law Section of the State Bar of Texas in 1984-1985. Virginia Military Institute,  B.S.,  civil engineering,  1965; University of North Carolina,  M.S.,  sanitary engineering,  1967; University of Virginia,  J.D.,  1972.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kevin A. Gaynor</B> (<I>Washington</I>) Practice includes all types of representation in environmental matters and for multinational corporations,  including negotiation and litigation of claims by and against governmental entities and private parties. Served as assistant section chief of the U.S. Justice Department's Environmental Enforcement Section of the Environment and Natural Resources Division,  former assistant U.S. attorney in the District of Maine where he tried a major NEPA case,  and former trial attorney at the U.S. EPA. University of Connecticut,  B.A.,  1970; University of Virginia School of Law,  J.D.,  1973.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Thomas R. Bartman</B> (<I>Washington</I>) Practice involves compliance counseling in areas of waste management,  chemical manufacturing,  and pesticide regulation; litigation in both federal and state courts under a range of environmental laws; environmental criminal defense; and design of environmental compliance management programs. Served as a senior trial attorney in the Environment Division of the U.S. Department of Justice from 1988 to 1990. Haverford College,  B.A.,  1975; Yale University,  M.Phil.,  1978; University of Virginia Law School,  J.D.,  1982.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Patrick F. Thompson</B> (<I>Austin</I>) Of counsel. Practice includes administrative law and litigation involving state agencies,  with a focus on energy law. He tries administrative cases before the Railroad Commission,  the Texas Department of Insurance,  the General Land Office,  the Motor Vehicle Division of the Department of Transportation,  the Texas Education Agency,  and various professional boards of registration. Served as a hearings examiner for the Railroad Commission and was legal advisor to the chairman of the commission. University of Texas,  B.A.,  with high honors,  1978,  Phi Beta Kappa,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Ky P. Ewing,  Jr.</B> (<I>Washington</I>) Practice involves antitrust and business litigation,  including merger and other investigations by the U.S. Department of Justice and the Federal Trade Commission,  antitrust counseling (with particular reference to mergers,  joint ventures,  health care provider issues,  and distribution arrangements),  securities law and fraud investigations,  and environmental regulatory issues. Served as deputy assistant attorney general,  Antitrust Division,  U.S. Department of Justice. Baylor University,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1956; Harvard Law School,  LL.B.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1959.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>C. Michael Buxton</B> (<I>Washington</I>) Practice involves litigation,  with a focus on white collar criminal defense. He has defended a number of environmental criminal cases. Served as an attorney-advisor,  Office of Legal Counsel,  U.S. Depart-ment of Justice,  and was a special assistant U.S. attorney,  District of Columbia. Also served as law clerk to Associate Justice William H. Rehnquist. Rice University,  B.A.,  1968; University of Kentucky,  J.D.,  with high distinction,  1971.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Larry J. Pechacek</B> (<I>Houston</I>) Practice involves compliance counseling in all areas of air,  water,  and solid waste management,  regulation,  and permitting,  as well as enforcement settlements. Texas A &M University,  B.S.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  civil engineering,  1982; University of Texas,  M.S.,  civil engineering,  1984; University of Houston,  J.D.,  1989.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kimberely J. Lesniak</B> (<I>Houston</I>) Practice involves environmental programs related to land use and development,  including storm water regulation,  wetlands,  endangered species,  and cultural resources. Practice also includes environmental litigation involving hazardous waste,  Superfund cost recovery,  takings,  land use,  and Native American issues. College of William and Mary,  B.S.,  environmental science,  1986; University of Virginia,  J.D.,  1989.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David J. Tuckfield</B> (<I>Houston</I>) Practice includes representation of clients before administrative agencies and in connection with multimedia inspections and enforcement initiatives. Brigham Young University,  B.A.,  <I>cum laud</I>e,  1985,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1989.<BR>
