<P>
<P>
<P><B>V</B>orys,  Sater,  Seymour and Pease has 25 full-time environmental lawyers,  including a former Ohio EPA director,  attorneys with technical backgrounds,  former corporate counsel,  and a Ph.D. chemist.
<P><BR><P>Our experience includes: Air and wastewater permitting for steel,  auto,  brick,  paper,  Fiberglas,  chemical,  foundry,  and other processes. RCRA permitting and closures for on- and off-site TSDs,  USTs,  and underground injection wells. Participation on steering and coordinating committees in Superfund cases nationwide. Defense of actions brought by the U.S. to impose CERCLA liability under 106 and 107. Defense of class action and individual suits for personal injury or property damage from exposure to hazardous or toxic substances. Defense of citizen-private party suits brought under RCRA,  Clean Water Act,  Clean Air Act,  and CERCLA and SARA. Opinions and involvement with SARA community right-to-know reportable quantity issues. Compliance with,  and exemption from,  environmental regulatory requirements. Assistance to corporations and trade associations in EPA,  OSHA,  CPSC,  and other federal and state notice-and-comment rulemakings and related litigation. Environmental audits and evaluations to ensure compliance in connection with real estate acquisitions and sales. Wetland permitting,  including delineation and mitigation. Toxic,  hazardous,  and solid waste disposal contracting in Eastern Europe.<BR><P>Among our clients are Occidental Chemical Company,  Owens-Corning Fiberglas Corporation,  Chemical Waste Management,  Inc.,  Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company,  General Electric Co.,  Honda of America Mfg.,  Inc.,  and Martin Marietta Energy Systems,  Inc.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Joseph D. Lonardo</B> (<I>Columbus; 614-464-6211</I>) Chief environmental litigation partner. Experienced in enforcement actions,  steering committees in Superfund sites nationwide,  private-plaintiff toxic tort suits seeking personal injury and property damages. Member: ABA Environmental Law Committee; International Association of Defense Counsel-Toxic and Hazardous Substance Litigation Committee. University of Michigan,  J.D.,  1972. Admitted in Ohio.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John W. Hoberg</B> (<I>Columbus; 614-464-6213</I>) Chief environmental regulatory partner. Represents manufacturers and trade associations before the Ohio and U.S. EPAs,  the Ohio Department of Natural Resources,  the Ohio Legislature,  and the courts. Experienced in air,  water,  and solid and hazardous waste permits; enforcement actions; and Superfund sites. University of Michigan,  J.D.,  1968. Admitted in Ohio.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert H. Maynard</B> (<I>Columbus; 614-464-5432</I>) Former Ohio EPA director; trial lawyer,  U.S. Department of Justice's Division of Land and Natural Resources; special assistant to solicitor,  U.S. Department of Interior; U.S. Senate legislative assistant for environment,  energy,  and natural resources (Clean Air Act of 1970,  FWPCA Amendments of 1972,  and other environmental and natural resources legislation). Georgetown University,  LL.M.,  1965. Admitted in Ohio,  Texas,  and the District of Columbia.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John W. Wilmer,  Jr.</B> (<I>Washington; 202-467-8819</I>) 23 years' experience in Washington,  D.C. in EPA and OSHA enforcement actions,  litigation,  and rulemakings for companies and trade associations nationwide. Center for Naval Analyses and Council of Environmental Quality,  1971-1973. Law clerk to Judge Pierce Lively,  U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit,  1975-1976.  Princeton University,  B.A.,  1970; Georgetown University,  J.D.,  1975. Admitted in Florida and the District of Columbia.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert J. Styduhar</B> (<I>Columbus; 614-464-8299</I>) Former environmental counsel at ChemLawn Corp.; assistant attorney general,  Natural Resources Section,  Maryland; assistant attorney general,  Environmental Law Section,  Ohio; and chief legal advisor,  Ohio EPA. Experienced in hazardous and solid waste,  USTs,  and community right-to-know. Case Western Reserve University,  J.D.,  1977. Admitted in Ohio and Maryland.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Elizabeth E. Tulman</B> (<I>Columbus; 614-464-6438</I>) Experienced in federal and state regulatory matters including water and air pollution,  hazardous waste,  and Superfund; and in private cost-recovery actions,  citizen suits,  and toxic tort litigation,  including class action certifications. Chair,  Environmental Law Committee,  Ohio State Bar Association,  and member,  Environmental Law Committee,  Columbus Bar Association; <I>Best Lawyers in America</I>,  Environmental and Natural Resources Section. University of Cincinnati,  J.D.,  1982.<BR>
