<HEAD>
<TITLE>Wilmer,  Cutler  & Pickering
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Environmental</H2>
<H3>Wilmer,  Cutler  & Pickering
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington:</B> 2445 M Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20037-1420<BR>
Tel 202-663-6000  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-663-6363  <B>*</B>  E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:law@wilmer.com">law@wilmer.com</A><BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Berlin,  Brussels,  London<BR>
<BR>
215 lawyers  <B>*</B>  14 lawyers in the environmental area<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/wilmer.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/wilmer.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/wilmer.html"> Corporate Securities</A>
   <LI><A HREF="..//wilmer.html"> International</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/wilmer.html"> Product Liability</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/wilmer.html"> White Collar Crime</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/wilmer.html"> Workout</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>W</B>C &P is a broadly diversified international law firm that handles a wide range of litigation,  corporate,  regulatory,  and legislative matters both in the United States and abroad. Our environmental group represents clients in matters arising under CERCLA,  RCRA,  the Clean Water Act,  TSCA,  the Clean Air Act,  the Safe Drinking Water Act,  NEPA,  OSHA,  and analogous state laws. In conjunction with the firm's trade practitioners and attorneys in WC &P's European offices,  the group also advises clients with respect to European Union and other international environmental requirements and counsels clients regarding the interface of trade and environmental policy.<BR><BR><P>WC &P's environmental attorneys handle civil and criminal enforcement cases,  judicial challenges to agency rules,  and private litigation allocating liability among corporations. We also counsel clients on a wide array of environmental and occupational safety and health compliance issues,  and assist them in developing compliance programs and conducting audits. We handle the environmental aspects of domestic and international business transactions,  performing due diligence reviews,  drafting and negotiating contractual provisions,  and providing advice on structuring transactions to limit liability. We also assist clients in developing and advocating positions before regulatory agencies,  Congress, and state legislative bodies.<BR><BR><P>WC &P makes innovative use of computer technology to provide efficient service to our clients. Attorneys and staff are linked by a local area network,  and many of our clients also are connected to our electronic mail system. Through our advanced computer technology,  we can retrieve information quickly from our extensive environmental library.<BR>
<BR><P>Some of WC &P's current environmental clients include the Alliance for Reasonable Regulation,  the American Iron and Steel Institute,  the Chemical Manufacturers Association,  Citizens Utilities Company,  Inco Ltd.,  INMETCO,  ITT Corp.,  Magma Copper Co.,  Owens-Corning Fiberglas Corporation,  and Sara Lee Corporation.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Laura B. Ahearn</B> Ms. Ahearn has handled environmental matters since 1984,  including litigation,  transactions,  counseling,  and matters concerning hazardous and solid wastes; radionuclides; air; water and groundwater; endangered species; cultural resources; and compliance programs and reporting. Ms. Ahearn serves as `liaison counsel' in complex multiparty Superfund litigation,  and handles negotiations with agencies,  works with cleanup contractors,  and leads settlement discussions with the government and among PRPs. Stanford University School of Law,  1984.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Carol Clayton</B> Ms. Clayton has practiced environmental law for 13 years,  working on litigation and counseling matters under CERCLA,  RCRA,  TSCA,  the Clean Water Act,  the Clean Air Act,  and NEPA. Ms. Clayton has assisted companies in a variety of industries in designing and implementing environmental compliance programs. She has lectured in the United States,  Canada,  and Europe on a variety of environmental law topics. University of Virginia Law School,  1982.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>C. Boyden Gray</B> Mr. Gray advises clients on a range of environmental issues,  including those relating to biotechnology,  clean air,  and risk management. He has extensive experience with the use of market incentives to achieve environmental goals,  and played a key role in initiating the Clean Air Act acid rain emissions trading system. Mr. Gray was legal counsel to Vice-President George Bush and counsel to the Presidential Task Force on Regulatory Relief,  chaired by Vice-President Bush. He served as counsel to Vice-President Bush,  as director of the Office of Transition Counsel for the Bush transition team,  and as counsel to President Bush from 1989-1993. University of North Carolina,  1968.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Neil J. King</B> For the past 18 years,  Mr. King has represented clients in EPA,  OSHA,  and comparable state agency rulemakings,  in litigation involving challenges to agency rules,  and in a variety of legislative matters. He has handled rulemakings and court actions involving air pollutant,  water pollutant,  hazardous waste,  and drinking water standards,  as well as a host of OSHA standards and other environmental regulations. Mr. King counsels clients on a range of international environmental issues,  and was a member of the EPA's Advisory Committee on Trade and the Environment. Harvard Law School,  1970.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>James A. Rogers</B> Mr. Rogers has practiced environmental law since 1971,  when he was an assistant attorney general for the State of Wisconsin,  prosecuting cases involving air and water pollution and waste disposal. From 1973 until 1981,  Mr. Rogers was with the EPA's Office of General Counsel,  including four years as associate general counsel for water and solid waste. In private practice,  he has been involved in over 50 Superfund matters and dozens of civil and criminal cases under RCRA,  the Clean Water Act,  and other statutes. Mr. Rogers serves on the Environmental Law Institute's Board of Directors,  and was chairman of the board from 1988 to 1990. University of Michigan Law School,  1969.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Daniel H. Squire</B> Mr. Squire has practiced environmental law since 1980. He has worked on litigation and settlements relating to numerous hazardous waste sites nationwide. Mr. Squire handles complex private cost-recovery litigation and advises clients on a variety of compliance issues. He has dealt extensively with the treatment of environmental liabilities in bankruptcy through his work for several clients and as a speaker for the Bankruptcy Litigation Institute. Harvard Law School,  1980.<BR>
<BR>


</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
