<HEAD>
<TITLE>Hall  & Evans,  L.L.C.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>ERISA</H2>
<H3>Hall  & Evans,  L.L.C.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<B><CENTER>Denver:</B> Suite 1700,  1200 Seventeenth Street,  Denver,  CO 80202-5800<BR>
Tel 303-628-3300  <B>*</B>  Fax 303-628-3368<BR>
<B>Colorado Springs:</B> Suite 600,  102 South Tejon,  Colorado Springs,  CO 80904-2264<BR>
Tel 719-578-5600  <B>*</B>  Fax 719-635-7458<BR>
<BR>
77 lawyers  <B>*</B>  3 lawyers specializing in ERISA and employee benefits<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/hall.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/hall.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/hall.html"> Labor</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>H</B>all  & Evans has provided legal services since 1932,  representing our clients on the local through international levels in litigation,  commercial transactions,  and regulatory and legislative affairs. We deliver innovative solutions,  prompt dispute resolution,  and multi-dimensional legal strategies in a practical,  timely,  and cost-effective manner.
<P><BR><P>We have a significant employee benefit practice which includes the selection and preparation of welfare benefit plans and pension benefit plans and representing clients in their capacity as fiduciaries of plans subject to ERISA,  the Employee Retirement Income Security Act. Our practice also addresses designing and implementing welfare benefit plans and qualified retirement plans as well as handling IRS and Department of Labor filings and representing clients in benefit disputes.<BR><P>The technical aspect of our practice includes working with clients in the selection and implementation of welfare benefit plans,  including cafeteria plans,  voluntary employees' beneficiary associations,  and qualified sick pay plans. With regard to compensation planning,  we work with our corporate,  governmental,  and non-profit clients in designing and implementing qualified and non-qualified retirement plans,  deferred compensation arrangements,  and qualified and non-qualified stock options as well as employee stock ownership plans.<BR>
<BR><P>There has been a tremendous growth in ERISA and other benefit-related litigation which is due,  in large part,  to the increasing number of significant decisions issued by the U.S. Supreme Court and other federal courts. Our attorneys assist clients in complying with statutes and regulations under the Internal Revenue Code and ERISA,  and also have defended ERISA plans and fiduciaries in federal and state court in Colorado,  Missouri,  New Mexico,  Texas,  and Utah. Cases we handle include issues of ERISA's preemption; matters concerning fiduciary obligations and breach of fiduciary duties; reporting and disclosure requirements under ERISA; MEWA-related claims; Department of Labor audits; wrongful denial of health,  disability,  life,  or accidental death benefits; and disputes regarding COBRA and conversion from group to individual benefits.<BR>
<BR><P>Representative clients include the AIG entities; The Chubb Group of Insurance Companies; Gemisys Trust Company; ITT Hartford; Lincoln Trust Company; Philadelphia American Life; Reliance National Insurance Company; Standard Insurance Company; and Trust Company of America.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Joyce H. Nakamura</B> (<I>303-628-3362</I>) has practiced law for 13 years. She works extensively with public and private clients in the selection and implementation of welfare benefit plans including cafeteria plans,  self-funded voluntary employees' beneficiary associations,  and qualified sick pay plans. Her work in the area of compensation planning includes the design and implementation of qualified and non-qualified retirement plans,  defined compensation arrangements,  qualified and non-qualified stock options,  and employee stock ownership plans. Additionally,  she assists clients in the claims review process and represents them in their capacity as trustees and plan administrators of ERISA plans. She frequently conducts educational seminars for her clients concerning the implementation,  administration,  and economics of employee benefit plans.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Clinton P. Swift</B> (<I>303-628-3319</I>) was admitted to practice in 1972 and concentrates on the defense of fiduciaries and directors and officers of private and public corporations. He is currently defending ERISA plans and trustees in both federal and state courts in Colorado,  New Mexico,  Missouri,  and Texas in lawsuits involving ERISA preemption; claims that MEWAs are insurance schemes not entitling them to the benefits afforded by ERISA in litigation; Department of Labor audits of a MEWA; and claims of wrongful denial of health,  severance,  and long-term disability benefits; together with disputes regarding COBRA and conversion from group to individual benefits. Mr. Swift also defends employers in wrongful termination and Title VII Civil Rights Act claims involving issues of national origin,  sex,  age,  and disability discrimination. He speaks frequently before bankers' conventions on fiduciary litigation,  fiduciary insurance,  and contracts.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Edward H. Widmann</B> (<I>303-628-3320</I>) was admitted to the bar in 1965. He is co-chair of the firm's Insurance Coverage Group and concentrates on defending and monitoring insurance coverage lawsuits concerning officer and director liability,  ERISA fiduciaries,  products liability,  insurance coverage,  and bad faith. He provides advice and litigation defense concerning substantial claims relating to insurance coverage,  including breach of fiduciary duties.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
