<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Kramer,  Levin,  Naftalis  & Frankel</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL><CENTER><H2>ERISA</H2><H3>Kramer,  Levin,  Naftalis   & Frankel</H3></CENTER><B><CENTER>New York:</B> 919 Third Avenue,  New York,  NY 10022<BR>Tel 212-715-9100  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-715-8000 <B>*</B> Home page: <A HREF="http://www.kramer-levin.com/">www.kramer-levin.com</A><BR><BR>150 lawyers  <B>*</B>  7 lawyers in ERISA practice<BR></CENTER><P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR><UL><BR>   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/kramer.html"> Antitrust</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/kramer.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/kramer.html"> Corporate Securities</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/kramer.html"> Intellectual Property</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/kramer.html"> Labor</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/kramer.html"> Product Liability</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/kramer.html"> White Collar Crime</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/kramer.html"> Workout</A></UL><P><P><P><B>O</B>ur employee benefits practice,  which covers the full range of benefits issues on which legal counsel is necessary or helpful,  primarily serves clients that regard benefits work as a technical area requiring attorneys specifically selected for their experience in the field.<P><BR><P><I>General Benefits Advice.</I> Our area of practice includes executive compensation arrangements; tax-qualified retirement,  profit-sharing,  and savings plans; ESOPs; and welfare plans (including cafeteria and flex plans). We counsel on design opportunities and constraints under ERISA,  the Internal Revenue Code,  the securities laws,  nondiscrimination and other labor laws,  and bankruptcy. Our counsel ranges from highly technical assistance for major public corporations with sophisticated in-house expertise to comprehensive advice relating to plan design,  implementation,  and compliance for other clients.<BR><P>We also represent plan sponsors and fiduciaries in benefits-related litigation in the appellate and lower courts. Examples include defense of individual and class actions involving such issues as the modification of post-retirement health benefits,  or the termination of eligibility to grow into early retirement subsidies on the sale of a subsidiary,  and alleged fiduciary breaches; and representation of a variety of employers,  ranging from major public companies to closely held companies,  in multiemployer liability plan withdrawal disputes.<BR><BR><P>In addition to such corporate clients of the firm as Liz Claiborne,  Inc. and MCI,  special clients of the department who have retained us specifically for advice on benefits matters include: Arrow Electronics,  Inc.,  BTR Inc.,  Citicorp,  Collins  & Aikman Group,  Inc.,  Lehman Brothers,  Sony Theaters,  Marsh  & McLennan Companies,  Inc.,  Mobil Oil Corporation,  New York Life Insurance Company,  Philips Electronics North America Corporation,  PaineWebber,  Sony Pictures Entertainment Inc.,  United States Trust Company,  United Technologies Corporation,  and Warner-Lambert Company.<BR><BR><P>Our expertise in the field also is recognized by other benefit specialists: our senior benefit partner often has been sought as an arbitrator in contested civil matters or as an expert witness (including by the U.S. Department of Labor,  which has recommended him as an expert witness on ERISA matters for the Comptroller of the Currency).<BR><BR><P><I>Transaction Counseling.</I> We act as special benefits counsel to management in corporate transactions and workouts. For example,  we advised the management of Praxair Inc. on benefit matters in its spin-off by Union Carbide Corporation; and we successfully defended the Air Micronesia-controlled joint venture against a $700 million claim asserted by the PBGC arising out of the Continental and Eastern bankruptcies,  and counseled on related issues in the restructuring of Air Micronesia into an independent airline.<BR><BR><P><I>Counsel to Institutions and Service Providers.</I> We also counsel brokerage and investment advisory clients with respect to the full range of ERISA and tax considerations associated with benefit plan investments and the furnishing of financial services to benefit plans (e.g.,  prohibited transaction,  unrelated business income,  `soft dollar' issues,  and group trust arrangements),  and with the use of prototype qualified plans and IRAs used in offering mutual funds and brokerage services.<BR><BR><P><I>Counsel to Plan Fiduciaries.</I> We represent plan fiduciaries in corporate transactions where the advice of independent counsel is required,  such as: the ESOP fiduciaries in the $2 billion ESOP leveraged buyout of Healthtrust Inc.-The Hospital Company from Hospital Corporation of America,  and in the subsequent refinancings and ESOP termination; the fiduciaries at Colt Industries in connection with its Savings Plan's receipt of different consideration than other stockholders in Colt's $1.6 billion leveraged recapitalization; Richardson-Vick's fiduciaries in connection with the buyout of its plan's stockholdings upon the acquisition of Richardson-Vicks by Procter  & Gamble; and the Macmillan ESOP trustees in connection with the proposed restructuring of Macmillan prior to its purchase by the Maxwell interests.<BR><BR><P>The benefits practice group is headed by Michael J. Nassau and Max J. Schwartz,  who have each worked on matters for the clients mentioned above.<BR><BR><UL><LI><B>Michael J. Nassau</B> has practiced in the area since 1961. He is past co-chair of the Committee on Employee Benefits of the New York State Bar Association's Tax Section,  and past chairman of the Subcommittee on Pension Legislation of the Tax Committee,  Association of the Bar of the City of New York. Yale University,  B.A.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1956,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1960; Phi Beta Kappa; Order of the Coif; note and comment editor,  <I>Yale Law Journal</I>.<BR><BR><LI><B>Max J. Schwartz</B> has practiced in the area since 1974. Prior to joining the firm in 1986,  he was a technical consultant at Towers Perrin where he advised the firm's actuaries,  consultants,  and clients,  and was in-house benefits counsel at General Signal Corporation. Fluent in French. Institut D'Etudes Politiques,  University of Paris,  B.A.,  1970; University of Michigan Law School,  J.D.,  1973; associate editor,  <I>Michigan Law Review</I>.<BR></UL><BR><P>Both Messrs. Nassau and Schwartz are active members of bar groups and committees focusing on benefits issues,  and frequent speakers at continuing education programs for the legal and actuarial professions. Separately and together,  they have authored more than 150 articles and outlines for publication in professional journals and course materials covering employee benefits.<BR><BR></UL></BODY></HTML>
