<TITLE>Morgan,  Lewis & Bockius LLP
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>ERISA</H2>
<H3>Morgan,  Lewis & Bockius LLP
</H3>

</CENTER>
<B><CENTER>Philadelphia:</B> 2000 One Logan Square,  Philadelphia,  PA 19103-6993<BR>
Tel 215-963-5000  <B>*</B>  Fax 215-963-5299<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Washington,  D.C.,  New York,  Los Angeles,  Miami,  Harrisburg, <BR>
Princeton (New Jersey),  Brussels,  Frankfurt,  London,  Tokyo<BR>
<BR>
715 lawyers  <B>*</B>  28 lawyers concentrating in employee benefits and executive compensation<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/morgan.html"> Labor</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/morgan.html"> White Collar Crime</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>F</B>ounded in 1873,  Morgan,  Lewis  & Bockius LLP is an international firm providing integrated legal services from multiple offices. The firm established its nationwide Employee Benefits and Executive Compensation Group,  which includes attorneys,  benefits analysts,  and legal assistants,  to combine specialized skills into a single practice group focusing on employee benefits. Lawyers in the Group are experienced in tax,  labor,  securities,  corporate,  banking,  insurance,  civil rights,  regulated industries,  and international law. Members of the Group also handle numerous state law questions.
<P><BR><P>In addition to representing clients in negotiation and litigation,  the Group also provides daily assistance to clients in connection with prospective legislation and regulation; statutory and regulatory compliance; document preparation and interpretation; agency filings (IRS,  SEC,  PBGC,  and Department of Labor); nonroutine regulatory matters (including special rulings and exemptions,  audits,  and investigations); plan feasibility examinations; plan design and implementation; establishment and maintenance of plan administrative systems; and employee communications.<BR><P>The Group provides legal services in the following areas: qualified pension,  profit-sharing,  thrift,  stock bonus,  401(k),  and employee stock ownership plans; nonqualified executive deferred compensation and supplemental benefit plans (including rabbi and secular trusts); incentive plans; severance benefit plans; stock option arrangements; phantom stock plans; executive life insurance programs; group life insurance; health and welfare plans (hospitalization,  medical and major medical,  optical,  and dental); long- and short-term disability income programs; cafeteria or flexible benefits plans; and plans for nonprofit institutions and governmental and quasigovernmental entities.<BR>
<BR><P>The Group represents clients from all areas of the firm's practice,  ranging from Fortune 500 companies to mid-size and emerging growth companies. Lawyers also represent nonprofit institutions,  governmental entities,  jointly trusteed multiemployer plans,  and highly compensated individuals.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Robert A. Bildersee</B> (<I>Philadelphia; 215-963-5355</I>) Mr. Bildersee has practiced actively in all aspects of employee benefits law since 1967,  lectures and teaches regularly in the field,  and is the author of several books.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Harry W. Burton</B> (<I>Washington; 202-467-7105</I>) Co-manager of the Group,  Mr. Burton's benefits practice covers ERISA compliance,  collective bargaining,  litigation,  and representation before government agencies,  including Department of Labor and Department of Justice investigations.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert J. Lichtenstein</B> (<I>Philadelphia; 215-963-5726</I>) Co-manager of the Group,  Mr. Lichtenstein concentrates in the areas of executive compensation,  litigation,  qualified plans,  and ESOPs.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert L. Abramowitz</B> (<I>Philadelphia; 215-963-4811</I>) and <B>I. Lee Falk</B> (<I>Philadelphia; 215-963-5616)</I> Their practices include qualified retirement plans,  executive compensation,  incentive programs,  and the handling of fiduciary and financing matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gary G. Quintiere</B> (<I>Washington; 202-467-7290</I>) and <B>Carol V. Calhoun</B> (<I>Washington; 202-467-7277</I>) Their practices concentrate in the tax aspects of employee benefits matters,  including representation before government agencies,  ESOPs,  and representation of governmental plans.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Frank H. Smith,  Jr.</B> (<I>Los Angeles; 213-612-1016</I>) Mr. Smith's practice involves all areas of employee benefits,  including pension and profit sharing,  tax-sheltered annuities,  and deferred compensation. He has served as president of the Los Angeles Chapter of the Western Pension Conference.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Steven D. Spencer</B> (<I>Philadelphia; 215-963-5714</I>) and <B>Mark E. Zelek</B> (<I>Miami; 305-579-0303</I>) Their practices concentrate on labor law aspects of employee benefits,  including litigation,  and multiemployer plans. Mr. Spencer has substantial experience with welfare plans,  and Title 1 of ERISA. Mr. Zelek has lectured in the U.S. and South America on labor and employee benefits issues.<BR>
