<B>Hong Kong:</B> 3A Chater Road,  Central,  Hong Kong<BR>
Tel 85-2-536-9933  <B>*</B>  Fax 85-2-536-9622<BR>
<B>Tokyo:</B> Akasaka Twin Tower,  17-22,  Akasaka 2-chome,  Minato-ku,  Tokyo 107,  Japan<BR>
Tel 81-3-3505-0291  <B>*</B>  Fax 81-3-3505-4540<BR>
<B>Beijing:</B> Scite Tower (Noble Tower),  Room 904,  22,  Jianguomenwai Dajie, <BR>
Beijing 100004,  People's Republic of China<BR>
Tel 86-1-512-3628  <B>*</B>  Fax 86-1-512-3631<BR>
<BR>
345 lawyers  <B>*</B>  7 lawyers in ERISA,  executive compensation,  and employee benefits<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/paul.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/paul.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/paul.html"> Corporate Securities</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/paul.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/paul.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/paul.html"> Product Liability</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/paul.html"> Workout</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>P</B>aul,  Weiss,  Rifkind,  Wharton  & Garrison is a globally oriented,  full-service firm. The firm's practice areas include a group of seven lawyers and one para-legal who work full time on all types of ERISA,  executive compensation,  and employee benefits matters. The department regularly provides general benefits advice to a number of major corporations,  both regular firm clients and also companies that have come to the firm specifically for that work. Typical client support includes assistance in the design,  installation,  and maintenance of broad-based plans and novel programs for key executives.
<P><BR><P>The benefits practice has included a great deal of transactional work,  such as dealing with the benefits issues connected with corporate takeovers and sales. Also,  the group has handled many nonrecurring work projects involving very difficult benefits problems,  such as handling the Senate and federal agency investigations into one client's purchase of annuities from the now-failed Executive Life Insurance Company.<BR><P>We routinely field questions involving ERISA's fiduciary responsibility and prohibited transaction rules. This work typically involves counseling for the plan sponsor or for the money manager. We have also handled fiduciary litigation and worked on a number of applications for exemption from ERISA's prohibited transaction rules. We have also represented clients whose plan management activities were under investigation by the Department of Labor.<BR>
<BR><P>Paul,  Weiss' ERISA group has also been involved in a considerable number of employee stock ownership (ESOP) transactions. For example,  we represented the United Airlines pilots in their historic multibillion-dollar effort to buy the airline through an ESOP,  and we represented the ESOP that successfully bought LTV's bar steel operations for the United Steelworkers. We have provided advice in several contests for corporate control where an ESOP figured prominently in defense strategy. For example,  we represented the Dan River textile company in connection with the ESOP established during its takeover battle with Carl Icahn,  and we represented the ESOP established by NCR following AT &T's acquisition overture. Together with our regular tax attorneys,  we have successfully worked on ESOPs in connection with corporate restructurings and tax-free sales of stock to ESOPs by individual stockholders.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Robert C. Fleder</B> Member,  New York State and American Bar Associations. Frequent lecturer to professional groups on matters involving ERISA,  employee benefits,  and executive compensation. Mr. Fleder's lecture activities have included the following: `Dealing with the Troubled GIC Issuer' (Practising Law Institute,  1991); `Advanced Level Analysis of the New Section 401(a)(4) and 410(b) Nondiscrimination Rules' (Enrolled Actuaries Annual Meeting,  1991); `ESOPs 1989: Advanced Techniques' (seminar chairman and lecturer,  Law Journal Seminars Press,  1989); and `Fiduciary and other ERISA Litigation' (Practising Law Institute,  1987).<BR>
<BR><P>Mr. Fleder's published articles include: `Golden Parachutes' (46 <I>New York University Institute on Federal Taxation</I>,  1988); `Two Insured Compensation Arrangements: Some Practical Observations' (40 <I>New York University Institute on Federal Taxation</I>,  ERISA Supplement,  1982); `Estate Planning for Retirement Benefits' (coauthor of chapter for <I>Estate and Gift Tax After ERTA</I>,  published by Practising Law Institute,  1982); and `Stock Options Under the Economic Recovery Tax Act of 1981' (coauthor of article published in Prentice-Hall's <I>Corporation Report</I>,  1981). Columbia College,  B.A.,  1969; Columbia University,  M.A.,  1971,  J.D.,  1973.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Donald F. Moore</B> Member,  Association of the Bar of the City of New York and New York State Bar Association. ERISA partner since 1974; represented or currently represents a wide variety of clients,  ranging from New York City's Municipal Assistance Corporation to Fortune 500 companies to small corporations,  partnerships,  and individuals,  on all aspects of employee benefit law. Fordham University,  A.B.,  1959; St. John's University,  LL.B.,  1962.<BR>
