<TITLE>Reish  & Luftman
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>ERISA</H2>
<H3>Reish  & Luftman
</H3>

</CENTER>
<B><CENTER>Los Angeles:</B> 11755 Wilshire Boulevard,  10th Floor,  Los Angeles,  CA 90025<BR>
Tel 310-478-5656  <B>*</B>  Fax 310-478-5831<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> One Massachusetts Avenue,  N.W.,  Suite 800,  Washington,  DC 20001-1401<BR>
Tel 202-745-0024  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-745-0005<BR>
<BR>
23 lawyers  <B>*</B>  16 lawyers in employee benefits<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>T</B>he firm's employee benefits practice covers the full range of plan issues: from single employer to multiemployer plans,  from retirement to welfare plans,  and from consulting to litigation.<BR>
<BR><P><I>Retirement Plan Counseling</I> This Group focuses on advising plans and their sponsors,  fiduciaries,  and service providers on legal issues in the design,  adoption,  administration,  investment management,  and termination of qualified and nonqualified retirement and incentive programs. Examples are:<BR><BR><UL><LI> Advice to fiduciaries on their responsibilities for plan transactions.<LI> Counsel to tax-exempt organizations on 403(b),  457,  and qualified plans.<LI> Counsel to employers on stock-based plans,  including the transactional aspects of employer stock ownership plans (ESOPs).<LI> Representation of employers,  plans,  and fiduciaries before all government agencies,  including the IRS,  Department of Labor,  and PBGC.<LI> Counsel to Taft-Hartley boards of trustees on operational,  fiduciary,  and benefits issues.<LI> Advice to employers on the design and operation of nonqualified deferred compensation programs,  including funding vehicles for those programs.<LI> Representation of service providers in drafting documents,  advising on fiduciary and professional liability issues,  and providing technical support.<BR></UL>
<BR><BR><P><I>Health and Welfare Counseling</I> This Group advises employers and service providers on the implementation and operation of funded and unfunded welfare plans,  including VEBAs,  cafeteria and flex plans,  self-insured health plans,  and managed and alternative health care programs. Examples include:<BR><UL><BR><LI> Structure and drafting of welfare benefit plans,  including self-insured arrangements,  severance plans,  and employee assistance plans.<LI> Advice to employers on compliance with the Americans with Disabilities Act for health and welfare benefits.<LI> Advice to employers on continuation of coverage issues under COBRA.<LI> Structure and drafting of preferred provider organization documents.<LI> Advice to administrators on state law compliance by health care systems.<BR></UL><BR><BR><P><I>ERISA Litigation</I> The firm has a national ERISA litigation practice,  handling fiduciary breach,  prohibited transaction,  and service provider malpractice litigation. We also represent clients before the Department of Labor,  IRS,  and PBGC. We have an active <I>amicus curiae</I> practice in the federal courts on behalf of a professional association. Examples of our litigation practice include:<BR><UL><LI> Defending ESOP fiduciaries from claims relating to stock valuation.<LI> Defending multiemployer trustees in Department of Labor litigation.<LI> Defending third-party administrators and actuaries in professional malpractice and fiduciary breach cases.<LI> Serving as expert witnesses in arbitration and in state and federal courts on issues including the duties of plan fiduciaries,  document interpretation,  and professional malpractice.<LI> Prosecuting and defending ERISA-related claims in bankruptcy courts.<BR></UL><BR><BR><P>Representative clients include Blue Cross of California; Great West Life Assurance Co.; Sumitomo Bank; Imperial Trust Company; Northern Trust Company; the Eastern Airline Retiree Health  & Benefit Trust; and the American Society of Pension Actuaries (ASPA).<BR>
<BR>
<BR><LI><B>C. Frederick Reish</B> (<I>Los Angeles</I>) represents clients on ERISA issues,  including disputes with the IRS,  PBGC,  and Department of Labor. He serves as an expert witness in fiduciary and service provider litigation. He is co-chair of the Los Angeles IRS Benefits Conference.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Bruce L. Ashton</B> (<I>Los Angeles</I>) counsels clients on ERISA,  nonqualified deferred compensation,  and health and welfare benefit plans. He has authored articles on ERISA issues for numerous publications,  including <I>The Journal of Taxation</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David R. Levin</B> (<I>Washington</I>) represents clients nationwide in Department of Labor,  IRS,  and PBGC audits,  and litigates on a wide range of ERISA issues,  including fiduciary breaches,  service provider malpractice,  and prohibited transactions.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Andrew R. McCorkle</B> (<I>Washington</I>) represents clients across the country with litigation and design issues involving qualified and nonqualified pension plans and health and welfare plans.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael A. Vanic</B> (<I>Los Angeles</I>) has been engaged in ERISA litigation for approximately 15 years,  representing plan sponsors,  fiduciaries,  and service providers in a wide range of ERISA claims including fiduciary breach,  denial of benefits,  and service provider malpractice.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Lynn B. Witte</B> (<I>Los Angeles</I>) represents clients in all aspects of employee benefits matters,  including counseling,  IRS and Department of Labor audits and litigation of fiduciary liability,  and bankruptcy issues affecting qualified plans. She is the author of several articles on protection of retirement benefits in bankruptcy following <I>Patterson </I>v. <I>Shumate</I>.<BR><BR>


</UL></BODY>
