<P>
<P>
<P><B>A</B>pproximately 20 lawyers practice ERISA and employee benefits law at Seyfarth,  Shaw,  Fairweather  & Geraldson. We assist employers in all aspects of employee benefits matters,  including tax-qualified retirement plans,  employee stock ownership plans,  executive compensation and incentive arrangements,  welfare benefit plans,  collectively bargained and multiemployer plans,  and the full range of employee benefits litigation issues.
<P><BR><P>In the area of tax-qualified retirement plans,  we assist in all phases of the plan's adoption and administration,  including plan design,  drafting,  tax qualification,  plan terminations and mergers,  and employee communications. With respect to welfare benefit plans,  we provide advice regarding health,  life insurance,  disability,  dependent care,  and other types of welfare benefit plans. We assist in plan adoption and administration,  plan design,  and the negotiation of insurance contracts and third-party administration agreements. We have extensive experience in designing and implementing severance programs,  including voluntary and involuntary reductions in force.<BR><P>Seyfarth Shaw attorneys work closely with clients regarding collectively bargained benefits and multiemployer plans for union-represented employees,  including negotiating employee benefits packages as part of collective bargaining agreements and in the context of plant shutdowns and reductions in force. The employee benefits practice works closely with the corporate,  securities,  tax,  labor,  litigation,  and estate planning groups,  as necessary,  in matters of executive compensation and incentive arrangements. We assist clients with nonqualified supplemental retirement plans,  deferred compensation arrangements,  golden and tin parachute agreements,  executive separation agreements,  and cash- and stock-based short- and long-term incentive programs.<BR>
<BR><P>We represent clients in all aspects of employee benefits,  pension,  and welfare benefits litigation,  including retirement plan terminations and reversions of excess retirement plan assets,  the reduction or elimination of retiree welfare benefits,  breach of fiduciary duty and conflicts of interest in administering retirement and welfare plans and managing plan assets,  oral misrepresentations,  bankruptcy,  and discrimination.<BR>
<BR><P>Seyfarth Shaw represents a large number of public sector and tax-exempt employers. We act as special counsel to boards of trustees of various police and firefighters pension funds. We assist in benefit claims and fiduciary matters and the design and implementation of Internal Revenue Code Section 403(b) tax-deferred annuity programs and Section 457 unfunded deferred compensation plans.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Eugene Jacobs</B> (<I>Chicago</I>) is the chair of the employee benefits group and has practiced employee benefits law since the passage of ERISA in 1974. He has extensive experience in structuring voluntary and involuntary reduction-in-force programs,  negotiating collectively bargained retirement and welfare plans,  and representing employers in multiemployer pension plan withdrawal liability disputes and retiree welfare benefits matters. He also serves as a professional management trustee on Taft-Hartley pension and welfare funds.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Howard J. Levine </B>(<I>Chicago</I>) has a broad general practice in tax-qualified retirement plans and extensive experience in executive compensation matters,  employee stock ownership plans,  and the employee benefits aspects of corporate acquisitions and divestitures.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Fredric S. Singerman</B> (<I>Washington</I>) practices employee benefits law and ERISA law with particular experience in all aspects of qualified retirement plans,  executive compensation,  and ERISA litigation and employee benefits issues in bankruptcy and receivership contexts.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Mitchel D. Whitehead</B> (<I>Los Angeles</I>) is head of the benefits practice in Los Angeles,  and has had a broad range of experience in all aspects of qualified retirement plans and welfare benefit plans since 1978. Mr. Whitehead has extensive experience in the representation of large Taft-Hartley pension and welfare funds,  and is currently counsel for several such funds.<BR>
<BR>
