imination,  prohibited transaction,  and `plan asset' issues. A significant part of our practice involves counseling venture capital,  leveraged buyout,  and other investment firms; their advisors; and employee benefit plan investors in light of these complex and technical regulations.<BR><BR><UL><BR><LI><B>Joseph A. Hugg</B> Mr. Hugg chairs the firm's ERISA group and is co-chair of the tax group. He has substantial experience in dealing with plan asset and fiduciary issues arising from investments in venture capital and other private investment funds. In addition,  Mr. Hugg advises investment managers and other plan fiduciaries regarding the tax and ERISA aspects of their investment activities.<BR><BR><LI><B>Jason Berger</B> Mr. Berger chairs the firm's labor and employment group and is an experienced litigator and labor negotiator. Mr. Berger handles ERISA audit and litigation matters,  involving severance,  retiree health,  diversification of 401(k) plan investments,  continuation of benefits under COBRA,  and ERISA pre-emption. He has litigated numerous cases in the appellate courts,  including oral argument of an ERISA case before the U.S. Supreme Court.<BR><BR><LI><B>Jin-Kyung (Kay) Kim</B> Ms. Kim practices in both the labor and employment and ERISA groups. She advises businesses on a range of employment-related concerns,  including qualified and nonqualified retirement plans,  welfare benefit plans,  compliance under COBRA and ERISA,  discrimination law,  employment agreements,  and corporate acquisitions. <BR><BR><LI><B>Kimberly M. Collins</B> Ms. Collins practices in the ERISA group. She has a broad range of experience relating to qualified and nonqualified retirement plans,  executive compensation arrangements,  and welfare benefit plans. Her practice includes drafting plans and advising plan sponsors and fiduciaries concerning compliance issues. She represents clients with respect to the Internal Revenue Service Voluntary Compliance Resolution (`VCR') program and counsels clients on ERISA fiduciary obligations and plan asset issues.<BR><BR></UL></UL></BODY></HTML>
