<HEAD>
<TITLE>Willkie Farr  & Gallagher
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>ERISA</H2>
<H3>Willkie Farr  & Gallagher
</H3>

</CENTER>
<B><CENTER>New York:</B> One Citicorp Center,  153 East 53rd Street,  New York,  NY 10022<BR>
Tel 212-821-8000  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-821-1555<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Washington,  D.C.,  Paris,  London<BR>
<BR>
350 lawyers  <B>*</B>  9 lawyers in Employee Benefits and Employee Relations Group<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/willkie.html"> Corporate Securities</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/willkie.html"> White Collar Crime</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>W</B>illkie Farr  & Gallagher,  founded in 1888,  is a full-service law firm. The firm engages in the general practice of law,  including the corporate and financial services,  bankruptcy and business reorganizations,  employee benefits and employee relations,  environmental,  intellectual property,  international trade,  legislative and governmental relations,  litigation,  real estate,  tax,  telecommunications,  and trusts and estates fields.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>The Employee Benefits and Employee Relations Group</H3></CENTER>

<P>The Employee Benefits and Employee Relations Group seeks to provide coordinated,  one-stop advice on substantially all federal laws related to employee benefits and employee relations. We regularly negotiate senior executive employment and severance packages,  representing executives as well as public and private corporations and board compensation committees.<BR><P>Through the firm's financial services practice,  we have broad experience with pension plan investments and complex fiduciary matters and with the negotiation of insurance and other funding arrangements for qualified and nonqualified employee plans. We have devised novel strategies for the creation of new types of investment funds for employee benefit plan assets,  and we regularly seek prohibited transaction exemptions and advisory opinions from the Department of Labor.<BR>
<BR><P>We design and draft qualified plans,  medical and other welfare benefit plans,  and executive compensation arrangements,  along with top-hat plans,  insurance-funded deferred compensation arrangements,  and stock option and other equity-based incentive compensation plans. We help resolve routine and complex administrative problems and assist with employee communications,  regulatory compliance,  and government agency audits.<BR>
<BR><P>We advise public and private corporations of all sizes on U.S. and international benefits issues,  such as identification and allocation of liability in acquisition and divestiture transactions,  reductions in force,  response to FAS 106 and IRC Section 162(m),  COBRA,  WARN,  financial product development,  and venture capital fund formation. We are familiar with the design of U.S. compensation arrangements for executives of foreign corporations and,  through our representation of defense contractors,  with the retirement plan aspects of government contracts.<BR>
<BR><P>We have extensive experience with Employee Stock Ownership Plans. We have been directly involved with the structuring of many ESOP-based corporate transactions,  have represented institutional lenders in over $4 billion of ESOP loan transactions,  and have advised many ESOP fiduciaries regarding their responsibilities under ERISA.<BR>
<BR><P>We have experience with all of the employee issues that arise in bankruptcy reorganizations,  including distress terminations of pension plans,  and Section 1113 and 1114 issues involving modification and termination of collective bargaining agreements and modification of retiree health and welfare benefit arrangements. We develop severance,  `stay bonus, ' and post-confirmation compensation arrangements to encourage retention of key management personnel. We also negotiate settlements with the PBGC concerning the treatment of underfunded pension plans in bankruptcy restructurings by businesses under common control.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Stephen T. Lindo</B> is head of the employee benefits practice group and has broad experience with executive compensation,  senior executive employment and severance arrangements,  merger and acquisition and bankruptcy-related employee benefits issues,  and qualified and nonqualified employee benefit plans in general. He is currently co-chairman of the New York State Bar Association,  Tax Section,  Committee on Qualified Plans and was formerly co-chairman of the Committee on Non-Qualified Employee Benefits from 1991 through 1994. Princeton University,  A.B.,  1969; Boston University,  J.D.,  1974; New York University,  LL.M.,  taxation,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael J. Segal</B> specializes in a broad range of employee benefits matters,  with particular focus on corporate transactions,  ESOP leveraged buyouts and restructurings,  and stock- and cash-based executive compensation. He is a member of the American Bar Association's Committee on Executive Compensation,  and its Committee on Employee Benefits Administration and Litigation (Section of Real Property,  Probate,  and Trust Law). Ohio State University,  B.S.,  1980,  J.D.,  1983.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert J. Kheel </B>specializes in labor and employment law litigation,  regularly representing,  among others,  professional sports organizations. Cornell University,  B.A.,  1965; London School of Economics and Political Science,  M.Sc.,  1966; University of Michigan,  J.D.,  1969.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


