<HEAD>
<TITLE>Winthrop,  Stimson,  Putnam  & Roberts
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>ERISA</H2>
<H3>Winthrop,  Stimson,  Putnam  & Roberts
</H3>

</CENTER>
<B><CENTER>New York:</B> One Battery Park Plaza,  New York,  NY 10004<BR>
Tel 212-858-1000  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-858-1500<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> 1133 Connecticut Avenue,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20036<BR>
Tel 202-775-9800  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-833-8491<BR>
<BR>
250 lawyers  <B>*</B>  8 lawyers in the Employee Benefits Practice Group<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profile in the following other directory:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/winthrop.html"> Workout</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>W</B>inthrop,  Stimson,  Putnam  & Roberts has approximately 250 lawyers with eight lawyers concentrating in employee benefits. In addition to our principal office in New York City,  we have domestic offices in Washington,  D.C.; Stamford,  Connecticut; and Palm Beach,  Florida; and international offices in London,  Brussels,  Tokyo,  and Hong Kong.
<P><BR><P><I>General Benefits Advice</I> Winthrop,  Stimson's employee benefits lawyers advise clients on a wide variety of employee benefits matters,  including the benefits implications of acquisitions and lending transactions,  qualified plans,  employee stock ownership plans,  executive compensation,  corporate transactions,  litigation,  and legislative and public affairs.<BR><P><I>ERISA Fiduciary Counseling</I> The Firm's lawyers advise trustees and investment managers on fiduciary matters,  the tax and ERISA implications of proposed investments,  and fiduciary issues that can arise in the representation of ESOP trustees. ERISA actions,  both for benefits and for fiduciary violations,  have increased steadily. Winthrop,  Stimson lawyers have addressed some of the most important issues arising under ERISA.<BR>
<BR><P><I>Executive Compensation</I> Winthrop,  Stimson regularly counsels companies and executives regarding the tax and securities law implications of various funded and unfunded deferred compensation plans,  as well as the implementation of stock-based compensation arrangements,  including stock option plans,  restricted stock plans,  stock purchase plans,  and phantom stock plans.<BR>
<BR><P><I>Legislative Affairs</I> Winthrop,  Stimson also acts in legislative affairs on behalf of both corporate clients and trade organizations,  as well as advising legislative and regulatory staff on technical and policy issues. The firm's benefit lawyers and its director of health legislative affairs consult with coalitions to address issues of current concern and significance,  such as national health care and retiree benefit issues.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Experience and Clients</H3></CENTER>

<P><BR><BR>
Recent matters include:<BR><UL><P><LI> implementation of qualified and nonqualified plans after corporate restructuring;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> a variety of ESOP issues including implementation of ESOPs and acting as trustee counsel in ESOP transactions;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> advice and assistance in the termination or renegotiation of employment contracts containing golden parachute and other takeover-related strategies; <BR>
<BR><P><LI> advice on implementation of global equity plans for multinational employers and arrangements for expatriate and third-country nationals;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> serves as ERISA counsel in various litigations on breach of fiduciary duty and benefit claims; and<BR>
<BR><P><LI> advice on retiree health plan changes under ERISA.<BR></UL>
<BR><BR><P>Representative clients include: BASF Corporation,  Bristol-Myers Squibb Company,  Baltimore Gas  & Electric Co.,  General Re Corporation,  and Stone  & Webster,  Inc.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Susan P. Serota</B> (<I>New York; 212-858-1125</I>) Partner in charge,  Employee Benefits Practice Group. Primary focus on various aspects of plan design,  regulatory compliance,  fiduciary duties,  executive compensation,  and plan investment issues. Chair,  ABA Tax Section Committee on Employee Benefits,  1992-1993; chair,  ABA Joint Committee on Employee Benefits,  1988-1989; member,  ABA Working Group on Health Care Reform,  1992- ; co-chair,  International Pension and Employee Benefits Lawyers Association,  1993. New York University School of Law,  J.D.,  1971.<BR>
<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Peter J. Hunt </B>(<I>New York; 212-858-1139</I>) Partner. Advises employers and financial institutions on fiduciary and compliance issues under ERISA and the Internal Revenue Code and on the employee benefits aspects of corporate acquisitions and dispositions. Chair,  Subcommittee on Technical Correction of the ABA Section of Taxation Employee Benefits Committee. New York University,  J.D.,  1984.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Leo T. Crowley</B> (<I>New York; 212-858-1740</I>) Partner. Primarily engaged in litigation,  employment,  and health care-related matters. Litigation practice focuses on representation of employers in employment and employee benefits litigation. Member,  Health Care Law Committee of the Association of the Bar of the City of New York,  1989- ; columnist,  <I>New York Law Journal</I>. Boston University,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1980; note editor,  <I>Boston University Law Review</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>G. Lawrence Atkins</B> (<I>Washington; 202-775-9818</I>) A non-attorney. Director of health legislative affairs and senior consultant on public policy issues involving employee benefits,  health care,  and legislative and regulatory representation. Primary focus is on health care reform and corporate health benefit plans,  private pension policy,  and congressional and federal agency representation. Member,  Advisory Council on Social Security,  1991; Republican staff director,  U.S. Senate Special Committee on Aging,  1987-1989. University of Kentucky,  M.A. 1971; University of Louisville,  M.S.,  1975; Brandeis University,  Heller School,  Ph.D.,  1985.<BR>
<BR>
</UL><BR>


</UL></BODY>
