<HEAD>
<TITLE>Arter  & Hadden
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Arter  & Hadden
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington:</B> 1801 K Street,  N.W.,  Suite 400,  Washington,  DC 20009<BR>
Tel 202-775-7100  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-857-0172<BR>
<BR>
350 lawyers  <B>*</B>  30 lawyers in the Intellectual Property Practice Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>F</B>ounded in 1843,  Arter  & Hadden is a national law firm with offices in Cleveland,  Columbus,  Dallas,  San Antonio,  Austin,  Washington,  D.C.,  Los Angeles,  San Diego,  San Francisco,  and Irvine,  California. The firm is comprised of more than 350 attorneys.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Overview of Practice Area</H3></CENTER>

<P><BR><P>Our Intellectual Property Practice Group consists of approximately 30 attorneys. Our Practice Group is headed up by James L. Bikoff,  who has over 25 years of experience in assisting clients in the protection and enforcement of their intellectual property rights.<BR><P>The firm formulates,  implements,  and supervises U.S. and worldwide intellectual property protection,  counseling,  and enforcement for numerous companies.<BR>
<BR><P>Our clients include Fortune 500 companies,  companies in the high-tech computer industry,  owners of famous brands of luxury goods,  sporting goods companies,  universities,  entertainment companies,  chemical and pharmaceutical companies,  and service businesses such as hospitals,  banks,  and insurance companies.<BR>
<BR><P>The firm's intellectual property specialists provide service to clients in three primary areas. First,  we protect and monitor intellectual property rights commencing at the beginning of the process,  i.e.,  when a client is selecting a trademark,  registering a copyright,  or exploring the possibility of patent protection. The Intellectual Property and Technology Group has extensive experience in prosecuting applications for registration at the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office and the U.S. Copyright Office.<BR>
<BR><P>Second,  we counsel clients on the most effective international marketing and licensing of their intellectual property rights.<BR>
<BR><P>Third,  we develop and implement comprehensive enforcement strategies to protect clients' intellectual property rights against infringement,  including trademark counterfeiting,  patent infringement,  and copyright piracy. Through a worldwide network of experienced investigators and associate counsel,  we quantify infringement problems and formulate strategies to deal with them most effectively.<BR>
<BR><P>In the United States,  our enforcement programs encompass civil,  criminal,  and administrative remedies. We have substantial expertise in litigating infringement actions and at securing <I>ex parte</I> temporary restraining and seizure orders.<BR>
<BR><P>The Intellectual Property and Technology Group also works closely with the U.S. Customs Service to assist clients in preventing importation into the United States of products bearing recorded trademarks and copyrights.<BR>
<BR><P>In dealing with infringement matters outside the United States,  our attorneys regularly consult with the Office of the United States Trade Representative and other U.S. and foreign government agencies.<BR>
<BR><P>The partners in the Intellectual Property Practice Group include:<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>James L. Bikoff</B> (<I>Washington</I>) is chairman of the firm's Intellectual Property and Technology Practice Group. He has over 25 years' experience directing worldwide protection and enforcement programs for clients such as Nintendo of America,  Fisher-Price,  the U.S. Olympic Committee,  and World Cup Soccer.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Roger P. Furey</B> (<I>Washington</I>) counsels clients regarding selection and protection of trademarks,  trade dress,  trade names,  trade secrets,  and copyrights,  and litigates and provides advice on advertising law and unfair competition.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>R. Lewis Gable</B> (<I>Washington</I>) advises clients in the areas of patents,  software and hardware and complex electronic technology. He prepares and prosecutes patent applications before the U.S. and foreign patent and trademark offices.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Mary Jane Saunders</B> (<I>Washington</I>) has expertise in computer law,  copyright,  trademark,  unfair competition,  licensing,  litigation,  and government relations matters. She represents several major software companies.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David I. Wilson</B> (<I>Washington</I>) primarily concentrates in international intellectual property counseling. He has extensive involvement in Special 301 investigations and U.S. Customs Service enforcement matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Thomas J. O'Connor,  Jr.</B> (<I>Columbus</I>) handles domestic and foreign patent applications and litigation. He has defended and prosecuted patent infringement cases involving biotechnology,  computer hardware,  and microelectronics.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Arthur Boos</B> (<I>Dallas</I>) counsels clients on licensing trademarks and computer software. He represents a major licensor of trademark rights.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Dennis McAteer</B> (<I>San Francisco</I>) handles patent,  trademark,  and copyright litigation.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Bart L. Kessel</B> (<I>Los Angeles</I>) handles patent,  trademark,  and copyright litigation.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Henry G. Kohlmann</B> (<I>Irvine</I>) prosecutes patents and trademark matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Stephen J. LaCount</B> (<I>Irvine</I>) handles corporate and business transactions,  technology protection,  development,  licensing and manufacturing arrangements,  and global product distribution.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
