<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Baker Donelson Bearman & Caldwell
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Memphis:</B> Twentieth Floor,  First Tennessee Building,  165 Madison Avenue, <BR>
Memphis,  TN 38103<BR>
Tel 901-526-2000  <B>*</B>  Fax 901-577-2303<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Chattanooga,  Johnson City,  Knoxville,  Nashville,  Washington,  D.C.<BR>
<BR>
200 lawyers  <B>*</B>  12 lawyers in Intellectual Property Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>T</B>he Intellectual Property Group regularly practices before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office in patent prosecution and trademark registration matters and before the Register of Copyright in copyright registration proceedings. The Group handles a wide variety of both domestic and international intellectual property matters,  including computer software and computer technology,  licensing,  and technology transfer. Members of the group also handle franchising,  antitrust,  and other trade regulation matters,  as well as all types of intellectual property litigation including representation before the International Trade Commission.<BR><BR><UL><LI><B>Grady M. Garrison</B> (<I>Memphis</I>) Partner. Mr. Garrison is chair of the Intellectu-al Property Group. His practice is concentrated in franchising,  trademark,  copyright,  and antitrust law. He is a member of the ABA Forum Committee on Franchising. He is president of the Memphis Area Franchise Association. Vanderbilt University,  B.A.,  1967; Memphis State University,  J.D.,  1972; New York University,  LL.M.,  trade regulation,  1977; Phi Eta Sigma; Phi Beta Kappa. Admitted in Tennessee,  1972.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Thomas O. Helton</B> (<I>Chattanooga</I>) Partner. Mr. Helton served as lead trial counsel in one of the largest patent jury cases ever tried in the Southeast and was successful in obtaining favorable verdicts on all patent issues as well as one of the few verdicts ever obtained finding antitrust liability in the patent context. University of Tennessee,  B.S.,  1963; Vanderbilt University,  LL.B.,  1966; associate editor,  <I>Vanderbilt University Law Review</I>,  1965-1966. Admitted in Tennessee,  1966; and Georgia,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James L. McElroy</B> (<I>Nashville</I>) Partner. Mr. McElroy's corporate practice includes representation of companies in the computer hardware and software industries in acquisitions,  licensing,  trade secret protection,  and related areas. Rhodes College,  B.A.,  with honors,  1969; Phi Beta Kappa; State University of New York,  Ph.D.,  history,  1974; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude,  </I>1980.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Scott K. Haight </B>(<I>Memphis</I>) Partner. Mr. Haight concentrates his practice on trademark,  licensing,  and computer software matters. Mr. Haight was instrumental in obtaining passage by the Tennessee House in 1993 of the revised Model State Trademark Bill. Davidson College,  B.A.,  1983; Emory University School of Law,  J.D.,  1986; managing editor,  <I>Emory Journal of International Dispute Resolution</I>; Phi Delta Phi. Admitted in Tennessee,  1986.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Steven J. Eisen</B> (<I>Nashville</I>) Partner. Mr. Eisen has experience in copyright and trademark matters. Vanderbilt University,  B.A.,  1979,  M.B.A.,  1983; Vanderbilt University School of Law,  J.D.,  1983. Admitted in Tennessee,  1983.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Charles G. Walker </B>(<I>Memphis</I>) Partner. Mr. Walker's litigation practice includes experience in patent,  trademark,  and copyright infringement matters. Southeastern Louisiana University,  B.A.,  1973; Loyola University,  J.D.,  1978. Admitted in Louisiana,  1978; and Tennessee,  1986.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Stephen E. Roth </B>(<I>Knoxville</I>) Partner. Mr. Roth's litigation practice includes trademark and unfair competition matters. University of Tennessee,  B.A.,  1982; J.D.,  1986; member,  National Moot Court Team and Moot Court Board; member,  <I>Tennessee Law Review,  </I>1985-1986 (author,  `<I>Firefighters Local Union 1784</I> v. <I>Stotts</I>, ' 52 <I>Tenn. L. Rev.</I> 489); Order of the Coif; Phi Beta Kappa; Phi Kappa Phi; Phi Alpha Delta. Admitted in Tennessee,  1986.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Deborah S. Humble</B> (<I>Chattanooga</I>) Associate. Ms. Humble concentrates her practice on chemical and biotechnology patent prosecution matters. University of Memphis,  B.S.,  biology,  1974,  J.D.,  1981. Admitted in Tennessee,  1981; Virginia,  1982; and District of Columbia,  1984.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Micheline Johnson</B> (<I>Chattanooga</I>) Associate. Ms. Johnson concentrates her practice on chemical and mechanical patent prosecution matters. Spring Hill College,  B.S.,  1982; Vanderbilt University,  M.B.A.,  1986; Vanderbilt University School of Law,  J.D.,  1986. Admitted in Georgia,  1986; and Tennessee,  1989.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Charles F. Morrow </B>(<I>Memphis</I>) Associate. Mr. Morrow has litigation experience in the areas of trademark and copyright. University of Louisville School of Law,  J.D.,  1989; Dean's List scholar. Admitted in Tennessee,  1979.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Hollie A. Smith </B>(<I>Memphis</I>) Associate. Ms. Smith has experience in copyright,  trademark,  and unfair competition matters. University of Arkansas,  B.S.,  1985; J.D.,  1991; Dean's List scholar. Admitted in Tennessee,  1991.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Brian S. Welborn</B> (<I>Memphis</I>) Associate. Mr. Welborn concentrates his practice primarily on mechanical and electrical patent prosecution and patent-related matters. Texas A &M University,  B.S.,  aerospace engineering,  1984; University of Tulsa,  J.D.,  1991. Admitted in Texas,  1993; and Alabama,  1993.<BR>
