<TITLE>Bradley,  Arant,  Rose & White
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Bradley,  Arant,  Rose & White
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Birmingham:</B> 2001 Park Place,  Suite 1400,  Birmingham,  AL 35203<BR>
Tel 205-521-8000  <B>*</B>  Fax 205-252-0264<BR>
<B>Huntsville:</B> 200 Clinton Avenue West,  Suite 600,  Huntsville,  AL 35801<BR>
Tel 205-517-5100  <B>*</B>  Fax 205-533-5069<BR>
<BR>
130 lawyers  <B>*</B>  6 lawyers in intellectual property<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>B</B>radley,  Arant is the only large general practice firm in Alabama which offers a full range of services in the intellectual property field and in the related fields of unfair competition and business torts. In a survey of in-house counsel sponsored by <I>The American Lawyer's Corporate Counsel Magazine</I>,  Bradley,  Arant,  Rose  & White was named one of the best firms in the United States in the areas of intellectual property and litigation. Bradley,  Arant is broadly represented in <I>The Best Lawyers in America</I>,  with 36 listings in the Alabama section of the 1995-1996 edition. Two members of the firm are listed in the intellectual property law section of that book,  of three total entries for Alabama IP attorneys.
<P><BR><P>The firm regularly litigates cases involving trademarks,  copyrights,  patents,  trade secrets,  tortious interference with business relationships,  breach of fiduciary duties,  design piracy,  and 43(a) of the Lanham Act. Three of the firm's lawyers are registered patent attorneys. We have litigated many landmark IP cases in Alabama,  including <I>Ramada Inns,  Inc. </I>v.<I> Gadsden Motel Co.</I>; <I>Pizitz,  Inc. </I>v.<I> Pizitz Mercantile Co.</I>; <I>L.A. Draper  & Son,  Inc. </I>v.<I> Wheelabrator-Frye,  Inc.</I>; <I>Jefferson Home Furniture Co. </I>v.<I> Jefferson Furniture Co.</I>; and <I>Arthur Young,  Inc. </I>v.<I> Arthur Young  & Co</I>. We also regularly advise on transactional issues arising out of the development,  acquisition,  and exploitation of intellectual property.<BR><P>The firm's trademark lawyers work closely with clients in the selection,  adoption,  and protection of their trademarks. We have extensive experience in securing trademark registrations in the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  in the various states,  and throughout the world. We have successfully prosecuted and defended numerous <I>inter partes</I> proceedings before the TTAB. The firm prepared the Alabama chapter for the INTA reference book <I>State Trademark and Unfair Competition Law</I>,  and updates the chapter annually.<BR>
<BR><P>Representative intellectual property clients include Russell Corporation,  Amerex,  SouthTrust Corporation,  ASCAP,  VuLCan Materials Corporation,  and Auburn University.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Thad G. Long</B> (<I>205-521-8259; tgl@barw.com</I>) Mr. Long represents clients in all matters relating to intellectual property,  with an emphasis on patent and trademark litigation and prosecution. He also undertakes antitrust and product liability litigation. A registered patent attorney,  Mr. Long also serves on the editorial board of <I>The Trademark Reporter</I> and is adjunct professor of law at the University of Alabama. Mr. Long is one of the drafters of the Alabama Trade Secrets Act and the Alabama Trademark Act. He is co-author of <I>Protecting Your Intellectual Property Under Alabama Law</I> (Cambridge Institute 1988,  rev. 1989,  1990,  1991); and <I>Unfair Business Practices Under Alabama Law</I> (Cambridge Institute 1989,  rev. 1990). Member: American Bar Association (Intellectual Property Law and Antitrust Sections); Alabama State Bar (chairman,  Antitrust Section,  1973-1974). Columbia University,  A.B.,  physics,  1960; University of Virginia,  J.D.,  1963. Order of the Coif; Omicron Delta Kappa; member,  <I>Virginia Law Review</I>,  1962-1963.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Linda Friedman</B> (<I>205-521-8274; laf@barw.com</I>) Mrs. Friedman's practice includes trademarks,  copyright,  marketing and distribution,  antitrust,  and business torts. She is a frequent lecturer on intellectual property and distribution issues. Mrs. Friedman is co-author of <I>Unfair Business Practices Under Alabama Law</I> (Cambridge Institute,  1989,  rev. 1990) and <I>Protecting Your Intellectual Property Under Alabama Law</I> (Cambridge Institute,  1988,  rev. 1989,  1990,  1991). She served as a law clerk to Judge Sam C. Pointer,  Jr.,  Northern District of Alabama,  1976-1977. Mrs. Friedman was elected to the Alabama Board of Bar Examiners,  serving in 1988 and 1989,  and to the American Law Institute in 1992. Member: American Bar Association (Intellectual Property Law,  Antitrust,  and Litigation Sections); Alabama State Bar (chair,  Antitrust and Business Torts Section,  1989- 1990). Kenyon College,  A.B.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1973; Vanderbilt University,  J.D.,  1976; Phi Beta Kappa; member,  <I>Vanderbilt Law Review</I>,  1975-1976.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>J. David Pugh</B> (<I>205-521-8314; jdp@barw.com</I>) Mr. Pugh,  a registered patent attorney,  practices in the areas of patent prosecution,  litigation,  and construction law. He is the co-author of `Enforcing Arbitration Agreements in Alabama: A Double Standard Dilemma, ' 54 <I>The Alabama Lawyer</I> 38 (1993). Member: American Bar Association; American Society of Civil Engineers. University of Alabama,  B.S.,  1984; Vanderbilt University,  J.D.,  1988.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Michael S. Denniston</B> (<I>205-521-8244; msd@barw.com</I>) Mr. Denniston practices in the areas of trademark,  copyright,  unfair competition,  licensing,  and antitrust law. Member: American Bar Association (Intellectual Property Law and Antitrust Sections). University of Virginia,  B.A.,  1986,  J.D.,  1989; Order of the Coif.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Kevin J. Henderson</B> (<I>205-521-8346; kjh@barw.com</I>) Mr. Henderson advises clients on the licensing of computer software. He served as law clerk to Judge William W. Wilkins,  Jr.,  U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit,  1989-1990. Member: American Bar Association. Clemson University,  B.S. 1985; Washington  & Lee University,  J.D. 1989.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>John W. Smith T</B> (<I>205-521-8521; jst@barw.com</I>) Mr. Smith T is a registered patent attorney,  who also practices in general litigation. Member: American Bar Association. Northwestern University,  B.S.,  nuclear engineering,  1987; University of Alabama Law School,  J.D. 1992; member,  <I>Alabama Law Review</I>,  1991-1992. Jessup International Moot Court Team.<BR>
