<HEAD>
<TITLE>Burns,  Doane,  Swecker & Mathis
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Burns,  Doane,  Swecker & Mathis
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Alexandria:</B> 699 Prince Street,  Alexandria,  VA 22314<BR>
Tel 703-836-6620  <B>*</B>  Fax 703-836-2021  <B>*</B>  E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:carolv@burnsdoane.com">carolv@burnsdoane.com</A><BR>
<B>Menlo Park: </B>3000 Sand Hill Road,  Building 4,  Suite 160,  Menlo Park,  CA 94025<BR>
Tel 415-854-7400  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-854-8275<BR>
<B>Raleigh/Durham:</B> P.O. Box 14846,  Research Triangle Park,  NC 27709-4846<BR>
Tel 919-941-9240<BR>
<BR>
60 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers practicing intellectual property law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>B</B>urns,  Doane,  Swecker  & Mathis is a national intellectual property law firm with offices in the Washington,  D.C.,  San Francisco and Raleigh/Durham,  North Carolina areas. The firm represents domestic and foreign corporations,  as well as private inventors,  in all areas of intellectual property law,  including:
<UL><BR>
<BR><P><LI> Patent infringement,  trade secret,  and trademark litigation in U.S. federal courts and the International Trade Commission (ITC)<BR><P><LI> Alternative dispute resolutions<BR>
<BR><P><LI> Patent application preparation and prosecution in all technologies<BR>
<BR><P><LI> Patent interference practice<BR>
<BR><P><LI> Trademark registrations,  oppositions,  and cancellations<BR>
<BR><P><LI> Copyright registrations including protection for maskworks<BR>
<BR><P><LI> Trade secret practice<BR>
<BR><P><LI> National and international licensing matters<BR>
<BR><P><LI> Unfair competition and antitrust matters<BR>
<BR></UL><P>The firm dates back to the 1920s,  and over the years has grown steadily to become one of the largest national firms concentrated in the practice of intellectual property law. The firm is dedicated to maintaining high-quality legal services at a reasonable cost,  without sacrificing the personal approach we have found to be effective in meeting client expectations.<BR>
<BR><P>In 1977,  the firm moved to its present location in the Old Town section of Alexandria,  Virginia,  and is conveniently located within minutes of National Airport,  the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  and Washington,  D.C. In 1981,  the firm opened its West Coast office in Silicon Valley and,  in 1995,  the office in Research Triangle Park,  North Carolina.<BR>
<BR><UL>
<LI><B>William L. Mathis</B> is an experienced counselor and arbitrator in patent and trademark matters. He is currently an adjunct professor of law at Georgetown University.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert S. Swecker</B> has special interest in Section 337 proceedings before the International Trade Commission. He is chairman of the International Trade Committee of the American Bar Association,  Intellectual Property Section.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Platon N. Mandros</B> has extensive experience in negotiating and drafting intellectual property licenses. He is currently vice-president of the Licensing Executives Society International and is past president of the Licensing Executives Society (U.S.A. and Canada).<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Benton S. Duffett,  Jr.</B> has special interest in plant patent protection pursuant to the Plant Patent Act and the general patent laws. He is active in the International Community of Breeders of Asexually Reproduced Ornamental and Fruit-Tree Varieties,  and lectures on protection of new plants in the U.S.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Norman H. Stepno</B> has extensive experience in intellectual property matters including licensing and litigation relating to pharmaceuticals,  biotechnology,  cosmetics,  agrichemicals,  polymers,  and industrial,  specialty,  and commodity chemicals,  both organic and inorganic.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Ronald L. Grudziecki</B> has extensive experience in litigation and licensing matters,  particularly relating to the materials area,  and is a trustee of the Licensing Executives Society (U.S.A. and Canada). He is also an adjunct professor of patent law at Georgetown University.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Frederick G. Michaud,  Jr. </B>is involved exclusively in litigation and intellectual property licensing,  and has represented both plaintiffs and defendants in resolving multimillion-dollar intellectual property disputes.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>R. Danny Huntington</B> has special interest in interference proceedings before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  particularly in matters relating to the chemistry and biotechnology arts.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James W. Peterson</B> has extensive experience in intellectual property matters,  including the application of material science to the electrical and mechanical arts.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert E. Krebs</B> was named as one of California's top patent lawyers in <I>California Lawyer</I> (March 1992),  and has extensive experience in technology licensing,  acquisitions,  and divestitures.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>T. Gene Dillahunty</B> is a frequent lecturer on intellectual property matters,  and has special interest in strategizing comprehensive intellectual property protection programs and procedures.<BR>
</UL>

</UL></BODY>
