<HEAD>
<TITLE>Collier,  Shannon,  Rill & Scott
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Collier,  Shannon,  Rill & Scott
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington:</B> 3050 K Street,  N.W.,  Suite 400,  Washington,  DC 20007<BR>
Tel 202-342-8400  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-338-5534  <B>*</B>  E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:Col1DC01.MHS@Compuserve.Com">Col1DC01.MHS@Compuserve.Com</A><BR>
<BR>
80 lawyers  <B>*</B>  4 lawyers in the Intellectual Property Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/collier.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/collier.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>C</B>ollier,  Shannon,  Rill  & Scott,  founded in 1963 in Washington,  D.C.,  today has approximately 80 lawyers. Intellectual Property is one of its primary areas of practice. The Firm's client base includes numerous Fortune 500 corporations,  small and mid-sized and entrepreneurial start-up companies,  and individual inventors,  engaged in a wide range of activities service providers; trade and professional associations; manufacturing; advertising; pharmaceuticals; chemical; finance; defense and government contractors; agriculture; food manufacture,  distribution,  and marketing; energy; and high-tech research and development.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>The Intellectual Property Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>Collier Shannon's Intellectual Property practice is nationwide in scope. We handle all types of intellectual property issues (patent,  trademark,  copyright,  trade secret,  and related licensing matters) in a wide variety of domestic and international settings and,  in particular,  where international or trade regulation issues are also involved.<BR><P>We represent clients before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office in connection with patent and trademark applications,  reexaminations,  reissues,  appeals,  petitions to the Commissioner,  and recording marks with the U.S. Customs Service.<BR>
<BR><P>We also represent clients before numerous U.S. district courts,  U.S. courts of appeals,  the U.S. Supreme Court,  and the International Trade Commission in connection with patent,  trademark,  copyright,  and/or related unfair competition and antitrust claims.<BR>
<BR><P>We encourage our clients to approach their intellectual property assets strategically. We attempt to resolve our clients' intellectual property needs effectively and efficiently,  avoiding litigation whenever possible. If litigation becomes necessary,  we provide the caliber,  depth,  and breadth of litigation resources that only a general practice firm can provide. We have been involved in some of the ground-breaking property issues,  including one of the first litigated cases involving the Grandfather Clause of the Process Patent Amendments Act of 1987,  and a leading case involving the <I>Noerr-Pennington</I> exception to the antitrust laws in the context of copyright infringement claim.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Representative Clients and Experience</H3></CENTER>

<P>ActMedia,  Inc.,  Adroit Systems,  Inc.,  Allegheny Ludlum Steel Corporation,  Electronic Retailing Systems,  Food Marketing Institute,  Mobil Oil Corporation,  National Association of Convenience Stores,  National Broiler Council,  National Electrical Manufacturers Association,  Shoppervision,  Inc.,  and Society for Human Resource Management.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Firm Attorneys</H3></CENTER>
<UL><LI><B>Patrick J. Coyne</B> (<I>202-342-8606</I>) is the head of the Section and specializes in intellectual property and related commercial litigation. He clerked for Judge Edward S. Smith of the U.S Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit (1982-1984) and is a registered patent attorney. He has been responsible for significant victories on behalf of: Allegheny Ludlum; Mobil Oil Corporation and Mobil Chemical Company; and Ovonic Battery Company. He argued the U.S. Supreme Court appeal in <I>Professional Real Estate Investors </I>v.<I> Columbia Pictures</I> in 1992. Mr. Coyne graduated from the University of Virginia Law School in 1982.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>John B. Williams</B> (<I>202-342-8435</I>) has focused his litigation practice on matters involving antitrust and intellectual property. He has represented both plaintiffs and defendants and won several substantial judgments in jury cases. Most recently,  he successfully defended Mobil Chemical Corporation in a jury trial patent infringement case. Mr. Williams graduated from Catholic University,  Columbus School of Law in 1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Sean L. Collin</B> (<I>202-342-8822</I>) specializes in international intellectual property matters and,  in particular,  in developing effective methods to expand our clients' activities overseas. He graduated from Otago Law School in New Zealand in 1988. Mr. Collin recently received a master's degree in international law from Georgetown University. Admitted in New York,  the United Kingdom,  Australia,  and New Zealand.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Diana E. Stein</B> (<I>202-342-8553</I>) specializes in intellectual property and general civil litigation. She has had significant responsibility in numerous patent infringement cases,  both in the U.S. district courts and before the International Trade Commission. Ms. Stein graduated from American University,  Washington College of Law in 1988.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Edward V. Charbonneau</B> (<I>202-342-8461</I>) specializes in patent prosecution and litigation and is a registered patent attorney. Mr. Charbonneau graduated from Southwestern University School of Law in 1989.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Christopher A. Gallo</B> (<I>202-342-8616</I>) specializes in patent prosecution and litigation,  worked as a patent examiner for five years,  and is a registered patent attorney. Mr. Gallo graduated from Catholic University,  Columbus School of Law in 1994.<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
