<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Covington  & Burling
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Covington  & Burling
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington:</B> 1201 Pennsylvania Avenue,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20004<BR>
Tel 202-662-6000  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-662-6291<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Brussels,  London<BR>
<BR>
300 lawyers  <B>*</B>  35 lawyers practice intellectual property  & licensing law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/covington.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/covington.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>C</B>ovington  & Burling represents businesses and individuals in regulatory and legislative matters,  litigation,  and transactional work throughout the United States and abroad. The practice of the Firm's intellectual property and licensing group spans the full range of patent,  trademark,  copyright,  trade dress,  false advertising,  unfair competition,  business tort,  and licensing issues. The Firm has been particularly active in protecting intellectual property owners against counterfeit and gray market goods,  and has been at the forefront of efforts to create and to protect property rights in computer software.
<P><BR><P>The Firm's intellectual property lawyers also utilize antitrust and business law expertise to help clients realize the full value of their intellectual property rights through licensing agreements,  joint ventures,  and distribution programs. Many are also experienced litigators. Covington  & Burling is thus able to provide assistance over the full range of intellectual property issues.<BR><P>Representative clients of record include American Personal Communications,  the Business Software Alliance (BSA),  the Coalition to Protect the Integrity of American Trademarks (COPIAT),  IBM,  Parfums Givenchy,  McCormick  & Company,  Inc.,  the Public Broadcasting Service,  and Sun Life Insurance Company of Canada.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Paul J. Berman</B> is a registered patent attorney with undergraduate training in computer science. He has advised both private enterprises and governments on intellectual property and telecommunications matters,  and is a director of the Harvard Program on Information Resources Policy. Harvard University,  A.B.,  1972,  J.D.,  1975.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Charles E. Buffon</B> litigates before courts throughout the United States in connection with intellectual property,  antitrust,  technology licensing,  franchising,  and distribution issues affecting domestic and international companies. He serves as lead counsel to the Coalition to Protect the Integrity of American Trademarks (COPIAT). Dartmouth College,  A.B.,  1961; Harvard University,  LL.B.,  1964.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Evan R. Cox</B> is resident in the London office. He serves as European legal counsel to the Business Software Alliance,  representing the software industry in European legislative matters and in their litigation program to combat copyright infringement. Michigan State University,  B.A.,  1982; University of California at Berkeley,  J.D.,  1987.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Herman De Bauw</B> is resident in the Brussels correspondent office. A member of the Brussels bar,  he has counseled clients on a variety of intellectual property matters and has been active in trademark enforcement litigation. Catholic University at Leuven,  1981; University of Virginia,  LL.M.,  1983.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Allen N. Dixon</B> is resident in the London office and works extensively on international intellectual property and corporate matters. He previously served in England as European legal director for two major software publishers. University of Maryland,  B.S.,  1977; American University,  Washington College of Law,  J.D.,  1983.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David R. Grace</B> has worked on a variety of copyright and trademark matters,  with particular emphasis on actions designed to combat the importation of gray market and counterfeit merchandise. Princeton University,  A.B.,  1978; Harvard University,  J.D.,  1981; Georgetown University,  LL.M.,  1984.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael S. Horne</B> advises various print media clients on copyright and related issues and has represented both broadcast television and cable television clients in connection with the compulsory copyright provision applicable to retransmission by cable television systems of over-the-air broadcast signals. University of Minnesota,  B.A.,  1959; Harvard University,  LL.B.,  1962.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Bingham B. Leverich</B> concentrates on antitrust,  unfair competition,  and trademark law issues. His practice includes counseling on trademark protection and licensing issues,  trademark litigation before the Trademark Trial and Appeal Board,  and in the courts. Wesleyan University,  B.A.,  1959; Yale University,  LL.B.,  1964.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Judith Sapp</B> has worked extensively on counseling and litigation of foreign and domestic trademark issues. She serves as trademark counsel to McCormick  & Company,  Incorporated. Her practice also includes litigation and counseling under the Copyright Act of 1976 and patent antitrust matters. Duke University,  LL.B.,  1984.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James C. Snipes</B> concentrates on international transactional matters,  with an emphasis on licensing of intellectual property. Mr. Snipes has extensive experience representing American high-tech companies in negotiations with foreign customers,  licensees,  and distributors. Much of his practice relates to Japan. Swarthmore College,  B.A.,  1975; Oxford University,  B.A.,  1977; Yale University,  J.D.,  1980.<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
