<HTML><HEAD><TITLE><*rb0>Crummy,  Del Deo,  Dolan,  Griffinger  & Vecchione</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL><CENTER><H2>Intellectual Property</H2><H3>Crummy,  Del Deo,  Dolan,  Griffinger  & Vecchione</H3></CENTER><CENTER><B>Newark:</B> One Riverfront Plaza,  Newark,  NJ 07102-5497<BR>Tel 201-596-4500  <B>*</B>  Fax 201-596-0545  <B>*</B>  E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:crummynk!info@attmail.com">crummynk!info@attmail.com</A> <B>*</B> WWW: <a href="http://www.crummy.net/">www.crummy.net</a><BR><BR>102 lawyers  <B>*</B>  8 lawyers in Intellectual Property Department<BR></CENTER><P><CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>A Professional Corporation</H3></CENTER><P><P><P><B>C</B>rummy,  Del Deo,  Dolan,  Griffinger  & Vecchione,  A Professional Corporation,  is engaged in a diversified practice. As one of New Jersey's largest law firms,  Crummy,  Del Deo represents an array of corporate and individual clients and nonprofit organizations in sophisticated matters. The practice areas in the firm include antitrust and trade regulation,  bankruptcy,  corporate and financial services,  employment rights,  environmental,  health care,  intellectual property,  land use,  product liability,  public finance,  real estate,  tax,  and trusts and estates. The firm works assiduously to maintain the highest standards of quality.<P><CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Intellectual Property Practice</H3></CENTER><P>Crummy,  Del Deo has extensive experience representing and counseling clients with respect to copyrights,  patents,  trademarks,  trade dress,  unfair competition,  trade secrets,  employee restrictive covenants,  confidentiality agreements,  and licensing matters. Moreover,  the knowledge of the attorneys at Crummy,  Del Deo spans a range of technical fields. We use this knowledge and experience to assist clients in identifying those aspects of their businesses that need protection,  and to aid clients in determining the appropriate methods of protection to employ. We obtain and review trademark,  copyright,  and patent searches; prosecute trademark and patent applications; obtain copyright registrations; prepare confidentiality,  employee nondisclosure,  assignment,  and licensing agreements; assist with due diligence in acquisitions and divestitures; assist in the development of intellectual property policies; and prepare and review software licenses.<BR><P>Crummy,  Del Deo has been involved in every type of intellectual property litigation. We have substantial experience representing both plaintiffs and defendants in expedited injunction and trial proceedings in both state and federal court. For example,  we obtained the leading decision in the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit regarding common law trademark rights,  <I>Natural Footwear Ltd. </I>v.<I> Hart-Schaffner  & Marx</I>. We have also represented clients in litigation in the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office.<BR><BR><UL><BR><LI><B>Ira J. Hammer</B>,  a member of the firm,  has been substantially involved in the litigation of copyright,  trademark,  trade secret,  and patent matters both in court and before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. His practice includes the prosecution of trademark and patent applications,  counseling of clients regarding intellectual property including acquisition of such property,  licensing of intellectual property including computer software,  and litigation of matters involving computer software.<BR><BR><LI><B>Michael D. Loprete</B> is a member of the firm who has previously served as in-house counsel with AT &T. He has extensive experience in private practice with regard to a wide variety of intellectual property matters. He has dealt extensively with trade secrets,  protection of proprietary information,  and antitrust aspects of joint research and development endeavors by competitors from both a transactional as well as litigation perspective.<BR><BR><LI><B>David J. Sheehan</B> is a member of the firm and has had extensive litigation experience in trademark,  patent,  and trade secret matters. He has successfully prosecuted claims against defecting employees seeking to improperly remove trade secret and proprietary information from their employers. He has also successfully obtained injunctive relief on behalf of several pharmaceutical companies to protect the trade dress of their respective products,  e.g.,  <I>Hoffmann-La Roche,  Inc. </I>v. <I>Premo Pharmaceuticals,  Inc</I>.<BR><BR><LI><B>Henry J. Walsh</B> is counsel to the firm,  having previously worked in the legal departments of Bell Laboratories,  Western Electric,  and AT &T,  where he was responsible for both the prosecution and litigation of patent and related matters. Since joining the firm,  he has prosecuted patent and trademark applications,  as well as litigated other intellectual property matters.<BR><BR><LI><B>Harold F. Broadman,  Jr.</B>,  counsel to the firm,  previously served as vice-president,  secretary,  and general counsel of Hoffmann-La Roche Inc. He has extensive experience in patent,  trademark,  and trade secret matters. Mr. Broadman is involved in emerging legal issues impacting the pharmaceutical and biotechnology industries.<BR><BR><LI><B>Matthew J. Hodulik</B>,  an associate with the firm,  has extensive experience in the preparation of high-technology patent applications for state-of-the-art electronic and electromechanical devices. He has prepared numerous licensing agreements in all areas of intellectual property and is admitted to practice before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office.<BR><BR><LI><B>David P. Krivoshik</B>,  an associate with the firm,  concentrates in patent prosecution. Prior to becoming an attorney,  he received a master's degree in electrical engineering and computer science,  and he ran his own engineering company,  specializing in computer systems integration,  for 12 years.</UL></UL></BODY></HTML>
