<HEAD>
<TITLE>Dickstein,  Shapiro  & Morin,  L.L.P.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Dickstein,  Shapiro  & Morin,  L.L.P.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington:</B> 2101 L Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20037<BR>
Tel 202-785-9700  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-887-0689<BR>
<BR>
170 lawyers  <B>*</B>  25 lawyers in the Intellectual Property Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profile in the following other directory:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/dickstein.html"> Corporate Securities</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>B</B>usinesses confront lawyers with a constant flow of legal and commercial questions related to their intellectual property rights,  particularly with so many industries still evolving. Dickstein,  Shapiro  & Morin's intellectual property practice offers clients a complete array of services,  both in obtaining and in the enforcement and defense of patents,  trademarks,  copyrights,  trade secrets,  and unfair competition cases.<BR><P>Companies in rapidly growing fields of technology,  including computers,  telecommunications,  electronics,  and biotechnology,  rely on Dickstein,  Shapiro  & Morin's counsel to establish programs that protect proprietary rights,  develop defensive strategies,  and license property rights. The group also educates clients on how to protect their rights under government contracts. To protect intellectual property rights,  we specialize in not only licensing and acquisition,  but in litigation. We appear in federal and state courts,  and before the International Trade Commission. Our role also extends to coordinating litigation abroad,  to serve both U.S. and international companies.<BR><P>Our goal is to act as a strategic partner,  by knowing both your company and how it fits into the larger industry. We work to guide companies toward reaching their business objectives,  while minimizing the risk of litigation. We have counseled clients engaged in research and development,  manufacturing and corporate transactions. The Intellectual Property group assists in establishing trademark programs for the marks used by companies and copyright programs for the distribution of materials and information.<BR><P>Representative clients:<BR><UL><LI>Ingersoll Rand<LI>Hitachi<LI>Encyclopaedia Britannica<LI>Allied Colloids<BR><BR></UL><P>Representative cases:<BR><UL><LI><I>Hoechst v. Allied Colloid</I><BR><LI><I>N.A. Philips v. Windmere</I><BR><LI><I>Ballard Medical Products v. Concord Medical</I><BR></UL><BR><BR><BR>
<LI><B>Thomas J. D'Amico</B> is a registered patent attorney with an undergraduate degree in electrical engineering (communications and computer science). He counsels corporate clients on all aspects of intellectual property law. He practices before the Patent and Trademark Office and litigates intellectual property issues throughout the United States. He also writes and lectures on topical intellectual property issues. Washington University,  B.S.E.E.,  1969; George Washington University,  J.D.,  1974.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Donald A. Gregory</B> concentrates on intellectual property law and has a background in nuclear engineering. He is a coauthor of the book <I>Introduction to Intellectual Property Law</I> (1994) and is a U.S. correspondent for patents and trademarks for <I>European Intellectual Property Review</I>. He was formerly in-house patent counsel for Philip Morris Incorporated and the Babcock  & WiLCox Company. University of Virginia,  B.S.,  1973; College of William and Mary,  J.D.,  1979.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jon D. Grossman</B>,  a registered patent attorney,  focuses on computer law and intellectual property issues,  including the acquisition of patents and copyrights,  the acquisition of computer technology,  and all aspects of computer software protection. As an adjunct professor at Johns Hopkins University,  he teaches high-technology law. University of Chicago,  B.A.,  1977; Johns Hopkins University,  M.S.,  1982; American University,  J.D.,  1986.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gary M. Hoffman</B> has been involved in litigation and licensing of intellectual property rights in the U.S. and abroad for over 20 years. He has actively handled over 90 lawsuits,  and was lead counsel in more than half. Mr. Hoffman has also drafted over 150 licensing agreements. A frequent lecturer in the U.S.,  Europe,  and Japan,  he has also chaired conferences and committees for AIPLA and ABA. He is a registered patent attorney. University of Pennsylvania,  B.S.E.E.,  1967; George Washington University,  J.D.,  1971.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Charles W. Saber</B> litigates all types of intellectual property cases in federal courts throughout the United States as well as in the Patent and Trademark Office and the International Trade Commission. He also has an extensive trademark and copyright counseling and prosecution practice. Mr. Saber is a coauthor of  <I>Introduction to Intellectual Property Law</I> (1994). University of Massachusetts,  B.A.,  1976; Georgetown University,  J.D.,  1979.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Mark J. Thronson</B>,  a registered patent attorney with a civil engineering background,  was formerly a primary examiner,  U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. Mr. Thronson is also an adjunct professor at Johns Hopkins University,  where he teaches legal issues in technology management. University of Wisconsin,  B.S.,  1982; George Washington University,  J.D.,  1988.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR><BR>


</UL></BODY>
