<HEAD>
<TITLE>Finnegan,  Henderson,  Farabow,  Garrett & Dunner L.L.P.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Finnegan,  Henderson,  Farabow,  Garrett & Dunner L.L.P.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington:</B> 1300 I Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20005<BR>
Tel 202-408-4000  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-408-4400<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Tokyo,  Brussels<BR>
<BR>
145 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers specialize in intellectual property law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>F</B>ounded in 1965,  Finnegan,  Henderson,  Farabow,  Garrett and Dunner has grown to become one of the largest specialized firms in the United States. Our practice,  both national and international,  encompasses all aspects of patent,  trademark,  and copyright law in virtually every technical field.
<P><BR><P>We regularly appear before federal and state trial and appellate courts and administrative agencies in actions involving infringement; trade secret misappropriation; unfair competition; license enforcement; and antitrust violations. We have developed a particular expertise handling appeals to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit.<BR><P>We have experience in domestic and international arbitration,  both as advocates and advisors. Nationally and internationally,  our attorneys prosecute patent and trademark applications,  including appeals,  reissues,  reexaminations,  interferences,  oppositions,  and cancellations. We also have experience in U.S. Customs Service actions to exclude infringing imports,  in obtaining appropriate licenses under the U.S. export control laws,  and in negotiating and litigating U.S. Government contract data rights provisions.<BR>
<BR><P>We provide advice and opinions on infringement and validity of intellectual property,  conduct intellectual property audits,  provide trademark watch services,  help formulate strategies for exploitation of intellectual property assets,  and negotiate and draft domestic and international intellectual property agreements.<BR>
<BR><P>Our attorneys are active in a variety of bar,  intellectual property-related,  and technical associations. Many firm attorneys also teach intellectual property law and appellate practice at local law schools and at CLE programs nationwide.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Douglas B. Henderson</B> is the founder of the Federal Circuit and Claims Court bar associations. He practices in all aspects of intellectual property law,  and is particularly skilled in counseling clients,  licensing,  and litigation both in federal courts and the U.S. Claims Court. Mr. Henderson is also actively involved in numerous bar associations and intellectual property committees.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Ford F. Farabow</B> is extremely well versed in the field of complex chemical technology. He built his reputation on his many successes as lead counsel in the trials and appeals of patent,  trademark,  trade secret,  and antitrust litigation. Mr. Farabow also handles licensing matters for the firm,  and is active in the Litigation,  Patent,  and Antitrust Committees of the American Bar Association and in the American Intellectual Property Law Association.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Arthur S. Garrett</B> has extensive experience with patent prosecution cases in the chemical and mechanical arts. He is considered an expert in practice and procedure before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office and foreign patent offices. He regularly advises a national and international clientele on all aspects of patent prosecution,  trademark,  and licensing matters,  and is extensively involved in validity and infringement opinion work.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Donald R. Dunner</B> has expertise in the pharmaceutical and biotechnology fields. He has extensive bench and jury trial experience and is often retained to appeal cases to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit. He has held numerous leadership positions in legal organizations,  including the American Bar Association,  the American Intellectual Property Law Association,  and the Advisory Committee of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Kenneth E. Payne</B> is active in the domestic and international litigation of patent trade secret,  copyright,  and antitrust matters. He has lectured and written extensively on technology transfer for the Practising Law Institute,  the Licensing Law and Business Institute,  and the Licensing Executives Society. He served as a U.S. Department of State delegate to the Inter-American Commission on Science and Technology Transfer,  and has been a consultant to the United Nations on matters involving technology transfer to developing countries.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Brian G. Brunsvold</B> is an expert in licensing. He has extensive experience negotiating,  drafting,  and litigating license agreements and has served as lead counsel in patent infringement cases before the federal courts and the U.S. International Trade Commission. Mr. Brunsvold also has a broad base of patent application preparation and prosecution experience and has written and lectured in the fields of licensing,  antitrust,  and patent misuse.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Susan H. Griffen</B> is well versed in biotechnology litigation and prosecution. Prior to her legal career Ms. Griffen was deeply involved in pharmaceutical research at the University of Iowa College of Medicine. In addition to success in the legal field,  she is the author of several articles concerning drug effects on tissue culture.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Lawrence R. Hefter</B> has over 20 years' experience in trademark matters,  including litigation,  licensing,  franchising,  and prosecution. Additionally,  he teaches trademark law at The George Washington University National Law Center.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>C. Larry O'Rourke</B> is experienced in complex electronic and computer intellectual property issues. He has substantial experience in patent prosecution and has successfully litigated numerous cases in federal district courts and before the ITC.<BR>
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
