<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Fish   & Neave
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Fish   & Neave
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>New York:</B> 1251 Avenue of the Americas,   New York,   NY 10020<BR>
Tel 212-596-9000  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-596-9090<BR>
<B>Palo Alto:</B> 525 University Avenue,   Palo Alto,   CA 94301<BR>
Tel 415-617-4000  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-617-4090<BR>
<BR>
120 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers practice intellectual property law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><B>F</B>ounded in 1878,   Fish   & Neave is one of the United States' oldest and best-known full-service intellectual property firms. Each of our 35 partners and 85 associates practices exclusively in the intellectual property field. The majority of our work is litigation,   but our non-litigation practice is also among the largest in the country. With offices in New York City and Palo Alto,   California,   we have a national practice and a substantial presence overseas.
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Practice Overview</H3></CENTER>

<P>During its early years,   the firm represented Alexander Graham Bell,   Thomas Edison,   the Wright brothers,   and many other clients in hundreds of patent disputes involving such fundamental inventions as the airplane,   automobile,   electric light bulb,   radio,   and telephone,   as well as trademark and other intellectual property litigation. Today,   the firm's clients include recognized leaders in every industry and area of technology.<BR>The firm litigates patent,   trademark,   copyright,   trade secret,   and related cases in federal courts throughout the country. We also represent our clients in patent interferences and trademark oppositions and cancellations in the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,   and in proceedings before the U.S. International Trade Commission. The firm represents its clients in connection with oppositions in European,   Japanese,   and other foreign patent offices,   and in infringement actions in national courts in Europe and other countries.<BR>
<BR>We also render patent and trademark opinions,   represent clients in connection with the intellectual property aspects of corporate transactions,   and prepare and negotiate a variety of agreements such as technology transfer,   patent,   trademark,   and other forms of licenses. The firm prosecutes hundreds of patent,   trademark,   and copyright applications every year. With the aid of computerized record-keeping systems,   we maintain thousands of patents and trademark registrations for our clients throughout the world.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Experience and Clients</H3></CENTER>

<P>Fish   & Neave represented Polaroid in its 15-year patent litigation with Kodak,   which resulted in an injunction against Kodak's manufacture and sale of instant cameras and film and a $925 million judgment for Polaroid. On behalf of Corning,   we obtained an injunction against Sumitomo's manufacture and sale of optical waveguide fiber in the United States. We successfully defended Biogen's patent on the recombinant production of alpha interferon in the European Patent Office over the opposition of nine parties,   and represented Cyrix in its successful litigation against Intel. In other recent patent disputes,   the firm has represented companies such as Allied-Signal,   American Cyanamid,   Atmel,   AT  &T,   Becton Dickinson,   Compaq,   Conner Peripherals,   Ford,   General Electric,   Gillette,   Hoechst Celanese,   Motorola,   Pitney Bowes,   Procter   & Gamble,   Schering-Plough,   and SciMed.<BR>Typical of the firm's trademark litigation is a 1992 case for Nestl,   which made new law in the First Circuit. Trademark and unfair competition cases on behalf of clients such as Coca-Cola,   Compaq,   Dreyer's,   Emerson Electric,   Home Box Office,   Lever Brothers,   Polaroid,   and Revlon have involved issues ranging from counterfeiting and gray market imports to trademark dilution and false advertising in violation of the Lanham Act.<BR>
<BR>We prepared an amicus brief in a highly publicized copyright case,   <I>Lotus </I>v.<I> Borland</I>. We represented the prevailing defendant in <I>Brandir Intern.,   Inc. </I>v. <I>Cascade Pacific Lumber Co.</I>,   a leading Second Circuit copyright decision. In other copyright cases,   we have appeared on behalf of clients such as Coca-Cola,   Corning,   NYNEX,   and Revlon. Becton Dickinson and Emulex are among the companies which have retained us to represent them in trade secret disputes.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>W. Edward Bailey</B> is Fish   & Neave's managing partner. He has over 20 years of experience in intellectual property litigation,   involving patents,   trademarks,   and trade secrets. He is a graduate of Auburn University,   B.S. (chemistry),   1965,   and the University of Virginia Law School,   J.D.,   1973. He did graduate study in biochemistry at Vanderbilt University,   served in the U.S. Marine Corps,   and clerked for U.S. District Judge Frank H. McFadden in the Northern District of Alabama.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
