<TITLE>Fish   & Richardson P.C.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Fish   & Richardson P.C.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Boston:</B> 225 Franklin Street,   Boston,   MA 02110-2804<BR>
Tel 617-542-5070  <B>*</B>  Fax 617-542-8906<BR>
<B>Houston:</B> One Riverway,   Suite 1200,   Houston,   TX 77056<BR>
Tel 713-629-5070  <B>*</B>  Fax 713-629-7811<BR>
<B>La Jolla:</B> 4225 Executive Square,   Suite 1400,   La Jolla,   CA 92037<BR>
Tel 619-678-5070  <B>*</B>  Fax 619-678-5099<BR>
<B>Menlo Park:</B> 2200 Sand Hill Road,   Menlo Park,   CA 94025<BR>
Tel 415-322-5070  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-854-0875<BR>
<B>Minneapolis:</B> 60 South Sixth Street,   Minneapolis,   MN 55402<BR>
Tel 612-335-5070  <B>*</B>  Fax 612-288-9696<BR>
<B>New York:</B> 45 Rockefeller Plaza,   New York,   NY 10111<BR>
Tel 212-765-5070  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-258-2291<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> 601 Thirteenth Street,   N.W.,   Washington,   DC 20005<BR>
Tel 202-783-5070  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-783-2331<BR>
<BR>
125 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers practice in intellectual property<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><B>F</B>ish   & Richardson P.C. is a national law firm with a focus on technology law trials,   transactions,   patents,   trademarks,   copyrights,   trade secrets,   entertainment law,   communications law,   FCC and FDA regulation,   and antitrust.
<P><BR>Nearly half of the firm's work is litigation. Fish   & Richardson's seasoned trial lawyers have significant jury trial experience. The firm's lawyers have tried cases both to enforce and to defend claims involving patent,   copyright,   trademark and trade dress,   license,   and trade secret rights.<BR>Fish   & Richardson P.C. obtained a $130 million damages award for patent infringement on behalf of one of its clients,   one of the largest verdicts in a patent infringement case. The firm represented New England Medical Center Hospitals,   Inc.,   and others in an action to enforce a patent relating to use of recombinant DNA technology for production of interleukin-lB in which the court awarded $2.7 million in damages,   attorneys' fees,   and interest based on $300,  000 of infringing sales. The firm represented Concept Design Electronics   & Manufacturing,   Inc. as cotrial counsel in successfully defending claims seeking hundreds of millions of dollars for alleged infringement of two patents relating to high-speed digital cassette duplicators. The patents were held unenforceable,   invalid,   and not infringed,   and Concept Design was awarded $900,  000 in damages for unfair competition. The firm represented PPG Industries Inc. in a patent jury case in which the jury awarded over $25 million in damages and found willful infringement.<BR>
<BR>Fish   & Richardson P.C. has strong patent prosecution capabilities in biotechnology,   electronics,   computer hardware and software,   chemistry,   medical devices,   and mechanical and electromechanical equipment.<BR>
<BR>The firm's offices share resources and expertise for the benefit of clients. No matter where a client is located,   the firm's lawyers are accessible through videoconferencing,   electronic mail,   and other advanced communications technologies.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Boston</H3></CENTER>

<P>The 52 lawyers in Fish   & Richardson's Boston office have experience in all areas of the firm's technology law practice. They can be contacted through the firm's Director of Client Services,   Kelly Largey.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Houston</H3></CENTER>

<P>Contact: <B>Michael O. Sutton</B>. Mr. Sutton is a trial lawyer with experience in intellectual property trials in the federal and state courts. He has also represented clients before the Trademark Trial and Appeals Board and the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>La Jolla</H3></CENTER>

<P>Contact: <B>John R. Wetherell</B>. Mr. Wetherell practices in the field of biotechnology,   including monoclonal antibodies,   immune response modulators,   immunodiagnostics,   and recombinant genetics.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Menlo Park</H3></CENTER>

<P>Contact: <B>James H. A. Pooley</B>. Mr. Pooley has extensive jury trial experience in commercial and intellectual property litigation,   particularly trade secrets matters. He is the author of <I>Trade Secrets: A Guide to Protecting Proprietary Business Information</I> (McGraw/Hill,   1982; Amacom,   1989).<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Minneapolis</H3></CENTER>

<P>Contact: <B>Wayne E. Willenberg</B>. Mr. Willenberg represents clients in patent,   trademark,   and trade secret litigation. He also counsel clients in licensing matters with emphasis in computer-based technology.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>New York</H3></CENTER>

<P>Contact: <B>John B. Pegram</B>. Mr. Pegram is a trial lawyer with extensive experience in patent and trademark litigation in state and federal courts and before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Washington,   D.C.</H3></CENTER>

<P>Contact: <B>Rene D. Tegtmeyer</B>. Mr. Tegtmeyer's practice emphasizes practice problems in the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. He was previously the assistant commissioner for patents,   assistant commissioner for trademarks,   and assistant commissioner for appeals,   legislation and trademarks in the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office.

</UL></BODY>
