<HEAD>
<TITLE>Fitch,  Even,  Tabin & Flannery
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Fitch,  Even,  Tabin & Flannery
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Chicago:</B> 135 South LaSalle Street,  Suite 900,  Chicago,  IL 60603<BR>
Tel 312-372-7842  <B>*</B>  Fax 312-372-7848<BR>
<B>San Diego:</B> 4250 Executive Square,  Suite 510,  San Diego,  CA 92037<BR>
Tel 619-552-1311  <B>*</B>  Fax 619-552-0095<BR>
<B>Arlington:</B> 2305 Wilson Boulevard,  Arlington,  VA 22201<BR>
Tel 703-243-9236  <B>*</B>  Fax 703-243-9207<BR>
<BR>
39 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers concentrate in intellectual property law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>F</B>itch,  Even,  Tabin  & Flannery,  founded in 1859,  is the oldest continuing law partnership in Chicago. The Firm services clients which require legal advice and services in all technological disciplines,  with concentration in the biochemical,  chemical,  electronic,  computer science,  and mechanical technologies.
<P><BR><P>We represent clients before all U.S. courts,  as well as the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  the Copyright Office,  the International Trade Commission,  and before the courts of those states in which our offices are located. The Firm offers comprehensive services in the area of litigation. We have been successful in achieving our clients' goals and in expediting the settlement process,  with an excellent success rate in winning judgments and in recovering attorneys' fees. In addition,  the Firm also handles international intellectual property matters.<BR><P>Fields within which the Firm practices include patent solicitation,  enforcement of patent rights,  patent validity and infringement opinions,  unfair competition and trade secrets,  prosecution and maintenance of trademark registrations and copyrights,  trademark registrability and infringement opinions,  licensing of intellectual property rights,  and client counseling in respect of all forms of intellectual property rights. We advise and assist clients in the negotiation of all manner of agreements involving or related to the transfer of rights in intellectual property,  e.g.,  acquisitions and divestitures,  assignments,  research and development agreements,  licenses,  consulting,  confidential disclosure,  and employment agreements.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Morgan L. Fitch,  Jr.</B> Mr. Fitch has been involved in all phases of litigation,  primarily in patent and trademark infringement actions,  and interference proceedings in the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  and the district courts,  including appeals in the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit. IIT,  B.S.Chem.E.,  1943; University of Michigan,  J.D.,  1948.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Francis A. Even</B> Mr. Even is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers; has been lead counsel in patent,  trademark,  and unfair competition cases around the country; and has tried theft of trade secrets cases in Illinois,  including appellate argument in the Illinois Supreme Court. University of Illinois,  B.S.M.E.,  1942; George Washington University,  J.D.,  1949.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Julius Tabin</B> Dr. Tabin's focus is in the areas of high technology,  including biotechnology,  nuclear physics,  electronics,  and chemistry. His practice involves client counseling,  litigation,  and licensing in the areas of patent,  trademark and copyright,  trade secrets,  and related contract and antitrust law. University of Chicago,  B.S.,  1940,  Ph.D.,  Physics,  1946; Harvard Law School,  LL.B.,  1949.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>John F. Flannery</B> Mr. Flannery has been primary counsel in numerous jury and bench trials and is familiar with all facets of litigation. His experience is in counseling and licensing,  patent,  trademark,  copyright,  trade secrets,  and related contract and antitrust matters. University of Illinois,  B.S.E.E.,  1950; Northwestern University,  graduate study in E.E.,  1953-1954; Loyola University,  J.D.,  1959.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Robert B. Jones</B> Mr. Jones' experience is in litigation,  client counseling,  proceedings before the ITC,  abatement of counterfeiting activities,  and trade secrets litigation,  as well as other commercial litigation and arbitration. Iowa State University,  B.S. Chem.E.,  1952; University of Michigan Law School,  J.D.,  1960.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>James J. Schumann </B>(<I>San Diego</I>) Mr. Schumann is experienced in patent and trademark litigation,  both bench and jury trials and appeals,  and patent interference cases. He has extensive experience in international patent prosecution,  particularly in biotechnology and pharmaceuticals. He also has been very active in the areas of patent,  trade secrets,  and trademark licensing,  including group licensing programs. IIT,  B.S. Chem.E.,  1955; Loyola University,  J.D.,  1962.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>R. Steven Pinkstaff</B> Mr. Pinkstaff has been involved in litigation,  and has a wide range of experience at both trial (jury and nonjury) and appellate levels,  including the ITC. Iowa State University,  B.S. Chem.E.,  1959; George Washington University,  J.D.,  1963.<BR><BR><LI><B>James J. Hamill</B> Mr. Hamill has extensive experience in client counseling,  prosecution of U.S. and foreign patents,  and licensing matters. Georgia Institute of Technology,  B.M.E.,  1957; George Washington University,  LL.B.,  1960.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Timothy E. Levstik</B> Mr. Levstik has experience both at the trial and appellate levels,  and has participated in the trial of cases involving patents,  trademarks,  unfair competition,  trade secrets,  and copyrights. Case Institute of Technology,  B.S.,  Chem.,  1967; University of Minnesota,  J.D.,  1970.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Joseph E. Shipley</B> Mr. Shipley has been principally involved in patent infringement litigation,  as well as in patent prosecution,  and counseling of clients. Northwestern University,  B.S.M.E.,  1979; University of Illinois,  J.D.,  1982.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Bryant R. Gold </B>(<I>San Diego</I>) Mr. Gold's concentration includes all phases of intellectual property law,  including patent,  trademark,  copyright,  licensing,  and employer/employee agreements. University of Utah,  B.S.E.E.,  1969,  J.D.,  1979; Southern Methodist University,  M.S.E.E.,  1976.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Robert J. Fox</B> Mr. Fox has extensive experience in patent litigation as well as in the prosecution of U.S. and foreign patent applications. University of Illinois,  B.S.,  Physics,  1972; John Marshall Law School,  J.D.,  1976.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Kenneth H. Samples</B> Mr. Samples' experience includes licensing agreements,  trade secrets protection,  and software copyright matters in several technical areas. He is also knowledgeable in international patent prosecution. University of Nebraska,  B.S.E.E.,  1969; John Marshall Law School,  J.D.,  1973.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Philip T. Petti</B> Mr. Petti's litigation experience is in complex patent accounting,  and in damage proceedings. Carlton College,  B.A.,  sociology,  1980; North Central College,  B.A.,  Chem.,  1982; Drake University,  J.D.,  1985.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>John S. Paniaguas</B> Mr. Paniaguas has extensive experience in all areas of intellectual property including patent,  trademark,  copyright,  trade secrets,  and unfair competition law with an emphasis on high technology. Purdue University,  B.S.E.,  1973; DePaul University,  J.D.,  1982.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Donald A. Peterson</B> Mr. Peterson has been involved in patent interference proceedings and litigation,  including before the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit. University of Illinois,  B.S.,  Chem.,  1950; John Marshall Law School,  J.D.,  1956.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>John J. Cavanaugh</B> Mr. Cavanaugh has had considerable involvement in patent and trademark prosecution,  copyright,  counseling,  unfair competition,  and litigation,  including before the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit. Georgetown University,  B.S.,  Chem.,  1949; J.D.,  1956.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>James R. McBride</B> Mr. McBride's experience is in licensing and patent prosecution. Purdue University,  B.S. Chem.E.,  1959; Colorado University,  LL.B.,  1964.<BR>
<BR><P><B>James A. Sprowl</B> Mr. Sprowl has extensive experience in intellectual property law,  counseling,  prosecution,  litigation,  and licensing with an emphasis on computer hardware and software. University of Michigan,  B.S.E.E.,  B.S.,  Eng. Physics,  1964; University of Michigan,  J.D.,  1967.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Bruce R. Mansfield</B> Mr. Mansfield's concentration is in all areas of intellectual property law,  with an emphasis on patent prosecution,  licensing,  and counseling. IIT,  B.S.E.E.,  1970; John Marshall Law School,  J.D.,  1975.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Joseph T. Nabor</B> Mr. Nabor's area of practice includes the prosecution of trademark applications in the U.S. and abroad,  as well as litigation,  licensing,  and counseling in trademarks,  copyrights,  and trade dress. Northeastern Illinois University,  B.A.,  1984; IIT,  Chicago-Kent College of Law,  J.D.,  1989.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Richard P. Beem</B> Mr. Beem has experience in all areas of intellectual property law,  including patent and trademark prosecution,  licensing,  counseling,  copyright,  trade secrets,  unfair competition,  and antitrust. Iowa State University,  B.S. Chem.E.,  1979; University of Houston Law School,  J.D.,  1985.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>James E. Turner,  Jr.</B> Mr. Turner's experience includes trademarks (both in the U.S. and abroad),  copyrights,  and trade secrets. He also has extensive experience in general corporate law,  contract law,  technology licensing,  and acquisition,  divestiture,  and merger activities. University of Virginia,  B.A.,  1964,  J.D.,  1972; University of Texas at Arlington,  M.B.A.,  1983.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Richard A. Kaba</B> Dr. Kaba has experience in client counseling and patent prosecution. Clemson University,  B.S.,  chemistry,  1969; Duke University,  Ph.D.,  Phys. Chem.,  1974; University of Michigan,  J.D.,  with honors,  1988.<BR>
