<HEAD>
<TITLE>Fried,  Frank,  Harris,  Shriver  & Jacobson
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Fried,  Frank,  Harris,  Shriver  & Jacobson
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>New York:</B> One New York Plaza,  New York,  NY 10004<BR>
Tel 212-859-8000  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-859-4000<BR>
<BR>
357 lawyers  <B>*</B>  21 lawyers in Intellectual Property Practice Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/fried.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/fried.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/fried.html"> White Collar Crime</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>F</B>ried,  Frank is a national law firm with a practice that is international in scope,  having its principal office in New York and other offices in Washington,  D.C.,  Los Angeles,  and London. The Firm's more than 350 attorneys represent businesses and individuals in complex matters,  many of them in the forefront of financial and legal developments.
<P>The Intellectual property practice Group spans the full range of patent,  trademark,  copyright,  trade dress,  false advertising,  unfair competition,  and business tort issues,  including matters under the federal Lanham Act and various state laws. These involve representations in complex litigations,  TRO and preliminary injunction hearings,  and Patent and Trademark Office activities,  including preparation and prosecution of applications and oppositions. Fried,  Frank lawyers are also often involved in synthesizing the patent and antitrust issues in ongoing business contexts. Fried,  Frank's intellectual property practice is augmented by the addition of several lawyers trained in the sciences who are members of the patent bar and who have graduate degrees and experience that cover all scientific applications.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Experience and Clients</H3></CENTER>

<P>Recent or ongoing illustrative litigations include the representation of: General Instrument Corporation and numerous satellite programmers,  including HBO,  Showtime,  and Turner Broadcasting,  in key patent infringement litigation challenging the method of scrambling satellite television programming; PSC in patent litigation involving laser bar-code scanners; L.A. Gear and Starter Corp. in a number of successful trademark infringement and counterfeiting actions,  and in connection with all the major professional sports leagues (NBA,  MLB,  NHL,  and NFL) and many of the licensed colleges and universities; W.B. Saunders,  a book publisher,  in a successful defense of a preliminary injunction hearing and appeal to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit in a copyright,  trademark,  and contract matter involving a medical treatise; Pullman Company in two patent infringement cases; Parklane Hosiery in the successful defense of a jury trial involving claims by a designer of women's actionwear for trademark infringement and breach of contract; Savoy Pictures in a successful trademark and unfair competition litigation against a party using a confusingly similar name; Tri-Star Pictures and Columbia Pictures in a suit challenging Tri-Star's refusal to distribute a motion picture because of a claim that the title of the motion picture infringed Columbia Pictures' common law rights in the classic motion picture <I>Bridge on the River Kwai</I>; General Instrument Corporation in connection with claims of patent and copyright infringement,  as well as signal piracy; Xerox Corp. in trademark infringement litigation; and AB Electrolux and its U.S. subsidiary,  White Consolidated Industries,  Inc.,  in various actions alleging patent and trade dress infringement.<BR>
Fried,  Frank also regularly counsels clients on intellectual property matters,  monitors the enforcement of clients' portfolios of patents and trademarks,  and evaluates intellectual property in connection with proposed business transactions. Representative additional clients include Chock Full O'Nuts,  Parklane Hosiery,  McCrory Corp.,  Forstmann Little  & Co.,  and Safelite Glass.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Allen Kezsbom</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8148</I>) Allen Kezsbom is a senior litigation partner who has a trial and appellate practice encompassing the broad range of patent,  trademark,  trade dress,  unfair competition,  business tort,  and copyright matters,  as well as antitrust and contract. These include trademark matters for Parklane Hosiery,  Chock Full O' Nuts,  and Xerox,  and patent matters for a variety of companies including Cortec Group,  Pullman,  General Instrument,  and 3M. He was,  for example,  trial attorney for Xerox in the <I>SCM </I>v.<I> Xerox</I> patent monopolization litigation and has written and spoken extensively on the trial of complex cases. Brooklyn College,  B.A.,  1962; Harvard University,  LL.B.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1965; <I>Harvard Law Review</I>,  1963-1965.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Maxim H. Waldbaum</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8381</I>) Mac Waldbaum is a senior litigation partner who is a member of the patent bar and has an intellectual property practice which encompasses the full range of patents,  trademarks,  and copyrights,  primarily in litigation,  as well as counseling in transactional matters including,  in particular,  international licensing and distribution agreements. He has written and spoken extensively on the patent laws including patent harmonization worldwide. He is coauthor of <I>Acquiring and Protecting Intellectual Property Rights</I> (Matthew Bender,  updated through 1994). President,  Federation Internationale Conseil Propriet &#232; Industrielle (FICPI),  1995-1998; council member,  1984-1994; secretary/treasurer,  1991-1994. Chairman,  Economic Impact Task Force,  International Committee,  International Trademark Association (INTA). Rutgers College,  B.S.E.E.,  1962; University of Pennsylvania,  Moore School of Electrical Engineering,  M.S.,  engineering,  1966; New York University,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  salutatorian,  1970; Order of the Coif.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert E. Juceam</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8040 and Washington; 202-639-7377</I>) Robert E. Juceam is a litigating partner who has a trial and appellate practice that encompasses complex civil litigation and representation before government agencies,  including matters involving corporate confidentiality; Freedom of Information Act,  Privacy Act,  and Sunshine Law litigation and counseling; and trademarks. He is coauthor of a series of articles,  `Representing the Employee in a Trade Secret Case, ' published by Business Laws,  Inc. Columbia College,  A.B.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1961; Columbia University School of Law,  J.D.,  1964; New York University School of Law,  LL.M.,  1966.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Barbara A. Reeves</B> (<I>Los Angeles; 213-689-5848</I>) Barbara Reeves is a litigation partner who has a trial practice that encompasses complex litigation and alternative dispute resolution matters involving antitrust and intellectual property. Recent cases include representation of five oil companies in major patent litigation,  and an antitrust matter for a high-tech company arising out of its intellectual property licensing arrangements. Recent publications include serving as editor of <I>Federal Criminal Litigation</I> (ABA) and articles on evidence and antitrust. Law clerk to Judge Alfred T. Goodwin,  U.S. Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit,  1973-1974. New College,  A.B.,  1971; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1973.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gregory P. Joseph</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8052</I>) Greg Joseph has a practice involving a wide range of intellectual property,  copyright,  trademark,  and patent litigation. Recent cases include representation of Dow Jones Inc.'s Telerate subsidiary in theft of intellectual property litigation; Bally Midway Corp. in copyright/trademark cases; and White Consolidated in patent litigation. He is the author of books on evidence,  sanctions,  and civil RICO. Fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers. Member of the U.S. Supreme Court's Advisory Committee on the Rules of Evidence. Member of the Governing Council of the Litigation Section of the American Bar Association. University of Minnesota,  B.A.,  1972,  J.D.,  honors,  1975; law review; Phi Beta Kappa.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William P. McGuinness</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8026</I>) Bill McGuinness has a wide-ranging commercial litigation practice,  which has included trial of trademark,  trade dress,  and patent matters on behalf of various clients,  notably White Consolidated Industries,  Inc. Association of the Bar of the City of New York; American Bar Association (chairman,  Section of Litigation,  Trial Practice Subcommittee on Complex Litigation); Federal Bar Council (Committee on Second Circuit Courts). Columbia University,  B.A.,  1975,  J.D.,  1979.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Ira S. Sacks</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8061</I>) Ira Sacks has a broad-based intellectual property litigation practice involving enforcement of registered and common law trademarks and trade dress,  as well as a variety of patent and copyright issues. Recent matters include successful preliminary injunction proceedings involving trademark rights for Savoy Pictures as well as a <I>certiorari</I> petition on trade dress issues for L.A. Gear. Other representative clients include Tri-Star Pictures,  Columbia Pictures,  and Montblanc USA. Massachusetts Institute of Technology,  B.S.,  1970; Georgetown University,  J.D.,  1974; senior topics editor,  <I>Law  & Policy in International Business</I>,  1973-1974.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Alexander R. Sussman</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8005</I>) Alex Sussman is a senior litigation partner who has trial and appellate experience in a variety of trademark,  copyright,  and unfair competition matters. He represented,  among others,  Bally Midway Corp. in protecting and enforcing its Pac-Man copyrights and trademarks; Mattel in prosecuting knockoffs of its He-Man toys; and Wheelabrator-Frye in defending against the alleged misappropriation of trade secrets. He has authored numerous articles on litigation and arbitration strategy and tactics. Law clerk to Judge Constance Baker Motley,  Southern District of New York,  1972-1973. Princeton University,  A.B.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1968; University of Bordeaux (France),  Fulbright Scholar,  1969; Yale Law School,  J.D.,  1972; <I>Yale Law Journal</I>,  1971-1972.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Elliot E. Polebaum</B> (<I>Washington: 202-639-7067</I>) Elliot Polebaum has a broad commercial litigation and arbitration practice,  which includes intellectual property cases involving copyrights,  trademarks,  trade secrets,  patents and technology licensing. He has written and spoken extensively on arbitration (both domestic and international),  intellectual property,  and technology licensing. Law clerk to Associate Justice William J. Brennan,  Jr.,  U.S. Supreme Court and Judge James L. Oakes,  U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit. Languages: English and French. Middlebury College,  B.A.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1972; Phi Beta Kappa; Harvard University,  M.P.A.,  1975; New York University School of Law,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1977; Order of the Coif.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Debra Torres</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8028</I>) Debra Torres has represented companies in patent and licensing disputes,  as well as trademark and copyright matters. Trademarks and Unfair Competition Committee of the Association of the Bar of the City of New York,  1992- . Yale University,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1977,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Peter L. Simmons</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8455</I>) Peter Simmons has a diverse complex commercial litigation practice,  including trademark,  trade dress,  copyright,  unfair competition,  and licensing disputes,  and a wide array of sophisticated contract cases. He handles matters at both the trial and appellate levels. Law clerk to Judge Lawrence W. Pierce,  U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit,  1987-1988. Columbia University,  A.B.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1985; Phi Beta Kappa; Cambridge University; Columbia University,  J.D.,  1987; Harlan Fiske Stone Scholar; treasurer and senior editor,  <I>Columbia Law Review</I>,  1985-1987.<BR>
