<TITLE>Hecker  & Harriman
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Hecker  & Harriman
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Sunnyvale:</B> 1250 Oakmead Parkway,  Suite 210,  Sunnyvale,  CA 94088<BR>
Tel 408-736-6723<BR>
<B>Other office:</B> Los Angeles<BR>
<BR>
8 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers specializing in patent,  trademark and copyright law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>H</B>ecker  & Harriman practices exclusively in intellectual property law,  including patents,  trademarks,  copyrights,  unfair competition,  trade secrets,  computer law,  licensing,  and litigation. The firm's emphasis is on high-technology matters. Our attorneys,  law clerks,  and staff scientists are also engineers and computer scientists,  with technical degrees from institutions including MIT,  Stanford,  Cal Tech and UC-Berkeley. 
<P><BR><P>Hecker  & Harriman is experienced in obtaining and enforcing patents involving state-of-the-art software,  hardware and systems technology. The firm has great depth and experience in obtaining patent protection in hundreds of advanced technologies,  including multimedia,  information systems,  semiconductors,  computer graphics,  artificial intelligence,  networking,  virtual reality,  object-oriented systems and cross platform technology. <BR><P>The firm is intellectual property counsel to the following representative companies: Novell,  Inc.,  Walt Disney,  Visa International,  TDK/Silicon Systems,  Automated Data Processing,  Creative Artists Agency,  NeXT,  Peoplesoft,  Dole Foods,  Pixar,  Farallon Computing,  Rogue Wave Software,  Samsung,  Emerald Systems,  Alesis Corp.,  Quarterdeck Systems,  and Network Appliance Corp.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Gary A. Hecker</B> is a registered patent attorney with diverse experience in obtaining and enforcing intellectual property rights,  including complex patent,  trademark,  and copyright litigation. He has more than 13 years of experience in all aspects of intellectual property law,  including writing patents for software,  establishing and `driving' patent programs for high-technology companies,  and litigating before the federal and state courts and the International Trade Commission. He served as counsel to Apple,  NeXT,  and Quarterdeck Systems in protecting their user interfaces. He is counsel for Novell,  Inc.,  in the network technology patent suit <I>Novell </I>adv.<I> IAS</I>. He was lead counsel for Dole Foods in its successful Plant Variety Protection litigation. He is presently lead trial counsel for TDK/SSi in the patent litigation <I>SSi </I>v.<I> Exar Corporation</I>. He has testified before the U.S. House of Representatives as an expert in software and hardware proprietary rights protection and unfair international trade practices,  and traveled to Southeast Asia as technical advisor and intellectual property counsel to the U.S. House Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigation of the Committee on Energy and Commerce (Rep. John Dingell,  Chair). University of Rhode Island,  B.S.,  engineering; University of San Diego,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>J. D. Harriman II</B> is a registered patent attorney who counsels clients primarily in the area of patents and trademark protection. Since 1984,  he has worked with hundreds of inventors in identifying and describing their inventions,  and has successfully prosecuted numerous patent applications in a wide range of technologies including multimedia,  computer graphics,  computer algorithms,  interfaces,  data structures,  architectures,  memory management,  semiconductor circuit design and processing,  disk drive technology,  optics,  computer imaging,  digital signal processing,  telecommunications,  servo schemes,  microprocessors,  virtual reality,  and many other software and electronic systems. Ohio State University,  B.S.,  ceramic and electrical engineering; University of Southern California,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Christopher A. Mathews</B> is a registered patent attorney focusing on patent prosecution,  patent litigation,  and trademark protection. University of California at Berkeley,  B.S.,  electrical engineering and computer science,  <I>magna cum laude</I>; Stanford University,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Frank M. Weyer</B> is a registered patent attorney focusing on patent prosecution and litigation. He was a legislative intern for the U.S. House of Representatives Science and Technology Committee,  and coordinator of the Rural Technology Unit of the U.S. Peace Corps. Mr. Weyer holds a J.D. from the University of California at Berkeley,  and a M.S. in mechanical engineering from the California Institute of Technology.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Elizabeth E. Blakey</B> is an attorney focusing on patent,  trademark and copyright litigation,  and trademark and copyright prosecution. University of Notre Dame,  B.A.,  philosophy; Loyola University,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Ross D. Snyder</B> is an attorney practicing in the area of patent prosecution in the computer science and electronic arts. Massachusetts Institute of Technology,  B.S. in electrical engineering; University of Southern California,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael Farjami</B> is an attorney practicing in the area of patent prosecution in the electronic arts. He is the author of `Protectable Trade Dress without Secondary Meaning-On Second Thought, ' <I>Loyola Entertainment Law Journal</I>,  Vol. 13,  Issue 2 (1993). University of California at Los Angeles,  B.S.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  M.S.,  electrical engineering; Loyola University,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Carole A. Quinn</B> is an attorney whose practice emphasizes intellectual property litigation and prosecution. Ohio State University,  B.A.,  psychology; California State University at Fullerton,  M.S.,  computer science; Ohio State University,  J.D.
</UL>


