<TITLE>Heller,  Ehrman,  White & McAuliffe
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Heller,  Ehrman,  White & McAuliffe
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Palo Alto:</B> 525 University Avenue,  Palo Alto,  CA 94301-1900<BR>
Tel 415-324-7000  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-324-0638<BR>
<B>San Francisco:</B> 333 Bush Street,  San Francisco,  CA 94104-2878<BR>
Tel 415-772-6000  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-772-6268  <B>*</B>  Email: info@hewm.com<BR>
<B>Seattle:</B> 701 Fifth Avenue,  Seattle,  WA 98104-7098<BR>
Tel 206-447-0900  <B>*</B>  Fax 206-447-0849<BR>
<B>Los Angeles:</B> 601 South Figueroa Street,  Los Angeles,  CA 90017-5758<BR>
Tel 213-689-0200  <B>*</B>  Fax 213-614-1868<BR>
<BR>
340 lawyers  <B>*</B>  33 lawyers in intellectual property practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>H</B>eller Ehrman offers a complete spectrum of intellectual property services,  primarily in its Palo Alto,  San Francisco,  Seattle,  and Los Angeles offices. The firm also has offices in Portland,  Tacoma,  Anchorage,  Washington,  D.C.,  Hong Kong,  and Singapore. Founded in 1890,  we have long provided solutions in the litigation,  transactional,  and tax arenas for clients' intellectual property problems. We were also among the first California law firms to add lawyers and patent agents,  skilled in various arts,  whose practice is devoted to drafting and prosecuting patent applications in the United States and foreign countries. Heller Ehrman provides lawyers experienced in filing and prosecuting trademark and patent applications,  domestically and in foreign countries; in licensing technology and intellectual property; in arranging financing,  joint ventures,  strategic partnerships,  sales and acquisitions for companies with significant intellectual property assets; and litigating,  in federal and state courts,  trademark,  trade secret,  copyright,  and patent cases and issues.<BR><BR><P>Representative engagements have included VISA U.S.A.,  for domestic and international trademark work; Atari Games Corporation,  in its patent,  copyright,  and antitrust dispute with Nintendo; Texas Instruments Inc.,  in patent and antitrust litigation relating to PC patents and microprocessor patents; Chips  & Technologies Inc.,  in patent litigation relating to microprocessor architecture; Atmel Corporation,  in several patent litigations involving semiconductor structures,  processes and circuit designs; Origin Medsystems,  Inc.,  in trade secret and patent litigation relating to laparoscopic instrumentation technology; Otsuka Pharmaceutical Co. Ltd.,  for patent licensing and joint ventures; Raychem Corporation,  in patent litigation involving gels under compression technology; Hoffmann-La Roche Inc.,  in litigation relating to PCR technology; and TRE Corporation,  for patent and trade secrets litigation. Other intellectual property clients include Affymax,  N.V.; ALZA Corporation; Biotek Solutions,  Inc.; British Telecom; Chevron Corporation; E-Mu Systems; Guidant Corporation; Identix,  Inc.; Penederm Inc.; Ricoh California Research Center; Tencor Instruments; and UUNET Technologies,  Inc.<BR>
<BR><P>In September 1995,  Neil Flanzraich,  senior vice-president and general counsel of Syntex Corporation,  Alan Krubiner,  director of Intellectual Property for Syntex,  and Kent Stormer,  director of Environmental Services at Syntex,  along with six other attorneys and two international patent specialists formerly with the legal department of Syntex,  joined Heller Ehrman in the Palo Alto office. Mssrs. Flanzraich,  Krubiner,  Stormer and their team had been responsible for Syntex's legal needs for the preceding 15 years. During that period,  Syntex faced the whole range of legal issues relating to the research,  development,  manufacturing,  and marketing of a wide range of products; the creation,  exploitation,  and defense of a substantial domestic and international patent and trademark portfolio; the development and implementation of a wide variety of creative collaborative relations with other life science companies; environmental compliance and remediation activities; and FDA and international regulatory compliance efforts.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Richard H. Abramson</B> (<I>Palo Alto</I>) Mr. Abramson practices high-technology intellectual property litigation,  including patent,  trade secret,  copyright,  and trademark litigation in both state and federal courts. He has litigated numerous cases involving complex technology,  including a seven-week trial to a specially-selected jury of semiconductor engineers. Mr. Abramson has published extensively in the technology area. Former law clerk to Judge William H. Orrick of the U.S District Court for the Northern District of California. Claremont McKenna College,  B.A.,  1978; University of California,  Boalt Hall School of Law,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Daniel L. Appelman</B> (<I>Palo Alto</I>) Mr. Appelman has a corporate practice emphasizing the protection and commercial exploitation of proprietary rights in high-technology products and services,  particularly in the computer hardware and software,  telecommunications,  and semiconductor industries. San Francisco State University,  B.A.,  1964,  M.A.,  1971; Temple University,  Ph.D.,  1983; University of California at Los Angeles School of Law,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Helen I. Bendix</B> (<I>Los Angeles</I>) Ms. Bendix has prosecuted and defended against defamation claims,  and has advised clients on malicious prosecution,  abuse of process,  trade secrets,  and business libel issues. She also has extensive antitrust experience and has counseled a major computer company and a major defense contractor on antitrust issues related to intellectual property. Former law clerk to Judge Shirley M. Hufstedler of the U.S Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit. Cornell University,  B.A.,  1973; Yale University,  J.D.,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John A. Dhuey</B> (<I>Palo Alto</I>) Mr. Dhuey's practice involves counseling senior-level research and business management on strategic and legal matters relating to technology transfers and collaborative research and development. He is licensed to practice before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office and acts as special counsel to the firm. University of Wisconsin,  B.S.,  chemistry,  1964; Northwestern University,  M.S.,  chemistry,  1968,  Ph.D. studies,  1970; Loyola University of Chicago,  J.D.,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Raymond C. Fisher</B> (<I>Los Angeles</I>) Mr. Fisher practices complex business litigation including trade secrets,  patent licenses and patent validity,  trademark and copyright infringement,  and antitrust and unfair competition. He frequently lectures on litigation procedure,  including serving on the faculty of Prentice Hall's Trial Advocacy Institute series on `Intellectual Property Litigation in Technology Cases.' Former law clerk to Associate Justice William J. Brennan,  Jr. of the U.S. Supreme Court and to Judge J. Skelly Wright of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit. University of California,  Santa Barbara,  B.A.,  1961; Stanford Law School,  LL.B.,  1966.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Neil W. Flanzraich</B> (<I>Palo Alto</I>) Mr. Flanzraich is chair of the Life Sciences Practice Group. Prior to joining Heller Ehrman,  he was responsible for directing all worldwide legal activities of a major pharmaceutical company,  including intellectual property,  regulatory,  commercial,  environmental,  litigation,  securities,  insurance,  tax,  and employment law. Mr. Flanzraich was particularly involved in a wide variety of complex domestic and international transactions such as purchase and sale of companies,  and structuring a large number of research and commercial strategic alliances (e.g.,  joint ventures and research,  license,  distribution,  and co-marketing arrangements). Harvard College,  A.B.,  1965; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  1968.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Joshua R. Floum</B> (<I>San Francisco</I>) Mr. Floum has litigated a wide range of cases in the intellectual property,  distribution,  and trade areas. He has particular expertise in the transnational piracy,  gray market,  and distribution problems which face many trademark and copyright holders. Former law clerk to Judge A. Wallace Tashima of the U.S District Court for the Central District of California. University of California at Berkeley,  B.A.,  1980; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  1983.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert D. Fram </B>(<I>Palo Alto</I>) Mr. Fram specializes in intellectual property litigation cases,  including computer software licensing disputes,  patent cases,  trade secrets,  and trademark cases. His litigation experience ranges from leadership of the ten-lawyer team in software licensing litigation for Computer Associates to service as special assistant district attorney,  trying a series of criminal cases to the jury. Former law clerk to Judge J. Skelly Wright of the U.S Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit. Princeton University,  A.B.,  1979; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  1985.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Derek P. Freyberg</B> (<I>Palo Alto</I>) Dr. Freyberg's practice involves U.S. patent preparation and prosecution for the pharmaceutical,  chemical,  and chemical engineering arts. He is licensed before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office and acts as special counsel to the firm. Victoria University of Wellington,  New Zealand,  B.Sc.,  1968,  M.Sc,  chemistry,  1970; University of Virginia,  Ph.D.,  chemistry,  1977; University of California at Berkeley and Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory,  postdoctoral fellow,  chemistry,  1977-1979; Santa Clara University,  J.D.,  1982.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard L. Goff</B> (<I>Seattle</I>) Mr. Goff has represented companies in various industries in prosecuting or defending claims relating to the licensing of patents and of software,  patent and copyright infringement,  misappropriation of trade secrets,  trademarks and tradenames,  antitrust,  unfair competition,  and other business torts. Former law clerk to Judge Charles M. Merrill of the U.S Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit. Pomona College,  B.A.,  1960; Harvard Law School,  LL.B.,  1963.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert T. Haslam</B> (<I>Palo Alto</I>) Mr. Haslam practices patent and technology litigation,  with significant experience in semiconductor design,  processes and operation,  and circuits. His other experience includes counseling and defending clients with software products with respect to copyright and trade secret issues. Massachusetts Institute of Technology,  B.S,  1968; Hastings College of the Law,  J.D.,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert B. Hawk</B> (<I>Palo Alto</I>) Mr. Hawk's practice has focused on licensing and contract disputes,  trademark counterfeiting,  state and federal antitrust claims,  derivative claims,  and securities fraud. He has tried cases in federal and state courts and before private arbitrators and has litigated cases for clients involved in a number of high-technology industries. Former law clerk to Judge Irving L. Goldberg for the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit. University of Texas,  B.S.,  1980; Stanford Law School,  J.D.,  1983.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kevin F. Kelly</B> (<I>Seattle</I>) Mr. Kelly practices commercial law,  with extensive experience in computer and technology licensing transactions. He has represented numerous corporations in the acquisition of large computer software and hardware systems and telecommunications systems and in biotechnology and pharmaceutical transactions. Former law clerk to Judge Eugene A. Wright of the U.S Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit,  and a former extern law clerk to Judge Stanley Mosk of the California Supreme Court. Gonzaga University,  A.B.,  1970; University of California at Berkeley,  Boalt Hall School of Law,  J.D.,  1973.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Martina W. Knee</B> (<I>Palo Alto</I>) Ms. Knee has represented health care,  drug delivery technology,  and other high-technology companies in their start-up and development stages and as publicly held companies. She has also represented venture capital investors and underwriters in financings,  including public offerings,  in these sectors. Ms. Knee also has substantial experience in mergers,  acquisitions,  leveraged buyouts,  and complex investment limited partnerships. Ms. Knee was profiled in <I>California Law Business</I> in 1994 as one of `25 Under 45' lawyers in the state. University of California at Berkeley,  B.A.,  1980; Phi Beta Kappa; University of California at Berkeley,  Boalt Hall School of Law,  J.D.,  1983.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Alan M. Krubiner</B> (<I>Palo Alto</I>) Dr. Krubiner is chair of the Patent Prosecution Practice Group. He has an intellectual property law practice,  emphasizing worldwide patent prosecution strategy and technology-based transactional matters. Prior to joining Heller Ehrman,  Dr. Krubiner was responsible for directing all aspects of domestic and international patent,  trade secrets,  trademark,  copyright,  unfair competition,  and technology-based transactional activities in the human and veterinary pharmaceutical,  medical diagnostic,  medical instrument,  ophthalmic,  cosmetic,  and dental product areas for a major pharmaceutical company. He is licensed to practice before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. Queens College,  City University of New York,  B.S.,  1961; University of California at Berkeley,  Ph.D.,  chemistry,  1965; Seton Hall University School of Law,  J.D.,  1974.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Julie Y. Mar-Spinola</B> (<I>Palo Alto</I>) Ms. Mar-Spinola has substantial experience in patent cases involving semiconductor technology,  personal computer architecture technology,  wafer inspection systems,  and highway paving equipment; trade secret and copyright litigation,  involving operating system and application software; and counseling clients on various intellectual property matters. She is licensed to practice before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office and acts as special counsel for the firm. San Jose State University,  B.A.Ch.,  1984; Santa Clara University School of Law,  J.D.,  1987.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Pamela S. Palmer</B> (<I>Los Angeles</I>) Ms. Palmer has litigated and advised clients concerning a wide range of commercial and business issues,  including unfair competition,  trademark,  and trade secrets. Former law clerk to Judge Walter Ely of the U.S Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit. University of California,  Irvine,  B.A.,  1978; University of Southern California Law School,  J.D.,  1982.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jessica S. Pers</B> (<I>San Francisco</I>) Ms. Pers practices civil litigation with an emphasis on intellectual property,  trademark,  and copyright disputes in both the literary and computer software fields and related to the food industry. She has counseled numerous clients in the computer industry and various manufacturing and service fields on trademark,  copyright,  and antitrust issues. Yale University,  A.B.,  1971; Harvard University Graduate School of Education,  Ed.M.,  1973; University of California at Berkeley,  Boalt Hall School of Law,  J.D.,  1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John W. Phillips</B> (<I>Seattle</I>) Mr. Phillips' intellectual property experience includes two patent infringement lawsuits venued in the Western District of Washington and numerous copyright and trademark cases and litigation over software property and licensing rights. Former law clerk to Associate Justice Robert F. Utter of the Washington Supreme Court. Colgate University,  B.A.,  1977; Stanford Law School,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael K. Plimack</B> (<I>San Francisco</I>) Mr. Plimack has litigated and advised clients on patent,  copyright,  trademark,  and trade secret protection. He has published articles on the copyright protection of computer programs. Former law clerk to Judge James R. Browning of the U.S Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit. Brown University,  A.B.,  1983; University of California at Berkeley,  Boalt Hall School of Law,  J.D.,  1986.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William Schmonsees</B> (<I>Palo Alto</I>) Dr. Schmonsees writes and files patents on drug delivery,  peptides,  neurotropic factors,  and gene therapy. He is licensed to practice before U.S. Patent and Trademark Office and acts as special counsel to the firm. Villanova University,  B.S,  1968; Wayne State University,  Ph.D.,  physical chemistry,  1974; University of Delaware Law School,  J.D.,  1984.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Peter A. Wald</B> (<I>San Francisco</I>) Mr. Wald has a litigation practice emphasizing complex commercial litigation,  including significant intellectual property disputes. His principal clients include computer hardware,  software and video game developers and manufacturers,  and materials science and entertainment companies. Former law clerk to Judge James R. Browning of the U.S Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit. Brown University,  A.B.,  1974; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kirk G. Werner</B> (<I>San Francisco</I>) Mr. Werner has a litigation practice emphasizing complex commercial litigation which has included patent,  trade secret,  and copyright matters. He has had extensive experience in the areas of intellectual property and biotechnology. His clients have included video game manufacturers and pharmaceutical manufacturers. Princeton University,  A.B.,  1973; University of Virginia,  J.D.,  1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Stanley Young</B> (<I>Palo Alto</I>) Mr. Young has a civil litigation practice which has included patent litigation,  trademark and unfair competition disputes,  trade secret litigation,  copyright matters,  and other commercial disputes. Among his clients are companies in the computer and semiconductor industries. Stanford University,  A.B.,  A.M.,  1982; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  1985.<BR>
</UL>


