<TITLE>Kane,  Dalsimer,  Sullivan,  Kurucz,  Levy,  Eiseleand Richard
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Kane,  Dalsimer,  Sullivan,  Kurucz,  Levy,  Eisele and Richard
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>New York:</B> 711 Third Avenue,  New York,  NY 10017<BR>
Tel 212-687-6000  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-682-3485<BR>
<BR>
23 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers practice intellectual property law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>K</B>ane,  Dalsimer,  Sullivan,  Kurucz,  Levy,  Eisele and Richard and its predecessors have been engaged in the practice of intellectual property law since 1906. The Firm specializes in domestic and foreign patent,  trademark,  and copyright prosecution,  litigation,  and licensing; protection of trade secrets,  and related unfair competition issues including false advertising.<BR>BR><P>Kane,  Dalsimer,  Sullivan,  Kurucz,  Levy,  Eisele and Richard provides its clients with comprehensive strategies for protection of intellectual property assets. Each client's needs are assessed taking into account the client's domestic and worldwide marketing strategies,  competitive activity,  and the need to achieve maximum protection at a reasonable cost.<BR><BR><P>The Firm enforces its clients' rights in U.S. and foreign courts and before the International Trade Commission. The Firm counsels clients in avoiding and defending claims by others,  and provides advice on intellectual property asset assessment and valuation in mergers and acquisitions.<BR>
<BR><P>Kane,  Dalsimer,  Sullivan,  Kurucz,  Levy,  Eisele and Richard represents a broad range of U.S. and foreign businesses and individuals. The Firm's experience and client base is highly diversified. Firm clients include domestic,  multinational,  and foreign corporations,  trade associations,  universities,  research institutes,  and individuals. The Firm provides intellectual property counseling to clients in the following areas:<BR><BR><UL><LI>Automotive<LI>Biochemical<LI>Chemical including polymer chemistry<LI>Communications<LI>Computer and computer software<LI>Electronics<LI>Environmental processes and apparatus<LI>Fashion<LI>Flooring<LI>Foods and beverages<LI>Genetic engineering<LI>Hand tools and hardware<LI>Hospitality and travel<LI>Insurance and securities<LI>Medical Devices<LI>Metallurgy<LI>Optics<LI>Packaging<LI>Paper Making<LI>Photography<LI>Publishing<LI>Retailing<LI>Textiles<LI>Toys
<BR></UL><BR>
<LI><B>Joseph C. Sullivan</B>'s practice focuses on patent prosecution,  litigation,  and licensing. Member of the Association of the Bar of the City of New York; New York Intellectual Property Law Association; American Intellectual Property Law Association; American Institute of Electrical Engineers. Manhattan College,  B.E.E.; St. John's University,  LL.B.; New York University LL.M.,  trade regulation.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John Kurucz</B>'s practice focuses on patent prosecution,  litigation,  and licensing. He has lectured before several bar associations and the Practising Law Institute. Member of ABA; New York Intellectual Property Law Association; American Intellectual Property Law Association; National Society of Professional Engineers. Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute,  B.C.E.; Georgetown University,  J.D. Admitted in New York,  Pennsylvania,  and Virginia.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David H. T. Kane</B>'s area of concentration is trademark and patent counseling,  litigation,  licensing,  and trials. Member of intellectual property organizations and past president of New York Intellectual Property Law Association; president-elect of The Federal Circuit Bar Association. Williams College,  B.A.; University of Virginia,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Siegrun D. Kane</B>'s practice focuses on litigation and counseling in the areas of trademark infringement,  false advertising,  and unfair competition. Ms. Kane is the author of <I>Trademark Law: A Practitioner's Guide</I>. She is a frequent lecturer for PLI,  ABA,  and other CLE programs. She has been appointed to the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office Advisory Committee for Trademark Affairs,  1989- ; BNA's Patent,  Trademark and Copyright Journal Advisory Board,  1988- ; and PLI's Intellectual Property Advisory Committee. Mount Holyoke College,  B.A.; Harvard University,  LL.B.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gerald Levy</B>'s practice focuses on patent prosecution,  litigation,  and licensing.   Member of the Association of the Bar of the City of New York; New York State and American Bar Associations; New York Intellectual Property Law Association; American Intellectual Property Law Association. Columbia University,  B.S.,  M.E; Brooklyn Law School,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Joseph T. Eisele</B>'s practice focuses on patents. He is a member of the Connecticut Patent Law Association; American Intellectual Property Law Association. Hofstra College,  B.A.; Brooklyn Law School,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Virginia R. Richard</B> has extensive experience in U.S. and international trademark and copyright litigation,  licensing,  and prosecution. She is a frequent lecturer on trademark and copyright litigation and a contributor to publications in the intellectual property field. Manhattanville College,  B.A.; New York University,  LL.B.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Ronald R. Santucci</B>'s practice focuses on patent prosecution,  litigation,  and licensing. Member of the ABA; New York Intellectual Property Law Association; American Intellectual Property Law Association; and Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers. Manhattan College,  B.C.E.; New York Law School,  J.D.<BR></UL><BR>


