<P>
<P>
<P><B>F</B>ounded 75 years ago,  Kaye,  Scholer has one of the largest litigation practices in the country and is well recognized in the fields of intellectual property litigation,  antitrust law,  and licensing. The firm was a pioneer among general practice firms in intellectual property litigation. Its involvement in patent litigation,  for instance,  goes back 20 years to the landmark patent-antitrust suit over Xerox's patents in the copier industry,  which culminated in the firm's successful defense of Xerox in the longest federal civil jury trial to date.
<P><BR><P>Kaye,  Scholer's practice covers all major areas of intellectual property litigation. The firm's Patent Group,  for example,  represents clients in diverse industries in high-profile patent litigation as well as in non-litigated matters requiring counseling and the rendering of opinions. Biotechnology,  pharmaceuticals,  medical devices,  fibers,  electronics,  and aerospace are among the industries for which Kaye,  Scholer regularly litigates patent matters. The firm has prosecuted ten multidistrict patent infringement actions on behalf of leading worldwide pharmaceutical and medical device companies relating to cardiovascular drugs,  and numerous other matters involving electronic air traffic control systems,  gyroscopes,  and plastic fibers. Among the Group's successes is a landmark case in which the firm prevailed in the longest biotechnology patent infringement trial to date. The firm also handles extensive patent opinion work; patent interference and reexamination proceedings; technology-based licensing and joint venture agreements; and related distribution and franchising arrangements. Many group members have degrees in engineering or the sciences and are admitted to practice before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office (PTO). The firm also counsels clients on the selection and use of trademarks,  prosecutes their state and federal trademark applications,  and regularly appears before the PTO in opposition and cancellation proceedings. In addition,  the firm has experience in advertising challenges before the National Advertising Division of the Council of the Better Business Bureau.<BR><P>The firm also litigates major trademark,  trade dress,  and false advertising matters for leading companies in a wide range of industries,  including cosmetics,  pharmaceuticals,  chemicals,  apparel,  food,  and luggage. Illustrative cases include the defense of Rhone-Poulenc,  Rorer,  Inc. in a false advertising suit over antacid products; the defense of a leading food manufacturer in false advertising suits concerning breakfast foods; and the representation of a major oil company in NAD proceedings. Kaye,  Scholer is also active in litigating copyright matters for members of the publishing industry and has represented Art Buchwald in his successful suit concerning the use of his idea for the movie <I>Coming to America</I>.<BR>
<BR><P>The partners in the intellectual property group include:<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Thomas L. Creel</B> is an experienced intellectual property litigator; he has appeared before the courts,  the International Trade Commission,  and the PTO. For example,  he represented Nippon Steel in successfully challenging the amorphous metals patents before the ITC. Mr. Creel lectures extensively on intellectual property law,  and,  since 1983,  has taught patent law at the Columbia University School of Law. University of Kansas,  B.S.,  1960; University of Michigan,  LL.B.,  1963.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Steven J. Glassman</B> is an experienced litigator and regularly handles patent litigations. For example,  he played a major role in the nifedipine patent cases. Before joining Kaye Scholer in 1976,  he was chief civil appellate attorney in the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Southern District of New York,  a patent examiner,  and an assistant chief of NASA's Technology Utilization Division. Massachusetts Institute of Technology,  B.S.,  1964; Georgetown University,  J.D.,  1968.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Joel Katcoff</B>,  who has a background in computer science,  has had extensive experience litigating in many areas including patents and antitrust. Much of his work has involved developing and presenting expert testimony in various areas of technology and economics. Brandeis University,  B.A.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1977; Harvard University,  J.D.,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Pierce O'Donnell</B> is an experienced litigator and was lead counsel in the <I>Coming to America</I> case. He has litigated numerous cases and counseled clients concerning trade dress,  copyright,  and trade secret law and idea theft,  as well as compensation and royalty issues in those areas. Mr. O'Donnell is a former law clerk to former U.S. Supreme Court Justice Byron R. White and is a fellow of the American Law Institute. Georgetown University,  B.A.,  1969,  J.D.,  1972; Yale University,  LL.M.,  1975.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Milton Sherman</B> is an experienced litigator with a graduate degree in electrical engineering who has handled major litigation in diverse areas including patents and trade secrets. He has lectured on technology-related litigation and the fundamentals of civil litigation. Columbia University,  A.B.,  B.S.,  1963; University of Illinois,  M.S.,  1965,  J.D.,  1967.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Randolph S. Sherman</B> has represented many clients in suits and challenges concerning false advertising,  including the breakfast cereal and instant rice products cases,  as well as numerous antitrust,  trade dress,  and trademark disputes. Cornell University,  B.S.,  1966; New York University,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1969.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Thomas A. Smart</B>,  co-chair of the group and lead counsel in the Rorer antacid case,  has litigated a wide variety of trademark,  trade dress,  trade secret,  copyright,  and false advertising cases. He has published and lectured on these subjects. Dartmouth College,  A.B.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1974; University of Pennsylvania,  J.D.,  1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gerald Sobel</B>,  co-chair of the group,  is an experienced litigator and regularly handles patent and other intellectual property cases. He was lead counsel in the Xoma and nifedipine patent cases,  and tried the patent portion of the Xerox patent-antitrust trial. Mr. Sobel is an adjunct associate professor of law at the New York University School of Law. He has published numerous articles on litigation,  antitrust,  and patent topics and has also been active in chairing and lecturing on these issues. City College of New York,  B.E.E.,  1960; New York University,  LL.B.,  1963.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Aaron Stiefel</B>,  who has a graduate degree in chemistry,  has a wide range of litigation experience and has frequently represented clients in technology-relatedmatters,  including patent litigations. Yeshiva University,  B.A.,  1978,  M.A.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1978; Harvard University,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William E. Thompson,  Jr.</B>'s practice covers the entire range of intellectual property matters,  with principal emphasis on litigation,  counseling,  and technology transfer. Mr. Thompson is an accomplished trial lawyer with extensive experience in complex patent infringement and other intellectual property disputes. His successful litigation of pharmaceutical,  biotechnical,  chemical,  engineering,  and computer technology cases has made him a recognized practitioner in his field. Mr. Thompson is resident in the firm's Los Angeles office. Bucknell University,  B.S.Ch.E.,  1957; Georgetown University,  J.D.,  1963.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Fredric Yerman</B> is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers. He regularly litigates cases involving,  and lectures on,  many areas of intellectual property law including trademarks,  trade dress,  copyrights,  false advertising,  and trade secrets. Brooklyn College,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1963; Columbia University,  LL.B.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1966.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Firm counsel who are members of the group include:<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard A. De Sevo</B> is a skilled litigator and has participated in numerous major trademark,  copyright,  antitrust,  trade regulation,  and false advertising cases including the Rorer antacid case as well as the General Foods breakfast cereal and instant rice products cases. He has published several articles in these fields and is a member of the editorial board of <I>The Trademark Reporter</I>. Syracuse University,  A.B.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1973; Georgetown University,  J.D.,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Mark D. Godler</B> has a background in advertising and has represented and counseled clients in all areas of copyright,  trademark,  and false advertising law. State University of New York at Stony Brook,  B.A.,  1976; New York University,  J.D.,  1982.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard G. Greco</B> is a skilled patent litigator and played a major role in the Xoma trial and the nifedipine patent cases. Pennsylvania State University,  B.A.,  with highest distinction,  1971; Columbia University,  J.D.,  1974.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
