<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Kenyon  & Kenyon
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Kenyon  & Kenyon
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>New York:</B> One Broadway,  New York,  NY 10004<BR>
Tel 212-425-7200  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-425-5288<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> 1025 Connecticut Avenue,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20036<BR>
Tel 202-429-1776  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-429-0796<BR>
<B>Frankfurt:</B> Bockenheimer Landstrasse 97-99,  60325 Frankfurt am Main,  Germany<BR>
Tel 69-97-58-05-0  <B>*</B>  Fax 69-97-58-05-99<BR>
<BR>
115 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers in intellectual property practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>K</B>enyon  & Kenyon is one of the largest,  oldest and most diversified law firms in the country concentrating on the practice of intellectual property law. Founded in 1879,  the Firm provides litigation,  prosecution,  licensing and counseling services for patents,  trademarks,  copyrights,  trade secrets,  and related matters. The Firm also is active in representing clients in unfair business and unfair trade matters,  including antitrust.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Perspective</H3></CENTER>

<P>Kenyon  & Kenyon is committed to comprehending our clients' products,  processes and services in the context of their industry. Understanding their business enables us to design and implement meaningful legal strategies to protect innovation essential to the health of the business,  and to avoid potential roadblocks. We help clients identify the appropriate form or forms of protection for their particular assets,  whether it be a patent,  copyright,  trademark,  trade secret,  licenses under those rights,  or a combination of these. We protect the value of these assets in court and at the ITC,  and also defend clients against claims by others.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Industry Experience</H3></CENTER>

<P>The Firm's experience spans the business spectrum. In technology we have worked for clients in such areas as computers (from hardware to software to databases),  biotechnology products and processes,  business machines,  pharmaceuticals,  and plastics. Additionally we have worked in aerospace,  photography,  medical devices,  metallurgy,  basic chemicals and petrochemicals,  environmental processes,  food and beverages,  transportation vehicles,  agribio products,  robotics,  and telecommunications. In other business areas,  we have represented clients in entertainment and the arts,  toys,  publishing,  travel,  sports,  marketing,  and advertising.<BR><P>Our lawyers address intellectual property matters in virtually any jurisdiction worldwide. To assist us abroad,  the Firm maintains a large network of foreign associates who assist in acquiring and protecting the intellectual property of our clients in their respective countries,  and with whom we can consult on matters of foreign intellectual property law. Recently,  the firm opened a European office in Frankfurt,  Germany,  from which we can more efficiently address the intellectual property needs of our clientele throughout Western and Eastern Europe.<BR>
<BR><P>Our Washington,  D.C. office gives us direct access to the nearby Patent and Trademark Office,  the Copyright Office,  the International Trade Commission,  and the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Clients</H3></CENTER>

<P>Kenyon  & Kenyon clients reflect a broad range of industries and geographic regions. Our clients include domestic and foreign businesses,  multinational corporations,  growth companies focused on emerging technologies,  universities,  research institutes,  and individual inventors.<BR><P>Representative clients include: American Home Products,  Automatic Data Processing (ADP),  BASF,  British Aerospace,  Cabot Corp.,  Ciba-Geigy,  Coca-Cola,  Colgate-Palmolive,  Cooper Industries,  Digital Equipment Corp.,  Exxon,  General Electric PLC,  Genetics Institute,  Himont,  Hiram Walker  & Sons,  Hitachi,  L'Air Liquide,  Lever Brothers,  Nippon Steel,  Olympus Optical,  Pharmacia,  Rayovac,  Robert Bosch,  Schering Plough,  Siemens,  Teva Pharmaceutical Industries Ltd.,  Thomson Consumer Electronics,  Toyota Motor,  the Upjohn Company and Xerox.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Recent Cases</H3></CENTER>

<P>Kenyon  & Kenyon successfully defended a subsidiary of Teva Pharmaceutical Industries Ltd. in an International Trade Commission investigation concerning a patent covering a process used in the making of diltiazem hydrochloride,  a billion-dollar-a-year drug useful in treating various cardiovascular diseases. On behalf of the Montgomery County Association of Realtors,  Inc.,  the Firm convinced the U.S. District Court of the District of Maryland that a computer database containing real estate listings possessed a degree of creativity and was,  therefore,  copyrightable. On behalf of American Home Products,  the Firm successfully enjoined a major competitor from using the client's patented oral contraceptive. In another recent case,  Kenyon  & Kenyon successfully defended Toyota and a number of other prominent automobile importers against a highly publicized,  but eccentric,  windshield wiper inventor who had previously won multimillion-dollar verdicts from Ford and Chrysler. On behalf of Oscar Mayer,  the Firm obtained a $10 million jury verdict and an injunction against ConAgra on patents concerning food additives. Kenyon  & Kenyon also recently won a precedent-setting case for Lever Brothers against the U.S. Customs Service in which goods made by a foreign affiliate were barred from importation because they were physically different from the identically marked U.S. goods.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Robert T. Tobin</B> is Kenyon  & Kenyon's managing partner. He has over 30 years' experience in litigation and counseling concerning all aspects of intellectual property including patents,  trade secrets,  trademarks,  and copyrights. Manhattan College,  B.E.E.; Boston College Law School,  J.D.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
