<HEAD>
<TITLE>King  & Spalding
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>King  & Spalding
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Atlanta:</B> 191 Peachtree Street,  Atlanta,  GA 30303-1763<BR>
Tel 404-572-4600  <B>*</B>  Fax 404-572-5100<BR>
<B>Washington: </B>1730 Pennsylvania Avenue,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20006-4706<BR>
Tel 202-737-0500  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-626-3737<BR>
<B>New York:</B> 120 West 45th Street,  New York,  NY 10036-4003<BR>
Tel 212-556-2100  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-556-2222<BR>
<B>Houston: </B>1100 Louisiana Street,  Suite 3300,  Houston,  TX 77002-5219<BR>
Tel 713-751-3200  <B>*</B>  Fax 713-751-3290<BR>
<BR>
315 lawyers  <B>*</B>  23 lawyers in the Intellectual Property and Technology group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profile in the following other directory:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/king.html"> White Collar Crime</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>K</B>ing  & Spalding's Intellectual Property and Technology (IPT) group provides both litigation and transaction services for the creation,  transfer,  and licensing of technology. Current profiles include:
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Trademark,  Copyright,  and PatentCounseling and Litigation</H3></CENTER>

<P>King  & Spalding serves as general counsel to the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games,  Inc. (ACOG) for the 1996 Summer Olympic Games. Our IPT group directs the worldwide trademark and copyright protection program for the 1996 Games. We have developed and implemented similar worldwide protection programs for many other clients. The IPT group is also actively involved in a full range of patent,  trademark,  trade dress,  copyright,  and related litigation and counseling matters on a nationwide basis for a large number of well-known trademark owners,  including The Coca-Cola Company and The Ritz-Carlton Hotel Company.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Intellectual Property  & Technology Transactions</H3></CENTER>

<P>King  & Spalding acts in a wide range of transactions throughout the world exploiting intellectual property and technology assets. The IPT group is particularly active in the fields of telecommunications and computer software. The firm represents Sprint Corporation in various domestic and international telecommunications ventures. We also represent A.D.A.M. Software,  Inc.,  in the global licensing of its interactive anatomical software. The IPT group has represented leading outsourcing vendors and customers,  in a variety of computer services transactions. The firm's IPT group has also assisted a number of clients in structuring complex and innovative financing vehicles based upon intellectual property assets. Our IPT group also represents ACOG in the sale of sponsorships and worldwide television rights for the 1996 Olympic Games.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>John C. Staton,  Jr.</B> (<I>Atlanta; 404-572-4985</I>) Counsel to Georgia Tech Research Corporation. Extensive experience in patent and trademark matters and problems relating to product distribution.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Horace H. Sibley</B> (<I>Atlanta; 404-572-4814</I>) Senior transaction counsel. Chairman of the Board of the Georgia Center for Advanced Telecommunications Technology. Coordinates the firm's work on behalf of ACOG.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Clarence H. Ridley</B> (<I>Atlanta; 404-572-4761</I>) Senior transaction counsel. Coauthor of a leading treatise on computer software,  <I>Computer Software,  Forms and Commentary</I>,  published by Warren,  Gorham and Lamont. Represents clients in a wide range of intellectual property transactions.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Joseph R. Bankoff</B> (<I>Atlanta; 404-572-4796</I>) Senior litigator with substantial experience in technology and communications matters,  including libel,  privacy,  and programming rights. Television counsel to ACOG.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Bruce W. Baber</B> (<I>Atlanta; 404-572-4826</I>) Extensive litigation experience in patent,  trademark,  and copyright disputes. Represents The Coca-Cola Company in significant trademark litigation.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William G. Roche</B> (<I>Atlanta; 404-572-4936</I>) Represents clients in merger,  acquisition,  licensing,  and joint venture transactions involving technology-based assets. Counsel to A.D.A.M. Software Inc.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Beth Hornbuckle</B> (<I>Atlanta; 404-572-3413</I>) Lead marketing counsel for ACOG. Focuses on complex transactions involving intellectual property marketing,  licensing,  research and development,  and joint ventures.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Louis N. Jameson</B> (<I>Atlanta; 404-572-3568</I>) Represents clients in intellectual property litigation,  with emphasis on disputes for unfair competition and infringement of patents,  trademarks,  and copyrights.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Joan L. Dillon</B> (<I>Atlanta; 404-572-4873</I>) Senior counsel on worldwide trademark law and practice,  including prosecution,  licensing,  and litigation. Member of the Board of Directors of the International Trademark Association. Oversees ACOG's international trademark protection program.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Thomas B. Gaines,  Jr.</B> (<I>Atlanta; 404-572-4933</I>) Specializes in licensing of intellectual property assets with emphasis on merchandising,  electronic data interchange and computer software development. Represents ACOG in its merchandise licensing program.<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
