<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Kramer,  Levin,  Naftalis   & Frankel</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL><CENTER><H2>Intellectual Property</H2><H3>Kramer,  Levin,  Naftalis   & Frankel</H3></CENTER><CENTER><B>New York:</B> 919 Third Avenue,  New York,  NY 10022<BR>Tel 212-715-9100  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-715-8000  <B>*</B>  Home page: <AHREF="http://www.kramer-levin.com/">www.kramer-levin.com</A><BR><BR>150 lawyers  <B>*</B>  7 lawyers in intellectual property practice<BR></CENTER><P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR><UL><BR>   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/kramer.html"> Antitrust</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/kramer.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/kramer.html"> Corporate Securities</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/kramer.html"> ERISA</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/kramer.html"> Labor</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/kramer.html"> Product Liability</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/kramer.html"> White Collar Crime</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/kramer.html"> Workout</A></UL><P><P><P><B>K</B>ramer Levin offers a unique blend of major-firm capabilities coupled with thepersonalized attention and responsiveness found in smaller firms.<P><BR><P>Our intellectual property lawyers are engaged in litigation at both the trialand appellate level; in licensing and other transactional work; and in counseling clientson copyright,  trademark,  trade secrets,  and unfair competition issues. We have alsoadvised and assisted clients with respect to proposed copyright legislation.<BR><CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Experience and Clients</H3></CENTER><P>Our firm has broad experience in litigating copyright and trademark actions. We havehandled false advertising,  product disparagement,  and trademark counterfeiting, diversion,  and licensing cases for major consumer products and service companies such asProcter  & Gamble,  Johnson  & Johnson,  and Bell Atlantic. We successfully representedMills Music,  Inc.,  before the U.S. Supreme Court in <I>Mills Music </I>v. <I>Snyder</I>, a pivotal copyright decision that determines the allocation of millions of dollars ofroyalties between songwriters and music publishers.<BR><P>In 1990-1991,  our firmrepresented a proposed class of 40, 000 songwriters and music publishers in an actionwhich claimed that Sony Corporation was contributorily infringing the copyrights of themembers of the class through the manufacture and sale of digital audio tape (DAT)recorders and blank cassettes. Our firm has also handled numerous trademark and copyrightinfringement disputes,  including a series of enforcement actions prosecuted for LizClaiborne,  Inc.<BR><BR><P>Our litigation efforts are complemented by the work of our corporate lawyers,  whorepresent clients in transactions affecting intellectual property,  increasingly focusingon the computer industry.<BR><BR><UL><BR><LI><B>Marvin E. Frankel</B> heads our litigation practice and chairs the firm'smanagement committee. Mr. Frankel has argued more than 20 cases before the U.S. SupremeCourt,  including <I>Mills Music </I>v.<I> Snyder</I>. He served as a U.S. District Judgein the Southern District of New York from 1965 to 1978. He has represented clients intrademark and copyright infringement suits. Assistant to U.S. Solicitor General, 1952-1956. Professor of law,  Columbia University,  1962-1965. Chair,  Lawyers Committeefor Human Rights,  1980- . Queens College,  A.B.,  1943; Columbia University,  LL.B., 1948; editor-in-chief,  <I>Columbia Law Review</I>.<BR><BR><LI><B>Harold P. Weinberger</B>'s practice includes false advertising and productdisparagement law. Apart from numerous recent matters for Procter  & Gamble,  Johnson  &Johnson,  and others,  Mr. Weinberger has lectured on false advertising issues at tradeand legal conferences. Law clerk,  Judge Paul R. Hays,  U.S. Court of Appeals for theSecond Circuit,  1970-1971. City College of the City University of New York,  B.A.,  1967;Columbia University,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1970; notes and comments editor, <I>Columbia Law Review</I>.<BR><BR><LI><B>Michael S. Oberman</B> represents clients in copyright and trademark infringementcases,  and also counsels clients on intellectual property issues. With Mr. Frankel,  hewas responsible for the recently settled DAT action against Sony. Law clerk,  Judge MiltonPollack,  U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York. Columbia University, A.B.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1969; Harvard University,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1972.<BR><BR><LI><B>Alan R. Friedman</B> represents clients in trademark infringement cases andcounsels clients on trademark issues. Law clerk,  Judge M. Joseph Blumenfeld,  U.S.District Court for the District of Connecticut,  1976-1977. Hamilton College,  A.B., 1973; Yale University,  J.D.,  1976.<BR><BR><LI><B>Kenneth P. Kopelman</B> represents clients in a variety of intellectual propertytransactions,  and has extensive experience in acquisition,  licensing,  and joint venturetransactions involving trademarks and software. He has advised a number of companies inthe software and multimedia development areas. London School of Economics and PoliticalScience; Cornell University,  A.B.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1973; Columbia University, J.D.,  1976.<BR><BR><LI><B>Jonathan M. Wagner</B>'s practice includes false advertising and productdisparagement cases. Law clerk,  Judge Charles P. Sifton,  U.S. District Court for theEastern District of New York,  1983-1984. Haverford College,  B.A.,  with honors,  1980;Columbia University,  J.D.,  1983; Phi Beta Kappa; Harlan Fiske Stone Scholar; editor, <I>Columbia Law Review</I>.<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR></UL></UL></BODY></HTML>
