<HEAD>
<TITLE>Lowe,  Price,  LeBlanc & Becker
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Lowe,  Price,  LeBlanc & Becker
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Alexandria:</B> 99 Canal Center Plaza,  Suite 300,  Alexandria,  VA 22314<BR>
Tel 703-684-1111  <B>*</B>  Fax 703-684-1124  <B>*</B>  E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:cfalb@ipfirm.cais.com">cfalb@ipfirm.cais.com</A><BR>
<BR>
40 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers in intellectual property practice and litigation<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>L</B>owe,  Price,  LeBlanc  & Becker provides clients in the United States and around the world with a full range of services in the field of intellectual property law. Our practice involves patent,  trademark,  and copyright matters,  and related issues such as unfair competition,  trade secrets,  and antitrust.
<P><BR><P>Our attorneys and agents specialize in obtaining and enforcing patents,  and we consistently rank in the top ten firms in the United States based on the number of patents issued per year. The firm's patent practice extends to all technical disciplines,  including the electrical and electronic arts,  with special emphasis on technologies related to computer hardware and software,  the mechanical arts,  the chemical arts (from inorganic to polymer chemistry),  and biotechnology.<BR><P>The firm has experience in clearing trademarks and in filing and prosecuting trademark applications in the United States and around the world. We counsel clients on the use,  protection,  and enforcement of trademarks and trade dresses. The firm's attorneys have litigated trademark,  trade dress,  and unfair competition disputes in state,  federal,  and international forums.<BR>
<BR><P>We handle a full range of licensing matters,  from reviewing and providing opinions on draft license clauses and agreements,  to assisting in license negotiations,  drafting license agreements,  and enforcing signed license agreements. Our broad licensing experience enables us to go beyond conventional procedures and develop strategies designed to expand and extend licensing terms and financial opportunities as they relate to both patentable and nonpatentable assets.<BR>
<BR><P>The firm's copyright practice offers advice on the existence and scope of copyright protection,  validity of copyrights and registrations,  authorship and ownership of copyrighted works,  infringement and damages,  and Copyright Office regulations. We also advise clients and negotiate on their behalf with respect to copyright issues and in relation to other types of contracts.<BR>
<BR><P>Our litigators possess trial skills in bench and jury trials as well as knowledge of all areas of intellectual property law and expertise in diverse technical areas.<BR>
<BR><P>Many of our attorneys are former patent examiners,  several of whom have also served as administrative patent judges and expert witnesses. Advanced technology degrees among the attorneys complement their legal skills.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Allan M. Lowe</B> has over 30 years of experience in writing and prosecuting patent applications as well as rendering infringement and validity opinions. He specializes in all aspects of electronics,  including computers,  as well as in certain aspects of physics and mechanical engineering,  and lectures on these topics.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert L. Price</B> is involved in obtaining worldwide patent protections for complex chemical inventions including in the inorganic and organic chemistry,  biochemistry and biotechnical areas,  and is experienced in interference proceedings and in counseling clients in validity and infringement matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Stephen A. Becker</B> has his practice primarily directed to patent procurement and licensing matters,  with special emphasis on electrical and computer-related inventions. He is the author of various publications,  including the <I>Patent Applications Handbook</I> (1992,  1993,  1994,  and 1995) published by Clark Boardman Callaghan.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert E. LeBlanc</B> is involved in patent procurement and the licensing of intellectual property,  principally in the field of telecommunications. He has authored many publications,  and for over ten years was an adjunct professor of trademark and unfair competition law at Georgetown University.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Benjamin J. Hauptman</B> is involved in preparing and prosecuting patent applications in the complex mechanical arts and in counseling clients in all aspects of related patent matters. He is also an adjunct professor of law at Franklin Pierce Law Center.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kenneth E. Krosin</B> specializes in patent,  trademark,  and unfair competition litigation and related validity and infringement matters,  and has counseled clients in numerous licensing matters. He has written and lectured extensively.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Frank P. Presta</B> is involved primarily in prosecuting trademark applications,  in the litigation of trademark and unfair competition matters,  and in related licensing matters. He has also written and lectured on various trademark topics.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Charles D. Ossola</B> specializes in litigation in all areas of intellectual property,  with particular emphasis in trademark,  copyright,  and unfair competition matters. His experience also includes contract negotiations and business transactions. He has written and lectured on various trademark and copyright matters and serves on the advisory board of several intellectual property law journals.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gilberto M. (Ybet) Villacorta</B> specializes in the life sciences,  including such practice areas as biotechnology,  biochemistry,  immunology,  drug therapy/discovery,  imaging,  and complex medical devices,  including biosensors. He has experience in legal issues concerning patentability,  validity,  infringement,  litigation,  foreign patent opposition,  prosecution,  licensing,  portfolio planning,  peer review/due diligence studies,  financing/partnering,  and general counseling.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
