<HEAD>
<TITLE>Marshall,  O'Toole,  Gerstein,  Murray  & Borun
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Marshall,  O'Toole,  Gerstein,  Murray  & Borun
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Chicago:</B> 6300 Sears Tower,  233 South Wacker Drive,  Chicago,  IL 60606<BR>
Tel 312-474-6300  <B>*</B>  Fax 312-474-0448<BR>
<BR>
44 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers practice intellectual property law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>M</B>arshall,  O'Toole provides a full range of services in intellectual property law and related litigation for domestic and international clients.
<P><BR><P>Experienced firm attorneys have litigated cases valued at well over $1 billion. The same intensity is devoted where the amount of damage recovery is secondary. We conduct thorough preliminary investigations and implement efficient discovery practices in preparing for jury and bench trials. We are particularly experienced at creating breakthrough opportunities via preliminary injunction,  seizures,  and summary judgment. A hallmark of our practice is the effective use of models,  animation,  video,  and electronic/print graphics to drive home key points. At the appellate level,  the firm has accounted for landmark decisions in both the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit and the U.S. Supreme Court. Recognizing the importance of alternative dispute resolution,  our attorneys also engage in arbitration and mediation proceedings,  serving as arbitrators and mediators,  as well as representing clients. Members of the firm serve as court-appointed special masters.<BR><P>Patent prosecution practice includes patentability searches,  preparation of patentability opinions,  and the preparation,  filing,  and prosecution of patent applications,  as well as reexaminations and reissue proceedings. We undertake all phases of interference and appellate proceedings before the Patent and Trademark Office and provide intellectual property counsel regarding scope of protection,  licensing,  mergers,  and acquisitions. Our foreign practice involves participation in revocation,  extension,  and opposition proceedings,  as well as the prosecution of foreign patent applications. We likewise represent foreign associates and companies seeking patent protection in the United States and counsel foreign clients regarding patent infringement,  licensing,  and validity issues.<BR>
<BR><P>Our litigation and patent prosecution practice encompasses all areas of technology with a strong orientation to the electronic,  mechanical,  chemical,  and biological sciences,  including protein chemistry,  molecular biology,  immunology,  pharmacology,  and all recombinant technologies.<BR>
<BR><P>In the trademark field,  our firm also provides clients with the registration and enforcement of trademarks and service marks. Trademark searches include conducting computerized trademark searches,  filing trademark applications,  prosecuting opposition and cancellation proceedings,  maintaining registered marks,  and computerized monitoring of client registration for renewal and infringing marks of others.<BR>
<BR><P>Representative clients include: Abbott Laboratories,  Amgen Inc.,  Dow Corning Corp.,  General Instrument Corp.,  Helene Curtis,  Inc.,  Inland Steel Company,  International Paper Co.,  National Gypsum Company,  PPG Industries,  Inc.,  Procter  & Gamble Co.,  Sara Lee Corporation,  The Upjohn Co.,  and the University of Illinois.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Michael F. Borun</B> has represented clients in a wide variety of intellectual property matters,  principally involving patent prosecution and litigation. He has extensive experience in domestic and foreign patent prosecution in biotechnology and chemical and pharmaceutical technologies,  including appeals and interferences.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Allen H. Gerstein</B>'s practice is devoted to the litigation of a wide variety of business disputes,  from contracts,  employment agreements,  securities fraud,  and libel,  to patents,  trademarks,  copyrights,  and trade secrets. Antitrust matters include <I>Walker Process </I>v.<I> FMC</I>. He has wide experience in trying such disputes to juries and the use of alternative dispute resolution procedures.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Owen J. Murray</B> A primary emphasis in his practice has been in the area of intellectual property litigation involving patent,  trademark,  trade secret,  and related unfair competition matters. Mr. Murray has served as an arbitrator and mediator as well as an advocate in numerous proceedings. He also was appointed special master to try the liability issues in a recent patent infringement civil action.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Edward M. O'Toole</B> has been chief trial counsel in matters covering a wide variety of technical arts and legal issues. In addition to his U.S. trial practice,  he has experience in working with foreign trial counsel on patent infringement litigation in London,  Paris,  Johannesburg,  Stockholm,  Munich,  Sydney,  and Mexico City. He was recently lead trial counsel in the landmark case of <I>Amgen </I>v. <I>Chugai</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Nate F. Scarpelli</B> has prepared and prosecuted U.S. and foreign patent applications in various technical areas,  including computer-based teaching systems,  plasma display and memory panels,  addressing and driver circuits for display panels,  log periodic antennas,  microwave communication systems and components,  and telephone circuits and switching systems. His extensive litigation experience includes <I>University of Illinois Foundation </I>v.<I> Blonder-Tongue Labs</I>.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
