<HEAD>
<TITLE>Merchant,  Gould,  Smith,  Edell,  Welter  & Schmidt
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Merchant,  Gould,  Smith,  Edell,  Welter  & Schmidt
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Minneapolis:</B> 3100 Norwest Center,  90 South Seventh Street,  Minneapolis,  MN 55402<BR>
Tel 612-332-5300  <B>*</B>  Fax 612-332-9081<BR>
<B>Saint Paul:</B> 1000 Norwest Center,  55 East Fifth Street,  Saint Paul,  MN 55101<BR>
Tel 612-298-1055  <B>*</B>  Fax 612-298-1160<BR>
<B>Los Angeles:</B> Westwood Gateway II,  Suite 400,  11150 Santa Monica Boulevard, <BR>
Los Angeles,  CA 90025<BR>
Tel 310-445-1140  <B>*</B>  Fax 310-445-9031<BR>
<BR>
93 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers in intellectual property practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>M</B>erchant,  Gould,  Smith,  Edell,  Welter  & Schmidt is engaged exclusively in the practice of intellectual property law,  including patent,  trademark,  copyright,  unfair competition,  trade secret,  advertising,  and computer law,  and related litigation including both trials and appeals. With offices in Minneapolis,  St. Paul,  and Los Angeles and more than 90 practicing attorneys,  the firm is one of the largest intellectual property law firms in the United States.
<P><BR><P>Merchant  & Gould was ranked first in the Midwest and third in the United States in intellectual property as reported in the survey `Lawyers on Lawyers in America 1994, ' conducted by the Global Research Organization,  a division of Euromoney Publications PLC. In addition,  six Merchant  & Gould attorneys were named in the publication <I>The Best Lawyers in America 1995-96</I>.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Clients</H3></CENTER>

<P>The firm represents a broad spectrum of clients,  including individual inventors,  emerging companies,  Fortune 500 corporations,  governmental bodies,  and academic institutions. Clients represent diverse industries and technologies including chemistry,  biotechnology,  computer hardware and software,  medicine,  and manufacturing.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Technical Expertise</H3></CENTER>

<P>Merchant  & Gould has substantial technical expertise to serve the needs of its clients. A number of attorneys have advanced degrees,  including Ph.D.s,  in their areas of expertise. In addition the firm employs staff engineers,  patent agents,  legal assistants,  and drafting personnel to provide a full range of cost-effective intellectual property legal services.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Practice Areas</H3></CENTER>

<P>Approximately one-half of the firm's practice involves securing,  licensing,  maintaining,  and counseling relative to intellectual property matters. The other half involves intellectual property litigation. Merchant  & Gould is able to obtain or provide its clients with worldwide legal services in its area of practice through an extensive network of foreign associates.<BR><P>The Litigation Practice Group represents clients in trials and appeals involving complex patent,  trademark,  copyright,  unfair competition and false advertising matters. In addition to practice before federal and state courts,  the firm has an extensive practice before the International Trade Commission. The firm also provides a full range of services in other contested matters,  including patent interferences,  reissues,  reexaminations,  validity opinions,  infringement opinions and licensing. This group is chaired by <B>Douglas J. Williams</B>,  whose practice includes substantial defense work in patent jury trials,  trademark and corporate identification development programs,  and entertainment and the arts.<BR>
<BR><P>The General Practice Group handles all nonlitigation matters and consists of four separate practice areas. This group is chaired by <B>A. James Nelson</B>,  Ph.D.,  whose practice emphasizes domestic and international chemical and biotechnology patent practice and litigation.<BR>
<BR><P>The Chemical Practice Section handles all areas of chemistry,  medicine,  polymer science,  biotechnology,  compositions,  articles of manufacture,  and related arts. The members of the Chemical Practice Section represent clients in administrative and contested matters in the United States as well as countries throughout the world. The section is chaired by <B>John J. Gresens</B>,  whose practice emphasizes domestic and international chemical patent prosecution and litigation. <BR>
<BR><P>The Electronic and Computer Law Practice Section's main focus is obtaining intellectual property rights in electronic,  computer,  and software technology through patents,  copyrights,  trade secrets,  licensing and other related forms of protection,  as well as enforcement of such rights. The section is chaired by <B>John P. Sumner</B>,  whose practice includes intellectual property protection for software and other computer-related inventions.<BR>
<BR><P>The Trademark Section handles all aspects of searching,  registering,  protecting,  and policing trademarks and service marks. Advertising,  entertainment law,  and unfair competition issues are also covered. The section is chaired by <B>John A. Clifford</B>,  whose practice involves trademark law,  including oppositions,  cancellations,  and litigation. <BR>
<BR><P>The International Section handles intellectual property matters for the firm's international associates and clients. In addition,  the International Section represents the firm's domestic clients on various international intellectual property matters in foreign countries. This section is chaired by <B>Curtis B. Hamre</B>,  whose practice includes patent prosecution,  domestic and international business planning,  and licensing and trademark law.

</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
