<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>>Morgan  & Finnegan,  L.L.P.</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL><CENTER><H2>Intellectual Property</H2><H3>Morgan  & Finnegan,  L.L.P.</H3><B>New York:</B> 345 Park Avenue,  New York,  NY 10154<BR>Tel 212-758-4800  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-751-6849<BR><B>Washington:</B> 1299 Pennsylvania Avenue,  N.W.,  Suite 960 West,  Washington,  DC 20004<BR>Tel 202-857-7887  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-857-7929<BR><BR>95 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers practice in Intellectual Property<BR></CENTER><P><P><BR><BR><P><P><B>M</B>organ  & Finnegan provides a full range of services in the field of intellectual property,  including patents,  trademarks,  copyright of computer software,  trade secrets,  unfair competition,  and related antitrust areas. Our lawyers and in-house scientific advisers provide counseling in these areas as well as in licensing,  marketing,  technology transfer,  security interests,  and trade dress. The scientific training of our lawyers and advisers enables us to render legal services in many areas,  including biotechnology,  pharmaceuticals and medical devices,  consumer goods and services,  electronics,  computers and telecommunications,  plastics,  chemical and petroleum products and processes,  and mechanical and electrical devices.<P><CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Experience and Clients</H3></CENTER><P>For 100 years,  Morgan  & Finnegan has been active in obtaining patent and trademark protection for clients around the world. The firm has also been active through the years in litigating all aspects of intellectual property in state courts,  federal district and appeal courts,  the U.S. Court of Claims,  and the International Trade Commission. We represent individuals and small,  medium,  and large corporations. Representative clients include the National Institutes of Health,  Procter  & Gamble,  Mobil Oil Corp.,  Citicorp,  Glaxo,  IBM,  Rhone-Poulenc AG Company,  Rhone-Poulenc Rorer,  S.A.,  and Syntex.<BR><UL><BR><LI><B>John D. Foley</B> (<I>New York</I>) Concentrates on <I>inter partes</I> matters in chemical and pharmaceutical arts. Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute,  chemical engineering,  1946; Georgetown University National Law Center,  1951. Admitted in New York.<BR><BR><LI><B>John A. Diaz</B> (<I>New York</I>) Area of concentration is chemical and biotechnical matters. Lehigh University,  chemical engineering,  1952; George Washington University National Law Center,  1959. Admitted in New York.<BR><BR><LI><B>Thomas P. Dowling</B> (<I>New York</I>) Area of concentration is counseling and litigation in areas involving computers,  electronics,  and software. Member: National Panel of Arbitrators and the American Arbitration Association. Polytechnic University,  electrical engineering,  1958; St. John's University Law School,  1958. Admitted in New York.<BR><BR><LI><B>John C. Vassil</B> (<I>New York</I>) Concentrates on <I>inter partes</I> matters in chemical and pharmaceutical arts. Carnegie Institute of Technology,  chemical engineering,  1952; George Washington University National Law Center,  1958. Admitted in New York.<BR><BR><LI><B>Warren H. Rotert</B> (<I>New York</I>) Area of concentration is counseling and litigation in mechanical arts and a variety of intellectual property matters. Lafayette College,  B.S.,  administrative engineering,  1952; George Washington University National Law Center,  J.D.,  1959,  Phi Delta Phi,  Order of the Coif; patent editor,  <I>George Washington University Law Review</I>,  1959-1960. Admitted in Virginia and New York.<BR><BR><LI><B>Alfred P. Ewert</B> (<I>New York</I>) Area of concentration is counseling and litigation in areas involving electrical engineering and computers. University of Michigan,  electrical engineering,  1955; George Washington University National Law Center,  1961. Admitted in New York.<BR><BR><LI><B>David H. Pfeffer</B> (<I>New York</I>) Area of concentration is counseling and litigation in chemical plastics,  metallurgical,  and related patent matters,  trademarks,  trade secrets,  and unfair competitions. Member,  Panel of Arbitrators,  American Arbitration Association. College of the City of New York,  chemical engineering,  1956; New York University Law School,  1961,  LL.M.,  trade regulation,  1967; Order of the Coif. Admitted in New York.<BR><BR><LI><B>Harry C. Marcus</B> (<I>New York</I>) Concentrates on patent and trademark counseling,  litigation,  and appellate matters. Syracuse University,  mechanical engineering,  1961; New York University Law School,  1964. Admitted in New York.<BR><BR><LI><B>John F. Sweeney</B> (<I>New York</I>) Area of concentration is litigation involving consumer products. Carnegie Mellon University,  mathematics,  1968; Georgetown University National Law Center,  1973. Admitted in New York.<BR><BR><LI><B>Harry F. Manbeck,  Jr.</B> (<I>Washington</I>) Area of concentration is as a consultant and expert witness,  and litigation in patent and trademark matters. U.S. Commissioner of Patents and Trademarks,  1990-1992. General patent counsel,  General Electric Company,  1970-1990. Chair of the Patent,  Trademark,  and Copyright Section of the American Bar Association,  1989-1990; president of the Association of Corporate Patent Counsel,  1978-1979; and director of Intellectual Property Owners,  Inc.,  1985-1990. Awarded the Whitney North Seymour Medal of the American Arbitration Association,  1984. Lehigh University,  B.S.,  electrical engineering,  1949; University of Louisville Law School,  LL.B.,  1955. Admitted in Kentucky and Connecticut.</UL></UL></BODY></HTML>
