<TITLE>Morrison  & Foerster
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Morrison  & Foerster
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>San Francisco:</B> 345 California Street,  San Francisco,  CA 94104<BR>
Tel 415-677-7000  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-677-7522<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Brussels,  Denver,  Hong Kong,  London,  Los Angeles,  Irvine (California),  New York,  Palo Alto (California),  Sacramento,  Seattle,  Tokyo, <BR>
Walnut Creek (California),  Washington,  D.C.<BR>
<BR>
525 lawyers  <B>*</B>  65 lawyers in Intellectual Property Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/morrison.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/morrison.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/morrison.html"> Labor</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>F</B>ounded in San Francisco in 1883,  Morrison  & Foerster provides legal counsel and representation to many of the world's leading corporations. The firm's intellectual property practice is the work of an interdepartmental group of lawyers with experience in patent,  trademark,  copyright,  trade secret,  unfair competition,  technology transfer,  and licensing arrangements,  and related intellectual property matters.
<P><BR><P>Representative clients include Acuson Corporation,  Chips  & Technologies,  Inc.,  Chiron Corporation,  Fujitsu Limited,  Oracle Corporation,  Tandem Computers,  The 3DO Company,  and MTS,  Inc. (Tower Records).<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Reid G. Adler</B> (<I>Washington; 202-887-8761</I>) Prior to joining Morrison  & Foerster,  Mr. Adler directed the Office of Technology Transfer at the National Institutes of Health from 1989 to 1993. University of Maryland,  B.S.,  1975; George Washington University National Law Center,  J.D.,  1982.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Charles S. Barquist</B> (<I>Los Angeles; 213-892-5400</I>) Practice focuses on intellectual property litigation and dispute resolution. University of Michigan,  A.B. 1975; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Donald Chisum</B> (<I>Seattle; 206-685-2996</I>) Of counsel. Professor of law at University of Washington. Author of <I>Patents: A Treatise of the Law of Patentability,  Validity and Infringement</I>,  the premier reference text on patent law. Stanford University,  A.B.,  1966,  J.D.,  1968.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Thomas E. Ciotti</B> (<I>Palo Alto; 415-813-5702</I>) Mr. Ciotti has over 25 years of patent experience in corporations and law firms. Former chairperson of the Intellectual Property Law Section of the State Bar of California and president of the San Francisco Patent and Trademark Law Association. Mr. Ciotti is co-chair of Morrison  & Foerster's Patent Group. University of Michigan,  B.S.,  1961; J.D.,  1964.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Paul Goldstein</B> (<I>San Francisco; 415-723-0313</I>) Of counsel. Stella W. and Ira S. Lillick professor of law,  Stanford Law School. Author of <I>Copyright: Principles,  Law and Practice</I>,  published in 1989 and updated annually. Brandeis University,  B.A.,  1964; Columbia University,  J.D.,  1967.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael A. Jacobs</B> (<I>San Francisco; 415-677-7455</I>) Practice concentrates on the litigation of advanced technology matters. Current chairman of the computer program copyright protection subcommittee of the American Bar Association's Section on Patent,  Trademark,  and Copyright Law. Mr. Jacobs is co-chair of Morrison  & Foerster's Intellectual Property Group. Stanford University,  B.A.,  1977; Yale Law School,  J.D.,  1983.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gladys Monroy</B> (<I>Palo Alto; 415-813-5711</I>) Practice focuses on patent law and biotechnology. Dr. Monroy was on the faculties of both the New York Medical College and the University of California at San Francisco. Hunter College,  A.B.,  1957; New York University,  M.S.,  1968,  Ph.D.,  1973; University of San Francisco School of Law,  J.D.,  1986.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kate H. Murashige</B> (<I>Washington; 202-887-1553</I>) Dr. Murashige is a member of the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office Biotechnology Institute Board and the National Biotechnology Policy Board for the National Institutes of Health. Dr. Murashige is co-chair of Morrison  & Foerster's Patent Group. Washington University at St. Louis,  B.A.,  1956; University of California at Los Angeles,  Ph.D.,  1962; Santa Clara University School of Law,  J.D.,  1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Anthony M. Radice</B> (<I>New York; 212-468-8020</I>) Practice focuses on business litigation with emphasis in securities,  antitrust,  and intellectual property litigation. His intellectual property practice has included the U.S. Supreme Court argument in the patent-antitrust case that determined the limits of the patent jurisdiction of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit. Cornell University,  A.B.,  1966,  J.D.,  1969.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William I. Schwartz</B> (<I>San Francisco; 415-677-7449</I>) Practice focuses on business transactions and counseling related to advanced technology,  including license agreements,  development agreements,  joint ventures,  and acquisitions. Mr. Schwartz is co-chair of Morrison  & Foerster's Intellectual Property Group. Amherst College,  B.A.,  1976; University of Chicago Law School,  J.D.,  1983.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James R. Shay</B> (<I>San Francisco; 415-677-6394</I>) Practice focuses primarily on mechanical,  electromechanical,  and software technologies,  particularly in the medical device industry. Princeton University,  B.S.E.,  1980; Georgetown University Law Center,  J.D.,  1986.<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


