<HEAD>
<TITLE>Oblon,  Spivak,  McClelland,  Maier  & Neustadt,  P.C.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Oblon,  Spivak,  McClelland,  Maier  & Neustadt,  P.C.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Arlington:</B> Fourth Floor,  1755 Jefferson Davis Highway,  Arlington,  VA 22202<BR>
Tel 703-413-3000  <B>*</B>  Fax 703-413-2220  <B>*</B>  E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:oblonpat@oblon.com">oblonpat@oblon.com</A><BR>
<B>Other office:</B> San Jose (California)<BR>
<BR>
50 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers practice intellectual property law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>O</B>blon,  Spivak,  McClelland,  Maier  & Neustadt,  P.C.,  established in 1968,  has grown to be one of the largest full-service firms in the United States devoted solely to intellectual property. This rapid growth is attributed to the firm's focus on quality service to its clients. In addition to assembling an exceptional staff of technically and legally expert attorneys,  the firm has focused on addressing the needs and concerns of its clients to provide top-quality legal services,  as well as many collateral services,  including client education. The firm's practice includes every aspect of intellectual property law,  from federal court litigation,  representation at federal agencies,  prosecution of patent and trademark applications,  copyright registrations,  and maskwork applications,  to all necessary support services. The firm's clientele includes numerous multinational corporations that are among the most active in the intellectual property field; foreign and U.S. government agencies; numerous universities; and businesses of all sizes.
<P><BR><P>The firm represents a major U.S. university in a landmark biotechnology litigation against major U.S. corporations. The firm has represented several U.S. clients in actions against the U.S. Government in the U.S. Court of Federal Claims,  has represented many corporations in patent infringement actions involving jury trials,  and has handled litigation before the International Trade Commission. The firm is presently handling a large number of interferences for major U.S.- and foreign-based clients.<BR><P>The firm has an extensive patent and trademark prosecution practice before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. The firm has conducted and successfully concluded numerous significant reexaminations and reissue procedures,  as well as a large number of appeals to the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office Board of Appeals and the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Norman F. Oblon</B>,  who founded the firm in 1968 after receiving his law degree with honors from George Washington University,  is the managing partner of the Chemical and Biotechnology Practice Group,  and frequently lectures in patent law nationally and internationally.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Marvin J. Spivak</B>,  who cofounded the firm in 1968 after receiving his law degree with honors from George Washington University,  is the firm's managing partner. He is also a managing partner of the firm's Electrical/Mechanical Section.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>C. Irvin McClelland</B> is a member of the Board of Directors of the firm. He is involved in the management of prosecution and processing of applications within the Electrical/Mechanical Section of the firm and in the general management of administrative affairs within the firm.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gregory J. Maier</B> is a managing partner of the firm's Electrical/Mechanical Section. He has particular expertise in licensing and patent strategy planning and has published articles on a wide range of subjects from software protection to alternative dispute resolution.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Arthur I. Neustadt</B> is a managing partner of the firm's Litigation Department and has been actively involved in intellectual property litigation for the past 25 years. He has successfully tried jury and bench cases before federal district courts,  the U.S. Court of Federal Claims,  and the International Trade Commission. He has successfully argued appeals before regional circuit courts of appeal and the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard D. Kelly</B> is a member of the firm's Board of Directors and a litigation specialist. He has been lead counsel in both federal district court litigation and International Trade Commission litigation. In addition,  he has served as an expert witness in patent law matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Charles L. Gholz</B> specializes in litigation,  particularly patent interferences,  and has served as an expert witness in patent litigation. He has written and lectured widely on patent and intellectual property law and is an adjunct professor of patent law at George Mason University Law School.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jeffrey H. Kaufman</B> is the managing partner of the firm's Trademark and Copyright Group and practices primarily in the areas of trademark,  copyright,  and unfair competition law,  with an emphasis on litigation and matters before the Trademark Trial and Appeal Board.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
