<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul,  Weiss,  Rifkind,  Wharton  & Garrison
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Paul,  Weiss,  Rifkind,  Wharton  & Garrison
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>New York:</B> 1285 Avenue of the Americas,  New York,  NY 10019<BR>
Tel 212-373-3000  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-757-3990<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> 1615 L Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20036<BR>
Tel 202-223-7300  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-223-7420<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Paris,  Hong Kong,  Tokyo,  Beijing<BR>
<BR>
345 lawyers  <B>*</B>  20 lawyers concentrating in intellectual property law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/paul.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/paul.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/paul.html"> Corporate Securities</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/paul.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/paul.html"> ERISA</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/paul.html"> Product Liability</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/paul.html"> Workout</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>P</B>aul,  Weiss,  Rifkind,  Wharton  & Garrison's intellectual property practice is far-reaching and diverse,  from the defense of a major Japanese electronics firm accused of theft of computer secrets to the championing of copyright in Charlie Chaplin's films,  from the creation of a trademark trust for a renowned designer to the licensing of performance rights for Cole Porter's tunes. Our clients range from struggling playwrights to media giants,  from individual composers to the country's largest performing rights society,  from entrepreneurs to established industrial corporations.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Copyrights</H3></CENTER>

<P>Paul,  Weiss has extensive experience in mergers and acquisitions,  financings,  and licensing matters involving copyright (and other intellectual property) assets,  including motion picture,  television,  cable,  music,  stage,  and publishing rights,  and computer software. The firm has litigated many landmark cases,  from the seminal case of <I>Arnstein </I>v.<I> Porter</I>,  which established the standards of proof for copyright infringement,  to <I>CBS </I>v.<I> ASCAP</I>,  in which the Supreme Court upheld ASCAP's blanket licensing system for copyrighted musical works. In recent years,  we have successfully prosecuted and defended numerous copyright infringement actions,  involving the `Indiana Jones' character,  Star Trek &#174;,  and other copyrighted properties.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Patents and Trade Secrets</H3></CENTER>

<P>We have assisted clients in a broad spectrum of patent and trade secret matters (litigation,  acquisitions,  and licensing) involving numerous technical and scientific disciplines. In the litigation arena,  we have in recent years prosecuted and defended patent infringement claims in diverse fields; defended a major European manufacturer against a claim (ultimately settled) that it misappropriated jet engine technology; obtained injunctive relief to prevent a client's competitor from misappropriating computer know-how; and secured an unprecedented summary determination of noninfringement in a patent proceeding before the International Trade Commission.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Trademarks,  Unfair Competition,  and Advertising</H3></CENTER>

<P>We have litigated countless trademark,  unfair competition,  and advertising disputes over the years. In recent years,  for example,  we have successfully defended one of the nation's largest tobacco companies in a nine-month jury trial involving trademark,  unfair competition,  and antitrust claims; and prosecuted trademark,  unfair competition,  and related claims with respect to the use of the trademark Bayer &#174; in the United States. On behalf of our client Castrol Inc.,  we obtained injunctions halting national advertising campaigns of Quaker State and Pennzoil on the grounds that they were false and misleading. We have handled major transactions involving many renowned trademarks.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Lewis R. Clayton</B> Mr. Clayton has extensive experience in trademark,  advertising,  unfair competition,  and trade libel litigation,  and regularly counsels clients in those areas. He is chair of the Committee on Intellectual Property of the New York State Bar Association's Commercial and Federal Litigation Section. Harvard University,  B.A.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1975,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jay Cohen</B> Mr. Cohen's intellectual property practice focuses on patent and trade secret litigation. Cornell University,  A.B.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1977; Univer-sity of Chicago,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Peter L. FeLCher</B> Mr. FeLCher's intellectual property practice covers a broad range of matters,  including work in the copyright and right of privacy and publicity areas,  and mergers,  acquisitions,  and financings,  particularly in the entertainment area. Princeton University,  A.B.,  1960; Yale University,  LL.B.,  1963.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Martin Flumenbaum</B> Mr. Flumenbaum has had extensive trial and appellate experience. His intellectual property practice focuses on copyright,  trademark,  and trade secret litigation. He serves as counsel to ASCAP in copyright litigation. Columbia University,  A.B.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1971; Harvard University,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1974.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Carey R. Ramos</B> Mr. Ramos is coordinator of Paul,  Weiss's Intellectual Property Practice Group. His practice covers a wide spectrum of intellectual property matters,  including the negotiation of computer software and other intellectual property licenses,  mergers and acquisitions,  financings,  and litigation. Yale University,  B.A.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1976; Stanford University,  J.D.,  1979.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


