<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Popham,  Haik,  Schnobrich  & Kaufman,  Ltd.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Popham,  Haik,  Schnobrich  & Kaufman,  Ltd.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Minneapolis:</B> 222 South Ninth Street,  Suite 3300,  Minneapolis,  MN 55402<BR>
Tel 612-333-4800  <B>*</B>  Fax 612-334-8888<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> 655 Fifteenth Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20005<BR>
Tel 202-824-8000  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-824-8199<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Denver,  Miami<BR>
<BR>
233 lawyers  <B>*</B>  30 lawyers in intellectual property practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>P</B>opham,  Haik,  Schnobrich  & Kaufman,  Ltd. provides a wide range of legal services to business,  financial,  and industrial clients throughout the world. In addition to its nationally recognized trial and litigation practice,  the firm has an extensive national and international transactional and administrative law practice.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Intellectual Property Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>The Intellectual Property Practice Group of Popham,  Haik,  Schnobrich  & Kaufman,  Ltd. has recently expanded to include the former firm of Mason,  Fenwick  & Lawrence. Established in 1861,  Mason Fenwick was a leading firm in the field of intellectual property law.<BR><P>The attorneys in this practice group represent individuals,  business entities,  and academic institutions in a wide range of transactions and litigation involving patents,  trademarks,  copyrights,  trade secrets,  and unfair competition. This practice includes every aspect of intellectual property law including licensing,  counseling in intellectual property law,  international intellectual property protection,  protecting trade secrets,  franchising,  international trade actions,  trademark,  and patent searches and investigations,  semiconductor chip protection,  publicity rights,  and filing and prosecution of applications for patents,  trademarks,  and copyrights. Lawyers from this group work with the firm's other practice groups in antitrust,  employment-related issues,  business dissolutions,  mergers and acquisitions,  bankruptcy,  international trade,  and products liability.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Experience and Clients</H3></CENTER>

<P><I>Patent.</I> The firm serves a broad spectrum of foreign and domestic clients by providing prior art investigations,  preparation of patent applications and infringement,  and validity counseling and litigation. The attorneys specializing in patent practice have degrees in engineering or the sciences,  and have expertise in the mechanical,  chemical,  biotechnical,  electronic,  and computer fields,  so as to enable practice in all technical areas of patent law.<BR><P><I>Trademark.</I> The firm serves both foreign and domestic clients in every phase of the adoption and protection of trademarks,  service marks,  collective marks,  and certification marks. Clearance and registrability investigations together with infringement opinions by experienced trademark attorneys form the foundation for the adoption and use of marks.<BR>
<BR><P><I>Copyright.</I> Services offered to clients in the copyright field include infringement reviews,  counseling and litigation,  registration for all types of works,  and negotiation of computer,  music,  film,  publishing,  and sound recording agreements domestically and internationally.<BR>
<BR><P>Clients of Popham Haik in the area of intellectual property law include Mead Data Central,  Quaker State,  and Dr Pepper.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Partners</H3></CENTER>

<BR><UL><LI><B>Wayne G. Popham</B> (<I>Minneapolis</I>) Mr. Popham practices in the area of litigation,  including antitrust,  patent,  and trade secret matters. Mr. Popham is a graduate of the University of Minnesota Law School,  1953,  a member of the <I>Minnesota Law Review</I>,  and a former Minnesota state senator.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Roger W. Schnobrich</B> (<I>Minneapolis</I>) Mr. Schnobrich practices primarily in the general corporate and commercial law area. He represents a large number of corporations involved in a variety of business activities,  including construction,  manufacturing,  wholesaling,  theatrical entertainment,  computer software,  and medical products. Mr. Schnobrich is a graduate of the University of Minnesota Law School,  1954,  and a member of Phi Delta Phi and Beta Gamma Sigma.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Allen W. Hinderaker</B> (<I>Minneapolis</I>) Mr. Hinderaker is a commercial trial lawyer with an emphasis on intellectual property litigation. He represents local and national companies in litigation of copyright,  trademark,  patent,  and trade secrets rights,  including computer and licensing litigation. He was a law clerk to Judge Gerald W. Heaney,  U.S. Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit,  1974-1976. He is a <I>magna cum laude</I> graduate of the University of Minnesota Law School,  1974,  and a member of Phi Beta Kappa and Blue Key National Honor Fraternity.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Allen S. Melser</B> (<I>Washington</I>) Chair. Mr. Melser,  formerly chairman of Mason,  Fenwick  & Lawrence,  has 20 years of experience in intellectual property law including licensing,  counseling,  patent,  and copyright preparation and prosecution and litigation in the U.S. including the International Trade Commission,  the federal courts,  and the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit. He has experience in many technical disciplines including microelectronics,  computers and peripherals,  servo-control systems,  multimedia technology,  medical and surgical diagnostic technology,  paper-making equipment,  lasers,  xerography,  photography,  optics,  communications,  coatings,  mining,  petroleum equipment,  marine technology,  and railroad technology. Mr. Melser is editor-in-chief of an international journal of intellectual property law. Mr. Melser has a B.S. in electrical engineering and is a graduate of Georgetown University Law School.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Nathaniel A. Humphries</B> (<I>Washington</I>) Mr. Humphries,  formerly of Mason,  Fenwick  & Lawrence and a former patent examiner in the U.S. Patent Office,  has been practicing intellectual property law for over 29 years. In those years he has developed policies for corporations and universities for the protection of intellectual property and provided legal options with respect to infringement,  validity,  and other aspects of patents,  trademarks,  and trade secrets. He has handled the preparation and prosecution of U.S. and foreign patent applications in a wide variety of arts including the automotive,  textile,  agricultural,  and mining fields. He has handled interference proceedings and appeals,  license preparation and negotiations,  patent infringement litigation in federal courts and the U.S. International Trade Commission,  and appeals before the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit and other circuits. Mr. Humphries has degrees in mechanical engineering and meteorology and received his J.D. from George Washington University.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David C. Gryce</B> (<I>Washington</I>) Mr. Gryce,  formerly managing partner of Mason,  Fenwick  & Lawrence,  practices in all phases of trademark,  copyright,  and unfair competition law,  with emphasis in intellectual property litigation and transactional matters,  including licensing,  asset acquisitions,  stock purchases,  and franchising. He has counseled clients regarding domestic and international use and protection of trademarks and copyrights,  and is an editor of an international publication. Mr. Gryce is a graduate of the University of Denver College of Law,  1983,  and is a member of the Order of Saint Ives for outstanding scholarly achievement.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Paul A. Koches</B> (<I>Washington</I>) Mr. Koches has more than 15 years of experience in complex civil litigation,  including antitrust and intellectual property law cases. He represents primarily Fortune 500 corporations in federal and state courts throughout the country as well as before administrative agencies. He has been lead trial and appellate counsel in a variety of cases involving such issues as attempted monopolization,  tying and price discrimination,  and fraud and deceptive trade practices. Mr. Koches is a <I>cum laude</I> graduate of the University of Miami Law School,  1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Bruce B. McPheeters</B> (<I>Minneapolis</I>) Mr. McPheeters has more than 10 years of experience in securities law and financing,  intellectual property law,  and computer law. He has negotiated a variety of technology licenses and distribution agreements,  and has negotiated computer hardware and software agreements with vendors and users. He has served as a faculty member in legal and industry education seminars concerning computer law,  and has served as chair of the Minnesota State Bar Association Computer Law Section. Mr. McPheeters also has experience in the areas of trademark,  trade secret,  and copyright law. Mr. McPheeters is a graduate of the University of Southern California Law School,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>B. Parker Livingston,  Jr.</B> (<I>Washington</I>) Mr. Livingston,  formerly of Mason,  Fenwick  & Lawrence,  practices in trademark,  unfair competition,  and copyright law and has been practicing intellectual property law for over 21 years. He has extensive experience with the selection of trademarks and in <I>ex parte</I> and <I>inter partes</I> trademark practice before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. He handles trademark matters for a substantial number of foreign clients as well as domestic companies. He was staff assistant to the assistant commissioner for trademarks,  1976-1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Bruce H. Little</B> (<I>Minneapolis</I>) Mr. Little is a trial lawyer whose practice focuses on patent,  copyright,  trademark,  trade secret,  and computer litigation. He is chairman of the Intellectual Property Committee of the Computer Law Section of the Minnesota State Bar Association and Eighth Circuit reporter for the Intellectual Property Committee of the Litigation Section of the American Bar Association. Mr. Little has published several articles on computer and copyright law. He is a <I>cum laude</I> graduate of the University of Illinois College of Law,  1984.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John W. Provo</B> (<I>Minneapolis</I>) Mr. Provo practices in the areas of intellectual property and technology licensing. He advises corporations and intellectual property owners with respect to all aspects of domestic and international contract negotiations,  royalty and distribution arrangements,  finance protection strategies,  and licensing transactions. He is also a frequent speaker to business and professional groups on these topics. Mr. Provo is a <I>cum laude</I> graduate of the University of Minnesota Law School,  1983.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Cecilia M. Michel</B> (<I>Minneapolis</I>) Ms. Michel concentrates in the areas of intellectual property and litigation. Software licensing and copyright issue are two areas of her experience. Ms. Michel has represented clients in state and federal courts and is admitted to practice in Minnesota and California as well as the U.S. Supreme Court. She is a <I>cum laude</I> graduate of William Mitchell College of Law,  1983.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Bassam N. Ibrahim</B> (<I>Washington</I>) Mr. Ibrahim,  formerly of Mason,  Fenwick  & Lawrence,  practices in all areas of trademark,  unfair competition,  and copyright law,  including advising clients on securing,  maintaining and protecting intellectual property worldwide. He has also counseled and been actively involved in many areas of intellectual property litigation,  and has extensive experience in <I>ex parte</I> and <I>inter partes</I> proceedings before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. Mr. Ibrahim is a member of the American Intellectual Property Law Association and the International Trademark Association,  where he is a reporter on the Central Asia and Middle East Committee. Mr. Ibrahim is admitted to practice in both the District of Columbia and Maryland,  as well as numerous federal courts. He is a graduate of the Georgetown University Law Center.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
