<HEAD>
<TITLE>Roper  & Quigg
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Roper  & Quigg
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Chicago:</B> 200 South Michigan Avenue,  Suite 1000,  Chicago,  IL 60604<BR>
Tel 312-408-0855  <B>*</B>  Fax 312-408-0865<BR>
<B>Other office:</B> Arlington (Virginia)<BR>
<BR>
11 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers in intellectual property practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>R</B>oper  & Quigg specializes in intellectual property disputes ranging from the simple to the most complex. Roper  & Quigg is actively engaged in the representation of major national and international companies. Roper  & Quigg's attorneys have extensive experience handling a broad spectrum of simple and complex technology-related causes before tribunals throughout the United States and in foreign countries.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>The Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>Roper  & Quigg is involved in all areas of intellectual property law,  including the patent,  trademark,  copyright,  trade secret,  unfair competition,  and antitrust fields,  with an emphasis on patent infringement litigation. The firm's attorneys have litigated cases in federal district,  administrative,  and state courts throughout the United States,  and have also appeared before the U.S. Supreme Court and the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit (and other courts of appeals).<BR><P>Roper  & Quigg's attorneys have been involved in some of the most complex patent infringement trials ever conducted in the United States,  with about half of the cases having been tried before juries. The firm's attorneys have also been involved in contested proceedings in the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  such as patent interference,  reissue,  and reexamination proceedings,  as well as trademark opposition and cancellation proceedings. Roper  & Quigg's attorneys have also participated in ADR proceedings including arbitration and mini-trial proceedings. Additionally,  Roper  & Quigg counsels clients regarding the worldwide protection of their intellectual property assets,  including prosecuting patent and trademark applications in the United States and foreign countries,  negotiating the licensing and transfer of intellectual property assets,  and performing evaluations of those assets.<BR>
<BR><P>To support the technology-related nature of our practice,  all Roper  & Quigg attorneys have significant backgrounds in science and engineering. The firm's attorneys have degrees in one or more of such varied disciplines as mechanical,  chemical,  and electrical engineering,  and chemistry.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Harry J. Roper</B> As lead counsel in dozens of patent trials,  Mr. Roper has successfully litigated cases in a broad spectrum of technological areas,  including polymer chemistry,  medical devices,  mechanical,  aerospace,  electronics,  and computer software. While Mr. Roper's principal concentration is in the trial and appeal of such patent matters,  he is experienced as well in handling all areas of intellectual property litigation,  licensing,  and client counseling. He has written and lectured extensively on patent infringement,  trade secret,  and antitrust litigation,  and he has acted as a special master in patent litigation. Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute,  B.E.E.,  1962; New York University Law School,  LL.B.,  1966.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Donald J. Quigg</B> Mr. Quigg served as Assistant Secretary of Commerce and Commissioner of Patents and Trademarks,  1985-1989,  Deputy U.S. Commissioner of Patents and Trademarks,  1981-1985,  and served on President Carter's Advisory Committee on Industrial Innovation,  1978-1979. He was general patent counsel for Phillips Petroleum Co.,  1971-1981. Mr. Quigg is an emeritus member of the Association of Corporate Patent Counsel and served on the Executive Committee,  1975-1979. Mr. Quigg manages the firm's Washington office and serves as a litigation consultant and expert witness in selected litigation. Oklahoma University,  B.S.,  business administration,  1937; University of Missouri at Kansas City,  J.D.,  1940.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>George S. Bosy</B> Mr. Bosy concentrates his practice on patent litigation,  trials and appeals,  intellectual property licensing matters,  related antitrust litigation,  and unfair competition matters. University of Illinois,  B.S.,  chemical engineering,  1974; Northwestern University,  J.D.,  1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William P. Oberhardt</B> Mr. Oberhardt served as an assistant attorney general with the Illinois Consumer Fraud and Protection Division,  1978-1984. He concentrates on patent litigation,  trials and appeals. Mr. Oberhardt is also experienced in trade secret and unfair competition litigation and patent and trademark prosecution. University of Notre Dame,  B.S.,  mechanical engineering,  with honors,  1975; DePaul University,  J.D.,  1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Raymond N. Nimrod</B> Mr. Nimrod concentrates his practice on patent litigation,  trials and appeals. Mr. Nimrod is also experienced in trademark and unfair competition litigation,  and patent and trademark prosecution. University of Notre Dame,  B.S.,  chemical engineering,  1981; Loyola University of Chicago,  J.D.,  with high honors,  1984.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Steven R. Trybus</B> Mr. Trybus concentrates his practice on patent litigation, trials and appeals. Mr. Trybus is also experienced in trademark,  copyright,  and unfair competition litigation,  as well as domestic and international patent and trademark prosecution. Illinois Institute of Technology,  B.S.,  chemical engineering,  with high honors,  1982; IIT Chicago-Kent College of Law,  J.D.,  with high honors,  1986.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
