<P>
<P><B>M</B>embers of Ross  & Hardies' Intellectual Property Group work with established and developing businesses in the United States,  Canada,  Central and South America,  Europe,  and Asia on matters related to intellectual property rights and disputes. The firm counsels clients on matters related to trademarks,  copyrights,  patent infringement,  trade secrets,  covenants not to compete,  advertising,  and marketing,  and litigates intellectual property disputes throughout the United States.<BR><BR><UL><LI><B>Keith P. Schoeneberger</B> (<I>Chicago</I>) Mr. Schoeneberger has counseled clients on intellectual property matters for over 15 years,  and has handled numerous intellectual property matters involving patents,  copyrights,  trade dress,  and trade secrets in courts throughout the United States. Mr. Schoeneberger is currently a contributing member of the Executive Communications Committee of the International Trademark Association. He also is a member of the Patent,  Trademark,  and Copyright Committee of the American Bar Association. Mr. Schoeneberger is a graduate of Georgetown University and Northwestern University School of Law.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>J. Joseph Bainton</B> (<I>New York</I>) Mr. Bainton handles intellectual property and complex civil litigation matters for a diverse client base. A former editor of <I>The Trademark Reporter</I>,  he is a member of the International Trademark Association. A graduate of Kenyon College,  Mr. Bainton received his law degree from Rutgers Law School and is a faculty member of the National Institute of Trial Advocacy.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert E. Wangard</B> (<I>Chicago</I>) Mr. Wangard concentrates his practice in the areas of corporate and international business law. He has represented numerous clients in a broad spectrum of inbound and outbound international business matters for more than 20 years,  and has counseled clients on a variety of corporate law issues,  including intellectual property rights and disputes. A graduate of the University of Wisconsin at Madison,  Mr. Wangard received his law degree from the University of Illinois College of Law,  where he was a member of the law review.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>C. Frederick LeBaron,  Jr.</B> (<I>Chicago</I>) Mr. LeBaron has broad experience in corporate,  communications,  and intellectual property matters. He is also experienced in legal matters relating to not-for-profit institutions. Mr. LeBaron received his law degree from Indiana University and his undergraduate education at the University of Michigan.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Marshall Beil</B> (<I>New York</I>) Mr. Beil has represented domestic and international corporations and individuals in publishing and intellectual property matters,  and has had primary responsibility for pre-trial proceedings,  trials and appeals in complex defamation,  copyright,  trademark,  and public interest matters in federal and state courts and arbitrations nationwide. Mr. Beil received his bachelor's degree from Swarthmore College. He is a <I>cum laude</I> graduate of Harvard Law School where he was articles editor for the <I>Harvard Civil Rights-Civil Liberties Law Review</I>. He is admitted in New York,  the U.S. Supreme Court,  and various federal district and circuit courts.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Daniel P. Hogan</B> (<I>Chicago</I>) Mr. Hogan has litigated intellectual property matters for more than ten years. Lead defense counsel in successful bench and jury trials involving patent and trade dress infringement,  false advertising,  and noncompetition agreements,  Mr. Hogan has also served as lead counsel in actions alleging misappropriation of trade secrets and unfair competition,  and has argued intellectual property claims before the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit. Prior to entering private practice,  Mr. Hogan clerked for Judge Stanley J. Roszkowski in the U.S. District Court for the Northern District of Illinois,  and participated in the resolution of numerous patent and copyright actions. An undergraduate at Northern Illinois University,  he received his law degree from Loyola University of Chicago.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Thomas D. Drescher</B> (<I>Chicago</I>) Mr. Drescher counsels clients on trademark and other intellectual property matters,  prosecutes trademark applications,  and has been involved in matters concerning trademark oppositions and infringement actions,  right of publicity issues,  and trademark licensing. A member of the editorial board of <I>The Trademark Reporter</I> of the International Trademark Association and the author of two lead articles on the history and role of trademarks,  Mr. Drescher holds a bachelor's degree from the University of Wisconsin at Madison and a master's degree from Simon Fraser University in Vancouver. He is a graduate of the Washington University School of Law and holds a doctorate from York University in Toronto.<BR>
