<HEAD>
<TITLE>Schnader Harrison Segal & Lewis
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Schnader Harrison Segal & Lewis
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Philadelphia:</B> 1600 Market Street,  Philadelphia,  PA 19103<BR>
Tel 215-751-2000  <B>*</B>  Fax 215-751-2205<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Atlanta,  Cherry Hill (New Jersey),  New York,  Pittsburgh, <BR>
Harrisburg (Pennsylvania),  Washington,  D.C.,  Washington (Pennsylvania)<BR>
<BR>
190 lawyers  <B>*</B>  9 lawyers concentrating in intellectual property<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>S</B>chnader,  Harrison,  Segal  & Lewis has been actively engaged in what is now known as intellectual property law,  including computer law,  for more than 25 years. The Intellectual Property Department includes eight registered patent attorneys. Scientific and technical backgrounds include undergraduate and graduate degrees in biology,  physics,  and chemical,  electrical and mechanical engineering.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Procurement of Rights</H3></CENTER>

<P>The Department represents domestic and foreign clients before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office in obtaining U.S. patents. Lawyers have handled patents for inventions relating to chemical and biochemical compositions and processes,  machinery,  medical equipment,  electrical power distribution equipment,  semiconductor devices and fabrication techniques,  and in the field of digital video signal processing. The Department also has substantial experience in design patent procurement. In the trademark field,  lawyers advise clients on the availability of proposed marks for use and registration,  prepare and prosecute applications for federal registrations,  and handle contested proceedings before the Trademark Trial and Appeal Board.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Protection of Rights</H3></CENTER>

<P>The Department responds quickly and forcefully to litigation situations. Lawyers have experience prosecuting and defending motions for temporary restraining orders and preliminary injunctions. They respond on short notice to the immediate needs of clients,  in addition to fulfilling their sustained technical litigation needs. The Firm represents plaintiffs and defendants in utility patent and design patent infringement actions. Recent clients have included European and U.S. manufacturers of products such as computer-controlled machines,  medical devices,  chemicals,  railroad equipment,  other electromechanical products,  and home and office supply products. The Department also prosecutes and defends cases involving trademarks,  trade names,  and trade dress for regional,  national,  and international clients.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Transactional Matters</H3></CENTER>

<P>The Department handles licensing,  leasing,  acquisitions,  and joint ventures involving clients ranging from large multinational corporations to emerging companies to individual entrepreneurs.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>William H. Murray</B> (<I>Philadelphia; 215-751-2383</I>) Chairman of the Intellectual Property Department. Substantial experience in the preparation and prosecution of patent applications in the fields of computer technologies,  semiconductors,  electrical power distribution,  and television. Also involved in licensing patents,  trademarks,  and copyrights.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert A. Koons,  Jr.</B> (<I>Philadelphia; 215-751-2180</I>) Administrative chairman of the Intellectual Property Department and also a member of the Firm's Litigation Department. Substantial experience in litigation of patents,  trademarks,  and copyrights,  and related complex and technical litigation,  including antitrust,  unfair competition,  and product liability matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James A. Drobile</B> (<I>Philadelphia; 215-751-2242</I>) Senior counsel on worldwide trademark law,  including prosecution,  licensing,  and litigation; domestic and foreign chemical patent solicitation. Counsel to higher educational institutions in intellectual property matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert E. Rosenthal</B> (<I>Philadelphia; 215-751-2680</I>) Extensive experience in patent prosecution and providing advice in physics and mechanical and electrical technologies; counseling and prosecution in domestic and international trademark and trade identity areas; intellectual property development and licensing arrangements.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Paul G. Gagne</B> (<I>Philadelphia; 215-751-2650</I>) Substantial experience in litigation of trademark,  copyright,  and related intellectual property matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John V. Silverio</B> (<I>Philadelphia; 215-751-2216</I>) Focuses on computer hardware and software patent preparation and prosecution. Significant experience in all areas of trademark law and intellectual property transfer and licensing.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Steve Mendelsohn</B> (<I>Philadelphia; 215-751-2204</I>) Extensive patent prosecution experience in electrical and computer-related inventions for major international corporations. Also has expertise in image/video processing patent prosecution matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>N. Stephan Kinsella</B> (<I>Philadelphia; 215-751-2157</I>) Extensive computer hardware and software patent prosecution experience for major international corporations.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>R. Anthony Diehl</B> (<I>Philadelphia; 215-751-2165</I>) Focuses on intellectual property litigation. Significant experience in chemical,  biomedical,  and biochemical patent prosecution matters.
