<HEAD>
<TITLE>Schuyler,  Roche  & Zwirner
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Schuyler,  Roche  & Zwirner
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Chicago:</B> One Prudential Plaza,  130 East Randolph Street,  Suite 3800,  Chicago,  IL 60601<BR>
Tel 312-565-2400  <B>*</B>  Fax 312-565-8300<BR>
<BR>
40 lawyers  <B>*</B>  7 lawyers concentrating in intellectual property practice and litigation<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/schuyler.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/schuyler.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/schuyler.html"> ERISA</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/schuyler.html"> Labor</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>W</B>ith roots going back more than 100 years,  Schuyler,  Roche  & Zwirner is one of the oldest law firms in Chicago. The firm has been involved since its inception in intellectual property litigation. Our experience includes the prosecution and defense of cases in all areas of intellectual property law,  both domestically and internationally. We have handled matters involving trademark,  service mark,  copyright,  and trade dress infringement; unfair competition; protection of trade secrets; enforcement of restrictive covenants and confidentiality agreements; and,  working with patent lawyers,  the prosecution and defense of patent infringement actions.
<P><UL><BR><BR>
<BR><P>The following are typical matters we have handled:<BR><P><LI> In a series of cases,  we represented a company which owned the rights to the names and likenesses of many well-known performing artists. We obtained preliminary and permanent injunctive relief and damages against various enterprises that produced and sold bootleg merchandise bearing the names and likenesses of those artists.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> We brought an action on behalf of a British manufacturer of orthopedic devices,  alleging `reverse passing off' i.e.,  the defendant was passing off our client's products as its own. We obtained a preliminary injunction prohibiting that practice. The case settled before trial on terms highly favorable to our client.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> We prosecuted an action for violation of a confidentiality agreement entered into by our client and a competitor when the two companies were discussing a potential business arrangement. We obtained a preliminary injunction against the opposing party which remained in effect for years,  survived an appeal,  and ultimately caused the competitor to stay out of the relevant product market.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> We filed a trademark opposition to stop our client's competitor from using a logo which was deceptively similar to our client's. The suit resulted in a settlement in which our client's competitor agreed to withdraw its trademark application.<BR>
<BR><P><LI> We obtained preliminary and permanent injunctions requiring our client's competitor to change its packaging and name because they were confusingly similar to our client's. We also obtained a judgment for damages.<BR>
<BR></UL><BR>
<LI><B>James D. Adducci</B> has represented major clients of the firm in numerous intellectual property disputes in both the international and domestic arenas. Recently,  he obtained a large jury verdict,  including a significant punitive damages award,  on behalf of a company whose trade secrets had been misappropriated.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David M. Allen</B> has brought a series of copyright infringement suits on behalf of a licensee of medical recording systems. In the resulting settlements,  our client's competitors were permanently enjoined from publishing,  marketing,  and selling any works infringing our client's copyrights.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Marshall L. Blankenship</B> represents one of the firm's principal corporate clients in connection with its ongoing enforcement and preservation of its trademarks,  patents,  and copyrights,  both nationally and internationally. He also recently won a sizable jury verdict in a trade secrets misappropriation case.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael F. Braun</B> successfully prosecuted an action under the Illinois Consumer Fraud Act which resulted in the recovery of significant damages and attorneys' fees for the client. He regularly participates in Consumer Fraud Act litigation and in employment-related disputes involving trade secrets or other intellectual property issues.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>L. Andrew Brehm</B> recently defended successfully one of the firm's clients before the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit against allegations of contributory and vicarious trademark infringement. He has also participated in Lanham Act and copyright infringement litigation.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael B. Roche</B> has broad experience in trademark infringement,  copyright,  and right of publication actions. He has obtained injunctive relief and substantial monetary awards on behalf of licensors of merchandising rights in their efforts to curtail the production and sale of unauthorized merchandise.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jeffrey E. Schiller</B> has substantial experience in prosecuting and defending claims under the Lanham Act and under the Illinois Consumer Fraud Act. Recently,  he defended a client against a trade dress claim.<BR>
<BR>
<BR><BR>


</UL></BODY>
