<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Senniger,  Powers,  Leavitt & Roedel
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>St. Louis:</B> One Metropolitan Square,  16th Floor,  St. Louis,  MO 63102<BR>
Tel 314-231-5400  <B>*</B>  Fax 314-231-4342<BR>
<BR>
23 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers in intellectual property practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>S</B>enniger,  Powers,  Leavitt  & Roedel,  founded in 1919,  is the largest intellectual property law firm in Missouri. The firm limits its practice to intellectual property and technology-related law,  including U.S. and international patent,  trademark,  copyright,  unfair competition,  antitrust,  and related litigation in U.S. courts and before the International Trade Commission.
<P><BR><P>The firm provides a full spectrum of services in this specialized area of the law,  ranging from government administrative matters,  such as obtaining patents,  trademarks,  and copyrights,  to all aspects of litigation to enforce and defend clients' rights with respect to intellectual property. Through its network of foreign associates,  the firm assists its clients in similar matters throughout the world. Our in-house state-of-the-art technology allows us instant communication with our clients and others throughout the world.<BR><P>Our attorneys are educated and experienced in specialized technologies which may be broadly categorized as mechanical,  electrical,  and chemical,  but which also include the more specific areas of: complex machinery,  electromechanical devices,  electronic circuitry,  computer hardware and software,  biomedical de-vices,  complex chemical processes,  biological developments,  metallurgical developments,  civil engineering concepts,  structural engineering techniques,  industrial engineering techniques,  and basic research chemistry.<BR>
<BR><P>Our practice includes: preparation,  filing,  and prosecution of patent and trademark applications in the United States and abroad; conducting patent and trademark searches; providing patentability and infringement opinions; licensing all forms of intellectual property nationally and internationally; patent,  trademark,  service mark,  and copyright litigation; antitrust litigation; unfair competition and theft of trade secrets litigation; patent interference proceedings; and trademark and service mark opposition and cancellation proceedings.<BR>
<BR><P>Representative clients: Rawlings Sporting Goods; Monsanto; Sigma Chemical/ Sigma International; General Electric; Boeing Aerospace  & Electronics; Novus International; LDDS Communications; B-Line Systems,  Inc; McBee Loose Leaf Binders; National Vendors.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Stuart N. Senniger</B> All aspects of intellectual property practice,  including litigation,  prosecution,  licensing,  and counseling in both U.S. and foreign patent and trademark matters. Serves on the Missouri Supreme Court Advisory Committee. Washington University,  J.D.,  1948.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Irving Powers</B> Mechanical engineering-related practice,  including patent litigation,  transfer of rights including licensing negotiations,  drafting and review of licenses,  patent evaluation,  and preparation and prosecution of patent applications. Former patent examiner. George Washington University,  J.D.,  1946.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Donald G. Leavitt</B> Patent,  trademark,  and copyright law,  concentrating in the fields of chemical and pharmaceutical patents and participating extensively in the practice of trademark and unfair competition law. Adjunct professor,  patent law,  St. Louis University,  1956-1992. University of Michigan,  J.D.,  1951.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John K. Roedel,  Jr.</B> Chemical patent prosecution,  litigation,  and antitrust causes. Over 25 years' experience in chemical and chemical engineering patent matters,  both organic and inorganic. Former chemical process engineer at Monsanto. St. Louis University,  J.D.,  1969.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael E. Godar</B> All areas of patent,  trademark,  and copyright practice,  including prosecution,  licensing,  and litigation of mechanical arts patents. University of Missouri at Columbia,  J.D.,  1975.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William E. Lahey</B> Multidistrict litigation involving patent,  antitrust,  and related issues. Patent prosecution in the United States and abroad relating to mechanical and electromechanical devices. Worked on weapon system design and development as an engineer with TRW,  Inc. University of Toledo,  J.D.,  1971.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Edward J. Hejlek</B> Broadly based practice ranging from patent,  trademark,  copyright,  and antitrust litigation to preparation of applications for patent and trademark registration. Adjunct professor,  patent and trademark law,  St. Louis University. University of Missouri at Columbia,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Frank R. Agovino</B> Intellectual property protection,  including litigation,  relating to electronics and computer software. Handled intellectual property matters at the Pentagon while a captain in the U.S. Army. Affiliate professor in electrical engineering,  Washington University. University of Cincinnati,  J.D.,  1973.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>J. Bennett Clark</B> Litigation of patent and trademark infringement,  copyright violations,  and other intellectual property disputes. Extensive trial and appellate litigation experience. Former assistant U.S. attorney. Faculty member,  University of Virginia Trial Advocacy Institute. University of Virginia,  J.D.,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>G. Harley Blosser</B> Full intellectual property practice,  including ITC proceedings,  formulating and prosecuting biochemical/biosciences patent applications,  trademarks,  and copyright applications. University of Missouri at Kansas City,  J.D.,  1988.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
