<HEAD>
<TITLE>Skjerven,  Morrill,  MacPherson,  Franklin & Friel
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Skjerven,  Morrill,  MacPherson,  Franklin & Friel
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>San Jose:</B> 25 Metro Drive,  Suite 700,  San Jose,  CA 95110<BR>
Tel 408-453-9200  <B>*</B>  Fax 408-453-7979<BR>
<B>Austin:</B> 100 Congress Avenue,  Suite 1050,  Austin,  TX 78701<BR>
Tel 512-404-3600  <B>*</B>  Fax 512-404-3601<BR>
<B>San Francisco:</B> 601 California Street,  Suite 800,  San Francisco,  CA 94108<BR>
Tel 415-986-838  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-982-7372<BR>
<BR>
60 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers in intellectual property<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>S</B>kjerven,  Morrill,  MacPherson,  Franklin  & Friel's practice is devoted principally to intellectual property law and related litigation and transactional work. Founded in 1976 in Silicon Valley,  the firm assists its clients in protecting their intellectual property in the workplace,  in the marketplace,  and in litigation. The firm represents domestic and international businesses of all sizes in the electronics,  computer hardware,  software,  medical technology,  biotech,  gaming,  and other industries. Many of the firm's attorneys have technical backgrounds and several have extensive experience in industry. Current representative clients include Adaptec,  Advanced Micro Devices,  GeneType,  A.G.,  National Semiconductor Corporation,  NEC Electronics,  and Xilinx.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Patent and Trade Secret Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>The firm's 32 patent attorneys prosecute patent applications in the United States and throughout the world. They also advise clients on the availability,  enforcement,  and validity of their patents and render advice on patent infringement. The group assists clients in establishing and maintaining programs to protect and manage their inventions and technical developments. The firm's patent attorneys also assist clients in acquiring,  protecting,  and licensing other intellectual property rights,  including trade secrets.<BR><BR><UL><LI><B>Alan H. MacPherson</B> has extensive experience in all aspects of intellectual property law,  including litigation,  International Trade Commission proceedings,  patent prosecution,  and licensing. He served as general patent counsel and director of patents and licensing for Fairchild Camera and Instrument Corporation from 1974 to 1980. Stanford University,  B.S.,  with distinction,  engineering; Massachusetts Institute of Technology,  M.S.; Harvard University,  J.D. Admitted in California,  1969; New York,  1965; and U.S. Patent Office,  1965.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Paul J. Winters</B> represents clients in obtaining patents for many different electrical and mechanical devices and in various intellectual property transactions. He was formerly chief patent counsel for both Fairchild Camera and Instrument Corporation and National Semiconductor Corporation. University of Pennsylvania,  B.S.,  engineering; University of Virginia,  J.D. Admitted in California,  1968; New York,  1966; and U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  1968.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>David W. Heid</B> represents clients in obtaining patents and in licensing technology. He is very familiar with computer memory devices,  semiconductor devices,  and manufacturing processes. He served as patent counsel for Memorex Corporation from 1975 to 1985. Auburn University,  B.S.E.E; University of Alabama,  J.D. Admitted in California,  1979; and U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  1970.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>David H. Carroll</B> represents clients in obtaining patents,  licensing technology,  and other aspects of intellectual property law. He is knowledgeable about digital systems,  remote sensing systems and devices,  and semiconductor fabrication and test equipment. Resident partner,  Austin office. Princeton University,  B.S.,  engineering,  with high honors; New York University,  J.D. Admitted in Texas,  1992; California,  1989; District of Columbia,  1979; and U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  1979.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Forrest E. Gunnison</B> has extensive experience with software,  computer systems,  ASICs,  digital circuits,  and video and data compression. He practiced engineering for ten years. Albion College,  B.A.,  with high honors; University of Illinois,  M.S.,  Ph.D.; Loyola University of Chicago,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>. Admitted in California,  1987; and U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  1987.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Norman R. Klivans,  Jr.</B> has experience with semiconductor,  video,  and communications technology,  as well as computer hardware and software. Yale University,  B.S.; Stanford University,  M.B.A.; Harvard University,  J.D. Admitted in California,  1978; and U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  1978.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>David E. Steuber</B> prosecutes patent applications for a variety of electrical and mechanical devices,  emphasizing semiconductor fabrication technology,  and represents clients in licensing transactions. Yale University,  B.E.,  with high honors,  LL.B. Admitted in California,  1974; New York,  1968; and U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  1970.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Brian D. Ogonowsky</B> is experienced with semiconductor devices and circuits,  wafer fabrication,  and video and data processing systems. Villanova University,  B.S.E.E; Suffolk University,  J.D. Admitted in California,  1985; Massachusetts,  1983; and U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  1983.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Laura Terlizzi</B> represents clients in the biotech and related industries. She has ten years' experience counseling these clients and in prosecuting biotech and medical patent applications. She also has ten years' experience in biomedical research at the University of Chicago and the University of California at San Diego. University of Illinois,  B.S; Loyola University of Chicago,  J.D. Admitted in Illinois,  1984; and California,  1987.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Edward C. Kwok</B> has extensive experience with semiconductor devices and circuits,  wafer fabrication,  computer-aided design and manufacturing,  video and data processing systems,  and software design. He represents clients in the semiconductor,  computer,  software,  and electronics industries. Massachusetts Institute of Technology,  S.B. (E.E.); University of California at Berkeley,  M.S.E.E.; Santa Clara University,  J.D. Admitted in California and U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  1989.<BR>
<BR></UL>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Litigation Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>The firm's 24 trial lawyers represent clients in a wide range of business and commercial disputes,  emphasizing cases concerning patent,  trademark,  and copyright infringement; misappropriation of trade secrets; and unfair competition. The firm's litigators represent clients in all types of proceedings,  including simple commercial disputes,  injunction proceedings,  and complex trials involving the latest technology and issues of intellectual property law. The group represents clients in state and federal trial and appellate courts,  in arbitrations,  at the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  and before the ITC and other agencies.<BR><BR><UL><LI><B>Robert B. Morrill</B> has had extensive experience in all types of intellectual property and business litigation since 1967. He most recently served as lead trial counsel in three complex trials involving novel legal issues of computer program copyright and trademark rights. University of Nevada,  B.S.; Harvard University,  L.L.B.,  <I>cum laude</I>. Admitted in California,  1964.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Thomas J. Friel,  Jr.</B> has over ten years' experience in all phases of intellectual property litigation,  including trials and injunction proceedings,  and related transactions. University of Michigan,  B.G.S.,  J.D. Admitted in California,  1978.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Anthony de ALCuaz</B> represents clients in intellectual property and business litigation. He has over 15 years of extensive trial and litigation experience in intellectual property law cases. He served as deputy district attorney in Santa Clara County from 1976 to 1980,  where he was chief prosecutor of high-tech crimes,  including <I>People </I>v.<I> Gopal</I>,  from 1978 to 1980. University of California at Santa Cruz,  B.A.; Hastings College of Law,  J.D. Admitted in California,  1975.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Joseph A. Greco</B> has over ten years of intellectual property law litigation and trial experience,  including serving as lead counsel in a medical instrument trade secrets jury trial and in various injunction proceedings. Dartmouth College,  B.A.,  <I>magna cum laude; </I>Stanford University,  J.D. Admitted in California,  1982.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Justin T. Beck</B> was lead counsel in three high-technology/intellectual propertytrials and has had ten years of intellectual property litigation experience. Stanford University,  B.A.; University of San Francisco,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>. Admitted in California,  1972.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Charles D. Chalmers</B> has extensive litigation experience in patent and literary and high-tech copyright cases and trade secret injunction proceedings. He is familiar with software,  semiconductors,  and electronics technology. California State University at Pomona,  B.A.; Stanford University,  J.D. Admitted in California,  1972.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Kenneth E. Leeds</B> is experienced in both intellectual property litigation and in prosecuting patent applications. He is familiar with semiconductor and disk drive technology. University of Pennsylvania,  B.S.E.E.,  B.S.,  economics; University of Santa Clara,  J.D. Admitted in California,  1985; and U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  1986.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Edward V. Anderson</B> represents clients in the computer,  semiconductor,  and software industries in intellectual property and business litigation. He has over 16 years' experience in intellectual property litigation and tried several complex patent infringement cases during that time. He also has extensive mediation and arbitration experience,  both in representing clients and as an arbitrator and mediator. Stanford University,  B.A.,  honors and distinction,  J.D. Admitted in California,  1978.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Michelle G. Breit</B> represents clients in all phases of intellectual property and business litigation,  including providing representation before the International Trade Commission. University of California at San Diego,  B.A.; Boalt Hall School of Law,  J.D. Admitted in California,  1989.<BR>
<BR></UL>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Trademark,  Copyright and Maskwork Right Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>Two of the firm's attorneys concentrate in the field of trademark,  copyright,  and maskwork law. They assist clients in registering trademarks,  copyrights,  and maskwork rights in the United States and in other countries. They also provide advice on the availability and enforcement of such rights and assist clients in a wide range of transactions and proceedings (including opposition proceedings in the Trademark Office) involving trademarks,  copyrights,  and maskwork rights.<BR><BR><UL><LI><B>Richard Franklin</B> represents clients in various intellectual property and business matters. He has extensive experience with all aspects of trademarks and literary and high-tech copyrights,  maskwork rights,  and trade secrets. He was director of the corporate legal department of Fairchild Camera and Instrument Corporation from 1969 to 1978. Queens College,  City University of New York.,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>; New York University,  J.D. Admitted in California,  1972; New York,  1956; and U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  1958.<BR></UL>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Transactional Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>All of the firm's attorneys,  including two who emphasize transactional work,  represent clients in a wide variety of licensing and technology development and transfer transactions. The firm's transactional specialists also represent clients in the formation and financing of corporations and joint ventures where the technology owned or to be developed is important,  as well as in domestic and international commercial transactions involving intellectual property law issues.<BR><BR><UL><LI><B>Richard H. Skjerven</B> represents software,  electronics,  and other companies in licensing,  technology transfers,  product development projects,  domestic and international joint ventures,  and a wide variety of commercial transactions. He has over 20 years' experience in representing clients in transactions involving intellectual property rights. Prior to founding the firm,  he was vice-president and general counsel of American Microsystems,  Inc. North Dakota University,  B.A.,  J.D.,  with distinction. Admitted in Texas,  1992; and California,  1964.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Marc David Freed</B> represents clients in domestic and international licensing transactions,  high-technology financings,  and joint ventures. He has over ten years of intellectual property law experience. Carleton College,  B.A.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>; Harvard University,  J.D. Admitted in California,  1977.<BR></UL>

</UL></BODY>
