<HEAD>
<TITLE>Spensley Horn Jubas & Lubitz
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Spensley Horn Jubas & Lubitz
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Los Angeles:</B> 1880 Century Park East,  Fifth Floor,  Los Angeles,  CA 90067<BR>
Tel 310-553-5050  <B>*</B>  Fax 310-553-4619<BR>
<B>Newport Beach:</B> 610 Newport Center Drive,  Suite 1129,  Newport Beach,  CA 92660<BR>
Tel 619-455-5100  <B>*</B>  Fax 619-455-5110<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> 2000 M Street,  N.W.,  Suite 720,  Washington,  DC 20036<BR>
Tel 202-223-5700  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-223-5704<BR>
<BR>
40 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers in intellectual property<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>D</B>uring the past four decades,  Spensley Horn Jubas  & Lubitz has developed the specialized expertise and meticulous methodology to successfully manage the most intricate intellectual property matters involving patent,  trademark,  copyright,  unfair competition,  trade secret,  and business and financial considerations. The firm's attorneys hold advanced degrees in engineering,  computers,  the sciences,  or business from some of America's most prestigious universities.<BR><BR><UL>
<LI><B>Stuart Lubitz</B> has,  since joining the firm in 1965,  represented key clients in virtually all aspects of intellectual property law. He is president of the firm and a member of the Board of Directors. University of Florida,  B.S.E.E.,  1957,  B.S.M.E.,  1958; George Washington University,  LL.B.,  1961.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Richard Zaitlen </B>is a member of the firm's Board of Directors and serves clients in a practice devoted to complex intellectual property litigation. Purdue University,  B.S.,  chemical engineering,  1969; George Washington University,  J.D.,  1973.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Evan Finkel</B> is a member of the firm's Board of Directors. Mr. Finkel specializes in patent,  trademark,  copyright,  trade secret,  unfair competition,  and computer law litigation,  with an emphasis on computer software technology. State University of New York at Binghampton,  B.S.,  1978; Hastings College of Law,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Alex Chartove</B> is resident in the Washington,  D.C. office and represents clients in matters before various federal tribunals and agencies in the capital. Brandeis University,  B.A.,  1976; Duke University Law School,  J.D.,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David Simon</B> represents clients in all phases of intellectual property law with a specialization in computer hardware and peripheral devices,  analog circuitry,  semiconductor physics,  electrodynamics,  and antenna design. Massachusetts Institute of Technology,  S.B.,  1979; Georgetown University Law Center,  J.D.,  1982.<BR><BR><LI><B>Victor Rodgers</B> practices in matters related to commercial litigation,  unfair competition law,  and trademark litigation. University of Southern California,  B.S.,  1978; University of California,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jay Finkelstein</B> is resident in the Washington,  D.C. office and serves clients through representation before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit,  and the Copyright Office. Drexel University,  B.S.,  1959; George Washington University,  J.D.,  1963.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David Grace</B> represents clients in matters involving civil litigation,  primarily involving copyright,  trademark,  patent,  unfair competition,  and the protection and licensing of trademarks and copyrights. George Mason University,  B.S.,  1978; University of Virginia,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Roger Wise</B> specializes in electrical and electronic patent matters,  including litigation,  prosecution,  infringement,  and validity studies. University of Illinois,  B.S.E.E.,  1978; The John Marshall Law School,  J.D.,  1984.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gary Mann</B> concentrates his efforts in the area of trade secret litigation,  as well as in general commercial litigation. United States Naval Academy,  B.S.,  physics,  1972; Indiana University,  J.D.,  1980.<BR>
