<HEAD>
<TITLE>Stroock  & Stroock  & Lavan
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Stroock  & Stroock  & Lavan
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>New York:</B> Seven Hanover Square,  New York,  NY 10004-2696<BR>
Tel 212-806-5400  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-806-6006<BR>
<BR>
294 lawyers  <B>*</B>  20 lawyers practice intellectual property law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>S</B>troock  & Stroock  & Lavan's intellectual property practice group represents clients engaged in an array of fields ranging from consumer goods to hightechnology products,  including computer software and multimedia,  in all aspects of intellectual property law. These include patents,  trademarks,  copyrights,  unfair competition,  trade secrets,  antitrust,  and licensing. This practice encompasses all phases of legal representation before state and federal courts,  the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  the U.S. Copyright Office,  and the International Trade Commission. In addition,  we have litigated cases in courts throughout the country and have developed extensive trial and appellate experience. Since many of our lawyers have professional training in physics or chemical,  electrical,  or mechanical engineering,  clients benefit from the combination of our technical education with our legal background.
<P><BR><P>Stroock's intellectual property practice is also international. Working with a worldwide network of foreign associate firms,  our lawyers have represented clients before patent and trademark offices,  courts,  and tribunals around the world.<BR><P>Current clients include: Advance Magazine Publishers Inc. (Conde Nast),  Baron Philippe de Rothschild S.A.,  Fuji Photo Film Co.,  Ltd.,  General Mills,  Inc.,  Joseph E. Seagram  & Sons,  Inc.,  Merrill Lynch  & Co.,  Inc.,  Newsweek,  Inc.,  Pantone,  Inc.,  Revlon Consumer Products,  Inc.,  Ringling Bros.-Barnum  & Bailey Combined Shows,  Inc.,  and Seiko Epson Corporation and Seiko Corporation.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Martin J. Beran</B> concentrates in virtually every aspect of U.S. and international trademarks and copyrights. He is an adjunct professor at the Benjamin N. Cardozo School of Law. He has served as a member of the editorial board of <I>The Trademark Reporter</I> for 30 years. Martin is the author of <I>An Introduction to Trademark Practice</I>,  as well as numerous articles on trademarks that have appeared in professional publications. Martin attended New York University where he received an A.B.,  an LL.B.,  and an LL.M. in trade regulation. Admitted in New York.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Howard M. Gitten</B> has a high-technology background with unique expertise in the prosecution,  licensing,  and protection of electrical and mechanical devices including computer hardware and software,  automated identification involving optical and radio frequency,  animal research,  and other technologies.<BR>
<BR><P>He is a member of the Trade Secrets Committee for both the American Bar Association and the New York Intellectual Property Law Association. Howard received a B.A.S. and a B.A. from the University of Pennsylvania. He graduated in 1985 from Case Western Reserve University where he received a J.D. While there,  he was selected articles editor of the <I>Case Western Reserve University Journal of International Law</I>. Admitted in New Jersey,  1985; New York,  1986. Registered to practice before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Laura E. Goldbard</B> has extensive experience in copyright and trademark litigation,  representing both plaintiffs and defendants,  particularly in the fields of textile and related home products,  clothing,  health and beauty aid products,  family entertainment,  and publishing. In addition to domestic trademark prosecution and litigation,  she has a substantial international trademark practice.<BR>
<BR><P>Laura graduated from Emory University with a Bachelor of Arts in 1978 and received her J.D. from the University of Miami. Admitted in New York.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Steven B. Pokotilow</B> is a litigator who manages the intellectual property portfolios of his clients,  including the counseling,  structuring,  negotiation,  and drafting of license agreements for clients with worldwide licensing programs. His clients include investors,  creators,  publishers,  and manufacturers of computer software,  electronic instruments,  health and beauty aids,  toys,  hobby items,  sports memorabilia,  and textiles that are sold internationally.<BR>
<BR><P>Steven received a B.S. in electrical engineering from the University of Maryland and his J.D. from American University. Admitted in New York. Registered to practice before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Lawrence Rosenthal</B>  concentrates in electronics and computers,  but he has handled matters in a wide range of technologies. Over the years,  he has managed extensive litigation in various trial and appellate courts and the International Trade Commission involving property rights of all types,  including patents on devices ranging from toys to sophisticated electronic devices; trademarks for products such as wines,  watches,  and magazines; and copyrights on fabrics and product packaging. <BR><BR><P>Larry received a B.S. in electrical engineering from Cornell University and an LL.B. and LL.M. in trade regulation from New York University School of Law. Admitted in New York. Registered to practice before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
