<P>
<P><B>V</B>inson  & Elkins L.L.P. is one of the world's largest international law firms,  representing clients in substantially all areas of law. The firm has worked with clients since 1927 to obtain,  protect,  and enforce intellectual property rights. Many of our lawyers practice in the traditional intellectual property areas of patents,  trademarks,  unfair competition,  and copyrights,  while others practice in related fields involving technical issues such as commercial contracts,  construction engineering,  business fraud,  and deceptive trade practices. Our lawyers also regularly handle matters involving confidentiality agreements,  employment and consulting agreements,  noncompetition covenants,  and risk allocation and indemnification. We participate in all phases of transactional work; in state and federal court litigation; and before administrative agencies. Our lawyers have academic degrees and work experience in virtually all scientific and technical disciplines. Substantially all of our lawyers are licensed to practice before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. Representative clients include Anchor Glass Container Corp.; Atlantic Richfield Co.; Baker-Hughes,  Inc.; Compaq Computer Corp.; Cyrix Corp.; Datapoint Corp.; DTM Corp.; Enron Corp.; Fina Oil and Chemical Co.; GTE Mobilenet; Halliburton Co.; Houston Advanced Research Center; Methodist Hospital System; SGS-Thomson Microelectronics; VideoTelecom Corp; and Vitro,  S.A.<BR><BR><UL><LI><B>J. Clark Martin</B> practices in all areas of intellectual property law,  litigation,  construction law,  and business risk issues. Fellow,  Texas Bar Foundation. Louisiana State University,  B.S.,  electrical engineering,  1963,  J.D.,  1966. Admitted in Texas,  1970.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William L. LaFuze</B>'s practice includes all areas of intellectual property law,  with particular emphasis on computer and computer-related law. Past president,  American Intellectual Property Law Association; past chairman,  Intellectual Property Law Section,  State Bar of Texas; past president,  Houston Intellectual Property Law Association; fellow,  Texas and Houston Bar Foundations; past president,  National Inventors Hall of Fame and National Council of Intellectual Property Law Associations. University of Texas,  B.S.,  physics,  1969; Southern Methodist University,  M.S.,  applied science (systems engineering),  1971; University of Texas,  J.D.,  1973. Admitted in Texas,  1973.<BR>
