<TITLE><\2>Vorys,  Sater,  Seymour and Pease
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Vorys,  Sater,  Seymourand Pease
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Columbus:</B> 52 East Gay Street,  Columbus,  OH 43215<BR>
Tel 614-464-6400  <B>*</B>  Fax 614-464-6350<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> 1828 L Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20036<BR>
Tel 202-467-8800  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-467-8900<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Cleveland,  Cincinnati<BR>
<BR>
285 lawyers  <B>*</B>  15 lawyers in intellectual property<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/vorys.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/vorys.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/vorys.html"> Corporate Securities</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/vorys.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/vorys.html"> Labor</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/vorys.html"> Product Liability</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/vorys.html"> White Collar Crime</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/vorys.html"> Workout</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>V</B>orys,  Sater,  Seymour and Pease,  one of the nation's 100 largest law firms,  provides its clients with national and international representation in all areas of the law.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Intellectual Property Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>Vorys' practice encompasses all phases of U.S. and foreign intellectual property law,  including counseling in the adoption,  development,  and use of intellectual property rights; obtaining appropriate protection of these valuable properties; negotiating and preparing patent,  trademark,  and copyright licenses (including software licensing); and litigating to enforce or defend clients' rights in the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office and state and federal courts. Vorys' attorneys prepare appropriate employee,  consultant,  supplier,  and distributor contracts; establish franchising programs; and counsel on tax implications of intellectual property matters.<BR><P>Representative clients of our intellectual property services are The Cooper Companies; CPC International Inc.; Century 21 Real Estate Corporation; MBNA America Bank,  N.A.; Trump Atlantic City Hotels and Casinos; Elvis Presley Enterprises,  Inc.; and Bob Evans Farms,  Inc.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Cory M. Amron</B> (<I>Washington; 202-467-8810</I>) Legal practice emphasizes intellectual property,  commercial real estate,  and transactional matters. University of Rochester,  B.A.,  with distinction,  1974; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Thomas R. Boland</B> (<I>Washington; 202-467-8802</I>) Chairs practice group,  manages Washington,  D.C. office. Domestic and foreign patent and trademark practice. Maintains an active federal litigation practice and supervises extensive prosecution practice in biotechnology,  biomechanics,  and chemical areas. Registered patent lawyer. University of Scranton,  B.S.,  chemistry and philosophy,  1960; Georgetown University,  J.D.,  1965.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Douglas R. Bush</B> (<I>Washington; 202-467-8804</I>) Domestic and foreign counseling,  registration,  licensing,  and trial and appellate practice in trademarks,  copyrights,  unfair competition,  and unfair trade practices. Brigham Young University,  B.S.,  1982; Brigham Young University J. Reuben Clark Law School,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1985.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Ellen A. Efros</B> (<I>Washington; 202-467-8806</I>) Trial and appellate practice in patent,  trade secret,  trademarks,  copyrights,  unfair competition,  and unfair trade practices. Case Western Reserve University,  B.A.,  with honors,  1971; Hofstra University,  J.D.,  with distinction,  1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Russell M. Gertmenian</B> (<I>Columbus; 614-464-6317</I>) Practices in the area of intellectual property law,  specializing in unfair competition and trademark and service mark law. Engages in the practice of general corporate and contract law including mergers,  acquisitions,  and divestitures. Acts as general counsel to a variety of public and private corporations. Is a member of the United States Trademark Association as well as the Columbus,  Ohio,  and American Bar Associations. Rutgers University,  A.B.,  1969; Columbia University,  J.D.,  1972.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael A. Grow</B> (<I>Washington; 202-467-8808</I>) Domestic and foreign counseling,  registration,  licensing,  and trial and appellate practice in trademarks,  copyrights,  unfair competition,  and unfair trade practices. Chairman,  D.C. Bar Intellectual Property Section. Weber State College,  B.A.,  1972; Washington University,  J.D.,  with honors,  1975.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Brian C. Harrison</B> (<I>Washington; 202-467-8811</I>) Concentration is in civil commercial litigation. Substantial experience in both the litigation and resolution of disputes relating to the exercise of intellectual property rights,  including the negotiation of publishing,  licensing,  and recording agreements. Served as legal counsel to the Songwriters Association of Washington (1988-1993). Drexel University,  B.S.,  high honors,  1981; George Washington University,  J.D.,  with honors,  1984.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jonathan D. Iten</B> (<I>Columbus; 614-464-5653</I>) Counsel to clients in all areas of the computer industry on issues of protection,  licensing,  leasing,  distribution,  sales,  and technology acquisition and transfer. Formerly a computer programmer and analyst in the industrial and academic arenas. Bowling Green State University,  B.A.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1978; Stanford University,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William Mack Webner</B> (<I>Washington; 202-467-8818</I>) Counseling,  registration,  licensing,  trial,  and appellate practice in trademarks,  copyrights,  and unfair competition for commercial clients and publicity rights of Elvis Presley and Charlie Chaplin. University of Akron,  J.D.,  1968; New York University,  LL.M.,  1974.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
