<HEAD>
<TITLE>Welsh  & Katz,  Ltd.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Welsh  & Katz,  Ltd.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Chicago:</B> 120 South Riverside Plaza,  22nd Floor,  Chicago,  IL 60606<BR>
Tel 312-655-1500  <B>*</B>  Fax 312-655-1501<BR>
<B>Arlington: </B>Crystal Plaza One,  Suite 808,  2001 Jefferson Davis Highway, <BR>
Arlington,  VA 22202-3603<BR>
Tel 703-415-4777<BR>
<BR>
30 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers in intellectual property law practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>W</B>elsh  & Katz,  Ltd. specializes in the practice of intellectual property law and in other areas of law involving science and technology. The practice includes patents,  trademarks,  copyrights,  unfair competition,  trade secrets,  trade dress,  and related antitrust matters. The firm has extensive litigation experience in these areas,  and also specializes in the preparation and prosecution of patent,  trademark,  and copyright applications both in the U.S. and worldwide,  licensing and contract negotiations,  and protection against counterfeiting and product simulation. The attorneys of Welsh  & Katz have educational backgrounds and practical experience in virtually every engineering and scientific discipline to facilitate in the licensing,  protection,  and enforcement of intellectual property rights.
<P><BR><P>The attorneys of Welsh  & Katz,  Ltd. are frequent participants and featured speakers in continuing legal education activities and industry forums.<BR><P>Representative clients: Abbott-Interfast Corporation; American Association of Individual Investors,  Incorporated; Amoco Corporation; Bally Entertainment Corporation; Bally's Health  & Tennis Corporation; Bell  & Howell Company; Citylink Group,  Inc.; Cytel Corporation; Eversharp-Fisher Pen Company; General Electric Company; Hard Rock Cafe; HEICO Corporation; Hillerich  & Bradsby Company; ICD Publications,  Incorporated; Konami,  Inc.; Mattel,  Incorporated; National Marine Manufacturers Association,  Incorporated; Northwestern University; Papst Licensing GmbH; Precious Moments,  Inc.; Samsonite Corporation; The Scripps Research Institute; Taligent,  Incorporated; Texas Instruments,  Incorporated; Time Warner Interactive; Underwriter's Laboratories,  Incorporated; Walt Disney Productions; Wm. Wrigley Company.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>A. Sidney Katz</B> Engaged primarily in client counseling,  licensing,  and litigation concerning all areas of intellectual property law,  including patents,  trademarks,  and copyrights. Has extensive experience in the electronics field and has achieved significant recognition for work in the protection of computer programs and video games under the copyright laws. Illinois Institute of Technology,  B.S.,  electrical engineering,  1962; George Washington University,  J.D.,  1966.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard L. Wood</B> Client counseling in all facets of intellectual property law,  including both U.S. and foreign patent application preparation and prosecution in the mechanical and electromechanical arts,  and counseling,  licensing,  and litigation related to patent,  trademark,  copyright,  and unfair competition matters. Serves as an expert witness relating to U.S. patent law and U.S. Patent and Trademark Office practice and procedure. University of Michigan,  B.S.,  mechanical engineering,  1958; University of Michigan,  M.B.A,  1959; George Washington University,  J.D.,  1964.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jerold B. Schnayer</B> Trial and appellate litigation in area of patent,  copyright,  and trademark law. University of Illinois,  B.S.,  electrical engineering,  1972; Illinois Institute of Technology/Chicago-Kent College of Law,  J.D.,  with honors,  1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Eric C. Cohen</B> Specializes in trial work involving trade secrets,  unfair competition,  trademark,  copyright,  patent infringement,  and related matters. Case Institute of Technology,  B.S.,  physics,  1971; University of Miami,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1974.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Joseph R. Marcus</B> Counsels clients in all facets of intellectual property law including direction of corporate identification programs; patent,  trademark,  and copyright matters; trade secret matters; preparation of licensing contracts; negotiations,  client counseling; preparation of validity,  right-to-use,  and infringement opinions; and participation in unfair competition and deceptive trade practice litigation matters. Carnegie-Mellon University,  B.S.,  chemical engineering,  1958; Illinois Institute of Technology/Chicago-Kent College of Law,  J.D.,  1965.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gerald S. Schur</B> Primarily engaged in client counseling and litigation,  i.e.,  patent,  trademark,  and copyright law,  as well as in all other areas of intellectual property law. Mr. Schur has considerable experience in the chemical and chemical engineering fields and in the chemical-mechanical and mechanical areas. Purdue University,  B.S.,  chemical engineering,  1957; John Marshall Law School,  J.D.,  1963,  M.P.L.,  1968.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gerald T. Shekleton</B> Primarily engaged in patent,  trademark,  and copyright matters. Xavier University,  B.S.,  chemistry,  1969; Cleveland State University,  J.D.,  1973.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James A. Scheer</B> Experienced in practice of intellectual property law including prosecution of patents and trademarks,  licensing,  client counseling,  and litigation. Has extensive experience in the fields of physics and electronics,  particularly digital electronics and computer software,  as well as in a wide variety of other technologies in the mechanical and chemical arts. Professor of intellectual property law at the John Marshall Law School in Chicago. Serves as an expert witness relating to U.S. patent law and U.S. Patent and Trademark Office practice and procedure. University of Notre Dame,  B.S.,  engineering science,  1969; M.S.,  electrical engineering,  1970; Northern Illinois University,  J.D.,  1978; John Marshall Law School,  LL.M.,  intellectual property,  1991.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Daniel R. Cherry</B> Lecturer and author for Patent Research Group (PRG). Litigation,  prosecution of patents,  interferences,  trademark clearance and registration,  licensing,  intellectual property aspects of corporate transactions,  and client counseling. Litigation practice includes trials and appeals of cases involving patent,  trademark,  and copyright infringements,  trade secret misappropriations,  contract disputes,  and unfair competition. Experience in both jury and nonjurytrials and nonlitigation alternatives to resolve disputes. Massachusetts Institute of Technology,  B.S.,  1970; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert B. Breisblatt</B> A former assistant U.S. attorney for the Northern District of Illinois. Has conducted investigations and trials of complex white collar criminal matters including video copyright cases and criminal trademark cases,  and has also litigated noncriminal matters in the areas of copyright,  trademark,  and trade secrets. Florida State University,  B.A.,  1969; Duke University,  J.D.,  1972.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James P. White</B> A former assistant U.S. attorney for the Northern District of Illinois,  engaged primarily in the preparation and trial of civil cases in which he represented federal agencies and officers in affirmative and defensive litigation. Trial and appellate court litigation in patent,  copyright,  and unfair competition related matters. Michigan State University,  B.S.,  1969; Suffolk University Law School,  J.D.,  1973.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>R. Mark Halligan</B> Concentration in litigation involving trade secrets; unfair competition; antitrust matters; and patent,  copyright,  and trademark infringement. Active lecturer on trade secrets law. Author of <I>How to Identify and Protect Trade Secrets: The Illinois Trade Secrets Act</I> (Illinois Institute for Continuing Legal Education,  1992). University of Cincinnati,  B.A.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1975; Northwestern University School of Law,  J.D.,  1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Howard B. Rockman</B> All phases of patent,  trademark,  copyright,  trade secret,  and unfair competition law,  including litigation in the federal and state courts,  prosecution before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  licensing,  and client counseling. Mr. Rockman was a patent examiner in the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. Upon graduation,  he joined the litigation staff of the U.S. Department of Justice in the Antitrust Division and the Patent Litigation Section. Drexel Institute of Technology,  B.S.,  mechanical engineering,  1959; George Washington University,  J.D.,  with honors,  1963.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Hartwell P. Morse III</B> Familiar with all facets of litigation involving patent,  trademark,  and copyright infringements,  trade secret misappropriations,  and unfair competition. Denison University,  B.A.,  with honors,  1979; Dayton Law School,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1982.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Edward P. Gamson</B> Specializes in patent solicitation in chemical and biochemical areas ranging from drugs,  cosmetics,  and polymers to monoclonal antibodies,  peptide libraries,  oligosaccharides,  and genetically engineered plants. Has had extensive industry experience in small molecule,  dye,  and polymer syntheses and reaction kinetics,  and uses his laboratory and research experience to assist clients in expanding their patent horizons by focusing on research directions and patent protection. Trinity College,  B.S.,  chemistry,  1965; Northwestern University,  Ph.D.,  organic chemistry,  1970; John Marshall Law School,  J.D.,  1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kara E. F. Cenar</B> Primarily engaged in the litigation of patent,  trademark,  copyright,  trade secret,  unfair competition,  licensing,  contract,  and other related matters. Loyola University,  B.B.A.,  1985,  J.D.,  1988.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kathleen A. Rheintgen</B> Engaged in patent,  trademark,  and copyright prosecution; corporate identification programs; and patent,  trademark,  and copyright litigation matters. University of Illinois,  B.S.,  1985; Loyola University,  J.D.,  1988.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Donald L. Welsh</B> Experience has extended to all phases of intellectual property law including the prosecution of both U.S. and foreign patent applications,  especially in the electronics field,  and prosecution of U.S. and foreign trademark applications. Extensive litigation experience including trial work in patent,  trademark,  copyright,  and unfair competition cases. Also experienced in licensing contract preparation and negotiation,  and client counseling. Purdue University,  B.S.,  electrical engineering,  1946; University of Illinois,  J.D.,  1948.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James W. Clement</B> Extensive experience in client counseling,  preparation and prosecution of applications,  licensing,  and litigation in patents,  trademarks,  and copyrights,  in the U.S. and overseas. Has dealt with mechanical,  chemical,  and electrical technologies in his practice of patent law. University of Illinois,  A.B.,  1935,  M.S.,  chemistry,  1936,  B.S.,  physics,  1943; Northwestern University,  J.D.,  1941.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Laurie A. Haynie</B> Primarily engaged in copyright,  patent,  and trademark litigation matters. University of Utah,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1981; Brigham Young University Law School,  J.D.,  1984.
</UL>


