<HEAD>
<TITLE>Willian Brinks Hofer Gilson  & Lione
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Willian Brinks Hofer Gilson  & Lione
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<BR>
<B>Chicago:</B> NBC Tower,  455 North Cityfront Plaza Drive, Chicago,  IL 60611<BR>
Tel 312-321-4200  <B>*</B>  Fax 312-321-4299<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Washington,  D.C.,  Arlington (Virginia),  Indianapolis,  Toledo<BR>
<BR>
125 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers concentrate in intellectual property law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>E</B>xpert in all aspects of intellectual property and authors of key standard works on patents,  trademarks,  licensing,  and trade secrets,  we are at the vanguard of rapidly changing and newly established regulations in the computer,  telecommunications,  biotechnology,  sports,  and entertainment industries. Indeed,  we are helping to set the standards as well as establish the precedents for such burgeoning new arenas as: software,  voicemail,  and e-mail; the proliferating components of the information superhighway; cancer treatments,  genetically engineered enzymes,  and antibodies; and licensing for the increasingly complicated world of sports and entertainment marketing.<BR><BR><P>To better service evolving technologies on an international basis,  we have formed Technical Practice Groups. Each group specializes in a particular technology in order to assess and establish the best protection for clients. Such groups include biotechnology which,  in addition to the standard protection and prosecution of patents,  utilizes state-of-the-art software for managing data and client information. For the all-encompassing electronics data revolution,  we have a comprehensive depth of expertise for each product category to provide up-to-the-minute analyses of all electronic developments.<BR><BR><P>We are the largest IP law firm in the Midwest and are among the largest in the United States. Our clients include multinational corporations and small businesses throughout the United States and abroad; lawyers and judges with special projects; and private individuals. Willian Brinks is headquartered in Chicago and has offices in Washington,  D.C.,  Indianapolis,  and Toledo. We have 126 attorneys (56 partners,  62 associates,  8 counsel).<BR>
<BR><P>Bringing a century of experience to intellectual property,  Willian Brinks:<BR>
<BR><UL><P><LI> litigates in all traditional and evolving fields of intellectual property and before all venues including state and federal courts,  the International Trade Commission,  and administrative agencies;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> counsels clients on protection and full utilization of intellectual property assets as well as protection against infringement of the intellectual property rights of others;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> prosecutes worldwide patent,  trademark,  and copyright applications;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> manages patent,  trademark,  and copyright portfolios to maximize worldwide protection cost-effectively; and<BR>
<BR><P><LI> negotiates licenses and other technology-transfer agreements throughout the world.<BR>
<BR></UL><P>Our presence in business and academia is enhanced through the efforts of our attorney instructors and authors. Fifteen of our lawyers are either current adjunct professors,  or have recently been on staff at a number of the nation's most well-recognized law schools. Courses which are taught range in a variety of intellectual property law topics including patent,  trade secrets,  entertainment,  art and sports law.<BR>
<BR><P>Current standard references that Willian Brinks lawyers have written include: <I>Patents and the Federal Circuit</I> by Robert Harmon; <I>Trademark Protection and Practice</I> by Jerome Gilson; <I>Trade Secrets Law</I> by Melvin Jager; <I>Computer  & Telecommunications Fraud</I> by William Cook; <I>How the Non-Specialist Should Handle Patent Issues</I> by John Crossan; <I>What Corporate and General Practitioners Should Know About Intellectual Property Litigation</I> by Ray Lupo; <I>Designing An Effective Intellectual Property Compliance Program</I> by Allan Sterstein,  Cynthia Homan,  Richard Kaplan,  and William Frankel; and Butterworth's <I>Patent Litigation Enforcing A Global Patent Portfolio</I>,  edited by Gary Ropski.<BR>
<BR><BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Patents and Trade Secrets</H3></CENTER>

<P>Our practice's primary focus is patent and trade secrets litigation. Most recent jury trials have included determinations of damages as well as of validity and infringement. We have also participated in arbitrations,  minitrials,  summary jury trials,  and other forms of alternative dispute resolution where our lawyers have served as special masters and arbitrators.<BR><P>Besides litigating,  we advise clients on infringement and licensing,  and procure patents in all technical fields. Our lawyers are skilled at assimilating technical information quickly and obtaining protection that anticipates and discourages challenges.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Trademarks,  Copyrights,  and Unfair Competition</H3></CENTER>

<P>Willian Brinks registers,  enforces,  and defends trademarks and opposes trademark claims. We advise clients on the legal risks of adopting particular trademarks,  franchising,  and managing trademark portfolios worldwide. We arbitrate trademark disputes.<BR><P>We register copyrights worldwide,  determine copyright protection,  and litigate copyright claims.<BR>
<BR><P>We represent victims of unfair competition and alleged infringers in matters of trade dress infringement,  counterfeit products,  dilution,  unfair trade practices,  rights of publicity,  and entertainment law.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>ITC Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>Willian Brinks represents both complainants and respondents before the U.S. International Trade Commission to resolve import disputes.<BR><P>Major clients include: Herman Miller,  Inc.,  Kimberly-Clark,  BP International,  Whitaker Corporation (AMP Incorporated),  Minolta Co.,  Taito Corporation,  Matsushita,  Kaken Pharmaceuticals,  Nike,  Inc.,  USX Corporation,  Hughes Aircraft,  and SGS-Thompson Microelectronics.<BR>
<BR><P>Major cases include: <I>Novo Industri A/S </I>v.<I> Travenol Laboratories Inc.</I>; <I>Goldberg </I>v<I>. Medtronic,  Inc.</I>; <I>Lear Siegler </I>v.<I> Sealy Mattress Company of Michigan,  Inc.</I>; <I>BF Goodrich Flight Systems Inc. </I>v.<I> Insight Instrument Corporation et al.</I>; <I>National Presto </I>v.<I> Daisy Corporation</I>; <I>Intermatic </I>v.<I> Chardonnay Corporation et al.</I>; <I>Coca-Cola </I>v.<I> Reed et al.</I>; <I>Kennecott </I>v.<I> Kyocera</I>; <I>Wolverine World Wide,  Inc. </I>v.<I> Nike,  Inc.</I>; <I>Amway Corporation </I>v.<I> Nartron Corporation</I>; <I>AMP Incorporated </I>v. <I>American Telephone and Telegraph Company</I>; <I>American Hospital Corp. </I>v.<I> Damon Corp.</I>; <I>Everpure </I>v. <I>Cuno</I>; <I>Cuno </I>v.<I> Pall</I>; <I>Williams  & Humbert </I>v.<I> W. H. Trademarks</I>; and <I>Palmer </I>v.<I> Fox</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Clyde F. Willian</B> specializes in litigation that involves technical subject matter,  and has participated in more than 100 litigated cases. His practice includes patents,  trade secrets,  unfair competition,  antitrust litigation,  and licensing. He lectures extensively on intellectual property issues before the American Bar Association,  American Intellectual Property Law Association,  Practising Law Institute,  The John Marshall Law School,  Northwestern University Corporate Counsel Institute,  Patent Resources Group,  Inc.,  and other groups. He is also the general counsel to the Licensing Executives Society.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Henry L. Brinks</B> litigates and counsels on all aspects of intellectual property. He lectures on litigation and patent law and is the author of <I>Preliminary Injunctions in Patent Infringement Cases in the United States and Germany</I>,  with Ulrich Fritze (Gewerblicher Rechtsschutz Und Urheberrecht Internationaler Teil,  1987). A member of the Board of Directors of the American Intellectual Property Law Association and the Intellectual Property Law Association of Chicago,  he is also a member of the International Association for the Protection of Industrial Property,  Chicago Bar Association,  Carolina Patent Law Association,  and Licensing Executives Society.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Roy E. Hofer</B> is the president of Willian Brinks. He specializes in patent,  trade secrets,  unfair competition,  antitrust,  and contract litigation as well as licensing. Mr. Hofer has written and lectured extensively on trial techniques and intellectual property law. He served as president of the Circuit Bar Association,  Chicago Bar Association,  and the Center for Conflict Resolution,  and as a member of the board of directors of the American Bar Association's sections of Patent,  Trademark,  and Copyright,  Litigation,  and Antitrust; Federal Circuit Bar Association; Illinois Institute for Continuing Legal Education; and Intellectual Property Law Association of Chicago.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jerome Gilson</B> specializes in trademarks and unfair competition. In addition to authoring a standard treatise on trademark protection,  he has written numerous articles for <I>The Trademark Reporter</I>,  <I>Southwestern Legal Foundation Patent Law Annual</I>,  and <I>CBA Record</I>. Mr. Gilson negotiated and drafted portions of the Trademark Law Revision Act of 1988,  the first comprehensive revision of the Lanham Act of 1946. He lectures before the American Bar Association,  U.S. Trademark Association,  American Intellectual Property Association,  and Chicago Bar Association. He is a reporter for the Trademark Review Commission of the U.S. Trademark Association; panelist for the Center for Public Resources/INTA Alternative Dispute Resolution Joint Venture; and counsel to the U.S./ International Trademark Association. He has also chaired numerous committees for the U.S. Trademark Association.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard G. Lione</B> counsels and litigates on patents,  trade secrets,  trademarks,  and copyrights. His patent litigation experience encompasses such diverse technologies as robotics,  machine tools,  aircraft instrumentation,  textile machinery,  packaging machinery,  publishing equipment,  electrical connectors,  and food chemistry. He has lectured on intellectual property litigation for the American Bar Association's Litigation Section. Mr. Lione was a patent examiner in the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office,  and has prosecuted matters before the PTO since 1960.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James B. Blanchard</B> practices patent and trade secrets litigation and licensing. He specializes in electronic and electromechanical systems.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert L. Harmon</B> practices patent,  trade secrets,  and antitrust litigation,  licensing and counseling. He has extensive experience in robotics,  electronics,  machine tools,  plastics machinery,  genetics,  electrostatic coating,  computers,  and agriculture.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Melvin F. Jager</B> practices patent,  trade secrets,  trademark,  copyright and antitrust litigation,  licensing and counseling. An authority on the subject,  Mr. Jager authored a treatise on trade secret law. In addition,  he has written and lectured extensively on trade secrets and has specialized in protection for computer software.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David A. Anderson</B> practices patent and unfair competition litigation and counseling. He specializes in the chemical and mechanical arts,  and in the handling of appeals before the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jack C. Berenzweig</B> practices patent,  trademark,  and copyright litigation. He is an expert in protecting manufacturers against the distribution of counterfeit copies of their products and has chaired the Anticounterfeiting Subcommittee of the U.S. Trademark Association. He is a past member of the Board of Directors of the International Trademark Association,  and presently serves on the Board of Directors of the Brand Names Education Foundation.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Jerold A. Jacover</B> practices patent,  unfair competition,  and entertainment litigation. He has extensive experience in a wide variety of technologies including electronic circuitry,  remote controls,  robotics,  electromechanical systems,  and food and beverage equipment.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John J. Pavlak</B> practices patent and trade secrets litigation,  and counseling. He is an expert in mechanical and chemical technologies including polymers,  plastics,  and chemical processes,  and has written extensively on patent damages and willful patent infringement.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gary M. Ropski</B> practices patent,  trademark,  trade secrets,  copyright,  and right of publicity litigation; counseling; and presenting and rebutting damage theories. He has extensive experience in robotics,  machine tools,  can ends,  biomedical devices,  consumer housewares,  electrical connectors,  conveying equipment,  navigational devices,  steelmaking processes,  and computer software. He has also won awards from the American Intellectual Property Law Association and the International Trademark Association for his patent and trademark articles.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William A. Webb</B> practices patent prosecution and counseling,  trade secrets,  antitrust,  and licensing. Before practicing law,  Mr. Webb worked as a project engineer for Baird Atomic,  Inc.,  where he specialized in computer-controlled optical systems.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Joel W. Benson</B> practices patent,  trade secrets,  antitrust and contract litigation,  technology licensing and intellectual property counseling. He prepares and prosecutes patent applications worldwide,  and prosecutes interferences and patent appeals in the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. Mr. Benson,  a former design and development engineer for Bell Laboratories,  is an expert in logic circuit design and has substantial expertise in computers and electronics.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John K. Lucas</B> practices patent,  trade secrets and copyright litigation,  licensing and counseling. He handles intellectual property matters in a wide variety of disciplines including food technology and electronic,  electromechanical,  and mechanical systems.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James R. Sobieraj</B> practices patent,  trade secrets,  related antitrust,  unfair competition,  and licensing litigation. He has extensive experience in electronics,  robotics,  electromechanical devices,  hydraulics,  chemical compositions and processes,  and packaging materials; and litigation experience with temporary restraining orders,  preliminary injunctions,  damages,  and alternative dispute resolution.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Allan J. Sternstein</B> practices patent,  copyright,  and trade secrets litigation,  counseling and licensing. He specializes in electronics,  computer-controlled products and processes,  medical products and equipment,  pharmaceuticals,  metals,  and plastic films.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Raphael V. Lupo</B> practices patent,  trademark,  copyright,  and trade secrets litigation and counseling. He has extensive trial and appellate experience in the federal courts and before the U.S. International Trade Commission,  has written and lectured on litigation practice before the ITC and specializes in semiconductors,  computers,  electronics,  and ion exchange resins.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jack Q. Lever,  Jr.</B> practices patent,  trademark,  copyright,  and trade secrets litigation and counseling. He specializes in federal,  appellate,  and U.S. International Trade Commission litigation,  and has written and lectured widely on practice before the ITC.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Susan Somers Neal</B> specializes in trademarks,  false advertising,  trade dress,  counterfeiting,  and unfair competition. An expert in trademark availability,  registration,  and licensing,  she has extensive experience in <I>inter partes</I> and <I>ex parte</I> proceedings before the Trademark Trial and Appeal Board.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Donna M. Tanguay</B> practices patent,  trademark,  copyright,  and trade secrets litigation and counseling. An authority on litigating before the U.S. International Trade Commission,  she also has extensive experience with the federal courts.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
