<HEAD>
<TITLE>Wilson Sonsini Goodrich & Rosati
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Intellectual Property</H2>
<H3>Wilson Sonsini Goodrich & Rosati
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Palo Alto:</B> 650 Page Mill Road,  Palo Alto,  CA 94304-1050<BR>
Tel 415-493-9300  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-493-6811  <B>*</B>  E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:wsgr@wsgr.com">wsgr@wsgr.com</A><BR>
<BR>
275 lawyers  <B>*</B>  63 lawyers in the Intellectual Property and Technology Practice Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>W</B>ilson Sonsini Goodrich  & Rosati is the largest law firm based in Silicon Valley and concentrates on the representation of high-technology,  life sciences,  and other emerging growth companies. The firm represents diverse domestic and international clients,  ranging from privately held startups to Fortune 500 companies,  including: Autodesk,  Borland International,  Broderbund Software,  Cell Genesys,  Conner Peripherals,  Cypress Semiconductor,  Geoworks,  Global Village Communication,  Novell,  Octel Communications,  Seagate Technology,  Silicon Graphics,  Solectron,  StarSight Telecast,  Sun Microsystems,  Sybase,  Synopsys,  SyStemix,  and Ventritex.
<P><BR><P>The firm's intellectual property practice includes:<BR><P><I>Intellectual Property Litigation:</I> Approximately 35 of the firm's attorneys are engaged in patent (both federal district court and International Trade Commission),  copyright,  trade secret,  and trademark litigation.<BR>
<BR><P>Representative cases include: <I>Lotus Development Corp. </I>v.<I> Borland International </I>(software copyright); <I>Intel </I>v.<I> ULSI</I>,  <I>IBM </I>v.<I> Conner Peripherals,  Inc.</I>,  and <I>Octel Communications </I>v. <I>Theis Research,  Inc.</I> (patent); <I>In the Matter of Certain Plastic Encapsulated Integrated Circuits</I> (337); <I>IBM </I>v.<I> Seagate Technology</I> and <I>Borland International </I>v.<I> Symantec</I> (trade secrets); and <I>Quality Semiconductor,  Inc. </I>v.<I> QLogic Corporation</I> (trademarks).<BR>
<BR><P><I>Technology Transactions:</I> The 20 lawyers in this group structure and negotiate agreements and provide counsel for the development,  protection,  manufacture,  licensing,  and distribution of products and technologies,  both domestically and internationally. Attorneys in the group focus on transactions in particular industries,  including computer software and hardware,  multimedia,  telecommunications,  and life sciences.<BR>
<BR><P><I>Patents:</I> The firm's Patent Group is involved in patent prosecution,  counseling,  and licensing. The attorneys in the Patent Group are registered to practice before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. The group advises clients in setting up offensive and defensive patent portfolios,  designing around valid patents,  and other methods to limit exposure to patent infringement.<BR>
<BR><P><I>Trademarks and Advertising Practices:</I> The firm's Trademark and Advertising Practices Group offers a range of services in connection with foreign and domestic trademark protection,  including registration,  <I>inter partes</I> proceedings,  licensing,  and related matters.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Michael Barclay</B>'s practice is focused on patent and other intellectual property litigation and counseling in the fields of electronics,  including semiconductors,  computer software and hardware,  and communications.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Henry V. Barry</B> heads the firm's Interactive New Media Practice Group. His practice focuses on the representation of emerging growth companies,  with a particular emphasis on the intellectual property issues those companies face.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>David J. Berger</B> has litigated many of the leading high-technology intellectual property cases,  including <I>IBM </I>v.<I> Seagate</I> and <I>Lotus </I>v.<I> Borland</I>. Mr. Berger is also a frequent author on intellectual property issues.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Andrew P. Bridges</B> heads the firm's Trademarks and Advertising Practices Group. His practice is directed exclusively to litigation and counseling concerning trademarks,  advertising practices,  marketing,  and unfair competition law.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Peter P. Chen</B> represents high-technology companies in the electronics and life sciences areas in intellectual property litigation and counseling matters involving patents,  copyrights,  trademarks,  and trade secrets.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Kenneth A. Clark</B> heads the firm's Technology Transactions Group. He represents technology and life sciences companies in a variety of transactions,  including strategic alliances,  and other licensing and development relationships.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>James A. DiBoise</B> is one of the firm's senior litigators practicing in the intellectual property area. Mr. DiBoise has handled significant cases in the areas of trade secrets (<I>IBM </I>v.<I> Seagate</I>),  and copyright (<I>Lotus </I>v.<I> Borland</I>),  as well as important patent issues for many of the firm's high-technology clients.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Stephen C. Durant</B> heads the firm's Patent Group. His practice includes patent prosecution,  licensing,  and counseling in intellectual property issues primarily in the electronics,  computer,  and software arts.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Michael A. Ladra</B> focuses on intellectual property litigation,  especially with respect to trade secrets,  trademarks,  and patent infringement. He successfully defended <I>Intel </I>v.<I> ULSI</I>,  which resulted in a published opinion of importance to the semiconductor industry. Most recently,  he has been engaged in the <I>Conner Peripherals </I>v.<I> IBM</I> and <I>Compaq </I>v.<I> Packard Bell</I> patent litigations.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Gary L. Reback</B> heads the firm's Technology and Intellectual Property Practice Group. He counsels and litigates on computer technology issues,  including copyright infringement of code and screen displays,  development of emulating or compatible software,  and technology licensing. He is lead counsel in a number of screen display cases,  including <I>Lotus </I>v.<I> Borland</I>. He was also counsel for the unnamed <I>amici</I> in <I>U.S. </I>v.<I> Microsoft</I>.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Ron E. Shulman</B>'s practice focuses principally on prosecuting and defending patent infringement actions in federal courts throughout the country. He has litigated patents concerning a broad spectrum of subject matter,  such as integrated circuits,  medical devices,  telecommunications equipment,  and various chemical compositions and processes.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Kenneth B. Wilson</B> practices patent,  copyright,  and trade secret litigation and counseling,  with particular experience in handling intellectual property matters before the International Trade Commission.
</UL>


