<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Hogan & Hartson LLP </TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL><CENTER><H2>International Practice</H2><H3>Hogan & Hartson LLP</H3></CENTER><CENTER><B>Washington:</B> 555 13th Street, N.W., Washington, DC 20004<BR>Tel 202-637-5600 <B>*</B> Fax 202-637-5910<P><B>Other offices:</B> Brussels, Budapest, London, Moscow, Paris (affiliatedoffice),Prague, Warsaw, Baltimore, Bethesda (Maryland), Colorado Springs, Denver, McLean(Virginia)<BR>435 lawyers  <B>*</B>  150 lawyers practicing in the international area<BR></CENTER><!---<P>See this firm's profile in the following other directory:<BR><UL><BR>   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/bass.html"> Workout</A></UL><P><BR>---><P>Founded at the turn of this century, Hogan & Hartson approaches the next centuryas one of the nation's most diverse and experienced law firms, and one ofWashington, D.C.'s largest. For over 90 years, the firm has assisted its clientsin achieving their global objectives, which today as never before involveinternational developments and transactions.</P><H4>International Corporate and Tax</H4><P>Hogan & Hartson's international corporate and tax practice combines extensivetransactional experience with practical industry knowledge. In addition, ourregulatory lawyers have experience resolving the full range of U.S., EuropeanUnion, and other governmental issues inherent in most large internationaltransactions. Our experience includes: U.S. and European acquisitions, strategicinvestments, and joint ventures; privatization of state-owned enterprises;cross-border debt and equity offerings and structured financings; technology andintellectual property licensing, transfer, and commercialization; public andproject financings; and the broad range of commercial transactions.</P><P>	Hogan & Hartson's corporate and tax representation of multinationalinvestors in Europe has included: cross-border acquisitions and divestitures ofaerospace, defense, telecommunications, chemical, engineering, and servicesbusinesses; refinancing and investing in the largest theme park in Europe;purchasing the largest commercial property project in London; internationalstrategic investment and joint operating arrangements for a major U.S. satellitemanufacturer; organizing a $500 million international telecommunications jointventure; and cross-border distribution, franchise, and licensing arrangements.Other examples of transactions handled by firm lawyers include: privatizationof, and joint ventures with, large Eastern European enterprises; investing inthe largest private television group in Italy; and European equity offerings inthe United States. We also have particular experience handling IRS transferpricing, Section 6038A, and related issues.</P><H4>Western European Practice</H4><P>Hogan & Hartson's offices in Brussels, London and Paris counsel American,European, and other international clients in a broad range of internationalbusiness law and commercial transactions. The firm's lawyers in Europe haveextensive experience in European transactional matters and in acting as generalEuropean counsel for multinational companies, taking responsibility for handlinglegal matters throughout Western and Eastern Europe. In addition, the officescounsel clients regarding Belgian and French corporate, commercial, financial,banking and labor law issues.</P><P>	The Brussels office also provides experienced and specialized representationin significant areas of European Union and national regulation, includingantitrust and trade regulation; aviation; environmental and safety laws; food,cosmetics and agriculture; international trade; public procurement; andtelecommunications. The European regulatory services provided include assistancein complying with EU regulatory requirements, analysis and advice concerning EUlegal developments, and representation before European Union institutions.</P><H4>Central and East European Practice</H4><P>The firm's approach to Central and Eastern Europe combines a unique blend ofsophisticated Western commercial experience, local lawyers with multilingualcapability, and industry knowledge provided by Hogan & Hartson's regulatorypractice in Washington and Brussels. By bridging cultures and providing lawyersexpert in the client's line of business, the firm most effectively assistsclients in achieving their business objectives. Representative matters handledby the firm include obtaining financing and insurance for foreign directinvestment in Central and Eastern European countries, privatizations, jointventures, acquisitions, sales of businesses, licensing and distributionactivities, cross-border secured loans by multilateral financial institutions,and extensive corporate finance and regulatory work in the fields of energy,telecommunications, pharmaceuticals, banking, food, and agriculture. The firm'sCentral and Eastern European offices also handle questions of local law,litigation, arbitration, and government affairs.</P><H4>International Trade</H4><P>Hogan & Hartson's extensive international trade practice assists clients locatedin foreign countries and the United States in the resolution of issues involvingrights and obligations under the WTO, NAFTA, and other regional arrangements, aswell as access to the European, U.S., Asian, and other international markets;alleged unfair trade practices (e.g., antidumping and countervailing dutycases); establishment and administration of foreign trade zones and similarprocedures; and commercial matters involving international trade and investmentissues. Additional areas handled by the Trade Group include trade policydecisions by the European Commission and the U.S. Congress and Executive Branch;trade negotiations, trade litigation under all European Union and U.S. tradelaws; import matters under customs laws; export licensing and enforcementmatters; regulation of foreign investment in the United States and Europe; andimmigration issues.</P><H4>Pacific Rim Practice</H4><P>Hogan & Hartson has a long tradition of representing corporations andgovernments located throughout the Pacific Rim, as well as U.S. interests doingbusiness in Asia. For U.S. clients, the firm has handled a broad range ofcommercial transactions in Asia and assisted clients in dealing with thegovernment sector in many Pacific Rim countries. Firm attorneys have structuredand advised on international investments, including acquisitions and jointventures; financing arrangements and securities offerings; technology transferand licensing agreements; and tax planning for international ventures.</P><P>	The firm also has an extensive base of Pacific Rim clients doing business inthe United States, for which the firm provides corporate and securities adviceand assistance, and handles multinational litigation. In addition, the firmassists Asian clients with U.S. government regulation and policy affecting theirability to enter and market their products in the United States. Hogan & Hartsonis a member of the Pacific Rim Advisory Council, a network of leading law firmsin that region.</P><BR>	<BR><LI><B>Jeanne S. Archibald</B>-General Counsel, U.S. Department of the Treasury,1990-1993; handles international trade and financial policy matters.	<BR><LI><B>Steven E. Ballew</B>-Assists companies in a variety of industries in assessingand implementing investment opportunities in Poland and Central Europe. Residentin Warsaw office.	<BR><LI><B>Michael D. Barnes</B>-U.S. Representative, 1979-1987 (chairman, Subcommitteeon Western Hemisphere Affairs; member, Subcommittee on Asian and PacificAffairs); international practice with emphasis on Latin America.	<BR><LI><B>Raymond J. Batla, Jr.</B>-Represents multinational and Central Europeanenterprises in energy project financing, privatization, strategic investment,and commercial transactions. Resident in Budapest, London, and Prague offices.	<BR><LI><B>Joseph C. Bell</B>-Served as advisor to Polish and Ukrainian governments.Advises on strategic and legal aspects of investment, finance, and commercialtransactions in Central and Eastern Europe.	<BR><LI><B>Rebecca B. Bronson</B>-Handles project and infrastructure finance, withparticular emphasis on highly structured debt financings for large capitalprojects. Resident in Moscow office.	<BR><LI><B>Raymond S. Calamaro</B>-Practiced in Brussels from 1990 to 1994. Representsboth U.S. and nonU.S. corporations before government agencies and officials inWashington, D.C. and in Brussels.	<BR><LI><B>Alan F. Cariddi</B>-Practices in the areas of corporate, commercial, banking,and financial law, labor law, and arbitration and litigation. Resident in Parisoffice.	<BR><LI><B>Michael L. Cheroutes</B>-Practices public/project finance law, with particularfocus on major infrastructure construction and privatization projects.	<BR><LI><B>Sergey B. Chetverikov</B>-Former deputy ambassador of the Russian Federation.Assists clients with business plans and activities in Russia and other republicsof the former USSR. Resident in Moscow and D.C. offices.	<BR><LI><B>Claudette M. Christian</B>-Practices principally in the international andtransactional area with particular emphasis in international and projectfinance.	<BR><LI><B>Dean W. Crowell</B>-Represents clients in international commercial transactions,including cross-border acquisitions, joint ventures, and strategic alliances,particularly in Central Europe and Russia. Resident in Paris and Moscow offices.	<BR><LI><B>Claud v.S. Eley</B>-Handles transactions such as acquisitions, divestitures,joint ventures, and mergers, as well as general ongoing corporate counseling forclients doing business in Europe. Resident in Brussels office.	<BR><LI><B>Frank J. Fahrenkopf, Jr.</B>-Former chairman, Republican National Committee;handles trade policy issues involving Central and East European countries, aswell as Korean and Taiwanese entities.	<BR><LI><B>Gerald E. Gilbert</B>-Handles U.S.Asian trade matters, with particular emphasison representation of Korean and Japanese clients, and handles litigation beforeIranian Claims and similar international tribunals.	<BR><LI><B>Kenneth J. Hautman</B>-Represents companies in commercializing technology aswell as companies acquiring technology, and has negotiated internationalagreements in the EU, Russia, and Central Europe.	<BR><LI><B>Robert J. Jeffers</B>-Handles international mergers, acquisitions, and jointventures; financings and technology matters; Foreign Corrupt Practices Actmatters; and international corporate transactions involving China and Australia.	<BR><LI><B>Lewis E. Leibowitz</B>-Board member and treasurer, National Association ofForeign Trade Zones, 1986-1989. Handles major trade litigation, e.g.,antidumping and countervailing duty cases.	<BR><LI><B>Daniel H. Maccoby</B>-Represents U.S., European, and Middle Eastern corporationsin acquisitions, joint ventures, financings, and privatization transactions, andin establishing European operations. Resident in London office.	<BR><LI><B>Mark E. Mazo</B>-Represents European corporations and major internationalinvestors in acquisitions, strategic investments, joint ventures, and financingsin the U.S. and Western Europe. Resident in Washington and Paris offices.	<BR><LI><B>Mark S. McConnell</B>-Heads International Trade Group's export control practiceand handles major trade litigation.	<BR><LI><B>Bruce C. Mee</B>-Practices in the areas of banking and financial law, commerciallaw, industrial and intellectual property law, and estate law. Resident in Parisoffice.	<BR><LI><B>Todd Miller</B>-Advises U.S. and foreign corporations on tax aspects ofinternational transactions and transfer pricing.	<BR><LI><B>Randy E. Miller</B>-Heads firm's International Group and represents clientsin EU and European commercial and regulatory matters. Resident in D.C. andBrussels.	<BR><LI><B>Kornelia Nagy</B>-Koppny-Handles corporate and project finance; banking,bankruptcy, and liquidation matters; real estate; entertainment law; and energylaw. Resident in Budapest office.	<BR><LI><B>Gerald E. Oberst, Jr.</B>-Practices in the area of telecommunications law,with an emphasis in international telecommunications and satellite regulatorymatters. Resident in Brussels office.	<BR><LI><B>James J. Rosenhauer</B>-Administers the firm's commercial practice. Representsclients in international mergers and acquisitions, joint ventures, project andother financings, and other commercial transactions in the U.S. and WesternEurope.	<BR><LI><B>Fabrice Ru&#233;</B>-Practices in the areas of tax law, banking and financiallaw, corporate law, labor law, intellectual property law, and energy law.Resident in Paris office.	<BR><LI><B>Joel S. Winnik</B>-Served in the FCC's Common Carrier Bureau, handlinginternational and satellite matters. Concentration on internationaltelecommunications issues involving U.S., European, Asian, and Latin Americanclients.	<BR><LI><B>Clayton Yeutter</B>-Former U.S. Trade Representative, 1985-1988; U.S. Secretaryof Agriculture, 1989-1991. Broad trade and commercial practice.<BR></UL></UL></BODY></HTML>
