<HEAD>

<TITLE>Kilpatrick & Cody

</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>



<CENTER>

<H2>International Practice</H2>

<H3>Kilpatrick & Cody

</H3>



</CENTER>

<CENTER>

<B>Atlanta:</B> Suite 2800, 1100 Peachtree Street N.E., Atlanta, GA 30309<BR>
Tel 404-815-6500 <B>*</B> Fax 404-815-6555 <B>*</B> E-mail: <a href="mailto:info@kilcody.com">info@kilcody.com</a><BR>
<B>Washington:</B> Suite 800, 700 13th Street N.W., Washington, DC 20005<BR>
Tel 202-508-5800 <B>*</B> Fax 202-508-5858<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Augusta (Georgia), London, Brussels

<BR><BR>

218 lawyers <B>*</B> 10 lawyers with international arbitration experience



</CENTER>
<!---

<P>See this firm's profile in the following other directory:<BR>

<UL><BR>

   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/bass.html"> Workout</A>

</UL>



<P><BR>

--->

<P>

<P>The lawyers of Kilpatrick & Cody serve clients around the world from offices in
Atlanta, Augusta, Washington, D.C., London, and Brussels. The hallmark of our
service is our ability to develop cost-effective relationships with our
clients-relationships based on quality, efficiency, and teamwork-to solve their
problems and achieve their goals.</P>

<H4>International Arbitration</H4>
<P>Since 1986, Kilpatrick & Cody has represented transnational business enterprises
in international arbitration disputes in the United Kingdom, France, Denmark,
Switzerland, Sweden, Mexico, and the United States. The arbitral forums have
included the International Chambers of Commerce, the London Court of
International Arbitration, the American Arbitration Association, the World
Intellectual Property Organization, the CPR Institute for Dispute Resolution,
and various Chambers of Commerce throughout Europe.</P>
<P>	The firm's clients in such matters have included companies from England,
Germany, Finland, Sweden, Latin America, and the United States. Industries
represented include telecommunications, construction, heavy machinery, and
consumer products. The subject matter of the disputes has included trademark and
patent rights, agency and distribution matters, franchise agreements, joint
ventures, and other commercial contracts. In most of these matters, Kilpatrick &
Cody has acted as lead counsel, with such assistance from qualified local
counsel as may be necessary.</P>
<P>	Kilpatrick & Cody's international arbitration practice has been rapidly
expanding in recent years, not only because of the quality of the service
provided and the results obtained, but also because of substantial competitive
cost advantages in using Atlanta-based counsel experienced in such matters to
perform time-intensive tasks. Current exchange rates further confirm these cost
advantages. European clients, as well as American-based companies, have
perceived and availed themselves of these advantages.</P>
<P>	Sophisticated communications technology and the firm's European offices
provide important support for the international arbitration practice.</P>
<P>	References provided on request. All contacts should be made with A. Stephens
Clay, through any of the firm's offices. Mr. Clay has been substantially
involved in international arbitration for ten years.</P>

<BR>


<BR><LI><B>A. Stephen Clay</B> (404-815-6514)-Experienced as advocate, arbitrator, and mediator
in ICC, LCIA, and AAA arbitrations in the U.S., Cyprus, Switzerland, Sweden, and
the United Kingdom. Certified as master mediator by CPR Institute, New York.

<BR><LI><B>Roderick C. Dennehy, Jr.</B> (404-815-6249)-Involved in the areas of commercial and
construction litigation, with experience in transportation matters.

<BR><LI><B>Thomas C. Harney</B> (404-815-6324)-Has handled significant cases in the areas of
unfair trade practices, real estate, banking and instruments, sales,
intrabusiness conflicts, contracts, breach of trust and fiduciary duty, fraud,
and creditor remedies.

<BR><LI><B>Neil I. Levy</B> (202-508-5820)-Involved in government contract, real estate, and
ERISA litigation; jury and nonjury trial and appellate experience in federal and
state courts, and in administrative and arbitration proceedings.

<BR><LI><B>Kent E. Mast</B> (404-815-6477)-Experienced in complex litigation with concentration
in antitrust/trade regulation, including criminal and FTC proceedings; product
distribution, marketing, communications, and consumer-protection matters.

<BR><LI><B>Mara McRae</B> (404-815-6574)-Experienced in complex commercial arbitration,
including practice before the ICC, LCIA, AAA, and Zurich Chamber of Commerce.

<BR><LI><B>Matthew H. Patton</B> (404-815-6460)-Represents companies in civil litigation and
dispute resolution involving telecommunications and other technology,
intellectual property, unfair trade practices, business disputes, and tort
matters.

<BR><LI><B>Caroline W. Spangenberg</B> (404-815-6488)-Represents companies in insurance
coverage, indemnity, products liability, and environmental disputes.

<BR><LI>Jeffrey J. Toney</B> (404-815-6266)-Experienced as an advocate in arbitrations
administered by ICC, the Zurich Chamber of Commerce, the Stockholm Chamber of
Commerce, and the AAA in the U.S. and Europe.

<BR><LI><B>Frederick H. von Unwerth</B> (202-508-5850)-Specializes in antitrust and trade
regulation litigation, Hart-Scott-Rodino Act premerger proceedings, federal and
state antitrust investigations, and business counseling to avoid antitrust
problems, including health care antitrust matters.
<BR>



</UL>





