<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton & Garrison</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL><CENTER><H2>International Practice</H2><H3>Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton & Garrison</H3></CENTER><CENTER><B>New York:</B> 1285 Avenue of the Americas, New York, NY 10019<BR>Tel 212-373-3000 <B>*</B> Fax 212-757-3990<BR><B>Washington:</B> 1615 L Street, N.W., Washington, DC 20036<BR>Tel 202-223-7300 <B>*</B> Fax 202-223-7420<BR><B>Paris:</B> 199, Boulevard Saint-Germain, 75007 Paris, France<BR>Tel 33-1-45-49-33-85 <B>*</B> Fax 33-1-42-22-64-38<BR><B>Tokyo:</B> Akasaka Twin Tower, 17-22, Akasaka 2-chome, Minato-ku, Tokyo 107, Japan<BR>Tel 81-3-3505-0291 <B>*</B> Fax 81-3-3505-4540<BR><B>Beijing:</B> Scite Tower (Noble Tower), Room 904, 22, Jianguomenwai Dajie,<BR>Beijing 100004, People's Republic of China<BR>Tel 86-1-512-3628 <B>*</B> Fax 86-1-512-3631<BR><BR>345 lawyers <B>*</B> 11 lawyers practice international arbitration</CENTER><!---<P>See this firm's profile in the following other directory:<BR><UL><BR>   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/bass.html"> Workout</A></UL><P><BR>---><P><B>T</B>he importance, complexity, and number of international arbitrations in whichPaul, Weiss attorneys, based in its offices in the United States, Europe, andAsia, have participated in recent years, either as lawyers for a party or asappointed arbitrators, means that the firm can offer to its clients vastresources of skill and experience in arbitrating international disputes.Moreover, by bringing to bear the combined talents and knowledge of seasonedinternational arbitration lawyers of several nationalities, the Firm providesthe international perspective required to protect the interests of its clientsdoing business across national borders, beginning with making crucial choicesregarding what type of dispute resolution provision to include in aninternational contract, through arbitration of the dispute in an internationalforum.<P>	The subject matters of the international arbitrations that Paul, Weissattorneys have handled are nearly as varied as international trade and commerceitself. These controversies have involved construction contracts, franchiseagreements, intellectual property rights, shareholders' agreements, andlong-term oil and gas supply contracts, to cite just a few examples. Paul, Weissalso represented the prevailing party in the first major International Chamberof Commerce (ICC) "fast-track" arbitration, where proceedings were held and anaward delivered within 60 days after the arbitration was commenced.	<P>	The firm has been intimately involved, through its Paris office, with allphases of one of the largest construction projects of this century, the ChannelTunnel, from its conception in 1985 through the arbitration of several sizeabledisputes which have arisen in connection with building and operating the Tunnel,which continue to this day; it has represented an African national against aEuropean oil company, successfully defeating a claim for breach of a long-termoil supply contract in an ICC arbitration in France; is currently representing aJapanese client in related European arbitrations concerning technology licensetransfers; represents a large South American industrial company in an ICCarbitration commenced against a leading Scandinavian manufacturer of heavyequipment; successfully represented a U.S. shareholder in a Danish corporationin an ICC arbitration governed by Danish law, brought by Danish shareholdersalleging violation of a shareholders agreement; represented a U.S. company in aChinese arbitration against a PRC claimant, and a Chinese bank against aEuropean exporter in an arbitration brought under the rules of the StockholmChamber of Commerce; and represented two principal parties in an ICC"fast-track" arbitration involving the validity and enforceability of along-term natural gas contract between a Canadian seller and a U.S. buyer, whichunderpinned a $2.5 billion CanadianU.S. pipeline project.	<P>In addition, Paul, Weiss attorneys have acted as arbitrators in many recentmatters, including a dispute between U.S. and U.K. parties, both leaders in thefield of glass production, with the seat of the arbitration in London; acontroversy concerning a construction project in Senegal, governed by the rulesprovided by the European Development Fund; an ICC arbitration in New Yorkbetween a U.S. company and its Malaysian and Singaporean franchisees; and adispute between the Hong Kong subsidiary of a U.S. company and a Shanghai firm,whose governing law was Chinese with the seat of the arbitration in Stockholm.</UL></UL></BODY></HTML>
