<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Steel Hector & Davis LLP</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL><CENTER><H2>International Practice</H2><H3>Steel Hector & Davis LLP</H3></CENTER><CENTER><B>Miami:</B> 200 South Biscayne Boulevard, Miami, FL 33131<BR>Tel 305-577-7000 <B>*</B> Fax 305-577-7001 <B>*</B> E-mail: <a href="mailto:bmcallis@counsel.com">bmcallis@counsel.com</a><BR><B>Other offices:</B> West Palm Beach, Tallahassee, Key West (Florida);Caracas<BR><BR>153 lawyers <B>*</B> 35 International Group lawyers <B>*</B> 5 InternationalArbitration lawyers</CENTER><!---<P>See this firm's profile in the following other directory:<BR><UL><BR>   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/bass.html"> Workout</A></UL><P><BR>---><P><P><B>L</B>ocated at the gateway to Latin America, Steel Hector & Davis providessophisticated, cost-effective representation to clients involved both indomestic and international arbitration. Founded in 1925 by three lawyers who,collectively, served in the Florida Legislature, the United States Senate and asa president of the American Bar Association, Steel Hector & Davis is today alarge, diversified firm with a sophisticated international practice. Ourfull-service business practice ranges from finance to corporate and securitieslaw to general and commercial litigation and alternative dispute resolution.</P><P>	Our lawyers speak a variety of languages including Spanish, French, German,Italian, Japanese, Chinese and Sindhi. Several of our lawyers are admitted topractice in foreign jurisdictions, including the Dominican Republic, Nicaragua,Venezuela, and Great Britain, and are thoroughly familiar with the legal systemsof their respective countries of practice. Many of our U.S.trained foreign languagespeaking lawyers lecture and work on legal matters in their nativelanguages and are able to quickly brief business executives and general counselon the legal, business, and cultural customs of other countries.</P><P>	Steel Hector & Davis is a member of Lex Mundi, a global association of 129independent law firms. Lex Mundi's members provide each firm's clients withimmediate access to high-quality legal service throughout the United States andin 71 countries outside the U.S. Each member firm is among the largest and mostestablished in its jurisdiction and is able to provide us and our clients promptaccess to, and the most current information about, formal and informalregulatory and business practices in each jurisdiction. In addition to LexMundi, we maintain working relations with leading law firms throughout theworld.</P><H4>International Arbitration</H4><P>Steel Hector & Davis has extensive experience in the use of alternate disputeresolution methods in international transactions, having represented residentsof the United States as well as foreign clients in disputes resolved under suchdiverse regimes as the Rules of the International Chamber of Commerce, the Rulesof Procedure of the Inter-American Commercial Arbitration Commission and theInternational Rules of the American Arbitration Association. Members of thefirm, in addition to advising clients of the implications of incorporatingclauses calling for arbitration (and other ADR methods) in contracts, andrepresenting them as parties in such tribunals, have served as arbitratorsappointed by parties or by various appointing authorities.</P><P>	In addition, international arbitration matters handled by members of thefirm have involved parties domiciled in most Latin American and Caribbeancountries as well as various European venues. These matters include, inter alia,securities laws, and contract cases in such diverse fields as construction,utilities, manufacturing, aircraft leasing, vendors in a variety of fields andmaritime disputes.</P><H4>International Finance</H4>Steel Hector & Davis's international finance practice, spanning more than fourdecades, provides daily opportunities to counsel U.S. and nonU.S. clients indomestic and international financing; through public and private equity and debtofferings; in cross-border lending and leasing, trade finance, facility andproject finance; and in cross-continent single-task and coordinated creditrecovery and workouts. Representative clients include both Latin American andU.S. companies, including Fortune 100 and Fortune 500 clients, public andprivate institutions, financial institutions, franchisors, individual investorsand developers. Representative transactions include the use of import/export,receivable and equipment financing, leveraged leases, municipal debt,partnerships, joint ventures, limited liability companies, offshore corporationsand domestic and foreign trusts, documentary letters of credit, and theprotection of copyrights, trademarks and trade secrets.<BR><BR><LI><B>Jos&#233; I. Astigarraga</B>-Head of our financial services group, Mr. Astigarragafocuses his practice on international, banking and bankruptcy litigation. Heserves on the NAFTA Commission's Advisory Committee on the Resolution of PrivateCommercial Disputes and the American Arbitration Association's Panel ofArbitrators for Complex Financial Disputes. (AAA certified arbitrator)		<BR><LI><B>Barry G. Craig</B>-Head of the firm's European task force and resident in ourMiami and London offices, Mr. Craig focuses his 22-year practice on corporate,banking, and tax-exempt financing law, particularly mergers and acquisitions andequity financings.		<BR><LI><B>Sonia de Cruz</B>-A U.S. and Nicaraguan lawyer, Ms. de Cruz's practice focuseson the structure of foreign investments, domestic and international bankingregulation and lending, including ExImBank transactions, and licensing andfranchising. For ten years, Ms. de Cruz served as first deputy director for theCentral Bank in Nicaragua.		<BR><LI><B>Mike F. Egan</B>-Formerly counsel at the New York firm of Mudge Rose GuthrieAlexander & Ferdon, Mr. Egan concentrates on project development, finance andrestructuring, equipment, leveraged leases, and lending transactions.		<BR><LI><B>George R. Harper</B>-Head of the firm's aviation group, Mr. Harper handles avariety of international transactions, including operational and financeequipment leases, ExImBank and OPICguaranteed transactions, and foreign debtrenegotiations. He is a founding director of the Cuban Banking Study Group.<BR><LI><B>Bradford D. Kaufman</B>-Mr. Kaufman's practice focuses on commercial litigation,securities and employment law. He has handled a variety of fee and otherarbitration disputes and has appeared before the NYSE, NASD, CFTC, SEC and theFlorida division of securities on behalf o his clients. He is a member of theNational Association of Securities Dealers. (AAA certified arbitrator.)<BR><LI><B>Peter M. Kramer</B>-Mr. Kramer is a litigator who concentrates his practice inalternative dispute resolution, insurance regulatory issues, and commerciallitigation. He is a certified Circuit Court mediator, serves on the CaribbeanLaw Institute Arbitration Revision Committee, and is a member of the AmericanMediation Association and the Lex Mundi College of Mediators. (AAA certifiedarbitrator.)<BR><LI><B>Burton A. Landy</B>-Mr. Landy serves as co-chair of the firm's internationaldepartment. With more than four decades experience, he has been at the forefrontof South Florida's development into a leading international trade and financecenter. He has served as president of the Inter-American Bar Association,chairman of the Latin American Business Promotion Advisory Council, and aschairman of the Beacon Council. Presently, Mr. Landy is general counsel to theFlorida International Bankers Association and a member of the U.S. Secretary ofState's Advisory Council on Private International Law. (AAA certifiedarbitrator.)<BR><LI><B>Bruce A. McAllister</B>-Head of the firm's admiralty and maritime practice, Mr.McAllister's practice focuses on virtually every aspect of maritime law handlingmatters before the Federal Maritime Commission, the U.S. Maritime Administrationand other federal agencies. Bruce serves on the Boards of Directors of the MiamiInternational Arbitration and Mediation Institute and the Maritime ArbitrationBoard of Miami, Inc. (AAA certified arbitrator.)	<BR><LI><B>James M. Meyer</B>-Resident in Caracas, Venezuela, Mr. Meyer practicesinternational, aviation and general corporate law, cross-border leasing andfinancing of capital equipment and commercial and executive jet aircraft.	<BR><LI><B>James E. Morgan III</B>-Mr. Morgan's practice highlights commercial banking andfinance. He has served as lender's, agent's and borrower's counsel in numeroussyndicated transactions, including syndicates involving domestic andinternational lenders.	<BR><LI><B>Diane Noller Wells</B>-Ms. Wells' focus is in bankruptcy, workouts and banking,including international lending, equipment leases, ExImBank and OPICguaranteed transactions, and short-form asset-based lending transactions.	Thomas R. Woolsey-Head of our Project Development and Structured Financegroup, Mr. Woolsey's work emphasizes corporate and public finance, includingproject development, finance and restructuring commercial lending, equipmentleasing, industrial development revenue bond financing, and loan restructuresand workouts.	<BR><LI><B>Miguel A. Zaldivar, Jr.</B>-A U.S. and Venezuelan lawyer, Mr. Zaldivar is ofcounsel with the firm. His focus is in international and corporate matters,assisting foreign and U.S. clients in their Latin American ventures and U.S.activities.</UL></UL></BODY></HTML>
