<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Bronson,  Bronson & McKinnon
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Labor</H2>
<H3>Bronson,  Bronson & McKinnon
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>San Francisco:</B> 505 Montgomery Street,  San Francisco,  CA 94111<BR>
Tel 415-986-4200  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-982-1394  <B>*</B>  E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:moreinfo@bronson.com">moreinfo@bronson.com</A><BR>
<B>San Jose:</B> 10 Almaden Boulevard,  Suite 600,  San Jose,  CA 95113<BR>
Tel 408-293-0599  <B>*</B>  Fax 408-999-6553<BR>
<B>Los Angeles:</B> 444 South Flower Street,  24th Floor,  Los Angeles,  CA 90071<BR>
Tel 213-627-2000  <B>*</B>  Fax 213-627-2277<BR>
<BR>
142 lawyers  <B>*</B>  10 lawyers in labor and employment law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/bronson.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/bronson.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/bronson.html"> Product Liability</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>T</B>he firm represents Fortune 500,  mid-size,  and foreign companies in all aspects of doing business in the United States,  and particularly in California. Its trial attorneys represent clients in litigation matters throughout the United States. The Labor and Employment Department works with other practice groups in the firm,  with other law firms,  and with the general counsel and human resource departments of its clients,  to determine the clients' human resource goals and to assist them in attaining those goals in a manner that considers the context,  peculiarities,  and risks of doing business and litigating in California.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Work of the Labor and Employment Group</H3></CENTER>

<P>Bronson's employment attorneys represent employers in the traditional areas of federal employment practice (NLRB,  EEOC,  OSHA,  ERISA,  FLSA,  OFCCP,  and ADA),  in state law wrongful termination and civil rights litigation (which often varies from federal standards),  in state and federal wage and hour matters,  in matters involving unfair competition and the theft of trade secrets,  and in other developing areas of employer/employee relations.<BR><P>We assist employers with litigation and other problems arising under Title VII,  the Civil Rights Act of 1991,  and the Americans with Disabilities Act,  and in the emerging areas of employee privacy,  drug testing,  AIDS,  gay rights,  employee defamation,  and an increasing number of controversies over employees' unauthorized use or theft of trade secrets and proprietary information. We work with employers in developing policies,  practices,  and procedures to comply with state and federal requirements and to avoid the risks and expense of employment litigation. The partners in the Labor and Employment Department all are experienced trial attorneys,  but they also are experienced in a variety of alternative dispute resolution procedures.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Charles N. Bland,  Jr.</B> (<I>Los Angeles</I>) Mr. Bland specializes in employment litigation,  including the emerging areas of invasion of privacy,  retaliatory dismissals,  defamation,  and ERISA. He also consults with a variety of clients regarding day-to-day employment matters,  litigation prevention,  loss control,  and the formulation and implementation of general employment policies in the insurance,  service,  and manufacturing industries.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Patricia H. Cullison</B> (<I>San Francisco</I>) Ms. Cullison represents management in wrongful termination and discrimination litigation and counsels employers in various matters relating to the employment relationship. She has litigated a variety of employment issues,  including cases involving defamation,  compensation,  contract,  unfair trade practices,  and protection of trade secrets.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Edwin L. Currey,  Jr.</B> (<I>San Francisco</I>) Mr. Currey has been with the firm since 1965 and has participated in the growth of employment law from a traditional NLRB practice through Title VII individual and class actions,  California civil rights,  and wrongful termination and trade secret litigation. He counsels corporations concerning problems of senior executives,  from compensation to malfeasance. He has tried two Title VII class actions to judgment,  in addition to numerous state and federal jury and court trials involving the employment relationship in a wide variety of businesses,  including the arts.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gilmore F. Diekmann,  Jr.</B> (<I>San Francisco</I>) Department chair. Mr. Diekmann's practice focuses primarily on labor and employment litigation,  an area in which he is a frequent lecturer and panelist. In his 24 years of practice,  he has defended over 30 class actions and over 200 individual employment cases in the state and federal courts. His clients include several major airlines,  a national truck line,  local manufacturing companies,  retail sales chains,  local law firms,  and companies in the real estate and property management field. He serves as a mediator and neutral evaluator in employment cases for the U.S. District Court for the Northern District of California.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert W. Tollen</B> (<I>San Francisco</I>) Mr. Tollen began his employment practice in the U.S. Department of Labor in 1964,  where he was responsible for enforcing the Fair Labor Standards Act and other wage and hour laws. He practiced labor law in San Francisco for 17 years prior to joining Bronson in 1983. He continues to handle labor-management disputes,  as well as wage and hour,  discrimination,  wrongful termination,  and other employment-related litigation.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Lynn A. Bersch</B> (<I>San Francisco</I>) Ms. Bersch's practice encompasses all aspects of labor and employment relations with particular focus on discrimination and wrongful termination litigation. She advises employers on compliance with state and federal laws governing the employment relationship,  wage and hour issues,  employee safety issues,  labor-management relations,  and personnel policies.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
