<HEAD>
<TITLE>
>Clifton Budd  & DeMaria
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Labor</H2>
<H3>
Clifton Budd  & DeMaria
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<BR>
<B>New York:</B> 420 Lexington Avenue,  New York,  NY 10170<BR>
Tel 212-687-7410  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-687-3285<BR>
<B>Other office:</B> Fort Lee (New Jersey)<BR>
<BR>
19 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers practicing in employment law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>
<BR>

<P><BR>

<P><B>C</B>lifton Budd  & DeMaria is a nationally known employment law firm representing management. It has one of the nation's oldest employment law practices dating back to the early 1900s,  when one of its predecessor firms tried the precedent-setting <I>Danbury Hatter </I>case. In 1969,  in order to better serve its clients,  the firm decided to limit its practice to employment law,  a decision which it believes has afforded its clients both knowledgeable and experienced representation.<BR>

<P><BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Overview of the Firm's Practice
</H3></CENTER>

<P>The firm represents many of the largest companies in the United States in all areas of employment law,  ranging from traditional union matters such as collective bargaining,  representation before the National Labor Relations Board,  and union avoidance,  to the less traditional areas involving advice on employee benefits plans,  employment discrimination,  occupational health and safety,  and employment litigation. Our clients represent household names in such industries as publishing,  aircraft production,  the cosmetics and chemical industries,  and many others. In addition,  the firm advises numerous smaller employers and has a number of clients in the hotel,  printing,  and soft drink industries,  as well as many in the health care industry. The firm also represents several public employers. On various occasions during the year,  the firm offers to its clients seminars on employment law topics of current interest. The firm publishes a bimonthly newsletter,  <I>Labor  & Employment Law</I>,  which is provided to firm clients without charge and is forwarded to nonclient companies on a subscription basis. In addition,  the firm produces training manuals and pamphlets on employment topics,  such as <I>Silence is Not Golden</I>,  together with training videos. These are provided to clients where appropriate. Because of its focused practice,  the firm is able to offer broad geographic experience in employment law,  permitting it to be competitive with regional firms across the United States.<BR>
<BR><P>As a result of the many complexities created by the introduction each year of new employment litigation,  the firm assigns certain partners and associates to maintain in-depth knowledge of all new legislation and interpretive decisions.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Thomas W. Budd</B> has been a labor and employment law practitioner since the early 1960s and has had a broad range of experience,  having often served as the chief spokesman for employers in collective bargaining negotiations,  as well as having represented employers in arbitration and before the National Labor Relations Board and the courts.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Alfred T. DeMaria</B>,  although experienced in all areas of labor and employment law,  is best known for his work in union avoidance,  having written <I>The Process of De-Unionization,  How Management Wins Union Organizing Campaigns,  Maintaining Non-Union Status,  Preventing White Collar Unionization in the 1990s</I>,  and other books and pamphlets,  as well as having produced videos in the field.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Carlyle M. Dunaway,  Jr., </B> and <B>Kevin J. McGill</B> are labor and employment lawyers with broad experience representing employers in job discrimination,  employment contract,  and wrongful discharge cases before state and federal administrative agencies and trial and appellate courts. Mr. McGill also litigates free speech issues. <B>David I. Rosen</B> and <B>Brian J. Clark</B> are partners with extensive employment litigation experience at both the state and federal level.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Eric S. Lamm</B> is a labor and employment lawyer with experience in both the private and public sectors. <B>Howard G. Estock</B> is a labor and employment lawyer with particular experience in the health care industry.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert A. Wiesen</B> and <B>G. Peter Clark</B> both have National Labor Relations Board experience. Before coming to the firm,  Mr. Wiesen was an attorney with Board Region 22,  where he twice won general counsel awards for superior performance. Mr. Clark was with the Board from 1973 to 1985 and,  before coming to the firm in 1985,  had achieved the position of supervising attorney for Region 22.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard K. Muser</B>,  in addition to general labor and employment law experience,  represents many of the firm's clients with employee benefit problems,  having litigated a number of cases in that area.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Leon Rosen</B> is a past president of The American Immigration Lawyers Association and special counsel to the firm. He represents many of our clients in employment-related immigration matters.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
