<HEAD>
<TITLE>Collier,  Jacob  & Mills
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Labor</H2>
<H3>Collier,  Jacob  & Mills
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Somerset:</B> Corporate Park III,  580 Howard Avenue,  Somerset,  NJ 08873<BR>
Tel 908-560-7100  <B>*</B>  Fax 908-560-0788<BR>
<BR>
12 lawyers  <B>*</B>  9 lawyers practicing in labor and employment law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>C</B>ollier,  Jacob  & Mills assists a wide spectrum of clients ranging from Fortune 100 corporations to family-run businesses by limiting its practice to the areas of labor and employment law and general commercial,  environmental,  and products liability litigation. Our labor and employment clients include publicly and privately held companies in a variety of industries including telecommunications,  pharmaceuticals,  banking institutions,  and educational institutions. Our lawyers have extensive experience representing clients in both state and federal courts and before both state and federal administrative agencies. The firm's location in central New Jersey gives it ideal access to all major corporate centers in the New York metropolitan area.
<P><BR><P>Collier,  Jacob  & Mills has a broad employment law practice,  exclusively representing private and public sector management. We litigate employer-employee and employer-union disputes,  at all levels,  in both state and federal courts,  including those involving the National Labor Relations Act,  Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964,  the Americans with Disabilities Act,  ADEA (the Age Discrimination in Employment Act),  the Fair Labor Standards Act,  ERISA (the Employee Retirement Income Security Act),  the Rehabilitation Act of 1973,  Executive Order 11246,  the New Jersey Law Against Discrimination,  and all associated regulations. We practice before state agencies such as the New Jersey Division on Civil Rights,  the New York Human Rights Commission,  and the Pennsylvania Human Relations Commission,  as well as federal agencies such as the National Labor Relations Board and the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.<BR><P>Collier,  Jacob  & Mills also advises private and public sector employers on compliance obligations and strategies with respect to federal and state laws and regulations. We counsel companies on the drafting and revising of personnel handbooks,  employee manuals,  and policies regarding drug and aLCohol programs; sexual harassment programs; and compliance with both state and federal laws regarding family and medical leaves.<BR>
<BR><P>The firm's attorneys regularly attend continuing legal education seminars in this practice area,  frequently participating as lecturers or panelists,  and work actively in substantive section and committee matters with the American and New Jersey bar associations. Our attorneys are admitted to practice in a number of jurisdictions.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Cynthia M. Jacob</B> has extensively litigated in the federal,  state,  and appellate courts. She concentrates on litigating employment-related cases,  including wrongful termination; employee benefits disputes; and race,  sex,  and age discrimination and sexual harassment. She is president-elect of the New Jersey State Bar Association. She serves on the U.S. District Court Lawyers' Advisory Committee and on several New Jersey Supreme Court committees,  including the Civil Charge Committee,  where she chairs the subcommittee that recently drafted the New Jersey jury charges on employment law. Vassar College,  A.B.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1963; Phi Beta Kappa; Yale University,  LL.B.,  1966.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Christopher H. Mills</B> joined the firm after a 12-year career as in-house labor counsel to a Fortune 100 corporation. He has extensive experience in traditional labor relations law,  employment discrimination,  workforce reduction,  and wrongful termination counseling and litigation. He has reviewed and drafted employers' personnel manuals and handbooks and has served as chief negotiator for both private and public sector employers. Currently he is the New Jersey chair of the New Jersey/Philadelphia Area EEOC Liaison Committee for the ABA's Com-mittee on Equal Employment Opportunity Law. Washington and Lee University,  B.A.,  B.S.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1969; Phi Beta Kappa; Yale University,  J.D.,  1972; Georgetown University,  LL.M.,  1975.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Rosemary S. Gousman</B> has represented employers before state and federal agencies and in state and federal court litigation on such matters as civil rights,  wrongful discharge,  wage and hour laws,  traditional labor law involving union-management relations,  and employee benefits matters. She has also counseled employers on labor and employment matters including drafting and revising personnel manuals and employee handbooks. St. Peter's College,  A.B.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1977; Rutgers University,  J.D.,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Alan G. Lesnewich</B> participates in both the firm's labor and employment and general litigation practices. He has represented employers in both state and federal court litigation,  and before state and federal agencies on matters involving allegations of unlawful discrimination,  wrongful discharge,  and employee benefits disputes. He served a clerkship with Justice Gary S. Stein of the New Jersey Supreme Court. He serves on the New Jersey Supreme Court Committee on Civil Practice. Colgate University,  B.A,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1975; Phi Beta Kappa; Seton Hall University,  J.D.,  1985.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Patricia S. Robinson</B> has represented employers before both state and federal agencies and in state and federal court litigation on matters involving civil rights,  wrongful discharge,  and claims of sexual harassment,  in addition to claims of discrimination based on race,  sex,  age,  handicap,  and national origin and employee benefit disputes. She is also active in the firm's personnel law counseling practice. Montclair State College,  B.A.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1975; Rutgers University,  M.Sc.,  chemistry,  1980,  J.D.,  1986.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
