<TITLE>Hall  & Evans,  L.L.C.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Labor</H2>
<H3>Hall  & Evans,  L.L.C.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Denver:</B> Suite 1700,  1200 Seventeenth Street,  Denver,  CO 80202-5800<BR>
Tel 303-628-3300  <B>*</B>  Fax 303-628-3368<BR>
<B>Colorado Springs:</B> Suite 600,  102 South Tejon,  Colorado Springs,  CO 80904-2264<BR>
Tel 719-578-5600  <B>*</B>  Fax 719-635-7458<BR>
<BR>
77 lawyers  <B>*</B>  11 lawyers in employment law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/hall.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/hall.html"> ERISA</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/hall.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>H</B>all  & Evans,  founded in 1932,  provides representation on the local through international levels in litigation,  commercial transactions,  and regulatory and legislative affairs. The firm's Employment Practice Group provides our clients with a full range of employment law services,  emphasizing strategies to minimize claims and maximize the ability to defend those claims aggressively and successfully when they occur.
<P><BR><P>Our practice is employer-oriented and involves all facets of the employment relationship in judicial,  administrative,  and governmental agency claims. We emphasize the risk management approach to employer-employee relations,  and our lawyers review and audit clients' employee manuals,  train and provide continuing education for supervisory personnel,  and communicate with management to insure that favorable litigation outcomes are maximized when claims arise. We stress effective communication between our lawyers and clients in order to create a `team approach' on decision-making and budget issues.<BR><P>Our lawyers have litigated some of the most significant cases decided in this region regarding the employment-at-will doctrine. Our private sector clients include Continental Airlines,  Inc.,  Diamond Shamrock Refining and Marketing Company,  EG &G Rocky Flats,  Inc.,  The Farmers Insurance Group of Companies,  Gates Rubber Company,  Jacor Broadcasting of Colorado,  Inc. (including Newsradio 85 KOA,  KTLK,  KBPI-FM,  and KRFX-FM),  Kaiser Hill Company,  L.L.C.,  Kmart Corporation,  Monfort,  Inc.,  Northern Automotive Corp.,  Pizza Hut,  Inc.,  Waste Management of North America,  and Western Geophysical Company of America. Our attorneys also represent public officials and entities such as the State of Colorado and the state's cities,  counties,  and school districts.<BR>
<BR><P>Abbreviated information on the practices of our employment group members follows. All members speak frequently before both public and private employers concerning recent trends in the law,  and their recent engagements include in-house seminars and programs for our private sector clients as well as appearances before public entity conferences such as the Annual Judicial Conference of the State of Colorado,  the New Commissioner and Elected Official Orientation for County Officials in Colorado,  the Colorado County Attorneys Association conferences,  the County Sheriffs of Colorado Conference,  and meetings of the International Association of Defense Counsel,  the American Law Firm Association,  and the National Association of Legal Assistants.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Daniel R. Satriana,  Jr.</B> (<I>303-628-3351</I>) co-chairs our Employment Practice Group. He has practiced law for 16 years and has extensive trial experience representing private and public employers in federal and state courts as well as before administrative agencies. Mr. Satriana also co-chairs the Employment Practice Group of the American Law Firm Association; his most recent publication,  the <I>50-State Compendium of Significant Cases and Statutory Laws Related to Employment Claims</I>,  was presented at the 1995 ALFA National Client Seminar.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Cathy Havener Greer</B> (<I>303-628-3412</I>) also co-chairs the group and has practiced law since 1981. Her practice emphasizes civil rights and employment,  where she provides claims defense and consultation from a risk management perspective. She focuses on defending claims against the state,  local governments,  and public officials and also frequently serves as a consultant to elected and appointed officials as well as to private employers.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David R. Brougham</B> (<I>303-628-3327</I>) was admitted to the bar in 1969. He has represented the state of Colorado in litigation involving monetary damages against it since the 1972 enactment of the Colorado Governmental Immunity Act; his clients also include counties,  cities,  and public officials.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John E. Bolmer II</B> (<I>303-628-3366</I>) has practiced law since 1983 and represents clients in a variety of wrongful discharge matters,  including non-competition and ADA issues. He frequently conducts seminars and training sessions which address employment law changes and trends as well as compliance methods.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Thomas J. Lyons</B> (<I>303-628-3355</I>) has practiced law for 18 years; his trial practice emphasizes defense of federal civil rights and discrimination matters,  employment disputes,  and claims brought against public entities. Drawing on his extensive experience in administrative law,  Mr. Lyons handles claims before governmental agencies on behalf of regulated and licensed businesses and professionals. Additionally,  his background in legislative drafting and analysis at the state and federal levels allows him to offer assistance to groups and businesses faced with proposed statutory changes and regulations.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Sean R. Gallagher</B> (<I>303-628-3406</I>) has a practice emphasizing employment and civil rights issues. He has practiced law since 1987 and litigates claims concerning sex,  race,  and national origin discrimination,  wrongful termination,  breach of express or implied contracts,  violation of covenants not to compete,  ERISA,  and constitutional tort claims.<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
