<HEAD>
<TITLE>Kauff,  McClain  & McGuire
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Labor</H2>
<H3>Kauff,  McClain  & McGuire
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>New York:</B> 950 Third Avenue,  New York,  NY 10022<BR>
Tel 212-644-1010  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-644-1936<BR>
<B>San Francisco:</B> 88 Kearny Street,  San Francisco,  CA 94108<BR>
Tel 415-421-3111  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-421-0938<BR>
<BR>
19 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers practice in labor and employment law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>K</B>auff,  McClain  & McGuire represents management clients throughout the country in matters such as collective bargaining and arbitrations; National Labor Relations Board proceedings; injunction proceedings in federal and state courts; and trial and appellate litigation relating to traditional labor matters,  discrimination claims,  and wrongful discharge claims. The firm is committed to the concept of preventive law,  advising clients on such matters as affirmative action,  compliance with federal and state discrimination laws,  union organization,  employee benefits,  occupational health and safety,  and the labor and employment law implications of business reorganization,  development,  and retrenchment. The firm's clients range in size from large public companies to family-owned businesses,  and include several multiemployer associations and nonprofit and public sector employers. The industries in which our clients operate include entertainment and the arts; manufacturing,  retailing,  and service operations; maritime services; construction,  real estate,  and building services; consumer products; wineries and distilleries; and businesses based on computer technology.<BR><BR<UL>
<LI><B>Jerome B. Kauff</B>,  who founded the firm in 1972,  has practiced labor and employment law for over 30 years. He has served as chairman of the Labor Law Committee of the Association of the Bar of the City of New York,  as well as of committees of the Labor and Employment Law Section of the New York State Bar Association,  and has also served as co-editor of numerous Practising Law Institute programs on subjects such as unjust dismissal,  workplace employment problems,  age discrimination,  and advanced employment law strategies. Mr. Kauff has had extensive experience as a representative of employers in collective bargaining,  and advises clients in all areas of labor and employment law.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Maureen E. McClain</B> is the senior partner in the firm's San Francisco office. Ms. McClain is highly experienced in all areas of labor and employment law and has tried numerous cases to verdict in both state and federal courts. Ms. McClain has written and lectured on a variety of subjects including wrongful discharge,  employment discrimination,  and labor litigation,  and she has served as co-editor of Practising Law Institute programs on unjust dismissal and at-will employment,  and as contributing editor to publications of the University of California Regents and continuing education programs of the California bar.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Raymond G. McGuire</B> is primarily responsible for counseling and litigation in the employment discrimination area,  and he also supervises the firm's work for clients in the construction,  maritime,  and telecommunications industries. He has extensive experience in collective bargaining and in trial and appellate litigation before state and federal courts and the National Labor Relations Board. Mr. McGuire previously served as chairman of the Maine Labor Relations Board and as professor of law at the University of Maine and Florida State University.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Alexander P. Rosenberg</B> advises clients on questions relating to the National Labor Relations Act,  ERISA,  OSHA,  and wage and hour laws,  and has particular expertise as to issues arising under collective bargaining agreements in the entertainment industry. He is also highly experienced in injunction litigation before both state and federal courts and,  before joining the firm,  served as an attorney with the National Labor Relations Board.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kenneth A. Margolis</B> has had broad experience representing management in all areas of labor and employment law and litigation,  with an emphasis in the entertainment,  maritime,  and building service industries. He has lectured before the New York State Bar Association and industry groups,  and has been a contributing author to Practising Law Institute programs in the employment law area.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>G. Daniel Newland</B>,  a partner in the San Francisco office,  represents clients in the entertainment,  construction,  and health care fields,  and has particular expertise in the labor and employment problems of law firms and private clubs and associations. Before joining the firm,  he served as labor and litigation counsel for major corporations in the pharmaceutical and petroleum industries.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Charlotte Addington</B>,  a partner in the San Francisco office,  specializes in the representation of management in all aspects of employment law and litigation,  with an emphasis in employment issues relating to educational institutions.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Dennis A. Lalli</B> is highly experienced in employment litigation. He has lectured on numerous employment law topics,  and has served as an adjunct professor at New York University.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jeffrey D. Polsky</B>,  a partner in the San Francisco office,  represents clients in wrongful discharge,  employment discrimination,  and complex litigation matters,  with a particular expertise in the health care industry.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Harlan J. Silverstein</B> has extensive experience in employment discrimination and labor litigation and collective bargaining,  and has served as co-author of Practising Law Institute programs on the law of unjust dismissal.<BR>
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
