<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Kramer,  Levin,  Naftalis  & Frankel</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL><CENTER><H2>Labor</H2><H3>Kramer,  Levin,  Naftalis   & Frankel</H3></CENTER><CENTER><B>New York:</B> 919 Third Avenue,  New York,  NY 10022<BR>Tel 212-715-9100  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-715-8000  <B>*</B> Home page: <A HREF="http://www.kramer-levin.com/">www.kramer-levin.com</A><BR><BR>150 lawyers  <B>*</B>  7 lawyers in employment and labor practice<BR></CENTER><P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR><UL><BR>   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/kramer.html"> Antitrust</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/kramer.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/kramer.html"> Corporate Securities</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/kramer.html"> ERISA</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/kramer.html"> Intellectual Property</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/kramer.html"> Product Liability</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/kramer.html"> White Collar Crime</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/kramer.html"> Workout</A></UL><P><P><P><B>K</B>ramer Levin's employment and labor practice has grown considerably in the past several years,  largely as a result of our success in providing the highest-quality representation while significantly reducing litigation costs for our clients.<P><BR><P>Our attorneys have extensive experience in personnel-related matters,  including employment discrimination (age,  sex,  race,  national origin,  and disability),  wrongful termination,  breach of contract,  and defamation actions. The firm also does significant work on traditional labor matters such as union organizing campaigns,  proceedings before the National Labor Relations Board,  and arbitrations.<BR><P>To help clients avoid expensive,  time-consuming,  and potentially damaging litigation,  we focus our practice on counseling employers in developing and implementing employee relations policies that minimize the litigation risks of employment decisions. We actively engage in alternative dispute resolution (i.e.,  arbitration,  mediation,  etc.) to reduce our clients' litigation costs.<BR><BR><P>In addition to counseling employers,  we handle the full range of litigations,  from commencement through appeal,  before federal and state courts,  administrative agencies,  and arbitrators. We also are in the forefront of the rapidly expanding area of the enforcement of restrictive covenants,  handling numerous litigations to enforce and defeat noncompetition and confidentiality agreements.<BR><BR><P>We have special expertise in litigation involving employee benefits and pensions under MPPAA,  ERISA,  and other pension laws,  often working closely with Kramer Levin's top-flight employee benefits group on these and other matters,  including mergers and acquisitions and executive employment agreement and severance issues.<BR><BR><P>Our employment law group represents companies engaged in diverse areas of business. Representative clients include Chubb  & Son,  Inc.,  Liz Claiborne Inc.,  Nationwide Cellular Service,  New York Law School,  Pace University,  Paramount Communications,  Related Management Corporation,  The Travelers Inc.,  Tuscan Dairy Farms,  and Zale Corporation.<BR><BR><P>We have considerable expertise in the financial services industry,  representing clients such as Lehman Brothers,  Smith Barney Shearson,  Burnham Securities,  Emigrant Savings Bank,  Atlantic Bank of New York,  and UMB Bank and Trust Co. Lehman Brothers and Smith Barney Shearson (and their predecessor Shearson Lehman Brothers),  for example,  have retained us in more than 200 employment-related actions,  ranging from multimillion-dollar class actions to agency proceedings involving individual claimants.<BR><BR><P>These representations give us significant comprehension of the intricacies of the financial services industry and allow us to effectively and efficiently serve our clients. Our attorneys have handled dozens of personnel-related arbitrations for clients before the New York Stock Exchange,  National Association of Securities Dealers,  and American Stock Exchange.<BR><UL><BR><BR><LI><B>Kevin B. Leblang</B> heads our employment law practice group and concentrates exclusively on employment,  employee benefits,  and labor law. He counsels employers on matters ranging from the adoption and application of employee relations policies to the evaluation and minimization of litigation risks of employment decisions. Mr. Leblang also represents management clients in litigations before federal and state courts,  administrative agencies,  and arbitrators. He has extensive experience advising and litigating in the rapidly growing field of employee noncompetition law. Member,  labor and employment law sections,  Association of the Bar of the City of New York,  and the New York State and American Bar Associations. Cornell University,  B.S.,  industrial and labor relations,  1981; Fordham Law School,  J.D.,  1984.<BR><BR><LI><B>Marvin E. Frankel</B> heads our litigation practice and chairs the firm's management committee. Mr. Frankel has argued more than 20 cases before the U.S. Supreme Court,  including the landmark labor case <I>NLRB </I>v.<I> Yeshiva University</I>. He served as a U.S. District Judge for the Southern District of New York from 1965 to 1978. During that time,  he presided over a number of employment discrimination cases involving race,  age,  sex and other alleged grounds of discrimination. Since his return to private practice,  Mr. Frankel has successfully defended,  or participated in the defense of,  a wide variety of clients against charges of discrimination on grounds of sex,  race,  or age. Assistant to U.S. Solicitor General,  1952-1956. Professor of law,  Columbia University,  1962-1965. Chair,  Lawyers Committee for Human Rights,  1980- . Queens College,  A.B.,  1943; Columbia University,  LL.B.,  1948; editor-in-chief,  <I>Columbia Law Review</I>.<BR><BR><LI><B>Michael J. Dell</B>,  a litigation partner,  has special expertise in dispute resolution involving employee benefits and pensions under MPPAA,  ERISA,  and other pension laws. He is general litigation counsel to large and small corporations,  ESOPs,  and multiemployer pension funds. Mr. Dell also counsels corporate clients,  in conjunction with the firm's Employee Benefits group,  on employee benefit-related issues arising from partial or complete terminations of pension plans and ESOPs,  changes in benefits,  and employment decisions. Law clerk,  Judge Stanley A. Weigel,  U.S. District Court for the Northern District of California,  1978-1979. Oxford University (Wadham College),  B.A.,  with honors,  1975; Harvard University,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1978; associate editorial director,  <I>Harvard Law Review</I>.<BR><BR></UL></UL></BODY></HTML>
