<HEAD>
<TITLE>Manatt,  Phelps  & Phillips
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Labor</H2>
<H3>Manatt,  Phelps  & Phillips
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Los Angeles:</B> 11355 West Olympic Boulevard,  Los Angeles,  CA 90064<BR>
Tel 310-312-4000  <B>*</B>  Fax 310-312-4224<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Washington,  D.C.,  Nashville<BR>
<BR>
166 lawyers  <B>*</B>  15 lawyers in Labor  & Employment Law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>M</B>anatt,  Phelps  & Phillips is a multidisciplinary firm providing the full range of legal services to clients throughout the country and internationally.
<P><BR><P>The Labor and Employment Law Department of Manatt,  Phelps  & Phillips represents employers in a full range of labor and employment law matters. The Department serves clients in numerous industries,  including financial services,  retail,  pharmaceutical,  insurance,  health care,  aerospace,  communications,  entertainment,  transportation,  professional sports,  and public entities. The Department's practice includes the representation of employers in all aspects of employment-related issues,  from traditional labor relations to complicated class action litigation instituted by the EEOC,  the U.S. Department of Justice,  and private litigants. Each of the attorneys is a litigator who specializes in specific employment issues. Collectively,  they handle the full scope of labor and employment issues arising under federal,  state,  and local law before federal and state courts and administrative agencies,  including those pertaining to wrongful discharge,  employment discrimination,  sexual harassment,  employment-related torts,  employment contracts,  OSHA,  OFCCP,  wage and hour,  unfair competition and trade secret,  unfair labor practices,  and ERISA litigation.<BR><P>In addition,  the Labor and Employment Law Department regularly provides counseling and guidance on OFCCP compliance reviews,  employee terminations and discipline,  staff reductions,  and plant closings,  as well as issues pertaining to equal employment opportunity,  family leave,  employee theft,  employee privacy,  violence in the workplace,  executive compensation,  ADA,  mergers,  acquisitions,  reorganizations,  unfair competition,  and trade secrets. Our attorneys draft personnel policies and procedures,  employee handbooks and manuals,  and affirmative action plans; conduct internal investigations and training programs; and counsel clients regarding the full panoply of labor and employment problems facing management,  including the full spectrum of issues involving unions and the collective bargaining process.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>James P. Mulkeen</B> is the chairman of the National Labor and Employment Law Department. Mr. Mulkeen has practiced equal opportunity and labor law for 25 years. He served as a trial attorney for the U.S. Department of Justice,  Civil Rights Division. He specializes in jury trials,  union organizing and collective bargaining issues,  lending discrimination litigation,  and Community Reinvestment Act protests. He is a frequent speaker on the subject of employment law,  lending discrimination,  and trial advocacy,  and is president of the City of Los Angeles Board of Civil Service Commissioners.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Alan M. Brunswick</B> has practiced in all areas of labor relations and employment law for 24 years. He has extensive experience in contract interpretation,  wrongful termination,  and wage and hour disputes in arbitration and mediation proceedings,  in state and federal courts,  and before various administrative agencies for a wide range of clients,  with emphasis in the entertainment and garment industries.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Catherine A. Conway</B> has been practicing law for 17 years. She is an experienced trial attorney in all phases of employment law,  practicing before the EEOC,  the California DFEH,  and federal and state courts. Ms. Conway served as a felony supervisory prosecuting attorney in Indianapolis for four years,  and in 1991 as deputy general counsel to the Christopher Commission in Los Angeles.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Donna F. Goldstein</B> has practiced equal opportunity and labor and employment law for 23 years. She served as a trial attorney for the U.S. Department of Justice,  Civil Rights Division,  and as an assistant U.S. attorney. Ms. Goldstein has extensive litigation experience in employment discrimination,  ERISA lawsuits,  including the defense of class actions,  suits by governmental entities,  and sexual harassment claims.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Sandra R. King</B> has specialized in labor and employment law for more than 15 years. She represents a variety of industries before state and federal courts and administrative agencies. Ms. King counsels clients on wrongful discharge and related tort claims,  the ADA,  the Family and Medical Leave Act,  wage and hour issues,  WARN,  privacy,  and OSHA.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John LeCrone</B> has been a trial attorney for 11 years,  specializing in labor law and employment litigation,  with extensive experience defending management in wrongful discharge,  discrimination,  and other employment-related issues.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert A. Pallemon</B> has been been a trial attorney for 18 years,  serving successively as assistant division chief in the Criminal and Civil Divisions of the U.S. Attorney's Office in Los Angeles between 1977-1990,  trying in excess of 45 cases. He has extensive experience in the defense of employment and wrongful termination cases.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert H. Platt</B> has been practicing in all areas of labor and employment-related law for 14 years. He has particular expertise in trade secret and unfair competition litigation and employment discrimination litigation,  and also counsels clients with respect to relationships with unions. Mr. Platt serves as general counsel for the Los Angeles Clippers.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
