<TITLE>Matkov,  Salzman,  Madoff & Gunn
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Labor</H2>
<H3>Matkov,  Salzman,  Madoff & Gunn
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Chicago:</B> 55 East Monroe Street,  Suite 2900,  Chicago,  IL 60603<BR>
Tel 312-332-0777  <B>*</B>  Fax 312-332-6130<BR>
<BR>
26 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers in labor and employment law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>M</B>atkov,  Salzman,  Madoff  & Gunn represents management exclusively in all types of employment and labor relations matters in the private and public sectors,  including manufacturing,  transportation,  hospitality,  food service,  health care,  retailing,  banking,  insurance,  publishing,  and electronic media. Our practice is hands-on and pragmatic,  with emphasis on problem-solving and preventive consulting.<BR><BR><UL><LI><B>George J. Matkov,  Jr.</B> Mr. Matkov heads up the Firm's labor negotiation and arbitration practice. He consults and has written extensively on sophisticated compensation systems and employee productivity and participation issues. Knox College; University of Iowa Law School,  LL.B.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1966; Order of the Coif. Admitted in Iowa and Illinois,  1966.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>James J. Salzman</B> Mr. Salzman represents clients in negotiations,  arbitrations,  NLRB proceedings,  and preventive maintenance of nonunion status. He consults on OSHA and employee toxic exposure issues,  absenteeism control,  and affirmative action programs. Georgetown University,  B.A.,  1965; University of Chicago,  M.B.A.,  1967; DePaul University,  J.D.,  1973. Admitted in Illinois,  1973.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jeffrey L. Madoff</B> Mr. Madoff represents clients in negotiations,  arbitrations,  NLRB matters,  and employment discrimination litigation. He consults on substance abuse programs,  employee handbooks,  WARN Act issues,  and Canadian employment matters. Wayne State University,  B.A.,  1967; University of Chicago Law School,  J.D.,  1974. Admitted in Illinois,  1974.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Allan Gunn</B> Mr. Gunn heads the Firm's practice in the area of employee benefits,  pension,  related corporate and tax law issues,  and retiree insurance benefit litigation. Carleton College,  B.A.,  1958; New York University Law School,  J.D.,  1961; University of Chicago,  M.B.A.,  1973. Admitted in Illinois,  1961.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Larry G. Hall</B> Mr. Hall represents clients in preventive maintenance of nonunion status,  negotiations,  arbitrations,  and all NLRB matters. Mr. Hall also counsels on successorship transactions,  construction law,  leased employee issues,  plant closing laws,  employee handbook matters,  and retiree insurance benefit litigation. Ferris State College,  B.A.,  1975; University of Michigan Law School,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1979. Admitted in Illinois,  1979.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kenneth T. Lopatka</B> Mr. Lopatka heads up the Firm's employment discrimination litigation practice,  including all discrimination matters,  class actions,  and employment defamation and wrongful discharge cases. He has been an adjunct professor of law at Northwestern University School of Law since 1983. Illinois Benedictine College,  B.A.,  1968; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1971; editor,  law review. Admitted in Illinois,  1971; and Massachusetts,  1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael W. Duffee</B> Mr. Duffee heads the Firm's construction industry and public sector employment law practice. He has lectured widely on labor law matters to university,  business,  and professional groups. DePaul University,  B.A.,  1974; Northwestern University School of Law,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1977; Order of the Coif. Admitted in Illinois,  1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jay G. Swardenski</B> Mr. Swardenski has over 25 years of experience in employment litigation,  collective bargaining,  and strategy development,  including bankruptcy-related proceedings and retiree health insurance matters. University of Wisconsin,  B.A.,  1961; Harvard Law School,  LL.B.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1964. Admitted in Illinois,  1964; and New York,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John N. Raudabaugh</B> Mr. Raudabaugh was a member of the NLRB from August 1990 through November 1993,  where he addressed employee participation programs in several important decisions. University of Pennsylvania,  Wharton School,  B.S.,  1968; New York State School of Industrial and Labor Relations,  M.S.,  1974; University of Virginia Law School,  J.D.,  1977. Admitted in Georgia,  1977; and District of Columbia,  1993.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Julia A. Martin</B> Ms. Martin represents clients in employment-related litigation,  including individual and class action discrimination,  wrongful discharge,  and contract suits. University of Illinois,  B.S.,  1979; Northwestern University School of Law,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1982. Admitted in Illinois,  1982.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Frank J. Saibert</B> Mr. Saibert heads the Firm's health care employment law practice,  with extensive experience in litigating wrongful discharge and discrimination matters,  negotiating labor contracts,  and advising corporate clients with respect to maintaining union-free environments. University of Illinois,  B.A.,  1980; University of Michigan Law School,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1983. Admitted in Illinois,  1983.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Steven L. Brenneman</B> Mr. Brenneman handles a wide range of employment and labor law litigation,  including discrimination matters and contract/wrongful discharge actions. Goshen College,  B.A.,  1982; University of Michigan Law School,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1985. Admitted in Illinois,  1985.
</UL>


