<HEAD>
<TITLE><*t(16.9106, 0, "1  ", 163, 2, "1  ", 166.6907, 0, "1  "):
>Mayer,  Brown  & Platt
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Labor</H2>
<H3>
Mayer,  Brown  & Platt
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<BR>
<B>Chicago: </B>190 South LaSalle Street,  Chicago,  IL 60603<BR>
Tel 312-782-0600  <B>*</B>  Fax 312-701-7711<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Brussels,  Houston,  London,  Los Angeles,  New York, <BR>
Tokyo,  Washington,  D.C.<BR>
<BR>
650 lawyers  <B>*</B>  20 lawyers in labor practice group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/mayer.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/mayer.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/mayer.html"> Product Liability</A>
   <LI><A HREF="..//mayer.html"> White Collar Crim</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>
<BR>

<P><BR>

<P><B>M</B>ayer,  Brown  & Platt is one of the oldest and largest law firms in the United States. MB &P has a broad-based commercial practice including trial and appellate litigation.<BR>

<P><BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>The Labor Practice Group
</H3></CENTER>

<P>The labor practice group is led by eight partners with extensive experience in all aspects of labor and employment law including union matters,  employment discrimination,  health and safety issues,  state law claims,  corporate reorganizations and related litigation,  and ERISA litigation.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Experience and Clients
</H3></CENTER>

<P>Mayer,  Brown  & Platt has an extensive regional and national practice representing employers in a wide range of labor and employment-related matters. In the discrimination and employment areas,  MB &P represents employers in proceedings arising out of alleged violations of federal and state antidiscrimination laws,  OSHA,  and wage and hour laws,  as well as in proceedings based on state law such as breach of contract,  wrongful discharge,  and defamation. We frequently practice before the EEOC,  the U.S. Department of Labor,  the Office of Federal Contract Compliance Programs,  and analogous state agencies,  as well as federal and state trial and appellate courts. A number of attorneys have appeared before the U.S. Supreme Court.<BR>
<BR><P>With respect to union issues,  we assist employers during union organizing campaigns; negotiate and draft collective bargaining agreements; counsel clients on contract administration,  grievances,  and strikes; and present client cases for arbitration. We regularly represent clients before the National Labor Relations Board. A number of attorneys have expertise regarding the Railway Labor Act.<BR>
<BR><P>We represent several major corporations in massive ERISA cases in the federal trial and appellate courts.<BR>
<BR><P>We also counsel clients on the many labor and personnel issues which arise in the context of corporate reorganizations and restructurings,  and regularly assist clients with the ever-increasing burden of complying with government regulation such as WARN and FMLA.<BR>
<BR><P>MB &P's labor clients include both manufacturing concerns and service organizations. A number of our valued clients include Abbott Laboratories,  American Brands,  American Farm Bureau Federation,  American Hospital Association,  American Institute of Certified Public Accountants,  American Red Cross,  Ameritech,  Amoco,  the Archdiocese of Chicago,  Bank of America,  Brunswick Corp.,  Chevron Corporation,  The Chicago Mercantile Exchange,  The Chicago Symphony Orchestra,  Clark Refining  & Marketing,  Inc.,  Coca-Cola Bottling Company of Chicago,  CPC International,  Ernst  & Young,  Ford Motor Company,  General Foods,  General Motors Corp.,  Goodyear Tire  & Rubber Co.,  Illinois Power,  Kemper Financial Services,  Inc.,  Leo Burnett Company,  Marsh  & McLennan,  McCrory Corporation,  Mobil Oil,  Nabisco Brands,  NaLCo,  Stepan Company,  Pittway,  and United Airlines.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Partners
</H3></CENTER>

<BR><UL><LI><B>Robert P. Davis</B> Bob,  who is resident in MB &P's Washington office,  served by appointment of President Bush as Solicitor of the U.S. Department of Labor from 1989 to 1991. In addition to his prior private practice in Washington,  D.C.,  Bob served as chief of staff to the Secretary of Transportation,  1983-1985; special assistant to the Deputy Attorney General of the United States,  1978-1980; and as a senior staff member in the Office of the Attorney General,  1974-1980. He served from 1989 to 1991 as chairman of the Tripartite Advisory Panel on International Labor Standards. Bob also has testified before committees of the U.S. Senate and House of Representatives on numerous labor and employment-related matters. Brown University,  A.B.,  1971; Boston University,  M.A.,  1972; Syracuse University,  M.P.A.,  1973; Georgetown University Law Center,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>, <I> </I>1980; board of editors,  <I>Georgetown Law Journal</I>. Admitted in the District of Columbia,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James W. Gladden,  Jr.</B> Jim has extensive experience in trying discrimination and employee rights cases in federal and state courts,  including class action litigation. Jim also has extensive experience in contract negotiation,  arbitration,  and union organizing campaigns. He has argued appeals before the U.S. Supreme Court and various state and federal courts of appeal. DePauw University,  B.A.,  1961; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1964. Admitted in Illinois,  1964.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Marcia E. Goodman</B> Marcia has a broad labor and employment practice including employment discrimination and other employment-related litigation,  collective bargaining,  and ERISA litigation. Marcia has lectured extensively in Japanese to Japanese companies in the U.S. and Japan on topics of labor and employment law and human resources. Marcia studied at the Tokyo University Faculty of Law in 1981 and was an adjunct professor at Georgetown University Law Center in 1982-1983. University of Michigan,  A.B.,  1974; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1980. Admitted in the District of Columbia,  1980; and Illinois,  1985.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James D. Holzhauer</B> Prior to joining MB &P,  Jim clerked for the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit and for Chief Justice Warren Burger of the U.S. Supreme Court. He has extensive experience in contract negotiations in both the private and public sectors,  arbitration,  trial and appellate litigation (including ERISA litigation),  and has argued before the U.S. Supreme Court and numerous federal courts of appeal. Jim is a former law professor at The University of Chicago Law School. New York University,  B.A.,  1970; University of Michigan Law School,  J.D.,  1980; notes editor,  law review. Admitted in Illinois,  1990; Washington,  1980; and the District of Columbia,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Danuta Bembenista Panich</B> Donna's practice emphasizes all forms of employment litigation in state and federal courts as well as before administrative agencies. She also handles arbitration,  collective bargaining and other union matters,  occupational safety and health issues,  and affirmative action compliance. Indiana University,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1975; Indiana University School of Law,  J.D.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1978; Order of the Coif. Admitted in Illinois,  1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David B. Ritter</B> David's practice includes the full range of labor issues. He frequently represents management in discrimination and other employment-related litigation in federal and state courts and before the EEOC and state administrative agencies. He has also represented management in labor contract negotiations,  arbitrations,  strike monitoring,  union organizing campaigns,  and NLRB proceedings. Cornell University,  B.S.,  1980; Case Western Reserve School of Law,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1985; law review. Admitted in Illinois,  1985.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael F. Rosenblum</B> Mike's practice includes employment discrimination and wrongful discharge suits as well as broad experience in representing clients before administrative agencies such as the NLRB,  EEOC,  OFCCP,  U.S. Department of Labor,  and state and local agencies. Prior to joining MB &P,  Mike worked at the Appellate Court Division of the NLRB. Harvard College,  A.B.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1962; Villanova Law School,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1968; board of editors,  law review. Admitted in Illinois,  1971; and the District of Columbia,  1968.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Barry A. White</B> Barry focuses on labor problems in corporate mergers,  acquisitions,  and reorganizations; union organizing campaigns and elections; and negotiating and drafting collective bargaining agreements. University of Wisconsin,  B.A.,  1970; Northwestern University School of Law,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1973; board of editors,  law review. Admitted in Illinois,  1973.<BR>
<BR>

</UL>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Of Counsel
</H3></CENTER>
<BR><UL><LI><B>Stuart Bernstein</B> Stu has practiced in all areas of labor and employment law and has particular experience under the Railway Labor Act. He is currently a company-appointee to the United Airlines Pilots System Board of Adjustment. Stu has argued before the U.S. Supreme Court and various federal courts of appeal. University of Chicago,  B.A.,  1942; University of Chicago Law School,  J.D.,  1947; Order of the Coif; editor-in-chief,  law review. Admitted in Illinois,  1947.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Marian C. Haney</B> Marian has extensive experience in labor and employment-related litigation before federal and state administrative agencies,  class actions,  and all phases of pretrial and trial practice,  both jury and bench,  and appellate practice in federal and state courts. She also has general litigation experience including class actions. Marian clerked for Judge Edwin A. Robson of the U.S. District Court for the Northern District of Illinois. Loyola University of Chicago,  B.S.,  1966,  M.B.A.,  1971,  J.D.,  1974; executive editor,  <I>Loyola Law Journal</I>. Admitted in Illinois,  1974.<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
