<HEAD>
<TITLE>Miles  & Stockbridge
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Labor</H2>
<H3>Miles  & Stockbridge
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Baltimore:</B> 10 Light Street,  Baltimore,  MD 21202<BR>
Tel 410-727-6464  <B>*</B>  Fax 410-385-3700<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Cambridge,  Easton,  Frederick,  Rockville,  and Towson (Maryland);<BR>
Fairfax (Virginia); Washington,  D.C.<BR>
<BR>
176 lawyers  <B>*</B>  17 lawyers in Labor and Employment Law Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>M</B>iles  & Stockbridge is a full-service regional law firm representing major businesses and financial institutions. Its labor and employment and litigation practices are national in scope. The firm's labor and employment law group consists of 17 lawyers specializing in all aspects of labor and employment law,  including discrimination and abusive discharge matters,  labor-management disputes,  NLRB proceedings,  labor arbitrations,  personnel advice,  OSHA and related claims,  contract and human resources advice,  and wage and hour proceedings. A discrete subgroup specializes in ERISA and other employee benefits matters,  counseling employers and preparing and reviewing employee benefit and executive compensation plans. The lawyers in the group have successfully litigated employment matters before administrative agencies and in state and federal trial courts and appellate courts in various parts of the United States.<BR><BR><UL><LI><B>James P. Gillece,  Jr.</B> A seasoned labor litigator,  he has tried labor,  employment,  and related matters in state and federal courts,  and practices before the National Labor Relations Board and state and federal employment discrimination agencies. He is president of the Notre Dame Law Association. LaSalle College,  1966; Notre Dame University Law School,  1969.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Gary C. Duvall</B> Resident in our Towson,  Maryland office,  he regularly advises clients with regard to all aspects of employment matters and litigates on behalf of management in the federal and state courts and before federal and state employment discrimination agencies. University of Maryland,  1971; Georgetown University Law School,  1974.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Edward J. Adkins</B> Responsible for the employee benefits and ERISA practice,  he is located in our Baltimore office. He specializes in advising employers with regard to employee benefit plans,  ERISA obligations,  and related employer concerns. University of North Carolina,  1969; University of Maryland Law School,  1972.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James P. Garland</B> Senior member of the Group,  he has long experience in labor management disputes,  employment actions,  and labor negotiations. A fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers,  he is a former chairman of the Labor Law Section of the Maryland State Bar Association. Loyola College,  1953; Villanova Law School,  1956.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Anthony W. Kraus</B> Concentrates his practice in large and complex labor and employment litigation. He has represented major employers in substantial litigation in various courts throughout the United States as well as in the state and federal courts in Maryland. Reed College,  1972; Cornell Law School,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Steven D. Frenkil</B> Concentrates his practice in the representation of employers in the defense of employment discrimination claims,  wrongful discharge actions,  and employment contract disputes,  and advises on human resources policies. George Washington University,  1974; University of Maryland Law School,  1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kathleen Pontone</B> Concentrates her practice in advising employers in sexual harassment,  disabilities law,  and occupational safety and health,  and in the defense of employment discrimination suits for both private and public sector employers. Vassar College,  1972; Duke University School of Law,  1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John H. Murray</B> Resident in the firm's Easton,  Maryland office,  he represents employers in employment discrimination and personnel matters both as counselor and as trial attorney. University of London; Virginia Wesleyan College,  1974; University of Virginia Law School,  1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Stephen M. Silvestri</B> Mr. Silvestri represents management in every aspect of labor management and employee relations law and defends management in ERISA litigation. He is a former chairman of the Labor Law Section of the Maryland Bar Association and is active in the labor and employment law activities of the American Bar Association. Providence College,  1976; Catholic University Law School,  1979.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Thomas J. St. Ville</B> Concentrates his practice in ERISA and other employee benefits matters. He advises management in all aspects of employee benefits and executive compensation law. Notre Dame University,  1975; University of Tulsa Law School,  1979; University of Denver Law School,  1982.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Douglas M. Topolski</B> Concentrates his practice in the representation of management in all aspects of labor/management and employment discrimination matters. He practices before various regions of the National Labor Relations Board and federal and state antidiscrimination agencies and in state and federal courts. University of Maryland,  1981; University of Baltimore Law School,  1984.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
