<HEAD>
<TITLE>Morgan,  Lewis & Bockius LLP
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Labor</H2>
<H3>Morgan,  Lewis & Bockius LLP
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington:</B> 1800 M Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20036-5869<BR>
Tel 202-467-7000  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-467-7176<BR>
<B>Philadelphia:</B> 2000 One Logan Square,  Philadelphia,  PA 19103-6993<BR>
Tel 215-963-5000  <B>*</B>  Fax 215-963-5299<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> New York,  Los Angeles,  Miami,  Harrisburg (Pennsylvania), <BR>
Princeton (New Jersey),  London,  Brussels,  Frankfurt,  Tokyo<BR>
<BR>
750 lawyers  <B>*</B>  115 lawyers concentrating in labor and employment.<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/morgan.html"> ERISA</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/morgan.html"> Product Liability</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/morgan.html"> White Collar Crime</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>M</B>organ,  Lewis  & Bockius LLP is nationally recognized for its labor and employment services to management in the private and public sectors. We represent large and small clients in the manufacturing,  transportation,  construction,  energy,  health care,  financial service,  pharmaceutical,  charitable institution,  professional sports,  chemicals,  consulting,  publishing,  hospitality,  communications,  service,  and agricultural sectors.
<P><BR><P><I>Employment Discrimination Advice and Litigation</I> We counsel clients concerning compliance with federal,  state,  and local statutes prohibiting employment discrimination to minimize the likelihood of employment discrimination claims. When claims are made,  we aggressively defend our clients' interests and have had notable success in administrative and judicial forums,  including jury trials.<BR><P><I>Employee Relations</I> We work actively with clients in reviewing and revising employment practices and policies,  training managers and supervisors,  drafting and defending affirmative action plans,  counseling on and structuring reductions in force (OWBPA and WARN),  and undertaking or implementing alternative dispute resolution mechanisms. Our practice includes ADA and FMLA compliance and advice in connection with sales,  mergers,  acquisitions and corporate restructuring.<BR>
<BR><P><I>Employee Benefits and Executive Compensation</I> The collective experience of our employee benefits lawyers covers the spectrum of executive compensation and employee benefit plans,  programs,  and arrangements. We regularly draft and defend plans including qualified pension,  profit-sharing,  thrift,  stock bonus,  401(k),  employee stock ownership,  nonqualified executive deferred compensation and supplemental benefit,  incentive,  severance benefit,  stock option and phantom stock,  executive and group life insurance programs,  health and welfare,  long-term and short-term disability income programs,  cafeteria and flexible benefits,  voluntary incentive plans used in restructuring situations,  and fringe benefits. Lawyers also serve as counsel to trustees of many of the largest collectively bargained multiemployer pension and welfare plans in the country.<BR>
<BR><P><I>Labor-Management Relations and Labor Disputes</I> We provide creative strategies for dealing with unions that represent or seek to represent our clients' employees. We advise and represent clients in collective bargaining,  labor mediations and arbitrations,  and union organizing campaigns.<BR>
<BR><P>We represent national multiemployer bargaining associations in various industries,  including coal,  over-the-road trucking,  and freight and passenger railroads. We also pioneered the use of construction project agreements with the Building and Construction Trades international and local unions to expedite dispute-free construction of major projects.<BR>
<BR><P>When clients and their unions are unable to resolve their disputes through negotiation,  we vigorously represent our clients' interests in forums,  including federal and state courts,  arbitration,  NLRB,  FMCS,  NMB,  and FLRA. We also provide advice during labor disputes,  including strike contingency plans and countermeasures for boycotts and `corporate campaigns.'<BR>
<BR><P><I>Occupational Safety and Health</I> Our OSHA practitioners conduct compliance audits,  advise clients regarding government inspections,  and select and supervise technical consultants to provide full representation of clients under state and federal occupational safety and health laws. We regularly represent clients contesting health and safety citations,  achieving success in litigation if necessary,  and equally important achieving agency withdrawal citations without costly litigation.<BR>
<BR><P><I>Wage and Hour Laws</I> Lawyers advise and represent clients in claims and disputes arising under the Fair Labor Standards Act,  Davis-Bacon Act,  Service Contract Act,  and analogous state statutes. We educate managers and supervisors regarding applicable legal requirements,  and provide advice during compliance audits. When enforcement proceedings are brought,  we represent clients in administrative and judicial forums.<BR>
<BR><P><I>Other Employment Law Claims</I> We counsel and defend employers against the many common law and statutory claims that are potentially available to would-be,  current,  and former employees. Those claims include express and implied contract and wrongful termination claims,  claims based on statutes addressing family and medical leave,  notices to workers of facility shutdowns or layoffs,  drug testing,  polygraph tests,  and whistleblower protection.<BR>
<BR><P><I>Railway Labor Act</I> We counsel and represent airline and railroad carriers in connection with their rights and responsibilities under the RLA,  including major and minor disputes; challenges to carriers' rights to change or interpret the status quo with respect to rates of pay,  rules and working conditions; and in matters before the National Mediation Board,  Presidential emergency boards,  and system boards.<BR>
<BR><P><I>Noncompetition Agreements and Related Obligations</I> We help clients protect trade secrets and other proprietary information through the use of noncompetition and nonsolicitation agreements,  intellectual property agreements,  and other contracts,  and represent them in the initiation or defense of litigation.<BR>
<BR><P><I>International Labor and Employment Law</I> We provide advice to U.S. companies with foreign operations and to foreign companies establishing operations in the United States. We have broad experience with the employment laws and practices in the European Union,  British Commonwealth,  Pacific Rim,  Latin America,  and other jurisdictions. Working with lawyers in the firm's international offices and an established group of international employment counsel,  we have the multinational capacity to advise on employment issues relating to start-ups,  sales,  mergers,  acquisitions and closings; executive employment and separation agreements; relations with unions,  workers' representatives,  and governmental agencies; representation of employers before ILO/OECD; and immigration issues,  including obtaining visas and representation before the INS.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>William J. Curtin</B> (Washington; 202-467-7100) Chairman of the Labor and Employment Law Section,  Mr. Curtin has served as counsel on numerous labor-management matters of national importance,  including representing the railroad industry during its 1991 and 1992 national strikes. He also negotiated on behalf of major construction projects,  including Walt Disney World,  the Trans Alaska Pipeline System and the Boston Harbor Clean-Up project labor agreement,  and represented the organized trucking industry in the negotiation of the National Master Freight Agreement. Mr. Curtin was recently appointed by the current National Labor Relations Board chairman to serve on the Board's Advisory Panel. He was previously selected as coordinator of a group of nine management lawyers to advise President Clinton's Commission on the Future of Worker- Management Relations.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Charles P. O'Connor</B> (<I>Washington; 202-467-7070</I>) Mr. O'Connor's practice concentrates on representing management in all phases of labor law and labor relations,  including collective bargaining and all facets of employee relations.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Harry A. Rissetto</B> (<I>Washington; 202-467-7130</I>) Mr. Rissetto's practice concentrates on the representation of airlines and railroads with respect to their rights and obligations under the Railway Labor Act.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert J. Smith</B> (<I>Washington; 202-467-7065</I>) Mr. Smith represents public and private sector employers in labor and employment matters,  including the defense of employment discrimination and preventive maintenance advice.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Thomas K. Wotring</B> (<I>Washington; 202-467-7080</I>) Mr. Wotring concentrates on the representation of management in all phases of labor relations and the representation of jointly trusteed multiemployer plans.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Mark S. Dichter</B> (<I>Philadelphia; 215-963-5291</I>) Mr. Dichter's practice concentrates in employee benefits and ERISA litigation,  employer-employee relations,  including management labor law and collective bargaining,  and wage and hour law.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Judith E. Harris</B> (<I>Philadelphia; 215-963-5028</I>) A former solicitor of the City of Philadelphia,  Ms. Harris's practice concentrates in employment discrimination counseling and litigation and public labor relations law.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Francis M. Milone</B> (<I>Philadelphia; 215-963-5670</I>) Mr. Milone's trial practice concentrates on complex benefits litigation,  employment discrimination,  wrongful termination,  and employment contract litigation.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>George A. Stohner</B> (<I>New York; 212-309-6092</I>) Mr. Stohner's practice concentrates in employment litigation,  counseling,  OSHA,  employee benefits,  and international labor matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William J. Emanuel</B> (<I>Los Angeles; 213-612-2550</I>) Mr. Emanuel advises and represents employers in labor relations and employment law,  including corporate mergers and acquisitions and collective bargaining negotiations.<BR>
<BR>
