<TITLE>Orrick,  Herrington & Sutcliffe
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Labor</H2>
<H3>Orrick,  Herrington & Sutcliffe
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Los Angeles:</B> 777 South Figueroa Street,  Los Angeles,  CA 90017<BR>
Tel 213-629-2020  <B>*</B>  Fax 213-612-2499<BR>
<B>New York:</B> 666 Fifth Avenue,  New York,  NY 10103<BR>
Tel 212-506-5000  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-506-5151<BR>
<B>Sacramento:</B> 400 Capitol Mall,  Suite 3000,  Sacramento,  CA 95814-4407<BR>
Tel 916-447-9200  <B>*</B>  Fax 916-329-4900<BR>
<B>San Francisco:</B> 400 Sansome Street,  San Francisco,  CA 94111-3143<BR>
Tel 415-392-1122  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-773-5759<BR>
<B>Menlo Park:</B> 1020 Marsh Road,  Menlo Park,  CA 94025<BR>
Tel 415-833-7800  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-614-7401<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> 1150 18th Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20036<BR>
Tel 202-463-3400  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-463-3401<BR>
<BR>
332 lawyers  <B>*</B>  40 lawyers in labor and employment practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>O</B>rrick,  Herrington  & Sutcliffe traces its origins to 1863,  when its earliest predecessor firm was organized to represent the San Francisco Bank,  now First Interstate Bank of California. Other early clients included Transamerica Corporation and Pacific Gas and Electric Company.
<P><BR><P>The firm's Labor and Employment Law Department has a national presence in representing both private and public sector employers in all facets of labor and employment law. Our practice includes client counseling and employment litigation in the areas of wrongful termination,  equal employment opportunity and affirmative action,  labor relations and collective bargaining,  ERISA,  wage and hour,  and worker health and safety,  as well as client counseling in connection with corporate transactions,  and other traditional and emerging issues in employment law. Representative clients include: A.C. Nielson,  Albertson's,  Inc.,  AT &T,  American Museum of Natural History,  Apple Computer,  Atlantic Richfield Company,  Contel Corporation,  Delta Air Lines,  Inc.,  Donaldson,  Lufkin  & Jenrette,  The Dun  & Bradstreet Corporation,  The GAP,  Inc.,  General Electric Company,  Hilton Hotels,  Hofstra University,  IBM,  International Paper,  Interstate Brands,  R.H. Macy  & Co.,  Inc.,  Merrill Lynch  & Co.,  Newsweek,  NYNEX,  Oracle Corporation,  Safeway Stores Inc.,  Seagate Technologies,  St. John's University,  Smith Barney Inc.,  University of Vermont,  and Virgin Atlantic Airways.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Ralph H. Baxter,  Jr.</B> (<I>San Francisco</I>) serves as the firm's chief executive officer. Ralph is among the nation's leading employment litigators,  with particular emphasis on wrongful termination litigation. Ralph lectures and writes extensively on developments in employment law and its implications for employers. He is a member of the American Bar Association and its Section on Labor and Employment Law. Ralph served as chair of the ABA Labor Section's Committee on Individual Rights and Responsibilities.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Stuart H. Bompey</B> (<I>New York</I>),  chair of the firm's Labor and Employment Law Department,  directs the group's activities in all areas of employment law. His practice is devoted to counseling and defending employers in all aspects of employment law and human resource management,  as well as employment litigation in state and federal courts and before stock exchange arbitration panels and administrative agencies. He has particular expertise in dealing with employment litigation and employment-related issues for financial institutions and colleges and universities. He lectures and publishes on labor and employment law issues and was cited in 1992 by <I>The National Law Journal</I> as among the nation's foremost employment litigators. In March 1995,  <I>New York</I> magazine listed Stu Bompey as one of the top ten employment lawyers in New York. He is the management chair-elect of the Equal Employment Opportunity Committee of the Labor and Employment Law Section of the ABA.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Lori A. Bowman</B> (<I>Los Angeles</I>) specializes in labor and employment law matters. Lori's practice is devoted to representing management in all aspects of employment law,  with particular emphasis on employment-related litigation. Additionally,  Lori represents various clients in dealing with traditional labor relations issues.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Steven A. Brick</B> (<I>San Francisco</I>) has concentrated primarily on complex civil litigation matters. Areas of substantive experience include jury and nonjury trials of wrongful discharge and discrimination claims and handling class actions under Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964,  as well as complex commercial litigation. He has supervised major litigation matters in state and federal courts in California,  Nevada,  Oregon,  Arizona,  Indiana,  and New Jersey.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael Delikat</B> (<I>New York</I>) does both labor and general civil litigation. His practice involves both active litigation and counseling,  with particular concentration in the publishing,  communications,  airline,  financial,  retail,  textile,  and apparel industries. Mike also specializes in copyright infringement and corporate litigation where he has handled a variety of significant cases.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard A. Gilbert</B> (<I>San Francisco</I>) practices employee benefits law and has long been involved in advising employers and investment management firms as to the fiduciary responsibility provisions of ERISA and public pension law,  the tax-efficient design and implementation of numerous executive benefit and flexible compensation plans,  and employee benefit issues involved in corporate transactions. He has special experience in the ERISA aspects of a wide variety of new investment instruments,  and has published a variety of articles.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Lynne C. Hermle</B> (<I>Menlo Park</I>) specializes in litigating employment issues and counseling employers on employment-related issues. Lynne has litigated numerous discrimination and wrongful termination cases,  including significant sexual harassment cases. Lynne lectures on trial advocacy issues and teaches continuing education on trial skills.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Norman C. Hile</B> (<I>Sacramento</I>) specializes in commercial and government litigation with an emphasis in employment matters. He has litigated complex cases in state and federal court,  before arbitration panels of the New York Stock Exchange and the National Association of Securities Dealers,  and under the judicial arbitration provisions of California's Code of Civil Procedure.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Herbert J. Levine</B> (<I>New York</I>) represents U.S. and multinational corporations engaged in various industries,  including radio and television broadcasting,  printing and publishing,  manufacturing,  hotels,  and airlines. Herb's area of concentration is primarily in the traditional labor relations areas of collective bargaining,  arbitration,  wage and hour,  and related litigation.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kenneth C. Mennemeier</B> (<I>Sacramento</I>) specializes in trial and appellate litigation,  including wrongful termination,  discrimination,  and sexual harassment cases. Ken has litigated cases in state and federal courts and before various industry forums.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Barbara Moses</B> (<I>New York</I>) represents employers in the financial and hotel industries and colleges and universities,  and has had extensive experience in securities,  intellectual property,  employment,  and complex commercial litigation. Barbara has published a variety of articles on securities litigation topics and is an active member of the American Bar Association,  the State Bar of California,  and the Bar of the District of Columbia,  as well as the litigation and securities sections of the ABA and the California State Bar.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Cynthia L. Remmers</B> (<I>Sacramento</I>) specializes in employment litigation and counseling,  including the various employment issues arising in connection with union representation,  mergers and acquisitions,  wrongful discharge,  discrimination,  and wage and hour disputes. She frequently lectures on the area of employment litigation,  including participation in numerous ABA-sponsored trial demonstration programs,  and has taught numerous seminars on employment topics to many law school students,  agencies,  companies,  bar associations,  and management groups.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jill L. Rosenberg</B> (<I>New York</I>) specializes in employment and labor litigation,  including cases in the federal and state courts,  in arbitration forums,  and before administrative agencies. She also counsels employers on a variety of employment issues. Jill has particular expertise in employment-related matters for colleges and universities and employers in the securities,  publishing,  hotel,  and airline industries.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gary R. SiniscaLCo</B> (<I>San Francisco</I>) has developed special expertise in equal opportunity,  affirmative action,  wrongful discharge,  and wage and hour matters. His practice involves both counseling on employment issues and litigation defense. He has handled numerous employment-related class actions and other employment cases before federal and state courts and administrative agencies. Gary was cited in 1992 by <I>The National Law Journal</I> as one of the nation's leading employment litigators. Gary lectures and publishes frequently on all aspects of employment law and is an active member of the Equal Employment Opportunity committee of the Labor and Employment Law Section of the ABA.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael D. Torpey</B> (<I>San Francisco</I>) specializes in both employment and general civil litigation. Mike's practice is primarily devoted to employers in the securities and financial services industries. Mike has extensive experience in class action litigation,  federal and state actions,  and litigation before stock exchange arbitration panels.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jeffrey D. Wohl</B> (<I>San Francisco</I>) specializes in employment litigation and counseling,  including wrongful discharge and discrimination cases. Jeff has developed an expertise in appellate court actions involving employment issues. Jeff has lectured and written numerous articles on employment issues.<BR>
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
