<TITLE>Ross  & Hardies
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Labor</H2>
<H3>Ross  & Hardies
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Chicago:</B> 150 North Michigan Avenue,  Chicago,  IL 60601<BR>
Tel 312-558-1000  <B>*</B>  Fax 312-750-8600<BR>
<B>New York:</B> 65 East 55th Street,  New York,  NY 10022<BR>
Tel 212-421-5555  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-421-5682<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> 888 16th Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20006<BR>
Tel 202-296-8600  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-296-8791<BR>
<B>Somerset:</B> 580 Howard Avenue,  Somerset,  NJ 08873<BR>
Tel 908-563-2700  <B>*</B>  Fax 908-563-2777<BR>
<BR>
190 lawyers  <B>*</B>  35 lawyers in labor and employment practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/ross.html"> Corporate Securities</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/ross.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/ross.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>R</B>oss  & Hardies has one of the largest management employment and labor law practices in the country. National labor counsel for many Fortune 500 companies,  the firm represents clients in virtually all aspects of labor law.
<P><BR><P>The practice includes counseling and litigation in matters related to equal employment obligations and discrimination under Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964; the Civil Rights Act of 1991; age discrimination claims under the Age Discrimination in Employment Act; handicap discrimination suits arising under the Americans with Disabilities Act and other federal and state discrimination acts; affirmative action plans; OFCCP compliance reviews under Executive Order 11246; and compliance with the Family and Medical Leave Act.<BR><BR><P>An important area of the practice involves the development,  documentation,  and administration of appropriate personnel policies for clients. Services in this area include preparation of personnel and compensation programs,  policies,  and manuals; advice on industrial relations and personnel matters,  including counseling on union prevention programs and collective bargaining issues; grievance arbitration matters; and proceedings before the National Labor Relations Board. The firm also has a comprehensive employee benefits practice and an OSHA practice.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Michael J. DiMattia</B> Mr. DiMattia,  who counsels and defends corporations in labor and employment matters throughout the country,  is a former National Labor Relations Board attorney who has concentrated his practice on labor and employment law since 1978. A contributing editor of <I>The Developing Labor Law</I>,  published by the American Bar Association,  he is a graduate of Cornell University and of the Albany Law School of Union University.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Timothy C. Klenk</B> Mr. Klenk's practice has involved the representation of major corporations,  agencies of the U.S. government,  and businesses of all sizes in cases involving employment discrimination and other labor matters,  ERISA,  defamation,  rights and obligations of officers and directors,  class actions,  and derivative actions. He is an arbitrator for the American Arbitration Association and a member of the American Judicature Society. He is a member of the Litigation,  Labor and Employment Law,  Banking and Business Law,  and Antitrust Law Sections of the American Bar Association,  and of the Illinois State Bar Association. He is a graduate of Wheaton College and of Northwestern University Law School.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard E. Lieberman</B> Mr. Lieberman,  who co-chairs the Labor Group,  has represented corporations in an extensive array of labor and employment law matters since 1974,  and has tried numerous age and wrongful discharge jury trials in federal and state courts throughout the United States. Prior to entering private practice in 1974,  Mr. Lieberman served as trial attorney for the National Labor Relations Board and the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission. He is a graduate of Miami University and of the University of Cincinnati Law School. He has written and lectured extensively on employment law and has been a featured speaker for the National Employment Law Institute and the American Bar Association's EEO Committee.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Carol Berlin Manzoni</B> Ms. Manzoni is an experienced trial attorney who is known nationally for her knowledge of traditional labor and employment discrimination law. Co-chair of the Labor Group,  she represents both domestic and foreign companies in equal employment opportunity litigation and counseling,  affirmative action compliance,  wrongful discharge litigation,  collective bargaining,  dispute resolution,  and NLRB proceedings. The author of <I>An Employer Guide for Establishing Drug and ALCohol Abuse Policies</I>,  she is a member of the American Bar Association's International Labor Law Committee and is a past chairperson of the ABA Public Sector Arbitration Committee. She is a graduate of Bucknell University and of the law school of Catholic University of America.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Leonard Rovins</B> Mr. Rovins has a national and long-standing reputation in school labor law; his 55-year career includes service as a director of the Connecticut Association of Boards of Education,  as a member of the Planning Board of the Carnegie Forum on Education and the Economy,  and as a member of the Connecticut State Department of Education Arbitration Panel. He is a graduate of the College of the City of New York and of the Brooklyn Law School.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard A. Wilsker</B> Mr. Wilsker has a national practice in management labor law. He has been active in the American Bar Association's Labor Section since 1978,  and was a member of the Executive Committee of the New York State Bar from 1982 to 1986. Mr. Wilsker is a graduate of Bucknell University and of New York University Law School.<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
