<HEAD>
<TITLE>Schuyler Roche  & Zwirner
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Labor</H2>
<H3>Schuyler Roche  & Zwirner
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Chicago:</B> One Prudential Plaza,  130 East Randolph Street,  Suite 3800,  Chicago,  IL 60601<BR>
Tel 312-565-2400  <B>*</B>  Fax 312-565-8300<BR>
<BR>
38 lawyers  <B>*</B>  13 lawyers concentrating in labor and employment<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/schuyler.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/schuyler.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/schuyler.html"> ERISA</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/schuyler.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>S</B>chuyler Roche  & Zwirner is a general practice law firm with an extensive labor and litigation practice in the state and federal courts,  in arbitrations,  and before administrative agencies.
<P><BR><P>The Labor and Employment Practice Group provides management labor representation to private and public sector clients for collective bargaining negotiations and related labor matters,  and provides representation in all aspects of employment law,  with an emphasis on client counseling and the prevention of litigation.<BR><P>When litigation does arise,  the Group prides itself on its ability to handle these matters efficiently and cost-effectively.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Overview of Experience</H3></CENTER>

<P>Schuyler,  Roche lawyers are experienced in counseling private and public sector management on union-related concerns in collective bargaining negotiations,  arbitrations,  and NLRB hearings. The firm's lawyers also have defended a variety of discrimination claims in federal and state courts,  before the Illinois Human Rights Commission,  the EEOC,  other state and federal agencies,  and in NASD arbitrations. The Labor and Employment Practice Group's experience includes the enforcement of noncompetition agreements and former employees' use of trade secrets and confidential information. In addition,  the Group has litigated extensively under ERISA and in connection with the termination of employee benefit plans. The Group's experience also includes the transactional,  employee benefits,  and tax knowledge necessary to prepare,  revise,  and amend employee benefit plans.<BR><P>The members of the Labor and Employment Practice Group are:<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Marshall L. Blankenship</B> has handled a variety of employment-related matters,  including prosecution and defense of claims under Title VII and ERISA.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael F. Braun</B> has litigated a number of employment discrimination,  civil rights and noncompetition claims. He recently prevailed on appeal in a case involving a medical service corporation's discharge of a doctor and enforcement of a noncompetition agreement.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Ralph E. Brown</B> has tried a variety of discrimination and noncompetition cases. He has represented management in labor negotiations,  arbitrations and NLRB hearings,  including decertification proceedings. On behalf of the employer,  he has negotiated separation agreements for senior management.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kael B. Kennedy</B> has successfully defended a number of corporations which were sued under ERISA for terminating welfare benefits to retirees. He has tried and defended employment discrimination,  trade secret,  and noncompetition claims in federal and state courts. He teaches a national program on arbitration and lectures regularly on the ADA.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Paul E. Lehner</B> has counseled a number of the firm's clients in employment matters,  including compliance with the ADA,  and has tried and defended employment discrimination,  trade secret and noncompetition claims in federal and state court and before various agencies.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert A. Michalak</B> has broad experience in ERISA and other employee benefits matters. He has drafted benefit plans and trusts,  summary plan descriptions and plan administrative forms,  and handled plan terminations. He also has provided substantial consulting services on various plan administration matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Randall L. Mitchell</B> has handled many discrimination and other employment-related claims,  including successfully defeating a sex discrimination claim against a major insurance company in a jury trial. He is a frequent speaker on employment issues.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Frank M. Pawlak</B> has substantial litigation experience representing private and public employers in employer-employee relations,  including arbitrations,  discrimination claims,  wrongful discharge and noncompetition matters. He also has served as co-negotiator in many collective bargaining negotiations.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jeffrey E. Schiller</B> has successfully litigated cases in the noncompetition,  trade secrets,  and employment discrimination areas. He recently prevailed in a noncompetition and trade secrets case which involved the brokerage industry.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Joseph J. Stevens</B> has substantial experience in the representation of private and public sector clients as the principal negotiator in many collective bargaining negotiations,  in NLRB and Illinois Labor Board proceedings,  in arbitrations (including interest arbitrations) and related matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard J. Walsh</B> and <B>Walter L. Adams</B> (who are of counsel to the firm) have substantial experience representing management before the NLRB,  in arbitrations,  and in collective bargaining negotiations. They also have handled numerous employment discrimination and other employment and labor-related claims.<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
