<HEAD>
<TITLE>Shawe  & Rosenthal
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Labor</H2>
<H3>Shawe  & Rosenthal
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Baltimore:</B> Sun Life Building,  20 South Charles Street,  Baltimore,  MD 21201<BR>
Tel 410-752-1040  <B>*</B>  Fax 410-752-8861<BR>
<BR>
16 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers practicing labor and employment law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>F</B>ounded in 1947,  Shawe  & Rosenthal is one of the oldest firms in the country devoted exclusively to the representation of management in labor and employment matters. Its 16 attorneys appear regularly before federal,  state,  and local courts and administrative agencies throughout the nation. In recognition of its position as a leader among labor law practitioners,  Shawe  & Rosenthal was selected by Matthew Bender Company to write the <I>Employment Law Deskbook</I>,  a practical guide to complying with labor and employment laws written especially for managers and human resources personnel.
<P><BR><P>Shawe  & Rosenthal's attorneys are knowledgeable concerning laws governing all aspects of the employer-employee relationship,  including the Civil Rights Act of 1964,  the Age Discrimination in Employment Act,  the Americans with Disabilities Act,  the Family and Medical Leave Act,  the National Labor Relations Act,  the Davis-Bacon Act,  the Fair Labor Standards Act,  ERISA,  and OSHA. The firm has successfully defended management against statutory employment discrimination claims,  as well as increasingly popular common law claims such as abusive discharge,  breach of contract,  fraud,  defamation,  and infliction of emotional distress. In addition,  Shawe  & Rosenthal has represented management in unfair competition and trade secret litigation,  and in employment-related immigration matters.<BR><P>The firm also represents both union and nonunion companies in traditional labor law matters. Since it was established,  Shawe  & Rosenthal has successfully represented nonunion clients in more than 3, 000 representation cases. For clients whose employees are represented by a union,  Shawe  & Rosenthal's attorneys serve as spokespersons at the collective bargaining table,  as advisors to human resources personnel on the administration of labor contracts,  and as advocates of management in arbitration and court proceedings arising out of contract disputes.<BR>
<BR><P>Shawe  & Rosenthal recognizes that it has been most successful when a client is not sued,  not when it ultimately prevails in court or before an administrative agency. Thus,  the firm places great emphasis on preventive law. To this end,  Shawe  & Rosenthal reviews and analyzes clients' personnel policies,  employment applications,  and employee benefit plans; develops,  reviews,  and monitors affirmative action plans; develops and implements equal employment opportunity audits; assists in the drafting and implementation of sexual harassment policies; advises management regarding sensitive employment decisions; instructs managerial employees in their equal employment opportunity obligations; and advises clients regarding important changes in the law through client seminars,  a firm newsletter,  and client advisories.<BR>
<BR><P>Shawe  & Rosenthal has for many years represented Maryland's four largest publicly held companies Black  & Decker Corporation,  United States Fidelity  & Guaranty Company,  Baltimore Gas  & Electric Company,  and Bethlehem Steel. The firm also serves as labor and employment counsel to such national concerns as McDonald's Corporation,  May Department Stores,  The Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond,  Jos. A. Bank Clothiers,  and Thiokol Corporation.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>The Firm's Principal Members</H3></CENTER>

<BR><UL><LI><B>Earle K. Shawe</B> served ten years with the National Labor Relations Board and was chief law officer of the board's Fifth Region in Baltimore. He left the board to found the firm in 1947,  and concentrates his practice in representing management in labor proceedings.<BR><LI><B>William J. Rosenthal</B> joined the firm in 1951,  and is nationally known for his representation of employers in National Labor Relations Board and unfair labor practice proceedings. He has been a contributing editor of <I>The Developing Labor Law</I>.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Stephen D. Shawe</B> served as an assistant U.S. attorney for the District of Maryland for three years (1967-1970) before becoming the first general counsel to the Maryland Commission on Human Relations. He rejoined the firm in 1971,  and has since represented employers nationwide in labor and employment litigation and at the collective bargaining table.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Arthur M. Brewer</B> has been with the firm since 1972,  practicing extensively in complicated litigation before the National Labor Relations Board and acting as chief spokesman for numerous employers in collective bargaining negotiations. He is the co-editor of the <I>Maryland Handbook on Labor  & Employment Laws</I>.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Bruce S. Harrison</B> served as a senior attorney at the EEOC from 1971 until 1976,  when he joined the firm to represent management in employment litigation. He has written numerous guides to assist employers in avoiding employment claims,  and chairs the Equal Employment Opportunity Subcommittee of the Litigation Section of the ABA.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Eric Hemmendinger </B>practices in all areas of labor and employment law,  with an emphasis on complex litigation and occupational safety and health matters. Eric is a frequent speaker at continuing professional education and business seminars.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>J. Michael McGuire</B> regularly represents management in proceedings before the National Labor Relations Board,  in employment discrimination litigation,  and in occupational safety and health matters. He is the chair of the Labor and Employment Law Committee of the Maryland Association of Defense Trial Counsel.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Gary L. Simpler</B> served for seven years with Region 5 of the National Labor Relations Board before joining the Firm in 1985. He represents employers in all areas of labor and employment law,  with an emphasis on labor-management relations,  union avoidance,  and collective bargaining.<BR></UL>

</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
