<HEAD>
<TITLE>Siegel,  O'Connor,  Schiff & Zangari,  P.C.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Labor</H2>
<H3>Siegel,  O'Connor,  Schiff & Zangari,  P.C.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Hartford:</B> 370 Asylum Street,  Hartford,  CT 06103<BR>
Tel 860-727-8900  <B>*</B>  Fax 860-527-5131<BR>
<B>New Haven:</B> 171 Orange Street,  P.O. Drawer 906,  New Haven,  CT 06504<BR>
Tel 203-789-0001  <B>*</B>  Fax 203-782-2766<BR>
<BR>
24 lawyers  <B>*</B>  15 lawyers in labor and employment practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>S</B>iegel,  O'Connor,  Schiff  & Zangari,  P.C.,  practices only in the representation of private and public sector management clients in labor and employment matters and specialized business and tax representation. The firm is experienced in the full range of legal issues surrounding the employment relationship,  including all aspects of employment litigation in state and federal administrative agencies and courts,  as well as all related appeals. Our lawyers have handled hundreds of union organizing drives,  National Labor Relations Board hearings,  grievance arbitrations,  collective bargaining negotiations,  and injunction proceedings. We regularly advise clients on all aspects of employee and labor relations,  wage and hour matters,  OSHA,  affirmative action,  workers' compensation,  unemployment compensation,  family and medical leave,  ERISA,  drug testing,  WARN Act issues,  sexual harassment,  disability,  and discrimination law. Our services in the areas of employment discrimination and wrongful discharge lawsuits range from preventive measures to representation before discrimination agencies and state and federal courts.<BR><BR><UL>
<LI><B>Richard D. O'Connor</B> was one of the founding partners of the firm. His practice is focused on the defense and trial of employee discrimination claims. He is a member of the Association of Trial Lawyers of America and former chairman of the Labor and Employment Section of the Connecticut Bar Association. He is also management co-chair of the International Labor Law Committee of the Section of Labor and Employment Law of the American Bar Association. Mr. O'Connor was regional coordinator for the National Manufacturers' Association Committee on Labor Law Reform,  an arbitrator with the American Arbitration Association,  and a member of the Magistrate Reappointment Review Committee for the U.S. District Court,  District of Connecticut.<BR>
<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Donald W. Strickland</B> is highly experienced in all areas of labor and employment law,  with an emphasis in the areas of school and municipal law. He has served as president and member of the Executive Committee and Board of Directors of the Connecticut School Attorneys Council,  chairman of the Labor and Employment Law Section of the Connecticut Bar Association,  and as a member of the Occupational Safety and Health Committee of the American Bar Association. Mr. Strickland was adjunct faculty member at Sacred Heart University,  and is a frequent lecturer and author in the employment law area.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Peter A. Janus</B>,  managing director of the firm,  concentrates his practice in labor relations and employment law with extensive experience in both the private and public sectors. Mr. Janus is an active member of the Committee on the Development of Law Under the National Labor Relations Act of the American Bar Association's Labor and Employment Law Section,  and an assistant editor of <I>The Developing Labor Law</I>,  published by the Bureau of National Affairs.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Edward F. O'Donnell,  Jr.</B>,  joined the firm in 1979 and has since been involved in a wide variety of labor law matters. He has extensive collective bargaining experience in the private and public sectors,  has counseled employers on plant closing and relocation issues,  and has represented clients in union organizing drives. Mr. O'Donnell has appeared numerous times before the National Labor Relations Board,  the Connecticut State Board of Mediation and Arbitration,  and state and federal courts.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Hugh W. Cuthbertson</B> has a broad range of experience in litigating employment discrimination and wrongful discharge suits. A former assistant U.S. attorney for the District of Connecticut,  Mr. Cuthbertson serves on a Panel of Special Masters for the New Haven Seat of the U.S. District Court for the District of Connecticut. He is a member of the New Haven County,  Connecticut,  Federal,  and American Bar Associations,  as well as the Connecticut Trial Lawyers and Defense Lawyers Associations. Admitted in Massachusetts,  Connecticut,  the District of Columbia,  and the U. S. Courts of Appeals for the Second,  Fifth,  and Eleventh Circuits.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Frederick L. Dorsey</B> is involved in a wide variety of labor relations and employment issues,  including contract negotiations and administration and employment discrimination matters in both the public and private sectors. Mr. Dorsey is a member of the American and Connecticut Bar Associations,  Connecticut School Attorneys Council,  National School Board Association Council of Attorneys,  American Bar Association's Section of Labor and Employment Law,  and Committee on State and Local Government Bargaining and Employment Law,  and is a participant in the American Arbitration Association's Labor Arbitration Advocacy Program.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Carole Williams Briggs</B> practices in the areas of business,  construction,  and environmental law with extensive experience in OSHA matters. Ms. Briggs is a member of the American,  Connecticut,  Minnesota and Hartford County Bar Associations. Admitted in Connecticut and Minnesota.<BR>
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
