our matters,  plant closings and reductions in force,  employee benefits,  occupational safety and health,  noncompetition and confidentiality agreements,  and employment contracts.<BR><P>Traditional labor matters,  including collective bargaining arbitration and representation of employers before the National Labor Relations Board,  are extremely active areas for the group. We counsel clients in managing effective responses to union drives.<BR><BR><P>The group regularly handles investigations,  fact-finding conferences,  and hearings before both federal and state discrimination and labor agencies,  such as the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission and the U.S. Department of Labor. We also represent clients in connection with the investigations of,  and proceedings before,  the Occupational Safety and Health Administration.<BR><BR><P>The group publishes a quarterly newsletter,  <I>Labor  & Employment</I>,  which focuses on current legal developments.<BR><BR><UL><BR><LI><B>Jason Berger</B> Mr. Berger is head of the Labor and Employment Practice Group. He has represented management for 20 years,  during which time he has practiced extensively before both state and federal courts,  including the U.S. Supreme Court. An active member of the Federal Bar Association and the Massachusetts Bar Association (MBA),  Mr. Berger served as chairman of the MBA's Labor and Employment Law Section from 1983 to 1984. He has lectured extensively on labor and employment law for a variety of institutions,  including Boston University,  Northeastern University School of Law,  Syracuse University,  The Massachusetts Academy of Trial Attorneys,  and the Boston Bar Association. Colby College,  B.A.,  1965; Indiana University,  M.A.,  1967; Boston University Law School,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1972.<BR><BR><LI><B>John F. Welsh</B> Mr. Welsh represents management in employment and labor matters with an emphasis on employment and labor-related litigation. He is a former trial and appellate attorney for the National Labor Relations Board in Washington,  D.C. and in Boston. Mr. Welsh is vice-chairman of the Labor Relations and Collective Bargaining Subcommittee of the Massachusetts Bar Association,  as well as a member of both the American and the Federal Bar Associations. Catholic University of America,  B.A.,  with honors,  1977; Boston College Law School,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1980.<BR><BR><LI><B>Jin-Kyung (Kay) Kim</B> Ms. Kim's practice is concentrated in labor and employment law and employee benefits. She has lectured in a number of different forums and for a variety of audiences including the American Corporate Counsel Association on topics such as the federal plant closing law,  the Americans with Disabilities Act,  sexual harassment,  and the Family and Medical Leave Act. Ms. Kim is a member of the Boston Bar Association,  the American Bar Association,  the Asian-American Lawyers Association,  and the Massachusetts Bar Association. Wellesley College,  B.A.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1983; University of Chicago Law School,  J.D.,  1986.<BR><BR><LI><B>Adam P. Forman</B> Mr. Forman's practice includes discrimination and wrongful discharge litigation; noncompetition agreements litigation; traditional labor work; the development of employee relations systems such as employee handbooks,  personnel policies,  and codes of conduct; and health and safety in the workplace,  including right-to-know laws,  the hazard communication standard,  and the laboratory standard. Mr. Forman is a member of the American Bar Association,  the Boston Bar Association,  and the Massachusetts Bar Association and its Labor and Employment Section. The Pennsylvania State University,  B.A.,  high distinction,  1984; Georgetown University Law Center,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1987; Phi Beta Kappa; associate editor,  <I>American Criminal Law Review</I>. Admitted in Massachusetts,  1992; Pennsylvania,  1987; U.S. Court of Appeals for the First Circuit,  1994; U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit,  1990; U.S. District Court for the District of Massachusetts,  1992; and U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania,  1987.<BR><BR></UL></UL></BODY></HTML>
