<P>
<P>
<P><B>V</B>orys,  Sater,  Seymour and Pease offers national and international representation in all areas of law,  including antitrust,  bankruptcy,  commercial,  corporate,  energy,  government contracting,  health care,  insurance,  intellectual property,  international,  labor,  legislation,  litigation,  public utilities,  real estate,  and white collar defense.<BR>

<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Labor and Employment Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>Vorys,  Sater has 30 attorneys in its Labor and Employment Practice Group. The group members have subspecialties in labor management and litigation matters including union avoidance,  employment discrimination,  ERISA and employee benefits,  employment privacy,  the Fair Labor Standards Act,  federal contract compliance laws and regulations,  wrongful discharge,  the Family and Medical Leave Act,  and workers' compensation and unemployment compensation laws,  as well as employment issues impacted by the health care reform movement.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Charles D. Minor</B> is counsel to the firm after having been senior partner of the Labor and Employment Law Group for more than 25 years. His practice includes the full range of collective bargaining,  labor,  and employment law issues,  as well as corporate and business law. Ohio State University,  J.D.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1952.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James P. Friedt</B>,  a partner in the Columbus office,  is the administrative head of the Firm's Labor and Employment Group. His practice subspecialty is occupational safety and health law. Mr. Friedt also is experienced in general labor and employment issues such as discrimination,  wage and hour,  workers' compensation,  and proceedings under the National Labor Relations Act. Ohio State University,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1968.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Thomas M. Tarpy</B>,  a partner in Columbus,  practices in the areas of labor,  employment,  and general business. Mr. Tarpy has extensive experience with negotiation and enforcement of labor contracts,  union organizing campaigns and elections,  strikes,  wage and hour issues,  civil rights and employment discrimination claims,  ERISA claims and enforcement,  and employment-at-will matters. Ohio State University,  J.D.,  1969.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>G. Ross Bridgman</B> has extensive litigation experience in employment termination,  contract,  and discrimination matters. Mr. Bridgman also deals frequently with affirmative action programs and enforcement of collective bargaining agreements,  grievance arbitrations,  union organizational campaigns,  representation elections,  union strikes,  picketing issues,  public employee collective bargaining,  and wage and hour matters. Northwestern University,  J.D.,  1973.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Mary Ellen Fairfield</B> is a partner in the Columbus office,  where her primary area of practice is general civil litigation in state and federal courts. She has extensive experience in the trial of employment matters,  including discrimination,  invasion of privacy,  and employment-at-will cases. Fellow,  American College of Trial Lawyers. Ohio State University College of Law,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1972.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert A. Minor</B> is a partner in the Columbus office who practices extensively in the area of labor and employment matters with an emphasis on employer liability and worker's compensation defense. Other areas of his practice include wrongful discharge,  employment discrimination,  employment-at-will matters,  and occupational safety and health. Ohio State University,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1975.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jonathan M. Norman</B> is a partner who has extensive experience in union avoidance and campaigns,  National Labor Relations Board administrative matters,  arbitrations,  contract negotiations,  and counseling on personnel policies and procedures. He has represented employers in matters involving wage and hour law,  employment discrimination,  defamation,  invasion of privacy,  and employment-at-will matters. Ohio State University,  J.D.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Chris J. North</B>,  a partner in the Columbus office,  has broad experience in the areas of labor and employment law and litigation,  including arbitration,  employment discrimination,  wrongful discharge,  labor relations,  personnel counseling,  employment litigation,  and wage and hour law. Ohio State University,  J.D.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Douglas L. Williams</B> is a partner practicing in the areas of equal employment opportunity and wrongful discharge litigation. He has also served as lead trial counsel in class actions under the Age Discrimination Employment Act and the Equal Pay Act. Ohio State University,  J.D.,  with honors,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
