<P>
<P><B>W</B>inston  & Strawn has more than 450 lawyers located in six offices. We provide assistance in virtually every major legal discipline to a wide range of clients throughout the United States and abroad,  including governments and governmental entities,  Fortune 500 companies,  and major commercial and financial institutions,  as well as individuals and small and midsize companies.
<P><BR><P>The firm represents management interests in labor and employee relations matters for firms in heavy and light manufacturing,  companies in health care,  banking,  insurance,  and other service industries,  as well as public sector agencies. Our attorneys have represented clients in litigation and investigations in various state and federal agencies and courts,  including the U.S. Supreme Court.<BR><P>Attorneys in the labor and employment relations practice group help clients in the development and implementation of policies that address drug and aLCohol testing,  disabled employee obligations,  and family medical leave rights. We regularly advise employers on ways to minimize their exposure in these areas,  and conduct training for supervisors designed to acquaint them with and sensitize them to these and other important areas of the law.<BR>
<BR><P>In cooperation with the firm's corporate department,  we advise clients on transactional matters,  including mergers and acquisitions,  executive employment agreements,  reductions-in-force,  separation agreements,  and noncompetition and trade secret agreements.<BR>
<BR><P>We frequently advise unionized clients on collective bargaining and contract administration matters,  and actively participate in collective bargaining negotiations. We also advise nonunion clients on policies and procedures designed to encourage productivity,  enrich employment,  and maintain nonunion status. We have counseled numerous clients in connection with NLRB representation elections.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Columbus R. Gangemi,  Jr.</B> is head of the firm's labor and employment relations practice group. He has broad experience in all areas of labor and employment relations and has represented clients before the NLRB,  the EEOC,  the Department of Labor,  the U.S. Supreme Court,  the U.S. Congress,  various federal and state courts and agencies,  and labor contract arbitrators. Mr. Gangemi has dealt with union `insider tactics' and `corporate campaigns' as well as strikes of national scope,  and has worked extensively with the firm's nonunion clients,  advising them on the maintenance of nonunion status and guiding them through union organizational activity.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Deborah Gage Haude </B>has extensive experience in the areas of ERISA litigation; EEO litigation and policies; reductions in force; negotiation of,  development of,  and litigation concerning executive employment agreements,  noncompetition provisions,  and other contracts; and employment at will. She has assisted clients in mergers,  acquisitions,  and divestitures,  and in developing employee relations and benefits programs and policies to address new and changing business and personnel needs.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Gregory J. Malovance</B> has been involved in the development of a comprehensive body of case law since the Illinois public sector bargaining legislation became effective in 1984. He has argued extensively in the Illinois Appellate Court and Supreme Court,  and has litigated employment cases involving constitutional issues,  public official and governmental liability,  and information disclosure. He has represented clients before the NLRB,  IELRB,  EEOC,  Department of Labor,  and labor arbitrators,  and has been involved in the collective bargaining process,  both as an advisor and a negotiator.<BR>
<BR></UL><P>The firm has recently expanded its labor and employment law group by adding several new partners and of counsel in its Washington,  D.C. and New York City offices:<BR><BR><UL><LI><B>William A. Carmell</B> heads the employment law practice group in the firm's New York office,  and has almost 25 years of experience in employment law,  including eight years as staff counsel on employment law matters at Union Carbide. He works extensively with Japanese clients and other U.S. clients,  counseling them on workforce issues including Title VII,  NLRA,  ERISA,  ADEA,  FLMA,  and employment at will.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Edmund D. Cooke,  Jr.</B> concentrates his practice in employment law and government relations. He has extensive experience in government service,  serving as staff counsel to the Subcommittee on Employment Opportunities of the Committee on Education and Labor,  Special Counsel to the Committee on House Administration,  and counsel to the House Committee on Education and Labor.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Robert J. Nobile</B> has represented clients in discrimination,  FLSA,  WARN,  OSHA,  affirmative action compliance,  administrative litigation,  management training,  and arbitration matters. He is an adjunct professor at several universities,  teaching courses in various aspects of employment law.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Dennis M. Devaney</B> joined Winston  & Strawn after completing his term as a member of the National Labor Relations Board. He has extensive experience in labor and employment relations law,  and served in various government positions from 1982 until 1988. He also has taught as a visiting professor at Cornell University,  Boston University,  and Wayne State University Law Schools.<BR>
