<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>B</B>eatie,  King  & Abate is engaged in a diverse and sophisticated litigation practice with an emphasis on complex mass tort products liability matters. In addition,  the firm is involved in a broad spectrum of other subject matters,  including insurance,  environmental,  securities,  real estate,  condemnation,  and general commercial and corporate litigation matters.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Experience and Clients</H3></CENTER>

<P>The firm is composed of three partners,  six associates,  and three paralegals,  and is led by Russel H. Beatie,  Jr. Mr. Beatie headed his own litigation firm from 1983 to 1989. Prior to that,  he was a litigation partner in a large Wall Street firm for more than ten years. Kenneth J. King and Samuel J. Abate,  Jr. joined Mr. Beatie's firm in 1983,  and two of the firm's associates joined that firm in 1987. In 1989,  the entire firm merged with a large Wall Street firm where,  subsequently,  Mr. King and Mr. Abate became partners. The group remained at this firm until January 1993 when Beatie,  King  & Abate was formed.<BR><P>Much of the firm's practice involves the defense of a major manufacturer of drugs,  pharmaceuticals,  and agricultural products in hundreds of multidefendant cases involving the drug diethylstilbestrol (DES). In the DES cases,  the firm has participated in national defense efforts,  coordinated work to be done by local law firms,  handled cases directly,  tried a large number of cases to verdict,  negotiated the settlement of large blocks of cases,  and participated in or managed national and regional settlement programs. In addition,  the firm has been retained by a major European pharmaceutical manufacturer to assist in the defense of the DES cases in the Netherlands and France.<BR>
<BR><P>The firm also represents a major computer manufacturer in the defense of the cases alleging repetitive stress injuries,  and is one of the firms which assist in the coordination of strategy in that litigation. In addition,  the group has been involved in the defense of asbestos and asbestos-related cases in New York,  including its representation of an asbestos defendant in a limited fund settlement class action brought by the company to resolve mass tort liability.<BR>
<BR><P>Mr. Beatie has also handled products cases for manufacturers of medical devices and other products,  including pacemakers and oral contraceptives. The firm has successfully defended cases involving a range of other pharmaceutical products such as insulin,  antibiotics,  phenobarbital,  diphtheria vaccine,  and antidepressants. In each instance it has handled complex scientific issues in order to take discovery,  deal with experts,  argue motions,  and try the cases.<BR>
<BR><P>Beatie,  King  & Abate has broad trial and appellate experience. The firm has tried products liability and other types of cases in Connecticut,  New York,  New Jersey,  Texas,  Delaware,  Maryland,  the District of Columbia,  Illinois,  Ohio,  Pennsylvania,  Oklahoma,  and California,  most of them to a jury. They have ranged from three days to four months. In addition,  the firm has argued numerous appeals on a variety of issues before the highest courts in the states of New York,  New Hampshire,  Connecticut,  Florida,  and New Jersey,  and the U.S. Courts of Appeal for the Second,  Third,  Fifth,  Sixth,  Ninth,  and Tenth Circuits. In the process,  the firm has produced a number of innovative trial and appellate rulings,  including establishing favorable law for product liability defendants on issues such as limited-fund-settlement class actions,  statute of limitations,  nonidentification liability,  the viability of spouse's loss of consortium claims,  and the viability of the claims of third-generation plaintiffs (and of parents for cost of raising an injured child).<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Russel H. Beatie,  Jr.</B> From 1980 to 1983,  Mr. Beatie served on an advisory committee to the board of directors of a corporation involved in asbestos litigation. He has served as part of a national counsel group that manages mass tort lawsuits nationwide,  and has also been involved in matters relating to insurance coverage for mass tort litigations. Mr. Beatie is a graduate of Princeton University and Columbia Law School.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kenneth J. King</B> Mr. King has worked on products liability and mass tort litigation for 11 years,  including the diethylstilbestrol and repetitive stress injury cases. He is currently a member of the Product Liability Committee of the Association of the Bar of the City of New York and the Product Liability Committee of the New York County Lawyer's Association. He has also served on the Torts Committee of the Association of the Bar of the City of New York. Mr. King is a graduate of Dartmouth College and George Washington University Law School,  where he was a member of the law review.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Samuel J. Abate,  Jr.</B> Mr. Abate has worked on products liability and mass tort litigation for 11 years and is responsible for managing the diethylstilbestrol litigation in New York. He is a graduate of Fordham College and the Fordham University School of Law.<BR>
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
</HTML>
