<TITLE>Campbell Maack  & Sessions
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Product Liability</H2>
<H3>Campbell Maack  & Sessions
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Salt Lake City:</B> One Utah Center,  13th Floor,  201 South Main Street, <BR>
Salt Lake City,  UT 84111<BR>
Tel 801-537-5555  <B>*</B>  Fax 801-537-5199<BR>
<BR>
16 lawyers  <B>*</B>  7 lawyers practicing product liability<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>C</B>ampbell Maack  & Sessions,  a litigation boutique,  was formed by highly experienced trial lawyers with the goal of providing the highest quality trial and appellate work in a small-firm setting to maximize efficiency,  minimize costs,  and facilitate personal service. Since the firm's inception,  Campbell Maack  & Sessions has defended manufacturers in product liability suits throughout Utah,  in neighboring states,  and nationally from Alaska to New England. Campbell Maack  & Sessions prides itself in providing the best defense possible while keeping in mind the clients' critical need for efficiency,  cost-effectiveness,  and working within budgets. To that end,  Campbell Maack  & Sessions has accumulated a vast repository of legal research,  motions and memoranda,  streamlined discovery,  and other trial pleadings to ensure the low cost and efficient delivery of legal services. The Firm places strong emphasis on client communication and coordination with in-house counsel to ensure a unified approach and defense strategy.
<P><BR><P>CM &S has served as regional counsel for major national and international manufacturers,  serving as discovery coordinator,  supervising counsel,  and lead trial counsel. The Firm has developed an invaluable network of experts in such fields as accident reconstruction,  mechanical engineering,  automotive design,  metallurgy,  human factors,  warnings,  biomechanics,  toxicology,  pharmacology,  emergency medicine,  neuropsychology,  vocational rehabilitation,  and economics. These experts understand the needs of manufacturers for the highest quality work within preestablished budgets. In addition to our relationships with these experts,  the Firm has established working relationships with attorneys throughout the Western United States to assist in matters where the Firm is retained outside Utah.<BR><P>Clients represented by the Firm include American Honda Motor Co.,  Inc.,  American Suzuki Motor Corp.,  Adams Elevator Equipment Co.,  The Ariens Company,  Associated Aviation Underwriters,  Cessna Aircraft Co.,  Ciba-Geigy Corp.,  Connaught Laboratories,  The Cooper Companies,  Inc.,  Emerson Electric,  Inc.,  Kawasaki Heavy Industries,  Ltd.,  Kubota Tractors,  Kenworth/Peterbilt,  Millar Elevator Service Co.,  Paccar,  Inc.,  Pepsi-Cola Co.,  Polaris Industries,  L.P.,  The Procter  & Gamble Co.,  Quaker State Oil Refining Corp.,  Richardson-Vicks,  Inc.,  Schering-Plough,  Schindler Elevator Corp.,  Showa Denko K.K.,  UpRight,  Inc.,  VuLCraft,  Westinghouse Canada Inc., Westinghouse Electric Corp.,  Wyeth Laboratories,  Yamaha Motor Corp.,  USA,  and Young Electric Sign Co. Inc.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Robert D. Maack</B> Robert D. Maack is a fellow in the American College of Trial Lawyers,  an advocate in the American Board of Trial Advocates,  a member of the Defense Research Institute,  and a master of the bench in the American Inns of Court. Mr. Maack is currently president of the Utah chapter of the American Board of Trial Advocates. For over 25 years Mr. Maack has specialized in product liability litigation involving complex scientific issues,  including products of all types,  and liability involving architects,  engineers,  pharmaceuticals,  transportation,  containers,  and other matters. Mr. Maack has particular emphasis in litigation involving motor vehicle,  semi-truck,  motorcycle,  ATV,  and water craft dynamics,  handling,  and stability; industrial machinery; heavy equipment; nuclear,  hydroelectric,  and coal-fired electrical generating facilities; utility and power plants; electrical power transmission lines; water treatment facilities; electrostatic precipitators; metallurgical processing facilities; firearms; fires and explosives; and environmental,  toxic waste,  and waste disposal matters. Mr. Maack has served as regional counsel in product liability litigation for major national and international manufacturers wherein he supervised and coordinated the defense of product liability litigation throughout the Western and Midwestern states. He is also knowledgeable in U.S. Consumer Products Safety Commission matters. Monterey Peninsula College; University of Utah,  B.S.,  honors,  1967,  J.D.,  honors,  1970; board of editors,  <I>Utah Law Review</I>.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Martin R. Denney</B> Mr. Denney is an experienced trial attorney who has handled product liability cases throughout the United States,  from Alaska to New England. Mr. Denney has worked as regional counsel,  coordinating complex discovery and trials throughout the West. Mr. Denney has litigated complex product liability cases in both state and federal courts and is adept at early case evaluation and analysis,  including case analysis through jury research and mock trials. Mr. Denney's concentration has been in the defense of personal injury claims associated with the use of consumer products such as semi-tractors and trailers,  automobiles,  motorcycles,  ATVs,  pharmaceuticals,  hand tools,  and medical devices including breast implants. Brigham Young University,  J.D.,  1985.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Tracy H. Fowler</B> Mr. Fowler has had extensive trial and appellate experience in products liability and personal injury litigation in Utah and other Western states. He has represented several general aviation manufacturers in cases involving alleged aircraft defects in state and federal trial courts as well as the Utah Supreme Court and the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit. He has also handled aviation-related personal injury cases for commercial airlines and component part manufacturers. Mr. Fowler also has a broad background in products litigation involving drugs and medical devices. He has handled over 20 toxic shock syndrome cases and numerous L-tryptophan cases. Mr. Fowler has represented manufacturers of a diverse range of additional products such as elevators,  escalators,  ladders,  small appliances,  bullet-resistant vests,  recreational vehicles,  and construction equipment. Member,  Executive Committee of the Utah State Bar Association Litigation Section. University of Utah,  J.D.,  1980; staff member,  <I>Utah Law Review</I>.<BR></UL>


</UL></BODY>
