<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>C</B>hamberlain,  D'Amanda,  Oppenheimer  & Greenfield was established in 1879 as a litigation firm. Since its inception the firm has been involved in every type of civil litigation. Litigation in federal and state courts involves product liability claims of defective design,  negligent manufacturing,  and lack of adequate warning. This work has been primarily insurance defense,  relating to countless products ranging from heavy industrial equipment to coffee pots,  and from exercise equipment to pharmaceuticals. Our trial lawyers are aggressive and innovative in their client representation,  responding immediately and bringing a strike force to bear in crisis situations. They constantly keep the economic realities of the matter in focus,  and through regular communication keep clients informed at all times of the status of the case.
<P><BR><P>The following are members of our litigation department:<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Sheldon W. Boyce,  Jr.</B> has a practice which includes commercial and contract litigation and white collar criminal matters. He has extensive experience in the field of toxic torts. He came to the firm from the Monroe County District Attorney's Office. Utica College,  B.S.,  1976; Albany Law School,  J.D.,  1979; <I>Albany Law Review</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Thomas G. Collins</B> is an appellate practitioner. Before joining the firm he served as law clerk for Justice Richard D. Simons,  New York Supreme Court,  Appellate Division,  Fourth Department,  and as staff law clerk to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit. He has served as Second Circuit editor for the American Bar Association's <I>Appellate Practice Journal</I>,  and has spoken and written on the subject of appellate practice. State University of New York at Buffalo,  B.A.,  1974,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Louis D'Amanda</B> is chairman of the firm's trial department and specializes in product liability,  insurance defense,  construction,  and fire loss claims. Recent cases have involved drill presses,  ladders,  and saw mill equipment. He is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers. Wesleyan University,  B.A.,  1951; Harvard Business School; Cornell University,  LL.B.,  1961.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>K. Wade Eaton</B> practices general civil litigation. He came to the firm after 13 years in the public advocacy division of the office of the New York State Attorney General. Yale University,  B.A.,  1967; Cornell Law School,  J.D.,  1972.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Henry R. Ippolito</B> practices in the product liability,  insurance defense,  and environmental areas. Recent cases have involved toxic torts,  pharmaceuticals,  and zinc. He has served as president of the Monroe County Bar Association. Instructor,  Cornell University Law School,  1973-1975. Syracuse University,  A.B.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1964; Phi Beta Kappa; Phi Kappa Phi; Cornell University,  J.D.,  with distinction,  1967; Order of the Coif.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Douglas Jones</B> has focused his practice in the environmental area,  construction disputes,  product liability,  general insurance defense,  and white collar criminal work. Recent cases have involved guarding and safety design of saws and cutting machinery,  tools,  and breach of warranties of fitness. He came to the firm from the Monroe County District Attorney's office. He is a member of the Town of Mendon Zoning Board. Dartmouth College,  A.B.,  1971; Syracuse University,  J.D.,  1976.<BR>
