<TITLE><*t(16.9106, 0, "1  ", 163, 2, "1  ", 166.6907, 0, "1  "):
>Clark,  Thomas  & Winters
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Product Liability</H2>
<H3>
Clark,  Thomas  & Winters
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<BR>
<B>Austin:</B> 1200 Texas Commerce Bank Building,  700 Lavaca,  Austin,  TX 78767<BR>
Tel 512-472-8800  <B>*</B>  Fax 512-474-1129<BR>
<B>Other office:</B> San Antonio<BR>
<BR>
80 lawyers  <B>*</B>  17 lawyers practicing in products liability<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>
<BR>

<P><BR>

<P><B>F</B>ounded in 1938,  Clark,  Thomas  & Winters is a full-service professional corporation representing a wide range of clients in most areas of civil practice from its offices in Austin and San Antonio.<BR>

<P><BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Products Liability Experience And Clients
</H3></CENTER>

<P>The firm's products liability group defends manufacturers in state and federal trial and appellate courts and in state administrative agency actions. Lawyers in the group have served as regional counsel for manufacturers in mass tort litigation,  defending cases throughout Texas and in Louisiana,  Arkansas,  Oklahoma,  Missouri,  Kansas,  New Mexico,  Colorado,  Montana,  Ohio,  Utah,  Minnesota,  and South Dakota.<BR>
<BR><P>Representative clients include: (<I>automotive</I>) Chrysler,  Nissan,  Toyota,  Volkswagen,  and Hyundai; (<I>pharmaceutical and medical</I>) American Home Products Corporation,  Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories,  A.H. Robins,  Elkins-Sinn,  McGhan Medical Corporation,  and Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing; (<I>other</I>) Carlisle Tire,  WelLCraft Marine Corporation,  Genmar Industries,  Inc.,  and Mitsubishi.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Burgain G. Hayes</B> Mr. Hayes has defended foreign and domestic manufacturers of products ranging from automobiles to building materials,  vaccines,  and other pharmaceutical products. He has been designated by two national manufacturers as their counsel in multistate regions. He has extensive experience with litigation involving complex engineering issues. Mr. Hayes has also tried RICO and complex insurance defense cases. School of International Service of American University,  B.A.,  1969; University of Texas,  J.D.,  1975. Admitted in Texas,  1975.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kenneth J. Ferguson</B> Mr. Ferguson's clients have included foreign and domestic automobile manufacturers,  tractor manufacturers,  oil field equipment manufacturers,  and a variety of other products liability defendants. He also has experience in jury trials over employment discrimination,  breach of contract,  banking,  and insurance defense cases. University of Texas,  B.A.,  with highest honors,  1974; Phi Beta Kappa; J.D.,  with honors,  1977. Admitted in New Mexico,  1977; and Texas,  1985.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael R. Klatt</B> Mr. Klatt has handled a wide range of products liability cases,  including extensive representation of manufacturers of pharmaceutical and biological products (including vaccines),  and medical devices and equipment. He has also represented boat and automobile manufacturers,  companies in ERISA and insurance litigation,  and clients before the State Board of Insurance and the Texas ALCoholic Beverage Commission. University of Texas,  B.A.,  with high honors,  1977; Phi Beta Kappa; Baylor University,  J.D.,  1980; <I>Baylor Law Review</I>. Admitted in Texas,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Leslie A. Benitez</B> Ms. Benitez represents corporations and manufacturers in statewide and national products liability cases. She has concentrated in the appellate area. She was also general counsel to the governor of Texas from 1984 to 1987. University of Texas,  B.A.,  with honors,  1974,  J.D.,  with honors,  1977. Admitted in Texas,  1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Chris Pearson</B> Mr. Pearson's practice has focused on products liability cases,  including representation of foreign and domestic automobile manufacturers,  as well as tool and machinery manufacturers. He also has experience in handling employment law cases and bad faith insurance cases. Lamar University,  B.S.,  1980; Texas Tech University,  J.D.,  1984; <I>Texas Tech Law Review</I>. Admitted in Oklahoma,  1984; and Texas,  1988.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Louis D. Bonder</B> Mr. Bonder represents manufacturers of pharmaceutical and biological products,  medical devices,  and equipment. He also has experience in medical malpractice litigation and in lawsuits against automobile manufacturers involving complex medical issues. St. Joseph's University,  B.S.,  with honors,  1977; Widener University,  Delaware Law School,  J.D.,  1986. Admitted in Texas,  1987.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Roy A. Spezia</B> Mr. Spezia,  a former staff counsel for a Fortune 500 corporation,  has represented both domestic and foreign automobile manufacturers. He has also represented manufacturers of various other products,  including boats and building products. University of Michigan,  B.A.,  1981; Wayne State University,  J.D.,  1985. Admitted in Michigan,  1985; and Texas,  1989.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David S. Lill</B> Mr. Lill's practice focuses on representation of manufacturers in the defense of product liability claims and lawsuits,  particularly involving medical devices. Further,  his practice includes commercial litigation,  `bad faith' insurance litigation,  and insurance defense. U.S. Marine Corps,  first lieutenant,  1982-1985. Baylor University,  B.A.,  1978,  J.D.,  1988; managing editor,  <I>Baylor Law Review</I>. Admitted in Texas,  1988.
