<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>W</B>ith 27 partners and 36 associates in its Litigation Department,  Goodwin,  Procter  & Hoar provides a full array of litigation services. The firm has particular concentrations in product liability and toxic torts litigation; complex business and securities litigation; intellectual property litigation,  including trial of patent infringement matters; environmental litigation; alternative dispute resolution; construction litigation; insurance litigation; and administrative proceedings and white collar defense.
<P><BR><P>The firm's product liability and toxic torts practice is concentrated in the defense of civil litigation against manufacturers and sellers of pharmaceuticals,  medical devices,  construction products,  industrial equipment,  motor vehicles,  chemicals,  paints,  tobacco,  asbestos,  recreational products,  and personal hygiene products. The practice includes representation of national and New England-based companies in litigation throughout the United States. The firm has acted as national and regional coordinating counsel in major product liability litigation and has extensive experience in the defense and management of mass tort cases. In addition,  the firm provides product liability counseling and risk management advice on issues such as product recall,  liability prevention,  product literature claims,  warnings,  investigations,  and related matters.<BR><P>Goodwin,  Procter  & Hoar is a principal regional counsel for Eli Lilly and Company in product liability matters,  and has represented Lilly throughout New England,  upstate New York,  the mid-Atlantic states,  and Florida. It has represented Philip Morris and its associated companies in tobacco and other litigation. Other clients include Sherwin-Williams (lead paint market share litigation); Volkswagen of America; Harris Graphics Corporation (printing presses,  graphic arts equipment,  and other industrial machinery); the Dalkon Shield Claimants Trust (IUD litigation); SmithKline Beckman and SmithKline Bio-Science Laboratories; Watts Industries,  Inc. (industrial valves); W.R. Grace  & Co. (construction products); and International Playtex (personal health care products).<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Marshall Simonds</B>,  a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers,  has been active in pharmaceutical defense work for many years. He has also handled cases involving pesticides,  heavy equipment,  chemicals,  medical malpractice,  and tobacco.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Shepard M. Remis</B>,  former chairman of the firm's Litigation Department,  has represented Volkswagen as regional counsel in product liability claims,  and has also defended such claims for Fiat and BMW. Mr. Remis was national coordinating counsel for W.R. Grace  & Co. in litigation involving asbestos-containing building products. He has also tried cases concerning chemicals,  UFFI,  and industrial equipment.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Don M. Kennedy</B> has litigated products liability cases involving pharmaceuticals,  surgical implant devices,  asbestos,  industrial equipment and chemical products. A frequent lecturer on product liability prevention and risk management,  Mr. Kennedy is co-author of a textbook,  Heafey and Kennedy,  <I>Product Liability: Winning Strategies and Techniques</I> (Law Journal Seminars Press,  1994).<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Thomas J. Griffin,  Jr.</B> has been Massachusetts trial counsel for Harris Graphics Corporation in the defense of products liability suits involving printing presses,  graphic arts equipment,  and other industrial machinery. He represents Philip Morris in the defense of tobacco litigation and SmithKline Beckman and SmithKline Bio-Science Laboratories in various tort cases in Massachusetts. Mr. Griffin has represented Sherwin-Williams in lead paint litigation in Massachusetts. He has also been trial counsel for cases involving asbestos,  surgical blades,  aerial lift devices,  textile machinery,  and motor vehicle components.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John Kenneth Felter</B> has been trial counsel in swimming pool product liability cases for Coleco Industries,  Inc. and for a major sports arena in personal injury litigation arising out of an electrical explosion,  and has represented a major manufacturer of medical surgical equipment.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Sandra Sue McQuay</B> has been national trial counsel for W.R. Grace  & Co. in product liability litigation involving asbestos-containing building products,  and has defended other manufacturers in cases involving cranes and various kinds of industrial machinery. She also has been trial counsel in cases involving chemicals and other toxic materials,  including PCBs,  heavy metals,  and volatile organic compounds.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard A. Oetheimer</B> has represented Eli Lilly and Company in DES litigation and W.R. Grace  & Co. in litigation involving asbestos-containing building products. He is currently Massachusetts trial counsel for the Dalkon Shield Claimants Trust. He has also represented manufacturers of swimming pools and playground equipment in defense of personal injury claims. In addition,  he has provided products liability advice to manufacturers of testing equipment and industrial and consumer products.
</UL>


