<HEAD>
<TITLE>Hoyle,  Morris  & Kerr
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Product Liability</H2>
<H3>Hoyle,  Morris  & Kerr
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Philadelphia:</B> One Liberty Place,  1650 Market Street,  Philadelphia,  PA 19103<BR>
Tel 215-981-5700  <B>*</B>  Fax 215-851-0436<BR>
<BR>
50 lawyers  <B>*</B>  20 lawyers concentrating in products liability practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/hoyle.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/hoyle.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/hoyle.html"> Environmental</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>H</B>oyle,  Morris  & Kerr has a national practice that includes a wide variety of commercial litigation. Firm attorneys are particularly experienced in products liability and toxic tort cases and associated insurance coverage disputes.
<P><BR><P>Since its inception,  the Firm has been heavily involved in the defense of products liability and toxic torts claims. For instance,  we currently handle toxic tort and products liability problems for a major chemical company nationally. We also serve as counsel for a Fortune 500 pharmaceutical company which has been sued in multiple jurisdictions in connection with a blood clotting concentrate administered to hemophiliacs linked to transmission of AIDS. On behalf of another Fortune 500 pharmaceutical company,  we defend cases involving claims of adverse effects allegedly attributable to its drug,  device,  and general health care products. Attorneys in the Firm represent other pharmaceutical companies in the defense of DES,  toxic shock syndrome,  and baby bottle syndrome cases.<BR><P>We have represented a major cement manufacturer in a multidistrict litigation proceeding arising from lawsuits filed by railroads complaining of alleged defects in prestressed concrete railroad ties. Our products liability practice has also included representing manufacturers of such diverse products as tires,  fork-lifts,  rifles,  toasters,  hand-presses,  apparel,  herbicides,  and underground storage containers.<BR>
<BR><P>We gained substantial experience in multijurisdictional toxic tort litigation through our role as national coordinating counsel and special bankruptcy counsel for a major building products manufacturer in asbestos litigation,  and we currently represent one of the largest former manufacturers of asbestos-containing fireproofing in asbestos property damage litigation. Notably,  we obtained defense verdicts in the first two asbestos property damage cases ever tried to conclusion before juries,  and have continued to earn a successful win-loss record in this litigation. We are particularly adept in selecting and working with experts to marshal the complex medical-scientific evidence on which modern toxic tort claims are based.<BR>
<BR><P>As a result of our defense of underlying litigation on behalf of companies whose insurance carriers have denied coverage,  we represent corporate policyholders in disputes with their carriers over coverage for environmental,  products liability,  and toxic tort claims,  as well as claims for business interruption and property losses.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Lawrence T. Hoyle,  Jr.</B> Mr. Hoyle's principal practice areas are products liability,  toxic tort,  and environmental litigation. Deputy attorney general,  Civil Litigation Division chief,  Department of Justice,  Commonwealth of Pennsylvania,  1971-1972; executive director,  Pennsylvania Crime Commission,  1972-1974. Fellow,  American Bar Foundation. Duke University,  A.B.,  1960; University of Chicago,  J.D.,  1965. Admitted in Pennsylvania,  1965.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Bernard J. Smolens</B> Mr. Smolens' principal practice areas are products liability,  construction,  and insurance litigation. Fellow,  American College of Trial Lawyers. University of Pennsylvania,  B.A.,  1938,  LL.B.,  1941; secretary,  <I>University of Pennsylvania Law Review</I>,  1940-1941. Admitted in Pennsylvania,  1946.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Susan K. Herschel</B> Ms. Herschel's principal practice areas are products liability,  toxic tort,  and medical malpractice. Law clerk,  Judge Daniel H. Huyett III,  U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania,  1974-1976. Syracuse University,  B.A.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1964; Rutgers University-Camden School of Law,  J.D.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1974. Admitted in Pennsylvania,  1974.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Arlene Fickler</B> Ms. Fickler's principal practice area is complex litigation,  including products liability class actions. Member,  American Law Institute. University of Pennsylvania,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1971,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1974; comment editor,  <I>University of Pennsylvania Law Review</I>,  1973-1974. Admitted in Pennsylvania,  1974; and the District of Columbia,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jill A. Douthett</B> Ms. Douthett represents corporate policyholders in insurance coverage litigation over underlying products liability,  toxic tort,  and environmental claims. Divisional deputy city solicitor,  commerical litigation,  City of Philadelphia,  1982-1984. London School of Economics; Tulane University,  B.A.,  1973; University of Virginia,  J.D.,  1976; Phi Beta Kappa. Admitted in Pennsylvania,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Eric B. Henson</B> Mr. Henson's principal practice areas are medical and technical issues inherent in toxic tort and environmental litigation. University of Kentucky,  B.A.,  1964; Harvard University,  M.A.,  1967; University of Pennsylvania,  J.D.,  1970; Phi Beta Kappa; Woodrow Wilson Fellow. Admitted in Pennsylvania,  1970.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Bebe H. Kivitz</B> Ms. Kivitz's principal practice areas are products liability,  toxic tort,  and medical malpractice litigation. University of Pennsylvania,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1976; Temple University,  J.D.,  1979. Admitted in Pennsylvania,  1979.<BR>
