<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Product Liability</H2>
<H3>
Kaye,  Scholer,  Fierman,  Hays  & Handler
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<BR>
<B>New York:</B> 425 Park Avenue,  New York,  NY 10022<BR>
Tel 212-836-8000  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-836-8689<BR>
<B>Other offices: </B>Beijing,  Hong Kong,  Los Angeles,  Washington,  D.C.<BR>
<BR>
345 lawyers  <B>*</B>  25 lawyers in product liability<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profile in the following other directory:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/kaye.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P><BR>

<P><B>K</B>aye Scholer has one of the largest litigation departments in the country,  with 40 partners,  15 counsel,  and 80 associates in New York,  Los Angeles,  and Washington. The department handles complex and technical matters in all major fields of litigation.<BR>

<P><BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Kaye Scholer's Product Liability Practice
</H3></CENTER>

<P><BR><BR>
Kaye Scholer's product liability practice centers upon the trial and appellate defense of product manufacturers or service providers in mass disaster,  mass tort,  and other complex product liability cases. Significant matters we have handled include:<BR>
<BR><UL>
<BR><P><LI> the defense of the fire alarm company in the San Juan Dupont Plaza Hotel fire litigation,  in which more than 2, 000 plaintiffs,  including the estates of 97 who were killed in the fire,  had sued;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> the representation as national coordinating counsel in more than 500 cases worldwide involving an artificial heart valve on behalf of a pharmaceutical/medical device company;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> the representation of General Public Utilities,  the owner of the Three Mile Island nuclear power plant,  in connection with the much-publicized nuclear accident;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> the defense of Stauffer Chemical Company in an EPA enforcement action relating to the alleged disposal of hazardous waste,  and in related property damage actions;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> acting as coordinating counsel for a leading manufacturer of agricultural pesticides in individual lawsuits claiming that the pesticide caused cancer and in class actions seeking damages for fear of cancer;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> acting as coordinating counsel for an electronics manufacturer's product liability litigation;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> the appellate defense of Bridgestone/Firestone in a `fear of cancer' case in the California Supreme Court;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> the defense of a large petroleum company in personal injury and property damage cases involving the alleged release of oil in groundwater underlying commercial and residential properties;<BR>
<BR>
<BR><P><LI> representing the Business Roundtable,  the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,  and the National Association of Manufacturers as <I>amicus curiae</I> before the Supreme Court of Georgia in overturning the largest punitive damage product liability verdict in history;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> due diligence investigations regarding potential exposure in product liability,  toxic tort,  and environmental litigation in connection with public offerings and major corporate transactions.<BR>
<BR><BR></UL>
<LI><B>David Klingsberg</B> (<I>New York</I>) is the firm's senior product liability litigator. He has served as a national coordinating counsel to a worldwide pharmaceutical/medical device company in the artificial heart valve litigation; as trial counsel for General Public Utilities in the Three Mile Island nuclear power plant litigation; and as appellate counsel to Beiersdorf,  U.S. Home,  and Curtiss-Wright in three cases reversing punitive damages awards in tort cases against those companies. He recently chaired a session of the Institutional Investor CEO Roundtable entitled `What Every CEO Should Know About Product Liability.'<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Pierce O'Donnell</B> (<I>Los Angeles</I>) heads the firm's Los Angeles office. A trial lawyer with extensive experience in product liability,  he is presently representing a Fortune 500 company against toxic tort and contamination claims,  and has argued the Bridgestone-Firestone toxic tort `fear of cancer' case in the California Supreme Court. He is also representing Lockheed in a toxic tort alternative dispute resolution proceeding. He has also been California trial and appellate counsel in the defense of a worldwide pharmaceutical/medical device company in several hundred lawsuits involving artificial heart valves.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Terrence B. Adamson</B> (<I>Washington</I>),  an experienced trial lawyer,  was chief spokesman for the Department of Justice in the Carter Administration. He has litigated mass tort claims on behalf of a manufacturer of DDT,  and was on the planning committee for the 1994 National Conference on Mass Torts sponsored by,  among others,  the Judicial Conference of the United States.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Steven Glickstein</B> (<I>New York</I>) chairs the firm's Product Liability Group. He served as lead counsel for the fire alarm company in the San Juan Dupont Plaza Hotel fire litigation,  and has substantial class action product liability experience in such diverse areas as medical devices and agricultural pesticides. He also has performed product liability due diligence investigations in connection with corporate acquisitions; and has advised clients in asbestos cases and in matters relating to the Consumer Product Safety Commission. He is on the board of editors of <I>Product Liability Law and Strategy</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David O. Bickart</B> (<I>Washington</I>),  former deputy counsel for the Environmental Protection Agency,  provides counseling and handles litigation concerning environmental matters,  including issues relating to the generation,  transportation,  and disposal of hazardous waste.<BR>
<BR>


</UL></BODY>
