<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Kramer,  Levin,  Naftalis  & Frankel</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL><CENTER><H2>Product Liability</H2><H3>Kramer,  Levin,  Naftalis  & Frankel</H3></CENTER><CENTER><B>New York:</B> 919 Third Avenue,  New York,  NY 10022<BR>Tel 212-715-9100  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-715-8000 <B>*</B> Home page: <A HREF="http://www.kramer-levin.com/">www.kramer-levin.com</A><BR><BR>150 lawyers  <B>*</B>  15 lawyers in product liability and insurance defense practice<BR></CENTER><P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR><UL><BR>   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/kramer.html"> Antitrust</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/kramer.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/kramer.html"> Corporate Securities</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95ERIFolder/kramer.html"> ERISA</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/kramer.html"> Intellectual Property</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/kramer.html"> Labor</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/kramer.html"> White Collar Crime</A>   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/kramer.html"> Workout</A></UL><P><P><CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Product Liability Practice</H3></CENTER><P><B>S</B>ophisticated commercial litigation at the trial and appellate levels is the largest segment of our practice and includes both consumer and industrial products liability actions. <B>Harold P. Weinberger</B>, <B> Arthur H. Aufses III</B>, <B> </B>and<B> Philip S. Kaufman</B> have led many of our recent product liability actions in both federal and state courts around the country. These matters often involve the development of complex testimony by engineering,  economics,  and medical experts.<P><BR><P>Mr. Weinberger has represented a major consumer products company in a number of actions involving a range of products and issues,  including questions concerning product design and testing as well as injury and damages. He is also experienced in handling false advertising cases under the Lanham Act involving the clinical testing of over-the-counter products,  cases which often raise issues similar to those in product liability claims.<BR><P>Mr. Aufses has represented Whittaker Corporation in defending product liability and warranty claims involving such diverse products as cabin cruisers,  railroad freight cars,  and survival capsules for offshore oil rigs. For example,  we successfully represented Whittaker's Trojan Yacht Division against claims that engine and electrical design defects contributed to a widely publicized collision between a Whittaker-built yacht and a barge that caused five deaths. When cracks appeared in coal-carrying railroad cars manufactured under design licenses by Whittaker's Berwick Forge  & Fabricating Division,  we prosecuted claims arising out of the design issues,  we defended against other claims brought by purchasers of the cars,  and we handled a host of insurance questions concerning those claims.<BR><BR><P>Mr. Kaufman successfully represented the New York State Urban Development Corporation against the Dow Chemical Company in its highly publicized action concerning structural failures in connection with the use of Dow's product,  Sarabond.<BR><BR><CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Insurance Defense Practice</H3></CENTER><P>Our insurance company clients including The Home Insurance Company,  National Union Fire Insurance Company,  Chubb  & Son,  Inc.,  and Aetna Life  & Casualty Company retain us not only to handle litigation to which they are parties,  but also to defend actions brought against their insured corporations,  fiduciaries,  and professional firms. We are thus experienced in a broad range of coverage issues,  involving both insurers and domestic and foreign reinsurers,  and in representing major insured corporations,  law and accounting firms,  corporate directors and officers,  and trustees under ESOPs and pension plans. We also counsel insurance companies in matters involving alleged employment discrimination and,  through our extensive white collar criminal practice,  in investigations concerning alleged criminal activity.<BR><UL><BR><LI><B>Philip S. Kaufman</B> has handled more than 100 cases on behalf of insurance companies and specializes in insurance defense litigation. He represents the insurers themselves in coverage and reinsurance disputes,  and the companies' insured law and accounting firms and corporate directors and officers in complex civil litigation involving alleged violations of the securities laws,  RICO,  ERISA,  and fiduciary obligations.<BR><BR><P>Mr. Kaufman's recent matters include representation of The Home Insurance Company in major litigation with 17 U.S.,  British,  and German reinsurers; defense of a prominent New York law firm in multidistrict securities litigation arising from the collapse of Towers Financial Corporation; and defense of a group of law firms charged with violations of RICO and the antitrust laws,  based on their successful representation of asbestos victims in actions against Keene Corporation.<BR><BR><LI><B>Gary P. Naftalis</B>, <B> Ellen R. Nadler</B>, <B> </B>and<B> Alan R. Friedman</B>,  members of our white collar criminal defense group,  are experienced in the defense of financial services firms,  corporate directors and officers,  and law firms charged with various types of misconduct. Recent matters include the defense of Kidder,  Peabody  & Co. Incorporated in numerous complex civil litigations resulting from allegations of insider trading by Ivan F. Boesky and others,  and representation of a major Washington,  D.C. law firm in obtaining the reversal on appeal of a $128 million judgment.<BR><BR><LI><B>Michael J. Dell</B> represents major accounting firms in professional liability litigation,  as well as employers,  ESOPs,  fiduciaries and multiemployer pension plans in litigation arising under ERISA and related statutes.<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR></UL></UL></BODY></HTML>
