<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Product Liability</H2>
<H3>Mayer,  Brown  & Platt
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Chicago:</B> 190 South LaSalle Street,  Chicago,  IL 60603<BR>
Tel 312-782-0600  <B>*</B>  Fax 312-701-7711<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Houston,  Los Angeles,  New York,  Washington,  D.C., <BR>
Berlin,  Brussels,  London<BR>
<B>Correspondent office:</B> Mexico City (J &#242;uregui,  Navarette,  Nader y Rojas,  S.C.)<BR>
<BR>
650 lawyers  <B>*</B>  40 lawyers in the product liability area<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/mayer.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/mayer.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/mayer.html"> Labor</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/mayer.html"> White Collar Crime</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>M</B>ayer,  Brown  & Platt is one of the oldest and largest law firms in the United States. MB &P has a broad-based commercial practice,  with more than 200 lawyers concentrating in trial and appellate litigation.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Product Liability Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>Our product liability lawyers provide representation in all aspects of the field. We defend our clients with respect to personal injury,  property damage,  and breach of warranty claims at the trial and appellate levels,  and represent our clients' interests in connection with governmental agencies' investigations. We also advise in mediation and other alternative dispute resolution procedures. We have extensive experience in defeating punitive damages claims. We provide counsel and assistance in the formation of safety procedures and the drafting of warranties,  warnings,  and other product literature. Our representations involve products in a variety of industries,  including construction equipment,  forklift trucks,  punch presses,  printing presses,  piping,  and other small and large industrial and automotive machinery,  tools and equipment,  motor vehicles,  safety seats,  chemicals,  drugs,  medical devices,  lubricants,  toxic substances,  food products,  fire prevention and detection equipment,  office furniture products,  clothing,  nuclear energy,  and natural gas.<BR><P>Among others,  we have provided product liability advice and representation for ADT Security Systems,  Inc.,  BMW,  Boeing,  Brunswick Corporation,  Caterpillar Inc.,  Chevron Chemical Company,  Chrysler Corporation,  CPC International,  Dow Chemical Company,  Eaton Corporation,  Fisher-Price,  Ford Motor Company,  Fruit of the Loom,  Inc.,  General Electric Co.,  General Motors Corporation,  H.K. Porter Company,  Hoechst Celanese Corporation,  Honda Motor Company,  Navistar International,  Northern Illinois Gas Co.,  Oscar Mayer,  Perle Systems,  Inc.,  Pfizer Inc. (Shiley Incorporated),  the Product Liability Advisory Council,  Remington Arms,  Rockwell International Corporation,  Sears Roebuck  & Co.,  the Upjohn Company,  Vaughn  & Bushnell Manufacturing Co.,  Weldbend Corporation,  and Whirlpool Corporation.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Fern C. Bomchill</B> has defended product liability claims involving industrial equipment and tools,  chemicals,  lubricants,  hazardous substances,  and fire safety products,  and has coordinated the defense of claims asserted against a major manufacturer of smoke detectors on a nationwide basis. She also prepares and consults on warranties,  warnings,  and other product literature. University of Michigan,  B.A.,  1969; University of Chicago,  J.D.,  1972. Admitted in Illinois,  1972.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael R. Feagley</B> has defended product liability claims involving automobiles,  construction and earth-moving equipment,  forklift trucks,  industrial machinery,  and natural gas delivery systems. He is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers,  and he lectures on evidence and trial practice. Wesleyan University,  A.B.,  1967; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  1973. Admitted in Massachusetts and Illinois,  1973.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Andrew L. Frey</B>,  a former U.S. deputy solicitor general,  has handled numerous appeals to the U.S. Supreme Court and other appellate courts in products cases,  including several significant punitive damages cases. Swarthmore College,  B.A.,  1959; Columbia Law School,  LL.B.,  1962. Admitted in the District of Columbia,  1966; and New York,  1962.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Erika Z. Jones</B>,  a former chief counsel of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration,  represents vehicle and consumer product manufacturers on federal regulatory and preemption issues. Georgetown University,  B.A.,  1976,  J.D.,  1980. Admitted in the District of Columbia,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Hugh R. McCombs</B> has defended product liability claims involving asbestos,  chlorine inhalation,  automobiles,  industrial equipment,  and tools. He has acted as national coordinating counsel for a manufacturer of hand-striking tools and as Midwest regional coordinating counsel in connection with asbestos claims. Yale University,  B.A.,  1968; Boston University,  J.D.,  1973. Admitted in Illinois,  1975.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Thomas B. McNeill</B> has acted as national counsel for a major manufacturer of printing presses and has defended claims involving heavy construction equipment,  automobiles,  automatic garage doors,  trailer hitches,  and herbicides. He is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers. University of Notre Dame,  B.A.,  1956; Notre Dame Law School,  J.D.,  1958. Admitted in Illinois,  1958.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Neil M. Soltman</B> has defended product liability claims in the automotive product,  chemical,  plumbing,  plastic products,  and pharmaceutical and medical product implant industries in both federal and state courts and in individual and class actions. Temple University,  B.A.,  1971; Catholic University School of Law,  J.D.,  1975. Admitted in California,  1975.<BR>
