<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Product Liability</H2>
<H3>Paul,  Weiss,  Rifkind,  Wharton  & Garrison
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>New York:</B> 1285 Avenue of the Americas,  New York,  NY 10019<BR>
Tel 212-373-3000  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-757-3990<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> 1615 L Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20036<BR>
Tel 202-223-7300  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-223-7420<BR>
<B>Paris:</B> 199,  Boulevard Saint-Germain,  75007 Paris,  France<BR>
Tel 33-1-45-49-33-85  <B>*</B>  Fax 33-1-42-22-64-38<BR>
<B>Tokyo:</B> Akasaka Twin Tower,  17-22,  Akasaka 2-chome,  Minato-ku,  Tokyo 107,  Japan<BR>
Tel 81-3-3505-0291  <B>*</B>  Fax 81-3-3505-4540<BR>
<B>Hong Kong:</B> 3A Chater Road,  Central,  Hong Kong<BR>
Tel 85-2-536-9933  <B>*</B>  Fax 85-2-536-9622<BR>
<B>Beijing:</B> Scite Tower (Noble Tower),  Room 904,  22,  Jianguomenwai Dajie, <BR>
Beijing 100004,  People's Republic of China<BR>
Tel 86-1-512-3628  <B>*</B>  Fax 86-1-512-3631<BR>
<BR>
345 lawyers  <B>*</B>  12 lawyers in products liability<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/paul.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/paul.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/paul.html"> Corporate Securities</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/paul.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/paul.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WOFolder/paul.html"> Workout</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>P</B>aul,  Weiss has substantial experience and expertise in all phases of products liability litigation,  case management,  and counseling. The defense of products liability cases has been an important part of the firm's litigation practice since our representation of General Motors in the Corvair cases brought in the 1960s. In the 1970s,  we were involved in the defense of the most catastrophic grain elevator explosion in history. Subsequently,  we have represented manufacturers of asbestos products,  cigarettes,  medical products,  valves for nuclear power plants,  school buses,  and washing machines in products liability cases across the country. A half-dozen litigation partners have spent significant amounts of their time on products liability matters in recent years.
<P><BR><P>Paul,  Weiss litigators have special expertise in coordinating multijurisdiction litigation,  having acted as national coordinating counsel for one of the principal tobacco companies in smoking and health litigation.<BR><P>We have advised a major corporation in the coordination of its defense of asbestos cases across the country,  and negotiated its membership in the Asbestos Claims Facility.<BR>
<BR><P>The firm also represents a large manufacturer of medical and hospital equipment in a series of cases across the country brought by individuals who claim to have contracted AIDS as a result of their use of our client's products.<BR>
<BR><P>Paul,  Weiss litigators have been active in litigation assessing governmental responsibility for damages in products liability cases. In that regard we have been engaged in the prosecution of an asbestos manufacturer's claims against the U.S. government,  seeking reimbursement for liability incurred as a result of manufacturing products made for the government according to government specifications,  or as a result of the government's negligence in maintaining the conditions under which the products were used.<BR>
<BR><P>The firm has also taken an active role in the defense and prosecution of design defect cases that have not resulted in personal injuries. We served as counsel in the defense of two claims seeking $700 million in damages for the alleged negligent design of a valve for a nuclear power plant.<BR>
<BR><P>We have also successfully prosecuted products liability actions for governmental agencies arising out of defectively designed products. Most notably,  we obtained an $80 million jury verdict for the New York City Transit Authority for the defective design of subway cars,  as well as a $46 million settlement for the same client relating to a fleet of buses that it purchased.<BR>
<BR><P>We regularly defend and counsel our domestic and foreign clients on products liability matters,  ranging from gasoline pipe leaks to oil platform explosions,  helicopter crashes,  and other catastrophic circumstances giving rise to actual or potential liability.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Martin London</B> Extensive experience in products liability matters,  including litigation involving smoking and health,  and defective design of industrial products. Lecturer on trial advocacy at law schools and bar association CLE groups. Fellow,  American College of Trial Lawyers. Cornell University,  A.B.,  1955; New York University,  LL.B.,  1957; associate editor,  <I>New York University Law Review</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Max Gitter</B> Counsel to a major corporation on asbestos-related matters; visiting lecturer,  Yale Law School,  1986-1988. Harvard University,  B.A.,  1965; Yale University,  LL.B.,  1968.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Leslie Gordon Fagen</B> Court-appointed legal representative of future claimants in connection with the Manville Personal Injury Trust. Represented governmental and private entities in design defect litigations. Law clerk,  Judge Jack B. Weinstein,  U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of New York. Yale University,  B.A.,  1971; Columbia University,  J.D.,  1974.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jay Cohen</B> Experience in a variety of products liability matters,  most extensively in smoking and health litigations. Lecturer to industry groups on products liability issues. Law clerk,  Judge James Hunter III,  U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit. Cornell University,  A.B.,  1977; University of Chicago,  J.D.,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
