<HEAD>
<TITLE>Perkins Coie
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Product Liability</H2>
<H3>Perkins Coie
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Seattle:</B> 1201 Third Avenue,  Seattle,  WA 98101-3099<BR>
Tel 206-583-8888  <B>*</B>  Fax 206-583-8500<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Anchorage; Bellevue (Washington); Hong Kong; London;<BR>
Los Angeles; Olympia (Washington); Portland (Oregon); Spokane (Washington);<BR>
Taipei; Washington,  D.C.<BR>
<BR>
330 lawyers  <B>*</B>  25 lawyers practicing product liability law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>P</B>erkins Coie,  which is the Pacific Northwest's largest law firm,  has a national and an international product liability practice. In the last five years over 40 manufacturers from the United States and abroad have retained us to help them resolve product liability problems. Four of these manufacturers retain us as national trial counsel and we handle claims made against them nationwide. Perkins Coie's largest product liability client is The Boeing Co.,  for which the firm handles all aviation product liability claims and litigation worldwide.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Experience and Clients</H3></CENTER>

<P>In their product liability practice,  Perkins Coie lawyers investigate,  evaluate,  and litigate product liability claims brought against clients; represent clients before government agencies; counsel clients on domestic and international product liability issues; conduct product liability workshops and exposure audits; and help clients write,  implement,  and evaluate product manuals,  warranties,  and disclaimers.<BR><P>Recent product liability clients of Perkins Coie have included AlliedSignal Inc.,  AMVAC Chemical Corporation,  AT &T Global Information Solutions,  AT &T Wireless Services Inc.,  Beech Aircraft Corp.,  The Boeing Co.,  Borden,  Inc.,  Bristol-Myers Squibb Co.,  Coleman Co. Inc.,  Chrysler Corporation,  John Deere  & Co.,  de Havilland Inc.,  Dow Chemical Co.,  ECI Building Components,  GAF Corp.,  General Electric Canada Inc.,  General Electric Corp.,  General Motors Corp.,  Genie Industries,  W.R. Grace  & Co.,  Hyundai Heavy Industries,  IBM,  Ingersoll-Rand,  IPTN North America Inc.,  Isuzu Motors America Inc.,  Louisiana Pacific Corp.,  MAFCO Consolidated,  Martin-Baker Aircraft Co.,  Matsushita Electric Co.,  Maytag Corp.,  Mobil Chemical Co.,  Nintendo of America Inc.,  O'Brien International,  Inc.,  Owens-Corning Fiberglas Corp.,  Precision Aerospace Corp.,  SpaceLabs Medical Inc.,  Twin Commander Aircraft Corp.,  U-Haul Corporation,  United Parcel Service,  Union Carbide Corp.,  Upjohn Co,  and Zausner Foods.<BR>
<BR><P>Perkins Coie publishes <I>Product Liability in the United States: A Primer for Manufacturers and Their Employees</I>. A copy in English or Japanese may be received free by any manufacturer by written request to Perkins Coie.<BR>
<BR><P>Members of Perkins Coie's product liability practice group include:<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Keith Gerrard</B> (<I>Seattle; 206-583-8462</I>) Mr. Gerrard is the senior product liability litigator in the firm. He has been in charge of The Boeing Co.'s product liability litigation for 22 years. He is a director of the Products Liability Advisory Council and a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers. He has lectured throughout the United States on product liability subjects and each year conducts product liability workshops for Perkins Coie and the National Association of Manufacturers. Harvard University,  A.B.,  LL.B.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>George A. Manfredi</B> (<I>Los Angeles; 310-788-3230</I>) Mr. Manfredi heads aviation and product litigation in the Los Angeles office. He has extensive trial experience in state and federal courts,  including a major air crash case for USAir and several asbestos-in-building cases for W.R. Grace  & Co. Brown University,  A.B.; New York University,  J.D.; <I>New York University Law Review</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John D. Dillow</B> (<I>Seattle; 206-583-8476</I>) Mr. Dillow has more than 23 years of litigation experience. He has a broad product liability and toxic torts practice that involves aviation,  automotive,  and industrial products. Mr. Dillow is national coordinating counsel for product liability claims against the largest manufacturer of personnel lifts. University of Washington,  B.S.; Duke University,  J.D.; Order of the Coif; <I>Duke Law Journal</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Steven S. Bell</B> (<I>Seattle; 206-583-8493</I>) Mr. Bell has more than 20 years of litigation experience,  with a primary focus on product liability. He has tried cases for aircraft,  chemical,  asbestos,  and ejection seat manufacturers,  among others. Mr. Bell also has significant international arbitration experience. University of Washington,  B.A.; University of California at Berkeley,  J.D.; Order of the Coif; <I>California Law Review</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Richard C. Coyle</B> (<I>Seattle; 206-583-8418</I>) Mr. Coyle has practiced product liability law for more than 18 years. He has tried product liability cases involving military,  commercial,  and general aviation; adhesives; and cranes. Cornell University,  A.B.; Columbia University,  J.D.; <I>Columbia Law Review</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Thomas J. McLaughlin</B> (<I>Seattle; 206-583-8483</I>) Mr. McLaughlin is a former Boeing Co. aeronautical engineer and has practiced product liability law for more than 18 years. He has tried cases for commercial and general aviation manufacturers and airlines. Mr. McLaughlin also has worked to achieve statutory product liability reform in Washington state,  and has written and lectured extensively on this subject. The Ohio State University,  B.A.A.E.,  M.S.; Harvard University,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert L. Deitz</B> (<I>Washington; 202-434-1604</I>) A former law clerk to U.S. Supreme Court Justice Byron White,  Mr. Deitz has 17 years of experience in litigating at both the trial and appellate levels in federal and state courts. He has been involved in toxic tort and product liability litigation. Middlebury College,  B.A.; Princeton University,  M.P.A.; Harvard University,  J.D.; <I>Harvard Law Review</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Clark R. Nichols</B> (<I>Anchorage and Seattle; 206-583-8731</I>) Mr. Nichols has conducted an aviation practice in Anchorage and Seattle since joining the firm in 1978. He has tried a number of aviation cases in Alaska. U.S. Air Force Academy,  B.S.; University of California at Los Angeles,  M.S.; Wright State University,  M.B.A.; University of Texas,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Paul T. Fortino</B> (<I>Portland; 503-727-2014</I>) Mr. Fortino came to the firm in 1980 after service as a U.S. Navy JAG officer. His product liability practice includes asbestos,  aviation,  chemical products,  and personnel- and material-lifting devices. University of Michigan,  B.B.A.; University of Notre Dame,  J.D.; <I>Notre Dame Lawyer</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Christopher W. Angius</B> (<I>Portland; 503-727-2037</I>) Mr. Angius has 13 years of litigation experience. He has a broad product liability practice that involves industrial products,  automotive,  aviation,  chemicals,  and food products. He is a member of the Product Liability Advisory Council. Columbia University,  A.B.; Harvard University,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>David T. Biderman</B> (<I>Los Angeles; 310-788-3220</I>) Mr. Biderman has practiced product liability law for a dozen years,  representing manufacturers of automobiles,  aircraft,  and chemical and industrial products. Emory University,  B.A.; University of Virginia,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Rex C. Browning</B> (<I>Seattle; 206-583-8553</I>) Mr. Browning has a broad product liability practice involving aviation,  medical devices,  automotive,  and other industrial and consumer products. Harvard University,  A.B.; University of Chicago,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Bruce D. Campbell</B> (<I>Seattle; 206-583-8414</I>) Mr. Campbell's product liability practice includes asbestos,  aviation,  and chemical products. University of Washington,  B.A.; Willamette University,  J.D.; <I>Willamette Law Journal</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John M. Devaney</B> (<I>Washington,  D.C.; 202-434-1624</I>) Mr. Devaney has ten years of litigation experience,  including four years at the U.S. Department of Justice before he joined Perkins Coie. His experience in the product liability area has focused on aviation and industrial products. Boston College,  B.A.; Catholic University,  J.D.; <I>Catholic University Law Review</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Mary Rose Hughes</B> (<I>Washington,  D.C.; 202-434-1606</I>) Ms. Hughes has practiced product liability law in Seattle and in Washington,  D.C. She has more than 11 years of experience in aviation and product liability litigation. Georgetown University,  B.S.; Catholic University,  J.D.; <I>Catholic University Law Review</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Ronald A. McIntire</B> (<I>Los Angeles; 310-788-3277</I>) Mr. McIntire's product liability practice includes air crash,  asbestos in buildings,  and construction equipment litigation. Dartmouth College,  B.A.; University of California at Los Angeles,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>J. Christian Moller</B> (<I>Seattle; 206-583-8634</I>) Mr. Moller has litigated suits involving a variety of products,  including propulsion equipment,  vending machines,  and cranes. He also regularly advises clients on product liability prevention and on dealing with federal and state regulatory agencies. His work has involved products such as toys,  engines,  commercial adhesives,  chemicals,  and food products. Harvard University,  A.B.; Georgetown University,  J.D.; <I>Georgetown Law Journal</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Sherilyn C. Peterson</B> (<I>Bellevue; 206-453-7332</I>) Ms. Peterson has practiced product liability law for a dozen years. Her practice has included commercial and general aviation,  as well as nonaviation product cases and counseling involving manufacturers of conveyors,  electrical turbines,  and medical devices. Northwestern University,  B.A.,  J.D.; <I>Northwestern University Law Review</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>James P. Savitt</B> (<I>Bellevue; 206-453-7308</I>) Mr. Savitt's experience in product liability matters includes litigation and counseling concerning asbestos in buildings,  airborne toxins,  electromagnetic fields,  and high-tech medical devices. Cornell University,  B.A.; Georgetown University,  J.D.; <I>Georgetown Law Journal</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Scott F. Seablom</B> (<I>Seattle; 206-583-8636</I>) Mr. Seablom has ten years of experience in product liability practice,  including both trial work and product liability-related counseling. His practice involves a variety of products (aircraft,  computer equipment,  and recreational products such as BB guns and divers' watches). George Washington University,  B.A.; University of Virginia,  J.D.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>V. L. Woolston</B> (<I>Seattle; 206-583-8514</I>) Mr. Woolston has practiced product liability law for more than 14 years. His experience includes toxic chemical,  nonionizing radiation,  and medical device cases,  as well as aviation litigation. Amherst College,  B.A.; Duke University,  J.D.<BR>
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
