<HEAD>
<TITLE>Schnader Harrison Segal & Lewis
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Product Liability</H2>
<H3>Schnader Harrison Segal & Lewis
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Philadelphia:</B> 1600 Market Street,  Philadelphia,  PA 19103<BR>
Tel 215-751-2000  <B>*</B>  Fax 215-751-2205<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> New York; Washington,  D.C.; Atlanta; Pittsburgh,  Harrisburg,  Norristown and Washington (Pennsylvania); Cherry Hill (New Jersey)*<BR>
<BR>
200 lawyers  <B>*</B>  30 lawyers concentrating in product liability law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/schnader.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/schnader.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/schnader.html"> Labor</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>L</B>itigation,  on both a national and international scale,  has traditionally been the largest area of practice at Schnader Harrison,  which has 80 litigators,  many of whom have experience in the product liability area. The firm specializes in developing sophisticated factual and expert defenses to product liability claims. Its attorneys have hands-on successful experience obtaining excellent results for product liability clients both at trial and through alternative dispute resolutions.
<P><BR><P>Within the past decade,  the firm has defended product liability claims involving machinery (including overhead cranes,  forklifts,  propane heaters,  punch presses,  tractors,  incinerators and lawn mowers),  bicycles,  bottles,  aircraft,  handguns,  asbestos,  pesticides,  insecticides,  tires,  tobacco,  weight loss programs,  food products,  chemicals,  pharmaceuticals,  and medical devices. Lawyers in the Product Liability Group have also coordinated and defended over 500 lawsuits brought in over 35 states against a company and its franchisees. The successful defense included trials in Virginia,  New York,  Alabama,  and Oregon.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Margaret S. Woodruff</B>,  chair of the Product Liability Group,  served as national coordinator and trial counsel for several hundred lawsuits throughout the United States involving personal injury claims asserted against a company and its franchisees. She worked extensively with experts and medical researchers to develop a successful defense and,  with firm member Philip G. Kircher,  served as trial counsel in a case selected by <I>The National Law Journal</I> as one of the top 15 defense verdicts for 1992. In addition,  she has represented manufacturers of pharmaceuticals,  medical devices,  chemicals,  incinerators,  computer chips,  and other products. She is the coauthor of <I>The Expert Witness: Law and Practice</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Dennis R. Suplee</B>,  a fellow of the International Academy of Trial Lawyers,  has handled product liability claims for,  among others,  a French manufacturer of Brie cheese,  a German manufacturer of overhead cranes,  and an American manufacturer of a gearshift. He is the coauthor of <I>The Expert Witness: Law and Practice</I> and <I>The Deposition Handbook: Strategies,  Tactics and Mechanics</I>.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Louis R. Moffa,  Jr.</B>,  New Jersey managing partner.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Ralph G. Wellington</B> heads the Aviation Litigation Group. Wellington has been the lead defense counsel in multiple lawsuits involving claims that aircraft or aircraft parts were defective,  and has also represented firearms manufacturers,  pharmaceutical companies,  and manufacturers of industrial machinery,  including punch presses. The Aviation Litigation Group also includes <B>J. Denny Shupe</B>,  who brings his experience as a fighter pilot in the U.S. Air Force Reserve to these matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Lisa R. Savitt</B>,  practicing in the New York and Philadelphia offices,  handles aircraft and helicopter product liability claims,  representing insurers and their insureds,  including domestic and foreign manufacturers and airlines. She is the president of the International Aviation Women's Association,  has practiced in London,  and began her aviation career with the FAA.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gerard J. St. John</B>,  co-chair of the firm's Litigation Department,  has defended claims involving at least 20 different types of products,  including bicycles,  lawn mowers,  snow throwers,  tires,  industrial machines,  and asbestos-containing products.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>George E. Yokitis</B> and <B>Mindy J. Shreve</B> practice in the firm's Pittsburgh office. They have defended product liability suits involving tires,  bottles,  rim assemblies,  gasoline containers,  uranium,  pesticides,  insecticides,  forklifts,  tractors,  and school buses.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Philip G. Kircher</B> worked with Ms. Woodruff for two years on the national coordination and defense of several hundred lawsuits involving a weight-loss program. Mr. Kircher has also defended claims involving products as diverse as medical devices,  kerosene,  telephone equipment,  and Mace.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Arlin M. Adams</B>,  who retired in 1987 from the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit,  and <B>Deena Jo Schneider</B> have represented several tobacco companies in matters including the landmark Third Circuit decision of <I>Haines </I>v.<I> Liggett</I>. Judge Adams has also counseled numerous manufacturers with respect to appropriate strategies for trials and appeals.<BR>
<BR>
