<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Smith Helms Mulliss  & Moore,   L.L.P.</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL><CENTER><H2>Product Liability</H2><H3>Smith Helms Mulliss  & Moore,   L.L.P.</H3></CENTER><CENTER>Smith Helms Mulliss  & Moore,   L.L.P.<BR>Greensboro:</B> 300 North Greene Street,   Suite 1400,   Post Office Box 21927,  <BR>Greensboro,   NC 27420<BR>Tel 910-378-5200  <B>*</B>  Fax 910-379-9558<BR><B>Other offices:</B> Charlotte and Raleigh (North Carolina)<BR><BR>150 lawyers  <B>*</B>  20 lawyers concentrating in product liability<BR></CENTER><P><P><BR><P><BR><P><B>S</B>mith Helms Mulliss   & Moore is a North Carolina law firm with a statewide,   regional,   and national product liability practice. The firm's clients include international,   national,   regional,   and local businesses; industrial firms; and insurance companies. Members of the firm are active in numerous bar and professional organizations,   and regularly try cases in state and federal court.<BR><P><BR><CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>The Firm's Experience</H3></CENTER><P>Smith Helms regularly provides statewide,   regional,   and national representation for manufacturers and sellers of a variety of products,   including drug and medical devices,   automobiles,   chemicals,   household products,   and industrial equipment. We represent manufacturers of various medical devices,   orthopedic devices,   and other implants,   as well as numerous pharmaceutical and medical products companies,   including Pfizer Inc.,   Becton Dickinson   & Company,   and Bristol-Myers Squibb.<BR>The firm also has an extensive background in representing chemical companies in complex litigation. For example,   we serve as national coordinating counsel for Monsanto Company,   and represent numerous other chemical clients in toxic tort and related product liability litigation.<BR><BR>We regularly counsel foreign and domestic manufacturers and distributors of automobiles,   ATVs,   and other motor vehicles. We also handle the defense of cases involving foods,   lawn mowers,   tires,   and various other products.<BR><BR><BR><UL><BR><LI><B>E. Osborne Ayscue,   Jr.</B> is a regent and the secretary of the American College of Trial Lawyers and a past president of the North Carolina Bar Association. He has defended manufacturers of automobiles,   bicycles,   lawn mowers,   and other products.<BR><BR><LI><B>Jonathan A. Berkelhammer</B> is actively defending a number of toxic tort matters for agricultural products companies and has been involved in the defense of a number of other products including motor vehicles,   presses,   and industrial equipment. He is active in the American Bar Association's Products Liability Committee.<BR><BR><LI><B>J. Donald Cowan</B> has tried numerous product liability cases,   including toxic torts,   property damage claims arising from use of allegedly contaminated agricultural products,   and personal injury matters. He is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers,   a former president of the North Carolina Bar Association,   and a member of the Product Liability Advisory Council.<BR><BR><LI><B>Richard W. Ellis</B> has defended numerous manufacturers of pharmaceuticals and medical products. He actively represents Bristol-Myers Squibb and Becton Dickinson   & Company,   among others. He is a member of the Defense Research Institute and the North Carolina Association of Defense Attorneys.<BR><BR><LI><B>Douglas W. Ey,   Jr.</B> is national coordinating counsel for an international insurance company. He regularly defends manufacturers of drugs and medical devices and services.<BR><BR><LI><B>Bynum M. Hunter</B> is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers and the International Association of Defense Counsel. He has defended manufacturers of tires,   industrial equipment,   airplanes,   automobiles,   and other products.<BR><BR><LI><B>David M. Moore II</B> serves as national counsel for Monsanto Company in litigation,   handling claims for personal injury,   medical monitoring,   enhanced risk of disease,   and fear of disease alleged to have resulted from exposure to various chlorinated compounds. He served as co-chair of the 1992 ABA National Institute on Toxic Torts,   and as chair of the Scientific Liaison Subcommittee of the Toxic and Hazardous Substances and Environmental Law Committee.<BR><BR><LI><B>Catherine E. Thompson</B> frequently represents manufacturers and distributors of automobiles,   as well as other product manufacturers. She is the immediate past president of the Mecklenburg County Bar Association and a permanent member of the Fourth Circuit Judicial Conference.<BR><BR><LI><B>William L. Young</B> has tried many product liability cases. He frequently represents manufacturers in litigation involving pharmaceuticals,   toxic tort claims,   and implantable products. He is a member of the Defense Research Institute.</UL></UL></BODY></HTML>
