<HEAD>
<TITLE>Spriggs  & Hollingsworth
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>Product Liability</H2>
<H3>Spriggs  & Hollingsworth
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington:</B> 1350 I Street,  N.W.,  Ninth Floor,  Washington,  DC 20005<BR>
Tel 202-898-5800  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-682-1639<BR>
<BR>
35 lawyers  <B>*</B>  20 lawyers concentrating in product liability defense and toxic tort litigation<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/spriggs.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/spriggs.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95WCCFolder/spriggs.html"> White Collar Crime</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>T</B>he firm represents manufacturers,  suppliers,  premises owners and other corporations in toxic tort and products liability litigation involving both personal injury and property damage claims. We serve as national coordinating trial counsel for the defense of such cases where multiple litigations are involved. With the help of contacts from our national network of local counsel and experts,  we are able to introduce our clients' most sophisticated and technical defenses into all parts of the country.
<P><BR><P>The firm defends individual lawsuits,  mass tort claims,  and class actions alleging products liability in connection with product design,  manufacture,  and warnings; chemical contamination; radiation contamination; and waste disposal. Because we are a litigation firm,  we handle cases from the earliest pre-trial and investigative stages through trial and through resolution on appeal. These cases involve asbestos-containing products,  hazardous wastes,  military hardware,  `sick buildings, ' chlorinated and other synthetic pesticides,  solvents,  detergents,  radioactive materials,  herbicides,  petroleum byproducts,  feedstocks and derivatives,  and various other chemicals and chemical products. We defend with a science-based motions and trial practice,  especially where plaintiffs allege that an occupational,  environmental,  or residential `exposure' (from air,  property or groundwater contamination) caused chronic disease or subclinical injury. We have litigated several of the most significant post-<I>Daubert</I> toxics cases,  and we attack junk science proponents outside the mainstream of recognized disciplines in their willingness to associate injury or `contamination' with exposure even to minuscule amounts of alleged toxins. The firm defends against allegations of chemical carcinogenicity,  leukemogenicity,  immunogenicity,  and latent toxicity.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Joe G. Hollingsworth</B> Emphasizes trial and appellate work in toxic tort,  toxic and pharmaceutical products liability,  and environmental law. As national trial counsel in the defense of myriad chemical and chemical product exposure claims,  he defends against allegations of toxic exposure and injury,  property damage,  groundwater contamination,  and toxic air emissions. Experience in mass tort,  class action,  and multijurisdiction litigation.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Donald W. Fowler</B> Experience in toxic tort ligation at both the trial and appellate levels.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Edward J. Beder,  Jr.</B> Involved in complex,  multiparty litigation covering a wide range of subjects. His practice has focused on the defense of toxic tort personal injury and property damage suits. He has been involved in the national coordination of complex litigation and in the development and implementation through numerous local counsel of common defenses,  especially as related to medical and scientific issues.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Bruce J. Berger</B> Practices in toxic tort litigation including medical and scientific issues.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Patrick R. Harkins</B> Practices primarily in the field of products liability.He has experience in defense of asbestos-related claims.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Katherine R. Latimer</B> Emphasizes toxic tort and products liability trial and appellate work involving pesticides,  solvents,  detergents,  and chemical compounds.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Bonnie J. Semilof</B> Emphasizes toxic tort trial work involving chlorinated and other synthetic pesticides and other chemical exposure matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Frank Leone,  Jr.</B> Emphasizes toxic torts,  environmental litigation,  and asbestos property damage cases.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</UL>


</UL></BODY>
