<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>S</B>tites  & Harbison traces its origins in Louisville to 1832,  when it was founded by Abraham Lincoln's future attorney general. The firm takes pride in its ability to defend through trial major product liability,  toxic tort,  and personal injury lawsuits. At the same time,  Stites  & Harbison is involved in preventive law activities aimed at reducing the incidence of product-related accidents,  preventing litigation,  and minimizing product liability costs.
<P><BR><P>The firm is experienced in handling serial product liability litigation on national and regional levels. These representations include Owens-Illinois,  Inc.,  Georgia Pacific,  Johns-Manville,  and other asbestos manufacturers in both personal injury and property damage cases; Brown-Forman in fetal aLCohol syndrome claims; Ciba-Geigy in benzidine dye lawsuits; Physio-Control Corporation in defibrillator litigation; Sofamor Danek Medical,  Inc. in medical devices; and Emerson Electric Co. in ladders and power tools. Other representative clients include Yamaha Motor Corp.,  General Motors,  Pfizer,  Procter  & Gamble,  Textron,  Inc.,  Corning,  Inc.,  American Suzuki Motor Corp.,  Sherwin-Williams Co.,  Blount,  Inc.,  Ophthalmic Mutual Insurance Co.,  Ingersoll-Rand,  O. F. Mossberg and Sons,  Playtex Family Products,  Vincenzo Bernardelli SPA,  Dornier System GmbH,  American Yard Products,  John Deere Insurance Co.,  and a variety of medical device manufacturers insured through MEDMARC.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Lively M. Wilson</B> (<I>Louisville</I>) is the firm's senior partner in products liability. He was the 1994-1995 president of the American College of Trial Lawyers and is an experienced national trial attorney in toxic tort litigation. Western Kentucky University,  B.A.,  1948; Harvard Law School,  LL.B.,  1951.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Charles J. (Mike) Cronan IV</B> (<I>Louisville</I>) is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers with experience in fire litigation,  firearms,  and medical devices. Mike is also the firm's managing partner. Wesleyan University,  B.A.,  1967; University of Louisville School of Law,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1970.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>John M. Famularo</B> (<I>Lexington</I>) is a former state court judge and an active trial lawyer experienced in automobile litigation and heavy machinery. He is also a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers. Loyola University,  New Orleans,  A.B.,  1968; University of Kentucky College of Law,  J.D.,  1971.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>W. Kennedy Simpson</B> (<I>Louisville</I>) is a contributing author to DRI's <I>Product Liability Defenses: A State by State Compendium</I> (1992) and the <I>Tort  & Insurance Journal</I>. Well-versed in pharmaceuticals and medical devices,  Kennedy is also a member of the steering committee for DRI's Drug and Device Committee. Washington  & Lee University,  B.A.,  1975; University of Kentucky College of Law,  J.D.,  1978.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert M. Connolly</B> (<I>Louisville</I>) is experienced in industrial equipment and consumer products and served on the discovery subcommittee of the ABA's Products Liability Committee. Dartmouth College,  B.A.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1977; Washington  & Lee University School of Law,  J.D.,  1980.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John L. Tate</B> (<I>Louisville</I>) chairs the firm's Products Liability Service Group,  is a contributing editor to the <I>Product Liability Desk Reference</I>,  and is on the editorial board for <I>Product Liability Law  & Strategy</I>. He is national trial counsel for Physio-Control Corporation and regional trial counsel for Emerson Electric Co. Wake Forest University,  B.A.,  1969; University of Louisville,  M.A.,  1971; University of Louisville School of Law,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>J. Clarke Keller</B> (<I>Lexington</I>) is a former U.S. Air Force helicopter pilot experienced in the defense of machinery and farm implements. University of Notre Dame,  B.B.A.,  with honors,  1973; University of Kentucky College of Law,  J.D.,  with high distinction,  1984.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Byron N. Miller</B> (<I>Louisville</I>) is a former defense attorney with the U.S. Army's Judge Advocate General's Corps and knowledgeable in the defense of medical and industrial products. University of South Dakota,  B.S.,  1977; University of South Dakota,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Rebecca F. Schupbach</B> (<I>Louisville</I>) is an experienced toxic tort trial attorney with five years as in-house counsel charged with product liability litigation management. University of Kentucky,  B.A.,  with highest distinction,  1973; University of Kentucky School of Law,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Carol Dan Browning</B> (<I>Louisville</I>) is a former civil engineer experienced in fire litigation and aviation claims. University of Kentucky,  B.S.C.E.,  1982; University of Louisville School of Law,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1987.<BR>
