<HEAD>
<TITLE>Bierman,  Shohat,  Loewy, Perry  & Klein,  P.A.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>White Collar Crime</H2>
<H3>Bierman,  Shohat,  Loewy, Perry  & Klein,  P.A.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Miami:</B> 800 Brickell Avenue,  Miami,  FL 33131-2944<BR>
Tel 305-358-7000  <B>*</B>  Fax 305-358-4010<BR>
<BR>
5 lawyers  <B>*</B>  All lawyers in white collar crime practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>B</B>ierman,  Shohat,  Loewy,  Perry  & Klein,  P.A.,  is a boutique law firm with an emphasis on complex federal criminal,  civil RICO,  forfeitures,  criminal tax,  and international extradition matters. The firm's three senior partners have been consistently listed in <I>The Best Lawyers in America</I>. The firm is fully bilingual in Spanish.<BR><BR><UL><LI><B>Donald I. Bierman</B> has over 30 years of experience in representing corporations,  partnerships and individuals who are the subject of either investigations or charges involving tax,  RICO,  antitrust,  and other white collar violations. This representation includes investigatory preparation,  grand jury representation,  conferences with appropriate prosecutorial authorities and full-scale jury and nonjury trials,  as well as full appellate representation. Mr. Bierman has developed an expertise in foreign export,  embargo,  and customs violations. In addition,  he has conducted in-house investigations for corporate clients. Mr. Bierman has represented numerous banking institutions and individuals in forfeiture and seizure cases,  recovering large amounts of money and property for innocent third parties in both formal and informal intervention with government authorities.<BR>
<BR><P>Prior to forming a firm in 1972,  Mr. Bierman served with the U.S. Department of Justice as a criminal appellate attorney; as an assistant U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia and the Southern District of Florida; and as special counsel to the Dade County Grand Jury. Mr. Bierman has also served as a special master in complex federal litigation by appointment of various federal judges. Admitted in Florida,  1965; the District of Columbia,  1966; and the U.S. Supreme Court.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Edward R. Shohat</B> has been in the private practice of criminal defense for over 24 years. Mr. Shohat has defended some of the nation's highest-profile criminal cases involving a variety of serious criminal charges with successful results and acquittals,  including mail and wire fraud; insurance fraud; tax; bribery; Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (achieving an acquittal for the former chairman of the Florida Democratic Party); money laundering; conspiracy; RICO (both civil and criminal); and civil and criminal forfeiture cases. He has successfully handled the jury trial defense of numerous lawyers in criminal and bar disciplinary matters. He is experienced in complex commercial and criminal litigation and trials,  including wiretap suppression issues,  and complex financial crimes involving SEC investigations and receiverships. He has been lead counsel in jury trials lasting four months,  seven-and-a-half months,  and eleven months,  among others. He has lectured extensively on criminal law issues. Member,  National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers; member and current vice-president and fellow,  American Board of Criminal Lawyers; and member and former president,  Florida Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers. University of Miami,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1972. Admitted in Florida and before various federal district and appellate courts and the U. S. Supreme Court.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Theodore Klein</B> has over 30 years of experience in the practice of white collar criminal law,  including RICO,  health care violations,  money laundering,  fraud,  banking,  and forfeitures. He has represented individuals and corporate entities in a variety of investigations before grand juries,  federal and state administrative agencies and boards,  and in quasi-trial and trial proceedings in all courts.<BR>
<BR><P>Mr. Klein served as an assistant U.S. attorney before entering into private practice. He has been an adjunct professor at the University of Miami School of Law for 25 years. He is a past president of the Florida Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers,  the local chapter of the Federal Bar Association,  and served for six years on the Board of Governors of the Florida Bar. He has appeared in courts at every level in the nation,  including the U.S. Supreme Court,  where he argued and won a case involving airport drug courier profile searches. He is often appointed as a special master in hotly contested federal and state litigation,  and also serves as a mediator in federal and state civil cases. He also represents individuals in bar disciplinary matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Ira N. Loewy</B> is a graduate of New York University Law School. A former Florida assistant attorney general and assistant state attorney for Dade County,  Florida,  he served as deputy chief assistant state attorney to Janet Reno,  where he supervised the Organized Crime/Public Corruption,  Economic Crimes and Narcotics Divisions. Since going into private practice in 1984,  Mr. Loewy has successfully represented white collar clients in both state and federal criminal prosecutions with a specialty in appeals and has handled a large number of both state and federal forfeiture matters.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Pamela I. Perry</B> is a graduate of the University of Miami School of Law,  where she is now an adjunct professor in the area of federal criminal law. Ms. Perry has successfully represented lawyers,  medical professionals,  and bank officers in criminal prosecutions,  appeals,  disciplinary proceedings,  and civil RICO and extradition matters.<BR>
<BR><P>Ms. Perry is a member of numerous bar organizations and a member of the Board of Directors of the Florida Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers and the University of Miami Law Alumni Association. She has authored a chapter on jury selection in high-profile cases in <I>Jury Work</I>,  the seminal treatise in the area.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
