<TITLE>Brown,  Rudnick,  Freed & Gesmer
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>White Collar Crime</H2>
<H3>Brown,  Rudnick,  Freed & Gesmer
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Boston:</B> One Financial Center,  Boston,  MA 02111<BR>
Tel 617-330-9000  <B>*</B>  Fax 617-439-3278<BR>
<B>Providence:</B> One Old Stone Square,  Providence,  RI 02903<BR>
Tel 401-276-2600  <B>*</B>  Fax 401-276-2601<BR>
<B>Hartford:</B> CityPlace I,  Hartford,  CT 06103-3402<BR>
Tel 203-525-8008  <B>*</B>  Fax 203-525-8212<BR>
<BR>
117 lawyers  <B>*</B>  7 lawyers in white collar crime practices<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>B</B>rown,  Rudnick,  Freed  & Gesmer is a full-service regional law firm. The Brown Rudnick model for client service replaces the traditional method of having lawyers define their practice by a substantive legal field. Our emphasis is to have our lawyers become knowledgeable about,  and practice in,  particular client industries (such as banking or health care) or client problem areas (such as environmental compliance,  insurance coverage recovery,  securitization,  affordable housing,  and zoning and land use).
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Business Investigations and Criminal Defense</H3></CENTER>

<P>The Business Investigations and Criminal Defense Group has responded to the increasingly complex regulation and criminalization of federal and state industry by forming a team approach to client service. Each complex matter is staffed both by a seasoned industry or service-area practitioner (such as a tax,  health care,  banking,  or environmental lawyer),  as well as by an experienced litigator (to provide investigative and defense skills). By doing so,  we immediately provide the in-depth industry knowledge and strategic skills necessary to best represent our clients. As a regional firm,  we are able to provide this service throughout New England.<BR><BR><P>Our recent activities include representation of: a manufacturer in connection with a criminal antitrust investigation conducted by the Department of Justice involving businesses throughout the United States; a Boston teaching hospital in connection with an investigation into alleged violations of the Medicare anti-kickback statute; a Massachusetts teaching hospital in connection with an investigation into billing practices for non-FDA approved medical devices,  and a well-known nonprofit corporation being investigated for violations of the Federal Clean Air Act.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Thomas M. Sobol</B>,  team leader for the Business Investigation and Criminal Defense Group,  is a litigator who has represented corporate and individual clients in a wide variety of criminal and administrative investigations concerning antitrust,  health care,  and environmental violations and institutional fraud. Mr. Sobol was appointed to the Federal Criminal Justice Act panel for Massachusetts in 1993. Clark University,  B.A.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1980; Phi Beta Kappa; Boston University School of Law,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1983. Admitted in Massachusetts and Rhode Island.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Douglas A. Cohen</B> is chair of the Environment and Resource Practice Group and resides in our Hartford office. For more than 13 years,  Mr. Cohen has practiced exclusively in the environmental field,  first at the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency,  then at the U.S. Department of Justice,  and most recently in private practice. Mr. Cohen is proficient in all areas of environmental law,  including environmental compliance investigations and counseling officers and directors on avoiding civil and criminal violations. State University of New York at Buffalo,  B.A.,  1977; National Law Center of the George Washington University,  J.D.,  1980. Admitted in Connecticut and the District of Columbia.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Lawrence B. Litwak</B> has a seasoned practice counseling health care businesses,  teaching and community hospitals,  physician groups and other providers in a variety of business transactions. Since the enactment of OBRA,  Mr. Litwak has advised and represented providers in connection with fraud and abuse matters. Princeton University,  A.B.,  1970; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1973. Admitted in Massachusetts.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jeffery M. Alexander</B> chairs the Health Care Practice Group for Rhode Island. For over a dozen years,  Mr. Alexander has assisted clients in all aspects of health care law,  including Medicare/Medicaid fraud and abuse issues for hospitals,  physicians,  durable medical equipment suppliers and other providers. Boston University,  B.S.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1977; Georgetown University Law Center,  J.D.,  1980. Admitted in Massachusetts,  Rhode Island,  and Florida.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Mark S. Baldwin</B> is the firm's senior litigator residing in Hartford. Mr. Baldwin has an extensive background defending claims against officers and directors of corporations and financial institutions. University of Michigan,  A.B.,  1983; Boston University School of Law,  J.D.,  1986. Admitted in Connecticut.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael Paris</B> is an associate who has handled criminal matters such as tax evasion,  bank bribery and insurance fraud. Mr. Paris regularly accepts court appointments,  <I>pro bono publico</I>,  on behalf of indigent criminal defendants. The American University,  B.S.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1986; Northeastern University School of Law,  J.D.,  1990. Admitted in Massachusetts.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Kathleen E. Cross</B> is an associate litigator. She has experience in the criminal and civil defense of antitrust matters. Ms. Cross clerked from 1990 to 1992 for Judge David S. Nelson of the U.S. District Court for the District of Massachusetts. Williams College,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1982; Northeastern University School of Law,  J.D.,  1990. Admitted in Massachusetts.
