<HEAD>
<TITLE>Davis Polk  & Wardwell
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>White Collar Crime</H2>
<H3>Davis Polk  & Wardwell
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>New York:</B> 450 Lexington Avenue,  New York,  NY 10017<BR>
Tel 212-450-4000  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-450-4800<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Frankfurt,  London,  Paris,  Tokyo,  Hong Kong,  Washington,  D.C.<BR>
<BR>
452 lawyers  <B>*</B>  15 lawyers practicing criminal law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>S</B>ince its founding in New York in 1849,  Davis Polk  & Wardwell has devoted its practice to advising clients with respect to complex civil and criminal litigation,  and corporate and tax problems.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Overview of the Practice Area</H3></CENTER>

<P>Davis Polk has a unique history of representing institutions and individuals in complex criminal cases. Over the years,  many of the firm's top litigators have held governmental positions as prosecutors or as enforcement officials,  and these experiences have provided the firm with significant expertise in matters involving questions of criminal liability. As a consequence,  we routinely advise and represent clients in the establishment and maintenance of corporate compliance programs,  internal investigations,  grand jury investigations,  and trials involving allegations of securities fraud,  bank fraud,  antitrust violations,  insider trading,  environmental crime,  money laundering,  bribery,  and violations of the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act. Many of the criminal cases we handle,  moreover,  involve `parallel proceedings.' Davis Polk's concurrent expertise in the areas of white collar crime,  complex civil litigation,  and regulatory enforcement make the firm particularly suited to the defense of such multifaceted cases.<BR><BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Experience and Clients</H3></CENTER>
<BR><BR><P>Davis Polk has been involved in some of the most complicated white collar cases of our time. The following is a partial list of the clients whom we have represented in criminal matters during the last few years:<BR>
<BR><UL><LI> Prudential Securities and Prudential Insurance in the federal grand jury investigation of the sale of $8 billion of limited partnerships during the 1980s. (We simultaneously represented both companies in a major SEC investigation,  in several class actions,  and in derivative litigation arising out of the same allegations.)<BR>
<BR>
<LI> Kidder,  Peabody and General Electric in the federal grand jury investigation of the Joseph Jett bond trading scandal. (We also represented both companies in an SEC investigation,  in derivative and class actions,  and in a major arbitration relating to the same scandal.)<BR>
<BR>
<LI> Warner Lambert in the federal grand jury investigation of alleged violations of the Federal Food,  Drug,  and Cosmetic Act.<BR>
<BR>
<LI> Exxon in three simultaneous and competing federal and state grand jury investigations of alleged environmental violations relating to the 1990 Arthur Kill oil spill.<BR>
<BR>
<LI> Clark Clifford in connection with simultaneous federal,  state,  and congressional investigations of the BCCI banking scandal.<BR>
<BR>
<LI> Recognition Equipment Inc. (REI) at trial on federal charges of bribery in connection with a $400 million postal contract. (REI was acquitted of all charges at the close of the government's case.)<BR>
<BR>
<LI> Emerson Electric in the federal `Ill Wind' grand jury investigation of fraud in the Pentagon procurement process.<BR>
<BR>
<LI> NYNEX at trial and appeal of criminal contempt charges relating to its compliance with a 1984 order of divestiture. (NYNEX's conviction was reversed on appeal.)<BR>
<BR>
<LI> David Brown,  the former chairman of General Development Corporation,  during his trial on charges of real estate fraud,  as well as in two simultaneous civil lawsuits concerning the availability of insurance coverage for his costs of defense. (Brown was victorious in the insurance litigation; in the criminal case,  he was acquitted on 72 counts and convicted on one. That conviction is now on appeal.)<BR>
<BR>
<LI> Robert Freeman,  a former Goldman Sachs partner,  in connection with federal criminal charges of insider trading.<BR>
<BR>
<LI> Christian Norgren,  a prominent international banker,  in connection with charges of insider trading brought by the SEC and by a federal grand jury.<BR>
<BR>
<LI> Various investment banks in connection with grand jury investigations relating to their public finance activities.<BR>
<BR>
</UL><BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>White Collar Practice Group</H3></CENTER>

<BR><LI><B>Robert B. Fiske,  Jr.</B> With Davis Polk from 1955 to 1957 after graduating from the University of Michigan Law School. Rejoined Davis Polk in 1961 after four years as an assistant U.S. attorney in the Southern District of New York. Became a partner in 1964. From 1976 to 1980,  was the U.S. Attorney for the Southern District of New York. From January 1994 to October 1994 was Independent Counsel to the Whitewater Investigation. President of the American College of Trial Lawyers,  1991-1992. Yale University,  B.A.,  1952; University of Michigan,  J.D.,  1955; associate editor,  law review; Order of the Coif. Admitted in Michigan,  1955; U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit,  1956; U.S. District Courts for the Southern and Eastern Districts of New York,  1957; and U.S. Supreme Court,  1961.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Guy Miller Struve</B> Joined Davis Polk in 1967 after graduating from Harvard Law School in 1966. Became a partner in 1973. From 1987 to 1993,  served with the office of Independent Counsel Lawrence E. Walsh in connection with the investigation of Iran-Contra matters. Law clerk to Judge J. Edward Lumbard,  Second Circuit (1966-1967). Yale University,  A.B.,  <I>summa cum laude</I>,  1963; Harvard University,  LL.B.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1966; law review. Admitted in New York,  1968; U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit,  1969; U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York,  1970; U.S. Supreme Court,  1971; U.S. Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit and U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of New York,  1973; U.S. Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit,  1976; U.S. District Court for the Northern District of California and U.S. Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit,  1979; the District of Columbia,  1985; U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia,  1987; U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit,  1988; and U.S. District Court for the Western District of New York,  1991.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>John P. Cooney,  Jr.</B> With Davis Polk from 1969 to 1972 after graduating from Duke University School of Law. Rejoined Davis Polk in 1977 after five years as an assistant U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New York. Became a partner in 1980. Has lectured extensively on the federal sentencing guidelines and other white collar criminal issues. Mr. Cooney is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers. Indiana University,  B.S.,  1966; Duke University,  J.D.,  1969; note editor,  law journal. Admitted in New York,  1970; U.S. Courts of Appeal for the Second and Fifth Circuits and U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York,  1972; and U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of New York,  1977.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Scott W. Muller</B> Joined Davis Polk in 1976 after graduating from Georgetown University Law Center and serving with the Watergate Special Prosecution Force. Served as an assistant U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New York from 1979 to 1982. Rejoined Davis Polk in 1982 and became a partner in 1985. Law clerk to Judge Francis L. Van Dusen,  U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit (1975-1976). Princeton University,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1971; Georgetown University Law Center,  J.D.,  1975; case and notes editor,  executive board,  <I>Georgetown Law Journal</I>. Admitted in New York,  1977; the District of Columbia,  1986; and U.S. Courts of Appeal for the Second,  Fifth,  and D.C. Circuits,  U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York,  U.S. Tax Court,  and U.S. Supreme Court.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gary G. Lynch</B> Joined Davis Polk as a partner in 1989 after 13 years with the Securities and Exchange Commission,  where he served as the director of the Division of Enforcement from 1985 to 1989. As enforcement director he spearheaded,  among others,  the investigations of Michael Milken,  Dennis Levine,  and Ivan Boesky. Syracuse University,  B.A.,  1972; Phi Beta Kappa; Duke University,  J.D.,  1975; law journal. Admitted in the District of Columbia,  1976; U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia,  1976; New York,  1990; and U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York,  1990.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Carey R. Dunne</B> Joined Davis Polk in 1987 after graduating from Harvard Law School in 1984 and serving as an assistant district attorney in the Manhattan District Attorney's Office from 1984 to 1987. Became a partner in 1993. Has frequently taught trial practice for the National Institute for Trial Advocacy,  and has lectured often on strategies for avoiding corporate criminal liability. Oberlin College,  A.B.,  1980; Harvard University,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1984. Admitted in New York,  1985; U.S. District Courts for the Southern and Eastern Districts of New York 1988; U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit,  1989; and U.S. Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit,  1992.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Denis J. McInerney</B> Joined Davis Polk in 1986 after graduating from Fordham University School of Law. Returned to Davis Polk in 1994 after serving from 1989 to 1994 as an assistant U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New York and from January 1994 to October 1994 as assistant independent counsel to the Whitewater Investigation. Law clerk to Judge Kevin Thomas Duffy,  U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York (1984-1986). Columbia College,  B.A.,  1981; Fordham University,  J.D.,  1984; <I>International Law Journal</I>; National Moot Court Team. Admitted in New York,  1985; and U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York,  1987.<BR>


</UL></BODY>
