<HEAD>
<TITLE>Farella Braun  & Martel
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>White Collar Crime</H2>
<H3>Farella Braun  & Martel
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>San Francisco:</B> 235 Montgomery Street,  San Francisco,  CA 94104<BR>
Tel 415-954-4400  <B>*</B>  Fax 415-954-4480<BR>
<B>St. Helena: </B>899 Adams Street,  St. Helena,  CA 94574<BR>
Tel 707-967-4000  <B>*</B>  Fax 707-967-4009<BR>
<BR>
80 lawyers  <B>*</B>  3 lawyers in White Collar Crime Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P>Farella Braun  & Martel is a full-service law firm with broad expertise in both business and litigation. We serve a diverse group of clients ranging from small local businesses to multinational corporations in a broad range of industries. Our litigation practice benefits from the services of experienced trial lawyers in a number of areas,  including white collar crime,  insurance coverage,  environmental,  securities,  antitrust,  construction,  employment,  intellectual property,  partnership and shareholder disputes,  professional malpractice,  and other commercial litigation. The firm's corporate and business practice offers services involving corporate and securities law,  mergers and acquisitions,  venture capital,  international transactions,  real estate,  environmental,  asset securitization,  and insolvency and loan workouts. The firm also features specialized practice groups serving the wine industry,  banks and financial institutions,  the hotel industry,  and multimedia and communications businesses. In 1996,  the firm will open a Wine Country office in St. Helena,  California.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>White Collar Crime Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>In the past decade,  Farella Braun  & Martel's reputation for trial and appellate work in complex litigation of every sort has expanded to include expertise in white collar criminal and RICO defense matters. Our work covers a wide variety of criminal and quasicriminal cases,  including areas such as defense procurement,  securities (including SEC investigations and enforcement proceedings),  antitrust,  tax fraud,  import and export violations,  and related areas. We have represented banks and credit card organizations in class actions against individual and corporate defendants involved in massive credit card schemes. We have also represented individuals,  including officers and directors of financial institutions and other organizations accused of mismanagement,  stockbrokers in criminal securities actions,  persons accused of insider trading,  grand jury witnesses,  and others. We have defended corporate presidents,  CEOs,  and other directors and officers,  and regularly represent major accounting firms and other institutional subjects of government investigations.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Douglas R. Young</B> serves as chair of Farella Braun  & Martel's Litigation Department as well as its White Collar Crime practice group,  and coordinates all matters in these areas. He joined the firm in 1977 and maintains a diverse litigation practice which emphasizes criminal defense and complex civil litigation of all types. Mr. Young's white collar criminal representations have included cases in the securities,  insider trading,  antitrust,  import and export,  environmental,  and banking areas. He serves on the Criminal Justice Act Defense Panel in the Northern District of California and currently represents (by court appointment) two individuals on California's death row. Mr. Young has also served as an officer or board member for various public-interest organizations,  and has acted as trial and appellate counsel for such organizations and for indigent individuals in several landmark cases. In 1992 he received the ABA's Pro Bono Publico Award. This year he appeared in the <I>Guide To The World's Leading White Collar Crime Lawyers</I>. Mr. Young is a member and officer of many professional legal organizations and is often a featured speaker at programs involving white collar crime and securities litigation. Mr. Young received a B.A. (<I>cum laude</I>,  highest honors in philosophy) from Yale University. After service in the U.S. Marine Corps,  he obtained his J.D. from Boalt Hall School of Law. Admitted in California,  1976; and the U.S. Supreme Court,  1983.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Claudia A. Lewis</B> maintains a complex litigation practice,  with expertise in white collar criminal defense. Her criminal defense work includes representing individuals and corporations in securities,  insider trading,  and tax matters. She is also currently working on two death penalty appeals. Prior to joining Farella Braun  & Martel,  Ms. Lewis clerked for Judge Jack B. Weinstein of the U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of New York,  and was associated for three years with the New York firm of Debevoise  & Plimpton. Ms. Lewis received a B.A. with distinction in American Studies from Yale College,  where she graduated <I>summa cum laude</I> and was elected to Phi Beta Kappa. She received a J.D. from Yale Law School in 1988,  where she was senior editor of the <I>Yale Law Journal</I>. Admitted in California and New York.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Gary Lloyd</B> is special litigation counsel and represents plaintiffs and defendants in complex securities and commodities litigation,  including class and derivative actions,  and antitrust litigation. His white collar crime practice involves representing clients before the SEC and in connection with other government investigations and litigation,  counseling public companies and other regulated entities on compliance matters,  and conducting internal investigations for corporate and other clients. Prior to joining Farella Braun  & Martel,  Mr. Lloyd served with the Securities and Exchange Commission in Washington,  D.C. and Los Angeles from 1984 to 1995. During his tenure as assistant director in the SEC's Division of Enforcement in Washington,  D.C.,  Mr. Lloyd worked on a wide variety of matters,  including the Drexel Burnham Lambert,  Inc. and Michael Milken case and other financial fraud and reporting cases,  insider trading,  and cases involving broker-dealers,  investment companies and investment advisers. He received a B.A. in Political Science and English from Kent State University and a J.D. from Case Western Reserve University School of Law. Admitted in California,  New York,  and Ohio.<BR>
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
