<TITLE>Fried,  Frank,  Harris,  Shriver  & Jacobson
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>White Collar Crime</H2>
<H3>Fried,  Frank,  Harris,  Shriver  & Jacobson
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>New York:</B> One New York Plaza,  New York,  NY 10004<BR>
Tel 212-859-8000  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-747-1526<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> 1001 Pennsylvania Avenue,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20004<BR>
Tel 202-639-7000  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-639-7003<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Los Angeles,  London<BR>
<BR>
357 lawyers  <B>*</B> 30 lawyers in White Collar Defense Practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ATFolder/fried.html"> Antitrust</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/fried.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95IPFolder/fried.html"> Intellectual Property</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>F</B>ried,  Frank,  Harris,  Shriver  & Jacobson represents a variety of clients including large corporations,  institutions,  and prominent individuals in white collar defense matters. The principal members of the Group,  each of whom has over a decade of experience in white collar defense work,  include four former prosecutors; a former general counsel and assistant general counsel of the Securities and Exchange Commission; and a former state prosecutor.
<P><BR><BR>
<BR><P>Our White Collar Defense Group has handled a wide array of criminal investigations and cases. The Group also regularly represents clients in SEC investigations and civil enforcement proceedings. Our attorneys are among the top criminal and civil RICO specialists in the country.<BR><BR><P>Clients represented by members of our White Collar Defense Group include:<BR>
<BR><UL><LI> Bahamas-based Bank Leu International,  in connection with the government's prosecution of Dennis Levine,  which led to the major Wall Street insider trading scandal of the late 1980s;<BR>
<BR><LI> Ivan Boesky in his negotiations with the Department of Justice and the SEC regarding alleged insider trading;<BR>
<BR><LI> Martin Siegel,  former head of mergers and acquisitions of Kidder Peabody,  for alleged insider trading;<BR>
<BR><LI> One of the world's largest Japanese trading companies in a customs fraud investigation;<BR>
<BR><LI> A major defense contractor in connection with criminal fraud allegations;<BR>
<BR><LI> Former officers of failed savings and loan institutions;<BR>
<BR><LI> Officers of generic drug companies; and<BR>
<BR><LI> Defendants in financial fraud cases involving charges of money laundering.<BR>
<BR></UL>
<BR><LI><B>Howard Goldstein</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8502</I>) Mr. Goldstein served in various trial units and as chief appellate attorney for the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Southern District of New York. He is the coauthor of <I>The Rights of Crime Victims</I> (Vol. 1,  1985),  <I>RICO: Civil and Criminal</I> (Vol. 1,  1989),  and a contributing author of <I>Corporate Sentencing Guidelines: Compliance and Mitigation</I> (Vol. 1,  1993). Northwestern University,  B.A.,  with distinction,  1970; Phi Beta Kappa; New York University School of Law,  J.D.,  1973; editor,  law review.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Harvey Pitt</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8170,  and Washington; 202-639-7100</I>) Mr. Pitt is the former general counsel of the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (1977-1978). He is a member of the New York Stock Exchange's Legal Advisory Committee and is chairman of its Subcommittee on Financial Institutions. From 1987 to 1989,  he was the chairman of the U.S. Senate's Ad Hoc Committee of Lawyers to Define the Crime of Insider Trading. He is the coauthor of the seven-volume treatise <I>The Law of Financial Services</I>,  and the coauthor of a law review article entitled `Minimizing Corporate Civil and Criminal Liability: A Second Look at Corporate Codes of Conduct.' In 1988,  he received the Judge Learned Hand Human Relations Award from the Institute for Human Relations. Brooklyn College,  B.A.,  1965; St. John's University School of Law,  J.D.,  1968.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Jed Rakoff</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8570</I>) Mr. Rakoff served as chief of the Fraud Unit for the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Southern District of New York. He is the coauthor of <I>Business Crimes</I> (six volumes,  1981),  <I>RICO: Civil and Criminal</I> (Vol. 1,  1989),  and <I>Corporate Sentencing Guidelines: Compliance and Mitigation</I> (Vol. 1,  1993). He is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers. Swarthmore College,  B.A.,  1964; Oxford University,  M.Phil.,  1966; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  1969.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Michael H. Rauch</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8060</I>) Mr. Rauch has served as an assistant New York State attorney general (1964-1968) and as a U.S. assistant special prosecutor (1981-1982). Princeton University,  B.A.,  1960; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  1963.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Richard Sauber</B> (<I>Washington; 202-639-7190</I>) Mr. Sauber served as the first chief of the Justice Department's Defense Procurement Fraud Unit during his seven years as a federal prosecutor. Yale University,  B.A.,  1972; Oxford University,  M.Litt.,  1975; New York University,  J.D.,  1977.<BR><BR><LI><B>James H. Schropp</B> (<I>Washington; 202-639-7110</I>) Mr. Schropp served with the Securities and Exchange Commission for six years (1973-1979),  the final two years as assistant general counsel. He is a frequent contributor of articles on securities enforcement and related subjects. Georgetown University Law Center,  J.D.,  1973.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Mark Stein</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8552</I>) Mr. Stein served as deputy chief of the Criminal Division for the U.S. Attorney's Office in the Southern District of New York. He also served as associate independent counsel on the Whitewater investigation. The State University of New York at Albany,  B.A.,  1980; University of Michigan Law School,  J.D.,  1983.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Audrey Strauss</B> (<I>New York; 212-859-8544</I>) Ms. Strauss served as chief appellate attorney and chief of the Fraud Unit for the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Southern District of New York. Ms. Strauss is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers. Barnard College,  A.B.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1968; Columbia Law School,  J.D.,  1971; Stone Scholar; Kent Scholar.<BR>
