<HEAD>
<TITLE>Gibson,  Dunn  & Crutcher
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>White Collar Crime</H2>
<H3>Gibson,  Dunn  & Crutcher
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Los Angeles:</B> 333 South Grand,  Los Angeles,  CA 90071-3197<BR>
Tel 213-229-7000  <B>*</B>  Fax 213-229-7520<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Century City (California),  Brussels,  Dallas,  Denver,  Hong Kong, <BR>
Irvine (California),  Jeddah,  London,  Menlo Park (California),  New York,  Paris, <BR>
San Diego,  San Francisco,  Seattle,  Tokyo,  Washington,  D.C.<BR>
<BR>
600 lawyers  <B>*</B>  30 lawyers in Business Crimes and Investigations Practice Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>G</B>ibson,  Dunn  & Crutcher's Business Crimes and Investigations Practice Group has vast experience in defending against a wide range of federal and state prosecutions in a variety of substantive areas including antitrust,  procurement fraud,  financial institution fraud,  securities fraud,  state and federal environmental violations and regulatory compliance,  health care fraud,  immigration fraud,  tax offenses,  RICO,  money laundering,  and civil and criminal forfeiture. The Group's members are highly experienced trial lawyers; several are former prosecutors while others have always been defense lawyers. These lawyers also have extensive experience in advising clients with respect to proceedings before federal and state grand juries and before suspension,  debarment,  and program exclusion authorities. We have represented clients in post-conviction sentencing,  <I>habeas corpus</I>,  and appellate proceedings in federal and state court and in interlocutory appeals during the pendency of the prosecutions. The practice group's investigative arm also assists clients who are the victims of fraud,  theft,  or embezzlement. Finally,  its lawyers have advised corporate clients on establishing corporate legal compliance programs and codes of conduct and ethics.
<P><BR><P>The firm's practice group is co-chaired by <B>Robert C. Bonner</B> and <B>Thomas E. Holliday</B>,  who are both located in Los Angeles. Mr. Bonner is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers and was U.S. Attorney for the Central District of California from 1984 to 1989. Thereafter,  he was appointed to the federal bench. From 1990 to 1993 he served as the administrator of the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration. Mr. Holliday is also a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers and has spent his entire 20-year career as a defense lawyer. His cases include <I>United States </I>v.<I> General Dynamics,  United States </I>v. <I>Parker,  </I>and <I>United States </I>v.<I> Goldberg</I>. <B>Stephen E. Tallent</B> is the founder of the practice group and works out of both the Los Angeles and Washington,  D.C. offices. Mr. Tallent is a nationally recognized expert in labor law and advises clients on internal investigations and corporate compliance obligations.<BR><P>The group also maintains a substantial practice in Washington. <B>F. Joseph Warin </B>is a former assistant U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia and specializes in criminal cases involving antitrust,  health care,  and FDA issues. <B>John H. Sturc</B> is also a former assistant U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia and spent six years as associate director of the SEC Division of Enforcement. Mr. Sturc specializes in securities defense and while at the SEC was involved in cases such as the investigation of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. <B>Theodore Olson </B>was the assistant attorney general for the Office of Legal Counsel in the Department of Justice during the Reagan administration. He handles appellate cases and specialized proceedings throughout the United States. <B>John A. Mintz</B> joined the Washington office following his retirement from the FBI where he had served as an assistant director. In addition to providing legal counsel,  Mr. Mintz is the group's chief investigator.<BR>
<BR><P>The group also has lawyers in several other offices of the firm. For example,  <B>Joel Sanders</B> is located in the San Francisco office and before joining the firm was a trial attorney with the Department of Justice's Antitrust Division. He now specializes in defending against alleged antitrust violations. <B>James P. Clark</B>,  located in the Century City office,  is an antitrust lawyer and former law clerk to Judge John Minor Wisdom. He coauthored the <I>Antitrust Laws and Trade Regulation</I> treatise and also specializes in the defense of antitrust cases. <B>David Palmer</B>,  located in the Denver office,  has an extensive practice in the defense of criminal and regulatory environmental cases and <I>qui tam</I> actions arising out of criminal investigations. The practice group also includes several associates,  including <B>Chad S. Hummel</B> and <B>Larry Byrne</B>. Mr. Hummel is a 1988 graduate of the University of Chicago,  who has tried several complex criminal cases,  including <I>United States </I>v.<I> Barrientos </I>and<I> United States </I>v.<I> Parker</I>. Prior to joining the firm,  Mr. Byrne served as deputy chief of the Organized Crime and Racketeering Section,  Criminal Division,  of the U.S. Department of Justice and was an assistant U.S. attorney in the Criminal Division of the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Southern District of New York.<BR>
<BR><P>In addition,  the firm's expertise in other substantive areas is called upon regularly to provide assistance to clients. For example,  <B>David R. Johnson</B> heads the firm's government contract practice and provides his expertise in procurement fraud cases and compliance programs. <B>Chris H. Buckley,  Jr.,  John D. Fognani,  Raymond B. Ludwiszewski,  </B>and<B> Michele C. Coyle</B> specialize in environmental law and offer guidance in that field. Prior to joining the firm,  Mr. Ludwiszewski was general counsel of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency. Ms. Coyle was on the staff of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency Regional Counsel,  and was a special assistant U.S. attorney assigned to the prosecution of environmental crimes. Mr. Buckley and Mr. Fognani have defended numerous cases involving violations of the Clean Water Act,  as well as federal and state hazardous waste statutes.

</UL></BODY>
