<HEAD>
<TITLE>Greenbaum,  Rowe,  Smith,  Ravin  & Davis
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>White Collar Crime</H2>
<H3>Greenbaum,  Rowe,  Smith,  Ravin  & Davis
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Woodbridge:</B> P.O. Box 5600,  Woodbridge,  NJ 07095<BR>
Tel 908-549-5600  <B>*</B>  Fax 908-549-1881<BR>
<BR>
70 lawyers  <B>*</B>  7 lawyers in White Collar Criminal Defense Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>G</B>reenbaum,  Rowe is one of New Jersey's largest law firms devoted to representing clients in areas of complex litigation,  banking,  securities,  general corporate,  tax,  and real estate. Its White Collar Criminal Defense Group is equipped to step in immediately and represent corporations,  their officers and directors,  and professionals whose business and social lives are shaped in large part by their reputations.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>White Collar Criminal Defense Group</H3></CENTER>

<P>Led by a team of former federal prosecutors,  Greenbaum,  Rowe's White Collar Criminal Defense Group has represented numerous corporations (both public and private) and individuals in federal and state investigations and prosecutions. The Group is frequently called upon by corporations to use its expertise and conduct internal affairs investigations to detect improprieties,  as well as to recommend strategies for implementing compliance programs to better position the corporate client in dealing with law enforcement. The Group's expertise includes defending against investigations and prosecutions of alleged insider trading and other types of alleged securities fraud,  antitrust violations,  government procurement and bank fraud violations,  food and drug violations,  political corruption,  and environmental and tax fraud matters. The Group is also active in defending against the numerous civil proceedings that may parallel criminal proceedings,  including actions by federal agencies such as the FDIC and RTC.<BR><P>The Group has extensive experience with statutes such as the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO),  the Bank Secrecy Act,  the Currency Transaction Bank Reporting Act,  and the Financial Institutions Reform and Recovery Act (FIRREA). Within the last several years,  the Group successfully obtained the acquittal of the president of a corporation in a highly publicized corruption case,  <I>State of New Jersey </I>v.<I> DeMarino,  et al.</I>; represented a director of the New York Federal Reserve Board in an insider trading case,  <I>United States </I>v. <I>Rough</I>; represented a number of attorneys,  directors,  and officers in bank fraud prosecutions including <I>United States </I>v.<I> Hartmann</I> (director and counsel to bank); and represented numerous corporations and individuals in criminal tax prosecutions,  including <I>United States </I>v.<I> Getty</I>.<BR>
<BR><P>The Group considers some of its most valuable services to be the numerous criminal prosecutions it has prevented. The Group is cognizant that frequently the most damage to a corporation's or individual's reputation occurs as a result of an indictment,  and not necessarily a conviction. Accordingly,  because of its knowledge and experience,  the Group often is called upon to dissuade prosecution.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Michael B. Himmel</B> chairs the firm's White Collar Criminal Defense Group. Mr. Himmel regularly defends corporations and individuals who are the subjects of criminal investigations and prosecutions involving tax fraud,  securities fraud,  bank fraud,  public corruption,  government procurement fraud,  environmental violations,  and food and drug violations. Mr. Himmel is a former assistant district attorney in Bronx County,  New York; trial attorney with the Organized Crime and Racketeering Section of the U.S. Department of Justice; and assistant U.S. attorney for the District of New Jersey. He is a lecturer for the Institute for Continuing Legal Education on topics such as the defense of white collar criminal cases.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Robert J. Kipnees</B> is a former assistant U.S. attorney for the District of New Jersey. He regularly defends individuals and corporations in matters involving securities fraud,  bank fraud,  environmental responsibility,  public corruption,  and tax fraud. Mr. Kipnees is an adjunct professor of law at Seton Hall University Law School,  currently teaching a course on white collar criminal practice.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Matthew E. Power</B> has defended clients in matters involving antitrust violations,  governmental procurement fraud,  and tax fraud. Prior to joining the firm,  Mr. Power was a criminal defense lawyer in New York.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Stephanie Kay Austin</B> defends clients in matters involving criminal antitrust violations,  food and drug violations,  and tax fraud.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Christopher S. Porrino</B> defends clients in complex matters involving criminal antitrust violations and bank fraud. Mr. Porrino also has extensive experience and regularly defends clients in the complex civil proceedings which often accompany criminal investigations.<BR>
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
