<HEAD>
<TITLE>Haynes and Boone,  L.L.P.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>White Collar Crime</H2>
<H3>Haynes and Boone,  L.L.P.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Dallas:</B> 901 Main Street,  Suite 3100,  Dallas,  TX 75202<BR>
Tel 214-651-5000  <B>*</B>  Fax 214-651-5940<BR>
<B>Fort Worth:</B> 801 Cherry Street,  Suite 1300,  Fort Worth,  TX 76102<BR>
Tel 817-347-6600  <B>*</B>  Fax 817-347-6650<BR>
<B>Houston: </B>1000 Louisiana Street,  Suite 4300,  Houston,  TX 77002<BR>
Tel 713-547-2000  <B>*</B>  Fax 713-547-2600<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Austin,  San Antonio,  Mexico City,  Washington,  D.C.<BR>
<BR>
213 lawyers  <B>*</B>  16 lawyers in Specialized Litigation and Government Investigations<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>H</B>aynes and Boone formally began its white collar practice in 1984. We provide clients with a full range of legal services ranging from compliance programs and counseling,  to representations in complex criminal or civil trials and federal appeals. While the majority of our representations start with the grand jury investigation,  we are frequently called upon to do internal investigations or respond to informal government inquiries.
<P><BR><P>We provide services nationwide and have represented clients in criminal proceedings in Baltimore,  Memphis,  Washington,  D.C.,  Little Rock,  Los Angeles,  Buffalo,  Florida,  Shreveport,  San Francisco,  Denver,  San Diego,  Chicago,  and Cedar Rapids,  as well as throughout Texas and the Southwest.<BR><P>Our substantive practice areas have included domestic and international antitrust,  consumer fraud,  environmental,  public corruption,  insider trading,  securities fraud,  insurance fraud,  foreign trade and customs violations,  money laundering,  tax evasion and fraud,  procurement fraud and defective pricing,  and health care fraud.<BR>
<BR><P>A partial list of our recent white collar criminal and corporate compliance representations includes: the successful defense of a worldwide energy industry client in nationwide criminal and civil price-fixing investigations; the representation of a national hospital chain in criminal and civil investigations throughout the country; an extensive internal investigation into fraud and mismanagement allegations for a major metropolitan school district; health care compliance audits for several major hospital systems; the grand jury defense of public corruption allegations against a national waste management company; counseling the national petroleum companies of Mexico and Venezuela regarding compliance with United States environmental laws and regulations; the grand jury defense of a petroleum services company involving alleged violations of the Clean Water Act and the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act; and representations of executives in Securities and Exchange Commission investigations into securities fraud and insider trading allegations.<BR>
<BR><P>Because of the confidential nature of these representations,  specific client references will be made available only upon request and after client consent.<BR>
<BR><UL><LI><B>Robin P. Hartmann</B> (<I>Dallas; 214-651-5578</I>) Rob is a former chair of the Antitrust and Trade Regulation Section of the State Bar of Texas and served for eight years on the Board of Directors of the Dallas Bar Association. Rob represents corporations and individuals in civil and criminal securities,  antitrust,  and defense procurement matters. University of Pennsylvania,  Wharton School,  B.S.,  1964; Washington and Lee University,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1971; Order of the Coif; editor-in-chief,  <I>Washington and Lee Law Review</I>.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Barry F. McNeil</B> (<I>Dallas; 214-651-5580</I>) Barry spent nine years with the Department of Justice where he served as chief of the Southwest Office of the Antitrust Division. He is a former chair of the Antitrust and Trade Regulations Section of the State Bar of Texas and is currently vice-chair of the Litigation Section of the American Bar Association. Barry is co-editor of <I>Internal Investigations: Conducting Them and Protecting Them</I>,  published by the American Bar Association in 1992. Barry represents corporations and individuals in civil and criminal antitrust,  health care,  federal fraud,  and public corruption matters. Texas Tech University,  B.A.,  1966; University of Texas,  J.D.,  1969.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Laurence K. Gustafson</B> (<I>Dallas; 214-651-5635</I>) Larry served in the Department of Justice for 12 years where he was a trial attorney in the Land and Natural Resources Division of the Environmental Crimes Section and assistant chief of the Southwest Office of the Antitrust Division. Larry represents corporations and individuals in civil and criminal environmental and antitrust matters. University of Texas at Arlington,  B.B.A.,  1970; Boston University,  J.D.,  1974.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Stacy L. Brainin</B> (<I>Dallas; 214-651-5584</I>) Stacy is a frequent lecturer in the area of government health care fraud enforcement and compliance programs. Stacy represents corporations and individuals in civil and criminal health care fraud enforcement and federal criminal matters. University of Texas,  B.A.,  high honors,  1981; University of Texas,  J.D.,  high honors,  1984; Order of the Coif; associate editor,  <I>Texas Law Review</I>.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Lawrence D. Finder</B> (<I>Houston; 713-547-2006</I>) Larry spent six years as a prosecutor in the Cook County (Chicago) State's Attorney's Office and nine years with the Department of Justice,  where he served as deputy chief of the Organized Crime Drug Enforcement Task Force,  chief of the Criminal Division,  first assistant U.S. attorney,  and U.S. Attorney for the Southern District of Texas. Larry represents corporations and individuals in federal criminal matters. Northern Illinois University,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1973; Loyola University,  J.D.,  1976.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Larry A. Gaydos</B> (<I>Fort Worth; 817-347-6617</I>) Larry spent 11 years in the U.S. Army where he prosecuted and defended military criminal cases and later served as a professor in the Criminal Law Division of the Judge Advocate General's School. He is currently a council member of the Antitrust and Business Litigation Section of the State Bar of Texas. Larry represents corporations and individuals in civil and criminal securities,  antitrust,  federal fraud,  and federal appellate matters. United States Military Academy,  B.S.,  distinguished graduate,  1973; University of Virginia,  J.D.,  1978.<BR></UL>

</UL></BODY>
