ud,  and tax fraud. The firm has represented numerous individuals and entities in grand jury investigations and in trial courts after indictment. The firm is frequently retained specially to conduct internal investigations when a particular issue has arisen. In addition,  the firm has been retained to represent individuals and corporations involved in congressional and administrative investigations.<BR><BR><UL><LI><B>John W. Nields,  Jr.</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-6639</I>) Co-chair. Mr. Nields specializes in white collar criminal defense work,  including defense of bank fraud,  bribery,  government procurement,  and other business and political crime cases. Assistant U.S. attorney,  Southern District of New York,  1969-1974; chief,  Civil Division 1973-1974; chief appellate attorney,  1972-1973; law clerk,  Justice Byron R. White,  U.S. Supreme Court,  1974-1977; chief counsel,  Committee on Standards of Official Conduct,  Korea Influence Investigation,  U.S. House of Representatives,  1977-1979; special counsel,  U.S. Department of Justice,  1979-1980; chief counsel,  U.S. House of Representatives Iran/Contra Committee,  1987-1988; special counsel to Governor's Commission to investigate the collapse of Rhode Island's privately insured financial institutions,  1990-1992.<BR><BR><LI><B>W. Neil Eggleston</B> (<I>Washington; 202-383-7433</I>) Co-chair. Mr. Eggleston represents individuals and entities at the grand jury,  trial,  and appellate stages. He also has substantial experience in corporate internal investigations and congressional inquiries. Most recently he served as associate White House counsel,  1993-1994. Law clerk,  Judge James Hunter III,  U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit,  1978-1979; law clerk,  Chief Justice Warren E. Burger,  U.S. Supreme Court,  1979-1980; assistant U.S. attorney,  1981-1987,  and chief appellate attorney,  1986-1987,  Office of the U.S. Attorney for the Southern District of New York; deputy chief counsel,  U.S. House of Representatives Iran/Contra Committee,  1987-1988; associate counsel to the President,  1993-1994.<BR><BR><LI><B>Thomas J. Nolan</B> (<I>Los Angeles; 213-892-7929</I>) Mr. Nolan has represented and defended corporations in litigation throughout the United States involving money laundering,  RICO violations,  securities fraud,  mail fraud,  tax fraud,  antitrust investigations,  grand jury investigations,  bid rigging,  government contracts procurement fraud,  Foreign Corrupt Practices Act violations,  criminal environmental law violations,  <I>qui tam</I> actions,  insider trading violations,  and health care fraud. Assistant U.S. attorney and chief of the Fraud and Special Prosecution Unit,  U.S. Attorney's Office for the Central District of California.<BR><BR><LI><B>Stephen D. Miller </B>(<I>Los Angeles; 213-892-7922</I>) Mr. Miller has represented corporations and individuals in significant federal and state civil and criminal litigation for the past 25 years. He served as lead counsel to General Dynamics Corporation in its successful defense against a major indictment charging defense contract fraud. Assistant U.S. attorney and assistant chief of the Special Prosecutions Division,  U.S. Attorney's Office for the Central District of California.<BR><BR><LI><B>William L. Webber </B>(<I>Washington; 202-383-7412</I>) Mr. Webber has substantial grand jury and trial experience. Assistant U.S. attorney,  U.S. Attorney's Office for the Central District of California,  1981-1984; trial attorney,  Antitrust Division,  U.S. Department of Justice,  1980-1981.<BR><BR><LI><B>George W. Buehler</B> (<I>Los Angeles; 213-892-7923</I>) Mr. Buehler specializes in complex civil and criminal litigation. Deputy attorney general,  California Attorney General's Office,  1975-1977.<BR><BR><BR></UL><BR></UL></BODY></HTML>
