<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>King  & Spalding
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>White Collar Crime</H2>
<H3>King  & Spalding
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Atlanta:</B> 191 Peachtree Street,  Atlanta,  GA 30303-1763<BR>
Tel 404-572-4600  <B>*</B>  Fax 404-572-510<BR>
<B>Washington:</B> 1730 Pennsylvania Avenue,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20006-4706<BR>
Tel 202-737-0500  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-626-3737<BR>
<B>New York:</B> 120 West 45th Street,  New York,  NY 10036-4003<BR>
Tel 212-556-2100  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-556-2222<BR>
<B>Houston:</B> 1100 Louisiana Street,  Suite 3300,  Houston,  TX 77002-5219<BR>
Tel 713-751-3200  <B>*</B>  Fax 713-751-3290<BR>
<BR>
360 lawyers  <B>*</B>  38 lawyers in Special Matters Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>I</B>n 1985,  King  & Spalding was retained by the board of directors of E.F. Hutton Company Inc. to conduct an exhaustive internal corporate investigation into facts that caused Hutton to plead guilty to approximately 2, 000 counts of wire fraud and mail fraud.
<P><BR><P>Shortly after the <I>Exxon Valdez</I> oil spill in Alaska in March 1989,  the board of directors of Exxon Corporation retained King  & Spalding to assist the appointed Independent Litigation Committee in investigating various allegations in shareholder derivative actions and demand letters.<BR><P>Based on its extensive involvement in Hutton's and Exxon's internal corporate investigations,  King  & Spalding formed a Special Matters Group,  consisting of trial lawyers experienced and knowledgeable in handling internal investigations for corporations and all related criminal and civil matters. The investigations are generally performed for a corporate board of directors,  the outside directors,  or the chief executive officer,  although they may be performed for an independent committee of the board of directors where a shareholder derivative suit has been filed. The primary objectives in these matters are to assess responsibility,  defend against the charges,  and structure creative solutions to the issues which gave rise to the investigations.<BR>
<BR><P>Services rendered by the Special Matters Group include representation in criminal or regulatory investigations; representation of businesses that have been victimized by dishonest employees,  vendors,  or others; and representation of the corporations and corporate officers against charges such as bank fraud in criminal or related shareholder derivative litigation. This Group also assists in legal audits and provides counseling in preventive law,  including advice about ethical programs and systems that monitor corporate and individual conduct.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Griffin B. Bell</B> (<I>Atlanta; 404-572-4879</I>),  a partner with the firm since 1953,  sat on the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit from 1961 until 1976. From 1977 to 1979,  he served as the 72nd U.S. Attorney General. Although his private practice is multifaceted,  a principal focus has been advice and counsel on matters related to corporate crime. He has experience and interest in all phases of internal corporate investigations and has been instrumental in organizing this practice group.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Larry D. Thompson</B> (<I>Atlanta; 404-572-3431</I>),  former U.S. attorney for the Northern District of Georgia,  represents businesses and individuals in a wide variety of matters,  including grand jury proceedings,  internal corporate investigations,  and trials. In July 1995,  he was named independent counsel for the HUD investigation,  replacing Judge Arlin Adams of Philadelphia.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William C. Hendricks III </B>(<I>Washington; 202-556-5611</I>),  formerly a trial attorney in the U.S. Department of Justice's Criminal Fraud Section,  practices in all phases of criminal law and criminal fraud. His experience lies in the investigation,  prosecution,  and trial of numerous criminal matters involving political,  corporate,  judicial,  and governmental misconduct.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Stephen S. Cowen</B> (<I>Atlanta; 404-572-4688</I>),  former court-appointed U.S. attorney in Atlanta,  focuses on white collar criminal defense,  civil fraud litigation,  and internal corporate investigations.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Joseph Sedwick Sollers III</B> (<I>Washington; 202-556-5612</I>) has experience in grand jury practice,  criminal environmental and FDA matters,  internal corporate investigations,  representation before congressional committees,  and federal criminal trials. Along with Judge Bell,  he represented former President Bush in the Iran-Contra and Clinton Passport independent counsel investigations.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Paul J. Larkin,  Jr. </B>(<I>Washington; 202-556-3748</I>) was an assistant to the Solicitor General in the U.S. Department of Justice and in the Organized Crime and Racketeering Section of the Department's Criminal Division. He has argued extensively before the U.S. Supreme Court and is admitted to practice before several federal appellate courts.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William S. Duffey,  Jr.</B> (<I>Atlanta; 404-572-4782</I>) has experience in complex criminal and civil litigation and internal corporate investigations. He recently rejoined the firm,  having served from 1994 to 1995 as deputy independent counsel in the Whitewater investigation.<BR>
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
