<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Kirkpatrick  & Lockhart LLP
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>White Collar Crime</H2>
<H3>Kirkpatrick  & Lockhart LLP
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>New York:</B> 1251 Avenue of the Americas,  45th Floor,  New York,  NY 10020-1104<BR>
Tel 212-536-3900  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-536-3901<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> Boston,  Harrisburg,  Miami,  Pittsburgh,  Washington,  D.C.<BR>
<BR>
Over 400 lawyers  <B>*</B>  19 lawyers practicing criminal law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>K</B>irkpatrick  & Lockhart has diversified areas of practice including litigation,  corporate,  insurance,  tax,  and environmental law. Lawyers from these areas often work on white collar cases.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Overview of the Practice Area</H3></CENTER>

<P>Kirkpatrick  & Lockhart has represented individuals,  corporations,  and their executives in a variety of criminal cases and investigations including parallel criminal and civil proceedings,  grand jury investigations,  trials,  and internal corporate investigations. Subject matters have included allegations of securities and commodities fraud,  political corruption,  embezzlement,  bank fraud,  environmental matters,  antitrust violations,  and regulatory matters.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Experience and Clients</H3></CENTER>

<P>White collar cases have included representation of: Warner Communications Audit Committee in an internal investigation of Westchester Premier Theatre; ABC in an internal investigation of Don King's Boxing Tournament; a co-defendant in <I>United States </I>v.<I> Milken</I>; a former mayor of Boston in an investigation of campaign funds violations and embezzlement; Donald Manes in a New York City corruption investigation; defendants against allegations of environmental law violations; witnesses in the `Ill Wind' investigation of contract abuses at the Department of Defense; an arbitrageur/money manager in a tax fraud investigation of repurchase transactions; a co-defendant in the Imelda Marcos case; a pharmaceutical company in an antitrust case; a jewelry retailer in sales tax evasion; the former counsel to the New York City Patrolmen's Benevolent Association in an embezzlement investigation; the controller of a large public company in an investigation of car rental charges to customers; and Ashland Oil regarding criminal and civil proceedings arising out of a spill of diesel fuel.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Richard L. Thornburgh</B> was the Attorney General of the United States from 1988 until 1991. He also served as Governor of Pennsylvania and Under- Secretary-General of the United Nations. He is counsel to Kirkpatrick  & Lockhart in its Washington,  D.C. office.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Michael F. Armstrong</B>,  a partner in the New York office,  served as chief of the Securities Frauds Unit in the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Southern District of New York; as district attorney for Queens County,  New York; and as chief counsel to the Knapp Commission,  which investigated New York City police corruption.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William O. Purcell</B>,  a partner in the New York office,  served as an assistant district attorney for New York County and was chief of the Criminal Court Bureau and a member of the Homicide Bureau.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Mary Corrarino</B>,  a partner in the New York office,  practices criminal litigation in New York state and federal courts and agencies,  and has represented clients in cases including allegations of fraud,  embezzlement,  and professional misconduct.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>D. Lloyd Macdonald</B>,  a partner in the Boston office,  was chief of the Political Corruption Unit of the U.S. Attorney's Office in the District of Massachusetts and was chief trial counsel of the Suffolk County (Boston) District Attorney's Aggravated Felonies Squad.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Roger M. Adelman</B>,  a partner in the Washington,  D.C. office,  was an assistant U.S. attorney in Washington,  D.C.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Mahlon M. Frankhauser</B>,  a partner in the Washington,  D.C. office,  was the Securities and Exchange Commission's assistant director of enforcement and then the New York regional administrator.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Stephen W. Grafman</B>,  a partner in the Washington,  D.C. office,  was in the U.S. Navy Judge Advocate General Corps and was an assistant U.S. attorney in Washington,  D.C.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Barry M. Hartman</B>,  a partner in the Washington,  D.C. office,  was the Justice Department's acting assistant attorney general for the Environmental and Natural Resource Division.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Jerry S. McDevitt</B>,  a partner in the Pittsburgh office,  has represented corporate and individual clients in criminal cases,  including defending the World Wrestling Foundation in connection with conspiracy charges and forfeiture.
</UL>


