harges. We have also represented institutions and individuals in the investigations of Drexel Burnham,  including Drexel customers and former Drexel executives. We successfully defended the general counsel and chief financial officer of The Southland Corporation against criminal proxy fraud charges,  and a First Jersey Securities broker in a case alleging perjury and obstruction of justice. Currently,  we are representing clients in various SEC and criminal investigations involving allegations of insider trading,  market manipulation,  stock `parking, ' antitrust violations,  and fraud.<BR><P>We represented E. Robert Wallach,  a San Francisco attorney and counsel to former Attorney General Edwin Meese,  in a lengthy federal criminal trial arising out of the Wedtech government contracting scandal. The charges against Mr. Wallach were subsequently dropped.<BR><BR><P>We recently successfully represented Saudi Arabian banker Sheik Khalid Bin Mahfouz against state criminal charges and in proceedings before the Federal Reserve Board relating to the disposition of his interest in the Bank of Commerce and Credit International. We also have represented other U.S. and foreign banking clients in regulatory actions before the Federal Reserve Board,  the FDIC,  and state banking authorities.<BR><BR><P>Other matters handled have included state and federal criminal tax investigations (of accountants,  lawyers,  and diverse business entities,  among others); federal environmental matters; representation of entities and individuals in Congressional inquiries; representation of broker-dealers,  hedge funds,  fund managers,  and individuals in proceedings brought by the SEC,  the NASD,  and the New York and American Stock Exchanges; representation of licensed professionals before the New York State Office of Professional Discipline; representation of labor union officials,  employers,  and others in grand jury and administrative proceedings; representation of companies and individuals in government contract matters; and trial and appellate representation of government officials in the New York City Parking Violations Bureau,  Ill Wind,  and Wedtech scandals.<BR><BR><UL><BR><LI><B>Gary P. Naftalis</B> heads our white collar practice. One of the nation's leading trial lawyers,  he served as an assistant U.S. attorney in New York for seven years,  holding the title of deputy chief of the criminal division. Mr. Naftalis has served on bar association committees focusing on white collar crime and is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers. He has written articles and outlines for seminars and for publication in professional journals,  and is the editor of the ALI-ABA treatise <I>White Collar Crime</I>. Mr. Naftalis is coauthor,  with Marvin E. Frankel,  a former U.S. District Judge and senior partner of our firm,  of <I>The Grand Jury: An Institution On Trial</I> (1977) and <I>Sentencing: Helping Judges Do Their Jobs</I> (1986). He recently acted as counsel to Ethel Rosenberg in the ABA Litigation Series Program,  `The Trial of the Century: <I>United States </I>v.<I> Julius and Ethel Rosenberg</I>.' Law clerk to Judge William B. Herlands,  U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York,  1967-1968. Rutgers University,  B.A.,  1963; Brown University,  M.A.,  1965; Columbia University,  LL.B.,  1967; Phi Beta Kappa; editor,  <I>Columbia Law Review</I>.<BR><BR><LI><B>David S. Frankel</B>'s practice concentrates on white collar criminal defense,  SEC enforcement actions,  and other administrative agency proceedings. He is the author or coauthor of articles and outlines on white collar crime,  internal corporate investigations,  and compliance programs. Law clerk,  Judge Irving R. Kaufman,  U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit,  1982-1983. Yale University,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1976; New York University,  J.D.,  1982; senior note and comment editor,  <I>New York University Law Review</I>.<BR><BR><LI><B>Debora K. Grobman</B> served for five years as an assistant district attorney in New York,  rising to the position of senior appellate counsel and advisor to the Frauds Bureau. Ms. Grobman concentrates in white collar criminal defense in federal and state courts and has represented clients in related administrative and regulatory proceedings. Brooklyn College,  B.A.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1959; Bank Street College,  M.S.,  1973; Fordham University,  J.D.,  1977; member,  <I>Fordham Law Review</I>.<BR><BR><LI><B>Alan R. Friedman</B> has broad experience in the defense of complex criminal cases,  as well as private civil actions and enforcement proceedings before the SEC,  the Federal Reserve Board,  and other administrative agencies. He is the author or coauthor of articles and outlines on insider trading and compliance issues. Law clerk,  Judge M. Joseph Blumenfeld,  U.S. District Court for the District of Connecticut,  1976-1977. Hamilton College,  A.B.,  1973; Yale University,  J.D.,  1976.<BR><BR></UL></UL></BODY></HTML>
