<HEAD>
<TITLE>Kravit,  Gass  & Weber S.C.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>White Collar Crime</H2>
<H3>Kravit,  Gass  & Weber S.C.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Milwaukee:</B> 825 North Jefferson,  Milwaukee,  WI 53202<BR>
Tel 414-271-7100  <B>*</B>  Fax 414-271-8135<BR>
<BR>
26 lawyers  <B>*</B>  5 lawyers in white collar and business criminal practice<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>K</B>ravit,  Gass  & Weber is a boutique law firm concentrating in aggravated litigation,  bankruptcy cases,  and resolution of difficult matters,  with special expertise in fraud and RICO. The Firm,  founded in 1985,  has highly credentialed lawyers,  many formerly associated with large law firms,  who choose to work in the environment of a smaller practice. All members of the firm have backgrounds of outstanding achievement,  such as fellow in the American College of Trial Lawyers; federal or state supreme court law clerk; member or editor of a law review; or former assistant U.S. attorney. The firm relies on talented staff and state-of-the-art computer support to deliver quality service in complex,  aggravated matters.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>White Collar and Business Criminal Practice</H3></CENTER>

<P>Defense of matters that have criminal implications involves both art and science. We are often called into situations that are rapidly deteriorating as events spin out of control. The key in such situations is to get control of the facts immediately and develop a strategy to interact with investigative authorities. We have significant experience in developing such strategies.<BR><P>We represent alleged perpetrators (corporations,  managers,  defrauders),  as well as victims (corporations,  employers,  people who have been defrauded). We know how to interact cooperatively with the government where necessary,  and how to beat it. We have helped companies by doing internal investigations and fraud consulting. We are intimately familiar with problems of parallel civil,  administrative,  and criminal litigation,  and have managed defenses involving multiple districts and nationwide interests.<BR>
<BR><P>This is an era of escalating complexity in criminal cases. Sentencing guidelines impact on all decisions at all stages of a federal criminal investigation and prosecution. We are skilled and experienced in guideline matters and sentencing trials. One of our lawyers served on the U.S. Sentencing Commission.<BR>
<BR><P>Wisconsin is very aggressive in certain business criminal areas,  especially in environmental,  securities,  and antitrust enforcement. We have significant experience with the special prosecutorial units that oversee these cases,  and with the district attorneys who may also be involved.<BR>
<BR><P>We work as a team, and have the resources to jump in and hit the ground running on short notice.<BR>
<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Stephen E. Kravit</B> Firm founder. Former assistant and special assistant U.S. attorney,  Eastern District of Wisconsin,  1976-1979; recipient,  U.S. Attorney General's Award for Distinguished Service,  1979; chairman,  State Bar of Wisconsin Criminal Law Section,  1984-1988; commissioner,  Milwaukee Fire and Police Commission,  1984-1987. Prosecuted numerous fraud cases,  including Jos. Schlitz Brewing Co. illegal payments case. Defended cases concerning national land fraud scheme,  national export violations,  bank fraud,  mail fraud,  kickbacks,  tax fraud,  money laundering,  securities fraud,  RICO,  RTC fraud,  and environmental dumping (including corporate and vicarious criminal liability),  with extensive grand jury and search warrant experience. Has lectured nationally on RICO and fraud to organizations concerned with fraud (e.g.,  American Society for Industrial Security,  International Association of Insurance Fraud Agencies,  and National Association of Insurance Commissioners) and at law schools (Harvard Law School,  University of Wisconsin Law School,  and Marquette University Law School) on criminal and trial topics. Represented Fortune 500 corporations as national fraud consultant. Member,  National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers. Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  1975. Admitted in Wisconsin and various federal courts,  including U.S. Supreme Court.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Janice A. Rhodes</B> Shareholder. Formerly associated with Jenner  & Block in the criminal defense area; former law clerk to Chief Justice of the Minnesota Supreme Court; chairman,  State Bar of Wisconsin Individual Rights Section,  1989-1990. Has defended cases involving organized crime,  mail and wire fraud,  bank fraud,  tax,  extortion,  kickback,  money laundering,  conspiracy,  RICO,  and civil and criminal forfeiture. Experienced in complex commercial and criminal litigation and trials,  including wiretap suppression issues,  e.g.,  <I>United States </I>v. <I>Dorfman</I>. Substantial nationwide experience in complex appeals,  e.g.,  <I>United States </I>v.<I> Doerr </I>and<I> Schmunk </I>v.<I> State</I>. Has written and lectured extensively on criminal law issues. Member,  National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers. Stanford University,  J.D.,  1980. Admitted in Illinois and Wisconsin.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Victoria I. Liccione</B> Former law clerk to U.S. District Judge. Served on U.S. Federal Sentencing Commission. Assistant U.S. attorney,  Southern District of West Virginia,  1991-1994. Has lectured on federal corporate sentencing guidelines,  and on numerous federal criminal issues at U.S. Attorney General's Advocacy Institute. Yale Law School,  J.D.,  1989; Coker Fellow. Admitted in Wisconsin,  West Virginia,  the District of Columbia,  and New York.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Sandra L. Botcher</B> Experienced in complex civil and criminal fraud litigation. University of Minnesota Law School,  J.D.,  <I>cum laude</I>,  1990. Admitted in Wisconsin,  Kansas and various federal courts.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Allen C. Schlinsog,  Jr.</B> Experienced in complex civil and criminal fraud litigation. John Marshall Law School,  J.D.,  <I>magna cum laude</I>,  1991. Admitted in Wisconsin,  Illinois,  and various federal courts.
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
