<HEAD>
<TITLE>Kronish,  Lieb,  Weiner & Hellman LLP
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>White Collar Crime</H2>
<H3>Kronish,  Lieb,  Weiner & Hellman LLP
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>New York:</B> 1114 Avenue of the Americas,  New York,  NY 10036-7798<BR>
Tel 212-479-0000  <B>*</B>  Fax 212-479-6275<BR>
<BR>
75 lawyers  <B>*</B>  3 partners practicing criminal law<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>K</B>ronish Lieb regularly represents individuals and institutional clients in a full range of white collar matters,  including internal investigations,  federal grand jury investigations and trials,  and investigations by the SEC,  CFTC,  IRS,  and other regulatory agencies. The firm frequently represents clients in matters that involve parallel proceedings,  including complex civil litigations. It also counsels institutional clients on establishing and maintaining compliance programs. The members of Kronish Lieb's white collar practice group work as a team,  thus offering clients the benefit of their collective experience and abilities.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Experience and Clients</H3></CENTER>

<P>Among Kronish Lieb's recent public white collar assignments are: the representation of Consolidated Edison on charges of environmental crimes in connection with the explosion of a manhole in the Gramercy Park section of New York City; the successful representation of James Sherwin,  the vice-chairman of GAF Corp.,  on charges of securities fraud and stock manipulation; the representation of Gitano,  a public corporation charged with criminal violations of the customs laws; and the representation of the Enka Group,  a Turkish conglomerate,  in connection with the Banco Lavoro-Iraqgate prosecution. The firm has represented individuals in connection with multiple-party investigations,  including the recent BCCI,  Woolworth,  Drexel,  and Prudential investigations,  and has represented a number of individuals at trial to successful verdicts. Kronish Lieb has also represented numerous individuals and entities,  including a large number of financial institutions,  in matters which are not public involving the fraud,  securities,  money laundering,  RICO,  and income tax laws.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Alan Levine</B> Clerked for Judge Lee P. Gagliardi of the Southern District of New York,  then served as an assistant U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New York for five years. Joined Kronish Lieb in 1980 and became a partner of the firm in 1982. Since joining the firm,  Mr. Levine has coordinated the representation of a number of financial institutions and corporations confronted with allegations of wrongful conduct. Many such representations have involved numerous individual witnesses and targets,  and the representations have commenced from the point of internal investigation through government enforcement action. He also has tried complex RICO,  tax shelter,  tax,  securities fraud,  and corruption cases from the defense side. Mr. Levine is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers. He graduated from New York University Law School in 1973,  where he served as an editor of the law review.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>William J. Schwartz</B> Clerked for Judge Marvin E. Frankel and Judge Abraham D. Sofaer,  both of the Southern District of New York. Joined Kronish Lieb as a partner in 1987 after five years as an assistant U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New York and deputy chief of the Criminal Division. Mr. Schwartz has extensive experience in both white collar criminal and civil litigation. He has represented numerous corporations and individuals as both targets and witnesses in complex criminal and enforcement investigations and in parallel civil actions. He has tried significant civil and criminal cases and has conducted major internal investigations. Mr. Schwartz graduated from Columbia University Law School in 1978,  where he served as an articles editor of the law review.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Celia Goldwag Barenholtz</B> Clerked for Judge Eugene H. Nickerson of the Eastern District of New York. Joined Kronish Lieb as a partner in 1989 after six years as an assistant U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New York and chief appellate attorney of the Criminal Division. Ms. Barenholtz has broad experience in private practice in criminal litigation and enforcement actions as well as corporate investigations. She also has had extensive experience in civil litigation,  including RICO and other complex federal actions. As an assistant U.S. attorney,  she investigated and tried white collar cases and was responsible for numerous appeals to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit. She is on the board of editors of <I>Money Laundering Law Report</I> and has written several articles on money laundering. She graduated from Columbia University Law School in 1979,  where she served as a notes and comments editor of the law review.<BR>
</UL>


</UL></BODY>
