<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>White Collar Crime</H2>
<H3>Lowenstein,  Sandler,  Kohl,  Fisher  & Boylan,  P.A.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Roseland:</B> 65 Livingston Avenue,  Roseland,  NJ 07068<BR>
Tel 201-992-8700  <B>*</B>  Fax 201-992-5820<BR>
<B>Other office:</B> Somerville (New Jersey)<BR>
<BR>
130 lawyers  <B>*</B>  12 lawyers practicing criminal defense<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CSFFolder/lowenstein.html"> Corporate Securities</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/lowenstein.html"> Environmental</A>
</UL>

<P>
<P>
<P><B>L</B>owenstein Sandler is among the largest general corporate practice firms in New Jersey. The firm provides full legal service to its clients. Areas of practice include white collar criminal defense,  complex commercial litigation,  and environmental and corporate law.
<P>
<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Overview of the Practice Area</H3></CENTER>

<P>The white collar criminal defense group is comprised of three partners and approximately nine associates who devote the bulk of their time to representing corporations,  corporate executives,  and political figures in a full range of white collar criminal matters. These matters include federal and state grand jury investigations; regulatory investigations,  e.g.,  SEC,  EPA; Congressional investigations; and the trial of all such matters. Lowenstein Sandler also counsels clients on the establishment and maintenance of corporate compliance programs.<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Experience and Clients</H3></CENTER>

<P>Examples of Lowenstein Sandler's white collar criminal assignments are: representation of former U.S. Secretary of Labor Raymond Donovan and other corporate executives of Schiavone Construction Co.; representation of Michael Milken in both civil and criminal matters; representation of several U.S. Congressmen in both grand jury investigations and trial; representation of Exxon Corporation,  American Cyanamid,  and Safety-Kleen Corp. in various environmental investigations; representation of various HUD officials in independent counsel investigations,  representation of various brokerage firms in criminal and SEC investigations and trials,  including James Regan,  the managing partner of Princeton-Newport,  and Michael Steinhardt,  the managing partner of Steinhardt Partners; representation of National Medical Enterprises and other health care concerns in various grand jury investigations; representation of Allen Antar in the `Crazy Eddie Antar' securities fraud criminal trial; and representation of New York Court of Appeals Justice Sol Wachtler.<BR>
<UL><BR>
<LI><B>Theodore V. Wells,  Jr.</B> Mr. Wells has more than 15 years of litigation experience,  primarily in the area of white collar criminal defense. In 1991 and 1994 <I>The National Law Journal</I> selected him as one of the `100 Most Influential Lawyers in America.' In 1992,  in its `Who's Who in the White Collar Defense Bar' edition,  <I>The National Law Journal </I>selected Mr. Wells as one of the top white collar criminal defense lawyers in America. He has been a faculty member of the Practising Law Institute Trial Advocacy Program and a teaching team member of the Harvard Law School Trial Advocacy Workshop. He has lectured on the use and scope of the RICO statute,  the defense of securities and environmental criminal investigations,  and federal grand jury procedures. He serves on the Board of Trustees of the New Jersey Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers and is a former co-chair of the White Collar Criminal Section of the National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers. He is a fellow of the American College of Trial Lawyers. College of the Holy Cross,  B.A.,  1972; Harvard Business School,  M.B.A.,  1976; Harvard Law School,  J.D.,  1976.<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>Matthew P. Boylan</B> Mr. Boylan has more than 30 years of experience in the area of white collar criminal defense. Prior to joining Lowenstein Sandler,  he served as director of the Division of Criminal Justice of the State of New Jersey and on several occasions has been appointed a special prosecutor to carry out state and federal investigations. He was an assistant U.S. attorney for the District of New Jersey from 1960 to 1963. As chief of the Organized Crime Section from 1961 to 1963,  he received a special commendation from U.S. Attorney General Robert F. Kennedy in 1963 for his prosecution of various high-ranking members of organized crime. Mr. Boylan is a fellow in the American College of Trial Lawyers and a fellow of the American Bar Foundation. College of the Holy Cross,  A.B.,  1954; Harvard Law School,  LL.B.,  1957.<BR>
<BR>

