<P>See this firm's profiles in the following other directories:<BR>
<UL><BR>
   <LI><A HREF="../95CLFolder/mayer.html"> Commercial Litigation</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95ENVFolder/mayer.html"> Environmental</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95LABFolder/mayer.html"> Labor</A>
   <LI><A HREF="../95PLFolder/mayer.html"> Product Liability</A>
</UL>

<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>M</B>ayer,  Brown  & Platt's Special Litigation Group represents corporations and individuals in both the investigation and defense of criminal and quasi-criminal matters. In addition,  the Group provides assistance to other practitioners in developing legal strategies and briefing legal issues and appeals in white collar cases. Our attorneys have experience in every aspect of federal and state criminal law problem-solving: preventive procedures,  corporate compliance programs,  internal investigations,  grand jury proceedings,  negotiations,  trials,  appellate litigation,  and the attentive monitoring of legislation or regulation affecting potential criminal situations.
<P><BR><P>Comprised of former federal prosecutors and assistants to the Solicitor General,  the members of the Special Litigation Group have extensive trial and appellate experience in representing both the government and defendants in complex criminal litigation. The senior members of the group include:<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Chicago Office</H3></CENTER>
<BR><BR><UL>
<LI><B>Tyrone C. Fahner</B> former Attorney General of the State of Illinois; former assistant U.S. attorney for the Northern District of Illinois (chief of Special Prosecutions Division). As Attorney General of Illinois,  Mr. Fahner served as chief legal and law enforcement officer of Illinois; prosecuted actions on behalf of the people and defended actions brought against the state,  its constitutional officers,  and its employees; and personally argued selected cases in U.S. district court and the Illinois Supreme Court. His litigation experience includes civil and criminal antitrust,  trade regulation matters,  products liability,  commodities,  securities,  multidistrict litigation,  representation of banking institutions,  `prime-rate' class action cases,  state and federal tax matters,  white collar crime,  criminal fraud,  and extensive jury trial experience in cases involving financial crimes including tax,  bankruptcy,  securities fraud,  and consumer fraud matters.<BR><BR><LI><B>Vincent J. Connelly</B> Former assistant U.S attorney for the Northern District of Illinois (chief of Special Prosecutions Division). Mr. Connelly's criminal litigation experience includes antitrust,  securities,  government contract and program,  RICO,  commercial and financial fraud,  and public corruption matters. He has had primary trial responsibility in more than 40 jury trials. He is a member of the American College of Trial Lawyers.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Thomas M. Durkin</B> Former first assistant U.S. attorney for the Northern District of Illinois. Mr. Durkin's federal criminal litigation experience includes commodities fraud,  RICO,  bank fraud,  public corruption,  bankruptcy fraud,  and complex tax cases. He has tried approximately 50 federal criminal jury trials.<BR>
<BR></UL>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Washington,  D.C. Office</H3></CENTER>

<BR><BR><UL><LI><B>Andrew L. Frey</B> Former deputy solicitor general,  with principal responsibility for criminal appeals and oral advocacy. Mr. Frey specializes in appellate litigation,  notably our U.S. Supreme Court practice,  where he has been responsible for briefs on the merits in several hundred cases,  a similar number of <I>certiorari</I> petitions,  and several thousand briefs in opposition to <I>certiorari</I> petitions. He has argued 60 cases in the U.S. Supreme Court and numerous cases in federal courts of appeals and state supreme courts. Among other cases,  he has secured the reversal of the convictions of presidential advisor Lyn Nofziger,  securities trader John Mulheren,  and sports agent Norby Walters. He also advises on appellate litigation strategy.<BR><BR><LI><B>Marc Gary</B> Former associate independent counsel (HUD investigation). As a litigator,  Mr. Gary represents corporations,  professional partnerships,  trade associations,  and individuals in state and federal courts in civil and criminal litigation involving antitrust,  RICO,  professional liability,  securities,  commercial,  trademark,  banking,  civil rights,  and constitutional law. In addition to extensive trial experience,  he regularly represents clients in grand jury,  inspector general,  and congressional investigations.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Lawrence S. Robbins</B> Former assistant U.S. attorney for the Eastern District of New York; former assistant to the solicitor general; and former associate independent counsel (HUD investigation). Mr. Robbins' trial litigation experience includes trying approximately 25 federal jury trials,  including income tax evasion,  public corruption,  export violations,  false statements,  mail and wire fraud,  and government fraud cases; extensive criminal investigations,  including complex grand jury matters,  involving government contract fraud,  public corruption,  false claims,  tax evasion,  and export violations; pretrial and post-trial litigation; and an extensive civil practice that includes antitrust,  mergers and acquisitions,  and general commercial litigation. He has also worked on more than 100 cases in the U.S. Supreme Court and numerous other cases in the courts of appeals,  and has argued 13 cases in the U.S. Supreme Court and approximately 25 cases in the U.S. courts of appeals.<BR>
<BR></UL>
<BR>
<BR>
