<TITLE><\3><\2>McKenna  & Cuneo,  L.L.P.
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF><UL>

<CENTER>
<H2>White Collar Crime</H2>
<H3>McKenna  & Cuneo,  L.L.P.
</H3>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<B>Washington:</B> 1575 Eye Street,  N.W.,  Washington,  DC 20005<BR>
Tel 202-789-7500  <B>*</B>  Fax 202-789-7756<BR>
<B>Los Angeles:</B> 444 South Flower Street,  Los Angeles,  CA 90071<BR>
Tel 213-688-1000  <B>*</B>  Fax 213-243-6330<BR>
<B>San Diego:</B> Symphony Towers,  750 B Street,  San Diego,  CA 92101<BR>
Tel 619-595-5400  <B>*</B>  Fax 619-595-5450<BR>
<B>Other offices:</B> San Francisco,  Denver,  Dallas,  Brussels<BR>
<BR>
272 lawyers  <B>*</B>  20 lawyers in White Collar Defense Group<BR>

</CENTER>
<P>
<P><BR>

<P>
<P><B>M</B>cKenna  & Cuneo,  L.L.P. has an active and long-standing white collar defense practice. It has evolved primarily out of the firm's representation of clients in regulated areas such as defense contracting,  environmental,  food and drug and health care. Our practice is diversified,  involving the defense of large corporations,  small businesses,  and individuals.
<P><BR><P>Led by former federal prosecutors and federal defenders,  each with many years of criminal jury trial experience,  the White Collar Defense Group defends clients at all stages of the investigative and criminal process,  most often against allegations of sophisticated criminal and civil fraud. Our practice is nationwide,  with active cases in virtually every region in the country. <BR><P>The Group regularly assists companies in conducting internal investigations and creating compliance programs consistent with the Federal Sentencing Guidelines. It also routinely provides advice on the various voluntary disclosure programs that are being offered by federal government agencies.<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Experience and Clients</H3></CENTER>

<P><BR><BR>
A representative list of matters recently handled includes the defense of:<BR><UL><P><LI> a Pennsylvania company in criminal,  civil,  and administrative proceedings relating to accusations of false claims for reimbursement of excise tax;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> a Florida company accused of dumping acid in the public water supply in violation of the Clean Water Act;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> numerous major companies confronted with <I>qui tam</I> actions under the civil False Claims Act;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> officers of a national medical testing laboratory accused of making false statements relating to unbundling practices;<BR>
<BR><P><LI> a Michigan company accused of paying bribes to a foreign government official in violation of the FCPA; and<BR>
<BR><P><LI> a California residential and commercial developer accused of bank fraud and false statements relating to a failed savings and loan institution.<BR>
<BR></UL>
<BR><LI><B>Robert S. Brewer,  Jr.</B> (<I>San Diego</I>) Mr. Brewer served in Los Angeles as deputy district attorney (1975-1977) and as an assistant U.S. attorney (1977-1981). He has tried over 80 jury trials and handles virtually all types of white collar matters. St. Lawrence University,  B.A.,  1968; University of San Diego,  J.D.,  1975.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Juanita R. Brooks</B> (<I>San Diego</I>) Ms. Brooks served as a trial attorney with the Federal Defenders of San Diego,  Inc. (1977-1980). She is a trial lawyer focusing on complex civil and criminal matters,  and has successfully represented,  for example,  automaker John Z. DeLorean in his RICO,  mail fraud,  and tax evasion trial. San Diego State University,  B.A.,  1974; Yale University,  J.D.,  1977.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Michael L. Fayad</B> (<I>Washington</I>) Mr. Fayad served as a trial attorney with the District of Columbia Public Defenders Service (1972-1976) and in the Fraud Section,  Criminal Division,  U.S. Department of Justice (1979-1989),  ultimately serving as chief,  Defense Procurement Fraud Unit. His primary focus is on procurement fraud. University of Detroit,  B.A.,  1967,  J.D.,  1970.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Richard A. Feinstein</B> (<I>Washington</I>) Mr. Feinstein served as a trial attorney and assistant section chief in the Antitrust Division of the U.S. Department of Justice (1977-1985). He represents corporations and individuals in antitrust and health care matters. Yale University,  B.A.,  1974; Boston College,  J.D.,  1977.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>T. Mark Flanagan,  Jr.</B> (<I>Washington</I>) Mr. Flanagan served as an assistant U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia (1984-1988). He defends corporations and individuals in a variety of criminal and civil fraud matters,  including procurement fraud,  environmental crimes,  and international transactions crimes. University of Notre Dame,  B.A.,  1976; University of Virginia,  J.D.,  1981.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Fred D. Heather </B>(<I>Los Angeles</I>) Mr. Heather served as an assistant U.S. attorney,  Central District of California (1983-1987),  during which he supervised a federal task force investigating fraud in defense contracts. He concentrates in complex civil fraud and white collar criminal defense matters,  particularly civil False Claims Act <I>qui tam</I> cases. Bucknell University,  B.A.,  1966; Hofstra University,  J.D.,  1977.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Daniel G. Jarcho</B> (<I>Washington</I>) Mr. Jarcho served as a trial attorney in the U.S. Department of Justice,  Office of Consumer Litigation (1988-1992). He handles complex civil and criminal cases,  with an emphasis on FDA matters. Harvard College,  B.A.,  1981; Harvard University,  J.D.,  1984.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Frederic M. Levy</B> (<I>Washington</I>) Mr. Levy,  who joined the firm in 1978,  focuses on procurement fraud,  both civil and criminal. He also has substantial experience in representing companies and individuals in suspension and debarment proceedings. Columbia University,  B.A.,  1975,  J.D.,  1978.<BR>
<BR><LI><B>Michael G. Scheininger</B> (<I>Washington</I>) Mr. Scheininger served as an assistant U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia (1972-1979). His focus is on the defense of business crimes and civil fraud,  and he also is an adjunct professor of law at Georgetown University,  teaching trial advocacy. Franklin  & Marshall College,  B.A.,  1969; University of Pennsylvania,  J.D.,  1972.<BR><BR>


</UL></BODY>
